{Wei Yi was having a really solid event and hence I was eager to beat him, but judging by how the game went... I wasn't even close to achieving what I wanted :).  Adhiban,B: 'Wei Yi was having a really solid event and hence I was eager to beat him, but judging by how the game went... I wasn't even close to achieving what I wanted :).  '} 1. Nf3 {Adhiban,B A pleasant surprise.} Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. d4 O-O 5. e4 d6 6. h3 {During our prep for the game I had asked my friend Vishnu what to do against 1.d4? He replied, "He doesn't play d4 against guys who play the KID" :).} Na6 7. Be3 c6 8. Rc1 Nc7 {Deviating from his game against Zhao.} (8... e5 {Adhiban,B} 9. d5 Nc5 (9... cxd5 10. cxd5 Ne8 11. g4 Kh8 12. Be2 (12. Bd3 $14) (12. Rg1 $5 $16) 12... f5 13. gxf5 gxf5 14. exf5 Bxf5 15. Ng5 Qe7 16. Bg4 Bh6 17. h4 Bg6 18. Bh5 Bf5 19. Bg4 Bg6 20. Ne6 Bxe3 21. fxe3 {Nepomniachtchi,I (2751)-Adhiban,B (2677) Tbilisi 2017} Rg8 $132) 10. Nd2 a5 11. Be2 {and although Black's c5 is better, than on c7, this is not a particularly good version of the Makogonov:} Bd7 (11... Nfd7 12. g4 a4 13. h4 Qa5 14. h5 Rb8 15. Kf1 Nb6 16. g5 Qb4 17. Rc2 Bd7 18. Kg2 a3 19. b3 cxd5 20. Nxd5 Nxd5 21. cxd5 b5 22. Rh4 Rbc8 23. hxg6 hxg6 {½-½ (44) Wei,Y (2732)-Tomashevsky,E (2705) chess.com INT 2020} 24. Nf3 $16 {[%cal Ye3d2]}) 12. b3 Ne8 13. O-O f5 14. Re1 b6 15. a3 f4 16. Bxc5 bxc5 17. Bg4 Bf6 18. Bxd7 Qxd7 19. Qg4 Qxg4 20. hxg4 $14 {Delgado Ramirez,N (2123)-Rain,R (2240) email 2017}) 9. Be2 ({I wonder why Wei Yi rejected} 9. Bd3 $5 {which was probably best.} b5 ({The lesser evil is} 9... e5 10. d5 {But what is the knight doing on c7? :)}) 10. cxb5 cxb5 (10... Nxb5 11. Na4 $16) 11. O-O b4 12. Ne2 Ba6 13. Ng3 {Adhiban,B: '' with a clearly superior position.}) 9... b5 (9... e5 10. d5 $14) 10. e5 (10. cxb5 Nxb5 $1 {The point! Black should be able to equalise here since White has to waste another tempo to defend the e4-pawn.} (10... cxb5 {is bad due to} 11. Bd3 Bb7 12. O-O b4 13. Ne2 Nxe4 14. Qc2 $18)) 10... dxe5 11. dxe5 {I was happy to see this, as I wasn't sure how to react against xe5.} ({There was the stronger and more principled} 11. Nxe5 {Adhiban,B: ''} bxc4 ({More passive but possibly more chances of equalising were offered by} 11... Bb7 $5 12. O-O bxc4 13. Bxc4 Nfd5 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. Qb3 $1 Rb8 16. Bxd5 cxd5 17. Qa4 $14 {and the light-squared bishop feels totally out of place.}) 12. Nxc6 $1 (12. Bxc4 Ncd5 13. O-O (13. Nxc6 Nxe3 14. fxe3 Qd6 15. Ne5 Nd7 $1 16. Nxd7 Qg3+ {is a nice line}) 13... Qd6 {looked decent for Black.} (13... Nxe3 14. fxe3 $16)) 12... Qd6 13. Bf3 Bd7 14. Ne5 Ncd5 15. Nxc4 {Adhiban,B: '' and White has won the pawn under favourable circumstances.}) 11... Nd7 12. cxb5 cxb5 13. O-O (13. Nxb5 Nxb5 14. Bxb5 Qa5+ $19) 13... Bb7 (13... Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 15. Bf3 $1 {I missed this idea when I went for ...b5.}) (13... b4 14. Nd5 $16) 14. Nxb5 Nd5 $5 {Too stubborn.} (14... Nxb5 15. Bxb5 Nxe5 16. Nxe5 Bxe5 {and I would have probably made a less impressive draw but... 4hrs earlier and without suffering, but where is the fun in that :)?}) 15. e6 $1 {Although I saw this I decided to allow it. Bravery or stupidity?} fxe6 (15... Nxe3 16. fxe3 Nb6 (16... fxe6 17. Nc7 $18) 17. exf7+ Rxf7 18. Nc7 Rc8 19. Qxd8+ Rxd8 20. Ne6 Rd6 21. Nxg7 Kxg7 22. Rfd1 $16) 16. Qb3 $1 $16 {A strong move after which I also have to worry about discovered attack's on the b7-bishop. Adhiban,B: 'A strong move after which I also have to worry about discovered attacks on the b7-bishop.'} (16. Ng5 Nxe3 17. fxe3 Qb6 $1 {and Black takes over the intiative.}) 16... Ne5 $5 {Exchanging some pieces and reducing the pressure.} 17. Nxe5 Bxe5 18. Bg4 Kh8 $1 19. Bd4 Bf6 (19... Qb8 20. Bxe5+ Qxe5 21. Rce1 Qb8 (21... Qg5 22. Nd4 $1 Nf4 23. Nxe6 Nxe6 24. Qxb7 {with a hopeless position for Black.}) 22. Rxe6 $18) 20. Bxf6+ (20. Bxe6 $2 Nf4 $1 $15) (20. Rfd1 $16 {just keeping the status quo was much better.}) 20... Rxf6 (20... exf6 21. Nc7) 21. Nc7 $1 Rb8 (21... Nxc7 22. Qxb7 Nd5 23. Rfe1 $16) 22. Nxe6 Qg8 $5 {What else?} (22... Qd6 {was my original intention but unfortunately allows the stunning Adhiban,B: 'was my original intention but unfortunately it allows the stunning'} 23. Qxb7 $1) 23. Nc5 ({During the game I was more concerned about} 23. Nc7 $1 {But luckily I have} Nf4 $1 (23... Nxc7 24. Qxg8+ Kxg8 25. Rxc7 {looked uninspiring.}) 24. Qxg8+ Kxg8 25. g3 h5 {with counterplay.}) 23... Ba6 24. Be6 $1 Rxb3 (24... Rxe6 25. Qxd5 $16) 25. Bxg8 Kxg8 (25... Bxf1 26. Bxd5 (26. Nxb3 Bxg2 27. Rc8 Nb6 {with equality.}) 26... Rxb2 27. Rxf1 Rb5 28. Rc1 Rf5 29. Ne6 $1 {Again this nasty motif, winning.}) 26. Nxb3 (26. axb3 $5 {was stronger:} Bxf1 27. Kxf1 {Compared to the game the white knight will be more active here.}) 26... Bxf1 27. Kxf1 Nb4 28. Rc7 (28. Rc8+ $1 {Adhiban,B: 'tr to 28.c8+.'} Kf7 29. Nc1 {was a nice defence and again I would face an uphill struggle to save this.}) 28... Nd3 (28... Ra6 {allows} 29. a3 Nd3 30. Nc5 {with a better endgame with good winning chances.}) 29. Rd7 (29. Rc2 $1 {offered the best chances.} Nb4 30. Rc8+ {tr to 28.c8+.}) 29... Nxb2 30. Rxa7 Nd3 31. f3 (31. Kg1 $5 Kf7 {Black has decent chances to save this.}) 31... Re6 32. Kg1 Nf4 (32... Re1+ $1 33. Kh2 Re2 {was the natural intention but I decided against it for some reason.} 34. Nd4 (34. Rd7 Nf4 35. Rd2) 34... Rb2 {with sufficient play to hold the balance.}) 33. Rd7 Ne2+ (33... Re2 34. Rd2 $16) 34. Kf2 (34. Kh2 Ra6 {going for the a2-pawn.}) 34... Nc3 35. Rd2 Ra6 36. Nc1 Kf7 {Somehow I have managed to tie up White's forces a bit.} (36... Ra3 {was my first intention.} 37. Rd3 $1) 37. Ke3 Ke6 (37... Ra4 $5 {was stronger, not allowing the activation of the king.}) 38. Kd4 $1 Nb5+ $5 (38... Nd5 {was the original plan but it started to feel uncomfortable after} 39. Nd3 $5 Ra4+ 40. Kc5 {White is very active in addition to the extra a-pawn.}) 39. Kc5 Nd6 40. Nb3 {White is very active hence his chances look really good.} Kd7 41. Kb4 Rb6+ 42. Kc3 Rc6+ 43. Kb2 ({Maybe a stronger move was} 43. Kd3 $5 {keeping the king active.}) 43... Kc7 44. Nd4 $1 {A nice trick which I understimated.} Rb6+ (44... Nc4+ 45. Kc3 Nxd2+ 46. Nxc6 $18) 45. Kc3 e5 {[%csl Yc3,Yd2] Using the king and rook placement to create the new threat of e4.} 46. Ne6+ Kc6 47. Kd3 (47. Re2 Kd5 {and the king looks active on d5.}) 47... Ra6 $1 {Activating the rook and preparing to annoy the king with a rook check on a3.} 48. Rc2+ Kb6 49. Nd8 Kb5 $1 {Now the knight is little bit silly on d8.} 50. Rb2+ Kc5 51. Ne6+ Kc6 52. Rc2+ Kb6 53. Kc3 $1 Ra3+ $6 {A loss of concentration, I forgot about White's reply.} (53... e4 54. fxe4 Nxe4+ 55. Kb4 $16) 54. Kb4 {I had completely overlooked this move.} ({I was expecting} 54. Kb2 Re3 {with good play.}) 54... Rd3 55. Nf8 (55. Nd8 Rd4+ 56. Kb3 Nf5 $1 {A nice trick to prevent c6+.}) 55... Rd4+ 56. Kb3 Nf5 $1 57. Kc3 (57. Nxh7 Rh4 $1 {At first this slipped my mind.} (57... Rd7 {doesn't work due to} 58. Nf6 Rf7 59. Nd5+)) (57. Re2 Rd8 $1 {and Black survives.} 58. Ne6 Re8 59. g4 (59. Rxe5 $6 Nd4+) 59... Rxe6 60. gxf5 gxf5 {with a draw.}) 57... Ne3 $1 58. Re2 Nd5+ 59. Kc2 {Here I had to make a difficult decision again.} Rc4+ 60. Kb3 Rc3+ $1 61. Kb2 Rc7 62. Rd2 (62. Ne6 Re7 63. Rxe5 Nf4 $1 64. Nc5 Rxe5 65. Nd7+ Kb5 66. Nxe5 Nxg2 {with a probable draw.}) 62... Rb7 $1 {I had to forsee this when I played 59...c4+, because otherwise the whole line doesn't work! Now the knight on f8 starts to feel bit ashamed about itself.} 63. Ne6 Kc6+ 64. Kc1 Ra7 $1 {Moving the rook out of the danger zone and keeping the pressure.} 65. Ng5 Nf6 $5 {Fighting for the e4-square.} (65... Kc5 66. Ne4+ Kc4 {looked funny but probably also possible. Adhiban,B: 'looked funny but was probably also possible.'} 67. Rc2+ Kd4 68. Nd6 Ke3 {and White doesn't have much advantage left.}) 66. Re2 $6 (66. Kb2 $1 {would still keep good chances to win.}) 66... Kd5 (66... h6 $1 {would have shortened the suffering.} 67. Ne4 (67. Ne6 $6 Kd6 68. Nf8 Rg7 {and the knight will meet its master soon :).}) 67... Nxe4 68. fxe4 Ra4 {with equality.}) 67. Kb2 Rb7+ 68. Kc2 ({A stronger try was} 68. Kc3 Rc7+ 69. Kd3 Ra7 70. Rd2 $1 {Borrowing the same trick which I used :).} h6 71. Ke3+ Kc6 72. Ne6 g5 {Black can fight on.}) 68... Ra7 69. Kb2 Rb7+ 70. Ka1 Rb4 ({A better move was} 70... Kd4 $5 {The king occupies a commanding position.}) 71. a3 (71. Ne4 Nxe4 72. Rxe4 Rxe4 73. fxe4+ Kxe4 74. a4 (74. Kb2 Kd3 75. Kc1 Ke2) 74... Kd3 {Suddenly I am playing for a win.}) (71. Rb2 $1 {was a good attempt} Rd4 72. Kb1 e4 $1 73. fxe4+ Nxe4 74. Nxh7 Kc4 {Though Black's active pieces should compensate for the pawn deficit.}) 71... Rd4 {Not allowing d2+.} (71... Rb3 72. Rd2+ $1) 72. Kb2 Rd3 73. a4 h6 $5 {I figured it was time to liquidate a bit, also because the a-pawn was starting to make me uncomfortable.} 74. Nf7 e4 75. fxe4+ (75. a5 {was the last chance} e3 76. a6 Nd7 77. a7 Nb6 78. Rc2 Rd4 79. Nd8 Ra4 80. Nc6 e2 $1 81. Ne7+ Kd4 82. Rxe2 Rxa7 83. Nc6+ Kd3 84. Re6 Rb7 $1 {Yes this trick again!} 85. Ne5+ Kd2 {and Black holds the balance thanks to his activity.}) 75... Nxe4 76. Nxh6 Rd4 $1 {Looked stronger than ...c5.} ({My main intention was} 76... Nc5 77. a5 Rb3+ 78. Kc2 Ra3 {is maybe also possible.}) 77. a5 Ra4 (77... Rb4+ $1 {was the easier way out.} 78. Ka3 Rb5 {winning the pawn.}) 78. Ng8 Kd4 $1 79. Ne7 Kd3 80. Rc2 (80. Re1 Rxa5 81. Nxg6 Rb5+ 82. Kc1 Rc5+ 83. Kb2 Rb5+ $11) 80... Rxa5 81. Nxg6 Ra2+ $1 {I calculated that I can stop the pawns in time (also I really didn't have any other option :))} 82. Kxa2 Kxc2 83. h4 Nf6 $1 {The black king and the knight will easily mop up the pawns as the white king is stranded on the other wing.} 84. Ne5 Kc3 (84... Kd2 85. g4 Ke3 86. g5 {I thought I wasn't in time but after} Nh5 {Black holds.}) 85. Kb1 Kd4 86. Nf3+ Ke3 87. Kc2 Kf2 88. Kd3 Kxg2 89. Nd2 Kg3 90. Ne4+ Kxh4 {Finally managing to save a completely lost position after a mammoth struggle! Thanks to this save, I kept my plus score intact.} 1/2-1/2


