{Bu seems to know his countrymen very well as he scored an amazing 4,5/5 score with the white pieces. In the current game against the probably strongest/ youngest GM in the world, Wei Yi, who is just 15 years old, Bu chooses a very solid opening and enters a slightly better endgame, which doesn't seem to be so serious at first, but slowly but surely he outplays his opponent which makes Wei Yi panic and lose the game on the spot at some point. Bu seems to know his countrymen very well as he scored an amazing 4,5/5 score with the white pieces. In the current game against the probably strongest/ youngest GM in the world, Wei Yi, who is just 15 years old, Bu chooses a very solid opening and enters a slightly better endgame, which doesn't seem to be so serious at first, but slowly but surely he outplays his opponent which makes Wei Yi panic and lose the game on the spot at some point.} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 {The best Chinese players usually choose the Slav or KID.} 3. b3 {Well, not the most agressive opening choice. Bu's strategy was probably just to play a chess game without going too deep into the theoretical lines. Well, not the most agressive opening choice. Bu's strategy was probably just to play a chess game without going too deep into the theoretical lines.} Bg7 4. Bb2 O-O 5. g3 {A double fianchetto opening is actually more tricky than it looks like, how to react now for Black?! A double fianchetto opening is actually more tricky than it looks like, how to react now for Black?!} d6 {is a possible reply, but I don't think it's the strongest one. To me the best reaction seems to be 5...c5 followed by Nc6 and d5. I think White should have no advantage there. In case of 5...c6, with the idea of playing d5 next, White could get a small advantage by playing d3 (not d4) and then Nbd2. is a possible reply, but I don't think it's the strongest one. To me the best reaction seems to be 5...c5 followed by Nc6 and d5. I think White should have no advantage there. In case of 5...c6, with the idea of playing d5 next, White could get a small advantage by playing d3 (not d4) and then Nbd2.} 6. d4 {was probably played against the e5 move. was probably played against the e5 move.} c5 {is another possible move, but I think one more time Black is not playing the most principled. is another possible move, but I think one more time Black is not playing the most principled.} (6... e5 $5 {!? seems to be the right way of playing to me, so in case of White's 7.dxe5 Black always has Ng4 or Nfd7, so there is no reason to be afraid of it. The next black move could be Nbd7, with an interesting position. seems to be the right way of playing to me, so in case of White's 7.dxe5 Black always has Ng4 or Nfd7, so there is no reason to be afraid of it. The next black move could be Nbd7, with an interesting position.}) 7. Bg2 {DIAGRAM} Qa5+ {Quite a creative move. Black is provoking the white bishop to c3 to have the d5 idea, but on the other hand maybe it is too creative because the black queen is not going to have the best position on c7. Quite a creative move. Black is provoking the white bishop to c3 to have the d5 idea, but on the other hand maybe it is too creative because the black queen is not going to have the best position on c7.} 8. Bc3 (8. Nbd2 Ne4 {looks more promising for Black. looks more promising for Black.}) 8... Qc7 9. Nbd2 {Black wanted to play Ne4.} cxd4 {Now we can see Black's idea. Now we can see Black's idea.} 10. Nxd4 d5 {If we look at the position from a logical point of view, Black lost a tempo with playing d6 and then d5 and the queen on c7 is only going to stand under attack, so I think White's position should be better here. If we look at the position from a logical point of view, Black lost a tempo with playing d6 and then d5 and the queen on c7 is only going to stand under attack, so I think White's position should be better here.} 11. O-O {Bu continues with logical moves. White should never be afraid of e5 because of Nb5. Bu continues with logical moves. White should never be afraid of e5 because of Nb5.} Rd8 12. Rc1 Qd7 {A cool mov e by Black in what is already quite a difficult position. It is not easy to find a way to develop the pieces. A cool mov e by Black in what is already quite a difficult position. It is not easy to find a way to develop the pieces.} (12... dxc4 {was losing on the spot:} 13. Nxc4 e5 14. Ba5) 13. Nc2 {Black already threatened to play e5 and it seems like the white knight has to move from d4, so Bu decides to play Nc2 with the future idea of playing Ne3-Nd5, which is quite logical. Black already threatened to play e5 and it seems like the white knight has to move from d4, so Bu decides to play Nc2 with the future idea of playing Ne3-Nd5, which is quite logical.} ({Also possible was} 13. N4f3 {and White would take the e5 square under control, which would make the g2 bishop even stronger. and White would take the e5 square under control, which would make the g2 bishop even stronger.}) 13... dxc4 {DIAGRAM} 14. Ba5 $1 {! Very strong play!} ({After the peaceful} 14. Nxc4 Nc6 {Black should be fine because of the bad position of the white knight on c2. Black should be fine because of the bad position of the white knight on c2.}) 14... Re8 15. Nxc4 {Now the black rook is much more passively placed on e8.} Nc6 16. Nb4 {I guess Bu planned this move when he played 13.Nc2. It looks quite strange to give up the bishop, but on the other hand the white knight and the bishop on g2 give White a clear initiative. The black bishop on g7 is somehow out of the game. I guess Bu planned this move when he played 13.Nc2. It looks quite strange to give up the bishop, but on the other hand the white knight and the bishop on g2 give White a clear initiative. The black bishop on g7 is somehow out of the game.} Nxa5 {Black has to take on a5.} 17. Qxd7 ({Of course not} 17. Nxa5 $2 {?} Qb5 $1 {!}) 17... Bxd7 {To play 17...Nxd7? is of course not an option.} 18. Nxa5 b6 $1 {! The only move after which Black is not losing the b7 pawn.} 19. Nc4 {White is transfering his knight over e5 to c6.} ({After} 19. Nac6 a5 20. Nd3 Rac8 {Black keeps on fighting for equality.}) 19... Rac8 20. Ne5 {The position almost looks like a draw, but White still keeps putting pressure, so Black needs to continue being very accurate. The position almost looks like a draw, but White still keeps putting pressure, so Black needs to continue being very accurate.} Bf5 {Maybe after this little inaccuracy Black is already finding himself in a bad position. Maybe after this little inaccuracy Black is already finding himself in a bad position.} ({It seems like the best way to fight was} 20... Bb5 {Of course White has different options too, but let us take a look at the most logical one: Of course White has different options too, but let us take a look at the most logical one:} 21. Bc6 Bxc6 22. Nexc6 Rc7 {Black is very passive but also very solid. Black is very passive but also very solid.} 23. Na6 Rb7 24. Rfd1 e6 {Of course White is still better, but it is very hard to prove that there are realistic chances for a win here. Of course White is still better, but it is very hard to prove that there are realistic chances for a win here.}) 21. Nbc6 $1 {! Another very strong move by White. The idea is to win the control over the c-file. Another very strong move by White. The idea is to win the control over the c-file.} Rc7 22. Nd4 {Attacking both the f5 bishop and the c7 rook. DIAGRAM Attacking both the f5 bishop and the c7 rook. DIAGRAM} Nd5 $6 {?! Once again Black doesn't take his best chance.} ({After} 22... Rxc1 23. Rxc1 Be4 24. Ndc6 {White has a solid advantage.}) ({The right way to defend seems to be} 22... Rec8 $1 {!} 23. Rxc7 Rxc7 24. Nxf5 gxf5 25. Rd1 h6 {and of course White is better here, but Black's chances for a draw are not that bad. In case White tried to win material with and of course White is better here, but Black's chances for a draw are not that bad. In case White tried to win material with} 26. Rd8+ Kh7 27. Nxf7 $2 {? Black could even take over the game with Black could even take over the game with} Rc1+ 28. Bf1 Ne4 {as the position is already totally unclear.}) 23. Nxf5 gxf5 24. Rxc7 Nxc7 25. Nc6 {After some forced exchanges, we are entering a position where White has a huge advantage. Not only the knight on c6 guarantees White a small plus, but the black knight from c7 doesn't have any good squares either and White just wants to enter with his rook to d7 by playing Rd1-Rd7. Black's position is on the verge of being lost. After some forced exchanges, we are entering a position where White has a huge advantage. Not only the knight on c6 guarantees White a small plus, but the black knight from c7 doesn't have any good squares either and White just wants to enter with his rook to d7 by playing Rd1-Rd7. Black's position is on the verge of being lost.} Nb5 26. Rd1 {Of course not letting Black play Nd4.} Bf6 27. a4 {Another nice move by White. It is clear that Black's only option is to somehow get an opposite colored bishop endgame with a pawn down and try to save it. By playing a4 White doesn't give Black any hope for it. Another nice move by White. It is clear that Black's only option is to somehow get an opposite colored bishop endgame with a pawn down and try to save it. By playing a4 White doesn't give Black any hope for it.} Nc3 {DIAGRAM} 28. Rd7 a5 {Black continues defending passively.} ({Black should have tried} 28... Nxe2+ 29. Kf1 Nc3 30. Rxa7 {and of course White's position is close to winning, but maybe Black could hope for some tricks with moves like e5, followed by e4 with some practical chances. In case Black just waited, White is just going to play b4-a5 and the a-pawn is going to be very hard to stop. and of course White's position is close to winning, but maybe Black could hope for some tricks with moves like e5, followed by e4 with some practical chances. In case Black just waited, White is just going to play b4-a5 and the a-pawn is going to be very hard to stop.}) 29. Bf3 $1 {! Solid and strong. White also keeps the Bh5 idea in mind. Solid and strong. White also keeps the Bh5 idea in mind.} b5 $6 {?! Black panicks and after this move the game is lost. Black panicks and after this move the game is lost.} ({To a very bad, but still a fighting position would lead} 29... e5 30. Bh5 Rf8 {and there doesn't seem to be a forced win for White, although Black's position is just horrible. and there doesn't seem to be a forced win for White, although Black's position is just horrible.}) 30. axb5 Nxb5 31. Rd5 {Now White just ends up a pawn up.} Nc3 32. Rxf5 a4 {It is too late for exchanges...} 33. bxa4 Nxa4 {DIAGRAM} 34. e4 $1 {! Accurate until the end. Black can't stop White from playing e5 and Bh5 next. It is game over. Accurate until the end. Black can't stop White from playing e5 and Bh5 next. It is game over.} Bg7 35. Bh5 {A very clean positional win by Bu, showing great domination of the bishop+knight, which is quite typical for Catalan structures where White often has a strong bishop on the a8-h1 diagonal. A nice game to learn from! A very clean positional win by Bu, showing great domination of the bishop+knight, which is quite typical for Catalan structures where White often has a strong bishop on the a8-h1 diagonal. A nice game to learn from!} 1-0


