1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Qb3 dxc4 6. Qxc4 O-O 7. e4 Be6 {This provocative move became popular recently, mainly because of two great Black wins by Giri and Svidler back in 2012. Black's idea is to provoke d4-d5 and then to attack white's center with c7-c6 and e7-e6.} 8. Qb5 {Loyal to our concept, I will offer you a not so popular move, but Svidler's choice for White. When Peter plays something in Grunfeld regardless the colour, then this move should be consider seriously.} (8. d5 {This is the most popular move, but it only supports Black's idea.} Bc8 {It seems that Black lost a tempo, but now c6 or e6 is coming. Then the maneuver Ne8-d6 gives Black a pleasant game.} (8... Bg4 $4 {We are already familiar with this mistake. I will give you the following example to see how even 2600 players can blunder.} 9. e5 Bxf3 10. exf6 exf6 11. gxf3 {And despite the fact that the game was about 50+ moves, Black simply can resign here. 1-0 (59) Cori Tello,D (2413)-Muzychuk,A (2606) Istanbul 2012}) 9. Be2 c6 10. O-O cxd5 11. exd5 Nbd7 12. Rd1 Ne8 13. Bg5 h6 14. Bf4 Nd6 {Black has a solid position. 0-1 (34) Andonovski,L (2274)-Safarli,E  (2616) Eilat 2012}) 8... Bd7 {As usual, Black does not want to defend b7-pawn.} 9. Qb3 (9. Qc5 $5 b6 10. Qg5 c5 11. dxc5 Bc6 12. Qh4 bxc5 13. Be2 e6 14. Bg5 h6 15. Bxh6 Nxe4 16. Qf4 Nxc3 {With an excellent position for Black. From this game starts the popularity of 7.î Pe6 0-1 (50) Morozevich,A (2770)-Giri,A  (2696) Biel 2012}) (9. Qxb7 $2 {Such a move should not even cross our mind.} Bc6 10. Qb3 Nxe4 {and White should start to think about equality.}) 9... c5 (9... Nc6) 10. d5 {We have no choice now.} (10. dxc5 $5 Bc6 {Is just very comfortable for Black.}) 10... Qb6 {After this White is simply better.} (10... b5 11. e5 c4 (11... Ng4 12. Bf4 Qc7 {This move was offered in a late comment after Svidler's game, but there after:} (12... Qb6 {This was tried recently. The threat is î ..:f2 followed by c4} 13. Qc2 Bf5 14. Qe2 $1 $146 {Black's pieces seem active, but there are not concrete threats and he will be attacked and doomed to a passive position soon.} (14. Bd3 $6 Bxd3 15. Qxd3 Nd7 16. Qe2 Qb8 $6 (16... b4 $1 17. Na4 Qc7 {Gives Black a good game.}) 17. O-O b4 18. Ne4 Ngxe5 19. Nxc5 Nxf3+ 20. Qxf3 $11 {1/2 (70) Checa,N (2362)-Mikhalevski,V (2526) Rockville 2015}) 14... f6 15. e6 {All Black's pieces on the king side seem strange, Nd4 is coming.} c4 16. Qd2 $14 b4 {is always well met by:} 17. Nd1 $16) 13. Nxb5 Bxb5 14. Bxb5 Nxe5 15. O-O $14 {White is simply better because of the better pawn structure and more active pieces.}) 12. Qd1 Ng4 13. Bf4 Qb6 14. Qe2 b4 15. Nd1 {With a clear advantage. 1-0 (36) Baron,T (2513)-Vucinic,G  (2343) Skopje 2014}) 11. Bc4 {I like Svidler's approach, he first develops his pieces and then starts ta take some concrete actions.} (11. e5 {This is first line of my engine, but there is no need to enter into some complications in a strategically better position.} Ne8 12. Bf4) 11... Bg4 12. Be3 Nbd7 (12... Bxf3 $5 {Maybe the best chance} 13. gxf3 Nbd7 14. Qxb6 axb6 15. Bb5 {White has a long-lasting advantage in the endgame.}) 13. Nd2 {Suddenly Black's bishop is in trouble and White manages to develop his pieces perfectly.} Ne5 14. h3 Bc8 15. Be2 $16 {White has an enormous advantage: f4-e5 is coming.  Because the game was at rapid chess, we shouldn't judge very harsh the Russian grandmaster that somewhere in the game he even find himself in a difficult situation.  The objective evaluation of the opening is that Black has big difficulties and he should try b5, which also not equalize but at least give some practical chances.  I left the rest of the game without comments, because it is irrelevant for our topic.} e6 16. Qxb6 axb6 17. f4 Ned7 18. dxe6 fxe6 19. Bc4 Nb8 20. O-O Nc6 21. e5 Ne8 22. a3 g5 23. fxg5 Nxe5 24. Be2 Nd6 25. g4 Bd7 26. Nce4 Nxe4 27. Nxe4 Bc6 28. Nf6+ Kh8 29. Bd2 Ng6 30. Bc3 e5 31. Kh2 h6 32. Nh5 hxg5 33. Bd3 Nh4 34. Nxg7 Nf3+ 35. Kg3 Kxg7 36. Bf5 Nd4 37. Rae1 Rae8 38. Re3 Rf7 39. Rfe1 Rxf5 40. gxf5 Nxf5+ 41. Kg4 Nxe3+ 42. Rxe3 Kf6 43. Re1 Bd7+ 44. Kg3 Bf5 45. h4 gxh4+ 46. Kxh4 Bd3 47. Kg4 Bf5+ 48. Kf3 Bd7 49. Rxe5 Rxe5 1/2-1/2


