{Wei Yi had a bad chess start in 2016, but still he continues his good run against the Najdorf.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 {The most aggressive line.} e6 7. f4 Nbd7 (7... Qb6 {Going for the poisoned pawn is also very dangerous. Here are a few important recent games:} 8. Qd2 Qxb2 9. Rb1 Qa3 10. e5 h6 11. Bh4 dxe5 12. fxe5 g5 13. exf6 gxh4 {One of the key positions of the 6.Bg5 Najdorf. You better play this line with a good computer, big work and greatmemory!} 14. Be2 Qa5 (14... e5 {!? is a very interesting novelty which I saw live:} 15. Nd5 exd4 16. Nc7+ Kd8 17. Nxa8 Nd7 {with a crazy position. Lampert-Ragger Grenke Open 2016}) 15. O-O Nd7 16. Rbd1 h3 17. g3 Bb4 18. Qe3 Bxc3 19. Nxe6 Qe5 {? The strong Ukrainian grandmaster could not cope with the opening problems over the board but later found the saving line:} (19... fxe6 {!} 20. Qxe6+ Kd8 21. Qe7+ Kc7 22. Qd6+ Kd8 23. f7 Bg7 24. f8=Q+ Rxf8 25. Rxf8+ Bxf8 26. Qxf8+ Kc7 27. Qd6+ Kd8 28. Bg4 Qb5 {!} 29. Qf8+ Kc7 {and a draw was soon agreed in Zeng-Areshchenko 2015.}) 20. Nc7+ Kf8 21. Qxe5 Bxe5 22. Nxa8 Nxf6 23. Nb6 Kg7 24. Nxc8 Rxc8 25. Rf5 {and White converted his material advantage in Wei Yi-Areshchenko 2015.}) 8. Qe2 {This might seem like an odd move but the f1 bishop doesn't necessarly move on the f1-a6 diagonal and the game will show that it is sometimes useful to have the queen in front of Black's king.} (8. Qf3 {is an important alternative.}) 8... Qc7 9. O-O-O Be7 10. g4 {DIAGRAM} h6 (10... b5 11. a3 O-O (11... Bb7 {is the main theoretical move.}) 12. Bh4 Rb8 13. g5 Ne8 14. f5 Nc5 15. f6 Bd8 16. e5 {with an unclear but visually very dangerous position to play as Black. Wei Yi- Vachier Lagrave 2015}) 11. Bh4 g5 {?! This typical idea doesn't really work in this position.} 12. fxg5 {*} Nh7 $6 {?} (12... hxg5 {is much better than the game even if after} 13. Bxg5 b5 14. a3 Ne5 {⩲ this important square for the knight doesn't fully compensate the pawn deficit.} 15. h4 {!?} (15. Rg1 {!?})) 13. Bg3 {!} (13. Nf5 {- 29/400}) 13... hxg5 {DIAGRAM} (13... Bxg5+ 14. Kb1 Ne5 15. h4 $16 (15. Nf3 {! ± An important typical move to fight for e5.})) 14. Nf5 $1 {! Black prob ably didn't really know the opening as this strong refutation has already been played. Now he goes for a logical but wrong continuation in a very difficult position.} exf5 (14... Ne5 {looks more solid but Black can't really defend without the important dark-squared bishop, for example:} 15. Nxe7 Qxe7 16. h4 Bd7 17. hxg5 O-O-O 18. Qf2 {! ± and the queen invades on a7 or b6.}) 15. Nd5 Qb8 $146 (15... Qd8 {could simply be met by} 16. exf5 Ndf6 17. Nxf6+ Nxf6 18. Rxd6 Bd7 19. Rxf6 Kf8 20. Bd6 {! +⁠−}) 16. exf5 Ne5 17. Nxe7 Kxe7 {DIAGRAM} 18. Rxd6 $1 $18 {! The crushing move.} Qxd6 19. Bxe5 Qd5 20. Bg2 Qxa2 {DIAGRAM} 21. Bd6+ {! White had many wins and chose the most forceful one. It is simply a long forced matingvariation!} Kxd6 22. Rd1+ Kc7 23. Qe5+ Kb6 24. Qd4+ Ka5 25. Qc5+ b5 26. Qc7+ {Mate is coming soon. An easy but nice attacking game.} 1-0


