{We will see another great game by Matlakov, where he crushes the lately so strong playing Wei Yi. After the opening White manages to quickly put a lot of pressure on Black's position and later on to totally dominate the game, even making Black resign in a position with equal material. A very nice game to watch. Enjoy!} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 {This time the game enters the very main Gruenfeld.} 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Qa4+ {This is a relatively rare line, the very main being 7.Nf3.} Qd7 {The main idea of 7.Qa4 is to avoid the c5 push for a couple of moves, which White needs to complete his development.} 8. Bb5 {Glenn Flear: '!?' Glenn Flear: 'The latest trend. Now Black can't avoid playing ...c6. The first game that I've found was played by Paul Eggers in Seattle 1989, but it never caught on, that is until the last few months.' Glenn Flear: '!?' Glenn Flear: 'The latest trend. Now Black can't avoid playing ...c6. The first game that I've found was played by Paul Eggers in Seattle 1989, but it never caught on, that is until the last few months.' Of course not exchanging the queens! If the queens are gone from the board, Black usually has an excellent endgame.} c6 9. Be2 ({A new twist is placing the bishop on d3 from where it protects the e4-pawn:} 9. Bd3 O-O 10. Ne2 c5 11. Qxd7 Nxd7 12. Be3 (12. Bg5 cxd4 13. cxd4 e5 14. d5 Nc5 15. Bc2 Bd7 16. Kd2 (16. Be7 {is safely met by} Rfc8) 16... Rfc8 17. Rhc1 b5 {Pilvett, D-Laclau, D Andorra 2015, with comfortable equality for Black.}) 12... Rd8 13. Rd1 b6 14. f3 Bb7 15. Kf2 Rac8 16. h4 e5 $5 ({Black has a wide choice, both} 16... h6) ({and} 16... h5 {coming into consideration}) 17. d5 c4 18. Bc2 Bf8 {Anton Guijarro, D-Gabuzyan, H Martuni 2015, with an acceptable game for Black.}) 9... O-O {Black wants to play c5.} 10. Qa3 {Glenn Flear: '!' Glenn Flear: 'This shuffle, slowing down ...c5, was introduced by Lysyj.' Glenn Flear: '!' Glenn Flear: 'This shuffle, slowing down ...c5, was introduced by Lysyj.' and White is preventing it.} ({Black has more or less solved his opening problems after the main alternative} 10. Nf3 {e.g.} c5 11. Bb5 {(is sharpest)} (11. Qa3 {(too late to worry Black here)} cxd4 12. cxd4 Nc6 13. Be3 Nxd4 (13... Qg4 $5) 14. Bxd4 Bxd4 15. Rd1 e5 $11 16. O-O (16. Nxe5 Qc7 17. Rxd4 Qxe5) 16... Re8 17. Rd2 Qe7 18. Qxe7 Rxe7 19. Nxd4 exd4 20. Rxd4 Be6 {0.5-0.5 Riazantsev, A-Grigoriants, S St.Petersburg rapid 2015.}) ({otherwise} 11. Qxd7 {has been played, but the bishop may be better placed on d3 (see above) if White intends trading queens:} Bxd7 12. Rb1 b6 13. Bb2 e6 14. O-O Bc6 15. Bd3 {(losing a tempo?)} Rd8 16. Rfe1 Nd7 $11 {Cech, P-Pribyl, J Prague 1990.}) 11... Qg4 12. O-O cxd4 13. Ba3 Nc6 $1 14. cxd4 Qxe4 15. Rfe1 Qd5 16. Bc4 Qa5 {Ivanisevic, I-Giri, A Al-Ain 2012, and Black was fine.}) 10... b6 {Yet again preparing the c5 push.} ({I'm not so sure about} 10... Qd6 $5 11. f4 {(ambitious)} c5 12. e5 Qc7 13. Be3 cxd4 14. cxd4 Be6 15. Bf3 Qd7 16. Ne2 Nc6 17. Kf2 Bd5 {Lysyj, I-Ragger, M Warsaw rapid 2013. Black has lost a couple of tempi with his queen, but on the plus side has organized a light-square blockade.}) 11. Nf3 {DIAGRAM} Bb7 {Maybe Wei Yi didn't choose the best move order.} ({Similar is} 11... c5 {which could transpose. The following encounter, however, went its own way:} 12. O-O (12. d5 e6 {Here we have a position which is close to the game but in a much better version for Black.}) 12... cxd4 13. cxd4 Bb7 {and I believe the position is a very fighting one, but should be close to equal.} 14. Qe3 {(one disadvantage of ...cxd4 is that it allows this defensive switch)} Nc6 15. Bb2 Rfd8 16. Rfd1 Na5 17. Rab1 e6 18. h4 {Moiseenko, A-Bok, B Biel 2015, and now instead of the loosening} f5 $6 ({the calm} 18... Rac8 19. h5 Nc4 {should be OK for Black.})) 12. O-O c5 {So Black finally pushes c5, but White has an excellent counter measure up his sleeve...} 13. d5 {! Perfect play! The black bishop on b7 is getting blocked now and the knight from b8 is having serious trouble getting into the game.} e6 {Diagram  Diagram  Diagram [#]} 14. Be3 $1 $146 {Glenn Flear: 'New.' Glenn Flear: 'New.' Another good move, preparing to play Rad1, bringing the last piece into the action.} ({Glenn Flear: 'In an earlier game, Wei Yi was able to capture on d5 after'} 14. Rd1 {- 125/(153) - 125/(153) - 125/(153) Glenn Flear: 'i.e.'} exd5 15. exd5 Bxd5 $1 {(the unfortunate position of the queen's rook stops White being able to profit from the pin)} 16. Bc4 Bxc4 17. Rxd7 Nxd7 {Lysyj, I-Wei Yi, Chinese league 2015, with at least enough compensation for the queen.}) 14... exd5 {Black doesn't have anything better.} 15. Rad1 {Glenn Flear: 'Having the queen's rook on d1 avoids any problems along the long dark-squared diagonal.' Glenn Flear: 'Having the queen's rook on d1 avoids any problems along the long dark-squared diagonal.' DIAGRAM} d4 $6 {Glenn Flear: '?' Glenn Flear: 'I suspect that this is just wrong. As a rule, opening up the centre with lagging development is fraught with danger.' Glenn Flear: '?' Glenn Flear: 'I suspect that this is just wrong. As a rule, opening up the centre with lagging development is fraught with danger.' ?! In my opinion this is at least a very risky decision.} ({Glenn Flear: 'The natural-looking alternative'} 15... Nc6 {Glenn Flear: '!' Glenn Flear: 'is better, when the plausible sequence'} 16. exd5 Ne7 17. c4 (17. Qb3 Nf5 18. Bf4 Nd6 {gives Black a solid enough position.}) 17... Nf5 18. Bf4 $14) (15... Qd6 16. exd5 Nd7 {and this quite typical position should be evaluated as minimally better for White.}) 16. cxd4 Bxe4 (16... cxd4 $6 17. Bxd4 Qc7 (17... Bxd4 18. Nxd4 Bxe4 19. Nb5 $16) 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. Rc1 Qf4 20. Qc3+ Kg8 21. Ne5 $1 $16 { g4  g4  Ng4}) (16... Qe7 17. dxc5 Nd7 18. Bb5 $1 Nf6 (18... Nxc5 $6 19. Rd7 $16) 19. Bd4 $16) 17. dxc5 {Now that the center is fully opened it is extremely important that White's development is much better than Black's one, so White has some time to create a few threats- and this is what Matlakov is going to do...} Qb7 {This is probably the best position for the black queen.} 18. Rfe1 {Glenn Flear: 'White is fully deployed, whereas Black isn't.' Glenn Flear: 'White is fully deployed, whereas Black isn't.' ! A silent but very unpleasant move for Black! White does not hurry to force things immediately, but is threatening to play Ng5 now, after which Bxg2 will not be possible any longer because of f3, and the rook on e1 could often be a useful piece.} (18. Rd6 {was another nice possibility.}) 18... Nd7 {The knight is finally out. DIAGRAM} (18... Bd5 19. Qd3 Be4 20. Qc4 $14) 19. Ba6 {! Another great move by White to destablize the position of the black pieces.} Qc7 {Diagram  Diagram  Diagram [#]} ({If} 19... Qc6 {then} 20. Rd6 {comes with a gain of time.} Qc7 21. c6 {and White is clearly better.}) 20. Bb5 $1 {Glenn Flear: 'Apart from the attack on the d7-knight, the bishop on e4 is also loose.' Glenn Flear: 'Apart from the attack on the d7-knight, the bishop on e4 is also loose.' Using the fact that Black can't take the c5 pawn.} Nf6 $6 (20... Ne5 21. Nxe5 Bxe5 22. Rd7 $1 Bxh2+ 23. Kh1 Qe5 24. Bd4 Bxg2+ 25. Kxg2 Qxe1 26. Kxh2 $16) (20... Nxc5 {? loses a piece after} 21. Bxc5 bxc5 22. Rxe4) (20... Bf5 21. c6 {but here White is also clearly better after} a6 22. Ba4 b5 23. cxd7 bxa4 24. Rd2 {and the d7 pawn gives White a big plus.}) 21. Bd4 {Black is suddenly in big trouble!} Bf5 {What else to do?! To play 21...Bxf3 22. Qxf3 and give White the bishop pair and a strong c-pawn is a very unpleasant option...} (21... Rad8 22. Be5 Qb7 23. Rxd8 Rxd8 24. Qb2 Qe7 25. Bc3 bxc5 26. Nd2 $18) 22. c6 $18 {Glenn Flear: '!' Glenn Flear: 'Such an advance can only be good when one has the clearly superior pieces.' Glenn Flear: '!' Glenn Flear: 'Such an advance can only be good when one has the clearly superior pieces.' It is very nice to see how the white pieces are dominating the center.} a6 ({After} 22... Rfe8 {White still replies} 23. Be5) 23. Be5 {A nice "zwischenzug" which allows White not to worry about the c6 pawn.} Qc8 (23... axb5 24. Qxa8 $18) 24. Ba4 b5 25. Bb3 {DIAGRAM} a5 {Wei Yi is still hoping to escape by creating some threats on the queenside.} (25... Qxc6 $4 {drops material after} 26. Rd6 {and the f6 knight is gone.}) 26. Qb2 {! Another safe and strong move by White!} a4 ({Following} 26... Nh5 {would lead to a total domination of the white pieces:} 27. Bxg7 Nxg7 28. Re7 a4 29. Bd5 {with a winning position for White.} Be6 30. Bxe6 Nxe6 31. Ne5 {the pressure is too strong.}) 27. Bxf6 Bxf6 28. Qxf6 axb3 29. axb3 Bc2 {Black is equalizing the material, but not saving the game. The white queen and knight make for an excellent combination to mate the black king...} 30. Rd7 Bxb3 {Glenn Flear: 'Material is equal, but not the relative security of the kings.' Glenn Flear: 'Material is equal, but not the relative security of the kings.' DIAGRAM} 31. h4 {Glenn Flear: '!' Glenn Flear: '!' ! Maxim shows no mercy. The simple threat of playing h5-h6 is deadly.} Ra6 (31... h5 32. Ree7 $18) 32. Ne5 {The c6 pawn is saved and Black is completely paralyzed. A really beautiful positional win by White and another example of how dangerous it is to play without the center and with a worse development, wspecially when the position is very opened.} ({Glenn Flear: 'After'} 32. Ne5 {Glenn Flear: 'if Black decided to play on with' Glenn Flear: 'if Black decided to play on with' The c6 pawn is saved and Black is completely paralyzed. A really beautiful positional win by White and another example of how dangerous it is to play without the center and with a worse development, wspecially when the position is very opened.} Qe8 (32... h5 $2 {loses on the spot to} 33. Nxg6) {Glenn Flear: 'then'} 33. Re7 Qc8 34. Nd7 Qxc6 (34... Rd8 35. Qc3 {with decisive threats.}) 35. Qb2 $18) 1-0


