1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Bc4 c5 8. Ne2 O-O 9. Be3 Nc6 10. Rc1 {Glenn Flear: 'The second most popular move, but perhaps the most tricky.'} (10. O-O {is another story altogether.}) ({The immediate} 10. h4 {can be met by} cxd4 11. cxd4 Qa5+ 12. Kf1 Qa3 13. Bb3 Na5 14. h5 Bd7 {Williams, S-Howell, D British league 2006, with double-edged play.}) 10... Qc7 ({Otherwise} 10... cxd4 11. cxd4 Qa5+ 12. Kf1 Qa3 13. Rc3 Qd6 14. h4 h5 15. f3 {was played in Hawkins, J-Gormally, D Liverpool 2008, see the archives.}) 11. h4 {Glenn Flear: '!?' '!?'} ({More ambitious than returning to the main line with} 11. O-O) 11... Rd8 (11... Qa5 {- 117/159}) ({Getting the queenside in motion with the direct} 11... b5 {seems playable:} 12. Bd3 Rd8 13. Qd2 (13. O-O c4 14. Bb1 e6 (14... Rb8 $1 15. h5 b4 {yields counterplay}) 15. h5 Bb7 16. Qe1 Rac8 {Lorenzo de la Riva, L-Boix Moreno, D Barcelona 2015, Black's play has been somewhat 'routine', and now} 17. e5 {creates some pressure.}) 13... Ne5 $5 14. dxe5 c4 15. Nd4 cxd3 16. f4 Qc4 $1 {Quintiliano Pinto, R-Cori Tello, D Manaus 2013, and Black was better.}) 12. h5 b5 ({Alternatively} 12... e6 13. hxg6 hxg6 14. Bg5 Rd7 15. Bb3 Qa5 16. d5 exd5 17. Bxd5 c4 18. Nf4 Ne5 {Gordievsky, D-Khatoev, E Loo 2015, is OK according to the engines, but that powerful bishop on d5 surely offers White good practical chances.}) 13. Bd5 $146 ({Glenn Flear: 'Varying from a relatively old game which continued'} 13. Bb3 Bb7 14. hxg6 hxg6 15. f3 a5 $5 ({I suggest} 15... c4 $1 16. Bc2 b4 $1 {as this creates some action on the left-hand side of the board, thus distracting White from fueling-up his kingside attack}) 16. a4 cxd4 17. cxd4 Qb6 {Kaufhold, T-Khodadadi, F Germany 1992, which was playable, but perhaps not fully equal. However, note that on move 15 Black can probably improve.}) 13... e6 {Glenn Flear: 'I personally prefer Wei Yi's approach (compare to the note to move 12). Eliminate the bishop and all should be in order!'} 14. Bxc6 Qxc6 15. hxg6 {Glenn Flear: 'Now Black has a difficult choice, which is known from many other analogous positions.'} fxg6 {Glenn Flear: '!?' '!?'} ({Recapturing with} 15... hxg6 {keeps the pawns more compact, but the h-file is then more difficult to protect.}) 16. f3 a5 17. Kf2 Ba6 {Diagram [#] Diagram } (17... Ra7 {(to defend along the seventh rank) looks like a reasonable alternative.}) 18. Qg1 $1 (18. Nf4 Qe8 19. Qb3 c4 20. Qa3 Bb7 (20... e5 21. dxe5 Qxe5 22. Rcd1 $14) 21. Qb2 Bc6 $13) 18... b4 (18... Qc7 $142 19. Bf4 e5 20. Be3 Bf6 21. d5 $14) 19. Qh2 ({After} 19. cxb4 $2 {the Chinese star no doubt intended} Bxe2 $1 {and White's king will be more of a problem than Black's.}) 19... h5 20. Nf4 Qe8 {Glenn Flear: 'There is great tension across the board and it's hard to judge who is better.'} ({After} 20... bxc3 21. Nxg6 Qb5 {White has} 22. d5 $3 Qe2+ 23. Kg3 Qxe3 24. Qxh5 {and Black has no defence! I wonder if the players saw this at the time.}) 21. Qg3 {Glenn Flear: '!' '!'} bxc3 (21... Kh7 22. Qg5 Bh6 23. Qxh6+ $1 Kxh6 24. Nxh5+ g5 25. Nf6+ $18) 22. Nxg6 {Glenn Flear: '!?' '!?'} ({Glenn Flear: 'Fedoseev perhaps saw that'} 22. dxc5 {Glenn Flear: '!' '!' Glenn Flear: 'could be met by'} Rd2+ {Glenn Flear: '!' '!' Glenn Flear: 'but then the complications following'} (22... Qf7 23. Nxg6 Rd2+ 24. Kg1 Re2 25. Ne5 $18) 23. Kg1 {Glenn Flear: '!' '!'} Rad8 (23... Rxa2 24. c6 $1 {seem to be better for White.}) 24. Qg5 $16) 22... cxd4 (22... Qb5 $2 23. Qf4 Rd7 24. Rxh5 $18) 23. Bf4 Qb5 24. e5 $2 {Glenn Flear: '??' '??'} ({Glenn Flear: 'This is the type of position where computers show their superiority over even strong grandmasters. The following variations would have been so hard to calculate at the time, so errors don't come as a surprise. It seems that White is on top after'} 24. Ne5 {Glenn Flear: '!' '!' Glenn Flear: 'as the following computer lines demonstrate:'} Rf8 (24... d3 {Glenn Flear: '!?' '!?'} 25. Qg5 $1 d2 26. Qxh5 $18) (24... Qb2+ 25. Kg1 $18 Rf8 ({or} 25... d3 26. Qg6 $1 Qb6+ 27. Kh2 Rf8 28. Kg3 $1 {and White's attack still gives him the advantage})) 25. Rxh5 Qe2+ (25... Qb2+ 26. Kg1 Ra7 27. Kh2 {Glenn Flear: 'with a very strong attack.'}) 26. Kg1 Rxf4 (26... Ra7 27. Bh6 $18) 27. Qxf4 Qe3+ 28. Qxe3 dxe3 29. Nc6 (29. Rxc3 e2 30. Kf2 Rd8 31. Rc2 Rd1 32. Rxe2 Bxe2 33. Kxe2 $16) 29... Bb7 30. Rc5 Bxc6 31. Rxc6 Bd4 32. Rc4 e5 33. Kf1 $16) 24... Kf7 $2 ({Glenn Flear: 'Correct is'} 24... Qb2+ 25. Kg1 d3 26. Rxh5 d2 {Glenn Flear: 'and Black crashes through  (first!).'} 27. Rd1 (27. Ne7+ Kf8 28. Rh7 dxc1=Q+ 29. Bxc1 (29. Kh2 Qh1+ 30. Kxh1 Qb1+ $19) 29... Qxc1+ 30. Kh2 Qh6+ $1 $19) 27... Qb7 28. Kh2 Bd3 29. Bh6 Bxg6 30. Qxg6 Qf7 $19) 25. Qg5 Qe2+ 26. Kg3 {Glenn Flear: '?' '?'} (26. Kg1 {was apparently the lesser evil, but g3 is the more active square.}) 26... Rd7 {Diagram [#] Diagram } 27. Rxh5 $2 (27. Qxh5 Bd3 $11 28. Nh4+ Kf8 (28... Kg8 29. Ng6 Kf7 $11 (29... Rb7 30. Rhe1 Qxa2 31. Bg5 $13)) 29. Rce1 Qc2 30. Rc1 (30. Bg5 Rb8 {( Rb2) ( b2)} 31. Rc1 Qe2 32. Rce1 $11) 30... Qxa2 31. Ng6+ Kf7 32. Nh4+ $11) 27... Qd3 {Glenn Flear: '!' '!'} 28. Nh4 Rg8 {Glenn Flear: 'Winning a key tempo due to the line-up down the g-file. Now we see why g3 wasn't such a great choice for the king.'} 29. Kh2 Bh8 30. Qh6 Bg7 31. Qg5 Bc4 $19 {Glenn Flear: '!' '!'} 32. Re1 Bf8 $1 {Glenn Flear: 'With the e6-pawn defended Black can hide his king on e8.'} 33. Qf6+ Ke8 34. Bg5 Be7 35. Qh6 Bf8 36. Qf6 Be7 (36... c2 37. Rc1 Be7 $19) 37. Qh6 Bd5 ({Houdini's favourite is} 37... c2) 38. Bf6 Bf8 39. Qf4 Qd2 40. Qxd2 cxd2 41. Rd1 Bb4 {Glenn Flear: 'White's attack has come to nothing and it's just a question of finding the right moment to resign.'} 42. Bg5 Rxg5 $1 43. Rxg5 Bxa2 44. Rg8+ Kf7 45. Rb8 Bb3 46. Rxd2 Bxd2 47. Rxb3 d3 48. Rb1 a4 {and the relentless advance of the pawns decides the issue.} 0-1


