1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Qb3 dxc4 6. Qxc4 O-O 7. e4 Nc6 {The modern main line.} 8. Be2 {The most popular try for White. Given White's difficulties in proving an advantage in the gambit line that follows, perhaps 8.Be3 or 8.Bg5!? (Holt, C (2530)-So, W (2788) Saint Louis USA 2015) deserve further investigation.} ({GCF: I agree that your suggestions do indicate some possible areas for research. Another idea that is worthy of attention is} 8. Bf4 {which has 'surprise value' as well as being quite promising.}) (8. Bf4 Bg4 (8... Nh5 9. Be3 Bg4 10. e5 $14 {as in Lalic, B-Tate, A Pardubice 2015, see the September 2015 update}) 9. d5 Nh5 10. Bg5 Na5 11. Qb4 b6 12. O-O-O {Stocek, J-Stella, A Benasque 2015, with a complex middlegame in prospect.}) 8... e5 $5 {A pawn sacrifice that leads to an interesting (and theoretical) battle.} 9. d5 Nd4 10. Nxd4 exd4 11. Qxd4 c6 12. Qc4 ({The main alternatives are:} 12. Qd1 Re8 13. O-O (13. dxc6 Qxd1+ 14. Nxd1 Nxe4 15. cxb7 Bxb7 16. Be3 Nd6 $44 {1/2-1/2 (68) Kozul, Z (2630)-Sadzikowski, D (2492) Jerusalem 2015}) 13... Nxe4 14. Nxe4 Rxe4 15. dxc6 Rd4 16. Qb3 bxc6 17. Bc4 Qc7 18. Re1 Bf5 19. Bg5 {Sandipan, C-Baron, Ta Benasque 2012, and now} Be4 $1 $11 {is important.  (Flear on ChessPublishing).}) ({And} 12. d6 Re8 13. Qd3 b5 14. f3 (14. a3 Be6 15. f3 Nh5 (15... Bc4 16. Qd1 Bxe2 17. Nxe2 Re6 $11 {(Flear)}) 16. Be3 Be5 17. g3 f5 (17... Qxd6 $11) 18. Bc5 a5 (18... f4 $5 19. g4 Qh4+ 20. Bf2 Ng3 {is unclear}) 19. Rd1 {Dambacher, M-Leenhouts, K Belgian league 2015, and now} Qd7 {keeps matters complicated.}) 14... Re6 15. Be3 Rxd6 16. Qc2 Nh5 {1/2-1/2  (66) Wang, H (2710)-Vachier Lagrave, M (2758) Beijing 2014}) 12... b5 13. Qxc6 ({An alternative here is:} 13. Qb3 {Retreating to b3 (it surveys ...b4, keeps the queen out of harm's way) was covered in the notes of Aronian-Giri, 2015 by Flear:} cxd5 14. exd5 Re8 (14... b4 15. Qxb4 Nxd5 16. Nxd5 Qxd5 17. O-O Qe5 18. Bf3 Rb8 19. Qa4 Qd4 20. Qxd4 Bxd4 21. Rd1 Bg7 22. Be3 Rxb2 23. Bc5 ({new, varying from} 23. Bxa7 Bb7 24. Bxb7 Rxb7 25. Bd4 Ra8 26. g3 Bxd4 27. Rxd4 Ra3 28. Rd2 Rba7 {when White couldn't make any progress, Riemersma, L-Swinkels, R Amsterdam 2013}) 23... Re8 24. Bc6 Rc2 25. Rab1 Bg4 26. Bxe8 Bxd1 27. Rxd1 ({a possible improvement for White here is} 27. Be3 $1 {e.g.} Be2 28. Rb7 Bc4 29. Bxf7+ $1 Bxf7 30. Rb8+ Be8 31. Rxe8+ Kf7 32. Ra8 Bd4 33. a4 Rc6 34. Rd8 Bxe3 35. fxe3 Ke6 {when White's extra pawn gives him an edge, even if a draw is the most likely result}) 27... Rxc5 28. g3 Rc7 {0.5-0.5 Li Zuhao, L-Zelesco, K Melbourne 2014.}) (14... Bb7 $5 {is a more lively try when} 15. Qxb5 Nxd5 $1 {is already equal}) 15. O-O b4 16. Qxb4 Nxd5 17. Nxd5 Rxe2 18. Qc4 Re5 19. Nc7 Be6 20. Nxe6 Rxe6 21. Be3 Bxb2 22. Rab1 Bf6 {1/2-1/2 (46) Zubov, A (2608) -Baron, T (2506) Rishon Le Ziyyon 2015}) 13... Bd7 14. Qd6 Re8 15. f3 {The most recent try for an advantage (and recommended by chess engines.) It leads to a very sharp position where Black has strong compensation due to his active pieces.} ({The most frequently played move has been:} 15. Bg5 $5 {and was indeed what I tried in my own game. However, this line tends to lead to a position where White has a material advantage but Black's active pieces and opposite colored bishops make it difficult to convert.} b4 16. Qxb4 Nxd5 17. Nxd5 Qxg5 18. O-O Rab8 19. Qd6 ({I looked at this alternative} 19. Qc5 {to try to keep more pieces on the board but ultimately it appears to peter out to equality.}) 19... Bh3 20. Nf4 Bg4 21. Bxg4 Be5 22. Qd7 Qxf4 23. g3 Qf6 ({My own game continued:} 23... Qxe4 24. Rae1 Qb4 25. b3 Re7 26. Qd1 Rbe8 27. Bf3 {Here I offered a draw because the ending with the opposite colored bishops looks difficult to convert. 1/2-1/2 (27) Schaefer, B-Whisenhunt, M Training Game 2016 [Schaefer, Bill]}) 24. Rad1 Bxb2 25. Qa4 Red8 26. Rxd8+ Rxd8 27. Qxa7 Kg7 28. Be2 Rd2 29. Qe3 Qc3 30. Qxc3+ Bxc3 31. Bc4 {1/2-1/2 (48) Aronian, L  (2797)-Giri, A (2784) Wijk aan Zee NED 2015 [Glenn Flear]}) 15... Nh5 16. Be3 {Developing and bringing his bishop where it can help defend the weakened e1-h4 dark squares.} ({An important alternative is:} 16. g3 f5 17. Bd3 ({In the June 2012 update, Glenn Flear analyzed:} 17. O-O Bf8 18. Qa6 Bc5+ 19. Kh1 b4 20. Nb5 fxe4 21. d6 $1 {with advantage to White.}) 17... a5 18. Be3 b4 19. Nd1 Nf6 20. e5 Ng4 21. fxg4 Bxe5 22. Qc5 Rc8 23. Qa7 Ra8 24. Qc5 Rc8 25. Qa7 {1/2-1/2 (41) Meier, G (2646) -So, W (2677) Saint Louis 2012}) 16... f5 $1 {Black immediately attacks White's center in view of the somewhat precarious position of White's king.} (16... Be5 17. Qa6 Nf4 18. Bxf4 Bxf4 19. g3 Be3 20. Bxb5 Rb8 21. Bxd7 Qxd7 22. Qd3 Bc5 23. O-O-O Rb4 24. Rd2 Reb8 25. Rc2 Qb7 26. b3 a5 27. Rd1 Qb6 28. d6 Rd4 29. Qe2 Ba3+ 30. Kb1 $16 {but White later went astray in the ending and lost 0-1 (68) Sandipan, C (2590)-Adhiban, B (2547) Moscow 2013}) 17. Qa3 {Places the queen in what seems to be a less vulnerable position.} (17. Qc5 {has the merit of strengthening White's control of the weakened dark squares. However, White's queen is vulnerable to attack.} Rc8 18. Qxa7) 17... b4 $1 {However, Black insists on drawing the queen back to the line of fire and activating his rook. This also makes a possible castling queenside look less inviting.} 18. Qxb4 Rb8 19. Qa3 {White's queen is forced back to a passive square far from the action on the kingside.} fxe4 20. f4 ({Certainly not:} 20. fxe4 $2 Bxc3+ 21. bxc3 Qh4+ 22. Bf2 Qxe4 23. O-O Qxe2 24. Rae1 Qc4 $17) 20... Qh4+ 21. g3 (21. Bf2 Qf6 22. O-O e3 23. Be1 Nxf4 24. Qxa7 (24. Kh1 Qg5 25. Bf3 e2 26. Rg1 Bd4 27. Bg3 Bxg1 28. Rxg1 Bg4 $17) 24... Nxe2+ 25. Nxe2 Qxb2 26. Qxd7 Qxa1 27. Bg3 Qxf1+ 28. Kxf1 Rb1+ 29. Be1 Rf8+ 30. Nf4 Rxf4+ 31. Ke2 Bd4 $11) 21... Nxg3 22. Bf2 (22. hxg3 $2 Qxh1+) 22... Qh3 23. Bxg3 Rec8 24. Bf1 {Here Ding Liren bails out of this sharp position with a draw by repetition.} (24. Rg1 {Preventing Black from entering with the queen on g2.} Bd4 (24... e3) 25. O-O-O Bc5 26. Qa5 Qf5 27. Rg2 Bb4 28. Qxa7 Bc5 29. Qa5 Bb4 30. Qa6 e3 31. Bd3 Rxc3+ 32. bxc3 Qf6 $11) 24... Qg4 25. Be2 Qh3 26. Bf1 Qg4 27. Be2 1/2-1/2


