1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 c5 4. d5 e6 5. Nh3 d6 (5... b5) 6. Nf2 b5 7. e4 Bg7 {The modern main line.} (7... b4 8. a3 a5 9. axb4 (9. dxe6 Bxe6) 9... cxb4 {Here I offered a draw because the ending with the opposite colored bishops looks difficult to convert. 1/2-1/2 (27) Schaefer, B-Whisenhunt, M Training Game 2016 [Schaefer, Bill]} {I looked at this alternative} 10. Be3 {to try to keep more pieces on the board but ultimately it appears to peter out to equality.} {An alternative here is:} Nfd7 {Retreating to b3 (it surveys ...b4, keeps the queen out of harm's way) was covered in the notes of Aronian-Giri, 2015 by Flear:} 11. Nd3 Na6 12. Nd2 (12. Qa4 Nac5 13. Nxc5 dxc5 14. Nd2 Bd6) 12... Bg7) 8. dxe6 {The most popular try for White. Given White's difficulties in proving an advantage in the gambit line that follows, perhaps 8.Be3 or 8.Bg5!? (Holt, C (2530)-So, W (2788) Saint Louis USA 2015) deserve further investigation.} Bxe6 $5 {A pawn sacrifice that leads to an interesting (and theoretical) battle.} 9. cxb5 O-O 10. Be2 d5 11. O-O a6 12. a4 axb5 13. Bxb5 Qb6 (13... Na6 14. Bg5 Qb6 15. Bxf6 (15. Nc3 Nc7 16. e5 Nfe8 17. Be7 {1/2-1/2 (48) Aronian, L  (2797)-Giri, A (2784) Wijk aan Zee NED 2015 [Glenn Flear]} {My own game continued:} Bxe5 18. Bxf8 Kxf8) 15... Bxf6 16. exd5 $1 {with advantage to White.} {The most frequently played move has been:} Rfd8 $5 {and was indeed what I tried in my own game. However, this line tends to lead to a position where White has a material advantage but Black's active pieces and opposite colored bishops make it difficult to convert.} 17. Nc3 Nc7 18. dxe6 (18. Bc6 Rab8 19. Nfe4 Bd4+ 20. Kh1 Nxd5 21. Nxd5 Bxd5 22. Bxd5 Rxd5) (18. Nfe4 Bd4+ 19. Kh1 Nxd5) 18... Rxd1 19. exf7+ Kxf7 20. Raxd1 Bxc3 21. bxc3 Nxb5 22. axb5 Qxb5 23. Ne4) 14. Nc3 dxe4 ({An important alternative is:} 14... d4 15. Ne2 Ne8 (15... Na6 16. Nf4) 16. Nf4 Nd6 17. Nxe6 fxe6 18. Bd3 (18. Be2 {1/2-1/2 (41) Meier, G (2646) -So, W (2677) Saint Louis 2012} {In the June 2012 update, Glenn Flear analyzed:} c4) 18... c4 19. e5 Bxe5 20. Qe2 Nd7 21. Bxc4 Nxc4 22. Qxc4 Rfc8 23. Qe2) 15. Nfxe4 {The most recent try for an advantage (and recommended by chess engines.) It leads to a very sharp position where Black has strong compensation due to his active pieces.} Nxe4 16. Nxe4 {Developing and bringing his bishop where it can help defend the weakened e1-h4 dark squares.} Bd4+ $1 {Black immediately attacks White's center in view of the somewhat precarious position of White's king.} (16... c4+ 17. Kh1 Na6 18. Bd2 Nc7 19. Bc3 Nxb5 20. axb5 Rad8 21. Qc1 Qxb5 22. Nf6+ Kh8 23. Ra5 Qb3 24. Qf4 $16 {but White later went astray in the ending and lost 0-1 (68) Sandipan, C (2590)-Adhiban, B (2547) Moscow 2013}) 17. Kh1 {Places the queen in what seems to be a less vulnerable position.} Nc6 $1 {However, Black insists on drawing the queen back to the line of fire and activating his rook. This also makes a possible castling queenside look less inviting.} (17... Na6 18. Bh6 Rfd8 19. Qe1 Bxb2 20. Rb1 Bd4 21. a5 Qc7 22. Qh4) 18. Bh6 Rfd8 19. Qe1 {White's queen is forced back to a passive square far from the action on the kingside.} Nb4 (19... Na7 20. Qh4 Bd5 (20... Nxb5 $17 21. Nf6+ {has the merit of strengthening White's control of the weakened dark squares. However, White's queen is vulnerable to attack.} Kh8 22. Bf8 h5 23. Qg5) 21. a5 Qe6 22. Bd3) 20. Qh4 Bf5 21. Bg5 Rd5 (21... Rf8 22. Bc4) 22. Bc4 Rd7 23. Rad1 Nc2 24. b3 {Here Ding Liren bails out of this sharp position with a draw by repetition.} (24. Rxd4 Rxd4 (24... Nxd4 25. Nf6+ Qxf6 $17 {Certainly not:} 26. Bxf6 $2) 25. Qh6 Rd6 (25... Rxe4 26. fxe4) 26. Bxf7+ Kxf7 27. Qxh7+ Ke6 28. g4 Rad8 (28... Bxe4 29. Qe7+ Kd5 30. Qxe4#) 29. gxf5+ gxf5 $11 30. Nc3) 24... Na3 25. Bf6 (25. Rxd4) 25... Nxc4 (25... Bxe4 26. Rxd4 (26. Bxd4 cxd4 27. Qxe4 Rad8) 26... cxd4 27. fxe4 Nxc4 28. Qh6 Qxf6 $11 29. Rxf6 d3 $2 30. Rf1 Re8 31. Qh3 (31. bxc4 d2) 31... Ne5) 26. Rxd4 Nd6 27. Qh6 (27. Qxh7+ Kxh7 28. Ng5+ Kg8 29. Rh4) 27... Ne8 {Preventing Black from entering with the queen on g2.} 28. Rxd7 Bxd7 (28... Nxf6 29. Rd6) 29. Be7 1/2-1/2


