{GET TO KNOW THE CHINESE LEAGUE! The Chinese Chess League is getting stronger every year, attracting more and more foreign players. But still it is not very well known in the international chess community. In this article I want to take a closer look at this very interesting tournament with the readers. While the first part will help you get an idea of the event, the second part is a selection of chess material from the 2016 edition. The Chinese Chess League has been successfully running for 12 years now. It contains 12 teams, the 2 teams ranked last are dropped down to Division B, while the 2 top teams from Division B are upgraded. Division A developed from one round-robin to a double round-robin, from one rapid game each team to an almost classical time control and from 10 to 12 teams (22 rounds!). Now we even have a very well-managed and strong Division B, which also attracted top foreign players. Young and talented Chinese players can gain a lot of experience in the League by playing against very famous competition, which is a big opportunity for them. In Division A each team is composed of five players and two reserves. The maximum number of Chinese players that can be registered for the team is seven, but there is no limit for registering foreigners. Boards 1-3 are male players, while Boards 4-5 are female players, plus one reserve each. In the male and female sections, the board order can change. When two foreign competitors have played, the hosting team's foreign player will move automatically to the next board to give Chinese local players more chances to play with foreigners.  There are normally six sessions: Among each session there are three to four rounds of games. Two match points are granted for a win and one for a draw. The time control is 90 minutes plus 30 seconds per move for the whole game. Each round starts at 1 pm and the Zero Tolerance rule applies. To assure the quality of the games, we also require the Sofia rule (draw offer after 30 moves only). The 2016 Chinese Chess League took place in Shen Zhen from April to December. For an idea of how strong the league is, it will be enough to mention that there were 12 players with an Elo rating of 2700 and higher. The winner of the 2016 edition was the Shanghai Team, composed of the following players: Ni Hua, Zhou Jianchao, Lou Yiping, Xu Yi, Ju Wenjun and Zhang Xiaowen from China, reinforced by Pentala Harikrishna, Dmitry Andreikin and Anna Zatonskih. I played for the Shandong Team that earned third place. I will start with our biggest hope, his name is Wei Yi! He is currently the youngest grandmaster in China, and his games are always interesting.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 {Diagram [#]} 6. Nb3 $5 {One of the features of Wei Yi is his approach to the openings. In this game he chooses a line that is not common in the Najdorf, but it is a new and interesting idea. White removes the knight from d4 before Black can play ...e5, threatening it. This makes Black unable to follow the normal routine in the variation.} e6 ({Playing the normal} 6... e5 {wouldn't do any good now, as it enables White to pin the f6-knight and take control over the d5square.} 7. Bg5 Be7 8. Qd3 $36 {. Also, White can decide to develop his bishop through g2.}) ({I think Black should consider playing with 6...g6, arriving at a Sicilian Dragon structure, where ...a6 can also be useful.} 6... g6 $5 7. Be3 Bg7 8. Be2 (8. f3 O-O 9. Qd2 Nc6 10. O-O-O) 8... O-O 9. O-O Nc6 $13) (6... Nbd7 $145 {Kanarek,Marcel 2532 - Wojtaszek,Radoslaw 2713, Polska (ch) 2016 - 128/75}) 7. g4 b5 8. Bg2 {Diagram  [#]} Bb7 ({If Black tries to drive away the white knight prior to attacking e4 his lack of development will result in a strong white attack.} 8... b4 9. e5 d5 10. exf6 bxc3 11. O-O Qxf6 12. bxc3 Ra7 13. Rb1 $40) 9. g5 {Diagram [#]} b4 {A delicate decision in this variation. It would have been better to finish the development first.} (9... Nfd7 10. O-O (10. Be3 Nc6 11. f4 Nb6) 10... Nc6 11. f4 Be7 $132) 10. Nd5 exd5 $146 {Black has no time to keep the position closed.} (10... Nxd5 11. exd5 e5 12. a3 $16 {This is why pushing the b-pawn too early is not good. And the bishop on b7 is badly placed. RR Bartel,Mateusz 2625 - Wojtaszek,Radoslaw 2713, Polska (ch) 2016}) 11. gxf6 dxe4 {Diagram [#]} 12. Qg4 $5 {White’s f6-pawn is like poison in Black’s territory. Black has to deal with it at once, but whichever path he may chose, it will always cause some problem.} ({Now White forces Black to take this poison, but I prefer} 12. Rg1 {Diagram [#]} gxf6 (12... Qxf6 13. Na5 Bc8 14. Bxe4 Ra7 15. Be3 $16) (12... Rg8 13. Bh3 Nd7 14. Bxd7+ Qxd7 15. Bh6 g6 16. Bxf8 Rxf8 17. Qd4) 13. Qh5 $36 {Compared to the actual game, Black suffers even more.}) (12. Be3 gxf6 (12... Nd7 13. fxg7 Bxg7 14. Qxd6 Bxb2 15. Rd1 Bc3+ 16. Bd2 Ne5 17. Bxc3 Qxd6 18. Rxd6 bxc3 $11) 13. Qh5 Rg8 14. Bh3 Nc6 15. O-O-O $40 {Van Foreest,Jorden 2615 - Van Wely,Loek 2667, Nederland (ch-rapid) 2016}) 12... gxf6 {It is better to take with the queen. White gains some activity, but Black’s pawn structure and king safety are guaranteed.} (12... Qxf6 13. Na5 Bd5 (13... h5 14. Qg5 Bc6 15. Nxc6 Qxg5 16. Bxg5 Nxc6 17. Bxe4 $44) 14. Qc8+ Qd8 15. Qxd8+ Kxd8 16. Be3 $44) 13. Be3 h5 {Diagram [#]} 14. Qe2 ({Yi did not give Rui the chance to use the white queen and develop his own pieces, like in case of} 14. Qf5 Qd7 15. Qxf6 Rg8 16. Rg1 $14) 14... Nd7 15. O-O-O $14 {White has two pawns less, but Black`s pawn structure and piece development are not good. White’s position is slightly better.} Qc7 $6 16. Bf4 f5 17. Bh3 O-O-O {Diagram [#]} 18. Rd4 $6 {White should have taken the pawn first, avoiding to trade the dark square bishop and then starting to attack Black`s weaknesses.} (18. Bxf5 Kb8 19. Kb1 $16) 18... Bh6 19. Bxh6 Rxh6 20. Rc4 ({Now White can also take the pawn, but this will allow Black to coordinate his pieces.} 20. Bxf5 d5 $14) 20... Nc5 21. Qe3 Rf6 {Diagram [#]} 22. Qd4 Qe7 23. Rd1 Rd7 24. Nxc5 dxc5 {Diagram [#]} 25. Rxc5+ $6 {White chooses to keep pieces for attacking, but overlooks Black’s counterplay. He should have entered in a rook and bishop ending, where material is equal, but White has more activity and a better pawn structure:} (25. Qxc5+ Qxc5 26. Rxc5+ Kd8 27. Bxf5 {Diagram [#]} Rxd1+ (27... Rdd6 28. Rd2 (28. h4 {is ok for White}) 28... h4 29. Kd1 $16) 28. Kxd1 Ke7 29. Ke2 Kd6 30. Ra5 $16) 25... Kd8 26. Qxb4 {Now it is not easy to go into the same ending.} (26. Qxd7+ Qxd7 27. Bxf5 Qd6 $14 {and Black’s intermediate move prevents the white king from joining the battle.}) 26... Rfd6 $2 ({Black missed a chance to draw:} 26... Rxd1+ 27. Kxd1 {Diagram [#]} e3 $1 28. Qa5+ Ke8 29. Re5 Re6 30. Rxe6 Qxe6 31. Qxf5 Qd6+ 32. Qd3 Bf3+ 33. Ke1 exf2+ 34. Kf1 Qe5 $11 {. Through attacking White’s king, Black reduced some pressure, and now the position is equal.}) 27. Rxd6 Qxd6 28. Qa5+ Ke8 29. Re5+ Re7 ({If Black avoids the rook exchange, he will have to trade his queen and enter into a slightly worse ending:} 29... Kf8 30. Qc5 $16) 30. Rxe7+ Kxe7 31. Qxf5 Qxh2 32. b3 Kf8 {Diagram [#]} 33. Kb2 $2 ({White does not want to play the pure queen and pawn ending and gives Black another opportunity.} 33. Qxh5 Qxf2 34. Qh8+ Ke7 35. Qe5+ Kf8 36. Qb8+ Kg7 37. Qxb7 Qe3+ 38. Kb2 Qxh3 39. Qxe4 $18) 33... Qd6 $6 $138 ({Under time pressure, Black chooses the wrong move. Keeping the h-pawn would have offered drawing chances:} 33... h4 $8 34. Qd7 (34. Qc5+ Ke8) 34... Qe5+ 35. Kb1 Qd5 $11) 34. Qxh5 Qd4+ 35. Ka3 {Diagram [#]} Bd5 $2 {After this move White could stabilize his territory and is heading towards victory.Black should have invaded White`s territory, with practical chances for a draw:} (35... Qc3 36. Qh6+ Kg8 37. Qg5+ Kf8 38. Qd8+ Kg7 39. Qb6 Bc6 40. Bf1 Bb5 41. Bxb5 axb5 42. Qxb5 Qxc2 $16) 36. Qh6+ Ke7 37. Qg5+ f6 38. Qe3 $18 {Diagram [#]} Qd1 39. Qc5+ Ke8 40. Qc8+ Ke7 41. Qc5+ Ke8 42. Bf5 Qc1+ 43. Ka4 Qf4 44. Qxd5 e3+ 45. b4 {Black is lost, and after some meaningless checks, he resigns. Wei Yi had some good ideas in the opening, and got an advantage thanks to powerful play. Although he had some inaccuracies later on, he kept attacking and didn’t allow his opponent to simplify. On his way to victory he found his opponent`s weaknesses and used them well.} 1-0


