bit better for White although he was unable to convert the point in the game: Saric,I  (2668)-Mamedyarov,S (2761) Baku AZE 2016}) (18. Rdf1 O-O-O 19. Rxf7 Qxa2 (19... Rh8 20. Qd3 Qxa2 21. c3 Nd5 $13) 20. c3 Nd5 21. Rxb7 $16) 18... O-O-O 19. Rxf7 Qxa2 20. c3 Qa1+ {Ended in a perpetual for Ter Sahakyan,S (2582)-Hovhannisyan, R (2631) Yerevan ARM 2017} 21. Kc2 Qa4+ 22. Kc1 Qa1+ 23. Kc2 Qa4+ 24. Kc1 Qa1+ {1/2-1/2 Ter Sahakyan,S (2582)-Hovhannisyan,R (2631) Yerevan ARM 2017}) 16... Nf5 {[%emt 0:12:45]} 17. Qf4 {[%emt 0:01:27]} (17. Qf3 Qd5 $11) 17... g5 {[%emt 0:03:42] Moulthun Ly: '!' '!' Moulthun Ly: 'Black needs to dislodge the queen and try to secure the outpost on ...f5 for the knight.' Schandorff,Lars: 'Passive play leads to trouble:'} (17... Qd7 {Schandorff,Lars} 18. g4 Ne7 19. Bd6 Nc8 20. Bc5 b6 21. Ba3 Ne7 22. Rh3 Rd8 23. Rf1 Rf8 {Kokarev,D (2622)-Lintchevski,D (2566) Kazan 2016, and now} 24. Bd6 $1 $16 {would have been hard for Black to get out of.}) (17... a5 18. Ba3 g5 19. Qd2 g4 (19... Qd5 20. Kb1 Qe4 21. Rhe1 Qg4 22. Bc5 $13) 20. Kb1 Qd5 21. Bc5 a4 $11) 18. Qf2 $146 {[%emt 0:07:46] Moulthun Ly: ''N'' Moulthun Ly: 'ChessBase II: 'N''} (18. Qf3 g4 (18... Qd5 $15) 19. Qxg4 Qd5 20. Qh5 O-O-O 21. Rh3 Qxg2 22. Rd2 Qg1+ 23. Rd1 Qg5+ 24. Qxg5 hxg5 25. Rxh8 Rxh8 26. Bc3 g4 27. Rg1 g3 28. Kd2 Rh4 29. Kd3 b5 30. a3 Kd7 31. b3 Rf4 32. Bb2 Rf3+ 33. Ke2 Rf2+ 34. Kd3 g2 35. Bc3 Rf3+ 36. Kd2 Nh4 {0-1 (36) Puranik,A (2475)-Melkumyan,H (2640) Warsaw 2016}) 18... g4 {[%emt 0:01:38] Schandorff,Lars: '!' '!' Moulthun Ly: 'The idea of the last move.' Schandorff,Lars: 'Preventing White from playing g4 himself. '} 19. c4 {[%emt 0:16:52]} (19. Rd3 {Schandorff,Lars} Qd5) (19. Kb1 Qd5 20. b3 O-O-O $11) 19... Qb6 {[%emt 0:11:55] Moulthun Ly: 'is okay for White now.'} (19... a5 {Schandorff,Lars is a possible improvement. A sample line is} 20. Bc5 b6 21. Ba3 Qg5+ 22. Kb1 Qe3 $1 $17) (19... Qg5+ $1 {is better.} 20. Bd2 Qg6 $15) 20. Bc5 {[%emt 0:03:23]} Qa6 {[%emt 0:02:13] Schandorff,Lars: 'A common square for the queen in the Caro-Kann. '} 21. b3 {[%emt 0:00:18]} g3 {[%emt 0:07:07] Moulthun Ly: 'I don't feel this move helps the Black position as much and I would have preferred to keep the pawns on the light squares.'} (21... h5 22. Kb2 Qa5 23. Bd6 O-O-O $132) 22. Qd2 {[%emt 0:05:38]} (22. Qe2 b6 23. Bd6 Nxd6 24. exd6 Qa3+ 25. Kb1 Qxd6 26. Qf3 O-O-O 27. Qxf7 $11) 22... O-O-O {[%emt 0:17:46] Schandorff,Lars: 'The opening has gone excellently for Black. The extra pawn is not that important yet, but it means that White must seek compensation all the time. '} (22... b6 23. Bd6 Nxd6 24. exd6 Qa3+ 25. Kb1 Qxd6 $15) 23. Kb2 {[%emt 0:00:44]} b6 {[%emt 0:05:38]} 24. Bd6 {[%emt 0:00:06]} Nxd6 {[%emt 0:00:09]} 25. exd6 {[%emt 0:00:06]} Rxd6 {[%emt 0:00:06] Moulthun Ly: 'The resulting position is objectively about equal due to Black's loose pawns.'} 26. Qf4 {[%emt 0:14:28]} Rd7 {[%emt 0:03:13]} 27. d5 {[%emt 0:00:28] Schandorff,Lars: '!?' '!?' Moulthun Ly: 'Trying to create complications before Black can consolidate but it should favour Black with accurate play.' Schandorff,Lars: 'The young Chinese player chooses the most active continuation. He could have grapped a pawn here or on the previous move, but true to his style goes for the initiative.'} (27. Qxg3 b5 $132) 27... cxd5 {[%emt 0:07:27]} 28. cxd5 {[%emt 0:00:18]} exd5 {[%emt 0:01:04]} (28... Rhd8 $1 29. Rc1+ Kb7 $36) 29. Qg4 {[%emt 0:01:49] Moulthun Ly: '!?' '!?' Moulthun Ly: 'Only move therefore best.' Schandorff,Lars: 'Black is three pawns up, but it is difficult to untangle his pieces.'} Qb7 {[%emt 0:16:30]} 30. Qf4 {[%emt 0:15:45]} (30. Rc1+ Kb8 31. Qxg3+ Ka8 32. Rxh6 Qb8 $15) 30... Qb8 {[%emt 0:11:11] Schandorff,Lars: '!' '!' Moulthun Ly: 'Starts to become a more serious advantage.'} 31. Qf6 {[%emt 0:00:14]} Kb7 {[%emt 0:00:13]} 32. Rxd5 {[%emt 0:00:08] Moulthun Ly: '!?' '!?'} Rxd5 {[%emt 0:02:02]} 33. Qxf7+ {[%emt 0:00:03]} Kc6 {[%emt 0:02:41] Schandorff,Lars: 'The best chance.'} (33... Qc7 {Schandorff,Lars} 34. Qxd5+ Kb8 35. Rc1 Rd8 $1 36. Qe4 {gave White good compensation.}) 34. Rc1+ {[%emt 0:00:05]} Rc5 {[%emt 0:00:04]} 35. Qf3+ {[%emt 0:00:03]} Kb5 {[%emt 0:05:18]} (35... Kc7 36. Qf4+ Kb7) 36. Qd3+ {[%emt 0:00:19]} Ka5 {[%emt 0:02:22] Schandorff,Lars: 'Forced to avoid the draw. It is not without risk, though, having your king on the wrong side of the pawn shelter. '} 37. Qd4 {[%emt 0:03:29]} Ka6 {[%emt 0:00:23] Moulthun Ly: 'Now Black is unable to escape from the checks and the game ends in a draw.'} (37... Qe8 {Keeps the game going.} 38. b4+ Ka6 39. bxc5 Qb5+ 40. Ka3 Rc8 $15) 38. Qa4+ {[%emt 0:00:05]} Ra5 {[%emt 0:00:31]} (38... Kb7 {Schandorff,Lars} 39. Qe4+ {Moulthun Ly: '=' Moulthun Ly: 'Leads to a draw.'} Kc7 40. Qe7+ Kc6 41. Qe4+ Kd7 42. Rd1+ Kc8 43. Qe6+ Kb7 44. Qe4+ {also ends in a lot of checks, that Black can't really get out of.}) 39. Qc4+ {[%emt 0:00:07]} Rb5 {[%emt 0:00:22]} (39... b5 {Schandorff,Lars} 40. Qe6+ Qb6 41. Rc6 $11) 40. Qa4+ {[%emt 0:00:00]} Ra5 {[%emt 0:00:26]} 41. Qc4+ {[%emt 0:00:26]} Rb5 {[%emt 0:01:20]} 42. Qa4+ {[%emt 0:00:05]} Kb7 {[%emt 0:00:35]} 43. Qe4+ {[%emt 0:00:05] Schandorff,Lars: '!' '!'} (43. Qxb5 {Schandorff,Lars} Qd6 {and Black has chances.}) 43... Ka6 {[%emt 0:00:02] Moulthun Ly: 'White's opening experiment with 16.Bb4!? didn't go according to plan as Black was able to find the correct response. After which White found himself on the back-foot and was perhaps slightly fortunate to escape with the half point. Overall I believe this line is harmless for Black and it may be time for White to consider other alternatives to play for an advantage.'} 1/2-1/2


