1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Bc4 Bg7 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 Nc6 9. h3 Nxd4 ({More common is} 9... Bd7 {with a view to possibly trading knights next time and parking the bishop on c6 e.g.} 10. Bb3 Nxd4 11. Qxd4 Bc6 {That has been looked at on ChessPublishing plenty of times but the text has also had appearances here.}) 10. Qxd4 Be6 11. Bxe6 fxe6 {In playing ...fxe6 Black has created a half-open f-file for himself and has extra control of the d5-square. The obvious drawback is the weakness on e6 and White's next move aims to show just how bad Black's pawn structure might look.} 12. e5 {Given the sheer amount of games that have been played, it is somewhat surprising that there are only 5 examples of this position in Megabase 13.} Nh5 $2 {What is even more shocking is that this is only the second time that this move (a clear mistake) has been played and the first time (mentioned on our site) was also by a player rated over 2600!} ({Our previous conclusion has been that} 12... Nd7 13. Qg4 {is an obvious sequence. Now Black must take on e5 but there is a choice:} Nxe5 (13... Bxe5 14. Qxe6+ Rf7 15. Be3 ({The immediate} 15. Ne4 $1 {is more accurate as it prevents the ...Bxc3 mixer. Now} Nf8 16. Qd5 e6 17. Qb3 {was also better for White in Lampe, D (2272)-Asendorf, J (2280) Germany 2002, Rather than being a strength, those black centre pawns are targets.}) 15... Rc8 $6 ({mixing things up with} 15... Bxc3 $5 {is a better try, my point being that the White knight is too powerful a piece as far as Black's light-squared holes are concerned.}) 16. Ne4 Nf8 17. Qb3 {with a clear advantage to White in Hunt, H (2315)-Delemarre, I (2210) Menorca 1996.}) 14. Qxe6+ Kh8 {when} 15. Ne4 Qc8 16. Qxe7 Qxc2 {would offer Black some action and so maybe 15 Be3 is best and a very slight edge to White.}) 13. g4 $1 {Yep knights on the rim are dim and that one is now trapped!} Bxe5 14. Rxe5 {Necessary of course but certainly good.} dxe5 15. Qxd8 Rfxd8 {Recapturing with the other rook is hardly a significant improvement.} ({Previously I wrote about} 15... Raxd8 16. gxh5 gxh5 {biting the bullet. Sure, Black has 2 pawns to go with his rook for the knight and bishop, but it's not the greatest pawn structure. The following game soon ended when Julian decided he'd had enough:-} 17. Be3 a6 18. Ne4 Rc8 19. c3 Rc4 20. Nd2 Rc6 21. a4 Kf7 {1-0 Emms, J-Hodgson, J Copenhagen 1996.}) 16. gxh5 gxh5 17. Be3 Kf7 18. Kg2 (18. Ne4 {also looks sensible but the key point is that White should preserve his remaining rook.}) 18... a6 19. Ne4 Rac8 20. c3 Rc4 21. Kf3 Rf8 22. Bh6 Rg8 23. b3 Rcc8 24. c4 {This is just all a bit bemusing and I'm still in shock about 12...Nh5?} b5 25. cxb5 axb5 26. a4 Rgd8 27. Be3 Rd3 28. axb5 Rxb3 29. b6 Rc6 30. Nd2 Rb2 31. Rb1 ({Again I reiterate that I would have kept the rook and surely} 31. Ra5 $1 {(or most over rook moves) are better. Still, Black has such lousy pawns that it probably doesn't matter.}) 31... Rxb1 32. Nxb1 Rc4 33. Nd2 Rb4 34. Ke2 {White is still winning, but it's going to take a bit longer.} Ke8 35. Nf3 Rb5 36. Ng5 h6 37. Nxe6 Kd7 38. Nc5+ Kc6 39. Ne4 Rb4 40. Kf3 h4 41. Nd2 Kd5 42. Kg2 Kd6 43. Bxh6 e4 44. Be3 Kd5 45. Kf1 Rb5 46. Ke2 Ra5 47. Bg5 Rb5 48. Bxh4 Rxb6 49. Bxe7 Re6 50. Bg5 Ke5 51. Be3 Re8 52. Bg5 Kf5 53. h4 Ra8 54. Kf1 Ra4 55. Kg2 Ra2 56. Nf1 Kg4 57. Ne3+ Kh5 58. Kg3 Rb2 59. Nd5 Kg6 60. Be3 Kf5 61. h5 Rb5 62. Nc3 Rb8 63. Ne2 Rg8+ 64. Kh3 1-0


