1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 Nc6 8. Qd2 O-O 9. O-O-O d5 {The game that in the last few weeks has featured the highest ELO rating average and in arguably the most critical variation of all.} 10. Qe1 {But here White deviates from the main line of 10 exd5 which theoretically still stands fine for Black.} ({The other relative side-line is} 10. Kb1 {after which} Rb8 {has always struck me as a cute response. It's purpose was illustrated in the recent} 11. h4 e5 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. exd5 cxd5 14. Nxd5 Qxd5 15. Qxd5 Nxd5 16. Rxd5 e4 {of Li, R (2394)-Bodek, M (2425) Saint Louis USA 2015. That queen's rook soon got some action and now} 17. Bd4 exf3 18. gxf3 Bb7 19. Bxg7 Rfe8 20. Re5 Bxf3 21. Bb5 Bxh1 22. Rxe8+ Rxe8 23. Bxe8 Kxg7 24. c4 {was an opposite coloured bishop ending destined for a draw.}) 10... e6 ({Upon} 10... e5 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. exd5 {regular subscribers will know that White has a slight edge after} cxd5 (12... Nxd5 {then is critical with for example} 13. Bc4 Be6 14. Kb1 Rb8 15. Ne4 f5 $5 {being the site annotated Edouard, R (2659) -Jones, G (2661) London Chess Classic Challenge 2014. Just one of several games in that line.}) 13. Bg5 Be6 14. Bc4 Qc7 15. Bxf6 dxc4 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 {although if White gets his move order wrong or gets greedy amongst that sequence there could be serious repercussions.}) 11. Kb1 {The text is I suppose a useful waiting move and in not committing the pawn to h4, White leaves that square free for his queen.} ({Previously on this site we have mainly focused our attention on} 11. h4 {having already concluded that}) (11. g4 $6 {is well met by} e5 {as this time after} 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. exd5 cxd5 14. Bg5 {the weakness of the f3-pawn is exploited by} Bb7) 11... Qe7 $5 {preparing to bring the rook to the d-file instead. Indeed that has received some air time in practice:} ({The main alternative here is} 11... Re8 {, placing the rook on the e-file file in anticipation of an eventual trade on d5. Then we have:} 12. Nb3 (12. g4 Nxd4 (12... e5 13. Nxc6 bxc6 {must also be an option.}) 13. Bxd4 ({Instead} 13. Rxd4 e5 14. Rxd5 $5 Nxd5 15. Nxd5 {looks like an interesting exchange sacrifice.}) 13... e5 14. Bf2 d4 15. Bb5 Rf8 16. Ne2 Be6 17. Nc1 a6 18. Ba4 Nd7 {which saw Black get have the better of an eventual draw in Lupulescu, C (2574)-Grecescu, G (2383) Predeal 2007.}) 12... Qc7 ({Instead} 12... b6 13. g4 Qc7 14. g5 Nh5 15. Bb5 a6 16. Bxc6 Qxc6 17. Bd4 dxe4 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. Nxe4 e5 20. Rd6 Qc7 {offered about equal chances but with} 21. Nf6 $6 Nxf6 22. gxf6+ Kh8 23. Qd2 Bf5 {had seen Black gain the upper hand in Hunt, H (2385)-Ferguson, M (2360) Hastings 1995.}) 13. Qh4 ({Needless to say} 13. exd5 $6 Nxd5 14. Nxd5 exd5 15. Rxd5 $2 {is completely out of the question given the e-file pin e.g.} Bh6 16. Rd3 Qb6 {Besides the text was always White's idea with Bg5 being prepared next to exert some pressure.}) 13... dxe4 14. fxe4 b6 $6 {with advantage White. Optimistically Black might point out that he has a solid pawn structure and potential for pressure against White's isolated e-pawn. However I think that the reality of the weak square on d6 and the looseness of the knight on f6 means that even without this move, the initiative was most certainly with White in Spraggett, K (2595) -Gerber, R (2408) Geneve SUI 2012.}) ({Finally there is nothing especially crafty about} 11... e5 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. exd5 cxd5 14. Bg5 Be6 15. Bc4 Qc7 16. Bxf6 dxc4 17. Bxg7 Kxg7 {It is merely the same position that we have previously assessed as a slight edge to White but with the king on b1 rather than c1. There are pros and cons of this but with all things considered it probably doesn't change the assessment!}) 12. Bg5 ({Alternatively} 12. Nb3 Rd8 13. Bc5 Qc7 14. Bb5 ({14 Nb5 Qe5 doesn't achieve much whilst} 14. exd5 Nxd5 15. Nxd5 exd5 16. Qh4 Bf5 {left Black pretty active with pressure against c2 in Klima, L (2420)-Ralis, P (2239) Stare Mesto 2009.}) (14. Nb5 Qe5) 14... dxe4 15. Rxd8+ Nxd8 16. Nxe4 Nxe4 17. Qxe4 Bd7 18. Bxd7 Qxd7 19. Bd4 {and Black hadn't been tested in the drawn game Ivanchuk, V (2705) -Georgiev, K (2660) Tilburg 1993.}) ({Although one of the main plans, it should be noted how} 12. Qh4 $2 {walks into the tactic} Nxe4 $1 13. Qxe7 Nxc3+) 12... h6 13. Bh4 (13. Bxf6 $2 Qxf6 {would naturally be better for Black. White must preserve his dark-squared bishop so that it can ultimately challenge the Dragon one.}) 13... Nxd4 14. Rxd4 Qc5 ({Upon} 14... g5 $6 15. Bf2 {the power of the discovered attack will have been nullified whereas Black may regret those pawn advancements on the kingside.}) 15. Rd1 dxe4 ({This ultimately works out okay but it isn't totally necessary for Black to seek such clarification. For example} 15... a6 {preparing ...b5 seems plausible as attempts to win that d5-pawn won't work out too well e.g.} 16. Bxf6 ({or} 16. exd5 Nxd5) 16... Bxf6 17. exd5 Bxc3 18. Qxc3 Qxc3 19. bxc3 exd5 20. Rxd5 Be6 {It's half a pawn at best with Black having adequate activity.}) 16. Bxf6 (16. Nxe4 Nxe4 17. fxe4 {is of no concern to Black who could either fianchetto his queen's bishop or possibly park it on e6 after ...e5.}) 16... Bxf6 17. Nxe4 Qe5 18. Nxf6+ {Always the intention was to grab this bishop but the mate threat on b2 accelerated matters.} Qxf6 19. h4 {Pausing here to assess, Black has a solid structure and it's basically a question of whether he can develop his bishop and involve his rooks before White gets anything serious going.} b6 20. h5 g5 21. Qe4 Rb8 22. Bd3 Rd8 {The point. The black queen is effectively deputising for the Dragon bishop. As h6 and h8 are under her majesty's control, Black need not fear the check on h7.} 23. Qh7+ Kf8 24. Bg6 {Rather visual but against careful defence not helping White's cause. Of course White could simply retreat his queen but Black should be fine.} Bd7 ({This or either of the other two bishop moves were best, basically ignoring White's shenanigans! Accepting White's offering through} 24... fxg6 $2 {would have been disastrous e.g.} 25. Rxd8+ Qxd8 26. Qxh6+ Kg8 27. hxg6 Qf6 28. Qh7+ Kf8 29. Qc7 Ra8 30. Rh8+ Qxh8 31. Qf7#) 25. Bd3 {Admitting that he wasn't going anywhere but now Black gets some ideas of going for a win.} Bc6 26. Be4 Bb5 27. Bd3 Bc6 28. Be4 Ba4 {Yep, avoiding the repetition and good on Black, although to be fair it's still about equal.} 29. b3 Ke7 $5 {Crafty! If White takes the bishop, then a .. .Rh8 will trap the queen.} 30. Bd5 $6 {Enabling the queen to retreat along the diagonal. I can't see why he didn't just drop it back to d3 but anyway, with both bishops en prise, it's all fun and games!} Rxd5 31. Rxd5 exd5 32. bxa4 Rc8 {With those shattered white queenside pawns and an equally exposed king, it's definitely advantage Black now although winning is another matter.} 33. Re1+ Kf8 34. Qd3 Rc5 35. Re3 Kg7 36. a3 Ra5 37. Qb3 Qd4 38. Rd3 Qxa4 39. Qb2+ $6 ({Presumably White didn't fancy defending} 39. Qxa4 Rxa4 40. Rxd5 Rxa3 41. Rd7 {but that rook and pawn ending must have offered reasonable drawing chances.}) 39... f6 40. Rb3 {Now White is a pawn down but rather passive.} Qe8 41. g4 Qe1+ 42. Ka2 Rc5 43. Rd3 Qe2 44. Kb1 a6 {Bringing ...Rb5 into play.} 45. a4 Qf1+ 46. Ka2 Qf2 $2 ({Rather a shame. Instead} 46... Rc4 $1 {would have kept White seriously under the pump.}) 47. c3 $1 {Now snatching at the opportunity to get a rook and pawn ending.} Qxb2+ 48. Kxb2 Kf7 49. Kc2 a5 50. Rd1 Ke6 51. Kd3 Ke5 52. Re1+ Kf4 53. Re6 Kxf3 54. Rxf6+ Kxg4 55. Rxh6 b5 {But now too many pawns are coming off.} 56. Ra6 1/2-1/2


