1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 dxe5 5. Nxe5 c6 6. Be2 Bf5 7. O-O Nd7 8. Nf3 e6 9. c4 N5f6 $1 ({Going for the exchange with} 9... Nb4 10. a3 $1 {leaves White on top, as shown by Tom Rendle in his notes to Z.Hracek - R.Appel, Bundesliga 2013 (1-0 in 31).}) 10. Nc3 Ne4 $5 {A logical move (trading pieces in a position with less space), which has resulted in six draws from six games in my database.} ({By far the most popular move is} 10... Bd6 {but White has a decent score there.}) 11. Qb3 {Logically targeting the weakness on b7.} (11. Bd3 Nxc3 12. bxc3 Bxd3 13. Qxd3 Bd6 14. Ng5 Nf6 15. Re1 O-O 16. Qh3 Re8 {and Black had equalised in R.Yu - A.Shimanov, Katowice 2014 (1/2-1/2 in 35).}) (11. Nxe4 Bxe4 12. Bf4 (12. Ng5 Bg6 13. d5 e5 14. Bd3 {was agreed drawn in Y. Zinchenko - V.Sergeev, Alushta 2005, though Black still needs to fully equalise.}) 12... Be7 13. Re1 O-O {was G.Papp - G.Schroll, Austria 2011 (1/2-1/ 2 in 44), and now} 14. Bd3 Bxd3 15. Qxd3 {looks like an edge for White.}) 11... Nxc3 (11... Qc7 {was tried in M.Luch - P.Shkapenko, Jastrzebia Gora 2015 (1/ 2-1/2 in 25). Here I like grabbing the bishop pair with} 12. Nh4 $14 {, which might transpose to the game.}) 12. bxc3 Qc7 13. Nh4 Be4 {Trying to provoke f3, in order to slightly disturb White's co-ordination and prevent Bf3.} (13... Bg6 14. g3 b6 15. Nxg6 hxg6 16. a4 Bd6 17. a5 O-O 18. Be3 $16 {was similar in H. Steingrimsson - V.Sveshnikov, Bratto 2014 (1/2-1/2 in 45)}) 14. Re1 Be7 15. Bf1 Nf6 16. f3 Bg6 17. g3 b6 18. a4 O-O 19. Nxg6 {Instructively, Wei Yi waited for Black to castle before playing this, since otherwise Black might consider generating counterplay down the h-file.} hxg6 20. a5 c5 21. Be3 (21. d5 {looks more convincing. Black should probably go for} exd5 22. cxd5 Bd6 23. Bd2 {with an enduring edge for White.}) 21... cxd4 22. cxd4 bxa5 $1 {Black has made a number of significant structural decisions, but he now (temporarily) has an extra pawn and the possibility of pressure on the white centre.} 23. c5 {Otherwise the black bishop can land on b4, but now Black gets the d5-square for his knight.} Nd5 24. Bf2 Rab8 {Black has managed to solve his opening problems and brings the position to safety.} 25. Qa3 Bd8 26. f4 Rb4 27. Bg2 Qb8 28. Bxd5 exd5 29. Qf3 Bf6 30. Red1 a4 31. Qxd5 Rd8 32. Qe4 Qb5 33. c6 Rc4 34. Rdc1 Bxd4 $1 {Liquidating to a draw.} 35. Bxd4 Rdxd4 36. Qxd4 Rxd4 37. c7 Rc4 38. c8=Q+ Rxc8 39. Rxc8+ Kh7 40. Rc3 Qb6+ 41. Kh1 Qb7+ 42. Kg1 Qb6+ 43. Kh1 Qb7+ 44. Kg1 Qb6+ {10...Ne4 keeps its excellent record, and against a very dangerous opponent. Black is certainly solid in this line.} 1/2-1/2


