{It's important to point out that this game was played at a classical time control, although obviously Nepo played a lot of rapid and blitz in Moscow.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Nd7 4. d4 cxd4 5. Qxd4 a6 6. Bxd7+ Bxd7 7. Nc3 e5 8. Qd3 h6 9. Nd2 Rc8 10. Nc4 Be6 (10... Qc7 {was played in S.Fedorchuk – R. Ponomariov, Spanish Team Championship 2011 (1-0 in 25) which I annotated in the Archives.}) 11. Ne3 Nf6 12. O-O (12. a4 {could transpose but led to original positions after} Qb6 $5 13. O-O Be7 14. Rd1 O-O 15. Bd2 Qd4 $5 16. Be1 Qxd3 17. Rxd3 $11 {R.Rapport - M.Lagarde, Karlsruhe 2018. Black always has enough counterplay on the c-file to hold the balance in such endgames.}) 12... Be7 (12... Qc7 13. a4 Be7 {is less flexible since the queen is committed to c7 (while Nepo prefers to place it on d7). This setup cuts out b3 and Bb2 but that doesn't seem like a serious option anyway.} 14. Rd1 O-O 15. Bd2 (15. Qe2 Qc5 16. Qf3 b5 17. axb5 axb5 18. Ra5 Bd7 $13 {N.Vignesh - J.Santos Latasa, Sharjah 2017 (1/2-1/2 in 52)}) 15... Rfd8 16. Be1 Rd7 17. a5 h5 18. h3 $11 {T.Gharamian - K.Sasikiran, Germany 2017 (1/2-1/2 in 28).}) (12... Qb6 13. b3 Be7 14. Bb2 O-O 15. Kh1 Qc5 16. f4 $6 {was agreed drawn in M.Munoz Pantoja - K. Oliva Castaneda, Sabadell 2016, a result which would have been more logical after a normal 16th move like 16. Ncd5.}) 13. a4 (13. Rd1 O-O 14. Bd2 Rc5 (14... b5 $5 {P.Velicka - V.Babula, Ostrava 2016 (1/2-1/2 in 65)}) 15. a4 Qc8 16. Be1 Rd8 $11 {was played in V.Anand - G.Kasparov, Saint Louis 2017 (1/2-1/2 in 31). Kasparov, who once dubbed 3.Bb5+ the choice of the "Pepsi generation", had worse career statistics in this line than his (awesome) results in Open Sicilians, but he had no problems in this game.}) 13... O-O 14. a5 Qd7 15. Bd2 Bd8 $5 ({Varying from his game with Duda in Dortmund 2018, where White was better after} 15... Rfd8 16. Rfd1 Bf8 17. Be1 Rc6 18. Na4 Qe8 19. c4 $16 {The draw in 58 moves was proof of Nepo's tactical resourcefulness/ swindling ability rather than the soundness of his position.}) 16. Ncd5 ({White retains chances for an edge after less committal play like} 16. Rfd1 {but this is a different game.}) 16... Nxd5 17. exd5 (17. Nxd5 f5 $132 {is very comfortable for Black.}) 17... Bg4 {A safe move, after which the game peters out. White doesn't want to get involved in a race between his queenside play and Black's kingside play.} 18. f4 ({The engine slightly prefers White after the subtle} 18. Rac1 {followed by the standard c4, b4 and c5 play. As Magnus has shown recently, Black has good practical chances in this structure even in objectively dubious versions. The point of the mysterious rook move is that} Bh5 {is well met by} (18... Bg5 $5 $13) 19. Qf5 $1 $14) ({By contrast,} 18. c4 Bh5 $1 {is quite comfortable for Black.}) 18... exf4 19. Nxg4 Qxg4 20. Bxf4 Re8 $5 (20... Qg6 $1 $11 {was quite safe.}) 21. Rf3 (21. Bxd6 Re2 22. Rf2 Rxf2 23. Kxf2 Qh4+ 24. Kg1 Bxa5 $1 $11 {is a nice shot.}) 21... Bf6 22. c3 Be5 23. h3 Qh4 24. Ra4 Bxf4 ({Black is not worse after} 24... Rc5 {but the rook endgame doesn't hold may dangers either.}) 25. Raxf4 Qe1+ 26. Rf1 Qe2 27. Qxe2 (27. Qf3 {doesn't change much:} Qxb2 28. Rxf7 Qxc3 29. Rxb7 Qd4+ 30. Kh1 Qe5 $11) 27... Rxe2 28. Rb4 Rc7 29. Rf2 Re1+ 30. Rf1 Re2 31. Rf2 Re1+ 1/2-1/2


