1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. c3 Nf6 5. Qe2 {A rare line, which I covered in I.Smirin - P.Eljanov, Netanya Masters 2019 (0-1 in 55).} Bg7 6. d4 cxd4 7. cxd4 O-O {Wei Yi plays provocatively, allowing either of his knights to be attacked.} 8. d5 (8. Nc3 d5 $1 9. e5 Ne4 10. O-O Nxc3 11. bxc3 Na5 $132 {A.Velea - A.Yedigaryan, Porto Carras 2018 (0-1 in 33).}) 8... a6 $1 (8... Nb8 9. Nc3 d6 $14 {is passive: M.Bartel - K.Bryzgalin, Warsaw 2011 (1-0 in 45).}) (8... Nb4 9. Nc3 d6 {O.Guigon - K.Roser, Le Port Marly 2014 (1/2-1/2 in 23)} 10. O-O $14) 9. Bd3 Nb4 10. Bd2 ({White doesn't have time for} 10. Bc4 $2 e6 $1 11. dxe6 dxe6 12. O-O b5 13. Bb3 $2 (13. a3 bxc4 14. axb4 Qd3 $15) 13... Qd3 $17 {P.Shuvalova - O.Nechaev, Sochi 2015 (0-1 in 43).}) 10... Nxd3+ 11. Qxd3 d6 $11 {Black can have no complaints from the opening, with two bishops and no weaknesses.} 12. O-O e6 13. dxe6 Bxe6 {This structure of e4 vs. d6 arises in the Spanish, but this looks like a pretty good version for Black. White can't be worse, but I don't think he's better.} 14. Re1 Nd7 15. Nc3 Ne5 16. Nxe5 dxe5 17. Nd5 f5 18. f3 fxe4 ({Engines prefer maintaining the tension with} 18... Rf7 {, though it's hard to tolerate the d5-knight for long.}) 19. fxe4 Bxd5 20. exd5 {Although the position remains equal, White's game has become easier to handle, with a passed d-pawn which looks more threatening than its counterpart on e5.} Qd6 21. Qb3 Rfd8 22. Bg5 Rd7 23. Rad1 h6 {Again disliked by the engine, but I don't see how Black is meant to tolerate the g5-bishop indefinitely.} 24. Be3 Rc8 25. Bb6 Kh7 26. a4 Rf8 27. a5 Rdf7 28. Rc1 Re8 29. Re4 Rf4 30. Qd3 Rf7 31. b4 {Aronian is playing beautifully and is exerting some pressure on Black's position.} Rd7 32. h3 h5 33. Rec4 Bh6 (33... Qxd5 34. Qxd5 Rxd5 35. Rc7 Kg8 36. Rxb7 e4 37. Rcc7 $14) 34. Rf1 Bf4 35. Re4 Rc8 36. g3 Bh6 37. Bc5 Qxd5 (37... Rxc5 38. bxc5 Qxc5+ 39. Kh2 Rxd5 40. Rf7+ Bg7 41. Qf3 Rd2+ 42. Re2 Qxa5 43. Rxb7 Qa2 44. Rxd2 Qxd2+ 45. Qg2 Qxg2+ 46. Kxg2 {and Black makes a draw even without the a- and e-pawns.}) 38. Qxd5 Rxd5 39. Rf7+ Kg8 40. Rxb7 Bf8 41. Bxf8 Rxf8 42. Re2 Rd3 43. Kh2 e4 44. Rb6 Kg7 45. Rxa6 Rff3 46. Re6 Rxg3 47. a6 Rxh3+ 48. Kg1 Ra3 49. b5 Rhb3 50. Rb6 h4 51. Rb7+ Kh6 52. a7 Rg3+ 53. Rg2 Rh3 54. Rg4 $2 {Finally the time control reveals itself, after pretty high quality play.} (54. Re2 $11 {was one of several moves to hold the balance.}) 54... Kh5 $2 ({The win was far from straightforward.} 54... Ra1+ 55. Kg2 (55. Kf2 Rf3+ 56. Ke2 Ra2+ 57. Ke1 Rh3 58. Rg1 Rhh2 $19) 55... Re3 $3 56. Kh2 (56. Rxh4+ Kg5 57. Rh8 Re2+ {and 58...Ra3#}) 56... Ree1 $3 $19 {, and the lines continue. I challenge anyone to find this even at a classical time control.}) 55. Rxe4 Rag3+ 56. Kf1 Rh1+ 57. Ke2 Rh2+ 58. Kd1 Ra3 59. Rxh4+ Rxh4 60. Rh7+ Kg5 61. Rxh4 Rxa7 $1 {The best move, even if the tablebases don't see a difference.} (61... Kxh4 62. b6 {is, remarkably, still a draw.} g5 $1 63. b7 Rxa7 64. b8=Q Ra4 $1 {and the rook gets to f4, with a fortress.}) 62. Rb4 Kf6 1/2-1/2


