1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 d5 3. d4 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 {A rare line, which I covered in I.Smirin - P.Eljanov, Netanya Masters 2019 (0-1 in 55).} c6 6. Qc2 Be7 7. e3 Nbd7 {Wei Yi plays provocatively, allowing either of his knights to be attacked.} 8. Bd3 h6 $1 9. Bh4 Nh5 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. O-O-O Nb6 $11 {Black can have no complaints from the opening, with two bishops and no weaknesses.} 12. Nf3 (12. h3) 12... Bg4 13. Kb1 Nf6 {This structure of e4 vs. d6 arises in the Spanish, but this looks like a pretty good version for Black. White can't be worse, but I don't think he's better.} 14. Rc1 Nfd7 15. Ka1 O-O-O 16. Nd2 Kb8 17. Na4 (17. Rhe1) 17... Nxa4 18. Qxa4 Qh4 (18... Qf6 19. Rhf1 Bf5) 19. Rcf1 Qf6 20. Qc2 {Although the position remains equal, White's game has become easier to handle, with a passed d-pawn which looks more threatening than its counterpart on e5.} Rc8 (20... Bh5) 21. Nb3 Rc7 22. Rc1 Rhc8 23. h3 Be6 {Again disliked by the engine, but I don't see how Black is meant to tolerate the g5-bishop indefinitely.} 24. Rhf1 (24. f4) 24... h5 (24... c5 25. Nxc5 Nxc5 26. dxc5 Rxc5 27. Qxc5 Rxc5 28. Rxc5 Qg5 29. g3 Bxh3 30. Rfc1) 25. f4 g6 (25... Nb6 26. f5 Bd7 27. Nc5 (27. Qf2)) 26. f5 gxf5 (26... Bxf5 27. Bxf5 gxf5 28. Rxf5 (28. Qxf5 Qxf5 29. Rxf5 Rg8) 28... Qg6 29. Qf2) 27. g4 hxg4 28. hxg4 Nb6 29. gxf5 Bd7 30. Nc5 Re8 31. Rce1 {Aronian is playing beautifully and is exerting some pressure on Black's position.} (31. Qf2) 31... Qd6 32. a3 (32. Rg1 $14) (32. Qf2 Bc8 $1 (32... f6 33. e4 Bc8 34. e5 fxe5 $132 {A.Velea - A.Yedigaryan, Porto Carras 2018 (0-1 in 33).} 35. Qg3 Nc4 36. Bxc4 dxc4 37. Na4) 33. f6) 32... Bc8 33. Qf2 Nd7 (33... f6 34. Rh1 Rce7 {O.Guigon - K.Roser, Le Port Marly 2014 (1/2-1/2 in 23)}) 34. e4 dxe4 35. Nxe4 Qf8 (35... Qd5 $15 36. Bb1) (35... Qh6 36. Qg3 $14 {is passive: M.Bartel - K.Bryzgalin, Warsaw 2011 (1-0 in 45).}) 36. Rg1 Rd8 37. Qh2 (37. f6 {and Black makes a draw even without the a- and e-pawns.} Nb6 38. Rg7 Rcd7 39. Bc2 (39. Ng5 Rxd4 $2 40. Nxf7 $17 {P.Shuvalova - O.Nechaev, Sochi 2015 (0-1 in 43).} Rxd3 41. Nxd8 Qxd8) 39... Rxd4 40. Bb3 R4d7 41. Ng5 $14 {Engines prefer maintaining the tension with} Nd5 {, though it's hard to tolerate the d5-knight for long.} {White doesn't have time for} 42. Bxd5 $2 Rxd5 $1 (42... cxd5 43. Qd4) 43. Nxf7) 37... Qh8 38. Qxh8 (38. Qf2 Nf6) 38... Rxh8 39. Rg7 Nb6 40. Nf6 Rd8 (40... Rh6) 41. Rg4 (41. Bb1 Rxd4 42. Ne8 Rcd7 43. Nf6 Rd8 44. Rxf7) 41... c5 42. Ne8 (42. dxc5 Rxc5 (42... Rxd3 43. cxb6 axb6 44. Re8 Rc1+ 45. Ka2 Kc7) 43. Bb1 Bxf5 $19 44. Rg5 $11 {was one of several moves to hold the balance.}) 42... Rcd7 43. dxc5 Rxd3 44. cxb6 axb6 (44... Bxf5 $3 $19 {, and the lines continue. I challenge anyone to find this even at a classical time control.} 45. bxa7+ Kxa7 46. Rgg1 Rd2 {and 58...Ra3#} 47. Nf6 R8d4 48. Rgf1 Be6) 45. Rf4 R8d5 46. Ref1 Rd1+ 47. Rxd1 Rxd1+ 48. Ka2 Rd5 49. Ng7 Bd7 50. Kb3 Kc7 51. Re4 Kd6 52. Ne8+ Kc6 ({The win was far from straightforward.} 52... Bxe8 53. Rxe8 Rxf5 $3 54. Rb8) 53. Ng7 Rd3+ 54. Kb4 $2 {Finally the time control reveals itself, after pretty high quality play.} Rg3 $2 55. Rc4+ Kd6 56. Rd4+ Kc7 57. Nh5 Rg2 58. Nf6 Bc6 (58... Bxf5 59. Nd5+ Kb8 60. b3 $1 {and the rook gets to f4, with a fortress.}) 59. b3 b5 60. Ng4 Re2 61. Nh6 Be8 $1 {The best move, even if the tablebases don't see a difference.} 62. Ng4 Bd7 63. Nh6 Be8 {is, remarkably, still a draw.} 64. Ng4 $1 1/2-1/2


[Event "Chinese Mind Games, Zaozhuang"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "2015.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Zhao Jun"]
[Black "Wei, Yi"]
[Result "0-1"]
[ECO "B33"]
[Annotator "Cyrus Lakdawala"]
[PlyCount "72"]
[EventDate "2015.??.??"]
[EventType "game"]
[SourceTitle "Sicilian Sveshnikov MBM"]
[Source "Everyman Chess"]
[SourceDate "2016.08.01"]

1. e4 c5 {When the young buck challenges the authority of an older leader, the herd watches. At the time of this writing, the 16-year old Chinese prodigy  (current FIDE rating: 2721!) is, in my opinion, an odds-on favourite to challenge Magnus Carlsen for the world title within the next ten years.} 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nd5 Be7 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. c4 b4 12. Nc2 O-O 13. Be2 {No fianchetto this time. --- QUESTION: What are the differences between playing Be2 and fianchettoing? --- ANSWER: With 13 Be2: -- 1. White saves a move by developing the bishop at once. -- 2. White avoids weakening the h3- and f3-squares. -- 3. White allows a potential black kingside build-up with ideas like ...Qh4. -- 4. White's chances of an f2-f4 break go down considerably. --- When White fianchettoes: -- 1. White can seize control over the critical g5-square with a future h2-h4. -- 2. White can meet Black's ...g6-g6 (and ...f7-f5) plan with h4-h5, threatening to open the h-file with h5xg6. --- Conclusion: I don't believe that either version is better than the other, and the one White picks is a matter of taste.} a5 ({In Negi-Kryvoruchko Black plays} 13... Bg5 {first, after which} 14. O-O a5 {would transpose below. --- QUESTION: Why isn't b4 hanging? --- ANSWER: Patience. We look at this very possibility in the next game.}) 14. O-O Bg5 {Black immediately seizes upon the fact that White hasn't played h2-h4 to post his dark-squared bishop on a good diagonal.} 15. Qd3 {A logical move, which prepares to put a rook to d1, while watching the b3-square.} ({Playing to exchange light-squared bishops with} 15. Bg4 {doesn't bother Black, who can simply respond} Be6 {. This obviously discourages Bxe6, since Black then seizes control over d5. G.Kamsky-T.Radjabov, Beijing (rapid) 2013, continued} 16. Bxe6 $5 {(hey, I said: "obviously discourages Bxe6")} fxe6 17. Nde3 Qe7 18. Qe2 $5 ({I would prefer} 18. Qd3 {, retaining control over d4}) 18... a4 ({or} 18... Nd4 {with a slight edge}) 19. b3 Rfb8 20. g3 Ra5 21. Ng2 Rba8 {and Black exerts mild pressure.}) 15... Be6 16. Rad1 ({The f1-rook can be posted to d1 too; for example,} 16. Rfd1 Rc8 17. Nde3 Bxe3 18. Qxe3 Qc7 19. Rd2 Rfd8 20. Rad1 Nb8 $1 {(intending to redeploy to the more active c5-square)} 21. b3 Na6 22. f4 f6 {and Black stood no worse, I.Nepomniachtchi-Wang Yue, Russia-China blitz match, Sochi 2009.}) 16... Ra7 {A useful deployment, which enables Black to reinforce the backward d6-pawn from d7, as well as to double heavy pieces on a queenside file at any opportune moment.} 17. b3 ({Or similarly} 17. Bf3 g6 18. Qe2 Qb8 19. b3 a4 20. Qd3 Ra5 21. Nde3 {½-½ A.Motylev-B.Grachev, FIDE World Cup, Baku (2nd rapid tie-break game) 2015. I slightly prefer Black at the end there.}) 17... Rd7 18. Bf3 {Nimzowitsch would be impressed with White's overprotection of d5, but I ask: Is White's control over d5 bothering Black in any way? I don't see how it is.} Nb8 $5 {Destination c5.} 19. a3 $5 {A new move which turns the queenside into a warring republic with no ruling authority. --- QUESTION: Is it in White's favour to open the queenside? --- ANSWER: White logically assails b4, hoping to gain some queenside traction by exploiting Black's knight retreat. However, this plan does help Black in one way: it opens the position for his bishop pair.} ({Previously, White played exclusively on the kingside:} 19. g3 {(aiming for an f2-f4 break)} Na6 20. Qe2 Nc5 21. Nce3 g6 22. Bg2 {, V.Kovalev-O.Ladva, European Rapid Championship, Warsaw 2011, and now} Bh6 23. f4 exf4 24. gxf4 Re8 {leaves the game dynamically balanced.}) 19... bxa3 20. Nxa3 Na6 $6 {I prefer White's position after this.} ({Seeing that the situation on the queenside has changed, Black should backtrack with} 20... Nc6 $1 {, retaining control over d4 and b4.}) 21. Nb5 $2 {When we pick an aggressive plan and then hesitate, we demand the privilege of ownership, without the commitment of paying for it. With one move White goes from better to worse.} ({He should play the more accurate} 21. Qc3 $1 {(allowing him to recapture on d5 with the rook)} Nc5 22. Nb5 g6 23. g3 Bh6 24. Bg2 {, when I think Black stands slightly worse due to the weaknesses at d6 and a5.}) 21... Bxd5 $1 22. cxd5 $6 ({Not} 22. Qxd5 $4 {, which self-traps the queen after} Nb4 {.}) ({Instead,} 22. exd5 {is probably the lesser evil, even if it does allow Black to activate his kingside pawn majority with} f5 {.}) 22... Rb7 $1 {Now White experiences serious issues in the protection of b3.} 23. Be2 ({Or} 23. Qc4 Qd7 24. Nd4 Nc5 25. Nc6 Rxb3 {might be played as well, since} (25... Nxb3 {and Black wins a pawn;} 26. Z0 (26. Z0)) 26. Nxe5 ({not} 26. Nxa5 $4 Rxf3 $1 {and wins}) 26... dxe5 27. Qxc5 {can be met by the temporary sacrifice} Rc8 28. Qxa5 Rxf3 $1 29. gxf3 Qh3 30. Rd2 {(returning the exchange is the only defence)} Bf4 31. Rfd1 Bxh2+ 32. Kh1 Bf4+ 33. Kg1 Bxd2 34. Qxd2 Qxf3 {with a clear advantage in the endgame.}) 23... Qb8 24. Ra1 ({After} 24. Nc3 Nc5 25. Qf3 Rxb3 {, Black has an extra pawn and White's knight is caught in a painful pin.}) {EXERCISE  (combination alert): White complies under duress. How did Black win material? --- ANSWER: Removal of a key defender.} 24... Nb4 $1 ({Rather than} 24... Nc5 $2 {, which allows White to hang on to his knight after} 25. Qc4 {.}) 25. Qc3 Rxb5 26. Bxb5 Qxb5 27. Qc7 {Black has won two minor pieces for the rook, but urgency presses upon White and it appears as if he has rustled up some counterplay against a5 and d6. However, Wei Yi's next move shows that Black's initiative comes first.} Qe2 $1 {Targeting both f2 and e4. If White's position hasn't quite reached hell, then it may be nearing the suburbs.} 28. Qxd6 Nd3 {Covering e5, while eyeing f2.} 29. Qa6 ({There is no time for} 29. Rxa5 $2 {in view of} Be3 $1 {(once begun, attacks take on a life of their own, almost independent of us, who started them) and if} 30. fxe3 $2 Qxe3+ 31. Kh1 {then} Nf2+ 32. Kg1 Nh3+ 33. Kh1 Qg1+ $1 {with a standard smothered mate.}) 29... Qxe4 30. Qc4 Qf5 $1 {Black must keep queens on the board to go after White's king. From f5 the queen enables a future activation of the rook into the attack with ...Rc8.} 31. Rxa5 ({If} 31. d6 {at once, then} e4 {and Black hangs on to his a-pawn.}) 31... h5 $1 {Offering his king luft, while worrying White about a future push of his h-pawn.} 32. d6 Rc8 33. Qc7 $5 {When we are losing, a single thought pops into our mind: How can we turn order into anarchy? Refusing to be enfeebled by long adversity, Zhao Jun fastens to his single strength in the position: his passed d-pawn. White refuses to impose limits on his spending and offers his queen. The idea is either a desperate bluff, or a cunning trap.} ({Objectively speaking,} 33. Qd4 {was correct, making use of the pin along the fifth rank, but that would only prolong White's suffering after} g6 34. Qa7 Rd8 {.}) ({QUESTION: Why can't he just play} 33. Qd5 {- ? --- ANSWER: Let's turn that into an exercise. --- EXERCISE (combination alert): Black to play and win. --- ANSWER:} Qxf2+ $1 {(when we are the victims of such shots, our emotions are the same as upon seeing a large oak tree, which has been a familiar sight all our lives, suddenly shattered into fragments in an instant by a bolt of lightning)} 34. Rxf2 Rc1+ 35. Rf1 Be3+ 36. Kh1 Rxf1# {. Forcing mate with a queen sacrifice is the chess equivalent of Christmas, your birthday and a visit from the tooth fairy and Easter bunny, all on the same day.}) 33... Rxc7 $1 {White's attempt at irony backfires; this is not one of those "Down-goes-Frazier" moments for Black. Sometimes an open challenge by our opponent undermines our rationality, to the point where we back down, when logic tells us we should accept the challenge. Wei Yi correctly accepts the queen. White's idea was merely an abstraction, without a real chance of application. He is unable to force promotion of the c7-pawn.} ({Chickening out with} 33... Bd8 $1 34. Qa7 Bxa5 35. Qxa5 Qg4 {wins easily too, when Black is a piece up and White's d-pawn is going nowhere.}) ({There is absolutely no reason to play an apathetic response like} 33... Rd8 $2 {, even if Komodo says Black is still winning anyway.}) 34. dxc7 Qc8 {"With great power comes great responsibility," says the queen, quoting Spiderman's uncle Ben. The queen isn't destined to be chained to c8 forever.} 35. Ra7 e4 {Threatening ...Bf4 and ...Bxc7.} 36. Rfa1 Kh7 $1 {Frustrating White's aim of a Ra8 pin, and c7 soon falls. --- SUMMARY: White's quiet set-up with 13 Be2 shouldn't cause us any problems. We can develop our pieces to sensible squares and await our chances. Note Black's idea of 16... Ra7, maintaining flexibility with the heavy pieces.} 0-1


