1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. Be2 $5 {We've seen this odd 'anti' crop up a few times recently. White will likely transpose back into a sort of open Sicilian against quiet play, but the principled approach for Black is of course to play a quick ...d7-d5. The future world champion shows that White can still drum up some chances in this case.} Nc6 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. O-O d5 6. exd5 Nxd5 7. d4 (7. b3 Be7 8. Bb2 O-O 9. Re1 Bf6 10. Qc1 Nxc3 11. dxc3 b6 $11 {is nothing special for White, but I watched my teammate pull off an important victory for White in 37 moves in McShane, L (2670)-Laznicka, V (2666) Germany 2015.}) ({I analysed} 7. Bb5 {in Harikrishna, P (2723)-Muzychuk, A (2544) Caleta 2015}) 7... cxd4 (7... Nxc3 8. bxc3 Be7 9. Re1 O-O 10. Bd3 cxd4 11. cxd4 b6 12. c3 {reaches a surprisingly normal-looking Panov-Botvinnik Caro-Kann structure where White can usually create some decent attacking chances on the kingside. For example,} Bb7 13. h4 $5 Bxh4 $6 14. Nxh4 Qxh4 15. Re3 $1 {led to a nice white victory in Ivanchuk, V (2731)-Sutovsky, E (2623) Tsaghkadzor 2015}) 8. Nxd4 Be7 9. Nxd5 exd5 10. Bf4 (10. Be3 {is a more regular placement of the queen's bishop against the isolated pawn. I have to admit that White would have gained a small opening advantage, had the game gone this way.} O-O 11. Re1 Re8 12. c3 $14) 10... O-O 11. Bf3 Bf6 12. Nb5 {Basically forced after White's choice of tenth move, but now White's initiative quickly fizzles out.} Bxb2 13. Rb1 Be5 14. Bxe5 Nxe5 15. Bxd5 Bf5 16. f4 (16. Bxb7 Qxd1 17. Rbxd1 Rab8 $11) (16. Re1 Rc8 $1 (16... Nd3 $6 17. cxd3 Qxd5 18. Nc7 Qxd3 19. Qxd3 Bxd3 20. Rxb7 $1 $16) 17. Rxe5 Bxc2 18. Qf1 Bxb1 19. Qxb1 Kh8 $1 $13 {, preparing ...Rc5.}) 16... Nd3 $1 {A nice equaliser.} 17. Qf3 Nc5 18. Rfd1 Qe7 19. Nd4 Be4 $1 $11 20. Bxe4 Nxe4 21. Rb5 Nd6 22. Rd5 Rfe8 23. Qa3 Ne4 24. Qxe7 Rxe7 25. Nf5 Ree8 {White's activity is offset by Black's slightly better structure.} 26. Rd7 Nc3 27. R1d6 b6 28. Rc6 Ne2+ 29. Kf1 Nxf4 30. Rcc7 Ne6 (30... Ne6 31. Rxa7 g6 32. Nd6 Rxa7 33. Rxa7 Rd8 $11) 1/2-1/2


