1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. h3 Bg7 6. d3 Nf6 7. Nc3 O-O 8. Be3 Nd7 $5 {Rarer than its more popular cousin, though of course quite logical.} ({We have looked at} 8... b6 9. Qd2 e5 {a few times on this site, most recently in Andriasian, Z (2624)-Grigoryan, K (2482) Yerevan 2012}) 9. Qd2 Re8 (9... e5 10. Bh6 {gets the bishop, and thus weakens Black's kingside as well as e5 and c5. Still, it's not so terrible for Black.} Qe7 11. Bxg7 Kxg7 12. O-O-O a5 13. Kb1 $6 (13. a4 $1 $14) 13... a4 $1 14. Ne2 b5 $1 $15 {1-0 (53) Motylev, A (2677)-Jones, G (2578) Aix-les-Bains 2011}) 10. Bh6 Bh8 11. h4 {Black has a horrible score from this position. I guess this is because White's game plays itself, because objectively White is only a little better.} Qa5 (11... e5 $6 12. h5 Nf6 13. hxg6 hxg6 14. O-O-O $40 {1-0 (40) Shirov, A (2713) -Leko, P (2749) Monte Carlo 2005}) (11... Nf6 $1 {looks best, taking advantage of the new g4-square.} 12. h5 Ng4 13. hxg6 hxg6 14. O-O-O Qa5 15. Rh4 b5 $132 {1-0 (29) Sutovsky, E (2465)-Muhtarov, L (2180) Ljubljana 1994}) 12. h5 Qb4 $6 {Strangely enough, this weak move was also played before.} (12... Nf6 $14 {was still possible.}) (12... b5 $14 {was consistent.}) 13. hxg6 hxg6 (13... fxg6 14. O-O-O Nb6 (14... Bxc3 15. bxc3 Qa3+ 16. Kb1 Nb6 {is a much better version of the game, although the endgame after} 17. Qc1 Qxc1+ 18. Rxc1 {is clearly better for white.}) 15. e5 $16 {1-0 (27) Titov, G (2490)-Markovic, M (2370) Vrnjacka Banja 1992}) 14. O-O-O Bxc3 $4 {Losing. This bishop was needed for the kingside, and now White has the opportunity to finish the game in spectacular fashion.} 15. bxc3 $1 (15. Qxc3 {gives White a very pleasant endgame, but there is no reason to exchange the queens White's attack along the h-file is much more dangerous than Black's.}) 15... Qa3+ 16. Kb1 Nb6 {Losing, but things were already beyond salvation.} (16... Nf6 17. Bg7 $3 Ng4 18. Ng5 $1 $18) (16... f6 {is best, but} 17. Qe1 {prepares Bc1, leading to an overwhelming attack down the h-file.}) 17. Bf8 $3 {A standard motif, leading in this case to mate in 14. Yi doesn't find the most precise continuation and thus prolongs the game, even giving Black serious chances, but there can be no doubt that his opening play was both powerful and instructive.} f6 18. Qh6 (18. Rh8+ $3 Kf7 19. Ng5+ $1 fxg5 20. Qxg5 Ke6 21. Rh7 {and mate soon follows.}) 18... Kf7 19. Qg7+ $2 (19. Ng5+ $3 fxg5 20. Qxg5 $18) 19... Ke6 20. Ng5+ fxg5 21. d4 $2 (21. Bxe7 $1 Rxe7 22. Qxg6+ Kd7 23. e5 c4 $1 24. dxc4+ Kc7 25. Qd6+ Qxd6 26. exd6+ Kd7 27. dxe7+ Kxe7 $16) 21... c4 $1 {Suddenly, Black's king is escaping.} 22. d5+ cxd5 23. exd5+ Kd7 24. d6 Kc6 25. Qxg6 $4 (25. dxe7 Kb5 26. Qxg6 $17) 25... Bd7 $4 (25... Bf5 $3 26. Qxf5 Na4 27. Qd5+ Kb6 28. Qd4+ Ka5 {and wins.}) 26. dxe7+ Kb5 27. Rh5 $1 Bc6 28. Qxg5+ Ka6 29. Qc5 Qxc5 30. Rxc5 {The smoke has cleared, and Black's king has survived. Moreover, his material advantage gives him a technically winning position, which, as justice would have it, he subsequently spoils.} Bxg2 31. Rd6 Rxf8 32. exf8=Q Rxf8 33. Rxc4 Rxf2 34. Rb4 {...I say technically winning, but of course Black has several obstacles to overcome in order to push towards the full point - namely, excavating his king and knight.} Bc6 35. Kc1 Nd5 {One piece out, one piece stuck!} 36. Ra4+ Kb6 37. Kb2 Ne3 38. Kb3 Rxc2 $4 (38... Rf1 $1 39. a3 Kc5 40. Rxc6+ bxc6 41. Rxa7 Nc4 $19) 39. Re4 Kc7 40. Rxe3 Rh2 $4 {Thus ends the official score, which makes me think Black must have lost on time. Of course, 40...Ba4+ is a draw.} 1-0


