1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. e4 d5 4. e5 d4 5. exf6 dxc3 6. fxg7 {"Everything new is well-forgotten old". This move is actually new to this site, but is one of the first things White tried, dating back to Nimzowitsch's games in the 1930s. Over time, theory moved on for good reason, since Black should be able to equalize without too much trouble. Nowadays, however, Black is doing fine in most major openings, so why not explore some of these more obscure sidelines?} (6. bxc3 {is the mainline. The PGN Archives contain nearly 50 annotated games starting with this move.}) 6... cxd2+ 7. Bxd2 Bxg7 8. Nf3 $5 {A very unusual move order, tempting Black with the b2-pawn. Instead:} (8. Qc2 {is the most common move, and transposes to the game after} Nc6 9. Nf3 {etc.}) (8. Qb3 {is also possible, and has been tried by Magnus Carlsen among others:} Nd7 (8... Nc6 9. Nf3 {when Black has played:} a5 (9... Qe7 10. Bd3 O-O {was played in Carlsen,M (2861)-Nakamura,H (2761) Abidjan 2019 1/2-1/2 (32), and now} (10... a5 $1 {to annoy White's queen, looks fine for Black}) 11. Be4 $1 {followed by doubling Black's c-pawns, gives White a slight advantage.}) 10. O-O-O a4 11. Qc2 Qe7 12. a3 Bd7 13. Bd3 Na5 14. Kb1 Nb3 15. Bc3 Bxc3 16. Qxc3 O-O-O {was roughly equal in Gukesh,D (2547)-Zarnicki,P (2514) Moscow 2019 0-1 (58)}) 9. Rd1 b6 10. Bc3 Bxc3+ 11. Qxc3 Qf6 12. Qxf6 Nxf6 13. Be2 Ke7 {was balanced in Harutyunian,T (2501)-Oparin,G (2622) Batumi 2018 1/2-1/2 (16)}) 8... Nc6 {Black continues with normal development. Here:} (8... Bxb2 {looks playable, although Wei Yi probably wanted to avoid any specific preparation. Now} 9. Rb1 {Reda,P-Kriger,I Wroclaw 2008 0-1 (73), and now Black should play} Bg7 {for example} 10. Qc2 O-O {(the b1-rook discourages Black from attempting queenside castling)} 11. Bd3 f5 12. c5 Nc6 13. O-O e5 14. Bc4+ Kh8 15. Rb3 {when White's active pieces and Black's loose king's cover, compensate for the missing pawn.}) 9. Qc2 Qf6 {Not a bad move, but the slightly awkward position of Black's queen sets up the preconditions for Black's inaccuracy on the next move. Alternatively:} (9... Nd4 10. Nxd4 Bxd4 11. Bc3 Qf6 12. Bxd4 Qxd4 13. Rd1 Qe5+ {Nimzowitsch,A-Kostic,B Bled 1931 1/2-1/2 (40), and now instead of trading queens with 14 Qe2, the move} 14. Be2 {leaves White somewhat better with greater activity and a more compact pawn structure.}) (9... Qe7 {is a reliable approach for Black, who can play ...Bc8-d7 and ....0-0-0 next, and the queen also eyes the b4-square.} 10. Bc3 (10. Bd3 Bd7 11. O-O (11. a3 O-O-O 12. O-O-O Nd4 13. Nxd4 Bxd4 14. Kb1 Bc6 15. Be4 Bxe4 16. Qxe4 Qf6 $11 {1/2-1/2 (19) Golcman,E (2200)-Sprotte,N (2171) Marianske Lazne 2014}) 11... Nb4 12. Bxb4 Qxb4 13. Rab1 {0-1 (29) Demensky,E (2220)-Ushacov,V (2145) Kemerovo 2010} O-O-O $11) 10... Bxc3+ 11. Qxc3 Qb4 12. Kd2 b6 13. Qxb4 Nxb4 14. Kc3 Nc6 15. Bd3 Bb7 $11 {1-0 (41) Iturrizaga Bonelli,E (2635)-Nowak,L (2257) Suwalki 2019}) (9... Bd7 {is also fine, with 10...Qe7 to follow}) 10. O-O-O {Here:} (10. Bc3 {is also worth considering. Now} Qf5 11. Bd3 Bxc3+ 12. Qxc3 Qa5 13. Qxa5 Nxa5 14. O-O-O {and Black hasn't fully equalized yet.}) 10... Bd7 $6 {An older game saw the better move:} (10... e5 11. h3 Be6 12. Bd3 O-O-O 13. Bg5 Bh6 14. Qd2 Bxg5 15. Qxg5 Qxg5+ 16. Nxg5 {with an approximately level endgame, Chandler,M  (2390)-Hurme,H (2310) Buenos Aires 1978 0-1 (54)} Rd4) 11. Bg5 Bh6 {Instead:} (11... Qg6 $4 {is the positionally desirable move, but fails because of} 12. Qd2 {and Black has no good way of saving the d7-bishop.} Nb8 (12... Bc8 13. Qd8+ Nxd8 14. Rxd8#) 13. Bd3 Qh5 14. Be4 {and White wins the b7-pawn at the very least, while keeping full control of the position.}) (11... Qf5 12. Qxf5 exf5 13. Bd3 {and White is for choice due to Black's ruined pawn structure.}) 12. h4 O-O-O 13. Qd2 {Forcing the trade on the g5-square which gives White a nice space advantage.} Bxg5 14. hxg5 Qe7 15. Qe3 e5 16. Bd3 Bg4 17. Be4 {White threatens 18 Bxc6 and is putting pressure on multiple points in Black position - the a7-, e5 and h7-pawns.} Qb4 $6 {Running after the c4-pawn opens up the game in White's favour. Going for simplifications with:} (17... Rxd1+ 18. Rxd1 Bxf3 19. gxf3 Rd8 20. Rxd8+ Kxd8 21. Bxh7 Qd6 {gives Black good chances to hold despite the pawn deficit.}) 18. Kb1 Rxd1+ 19. Rxd1 Qxc4 20. Rc1 Qa6 21. Bxc6 bxc6 22. Nxe5 {The doubling of the c-pawns has created a lot of weaknesses, and White is clearly better here.} Be6 23. b3 Bd5 24. Qf4 $6 {Allowing Black back into the game. Stronger was:} (24. Nd3 {The knight will be a monster on the c5-square, and} Bxg2 $2 25. Nc5 Qa3 26. Rg1 Bd5 27. Rg4 {leaves Black's queen close to trapped}) 24... Re8 25. f3 Kb7 $6 (25... Qb5 {prevents the knight from reaching the c5-square and Black is doing OK here.}) 26. Nd7 {Now White is back on track. White's own king looks to be exposed, but Yu shows that Black can't really get to it.} Qd3+ 27. Rc2 Qb5 28. Nc5+ Kb8 29. a4 Re1+ 30. Kb2 Qf1 31. Qf6 {White plays it safe, although he can even grab the a7-pawn with impunity:} (31. Qb4+ Kc8 32. Qb7+ Kd8 33. Qxa7 {for example} Rb1+ 34. Ka3 Ra1+ 35. Kb4 Qe1+ 36. Rc3 {and the checks run out.}) 31... Re8 32. Qc3 Ka8 33. Qd2 Qe1 34. Qxe1 Rxe1 35. a5 Kb8 36. Kc3 Kc8 37. Kd3 Kd8 38. Re2 Rd1+ 39. Kc3 Rc1+ {Chasing White's king where it wants to go. Instead:} (39... Rh1 {with the idea of ...h7-h6 to eliminate the weak h7-pawn, keeps White's advantage with bounds.} 40. Ne4 h6) 40. Kd4 Ra1 41. a6 Rd1+ 42. Ke5 Ke7 43. Kf5+ Be6+ 44. Nxe6 {The rook endgame is great for White because of his active king and all of Black's weak pawns.} Rd5+ 45. Kg4 fxe6 46. g3 Kf7 47. f4 Ra5 48. Rh2 Kg7 49. Rh6 {Black threw in the towel, since after, for example} (49. Rh6 Rxa6 50. Rxe6 Rb6 51. Re7+ Kg8 52. f5 Rxb3 53. f6 {Black is hopelessly lost.}) 1-0


