1. b3 {Cabrilo,Goran} e5 2. Bb2 Nc6 3. e3 g6 {We looked at this King's-Indian style setup in the March 2019 Update, when Wei Yi used it to score a convincing win playing Black! To balance the coverage, we now see how he handles it from White's perspective.} 4. f4 {A logical idea, using the pin on the e5-pawn. White also has:} (4. h4 $6 Nf6 5. Bb5 Qe7 6. Nf3 e4 {didn't end well for White in Antipov-Wei, see the game in the Archives.}) (4. c4 Bg7 5. Nf3 d6 6. d4 {is a more positional approach that is covered in Fedoseev-Vitiugov in the Archives.}) (4. Bb5 {(Cabrilo,Goran) - 139/1}) 4... Bg7 5. Nf3 d6 6. fxe5 {White seeks clarification of the pawn structure right away. Instead:} (6. Bb5 {has been played more often, but after} Nge7 7. fxe5 O-O 8. O-O dxe5 {it is not obvious what the bishop is doing on the b5-square, for example} 9. Nc3 a6 10. Bc4 b5 11. Bd3 h6 12. Qb1 Kh8 13. a4 b4 14. Ne2 Qd6 {and Black's well centralized position gives him the advantage, Artemiev,V (2660)-Khairullin,I (2625) Khanty-Mansiysk 2014 1-0 (98)}) 6... Nge7 {Black has also played:} (6... Nxe5 7. Nxe5 {and now:} dxe5 (7... Bxe5 8. Bxe5 dxe5 9. Nc3 c6 10. Qf3 Qh4+ 11. g3 Qg4 12. Qf2 Qf5 13. Qg2 $5 Nf6 (13... Qxc2 $5 {is the critical test}) 14. Bd3 Qh3 15. Qf3 Nh5 16. Ne4 O-O 17. Be2 Qf5 18. Qxf5 Bxf5 19. Nd6 {and White has the better endgame chances, Wei,Y (2727)-Liu, G (2452) China 2017 1/2-1/2 (81)}) 8. Nc3 Nh6 (8... Ne7 {would transpose to the main game}) 9. Qf3 O-O 10. Bc4 c6 11. a4 Bf5 $6 (11... a6 $5 {with the idea of ...Bc8-g4 followed by a quick ...b7-b5, keeps Black on at least level terms}) 12. e4 Bg4 13. Qg3 Qd7 {was played in Mamedyarov,S (2804)-Dreev,A  (2653) chess. com INT 2018 0-1 (89), and now} 14. h3 Be6 15. Bxe6 Qxe6 16. Ba3 Rfd8 17. O-O-O {slightly favours White due to his more active minor pieces, although the position is doubled edged due to opposite side castling.}) (6... dxe5 {is a rarer choice here. After} 7. Bb5 {the pressure on the e5-pawn forces Black to go} Bd7 {but this also appears playable for Black, for example} 8. O-O f5 $5 {followed by ...Qd8-e7 threatening ...e5-e4 ideas.}) 7. Nc3 Nxe5 {An earlier Wei Yi game saw Black keep all the knights on the board:} (7... dxe5 8. Qe2 (8. Bc4 {followed by short castling, is another valid plan.}) 8... O-O 9. O-O-O a5 10. a4 Nb4 11. h4 h5 12. Qf2 Bf5 $6 (12... Nf5 {keeps the structure fluid, since} 13. e4 $2 Nd4 {is strong for Black}) 13. e4 Bg4 14. Bc4 Nec6 15. Ng5 Bf6 {Wei,Y (2739)-Karjakin,S (2760) Medias 2017 0-1 (62), and now} 16. Rdf1 {maintains strong pressure on the f7-weakness.}) 8. Nxe5 dxe5 {Black goes for the pawn structure we have seen in several of the earlier notes. Alternatively: would transpose to the main game} (8... Bxe5 {cedes more central squares. Now} 9. Qf3 d5 10. O-O-O Be6 11. h3 Qd7 12. Ne2 {There was no rush to trade bishops.} (12. Kb1 O-O-O 13. d4 {looks a little more pleasant for White.}) 12... Bxb2+ 13. Kxb2 O-O (13... O-O-O {is less double edged}) 14. Qf6 a5 15. Nf4 a4 16. b4 a3+ {gave Black good counterplay in Jobava,B (2676)-Lalith,B (2573) Moscow 2016 1/ 2-1/2 (58)}) 9. Bc4 Nf5 {The first new move. Instead: Cabrilo,Goran: 'N!?'} (9... O-O 10. O-O Be6 $2 {(a needless, major weakening of the pawn structure)} 11. Bxe6 fxe6 12. Rxf8+ Qxf8 13. Qe2 Nd5 14. Qc4 c6 15. Ne4 {and White is clearly better because of the blockade of the doubled e-pawns, Roe,S (2224)-Reitemann,J (1882) Bregenz 2018 1-0 (37)}) 10. O-O Nd6 11. Ba3 O-O (11... f5 {Cabrilo,Goran} 12. Qf3 c6 $13) 12. Qf3 Kh8 {sensibly moving the king out of the pin along the a2-g8 diagonal.} 13. Nb5 f5 {Black has played the opening well and after regular moves will have nothing to worry about. So now Wei Yi tries to mix things up with} 14. Qd5 $5 {Forcing Black to find some accurate moves in the forcing sequence that follows. Cabrilo,Goran: 'Diagram '} Nxb5 {Best. After: Cabrilo,Goran: '!'} (14... Nxc4 15. Qxc4 {White has a double attack on the c7-pawn and f8-rook.} c6 (15... c5 {Cabrilo,Goran} 16. Bxc5 Rf6 17. d4 $14 (17. Bxa7 $2 b6 $17)) 16. Bxf8 Bxf8 17. Nc3 {nets White the exchange.}) 15. Bxf8 Qxf8 16. Qxb5 c6 $1 {White's queen is short of squares, and is forced back to the c3-square, whereupon Black regains the lost exchange with ...e5-e4.} 17. Qa5 b6 18. Qc3 e4 19. d4 {The only move, but now after} exd3 20. Qe1 (20. Qxd3 $2 {Cabrilo,Goran} b5 $17) 20... Bxa1 21. Qxa1+ Qg7 {Black is fine.} 22. Qd1 {Cabrilo,Goran: 'Diagram '} (22. Bxd3 {Cabrilo,Goran} Bd7 23. e4 fxe4 24. Bxe4 Re8 25. Bf3 $11) 22... b5 (22... Bb7 $1 {Cabrilo,Goran} 23. Bxd3 c5 $15) 23. Bxd3 Be6 24. Qf3 Bd5 {The position is completely equal, although Wei Yi later manages to outplay his opponent from a level endgame.} 25. Qf4 (25. e4 $4 {Cabrilo,Goran} fxe4 26. Bxe4 Qd4+ $19) 25... Re8 26. Qd4 Be4 27. Rd1 Qxd4 28. exd4 Bxd3 29. Rxd3 {Cabrilo,Goran: '='} Kg7 30. Kf2 Kf6 31. Rc3 Re6 32. b4 Rd6 33. Ke3 {The rook endgame should be drawn, but White conjures up some resources out of nowhere.} Ke6 $2 {This turns out to be a serious mistake, since Black ends up with the passive rook vs. White's active rook. Instead: Cabrilo,Goran: '?!'} (33... Re6+ {Cabrilo,Goran: ''} 34. Kd3 (34. Kf3 {Cabrilo,Goran} Rd6 $11) 34... f4 {creates the threat of counterplay for Black on the kingside. Cabrilo,Goran: ''}) 34. Kd3 {Cabrilo,Goran: 'Diagram '} h6 {Or: Cabrilo,Goran: '?'} (34... g5 35. Ra3 Rd7 36. Ra6 Rc7 {and now} 37. a4 $1 bxa4 38. b5 {and White is on top.}) (34... f4 $142 $1 {Cabrilo,Goran} 35. Ke4 $140 (35. Ra3 $140 Rd7 36. Ke4 g5 37. Ra6 Kd6 38. Kf5 Kd5 $132) 35... Kf6 36. Rc5 g5 $11) 35. Ra3 {White's queenside play is well underway, while Black's kingside majority is too far back. Cabrilo,Goran: '!'} Rd7 36. c4 (36. Ra6 {is similar to the previous note. Cabrilo,Goran: '!'} Rc7 {Cabrilo,Goran} (36... Kd5 {Cabrilo,Goran} 37. a4 $18) 37. a4 Kf7 (37... bxa4 38. b5 $18) 38. axb5 cxb5 39. g3 $16) 36... bxc4+ 37. Kxc4 f4 38. Ra6 Rc7 $2 {Again too passive. Perhaps Black didn't have enough time to calculate that the upcoming pawn endgame is lost. Instead:} (38... Kf5 {Cabrilo,Goran: ''} 39. Rxc6 Re7 {keeps the game going} 40. Ra6 $16 {Cabrilo,Goran}) 39. d5+ {Cabrilo,Goran: '+-'} Kd7 (39... Ke5 $142 {Cabrilo,Goran} 40. Rxc6 Rd7 41. Rxg6 $18) 40. dxc6+ Rxc6+ (40... Kd6 {Cabrilo,Goran} 41. b5) 41. Rxc6 Kxc6 42. a4 g5 {Now it is hopeless as White's king comes over to capture the kingside pawns.} 43. Kd4 g4 44. Ke4 f3 45. gxf3 gxf3 46. Kxf3 Kd5 47. Kg4 Kc4 48. Kh5 Kxb4 49. Kxh6 Kxa4 50. h4 {White queens first and wins with a few tempi to spare.} 1-0


