1. Nf3 {Wei Yi is known as an 1 e4 player, but as part of his tournament victory in Danzhou, in this game he joined the ranks of Flank Openings players with a creative win over Ruslan Ponomariov.} Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 dxc4 5. O-O {The most ambitious reply.} (5. Qa4+ {regains the pawn immediately, but loses time with the queen. Black has been doing fine here, see for example Grischuk-Eljanov in the Archives.}) 5... Nbd7 {Black's most popular move, although I think he should prefer:} (5... a6 6. Qc2 Bd6 {and now for example} 7. Qxc4 b5 8. Qb3 Bb7 9. a4 Nbd7 10. axb5 Bd5 11. Qc2 axb5 12. Rxa8 Qxa8 13. Nc3 Bc6 14. d3 O-O 15. Bg5 h6 16. Bxf6 Nxf6 17. Rc1 Rc8 {with balanced chances, Howell,D (2667)-Shankland,S (2666) Saint Louis 2017 1/2-1/2 (80). This approach appears to be very solid for Black. See the notes to Aronian-Naiditsch for further details.}) 6. Qc2 Nb6 {As I wrote in my notes to Aronian-Naiditsch, this is a critical try, holding on to the pawn for now. Alternatively:} (6... c5 7. Na3 Nd5 8. Nxc4 b5 9. Ne3 Bb7 10. Nxd5 Bxd5 11. e4 Bb7 12. d4 {and White got the upper hand in Aronian-Naiditsch, see the game in the Archives}) 7. a4 {White wants to play Nb1-a3 without taking on doubled a-pawns. Instead:} (7. Na3 Bxa3 8. bxa3 Bd7 9. Bb2 Bc6 (9... Ba4 10. Qc1 Bc6 {is similar but with the queen on c1}) 10. Ne5 Bxg2 11. Kxg2 Qd5+ 12. f3 O-O 13. Rfd1 Nfd7 14. Ng4 {when White has some play for the pawn, but a materialistic player may also be fairly happy to play Black here, Gajewski,G (2648)-Cornette, M (2590) Montpellier 2015 1-0 (29)}) 7... a5 8. Na3 Bxa3 9. Rxa3 {This rook looks fairly modestly placed right now, but has a great career ahead of it!} O-O 10. e4 {A new move, fighting for the centre. In earlier games, White has tried:} (10. d3 {making the pawn sacrifice permanent, in return for open lines} cxd3 11. Rxd3 Nbd5 12. Ne5 Qd6 13. Bf4 {with chances for both sides, Vishnu,P  (2340) -Van den Doel,E (2574) Leiden 2011 0-1 (43)}) (10. Rd1 Nfd5 11. Ne5 Nb4 12. Qc3 N4d5 13. Qc2 {led to a repetition with} Nb4 14. Qc3 N4d5 15. Qd4 Nb4 16. Qc3 N4d5 {1/2-1/2 (16) Miroshnichenko,E (2538)-Klovans,J (2417) Cappelle-la-Grande 2003}) 10... e5 {Black decides to provoke an exchange of queens. He could also target the a4-pawn with the alternative:} (10... Qe8 $5 {for example} 11. Ne5 Bd7 12. Nxc4 Bxa4 13. b3 Nxc4 14. Rxa4 Ne5 15. d4 Nc6 16. Qc3 {and White retains typical compensation for the pawn}) 11. Nxe5 Qd4 12. Qc3 Qxc3 13. Rxc3 {White keeps his rook active, even though the a4-pawn is dropping} Be6 14. d4 Nxa4 15. Ra3 b5 16. f4 Nb6 17. g4 $5 {Objectively, this move should probably get a "?!" annotation, but it is a very creative and aggressive idea, opening the 3rd rank for the a3-rook.} (17. d5 {is more conventional, and after} Bc8 18. Be3 {chances are roughly balanced}) 17... Nxg4 18. f5 (18. Nc6 $5 {was worth considering}) 18... Nxe5 19. dxe5 Bd7 20. Rg3 {White is trying to drum up a kingside attack, with ideas of Bc1-h6 and e5-e6 in the air.} Bc6 $5 {Black offers an exchange in order to relieve the pressure, hoping then to exploit his queenside pawn mass. Alternatively:} (20... b4 $1 {was a better implementation of the same idea. After} 21. Bh6 g6 22. Bxf8 Rxf8 {and Black is on top, since his queenside pawns are moving fast down the board}) (20... Rfe8 $2 {shows the potential of White's attack after} 21. Bh6 g6 22. e6 $1 fxe6 23. fxg6 hxg6 24. Rf6 {with a winning attack}) 21. Bh6 g6 22. Rg5 $6 {Another objectively dodgy move that further unbalances the position. Instead:} (22. Bh3 $5 Bxe4 23. fxg6 hxg6 24. e6 {keeps some initiative going in an unclear position}) (22. Bxf8 Rxf8 23. h4 Nd7 24. e6 fxe6 25. h5 {is also roughly balanced}) 22... c3 $2 {A very odd move, giving up his most advanced pawn - Black appears to crack under the pressure. Instead} (22... Na4 $1 {going after the b2-pawn, is better for Black. If now} 23. e6 $6 fxe6 24. Bxf8 Rxf8 25. fxe6 Rxf1+ 26. Bxf1 Kg7 {Black can handle the e6-pawn and is winning}) 23. bxc3 {Now Black's queenside pawns take much longer to get going, and White is suddenly taking over} Nc4 $6 {Making matters worse.} (23... Nd7 {was more resilient, bringing the knight closer to the kingside}) 24. fxg6 fxg6 25. Bxf8 Rxf8 26. e6 {White is clearly better now - he is the exchange up for only a pawn, and with a dangerous passed e-pawn. The roaming rook now does great work along the 5th rank.} Be8 27. Rd1 Rf6 28. Rd8 Kf8 {Instead:} (28... Rxe6 29. Rxb5 Nd6 30. Rd5 Re7 31. Ra8 {is also a winning endgame for White}) 29. Rxb5 {Breaking up Black's connected pawns. White can easily contain the a5-pawn, so can comfortably realize his material advantage.} Ke7 30. Rbb8 Bc6 31. Rdc8 Rxe6 32. Rxc7+ Kd6 33. Rxh7 a4 34. Ra7 Kc5 35. e5 Bxg2 36. Kxg2 a3 37. Rc7+ Rc6 38. Rxc6+ Kxc6 39. Rc8+ Kd5 40. e6 {A nice finishing touch. After} (40. e6 a2 (40... Nd6 41. e7 {wins}) 41. Ra8 Kxe6 42. Rxa2 {and White's extra pawn makes this a simple win for the rook vs. the knight}) 1-0


[Event "FIDE Grand Prix"]
