[Round "28.1"]
[White "Wei, Yi"]
[Black "Nepomniachtchi, Ian"]
[Result "0-1"]
[ECO "A33"]
[WhiteElo "2725"]
[BlackElo "2767"]
[Annotator "David Cummings"]
[PlyCount "192"]
[EventDate "2019.??.??"]
[EventType "team-tourn"]
[EventCountry "ISR"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 e6 6. g3 Qb6 7. Ndb5 {Varying from:} (7. Nb3 {which Ian faced in Gelfand-Nepomniachtchi in an earlier round of the same event, a game that is also covered in this month's Update. As alluded to in the notes to that game, the 6 g3 Qb6 variation is quite a labyrinth, putting the onus on Black to carry a lot of opening knowledge, since it is White that has significant options on almost every move.}) 7... Ne5 8. Bg2 {Another major line is:} (8. Bf4 {- see Topalov-Caruana and earlier games in the Archives.}) 8... a6 9. Qa4 {White's most popular move, protecting the c4-pawn while exploiting the pin along the a-file. Black also has to be ready for a couple of other lines, both of which offer the c4-pawn as a gambit:} (9. Na4 Qd8 {and now:} 10. Nbc3 (10. Nd6+ Bxd6 11. Qxd6 Nxc4 12. Qc5 d5 13. b3 Bd7 14. bxc4 Bxa4 15. Qa3 (15. cxd5 Nxd5 16. O-O {is the subject of Kobo-Salgado Lopez in the Archives}) 15... Qd7 16. Bb2 b5 $6 (16... dxc4 17. O-O Bc6 {maintains the balance}) 17. cxd5 exd5 18. Bxf6 gxf6 19. O-O {and White was clearly better in Dubov,D (2700)-Vachier Lagrave,M (2775) Paris  (Rapid) 2019 0-1 (62). Black's pawn structure is shattered and his a4-bishop out of play.}) 10... Nxc4 11. b3 {which is analyzed in Navara-So in the Archives}) (9. Na3 Bxa3 10. bxa3 Nxc4 {is covered in Howell-Jumabayev in the Archives}) 9... Rb8 {An essential move, forcing White to react to the attack on the b5-knight. Instead:} (9... Bc5 $2 10. Bf4 {ended in a quick win for White in Ganguly-Wei Yi from the September 2019 Update. Perhaps that game inspired Wei Yi to try this from White's side!}) 10. Na3 {White offers the c4-pawn, a theme we have already seen in the note to White's 9th move above. The alternative is:} (10. Be3 {which is examined in Harikrishna-Grischuk in the Archives.}) 10... Bc5 {Black continues with an active developing move. The alternatives are:} (10... Bxa3 11. Qxa3 {White gets compensation for the pawn in the shape of a lead in development and latent pressure on the dark squares. Objectively, it doesn't appear to be enough for an advantage, but White has scored 6 wins and 5 draws in over-the-board games in my database, starting from this position.} Nxc4 12. Qb3 {and now:} d5 (12... Qxb3 13. axb3 Ne5 14. Bf4 d6 15. O-O-O Ke7 {and here White sacrifices the exchange with} 16. Rxd6 Ng6 (16... Kxd6 17. Rd1+ Ke7 18. Bxe5 Ra8 19. Bd6+ Ke8 20. f4 {with dynamic compensation Greenfeld, A (2561)-Phadke, S (2208) Mumbai 2010 1-0 (34)}) 17. Rd8 Rxd8 18. Bxb8 Bd7 19. Ba7 Rc8 20. Kb1 Bc6 21. e4 {and Black held the endgame in Grandelius,N (2635)-Ragger,M (2689) Caleta 2016 1/2-1/2 (74)}) (12... Qc7 {when White has tried:} 13. Bf4 {was played in a 2018 correspondence game, which was dynamically balanced throughout, continuing} (13. O-O b5 14. Rd1 d6 15. Bg5 {this loses some time} (15. Qb4 {is better, with typical compensation}) 15... Ng4 16. Ne4 O-O 17. h3 Nge5 18. Qc3 {Svane,R (2546) -Menezes,C (2408) Bhubaneswar 2016 1/2-1/2 (31), and here} f6 {would have left White with not quite enough for the pawn.}) 13... d6 14. Qb4 e5 15. Bg5 Be6 16. b3 Qa5 17. Qxa5 Nxa5 18. O-O-O Ke7 19. Kb2 h6 20. Be3 Rhc8 21. f4 Nc6 22. Rd2 b5 23. Rhd1 b4 24. Ne4 Nxe4 25. Bxe4 {and now Black has to return the pawn with} Nd4 26. Bxd4 exd4 27. f5 {1/2-1/2 (27) Nyvlt,Z (2425)-Babic,D (2475) ICCF email 2018}) 13. e4 (13. Bf4 {is also possible}) 13... Bd7 14. O-O d4 $6 15. Qxc4 {and after restoring material parity, the bishop pair gave White an edge in Matlakov-Rambaldi, which is included in the Archives.}) (10... Be7 {is a sensible alternative, leading to a hedgehog structure after} 11. O-O O-O 12. Bf4 d6 13. b4 Qc7 14. Rac1 Ng6 15. Be3 b6 16. Qb3 Bb7 17. f3 Rfc8 {with balanced chances, Lupulescu,C (2643)-Howell,D (2694) Douglas 2019 1/2-1/2 (129)}) 11. O-O O-O {A reasonable solution here was demonstrated by Peter Leko:} (11... Neg4 {Black provokes e2-e3, blocking in the c1-bishop, before reverting to a hedgehog setup.} 12. e3 O-O 13. Rb1 Be7 14. b4 Qc7 15. Bb2 d6 16. Rbc1 b6 17. Qd1 Bb7 18. e4 Rbc8 19. Qe2 Ne5 {with an acceptable position for Black, Inarkiev,E (2693)-Leko,P (2679) Germany 2018 1/2-1/2 (55)}) 12. Rb1 Qb4 {After this move, White has several paths to a small advantage. Instead:} (12... d6 13. b4 Bd4 {leaves Black's d4-bishop awkwardly placed, and he will likely soon have to cede the two bishops. Now} 14. Qb3 Bd7 {was played in Nihal,S  (2598) -Rodshtein,M (2699) Brest 2019 1/2-1/2 (29), and here} 15. Na4 Bxa4 16. Qxa4 Qc7 17. Rd1 Ba7 18. Bf4 {would give White a pleasant advantage}) (12... Neg4 {would transpose to Inarkiev-Leko (see the note to Black's 11th) after} 13. e3) (12... Bxa3 {could also be tried. Although Black lost a tempo by moving the bishop twice, he has castled, which is in contrast to the situation after 10... Bxa3. Now a sample line is} 13. bxa3 Qc7 14. Qb4 (14. Bf4 d6 15. Qb4 Nxc4 16. Rfd1 {is similar}) 14... Nxc4 15. Rd1 {with compensation for the pawn}) 13. Qd1 {A decent move which was, however, the product of a 53 minute  (!) think, leaving White short of time later on. White actually has a choice of good moves:} (13. Qxb4 Bxb4 14. Nc2 {and now for example} Bxc3 15. bxc3 Nxc4 16. Na3 d5 17. Nxc4 dxc4 18. Bf4 Ra8 19. Rfd1 {gives White an annoying bind. He can easily regain his pawn at some point, while playing for more.}) (13. Bf4 d6 14. Nc2 Qxa4 15. Nxa4 Ba7 16. c5 Bd7 17. cxd6 Ng6 18. Nc3 Nxf4 19. gxf4 {and this time White has the extra pawn. His pawn structure is a bit weakened, and Black has the two bishops, but White is still for choice.}) 13... d6 {This time, Black should not grab the c4-pawn:} (13... Nxc4 $2 {since White now has} 14. Nc2 Qb6 15. Na4 Qc7 16. Nxc5 Qxc5 17. b3 Ne5 18. Ba3 {winning material}) 14. Na4 {Instead:} (14. Bg5 {looks good. White threatens to damage Black's kingside while his forces are mainly concentrated on the other side of the board. Some sample lines:} Ned7 (14... Nxc4 $2 {leaves the c5-bishop trapped after} 15. Nc2 Qb6 (15... Qa5 16. Bxf6 gxf6 17. b4 {wins}) 16. b4 {etc.}) (14... Bd7 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. Ne4 {with a sample line} Ba4 17. Qc1 Kg7 18. Qf4 f5 19. Nxc5 Qxc5 20. b4 Qc7 21. Rfc1 {giving White an edge: better structure and more space.}) 15. Na4 {and now} b5 16. Nxc5 Qxc5 17. Be3 {is very strong, since} Qc7 18. cxb5 axb5 19. Rc1 Qa5 (19... Qd8 20. Ba7 {wins the exchange}) 20. Qxd6 {and White is on top}) 14... b5 {Alternatively:} (14... Nxc4 {is again a consideration. Now} 15. Nxc5 Nxa3 16. Nd3 Qb5 17. Ra1 Nc4 18. Qc2 {gives White the typical compensation}) 15. Nxc5 Qxc5 16. cxb5 {White could also start with} (16. b4 {or 16 Be3, since pushing the queen back limits some of Black's options}) 16... axb5 17. Bg5 {In contrast to 14 Bg5, this appears to be rather harmless. Having traded off his c3-knight, White has fewer attackers with which to threaten Black's king, and Black's queen is also more centralized. A subsequent Bg5xf6 may give White chances of a perpetual check (as in fact happened in the game), but to press for an advantage it was more promising to play in the centre with, for example:} (17. Be3 Qc7 18. Qd4 Ba6 19. Rbc1 Qd7 20. Nc2 {and after bringing his offside knight back into the game, White is slightly better thanks to his bishop pair, and potential play against the b5- and d6-pawns.}) 17... Ba6 (17... Bb7 {is also possible, and roughly equal}) 18. Nc2 (18. b4 {was the last chance to fix the b5-pawn}) 18... b4 {Black has successfully freed his position and the game is now roughly balanced. Black's b-pawn has been transformed from a weakness into a strength, constraining White's queenside.} 19. Nd4 Bb7 20. Rc1 Qa5 21. Bxb7 Rxb7 22. Bxf6 gxf6 23. Qb3 Ra8 24. f4 Qa7 25. e3 Nd7 26. Qd1 {Leaving the a2-pawn to its fate in order to play against Black's exposed king.} Qxa2 27. Qg4+ Kh8 28. Qh5 Kg8 29. Qg4+ Kh8 30. Qh5 Kg8 31. Nb5 $6 (31. Qg4+ {with a draw by repetition would have been a logical conclusion to the game. Instead, in time trouble, White goes for more, but this is very risky.}) 31... Rxb5 $1 {Black gets two pawns for the exchange, and White's king is exposed along his 2nd rank.} 32. Qxb5 Qxb2 33. Rb1 (33. Qxd7 $2 {loses to} Ra2 {with mate on the 7th rank}) 33... Qc2 34. Rfc1 $2 {It was essential to trade off a pair of rooks, to limit Black's attacking potential:} (34. Ra1 Rxa1 35. Rxa1 {and now a possible continuation is} b3 36. Ra7 b2 37. Rb7 Qc1+ 38. Kg2 Qxe3 39. Qxb2 Qe4+ 40. Kh3 Qf5+ 41. Kg2 Qe4+ {with a draw}) 34... Qd2 35. Qxb4 Qxe3+ 36. Kh1 Ra2 37. Rc8+ Kg7 38. Rb2 Qf3+ {Instead:} (38... Ra3 $1 {is a subtle move which leaves White defenceless against the threat of ...Ra3-d3 followed by a mating attack, for example} 39. Rcc2 Qf3+ 40. Kg1 Rd3 41. Rd2 Nc5 $1 {and the knight enters the attack with decisive effect}) 39. Kg1 Qd1+ (39... Ra3 $1 {was again strong}) 40. Kg2 Ra1 41. Qb5 f5 $6 (41... h5 $1 {was a better configuration, adding the h-pawn as an attacking unit. Now, for example} 42. Qe2 Qd5+ 43. Kh3 (43. Qf3 $2 Rg1+ {wins the queen}) 43... Qf5+ 44. Kg2 h4 45. Rd2 h3+ 46. Kf2 Rh1 47. Ke3 Nc5 {and White's king won't survive.}) 42. Qe2 Qd5+ 43. Kh3 Nf6 44. Rbb8 (44. Rd2 $1 {pushes the queen off its centralized post. Now} Qb7 45. Rd8 d5 46. Rb2 {limits Black's attacking options and White should hold}) 44... Ra2 45. Rc2 Rxc2 46. Qxc2 Qf3 {Black has a nagging edge, and continues the squeeze in "do not hurry!" mode for another 40 moves before White makes the decisive mistake. Along the way, the engine shows how both sides could have improved at various points, but I will only give a few of these in the notes.} 47. Rb3 Qf1+ 48. Qg2 Qe1 49. Qb2 Kg6 50. Kg2 d5 51. Rb8 Qe4+ 52. Kh3 (52. Kg1 {was a better location for the king, enabling White to keep his pieces centralized}) 52... Qf3 53. Rb3 Qf1+ (53... Qd1 54. Kg2 d4 {was already a winning advantage for Black, who also had several later chances to get in ...d5-d4 under favourable circumstances.}) 54. Qg2 Qe1 55. Qc2 Qf1+ 56. Qg2 Qc4 57. Rb8 h6 58. Kh4 Qd3 59. Rb2 Ng4 60. Qe2 Qd4 61. Kh3 Qg1 62. Qg2 Qd4 63. Qe2 Qc5 64. Qc2 Qg1 65. Qg2 Qe3 66. Qe2 Qd4 67. Qc2 Ne3 68. Qb3 Nd1 69. Re2 Nf2+ 70. Kg2 Ng4 71. Qb8 Nf6 72. Qb2 Qc5 73. Rc2 Qe3 74. Re2 Qa7 75. Qa2 Qc5 76. Qc2 Qd6 77. Qb2 Ne4 78. Qd4 Qa6 79. Rc2 Nf6 80. Rd2 Qa5 81. Re2 Qa3 82. Qb2 Qa7 83. Qa2 Qd7 84. Qb2 (84. Rd2 $1 {would have prevented the d-pawn from advancing}) 84... d4 85. Rd2 Qd5+ 86. Kg1 d3 87. Qe5 $2 {Now it is all over.} (87. Qa3 Qd4+ 88. Kg2 Qe4+ 89. Kh3 Qe1 90. Qxd3 Ne4 91. Rc2 Nf2+ 92. Rxf2 Qxf2 {would enable White to fight on in the queen endgame}) 87... Qe4 $1 88. Qxe4 {Allowing the connected passed pawns offers no hope, but:} (88. Rb2 Qc4 89. Qe3 Ng4 90. Qd2 Qd4+ 91. Kh1 Ne3 {also wins for Black}) 88... fxe4 89. Kf2 Nd5 90. Ke1 Kf5 91. Rd1 e5 92. Kd2 exf4 93. gxf4 Nxf4 94. Ra1 Ke5 95. Ra6 h5 96. Ra8 f5 0-1


