1. Nf3 d5 2. b3 Bf5 3. Bb2 e6 4. d3 h6 5. Nbd2 Nf6 6. g3 {The game has transposed to a Reti system, where White meets Lasker's ...Bc8-f5 system with a double fianchetto. In this game, White successfully aims for the e2-e4 pawn break. Instead, the c2-c4 plan was part of Reti's own original opening concept, and leads to quieter play, for example:} (6. c4 c6 7. g3 Be7 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O Nbd7 {which is covered in Rapport-Carlsen in the Archives}) 6... c5 {A strategically risky idea. Black gains space but the combination of ....c7-c5 and the f5-bishop (which usually cannot return to the queenside) weakens the light squares. Black more often bolsters his central pawn chain with ...c7-c6. Here:} (6... Be7 7. Bg2 O-O 8. O-O c6 9. Re1 (9. Qe1 {is an alternative way of achieving the e2-e4 break. After} a5 10. a3 Bh7 11. e4 c5 12. Ne5 {we have the game Li Chao-Mareco, in the Archives.}) 9... Bh7 10. e4 {is analyzed in Fedoseev-Shankland in the Archives}) 7. Ne5 {A thematic move, controlling key squares in Black's camp and aiming for a turbo-charged e2-e4, which his opponent in fact allows. Alternatively:} (7. Bg2 Nc6 8. O-O Be7 9. e4 Bh7 {The e4-pawn cannot be captured since the g7-pawn would be hanging. However, the "reflex" retreat to the h7-square is not the best here.} (9... Bg6 {is more flexible and allows Black to activate the bishop with a possible ... Bg6-h5. This gives Black a better chance of equalizing.}) 10. Ne5 Nxe5 11. Bxe5 O-O 12. Qe2 Re8 13. Rad1 Nd7 14. Bb2 Bf6 15. e5 Be7 16. c4 {with a favourable structure for White - space advantage and play on the light squares, Grischuk, A (2766)-So,W (2778) Leuven (blitz) 2018 1/2-1/2 (35)}) (7. e4 {(!) may be White's most accurate move order. Some sample lines:} Bg4 {keeps the game in standard patterns, but White has gained a free tempo with e2-e4. Now one sample line is} (7... dxe4 $6 8. dxe4 Nxe4 {gives White a powerful initiative after} 9. Bb5+ Nc6 10. Bxc6+ bxc6 11. Qe2 Nxd2 (11... Qa5 12. O-O {and Black struggles to develop his kingside}) 12. O-O-O $1 Nxb3+ 13. axb3 Qc8 14. Ne5 {and White is clearly better despite a two pawn deficit.}) (7... Bh7 8. exd5 exd5 9. Qe2+ Be7 10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. Bh3 {gives White a firm grip on the light squares}) 8. h3 Bxf3 9. Nxf3 d4 10. Bg2 Nc6 11. Qe2 e5 12. h4 {with a good reversed King's Indian for White. Interestingly, this is one of those positions where the leading engines disagree on the assessment. LC0 gives White a small advantage while Stockfish 10 thinks Black is at least equal.}) 7... Nbd7 $6 {This move is the real culprit. Bear in mind that this was a Rapid playoff game - the rest of the game has a one-sided feel to it, but Wei Yi's execution of the light-squared strategy is very instructive for Reti players.} (7... Be7 {has also been tried. Now:} 8. e4 {is most efficient, for example} (8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O {White continues with routine development and misses his chance to exploit his opponent's setup.} (9. e4 {can still be tried}) 9... Bh7 10. c4 Nbd7 11. cxd5 Nxe5 12. Bxe5 Nxd5 {with level chances, Kharlov,A (2557)-Dreev,A (2655) Fuegen 2006 1-0 (56)}) 8... Bh7 9. Bg2 O-O 10. O-O Nbd7 11. Qe2 {with a pleasant position for White}) (7... Bd6 $1 {appears to give Black a satisfactory game. Now} 8. e4 Bxe5 9. Bxe5 Bg4 (9... Bg6 {is also OK}) 10. f3 Bh5 11. Bg2 Nc6 12. Bb2 O-O 13. O-O e5 {is roughly equal. Black's pawn centre constrains White's bishop pair.}) 8. e4 $1 Bh7 {Instead, capturing on the e4-square unmasks the f1-bishop. Some sample lines:} (8... dxe4 9. dxe4 Bxe4 (9... Bh7 10. Nxd7 Qxd7 11. a4 a6 12. Bg2 Be7 13. Qe2 O-O 14. Nc4 {gives White a clear positional advantage, his minor pieces are all better placed than their counterparts}) 10. Nxe4 Nxe5 11. Bb5+ Ke7 12. Bxe5 Nxe4 13. O-O Qxd1 14. Rfxd1 a6 15. Bf1 f6 16. Bg2 {and White retains a strong initiative despite the reduced material}) 9. Nxd7 Qxd7 10. Bg2 Qd8 $6 {White is already better, but after this further misstep Black ends up in a fairly hopeless position. Instead:} (10... Be7 11. e5 Ng8 {unfortunately, the only square for the knight} 12. c4 {and if} Bxd3 13. Qf3 Bg6 14. cxd5 exd5 15. Qxd5 Qxd5 16. Bxd5 {and White's minor pieces dominate}) (10... d4 {releases the tension and cedes more light squares, but this should be tried. White has various ways of continuing, including} 11. a4 Be7 12. Bc1 O-O 13. h4 {with a favourable King's Indian Attack for White, but the game continues.}) 11. exd5 exd5 {Or:} (11... Nxd5 12. O-O Qd7 13. Re1 O-O-O 14. Nc4 {and White will drum up an attack against Black's castled king}) 12. Qe2+ {A key intermediate check, aiming to double Black's f-pawns.} Be7 {Interposing with the queen just drops the d5-pawn:} (12... Qe7 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. Bxd5 {with a technically winning endgame to follow}) 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. O-O Bf5 15. Rae1 Be6 16. Qh5 Qd7 {Allowing an immediate breakthrough, although after:} (16... Kf8 17. Bh3 (17. f4 {is also strong}) 17... Qd7 18. Bxe6 fxe6 19. Nf3 {White will continue to improve his pieces with Nf3-h4 and activate his rooks. It is hard to see Black surviving at this level.}) 17. Rxe6 $1 Qxe6 18. Bxd5 {White gets two pawns for the exchange and an ongoing attack.} Qd7 (18... Qe5 19. Qxf7+ Kd8 20. Bxb7 {puts White ahead on material, with Black's king no closer to safety}) 19. Bxf7+ Kd8 20. Re1 Kc7 21. Be6 Qd8 22. Nc4 a6 {The light squares are so weak that Black is doomed in the long run, for example} (22... Rf8 23. Qf3 Bd6 24. Bd5 Rb8 25. Re6 {and White wins.}) 23. Bd5 Ra7 24. Qf7 Re8 25. Bf3 b5 {Or:} (25... Kb8 26. Re6 h5 27. Nd6 {winning material}) 26. Na5 Kb6 27. Nc6 1-0


