{Wei Yi, the current world junior number two behind Richard Rapport, started the Aeroflot Open badly by losing a miniature.} 1. c4 g6 2. e4 {An anti-Grunfeld line that has had a number of high-level outings in recent years. An anti-Grunfeld line that has had a number of high-level outings in recent years. An anti-Grünfeld line that has had a number of high-level outings in recent years.} e5 {This move takes the game into a line with its own unique flavour. Not the most usual move, but many Grunfeld players tried it against this move order.} ({Instead,} 2... Bg7 {will lead to a King's Indian or Modern Defence after} 3. d4 {which is usually not to the taste of the Grünfeld player.}) 3. d4 {The critical line. Instead} ({Instead} 3. Nf3 {leads to a Maroczy Bind/King's Indian hybrid after leads to a Maroczy Bind/King's Indian hybrid after leads to a Maroczy Bind/King's Indian hybrid after} Bg7 4. d4 exd4 5. Nxd4 Nf6 6. Nc3 {for example} O-O 7. Be2 Re8 8. f3 c6 9. Bf4 (9. Bg5 {but here Black can free his game with} d5 {was played in Lautier-Taddei, in the Archives} (9... Qb6 10. Qd2 d5 $1 {leading to a concrete line which equalized in A.Lenderman-W.So, USA Championship, Saint Louis 2016.})) 9... d5 10. cxd5 cxd5 11. Ndb5 Na6 12. O-O d4 13. Nd5 Nxd5 14. exd5 d3 15. Bxd3 Qxd5 {with equality, Ding, L (2749)-Wei, Y  (2724) Danzhou 2015 1/2-1/2 (30)}) 3... Nf6 4. Nf3 {Again the best move.} ({After} 4. dxe5 {was tried with success last year by So against Giri:} Nxe4 5. Bd3 Bb4+ (5... Nc5 $1 {is better is better , Black is doing well in theory and practice;}) 6. Kf1 $1 {is an early king move that led to success for White in So-Giri which can be found in the Archives is an early king move that led to success for White in So-Giri which can be found in the Archives on the other hand, was good for White in W.So-A.Giri, Shamkir 2015.} Nc5 7. Nf3 Ne6 8. a3 Be7 9. Nc3 {with a clear advanatge for White but it seems Black has the strong move 5....d5! 6.exd6 Nc5.}) 4... exd4 ({Black already has several alternatives here:} 4... Bg7 $6 {is dubious.} 5. dxe5 Nxe4 {and now:} 6. Bd3 $1 (6. Qd5 $6 f5 7. Nc3 c6 {and Black has no problems, E.Inarkiev-Xu Xiangyu, Chinese League 2016}) 6... Nc5 7. Bg5 f6 8. exf6 Bxf6 9. Qe2+ {and White will emerge on top.}) (4... Nxe4 5. Bd3 {and neither main move is fully satisfactory for Black:} Bb4+ (5... d5 6. O-O Nd6 {was played in L.Portisch-J.Timman, Buenos Aires Olympiad 1978, and here Timman gives the improvement} 7. Re1 $1 (7. Bg5 $1 {looks good as well}) 7... e4 8. Nc3 Bg7 9. Nxd5 {and White is much better.}) 6. Kf1 d5 7. Qb3 ({the sharp} 7. cxd5 {may be even stronger}) 7... c5 $2 (7... a5 8. a3 Be7 9. cxd5 Nf6 10. Nxe5 {is slightly better for White, as Black's weakened kingside is a permanent feature of the position}) 8. cxd5 Nf6 9. dxe5 Nxd5 10. Bg5 Qd7 11. a3 {led to a quick win for White after} b5 12. Be4 c4 13. Qc2 Ba5 14. Nc3 Bxc3 15. Bxd5 {1-0 in A.Miles-G.Wall, British League 1999.}) (4... Bb4+ 5. Bd2 {and now:} Qe7 {and here White can try the novelty} (5... Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 Nxe4 7. Qe3 {was played in several games from the early days of this variation:} f5 (7... d5 8. cxd5 Qxd5 {as played in T.Ghitescu-C.Meleghegyi, Zalaegerszeg 1979, but now White should play} 9. Nxe5 $1 O-O 10. Bc4 Qa5+ 11. Nc3 {when White has a strong initiative}) 8. dxe5 Qe7 {, was seen in J.Speelman-W.Hartston, Hastings 1978, and now} 9. Bd3 $1 Qb4+ 10. Nbd2 {:} Nxd2 (10... Qxb2 11. Rb1 Qc3 12. Bxe4 Qxe3+ 13. fxe3 fxe4 14. Nxe4 {and despite his split pawns, White is much better, for example} O-O ({or} 14... b6 15. Nf6+ Kf7 16. Nd5 Na6 17. O-O Kg7 18. Ng5 c6 19. Nf6 h6 20. Nge4 Rf8 21. Nd6 {and Black is tied up}) 15. O-O Nc6 16. Nf6+ Kg7 17. Nd5 {, picking up the c7-pawn.}) 11. Qxd2 Qxd2+ 12. Kxd2 {with slightly better chances for White, due to his space and development advantage.}) 6. Nxe5 $5 {, for example} Nxe4 7. Be2 Nxd2 8. Nxd2 O-O 9. O-O Nc6 10. Nef3 {with a better structure for White. The b4-bishop is awkwardly placed and likely has to be traded for the d2-knight.}) 5. e5 Ne4 {This has been played in almost all the modern games in this line;} ({but the older move} 5... Bb4+ {may be more solid, although not the kind of dynamic play the Grünfeld player is looking for:} 6. Bd2 Qe7 ({or} 6... Bxd2+ 7. Qxd2 Qe7 8. Be2 Nh5 9. Qxd4 Nc6 10. Qe3 d6 {, I.Stohl-D.Navara, Czech League 2002, and now after} 11. exd6 Qxe3 12. fxe3 cxd6 13. Nc3 {, White is better, as the weakness of the d6-pawn is more important than that of the e3-pawn}) 7. Bxb4 Qxb4+ 8. Qd2 Qxd2+ 9. Nbxd2 Nh5 10. Nxd4 Nc6 {. In this queenless middlegame White has:} 11. N2f3 $5 {is a new move, but seems to ask Black some questions, as 12 Nb5 is threatened. Black needs to respond with:} (11. Nxc6 dxc6 {enters a position with a similar pawn structure to the Berlin endgame, but with some differences – Black has castling rights but does not have the two bishops. Again, not what Black had in mind when he started out to play the Grünfeld with 1...g6. Now} 12. O-O-O Bf5 13. f3 Ng7 14. g4 Be6 (14... Bd7 {leaves the e6-square available for the g7-knight}) 15. Ne4 h5 {L.Polugaevsky-J.Timman, Bugojno 1980, and now} 16. h3 $1 {makes it harder for Black to equalize according to Timman.}) 11... a6 (11... O-O $6 12. Nb5 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Re8 14. O-O-O Rxe5 15. Nxc7 Rb8 16. Nd5 {is better for White as Black's d-pawn will be a liability}) 12. O-O-O O-O 13. g3 {and now two sample lines are:} f6 (13... Re8 14. Nxc6 dxc6 15. h3 Ng7 (15... Bf5 {can be met with the paradoxical} 16. Nd2 $1 {followed by g3-g4 and Nd2-e4}) 16. Bg2 Bf5 17. Rhe1 Rad8 18. Nd4 Bc8 19. Nb3 {and White can certainly play this version of the endgame for a win. At the moment, Black's queenside is frozen by White's minor pieces.}) 14. exf6 Nxf6 15. Bg2 Nxd4 16. Rxd4 {with a slightly better structure for White.}) 6. Qxd4 Bb4+ {[#]} 7. Kd1 $5 {A "caveman" move which had only been played once before. Potkin had only used a few minutes on the clock to this point, so had clearly prepared this surprise for his opponent. A "caveman" move which had only been played once before. Potkin had only used a few minutes on the clock to this point, so had clearly prepared this surprise for his opponent. A "caveman" move which had only been played once prior to this game. This move is not for the faint hearted, but as the game shows, even an amazing attacking player like Wei Yi was not able to deal with it from the Black side. It turns out that White's king is close to safety on the c1– or c2-squares, while Black's king will always be quite exposed on the kingside. There is clearly much to be explored here. !? An interesting idea by the 2011 European Champion.} (7. Nbd2 {is the normal move, when after is the other main move, and is certainly a decent backup to 7 Kd1. Now Black has two knight moves:} Nxd2 (7... Ng5 {was played in the earlier game Nakamura-Svidler - see the Archives was played in the earlier game Nakamura-Svidler - see the Archives has a bit more spice to it. After} 8. Be2 Nc6 9. Qe3 Nxf3+ 10. Bxf3 O-O 11. O-O Re8 {, White can now try} 12. Bd5 {which is a new move suggested by Volokitin. After} d6 13. Ne4 Rxe5 14. Qg3 Nd4 15. Qd3 c6 {, Svidler gives a long line which starts} 16. Bxf7+ Kxf7 17. Qxd4 Bf5 18. Ng3 Qf6 19. Be3 Kg8 20. Bf4 Re6 21. Qxf6 Rxf6 22. a3 Bc5 23. b4 Bd4 24. Rad1 c5 {, when White is the one pressing, but Black should be able to hold.}) 8. Bxd2 Nc6 9. Qf4 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 Qe7 11. O-O-O {with chances for both sides, as seen in Svidler, P (2751)-Gelfand, B (2753) Jerusalem 2014 1/2-1/2 (39) and Svidler, P (2753)-Carlsen, M (2881) Flor & Fjaere 2014 0-1 (37)} b6 {was played in a few games with a roughly equal game.} 12. Bd3 Bb7 13. Be4 O-O-O 14. Rhe1 f6 15. exf6 Qxf6 16. Qg5 Qg7 17. h4 Rhe8 {with balanced chances, P.Svidler-M.Carlsen, Flor & Fjaere (blitz) 2014.} (17... Z0)) 7... f5 {The only move, since The only move, since The only move; The only way to defend the knight properly.} ({since} 7... Nc5 {is answered by} 8. Bg5 {while while ;}) ({while} 7... d5 {isn't possible because of} 8. cxd5 {.}) 8. exf6 {Because Black's last move was forced, White can now open up the position around Black's king. The dark squares are weak with Black's bishop absent on b4. Because Black's last move was forced, White can now open up the position around Black's king. The dark squares are weak with Black's bishop absent on b4. Because Black's last move was forced, White can now open up the position around Black's king. The dark squares are weak with Black's bishop absent on the b4-square.} Nxf6 9. Qh4 {The only other game to reach this position continued The novelty.} ({The only other game to reach this position continued} 9. Bh6 {was played in Nabaty-Fier 2015, but Black has the strong reply} Qe7 $6 (9... Nc6 $1 {is better !} 10. Qf4 d5 {!} 11. Bg7 Rf8 {!} 12. Bxf8 Kxf8 {with more than compensation for the exchange.}) 10. Bd3 Nc6 11. Qh4 d5 12. a3 Ng4 13. Bg5 Qd6 {and now Black would be in big trouble after} {Black would be in big trouble after} 14. axb4 {, for example} (14. Kc1 Bc5 15. Re1+ {1/2-1/2 was agreed drawn here in Nabaty, T (2590)-Fier, A (2601) Skopje 2015, although White can still play for a win after 1/2-1/2 was agreed drawn here in Nabaty, T (2590)-Fier, A (2601) Skopje 2015, although White can still play for a win after was agreed drawn here in T.Nabaty-A.Fier, Skopje 2015, although White can still play for a win after} Kf7 16. Re2 {etc.}) 14... dxc4 15. Re1+ Kf7 16. Kc1 cxd3 17. h3 {and White has a winning position and White has a winning position and White has a winning position}) (9. Bg5 {is also a decent try but Black has some ways to play. The easiest is} Be7 10. Nc3 Nc6 11. Qh4 (11. Qd2 d6 {∞}) 11... d5) 9... d5 {Played after 26 minutes thought. Opening up the d-file leading to the White king is a hard move to resist, although the engine prefers piece development with Played after 26 minutes thought. Opening up the d-file leading to the White king is a hard move to resist, although the engine prefers 