1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nc6 {This was the second classical game in a two game knock-out match, and was a must win for Wei Yi, after he had lost the first game with White. He does his best to mix things up right in the opening by calling upon Harry the h-pawn! The specific line he chose is new to this site, although we have looked at similar ideas such as:} (2... h5 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nd5 a5 5. a3 Bc5 6. e3 {- see Bruzon Batista-Rakhmanov in the Archives}) 3. Bg2 h5 $5 {This has been tried a few times by Nepomniachtchi (in rapid and blitz games), albeit with a different follow up on the 4th move.} 4. h3 {This is fine for White, of course, but I always feel that reacting with such a move slightly justifies Black's early h-pawn thrust. Instead:} (4. d3 h4 5. g4 {isn't a great answer. After} h3 6. Be4 Nf6 7. Bg5 Be7 8. Bxf6 {which was played in Ivanchuk,V (2757) -Nepomniachtchi,I (2766) Leuven (Rapid) 2017 1-0 (74), the simple} Bxf6 {leaves Black already slightly better due to his control of the dark squares.}) (4. Nf3 $1 {is sharper and looks good. Now:} h4 (4... e4 5. Nh4 g5 (5... Be7 {can be met by} 6. Nf5) 6. Nf5 d5 7. cxd5 Qxd5 8. Ne3 Qe5 9. Nc3 f5 {Queiroz da Costa,A (1562)-Pereira,G (2006) Florianopolis 2018 0-1 (41) leaves Black way over-extended. After} 10. d3 $1 {his edifice will soon collapse}) 5. Nxh4 Rxh4 6. gxh4 Qxh4 7. d3 Bc5 8. e3 {doesn't give Black enough for the exchange, Bartel,M (2629)-Maier,C (2354) Basel 2013 1/2-1/2 (28), although Black did end up drawing somehow.}) 4... d6 {Instead, Nepo's practice has seen him score a lot of wins in blitz from questionable but double edged opening positions:} (4... Bc5 5. Nc3 d6 {and now:} 6. d3 (6. e3 Be6 7. b3 Nge7 8. Nge2 d5 9. d4 exd4 10. exd4 Bb4 11. O-O Bxc3 (11... Qd7 12. cxd5 (12. Kh2 {is called for}) 12... Nxd5 13. Nxd5 Bxd5 14. Bxd5 Qxd5 15. Nf4 Qf5 16. d5 Ne5 {and Black took over the initiative in Le,Q (2714)-Nepomniachtchi,I (2763) St Petersburg (blitz) 2018 0-1 (57)}) 12. Nxc3 Qd7 13. cxd5 Nxd5 {was Ding,L (2805)-Nepomniachtchi,I (2773) Abidjan (blitz) 2019 0-1 (42), and here} 14. Ne4 {followed by Ne4-c5 is better for White}) 6... Nge7 7. Nf3 a6 8. a3 f6 9. b4 (9. e3 {followed by d3-d4 leaves White with more space and a better pawn structure}) 9... Ba7 10. e3 Be6 11. Bb2 Qd7 12. Qc2 d5 {and Black had again achieved good counterplay, and won in Svidler,P (2729)-Nepomniachtchi,I (2774) Amsterdam (blitz) 2019 0-1 (65)}) 5. Nc3 h4 6. g4 f5 7. gxf5 Bxf5 8. d3 Nf6 {At this point, Black was probably happy to have achieved an unbalanced fighting position, even if objectively White should be able to claim an edge. An earlier game saw:} (8... Qd7 9. e4 Be6 10. Nge2 (10. Nf3 {is more active and leaves White slightly for choice}) 10... g6 11. Be3 Bg7 12. Qd2 {Moor,R (2392)-Degtiarev,E (2425) Switzerland 2015 1-0 (38), and now} O-O-O {takes Black's king to safety, with at least a balanced position}) 9. Nf3 Be7 10. d4 {White goes for a queen trade, perhaps in an attempt to clarify the situation, although in fact the queenless middlegame is far from clear.} (10. Qb3 {puts the question to the b7-pawn, so that after} Rb8 {Black's king doesn't have an obvious safe haven. Now} 11. Be3 {looks pleasant and fairly low risk for White}) 10... Qd7 11. dxe5 dxe5 12. Qxd7+ Nxd7 13. O-O O-O-O 14. Nd5 Bf6 {Black has completed development, while it is not so easy for White to do the same.} 15. Be3 e4 16. Nd2 Rhe8 {Black should probably grab the b-pawn with:} (16... Bxb2 17. Rab1 Ba3 {and if now} 18. Nxe4 Nde5 {targeting the weak c4-pawn leaves Black better}) 17. Nxf6 gxf6 18. Rac1 Nf8 19. Nb1 Bh7 20. Nc3 f5 21. Nd5 $14 Ne6 22. Rcd1 Rf8 23. f4 Rd7 {Black invites White to pick up the h4-pawn - a double edged decision. After:} (23... Bg6 24. Bf2 Rh8 {the chances are roughly even}) 24. Bf2 Rg7 25. Bxh4 Ncd4 26. Rd2 c6 27. Ne3 {White could leave the knight where it stood and get off the g-file pin with:} (27. Kh1 $1 {since} cxd5 28. cxd5 Rfg8 29. dxe6 Nxe6 30. Rc1+ Kb8 31. e3 {gives White a huge advantage. He has an extra pawn and Black's minor pieces are stymied.}) 27... Bg6 28. Kh2 Bh5 29. Rf2 Rd7 30. Bf1 a5 31. Ng2 a4 32. Kh1 $6 {A strange move, wasting a tempo and leaving the h3-pawn loose.} (32. Bg5 {was called for}) 32... Rh7 33. Bg5 {Now:} (33. Kh2 {"back" is more solid}) 33... c5 {Instead:} (33... Nxg5 34. fxg5 Ne6 35. Rd6 Nxg5 {leaves Black well on top. White is passive and his kingside is weak.}) 34. h4 Re8 35. Ne3 Reh8 $6 (35... Nxg5 {maintains the advantage}) 36. Rh2 {Missing a chance to turn the tables with:} (36. Bf6 Rg8 37. Bh3 {and suddenly White is pressing on Black's weak pawns.}) 36... Nxg5 37. fxg5 $2 {The wrong recapture. Instead:} (37. hxg5 $1 {is OK tactically, for example} Bf3+ 38. exf3 Nxf3 39. Rxh7 Rxh7+ 40. Kg2 Rh2+ 41. Kg3 Rxd2 42. Bh3 {and White has enough compensation for the exchange}) 37... f4 {Now Black crashes through} 38. Nd5 e3 39. Rxd4 {Or:} (39. Rd3 Bg6 {followed by ...Rh7xh4}) (39. Rd1 f3 {and Black wins}) 39... cxd4 40. Nxf4 Be8 41. Kg2 Rxh4 42. Rxh4 Rxh4 {Here White doesn't have enough for the exchange. Black manages to contain the passed g-pawn and wraps up the win.} 43. Kg3 Rh1 44. Bh3+ Kc7 45. Ne6+ Kd6 46. Nxd4 Rb1 47. Kf4 Rxb2 48. Bf5 Rxa2 49. g6 a3 50. g7 Bf7 51. Bh7 Rxe2 52. Nb5+ Kc5 53. Nxa3 Ra2 0-1


