1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 {This was the second classical game in a two game knock-out match, and was a must win for Wei Yi, after he had lost the first game with White. He does his best to mix things up right in the opening by calling upon Harry the h-pawn! The specific line he chose is new to this site, although we have looked at similar ideas such as:} 3. Nc3 d5 $5 {This has been tried a few times by Nepomniachtchi (in rapid and blitz games), albeit with a different follow up on the 4th move.} 4. d4 {This is fine for White, of course, but I always feel that reacting with such a move slightly justifies Black's early h-pawn thrust. Instead:} c6 {Instead, Nepo's practice has seen him score a lot of wins in blitz from questionable but double edged opening positions:} 5. Bd2 dxc4 6. e4 b5 7. e5 Nd5 8. Ne4 Be7 {At this point, Black was probably happy to have achieved an unbalanced fighting position, even if objectively White should be able to claim an edge. An earlier game saw:} (8... Nd7) 9. b3 cxb3 10. axb3 {White goes for a queen trade, perhaps in an attempt to clarify the situation, although in fact the queenless middlegame is far from clear.} Na6 11. Bd3 (11. Ba5 Qd7 12. Bd3 c5 13. Rc1) 11... Nab4 12. Bb1 a5 13. Bg5 O-O 14. h4 (14. O-O Bxg5 15. Nexg5 h6 16. Ne4) 14... Ra7 {Black has completed development, while it is not so easy for White to do the same.} (14... a4 {is more active and leaves White slightly for choice} 15. bxa4 bxa4 16. Rxa4 {and now:} Ba6) 15. Bxe7 Qxe7 16. g4 (16. O-O {takes Black's king to safety, with at least a balanced position}) 16... f6 {Black should probably grab the b-pawn with:} (16... a4 17. bxa4 bxa4 18. Qd2 a3 {Moor,R (2392)-Degtiarev,E (2425) Switzerland 2015 1-0 (38), and now}) 17. exf6 gxf6 (17... Nxf6 18. Ne5 {and suddenly White is pressing on Black's weak pawns.} Nxe4 {maintains the advantage} 19. Bxe4 c5 20. g5 (20. Rc1 Rc7) 20... Qd6 21. O-O {leaves Black well on top. White is passive and his kingside is weak.} (21. Bxh7+ {was called for} Kxh7 $1 {since} 22. g6+ Kg8 23. Qh5 Nc2+ 24. Kf1 Rf5 25. Qh7+ Kf8 {gives White a huge advantage. He has an extra pawn and Black's minor pieces are stymied.} 26. Qh8+ Ke7 27. Qxg7+ {the chances are roughly even} Ke8 28. Qxa7 Qxd4 {and if now} 29. Qe7+ Kxe7 {targeting the weak c4-pawn leaves Black better} 30. Nc6+ {puts the question to the b7-pawn, so that after} Kf6 {Black's king doesn't have an obvious safe haven. Now} 31. Nxd4 {looks pleasant and fairly low risk for White} cxd4) 21... g6 {"back" is more solid}) 18. g5 e5 19. gxf6 Nxf6 20. Nxe5 Bf5 21. Rg1+ $14 (21. Nc5 Bxb1 22. Rxb1 {and White has enough compensation for the exchange} Nfd5) 21... Kh8 22. Ng5 Nd7 23. Bxf5 Nxe5 {Black invites White to pick up the h4-pawn - a double edged decision. After:} 24. dxe5 Qxe5+ 25. Kf1 Nd5 26. Ra2 Rd7 27. Qa1 {White could leave the knight where it stood and get off the g-file pin with:} Qxa1+ 28. Rxa1 Rxf5 29. Rxa5 Kg7 30. Ra6 Nb4 31. Ra1 Kh6 32. Re1 $6 {A strange move, wasting a tempo and leaving the h3-pawn loose.} Rf6 33. Rg3 {Now:} Nd5 {Instead:} 34. Ne4 Rf4 35. Ng5 Re7 $6 36. Rxe7 {Missing a chance to turn the tables with:} Nxe7 37. Re3 $2 {The wrong recapture. Instead:} Ng6 {Now Black crashes through} 38. Nf3 c5 39. Rc3 {Or:} b4 40. Rd3 c4 41. bxc4 Rxc4 42. Rd6 Kh5 {Here White doesn't have enough for the exchange. Black manages to contain the passed g-pawn and wraps up the win.} 43. Rd5+ Kg4 44. Ne5+ Nxe5 45. Rxe5 Kxh4 46. Kg2 Kg4 47. Re7 h5 48. Rb7 h4 49. Rg7+ Kf4 50. Rh7 Ke5 51. Rh5+ Kd6 52. Rb5 Kc6 53. Rb8 Kc5 54. Kf3 Kd4 {followed by ...Rh7xh4} 55. Ke2 Kc3 {and Black wins} 56. Kd1 $1 {is OK tactically, for example} Kb2 57. Rf8 b3 58. f4 h3 59. Rh8 Rc1+ 0-1


