1. b3 e5 2. Bb2 Nc6 3. e3 g6 {Black wants to play a King's-Indian style setup. This is an interesting move-order that I last looked at in the September 2018 Update.} 4. h4 $6 {It is hard to be shocked by an early h4-thrust these days! This one has been played several times by (you guessed it) 1 b3 guru Baadur Jobava, albeit it in blitz and rapid games. Antipov bravely ventures it in an important classical game. Instead, the level-headed alternative:} (4. c4 Bg7 5. Nf3 d6 6. d4 {is analyzed in Fedoseev-Vitiugov in the Archives.}) 4... Nf6 {Wei Yi calls White's bluff, going for fast development rather reacting to the h-pawn. There are only about a dozen games in the database featuring 5 h4, and Black's most popular reply has in fact been the alternative:} (4... h5 {but if this is indeed Black's best move, it tends to justify 5 h4. Now} 5. Nf3 Bg7 6. c4 d6 7. d3 {and Black has played:} Nge7 (7... Nf6 8. Nc3 a6 9. Be2 Ne7 $6 10. Qc2 (10. d4 $1 {would give White a pleasant position}) 10... Nf5 11. O-O-O Ng4 12. Ne4 O-O 13. Nfg5 c6 14. Bxg4 hxg4 15. h5 f6 16. hxg6 $6 fxg5 {when White didn't get enough for the sacrificed piece, Jobava,B (2627)-Svidler, P (2737) St Petersburg 2018 (blitz) 0-1 (30)}) 8. Nbd2 a5 9. a3 O-O 10. Qc2 Rb8 11. Be2 {is the subject of Jobava-Dubov in the Archives}) 5. Bb5 {White's has also essayed the "Harry" move:} (5. h5 {and now:} g5 $6 (5... Nxh5 $1 {is the engine's cold-blooded suggestion. Now} 6. Be2 (6. Rxh5 gxh5 7. Qxh5 d6 {doesn't appear to give White enough compensation}) 6... Nf6 7. Nf3 d6 {just looks like a pawn up for Black.}) 6. Bb5 d6 7. d4 Bd7 8. dxe5 (8. Ne2 {promises White good play on the light squares}) 8... dxe5 9. Nf3 Bb4+ 10. Nbd2 Ne4 11. a3 Bc3 12. Qc1 g4 13. Bd3 gxf3 14. Bxe4 fxg2 15. Bxg2 Bxb2 16. Qxb2 Qe7 17. O-O-O {and White was more active in Artemiev,V (2696)-Dubov,D (2677) Sochi (blitz) 2017 1-0 (29)}) 5... Qe7 $1 {The first new move, deviating from an earlier Jobava game:} (5... d6 6. Ne2 Bg7 7. d4 exd4 8. Nxd4 Bd7 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. Bd3 h5 11. Nc3 O-O 12. Qd2 a5 13. O-O-O c5 14. f3 a4 {and in this opposite-side castling scenario, Black's attack was faster, Jobava,B (2690)-Le, Q (2737) Riadh (blitz) 2017 0-1 (31)}) 6. Nf3 $6 {White's position already doesn't appear to hang together very well, and he soon ends up clearly worse. Here:} (6. Nc3 {just developing, may be a better try.} a6 7. Bc4 d6 8. Nd5 Nxd5 9. Bxd5 {although White is short of equality.}) 6... e4 {One of the points of Black's last move is that the e4-pawn is well protected.} 7. Ng5 Bg7 8. Nc3 O-O $1 {Defending against the threat of Nc3xe4, and not fearing ghosts by castling "into it".} 9. h5 d5 {It is nice to see that the classical principles still  (sometimes) apply - meeting White's flank demonstration with strong control of the centre!} 10. hxg6 fxg6 11. Bxc6 {It becomes obvious that White's opening strategy has gone badly wrong. Here:} (11. d4 {not giving up the light-squared bishop, may be more resilient, although after} exd3 12. Bxd3 h6 13. Nf3 Bg4 {Black keeps a strong initiative.}) 11... bxc6 12. Qe2 Bg4 13. Qa6 $6 {White leaves his king in the centre, trapped by the g4-bishop. Instead:} (13. f3 exf3 14. gxf3 Bh5 15. O-O-O {at least gets the king to safety. After} h6 16. Nh3 Ne4 {Black is still much better.}) 13... Nh5 14. Nh3 Qe6 15. Rf1 {It is hard to give White any good advice here, and Black has a number of ways to convert this position. Wei Yi's method is very precise and elegant.} Be5 16. Na4 Bxb2 17. Nxb2 Qe5 18. c3 Qh2 {White's kingside collapses.} 19. Nf4 Rxf4 $1 {Establishing a monster knight on the f4-square.} 20. exf4 Nxf4 21. f3 exf3 22. gxf3 Bc8 $1 {A nice finishing touch. White's queen has no squares that prevent mate on the e2-square.} 0-1


