1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. b3 b6 {Black wants to play a King's-Indian style setup. This is an interesting move-order that I last looked at in the September 2018 Update.} 4. Bb2 $6 {It is hard to be shocked by an early h4-thrust these days! This one has been played several times by (you guessed it) 1 b3 guru Baadur Jobava, albeit it in blitz and rapid games. Antipov bravely ventures it in an important classical game. Instead, the level-headed alternative:} Bb7 {Wei Yi calls White's bluff, going for fast development rather reacting to the h-pawn. There are only about a dozen games in the database featuring 5 h4, and Black's most popular reply has in fact been the alternative:} 5. Nc3 {White's has also essayed the "Harry" move:} Nc6 $1 {The first new move, deviating from an earlier Jobava game:} 6. d4 $6 {White's position already doesn't appear to hang together very well, and he soon ends up clearly worse. Here:} cxd4 {One of the points of Black's last move is that the e4-pawn is well protected.} 7. Nxd4 Nf6 8. Nxc6 Bxc6 $1 {Defending against the threat of Nc3xe4, and not fearing ghosts by castling "into it".} 9. Bd3 Bb4 {It is nice to see that the classical principles still  (sometimes) apply - meeting White's flank demonstration with strong control of the centre!} 10. Qf3 (10. O-O) 10... Qb8 (10... Qc7 $6 11. O-O-O Rc8 12. Ne2) 11. O-O-O {It becomes obvious that White's opening strategy has gone badly wrong. Here:} Bd6 (11... Qe5 12. Ne2 Qc5 (12... Qg5+ 13. Kb1 Qg4 14. Qe3 Bc5 {and in this opposite-side castling scenario, Black's attack was faster, Jobava,B (2690)-Le, Q (2737) Riadh (blitz) 2017 0-1 (31)} 15. Bd4 {and now:}) 13. Kb1 Ba3 14. Ba1 a5) 12. g3 Be5 13. Qe3 $6 {White leaves his king in the centre, trapped by the g4-bishop. Instead:} Ng4 14. Qe2 Nf6 15. f4 {It is hard to give White any good advice here, and Black has a number of ways to convert this position. Wei Yi's method is very precise and elegant.} Bd4 16. Kb1 O-O 17. e5 Bxc3 (17... Bxh1 {although White is short of equality.} 18. exf6 Bc6 19. Bxh7+ Kxh7 20. Qh5+ Kg8 21. Nd5) 18. exf6 Bxb2 {White's kingside collapses.} 19. Kxb2 gxf6 $1 {Establishing a monster knight on the f4-square.} (19... g6 20. Rhf1) 20. Qg4+ Kh8 21. Qh4 f5 22. Qf6+ Kg8 $1 {A nice finishing touch. White's queen has no squares that prevent mate on the e2-square.} 23. g4 Qd8 24. Qh6 f6 25. gxf5 {at least gets the king to safety. After} Qe7 26. Rhe1 Bd5 {Black is still much better.} 27. fxe6 {not giving up the light-squared bishop, may be more resilient, although after} dxe6 28. Bxh7+ (28. Bxh7+ Qxh7 29. Rg1+ {Black keeps a strong initiative.} Kh8 {just developing, may be a better try.} 30. Qxh7+ Kxh7 31. Rd3) 0-1


