1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6 4. O-O Bd7 5. Re1 Nf6 6. c3 {One of White's many attempts to try and gain an edge against the 5...e6 Fischer system} a6 $5 {A typical move in the Fischer system, but a bold one to play before completing development. Wei Yi had played the same move in 2015, so presumably Adams was prepared for this. Instead} 7. Ba4 (7. Bxc6 Bxc6 8. d4) 7... b5 (7... c4 8. d4 cxd3 9. Bg5 b5 (9... e6 10. Qxd3 g6 11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. e5 dxe5 13. Nxe5 Ra7 14. Qf3 (14. Nxc6 Bxc6 15. Qxd8+ Kxd8 16. Bxf6+ Be7 17. Bxh8) 14... Be7 15. Nd2 h6 16. Be3 Rb7 17. Ne4 Rh7 18. Nxf6+ Bxf6 19. Nxd7 Rxd7 20. Rad1 Be5 21. Qxc6) (9... Ne5 10. Bxd7+ Nfxd7 11. Nd4 Qb6 12. b3 g6 13. Be3 Qc7 14. c4) 10. Bb3 Ne5 11. Nxe5 dxe5 12. Qxd3 e6 13. Nd2 h6 14. Bh4 Bc6 15. Qxd8+ Rxd8 16. Nf3 Bd6 17. a4) 8. Bc2 {White has also played:} Rc8 (8... Bg4 9. d3 (9. h3 Bxf3 10. Qxf3 g6 11. a4 Rb8 12. axb5 axb5 13. Na3 Bg7 14. Nxb5 O-O (14... Rxb5 15. e5 Nxe5 16. Rxe5 dxe5 17. Qc6+ Qd7 18. Ra8+ Rb8 19. Rxb8#) 15. Na3) (9. d4 cxd4 10. cxd4 Bxf3 11. gxf3) 9... e6 10. Nbd2 Be7 11. h3 Bh5 12. Nf1 O-O (12... Nd7 13. Ng3 Bg6 14. d4 cxd4 15. Nxd4 Nxd4 16. cxd4 O-O 17. Nf5 Rc8 18. Bd3 exf5 19. exf5 Bg5 20. fxg6 hxg6 21. Bxg5 Qxg5) 13. Ng3 Bg6 14. Nh4 Nd7 15. Nxg6 hxg6 16. Be3 d5 17. Ne2 Nb6 18. d4 Nc4 19. exd5 exd5 20. Bc1 cxd4 21. cxd4 Bf6 22. b3 Nd6 23. Ba3 Re8 24. Bc5 Ne4 25. Rc1 Bg5 26. f4 Bh4 27. Rf1 Nxc5 28. dxc5 Qe7 29. Bd3 (29. Bxg6 fxg6 30. Qxd5+ Qe6 31. Nc3) 29... Nb4) (8... e5 9. h3 (9. d4 cxd4 10. cxd4 Bg4 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Bf4 Bxf3 13. gxf3 Nh5 14. Bxe5 dxe5) 9... Be7 (9... g6 10. d4 Bg7 11. Be3 cxd4 12. cxd4 exd4 13. Nxd4 O-O 14. Nc3 b4 15. Nxc6 Bxc6 16. Nd5 Nxd5 17. exd5 Bb5 18. Rb1 Re8) 10. d3 O-O 11. Nbd2 Qc7 12. Nf1 d5 13. exd5 Nxd5 14. Ng5 h6 15. Ne4 f5 16. Neg3 Kh8) 9. a4 g6 (9... e5) 10. axb5 axb5 11. d4 cxd4 (11... Bg4 12. dxc5 dxc5 13. Qe2 Qb6 14. Na3 c4 15. h3) 12. cxd4 Bg4 (12... Bg7 13. Nc3 b4 14. Nd5) 13. Nc3 b4 {The first new move, varying from Wei Yi's earlier game, which continued} (13... Bxf3 14. gxf3 b4 15. Ba4 bxc3 16. d5) 14. Ne2 (14. Nd5 Bg7 (14... Nxd5 15. exd5 Nb8 16. Ba4+ Bd7 (16... Nd7 17. h3) 17. Qb3) 15. Ba4 (15. Bg5) 15... O-O 16. Bxc6 Rxc6 17. Qa4) 14... Bg7 {According to the official site, Wei Yi thought for almost an hour on this move!} (14... Bxf3 15. gxf3) (14... d5 15. Ne5 {was Ipatov-Cmilyte} Nxe5 16. dxe5 Nxe4 $6 {is the speculative piece sac which worked as a one game weapon in Radjabov-Ivanchuk} 17. f3 Rxc2 18. Qxc2 Qb6+ 19. Nd4 Qxd4+ 20. Be3 Qc4 21. Ra8+) 15. d5 $6 {This cedes some key squares to Black's control, and in the long term exposes White's advanced h-pawn to attack from the g6-square} Bxf3 (15... Ne5 16. Nxe5 dxe5 17. Ba4+ Bd7 18. Qd3 O-O 19. Bd2) 16. gxf3 Ne5 {Guarding the b7-bishop before activating the c6-knight} 17. Ba4+ Nfd7 18. Nd4 O-O 19. f4 Nc4 {Any slight initiative that Adams had has gone and now it is White that needs to be careful} 20. Nc6 Rxc6 (20... Qe8 {was Milov-Sermek} 21. Qb3) 21. dxc6 $6 {Creating more weaknesses} (21. Bxc6 Nxb2 22. Qe2 Nd3) 21... Nc5 22. Qe2 (22. Qc2) (22. e5) 22... Nb6 $6 23. Bb5 {Relieving some of the pressure, though Black is still somewhat better} Nb3 24. Ra6 (24. Ra7 {is another natural reply that leads to lines we have covered in the Archives:} Nd4 25. Qd3 Qc8 26. Rb7 Qg4+ 27. Qg3) 24... Nd4 25. Qd3 Na8 (25... Qb8 26. Bd2 {winning a pawn}) 26. Ra4 (26. Ra7 Qb6 (26... Nc7 27. Ba4) 27. Rb7 {penetrating on the dark squares}) 26... Nc7 27. Rxb4 (27. Bc4 Nxc6 {puts Black in a tough spot, for example} 28. Rd1 {or}) 27... Qb8 (27... Ncxb5 28. Rxb5 Nxb5 29. Qxb5 Qc7 {was a quick draw in Ribli, Z (2610)-Sosonko, G (2545) Amsterdam 1980 1/2-1/2 (17)} 30. Re2 $5 {has not been tested, but may be White's best try. It keeps more tension in the position since after} Rb8 31. Qc4 {Black cannot simplify as in the main game with} Qc8 $6 {since} 32. f5 $1) 28. Rxd4 Bxd4 29. Qxd4 Qxb5 30. f5 (30. Qc3 Rc8 31. b4 Na6 32. Bb2 f6) 30... Rc8 31. Bh6 {White's h6-pawn has dropped off, but he is now able to centralize his pieces and keep Black's advantages within bounds} (31. f6 {would give White an advantage} exf6 {is better, and Black should be fine} (31... Ne6 32. Qd5) 32. Qxf6 Ne6 (32... Qxc6 33. Bh6 Ne6) 33. Bd2) 31... Ne8 32. e5 (32. Ra1 Qxc6 33. Ra7 $6 {Hillarp Persson, T (2564) -Wiedenkeller, M (2479) Borlange 2014 1-0 (28), and here}) 32... Rxc6 33. exd6 Rxd6 34. Qe5 Qxe5 35. Rxe5 Rd7 36. Rc5 (36. Rb5) 36... f6 37. fxg6 hxg6 38. Be3 Rb7 39. Bd4 (39. Rc2) 39... Kf7 40. Kg2 Nd6 41. Bc3 {Black's weak f5-pawn makes it hard for him to improve his position} e5 42. Ra5 (42. Rc6) 42... Nc4 43. Ra1 Rb6 (43... Nxb2 44. Rb1 {when Black's h7-pawn is terminally weak}) 44. b4 Nd6 45. Rb1 (45. Kf3) 45... Ke6 46. Bd2 f5 47. Be3 Rb7 48. Bc5 (48. f3) 48... Ne4 {Black has made no progress and he soon decides to call it a day} 49. Rd1 Rc7 50. Bb6 Rc6 51. Ba7 (51. Ba5 Rc2 52. Bb6 Rb2 53. Bc5 g5) 51... Ra6 52. Be3 (52. Bc5 Nxc5 53. bxc5 Rc6 54. Rc1 {Zeng, C (2541)-Wei, Y (2706) China 2015 1/2-1/2 (33), and here} Kd5 $1 {would give White a significant edge, for example}) 52... f4 53. Bc1 (53. Bc5) 53... Ra4 {gives Black a tangible advantage, since here the freeing move} 54. Re1 {is not an option due to} Kf5 55. Bb2 Rxb4 {and Black breaks through} 56. Bxe5 (56. Re2 Rb5) 56... f3+ 57. Kxf3 Kxe5 58. Kg4 {is preferable} Kf6 {is better, although Black is OK as long as he plays} 59. f4 {to keep the d-file closed} Nf2+ 60. Kg3 Nd3 61. Rf1 Kf5 1/2-1/2


