1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. a4 Nc6 {In practice, this move has shown to work well in order to get a draw as Black.} 8. Qe2 {The most direct path, but there are other possibilities:} Qc7 9. Nc3 Bd6 10. b3 O-O 11. Bb2 b6 12. d5 $1 (12. Rad1 h6 13. Kh1 Re8 $11 14. d5 $5 $146 {I like this quiet continuation, and it would probably be my improvement if I have to face this position over the board. It's a bit provocative, but it's also actually logical since it stops the action of the bishop on d6.} exd5 {Maybe the only way to try to exploit White's slow development.} 15. Nxd5 Nxd5 16. Bxd5 Be6 17. e4 $1 Bxd5 18. Rxd5 Nb4 19. Rh5 Qc6 20. Bxg7 Kxg7 21. Qb2+ $14 {We played the strange looking move g2-g3, but the other criteria claims that it is a good version of an isolani for White.} Kg8 $2 22. Rxh6 Be5) (12. h3 $17 Bb7 13. Rfd1 cxd4 14. exd4 Na5 15. d5 Nxc4 16. bxc4 Rfe8 17. Qd3 Rac8 18. Ng5 $14 h6 19. Nge4 Bh2+ 20. Kh1 $1 Be5 21. d6 Qc6 22. Nxf6+ $11 Bxf6 23. f3 Red8) (12. Rfd1 Bb7 13. d5 (13. Rac1 Rfd8 14. h3 $14 Na5 15. Ne5 cxd4 16. exd4 Nxc4 17. Nxc4 Bh2+ 18. Kh1 Bf4) 13... Ne5 (13... exd5) 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 15. dxe6 $14 Bxh2+ 16. Kh1 fxe6 17. f4 Bg3 18. Bxe6+ Kh8 19. Bd5) 12... Ne5 (12... exd5 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. Bxd5 $15 {Objectively equal, but with the rook on a3, Black is the one pressing.} Bb7 $1 {This is more straightforward in order to achieve a draw.} 15. Qc4 Rae8 16. Rad1 Ne5 17. Bxe5 Bxe5 18. Bxb7 Qxb7 $11 19. Nxe5 $5 {This has been played in the two other games that reached this position, and I think it's more precise.} Rxe5 20. Rd6 $1 {The only chance for White to get something.} b5 21. Qc2 Rfe8 22. Rfd1) (12... Na5 13. dxe6 (13. e4 Ng4 14. h3 Nh2 15. Rfd1 Nxf3+ 16. Qxf3 Bh2+ {1/2-1/2 (25) Bauer,C (2646)-Ragger,M (2658) Austria 2015} 17. Kh1 $1 {Black still has to fight a bit to achieve a draw, but the thing is we don't really know how White will make any progress.} Be5 $44) 13... Nxc4 14. exf7+ Qxf7 15. bxc4 (15. Qxc4 $11 {I won't go deeper in this line. White had small chances but still couldn't get more than a draw in ½-½ (54) Topalov,V (2785)-Anand,V (2770) Khanty-Mansiysk 2014.} Be6) 15... Bg4) 13. Nxe5 {White has gained a pawn. Black finds immediately a solution for his king} Bxe5 $1 14. dxe6 $6 Bxh2+ (14... Bxe6 $1 {It was important to prevent the rook from invading the second rank.} 15. Bxe6 $1 fxe6 16. f4 Bxc3 17. Bxc3 Ne4 18. Be5) 15. Kh1 Be5 16. exf7+ Kh8 17. f4 Bd6 (17... Bxc3 18. Bxc3 Qe7 $2 {This is Black's turn to return the favour, and he lets the White rook on to the d-file} 19. Bxf6 (19. a5 b5 20. Bxf6 gxf6 $1 {This was the right rook} (20... Qxf6 21. Bd5 Ra7 22. Rac1 $17 {This may still be a draw, but White needs precision.}) 21. Bd5 Bb7 22. Rad1 Bxd5 $17 {The pawn on c4 is going to fall soon, and Black should manage to convert this endgame.} 23. Rxd5 Rxf7 24. Rc1 Rc8 25. Qd3) 19... gxf6 (19... Qxf6 20. a5 b5 21. Bd5) 20. Rac1 Be6 21. a5 $11 {Now White forces the draw easily.} Rab8 22. Bxe6 Qxe6 23. axb6 Rxb6 24. Rxc5 Qxf7 25. Ra5) 18. Nd5 Nxd5 {This is a slightly worse version for White than 14.d2, because the king has castled and is far from the weak queenside pawns.} (18... Bg4 19. Qe1 Nxd5 20. Bxd5 Qe7 21. Qg3 $2 h5 $1 {Now, White is in trouble.} 22. Bxa8 Rxa8 23. e4) 19. Bxd5 Rd8 (19... Bb7 20. Qg4 Rxf7 21. Bxf7 Qxf7 22. Rad1) 20. Qh5 1/2-1/2


