{[%evp 0,49,29,-15,40,5,3,18,11,-2,19,7,17,23,17,31,10,7,5,8,-19,22,33,20,4,13,29,10,8,13,20,0,61,78,57,58,67,78,101,91,118,93,107,106,100,74,99,122,111,116,209,185]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bc4 Nc6 4. d3 Bb4 (4... Na5 5. Nge2 Nxc4 6. dxc4 Bc5) 5. Nge2 d5 6. exd5 Nxd5 7. O-O Be6 (7... Nxc3 $14 {0-1 (63) Papin,V (2520)-Ponkratov,P (2603) RUS 2010} 8. bxc3 Bd6 9. Ng3 O-O 10. Qh5) 8. Bxd5 (8. a3 Bxc3 9. bxc3 O-O 10. Bxd5 Qxd5 11. Be3 b6) 8... Bxd5 9. f4 f6 10. fxe5 $5 Nxe5 $146 11. Nf4 $1 (11. Nxd5 Qxd5 {is also a solid setup for Black, and it's difficult to say what Artemiev wanted to come up with. The engine comes up with the interesting} 12. d4 $5 {which may be worth having a look at.} Ng6 13. Nf4 Nxf4 14. Bxf4 O-O-O 15. c3 Bd6) 11... Bxc3 (11... Bf7 {and here I could easily imagine an (almost) novelty like} 12. d4 Ng6 13. Re1+ Be7 14. Ne6 {making Black's play slightly unpleasant.} {or} Bxe6 15. Rxe6 Qd7 16. Re1 O-O-O 17. Be3) 12. bxc3 O-O $6 {With this move, problems start.} 13. c4 Bf7 14. Rb1 b6 15. Qe1 $6 Re8 $2 16. Qg3 Qd7 {Now we reach a kind of endgame that is very unpleasant for Black, as the g2-bishop is a true monster.} 17. h3 Qa4 18. Rb3 Qxa2 19. Ne2 Qa4 (19... Qxc2 20. Nd4 {should be close to a draw} {The usual} Qa2 21. Ra3 {hardly brought White any advantage.} {In the event of} Qb1 {Artemiev probably had a similar idea:} 22. Bh6 Qxf1+ 23. Kxf1 $5) 20. Rxf6 Qd7 21. Rf2 Ng6 22. Bb2 Qd6 23. Qxd6 cxd6 24. Ng3 Be6 $2 25. Nh5 $1 {An elegant finish. Incredible how quickly Black's position became so bad from a very timid line by White.} {After} Ne5 26. Rb5 Bf7 {Black would still be in the game, but of course White is close to winning.} 27. Ng3 Bg6 {is not something Black wants...} 28. Rd5 $5 $16 Rad8 29. Bc3 h6 30. Rf1 $14 Nc6 $14 31. h4 $14 Rf8 32. Re1 Bf7 33. Rb5 $14 Rfe8 $1 34. Rxe8+ Bxe8 {with the idea of ...Nc3, should be fine for Black.} 35. Nf5 $1 {was more precise.} Rd7 $1 {would be fine for Black. It is weird to leave the black queen awkwardly placed on b4, but White can't take advantage of it.} 36. Rd5 Ne7 $1 {A nice prophylactic move against d6.} 37. Nxe7+ Rxe7 38. Rxd6 Ba4 39. Bb4 Rf7 40. c3 Rd7 41. c5 bxc5 42. Rxd7 Bxd7 $11 43. Bxc5 $5 {running away with the queen through a6 is also fine. White can play} a5 {and win the bishop pair, but Black's activity compensates.} (43... Bf5 44. d4 Kf7) 44. Kf2 Kf7 45. Ke3 Ke6 46. c4 Bc6 47. g3 Bg2 48. Bf8 Kf7 49. Ba3 {and again the position is about equal.} {Anand had chosen} Bf1 {against the same Artemiev, and after} 50. Kd4 g5 {and here perhaps} 51. hxg5 $5 $146 {would be worth having a look at!} hxg5 52. Kc3 Ke6 53. d4 g4 54. Bc1 a4 55. d5+ Kd6 56. Kd4 Bg2 57. c5+ $44 {1-0 (63) Sargissian,G (2671)-Dominguez,L (2757) Linares ESP 2013} Kc7 $5 58. Ke5 Bf3 59. Ke6 $1 Bg2 60. d6+ 1-0


