{[%evp 0,49,29,-15,40,5,3,18,11,-2,19,7,17,23,17,31,10,7,5,8,-19,22,33,20,4,13,29,10,8,13,20,0,61,78,57,58,67,78,101,91,118,93,107,106,100,74,99,122,111,116,209,185]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. O-O Be7 5. d3 (5. c4) (5. d4 O-O 6. c4) 5... O-O 6. Bf4 (6. Nbd2) 6... c5 7. e4 Nc6 (7... dxe4 8. dxe4 Nxe4 9. Qe2 Nf6 10. Rd1 Qb6 (10... Qa5 11. Ne5 Nd5 12. Bd2 Qb6 13. Nc3) (10... Qe8 11. Nc3 Bd7 (11... Nc6 12. Nb5 Nd5 13. Rxd5 exd5 14. Nc7 Qd8 15. Nxa8 Bd6 16. Bxd6 Qxd6 17. Qb5 Qe7 18. Nc7 Qxc7 19. Qxc5)) 11. Na3 Nc6 (11... Qxb2 12. Nb5 Nd5 13. Rab1 Nxf4 14. gxf4 Qf6 15. Nc7 Nc6 16. Nxa8 Qxf4 17. a4 Qb8 18. a5 Qxa8 19. a6 Qb8 (19... bxa6 20. Ne5 Bb7 21. Rxb7 Qxb7 22. Nxc6) 20. axb7 Bxb7 21. Rxb7 Qxb7 22. Ne5 Rd8 23. Nxc6 Rxd1+ 24. Qxd1) 12. Nc4 Qa6 13. a4 Bd7 14. Bf1) 8. Ne5 Nxe5 9. Bxe5 Nd7 10. Bf4 $5 (10. Bc3) 10... d4 $146 (10... e5 11. Bd2 d4 12. a4) 11. a4 $1 (11. e5 g5 12. Bd2 Nxe5 13. f4 Ng6 14. fxg5 Bxg5 15. Qh5 Bxd2 16. Nxd2 f5 17. Rae1 Kg7 18. Nf3 h6 (18... Qf6 19. Ng5 h6 20. Bxb7 Bxb7 21. Nxe6+ Kh7 22. g4 (22. Nxf8+ Rxf8 23. Re2 Ne5) 22... f4 23. g5 Qf7 24. Qxh6+ Kg8 25. Nxf4 Nxf4 26. Rxf4 Qxf4 27. Qg6+ Kh8 28. Qh6+ Kg8) 19. Ne5 Nxe5 20. Rxe5 Qd6 21. Rfe1) 11... e5 12. Bd2 Nb8 $6 {With this move, problems start.} 13. Na3 Nc6 14. f4 exf4 (14... f6 15. f5 Bd7 (15... b6 16. Bf3 a6 17. h4 (17. Bh5 Rb8 18. Bg6 Qd7 19. Bh5 (19. Qh5 hxg6 20. fxg6 Qh3) 19... b5) 17... Rb8 18. Bh5 b5 19. Bg6 Rb7 (19... hxg6 20. fxg6) 20. Qh5 h6 21. axb5 axb5 22. b3 Bd6 23. g4) 16. Nc4 Be8) 15. gxf4 $6 f5 $2 16. Nc4 Be6 {Now we reach a kind of endgame that is very unpleasant for Black, as the g2-bishop is a true monster.} 17. a5 (17. exf5 Bxf5 18. Qf3 Kh8 19. Rae1 Qc7 20. a5) 17... Qd7 (17... Rc8) 18. exf5 Bd5 (18... Bxf5 19. Qf3 Rab8 20. a6 b5 21. Qd5+ (21. Ne5 Nxe5 22. fxe5 Be6 (22... c4 23. Qd5+ Kh8 24. Qxd7 Bxd7 25. Rxf8+ Bxf8 (25... Rxf8 26. Ba5)) (22... Kh8 23. Qb7 b4 (23... Rxb7 24. axb7 Rb8 25. Rxa7) 24. Rxf5 Qxf5 25. Qxe7 Qf2+ 26. Kh1 Qxd2 27. Qxa7 b3 28. cxb3 Qxb2 29. Rg1 Qxb3 30. Qxc5) 23. Qb7 Rfd8 (23... Rbd8 24. Ba5) (23... Rxb7 24. Rxf8+ Bxf8 25. axb7 Qc7 26. Rxa7) (23... Rxf1+ 24. Kxf1 Rf8+ 25. Kg1)) 21... Qxd5 (21... Kh8 22. Qxd7 Bxd7 23. Ne5 Nxe5 24. fxe5) 22. Bxd5+ Kh8 23. Ne5 Nxe5 24. fxe5) 19. Ne5 Nxe5 20. Bxd5+ Qxd5 21. fxe5 Qxe5 22. Qf3 Rad8 (22... Bh4 $5 23. Qxb7 {and here I could easily imagine an (almost) novelty like} Rae8 (23... Rab8 24. Qxa7 Rxb2 25. Qd7 Rxc2 26. Bf4 Qe2 27. Qe6+ Rf7 28. Qxe2 Rxe2 29. a6) 24. Qxa7 (24. Be1 Qe3+ 25. Kh1 Bxe1 26. Raxe1 Qxe1 {is also a solid setup for Black, and it's difficult to say what Artemiev wanted to come up with. The engine comes up with the interesting} 27. Rxe1 $5 {which may be worth having a look at.} Rxe1+ 28. Kg2 Re5 29. Qxa7 Rexf5 30. Qb7 Rg5+ 31. Kh3 Rf6 32. Kh4 Rg1 33. Qd5+ Kf8 34. Qd8+ Kf7 35. Qd7+ $14 {0-1 (63) Papin,V (2520)-Ponkratov,P (2603) RUS 2010} Kf8) 24... Qe2 25. Bf4 Rxf5 {making Black's play slightly unpleasant.} {or} 26. Qd7 Re6) 23. Qxb7 Rxf5 (23... Bd6 24. Bf4 Qf6 {should be close to a draw} {The usual} 25. Qd5+ Kh8 {hardly brought White any advantage.} {In the event of} 26. Bxd6 {Artemiev probably had a similar idea:} Rxd6 27. Qb7) 24. Rfe1 Qf6 $2 25. Rxe7 $1 {An elegant finish. Incredible how quickly Black's position became so bad from a very timid line by White.} {After} Rf8 26. Ree1 Qg6+ {Black would still be in the game, but of course White is close to winning.} (26... h6 $14 27. Qe4 $14 Rf2 28. Rad1 Kh8 29. Qg4 $14 Qd6 $1 30. Qg3 Qf6 {with the idea of ...Nc3, should be fine for Black.} 31. Kh1 $1 {was more precise.} (31. b4 Qf5 32. bxc5 Rf6 33. Bxh6 (33. c6 Rf3 34. Qg2 Rg6) 33... Rg6 (33... Rxh6 {and here perhaps} 34. Re5 $5 $146 {would be worth having a look at!} (34. Qxf2 Rg6+ $44 {1-0 (63) Sargissian,G (2671)-Dominguez,L (2757) Linares ESP 2013} 35. Qg3 $5 Rxg3+ 36. hxg3 Qxc5 $1) 34... Qf6 35. Re8+ Kh7 36. Qxf2 Qg6+ 37. Kh1 Qxe8 38. Qf5+ Kh8 39. Rf1) 34. Qxg6 Qxg6+ {and again the position is about equal.} {Anand had chosen} 35. Kxf2 {against the same Artemiev, and after} Qxh6) 31... Qf7 $1 {would be fine for Black. It is weird to leave the black queen awkwardly placed on b4, but White can't take advantage of it.} 32. Re4 Rf3 $1 {A nice prophylactic move against d6.} 33. Qg2 Rf2 34. Qg4 h5 35. Qg3 Rf3 36. Qg5 Rf5 37. Rf4 Rxf4 38. Bxf4 Qxf4 $11 39. Qxh5+ $5 {running away with the queen through a6 is also fine. White can play} Kg8 {and win the bishop pair, but Black's activity compensates.} 40. Qd5+ Kh7 41. Rg1) 27. Kh1 Rf2 {is not something Black wants...} 28. Qd5+ $5 $16 Kh8 29. Rg1 Qe8 30. Rg2 $14 1-0


