{Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'The last time Wei Yi played against Karjakin, he started out with 1.b3 and it didn't go well. Now he seems to have gained more confindence and his preparation today was surely impressive. '} 1. e4 {[%emt 0:00:00] Hillarp Persson,Tiger Hillarp Persson,Tiger Hillarp Persson,Tiger Mikhalevski,V Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'Hillarp Persson,T'} e5 {[%emt 0:00:05]} 2. Nf3 {[%emt 0:00:00]} Nc6 {[%emt 0:00:03]} 3. Bb5 {[%emt 0:00:00] Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'The Scotch is not for everyone and somewhat harsh against mistakes. The Giuoco Piano is like an amarone, in that it is hard to go wrong with it. The Ruy Lopez is more complex with oaky notes. A full bodied opening.'} Nf6 {[%emt 0:00:07]} 4. d3 {[%emt 0:00:00] Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'Avoiding the Berlin Defence main lines is the dish of the day for those rated above 2600.'} ({Last year's clash continued} 4. O-O {Hillarp Persson,Tiger} Nxe4 5. Re1 Nd6 6. Nxe5 Be7 7. Bf1 Nxe5 8. Rxe5 O-O 9. Nc3 Ne8 10. Nd5 Bd6 11. Re1 c6 12. Ne3 Be7 13. c4 Nc7 14. d4 {and here Karjakin played} d6 {Wei Yi (2705)-Karjakin,S (2765) 78th Tata Steel GpA 2016; and ended up in a worse position.} ({Instead} 14... d5 15. cxd5 Bb4 16. Bd2 Bxd2 17. Qxd2 Nxd5 {has been proved to draw with ease for Black (in about twenty games).})) 4... Bc5 {[%emt 0:00:08]} 5. c3 {[%emt 0:00:08]} (5. Bxc6 {Hillarp Persson,Tiger} dxc6 6. h3 {was played by Magnus Carlsen in a number of blitz games last year.} ({However, his} 6. Qe2 {against Wesley So in the Masters Final, indicates that White is scraping the bottom of the barrel for ideas here.} Qe7 7. Nbd2 Bg4 8. h3 Bh5 9. a3 Nd7 10. b4 Bd6 11. Nc4 f6 12. Ne3 a5 13. Nf5 Qf8 14. bxa5 Rxa5 15. O-O Qf7 16. a4 Nc5 17. Qe1 b6 18. Nd2 Rxa4 19. Nc4 Bf8 20. Be3 Kd7 21. Qc3 Nxe4 22. Nxb6+ cxb6 23. dxe4 Qc4 24. Qd2+ Kc7 25. g4 Bg6 26. Rfd1 {1-0, Carlsen,M (2855)-So,W (2770) 9th Masters Final 2016})) ({It seems the reason why White often prefers 5.c3 over} 5. O-O {Hillarp Persson,Tiger is that} Nd4 6. Nxd4 Bxd4 {gives Black an easier game. Still, White has been able to squeeze a few wins here too, even on a high level.}) 5... O-O {[%emt 0:00:43]} ({Black has also tried} 5... d5 {Hillarp Persson,Tiger , which seems very principled.} 6. exd5 Qxd5 7. Bc4 Qd6 8. Qe2 O-O 9. Nbd2 a5 10. Ng5 Bf5 (10... Qe7 11. Nde4 Bd6 12. a4 h6 13. h4 $1 Nd8 14. Qf3 Ng4 15. Qe2 Kh8 16. f3 Nf6 17. Nxf6 Qxf6 18. g4 Ne6 19. Qe4 $1 {Svidler,P (2745)-Inarkiev,E (2730) 69th ch-RUS 2016. The last move gave White a winning advantage..}) 11. Nde4 Nxe4 12. Nxe4 Bxe4 13. dxe4 Nd8 14. Bd2 c6 15. a4 Ne6 16. Rd1 Qe7 17. g3 {Topalov, V (2760)-Aronian,L (2790) 4th Sinquefield Cup 2016, and the bishop pair (especially the strong light-squared bishop) gave White some edge. The game Rozentalis - Smith, Gothenburg 2013, is an excellent example of the challenges that Black faces here.}) (5... d6 {Hillarp Persson,Tiger is a please-don't-take-my-pawn move, that leads to a position that very much resembles the Giuoco Piano, but where the bishop is somewhat more annoying on b5. After} 6. O-O O-O 7. Nbd2 Ne7 8. d4 exd4 9. cxd4 Bb6 10. Re1 Bg4 11. h3 Bh5 {White has been doing well with} 12. a4 {lately.}) 6. Bxc6 {[%emt 0:00:09] Mikhalevski,V: 'An important alternative to 6.0-0, which hasn't been seen on our pages yet.'} ({Earlier we only covered the mainline} 6. O-O {(Mikhalevski,V) Topalov,V (2816)-Caruana,F (2808)/Saint Louis USA 2015/[Mikhalevski,V].}) ({and} 6. Bg5 {(Mikhalevski,V) Carlsen,M (2853)-Karjakin,S  (2772)/New York USA 2016/[Mikhalevski,V].}) 6... bxc6 {[%emt 0:00:31]} (6... dxc6 {(Mikhalevski,V) is a pretty rare recapture with only one test at the GM level.} 7. Nxe5 Re8 8. Nf3 Bg4 9. h3 Bh5 10. O-O $14 {and Black's compensation seems to be insufficient. Savchenko,B (2567)-Bindrich,F (2594)/Berlin World Blitz championship 2015.}) 7. Nxe5 {[%emt 0:00:08] Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'An incredibly prosaic sequence; to stop d4, not castle and then just snatch a pawn. Two decades ago most GMs would have shunned such simplistic (although possibly efficient) moves. Perhaps the change is due to the engines, but also because the Kasparov era was all about keeping the tension.'} d5 {[%emt 0:00:13] Mikhalevski,V: 'This idea was first introduced by Adolf Anderssen in 1864(!), and he played it at least four times.'} 8. d4 {[%emt 0:00:08]} (8. O-O {(Mikhalevski,V) yields Black some choice after} dxe4 9. d4 {when the latter can either retreat to b6, transposing to the game, or retreat to d6.} Bd6 {Mikhalevski,V}) ({White must stay clear of} 8. Nxc6 $2 {Hillarp Persson,Tiger} Qe8 9. Nd4 dxe4 10. O-O Ba6) 8... Bb6 {[%emt 0:16:04] Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'This is the main line, but Black has tried some alternatives:'} (8... Qe7 {Hillarp Persson,Tiger} 9. O-O dxe4 10. Nxc6 Qe6 11. dxc5 Qxc6 12. Bg5 {Safarli,E (2644)-Fedorchuk,S (2653) Kocaeli 2015, was rather balanced, but I'm curious as to what Black would have replied to a setup similar to Wei Yi's.}) (8... Qe8 {Hillarp Persson,Tiger} 9. O-O {Again and again we come to this crossroads, where Black has to decide whether to take with the pawn or the knight on e4. Taking with the knight is usually more solid, but leads to positions where Black lacks dynamic play. It's more challenging to take with the pawn.} dxe4 (9... Nxe4 10. Nd2 Nxd2 11. Bxd2 Bd6 12. Re1 f6 13. Nc4 Be6 14. Nxd6 cxd6 {looks pretty dull to me, but Black will suffer a bit due to the messed up pawn structure.}) 10. Nd2 (10. Qa4 $5) (10. Re1 Bd6 11. Nc4) 10... Bd6 11. Ndc4 Be6 12. Re1 c5 13. Be3 Nd5 {(Tari,A (2520)-Fressinet, L (2712) Oslo 2015) was unconvincing for White. I don't understand much of this structure, so my recommendations on move 10 are pretty much 100% silicon based.}) (8... Bd6 {Hillarp Persson,Tiger} 9. Nxc6 Qe8 10. e5 Qxc6 11. O-O Ba6 12. Re1 Rfe8 13. Bf4 Qb5 14. Nd2 (14. b3) 14... Qxb2 15. Qb3 Reb8 $11 {Tari,A (2520)-Hammer,J (2665) Oslo 2015}) 9. O-O {[%emt 0:00:24]} dxe4 {[%emt 0:15:33]} ({Caruana tried} 9... Nxe4 {(Mikhalevski,V) in a blitz game, but also lost.} 10. Nxc6 (10. Nd2 {Hillarp Persson,Tiger} Nxd2 11. Bxd2 c5 12. dxc5 Bxc5 13. Qf3 Be6 14. Rfe1 {Xu,X (2445)-Malakhov,V (2695) TCh-CHN 2016, was microscopically better for White, since the knight can dream of out-witting the light squared bishop at some point.}) 10... Qf6 (10... Qd6 {is more accurate. Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'is the older line, which also seems good enough for Black.'} 11. Nb4 Re8 12. Na3 a5 13. Nd3 Ba6 14. f3 Nf6 15. Nc2 c5 {with good compensation for the sacrificed pawn in Jamwan,K (2518)-Kuhne,K (2506)/Engine Room 2015.}) 11. Nb4 Be6 12. Nd2 $14 {So,W (2773)-Caruana,F (2795)/Saint Louis USA 2016.} c5 {Hillarp Persson,Tiger} 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. Nxe4 dxe4 15. Nd5 Qe5 16. Be3 Bxe3 17. Nxe3 f5 {So,W (2770)-Caruana,F (2795) Ultimate Blitz Challenge 2016, left Black with decent compensation.}) 10. Bg5 {[%emt 0:00:24] Mikhalevski,V: '!' Mikhalevski,V: 'The mainline.' Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'White has a clear plan: to use the bind on f6 to attack the pawn on e4. Black needs to undermine White's centre as fast as possible.'} ({The first predecessor to the game featured} 10. f4 $2 {Mikhalevski,V} c5 {and after} 11. dxc5 $2 Bxc5+ 12. Kh1 {Mayet, C-Anderssen,A/Berlin 1862 Black could have finished the game by means of} Qxd1 13. Rxd1 Bg4 14. Rf1 ({or} 14. Re1 Bf2 15. Rf1 e3 $19) 14... Rad8 {and the advance of the e-pawn decides the game.}) ({White also tested Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'After'} 10. Nxc6 {Mikhalevski,V} Qd6 (10... Qe8 {Hillarp Persson,Tiger} 11. Ne5 c5 12. Re1 Qe6 13. Be3 Nd5 (13... Rd8 $5) (13... cxd4 14. cxd4 Nd5) 14. Nd2 f5 15. Ndc4 Bb7 16. dxc5 ({The silicon monster indicates that} 16. Qb3 {is very good for White, so something has gone wrong for Black in the last four moves. Perhaps 13...d5 was a mistake.}) 16... Nxe3 17. fxe3 Bxc5 {Sokolov,I (2640)-Lorparizangeneh,S (2465) 1st Stars Cup 2016, Black had enough compensation for the pawn.}) 11. Ne5 Ba6 12. Re1 c5 13. Na3 cxd4 (13... Qe6 $5) 14. Nac4 Qe6 15. Nxb6 axb6 16. cxd4 Nd5 17. f3 exf3 18. Nxf3 {and a draw was agreed in Anand,V (2792)-Topalov, V (2801)/Monte Carlo 2006. despite White's extra pawn Black's chances are no worse.}) ({and} 10. b4 {Mikhalevski,V} Re8 $1 11. Bg5 a5 12. Nd2 axb4 $2 (12... Qd5 {is necessary, with roughly equal chances.}) 13. Nxe4 Qd5 $2 14. Nxf6+ gxf6 15. Bxf6 {and Black resigned. Kudrin,S (2607)-Vigorito,D (2372)/Reno 2004.}) 10... c5 $1 {[%emt 0:05:49] Mikhalevski,V: 'The most logical. Black undermines the centre.' Ehlvest,Jaan: '!'} 11. Nd2 {[%emt 0:00:22] Diagram [#] Mikhalevski,V: '!' Ehlvest,Jaan: 'Diagram [#]'} cxd4 $2 $146 {[%emt 0:22:51] Mikhalevski,V: '?' Mikhalevski,V: 'Karjakin underestimates the danger.' Hillarp Persson,Tiger: '?!' '?!' '?!' Ehlvest,Jaan: 'N?' Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'This does look natural, but seems to be a serious mistake.'} ({Mikhalevski,V: 'He should have protected the e4-pawn by means of' Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'I presume Wei Yi had something prepared against'} 11... Bb7 $1 {Hillarp Persson,Tiger: ', which has been seen in two games.'} 12. dxc5 (12. Ng4 {Hillarp Persson,Tiger} cxd4 13. Nxf6+ gxf6 14. Bh6 Qd7 $13) 12... Bxc5 13. Nb3 $13 Bb6 {Hillarp Persson,Tiger} (13... Bd6 {Hillarp Persson,Tiger} 14. Ng4 Be7 15. Qxd8 Raxd8 16. Nxf6+ Bxf6 {Pogonina,N (2448) -Olsarova,K (2267) Istanbul 2012, where instead of} 17. Be3 ({White should have exchanged the bishops} 17. Bxf6 gxf6 {and kept some pressure. The knight can access the weak squares on the queenside, and the ligh-squared bishop is playing in a parallel dimension where there's nothing to attack.})) 14. c4 (14. Qxd8 $5 Rfxd8 15. a4) 14... Qd6 (14... e3 $5 15. Qxd8 exf2+ 16. Kh1 Rfxd8 17. c5 Rd5 18. Bxf6 gxf6 19. Ng4 Rxc5 20. Nxc5 Bxc5 21. Rfc1 $1 Bb6 22. Rc2 f5 23. Nxf2 f4 {is possibly balanced, but quite hard to handle for both sides.}) 15. Qxd6 cxd6 16. Bxf6 gxf6 17. Ng4 Rfc8 18. Rac1 Kf8 19. Ne3 Ba6 20. Nd2 Bd4 21. b3 {Balogh,C (2601)-Naiditsch,A (2684) Aix les Bains 2011, with an advantage for White. Both sides could have played better here and if I was to enter these positions with any colour, then this is where I would be looking for improvements.}) 12. Nxe4 {[%emt 0:00:09] Mikhalevski,V: '' Mikhalevski,V: 'Black's position is already highly unpleasant.' Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'This sets a forced sequence in motion...'} dxc3 {[%emt 0:00:13] Diagram [#] Mikhalevski,V: '!' Mikhalevski,V: 'The best defence.' Ehlvest,Jaan: 'Diagram [#]'} (12... Bf5 $2 {(Mikhalevski,V) is bad because of} 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. Nc6 $18) (12... Bb7 $2 {Mikhalevski,V} 13. Nxf6+ gxf6 14. Bh4 $18 {is also hopeless.}) 13. Qf3 $1 {[%emt 0:44:19] Mikhalevski,V: 'White puts pressure on f6 and forces' Ehlvest,Jaan: '!'} Bb7 $8 {[%emt 0:00:19] Mikhalevski,V: '!' Mikhalevski,V: 'The only defence.' Ehlvest,Jaan: ''} (13... cxb2 $2 14. Nxf6+ gxf6 15. Bxf6 $18 (15. Bh6 $18 {(Mikhalevski,V) is resignable.})) 14. Bxf6 {[%emt 0:03:32] Mikhalevski,V: '!'} Bxe4 {[%emt 0:00:07] Mikhalevski,V: '!'} (14... gxf6 $2 {(Mikhalevski,V) is impossible.} 15. Nxf6+ Kg7 (15... Kh8 16. Qf5 $18) 16. Nh5+ Kh6 17. Qf5 $1 Qg5 18. Ng4+ Kxh5 19. Nf6+ Kh6 20. Qxh7#) 15. Qxe4 {[%emt 0:00:06] Mikhalevski,V: '!'} Qxf6 $6 {[%emt 0:00:03] Mikhalevski,V: 'Sergey decides to sacrifice an exchange, but the endgame is technically winning for White.' Ehlvest,Jaan: '?!' Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'An accident rarely comes alone.'} (15... gxf6 {Diagram [#] Mikhalevski,V: 'is better, but White's advantage is already beyond question, he has a pleasant choice between'} {Mikhalevski,V: 'and'} 16. Ng4 $1 (16. Nc6 Qd2 (16... Qd7 {Mikhalevski,V} 17. Rad1 Qe6 18. Qf3 Rae8 $1 ({After} 18... cxb2 19. Rfe1 {Black's queen is dominated by the white pieces.} b1=Q 20. Rxb1 Qxa2 21. Ne7+ Kg7 22. Rxb6 $1 cxb6 23. Nf5+ Kh8 24. Qc3 Qe6 25. Rxe6 fxe6 26. Nd4 $18 {and White wins.}) 19. Qxc3 Qxa2 20. Rd3 Qe6 21. h3 $1 $16 {with the ideas of 22.Rg3 Kh8 23.Rf3, and 23.Rfd1 and White is clearly better.}) (16... Qd6 {Mikhalevski,V} 17. Rad1) 17. bxc3 $14 {Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'was the better way to fight on. In the game Black gets no chance.'}) (16. Rad1 {Mikhalevski,V} Qe7 17. Qg4+ Kh8 18. Nc6 Qe6 19. Qf3 Rae8 20. Qxc3) 16... cxb2 (16... f5 {Mikhalevski,V} 17. Nh6+ Kh8 18. Qe5+ f6 19. Qxc3 $16) 17. Rad1 f5 18. Nh6+ Kh8 19. Qc6 Qe7 20. Rd7 Qh4 21. g3 $16) 16. Nd7 {[%emt 0:00:26]} Qg6 {[%emt 0:10:36]} (16... Qd4 17. Qxd4 Bxd4 18. Rad1 $18) 17. Qxg6 {[%emt 0:00:16]} hxg6 {[%emt 0:00:49]} (17... fxg6 {(Mikhalevski,V) doesn't change much.} 18. Nxf8 cxb2 19. Rab1 Rxf8 20. Rxb2 $18) 18. Nxf8 {[%emt 0:00:09]} cxb2 {[%emt 0:00:09]} 19. Rab1 {[%emt 0:00:07]} Kxf8 {[%emt 0:01:48]} 20. Rfd1 $1 {[%emt 0:01:51] Mikhalevski,V: '+-!' Mikhalevski,V: 'The rest is a matter of technique.' Ehlvest,Jaan: '!' Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'With an extra couple of pawns on - let's say - e3 and e5, Black would have some chances of holding the position (...e6), but with so many open lines, Black's king is stuck on the kingside where it becomes vulnerable to attack. Black is also unable to launch the c-pawn any further than c5, without losing it, so it is better to keep it in the starting position where it doesn't obstruct the bishop.'} Ke7 {[%emt 0:12:00]} ({Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'It looks like Karjakin had resigned himself to losing, or otherwise he might chosen something more active, like'} 20... Re8 21. Kf1 Re4 22. Rxb2 $16 Rc4 {Hillarp Persson,Tiger Still, the final result is in little doubt.}) 21. Rxb2 {[%emt 0:17:52] Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'It's hardly even clear where Black made his mistake, but suddenly he is lost.'} g5 {[%emt 0:00:32]} 22. Rbd2 {[%emt 0:03:16]} Rh8 {[%emt 0:01:54]} (22... f5 23. Re2+ Kf6 24. Rd7 g4 25. g3 Rf8 26. Kg2 Rh8 27. Rde7 Kg6 28. R2e6+ Kh7 29. Rf7 $18 {Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'and the f-pawn is lost. Generally speaking, Black's hope in such a positon as this is to keep his weaknesses to a minimum and thus not move the pawns too far (unless they can be used to attack something).'}) 23. g3 {[%emt 0:00:57]} Rh5 {[%emt 0:02:29] Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'This looks weird. Perhaps Karjakin was trying to keep his rook from being exchanged. Three rooks on the board or a single one; it doesn't matter since White is winning in both scenarios. '} 24. Kg2 {[%emt 0:03:08]} Kf6 {[%emt 0:01:33]} (24... Rh6 25. Rd7+ Ke6 26. R7d5 Rf6 27. f3 g4 28. f4 $18) 25. h3 {[%emt 0:04:51]} Rh6 {[%emt 0:03:45]} 26. Rd8 {[%emt 0:05:17]} Ke7 {[%emt 0:00:24]} 27. R1d7+ {[%emt 0:00:09]} Ke6 {[%emt 0:00:06]} 28. Rd2 {[%emt 0:00:04]} Rf6 {[%emt 0:02:11] Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'This makes it easy for White, but the fight was hopeless anyway. '} 29. Rg8 {[%emt 0:00:06]} Rg6 {[%emt 0:00:11]} 30. Re8+ {[%emt 0:00:18]} Kf6 {[%emt 0:00:26]} 31. Rd7 {[%emt 0:01:02] Mikhalevski,V: 'and Black resigned as he can't stop 32.Ree7. A surprisingly easy win for the young Chinese GM and a rare case where Karjakin gets a bad position right out of the opening. 11... cxd4? is a clear mistake, as Black should play 11...Bb7.' Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'There is no defence against f8, so Black resigned.'} 1-0


