)} Be5 $1 15. f4 Bxc3 16. Bxc3 e5 $11) 13. cxb5 {[%emt 0:30:32]} axb5 {[%emt 0:00:11]} 14. Nxb5 {[%emt 0:00:11]} Rxa2 {[%emt 0:00:27]} 15. d4 {[%emt 0:08:18]} ({It is a running joke in my circle that whenever possible, I will suggest moves like} 15. Bxf6 {to try and exploit, after a further 50 moves, some perceived superiority of White's compact structure. This may or may not be present, but on objective grounds the move deserves consideration. Play could continue} Nxf6 16. Nfd4 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Ne4 18. Rfd1 $11 {when White has the 'threat' of c3, exchanging off more pieces and thus getting closer to the ideal  v  position, where in theory the backward c-pawn could become a factor.}) 15... Qb8 {[%emt 0:09:27]} 16. Ra1 {[%emt 0:00:43]} Rxa1 {[%emt 0:01:41]} 17. Rxa1 {[%emt 0:00:05]} Bf8 {[%emt 0:00:18]} 18. Nc3 {[%emt 0:01:51]} c5 {[%emt 0:00:30]} 19. Rb1 {[%emt 0:02:34] Maybe a slightly slack move.} (19. Qb5 cxd4 20. Nxd4 Bxg2 21. Kxg2 $11) 19... cxd4 {[%emt 0:01:34]} 20. Nxd4 {[%emt 0:00:04]} Bxg2 {[%emt 0:00:06]} 21. Kxg2 {[%emt 0:00:05]} Qa8+ {[%emt 0:01:47]} (21... Rc8 {created a threat and would not have been a totally unreasonable move to play on with.} 22. Ba1 Qa8+ 23. Qf3 Qa3 24. Ndb5 Qa6 $11 {and while the position is objectively level, White's pieces are a little bit tangled up and a bit less active.}) 1/2-1/2


