. Na6 Ra8 21. Nc7 Rab8 22. Na6 {1/2-1/2 (22) Saduakassova,D (2428)-Xu,Y (2540) Ho Chi Minh City VIE 2017}) 19... Kf8 20. Nc7 Rab8 21. Rc6 {The knight on c7 is a powerful asset.}) 18. Nc7 Rab8 19. a4 Nc5 $2 20. dxc5 Rxc7 21. cxb6 Rxc1 22. bxa7 $1 Ra8 23. Rxc1 Rxa7 24. b3 g6 25. Nd4 Kg7 26. Nc6 Rb7 27. b4 {1-0 Speelman,J (2511)-Ionov,S (2535) Hersonissos GRE 2017}) 12. Qb3 {[%emt 0:00:12]} (12. Qa4 {was the path followed by a noteworthy predecessor.} a6 (12... Rc8 $1 {improves, e.g.} 13. Rxc8 Qxc8 14. Na3 a6 15. Rc1 Qa8 $11) 13. Rc7 $5 (13. Nbd2 Rc8 14. Qd1 Nh5 15. Rxc8 Bxc8 16. Rc1 Nxf4 17. gxf4 Bb7 18. e3 Qb8 $11 {Ghaem Maghami,E-Wei,Y Tashkent 2016}) 13... Rb8 (13... e5 14. dxe5 Qxc7 15. exf6 Bd6 16. fxg7 $14) 14. Nbd2 b5 15. Qc2 Nh5 16. Rxd7 Qxd7 17. Bxb8 Rxb8 18. Ne5 Qd8 19. Nb3 $36 {White has a very pleasant position- but the question of an advantage is a different one.}) 12... Rc8 {[%emt 0:10:08]} 13. Rxc8 {[%emt 0:00:12]} Qxc8 {[%emt 0:00:07]} 14. Nc3 {[%emt 0:00:04]} Nh5 {[%emt 0:04:12] A principled reaction, but not the best.} (14... a6 15. Rc1 Qa8 16. Na4 $5 {is presumably the wrinkle intended by 12.b3. White could have a little something here, especially if Black's best is ...a7, but looking at some concrete details, my opinion is that this isn't true:} b5 17. Nc5 Rc8 $1 (17... Nxc5 18. dxc5 Ne4 19. Qe3 $132) 18. Nxb7 Qxb7 $11) 15. Bg5 {[%emt 0:00:10]} Bxg5 {[%emt 0:04:29]} 16. Nxg5 {[%emt 0:00:20]} Qb8 {[%emt 0:12:23]} ({Logical is also:} 16... Nhf6 17. e3 Ba6 18. a4 Qb8 19. Bf1 Bxf1 20. Kxf1 Rc8 21. Nf3 Ne4 22. Rc1 Ndf6 23. Rc2 Nxc3 24. Rxc3 Ne4 25. Rc2 Rc7 {We have equal chances here in Dragnev,V (2466)-Bluebaum,M (2643) Munich GER 2018 1/2-1/2 (79)}) 17. e3 {[%emt 0:02:03]} Nhf6 {[%emt 0:01:35]} 18. Bf1 {[%emt 0:01:05]} h6 {[%emt 0:17:17]} 19. Nf3 {[%emt 0:00:05]} Ne4 {[%emt 0:01:19]} (19... Rc8 20. a4 $1 a5 21. Rc1 {It may appear equal but its not a dry position, there are aspects that can be used to continue a game, as we will see...} Qa8 22. Rc2 Ba6 23. Bxa6 Qxa6 24. Nb5 Ne4 25. Ne1 Nb8 26. f3 Nf6 27. Nd3 Rxc2 28. Qxc2 Qb7 29. Ne5 {Already we see that White slowly managed to progress, therefore we can say that White is slightly better here. Vidit,S (2718)-Bluebaum,M (2640) Wijk aan Zee NED 2018 1/2-1/2 (44)}) 20. a4 {[%emt 0:07:20] Milos Pavlovic: '!' '!'} Rc8 {[%emt 0:09:25] Milos Pavlovic: 'Black ignores the a4-a5 idea, which is an important defensive idea.' Now White gets a relatively pleasant game.} (20... a6 $5 $11 {is now a good reflex, refusing to allow pawn weaknesses.}) 21. a5 {[%emt 0:00:14]} bxa5 {[%emt 0:07:14]} 22. Rxa5 {[%emt 0:00:58]} Bc6 {[%emt 0:00:39]} 23. Qa3 {[%emt 0:10:36]} Rc7 {[%emt 0:00:18]} 24. Nxe4 {[%emt 0:09:49]} dxe4 {[%emt 0:00:06]} 25. Nd2 $14 {[%emt 0:00:03] With two pawn weaknesses to White's none (after b3) Black is reduced to playing responsive chess. Thankfully for him, the position is quite solid.} Bd5 {[%emt 0:04:03] Milos Pavlovic: 'The position is equal, as although the pawn on a7 is a target Black has good piece coordination.'} 26. b3 {[%emt 0:00:27]} Rb7 {[%emt 0:06:29]} 27. Ba6 {[%emt 0:09:20]} Rc7 {[%emt 0:00:07]} 28. Bc4 {[%emt 0:00:24]} Nf6 {[%emt 0:04:43] Milos Pavlovic: '!' '!' Milos Pavlovic: 'Firmly keeping the d5-square.'} 29. Qd6 {[%emt 0:07:56]} Ne8 {[%emt 0:00:56]} 30. Qa3 {[%emt 0:02:54]} (30. Qe5 Nf6 31. Rc5 Rb7 32. Qxb8+ Rxb8 33. h3 $14 {might have been my choice, given how much easier it is to outplay someone when there are few pieces on the board!}) 30... Nf6 {[%emt 0:00:05]} 31. Kg2 {[%emt 0:00:03]} Rb7 {[%emt 0:00:19]} 32. h3 {[%emt 0:08:09]} Kh7 {[%emt 0:00:25]} 33. Ba6 {[%emt 0:05:49]} Rb4 {[%emt 0:00:18]} 34. Bc4 {[%emt 0:03:40]} Rb7 {[%emt 0:00:24]} 35. Ra6 {[%emt 0:03:27]} Nd7 {[%emt 0:02:03]} 36. Ra5 {[%emt 0:11:56] Karjakin doesn't see a way to continue the game.} (36. Qd6 Qxd6 37. Rxd6 Nb6 38. Bxd5 exd5 39. Rc6 {is still slightly interesting}) 1/2-1/2


