{Ding Liren is another one to try the less played 4.cxd5, which avoids the theoretical mainlines in the Mikenas, and easily got a good position. I think the popularity of this idea should increase a lot in the coming months.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 {This line is increasingly popular since sometimes the positions with 4.e5 are a bit too simple,} dxc4 5. a4 Bf5 6. Ne5 e6 7. f3 Bb4 8. Nxc4 O-O 9. Kf2 {This is the main point of waiting to develop the knight. Here it protects c3 and d4 and leaves the f-pawn free to annoy the knight on e4.} (9. e4 Nxe4 10. fxe4 Qh4+ 11. Kd2 Qxe4) (9. Bg5) 9... e5 (9... b5 10. axb5 cxb5 {with a clear positional advantage.} 11. Nxb5 Nc6 12. e3 Qb8 $18 13. Nc3 e5 14. d5 Rd8 15. Qa4 Ne7 16. e4) (9... Nd5 10. Na2 b5 {tries to keep the bishop but White can claim an edge after} 11. Nxb4 bxc4 12. Na2 {hitting d5} c5 13. e4 cxd4 14. Bxc4 (14. exd5 {makes little sense,} d3) 14... Nb6 15. Be2 Bg6 16. a5 $14 {White has a clear plan of attacking on the kingside while Black still needs to find something concrete on the queenside.} Nc8 17. Nb4 $16) (9... Nbd7 10. e4 Bg6 11. Be3 {and Black has nothing to worry about.} Qb8 12. g3 a5 {is also interesting and was analyzed by Watson in the game Korchnoi-Nielsen, see the archives.} 13. Be2 {is comfortable for White} Ne8 14. Rc1) (9... Bg6 10. e4 Qc7 11. Qb3 c5 (11... a5 12. Na2 {looks promising for White, with the bishop pair and better structure.} c5 13. Nxb4 axb4 14. dxc5 {is also possible} Na6 $2 {is now answered by} 15. Be3 $17) 12. Na2 Nc6 13. Nxb4 cxb4 $14 {San Segundo Carrillo, P (2495)-Mitkov, N (2455)/ESP-chT Ponferrada 1997.} 14. Be3 {is the main alternative and has the same idea as 4. e5 d4, but the important difference is that the e-file is now open, giving White the opportunity to play Qe2+ sooner or later,} Rfd8 15. Rd1 Rd7 $5 {I prefer this move, developing one more piece before the check} 16. Ne5 Nxe5 17. dxe5 Rxd1 18. Qxd1 Qxe5 19. Qd4 Qa5 20. Be2 Qxa4 21. Rc1 h6) (9... c5 {would be natural, but allows White to wait before taking the pawn on c3} 10. e4 Bg6 (10... Bxc3 11. bxc3 Bxe4 12. fxe4 Nxe4+ 13. Kg1 Nxc3 14. Qe1 cxd4 15. Ba3 Nc6 (15... Re8 16. Nd6 Re7 17. Nb5 Rd7 18. Nxc3 dxc3 19. Qxc3 Nc6 20. Rc1 Qh4 21. Bb2 e5 22. h3) 16. Bxf8 (16. h4 Qd5 17. Bxf8 Rxf8 18. Rh3) 16... Qxf8 17. h4 Qc5 18. Nd2 Nb4 (18... Ne5 19. Rh3 Ng4 20. Bd3 Ne3 21. Nf1) 19. Qf2 Rd8 20. Rh3 Nbd5 21. Rd3 e5 22. Re1 Qc7 23. Ne4) 11. Na2 $14 (11. Be3 cxd4 12. Qxd4 Qe7) 11... Nc6 12. Nxb4 Nxb4 13. Qb3 (13. Bd2 Qxd4+ 14. Be3 Qxd1 15. Rxd1 b6 16. a5 Rfb8 17. Bf4 Rb7 18. g4) 13... Nxe4+ (13... Bxe4 14. fxe4 Qxd4+ (14... Nxe4+ 15. Kg1 Qxd4+ 16. Be3 Qd5 17. Rd1 Qh5 18. Bf4 Rad8 19. Re1) 15. Be3 Qxe4 16. Be2) 14. fxe4 Bxe4 (14... Qxd4+ 15. Be3 Qxe4 16. Kg1 Rfd8 17. h4 Nc2 18. Rc1 Nxe3 19. Nxe3 Qf4 20. Rh3) 15. dxc5 (15. Bf4 Qf6 16. Qe3 Rad8 17. Kg1 Nc2 18. Qxe4 Nxa1 19. Be5 Qe7 20. Bd3 f5 21. Qf4) (15. Bd2 Nc2 16. Rc1 Nxd4 17. Qe3 Bc6 (17... Qd5 18. Bc3) 18. a5 Qd5 19. Bc3 Qf5+ 20. Kg1 Rad8 21. h4) 15... Nc2 16. Ra3 (16. Ra2 Rc8) 16... Qd1 17. Bf4 {gives Black nice compensation. It's still not clear how White is going to finish his development.} Rfd8 18. Nd6 Bd5 19. Qd3 Qe1+ 20. Kg1 {is much more common by far.} Nxa3 21. Qxa3 b6 22. h4 bxc5 23. Rh3) 10. Nxe5 (10. dxe5 Nfd7 11. e4 Be6) (10. e4 exd4 11. Na2 Bc5 12. b4 (12. exf5 b5 13. Nd2 d3+ 14. Kg3 Nh5+ 15. Kg4 Bf2 16. g3 Nf4 17. Kxf4 h5 18. Ne4 {looks dangerous for Black as well.} g5+ $6 19. Nxg5 Qd6+ 20. Ke4 Qd4#) 12... b5 13. bxc5 $11 bxc4 {would be an option, to activate the bishop,} 14. Bxc4 Be6) 10... Bc2 11. Qd2 c5 12. d5 Bb3 13. e4 Re8 {After this move Black is in real danger but the position is already more pleasant for White.} 14. Qf4 c4 15. Nxc4 Nbd7 16. Be3 Nf8 $6 {I don't think Black can survive with two white pawns on e5 and f5.} 17. Bd4 Ng6 18. Qf5 (18. Qc1 Rc8 19. Nd2 Nxe4+ {White has a better knight and a passed pawn, but Black can still fight at least.} 20. fxe4 $2 {is not advisable} Bxd5 21. Qd1 $1 {White can still draw by finding some good moves} Bc6 22. Be3) 18... Bxc4 19. Bxc4 Qc7 20. Be2 (20. Bb5 Bc5 21. Bxc5 Qxc5+ 22. Kf1 Re5 23. Qh3) 20... Bc5 21. Bxc5 $1 Qxc5+ 22. Kf1 h6 (22... Re5 23. Qh3 {is also good for White} Qb4 24. Rb1 Nf4 25. Qg3 {doesn't change so much} N6h5 {this should be played}) 23. Rd1 (23. g3) 23... Qb6 (23... Qb4 {and Black is in trouble.} 24. Rd2) (23... a6) 24. Rd2 Qe3 25. Rc2 a6 26. Qh3 b5 27. Qg3 b4 (27... Rec8 28. axb5 axb5 29. Nd1 Qd4 $18 30. Rxc8+ {gives a nice place for the knight} Rxc8 31. Qf2 Qb4 32. Qe3 Rc2 33. g3) 28. Nd1 Qb3 29. Rd2 Qxa4 30. Qf2 {Opening the position. White is still better, but now the endgame requires precision and a lot of effort.} Qd7 31. g3 Qh3+ 32. Kg1 a5 33. Qd4 Nh5 34. Nf2 Qd7 35. f4 Nhxf4 36. gxf4 Nxf4 37. Kf1 Qd6 38. Rg1 f6 39. Bb5 Re7 40. b3 Rf8 41. Rc2 Ne6 42. Qe3 Ng5 43. h4 Nf7 44. Rc6 Qb8 45. Qc5 Qd8 46. Rxf6 Kh8 47. Rf5 Rc7 48. Bc6 a4 49. bxa4 b3 50. Rg3 b2 51. Rb3 Nd6 52. Rxf8+ Qxf8 53. Rxb2 Qf4 54. Rb8+ Kh7 55. Qc2 Re7 56. e5+ Nf5 57. Qe4 Qc1+ $1 {would be enough for the win} 58. Kg2 g6 59. Rb3 1-0


