{Ding Liren is another one to try the less played 4.cxd5, which avoids the theoretical mainlines in the Mikenas, and easily got a good position. I think the popularity of this idea should increase a lot in the coming months.} 1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 e6 3. e4 d5 4. cxd5 {This line is increasingly popular since sometimes the positions with 4.e5 are a bit too simple,} (4. e5 d4 5. exf6 dxc3 6. bxc3 Qxf6 {is much more common by far.}) 4... exd5 5. e5 Ne4 (5... Nfd7 {is comfortable for White} 6. d4 c5 7. Nf3 Nc6 8. Bb5 a6 9. Bg5 Qa5 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. O-O $14 {San Segundo Carrillo, P (2495)-Mitkov, N (2455)/ESP-chT Ponferrada 1997.}) (5... d4 {is the main alternative and has the same idea as 4. e5 d4, but the important difference is that the e-file is now open, giving White the opportunity to play Qe2+ sooner or later,} 6. exf6 dxc3 7. Bb5+ $5 {I prefer this move, developing one more piece before the check} (7. Qe2+ Be6 8. dxc3 Qxf6 9. Qb5+ Nd7 10. Qxb7 Qe5+ 11. Ne2 Bd5 12. Qb5 Bc5 {gives Black nice compensation. It's still not clear how White is going to finish his development.}) 7... Nc6 (7... c6 {would be natural, but allows White to wait before taking the pawn on c3} 8. Qe2+ Be6 9. Bc4 $14) 8. Qe2+ Be6 9. dxc3 (9. Bc4 $2 {is now answered by} Nd4 $17) 9... Qxf6 10. Nf3 Bd6 11. Nd4 O-O 12. Nxe6 Rae8 13. Bc4 (13. Nxf8 Rxe2+ 14. Bxe2 Kxf8 {is also possible}) 13... fxe6 14. O-O {looks promising for White, with the bishop pair and better structure.}) 6. d4 (6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Bb5 {is also interesting and was analyzed by Watson in the game Korchnoi-Nielsen, see the archives.}) 6... Bb4 7. Qa4+ Nc6 8. Bb5 Bd7 9. Nge2 {This is the main point of waiting to develop the knight. Here it protects c3 and d4 and leaves the f-pawn free to annoy the knight on e4.} (9. Bxc6 {makes little sense,} Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 Bxc6 11. Qc2 Bb5 {and Black has nothing to worry about.}) 9... O-O 10. O-O Bxc3 (10... Nxc3 {tries to keep the bishop but White can claim an edge after} 11. bxc3 Be7 12. Qb3 {hitting d5} Na5 (12... Be6 13. Bd3 $16) 13. Qb1 Bxb5 14. Qxb5 c6 15. Qd3 Nc4 16. Ng3 $14 {White has a clear plan of attacking on the kingside while Black still needs to find something concrete on the queenside.}) 11. bxc3 (11. Nxc3 Re8 (11... Nxc3 12. bxc3 Re8 13. f4) 12. Bxc6 Bxc6 13. Qc2) 11... a6 12. Bxc6 Bxc6 13. Qc2 f6 {After this move Black is in real danger but the position is already more pleasant for White.} (13... Bb5 {would be an option, to activate the bishop,} 14. a4 Bc4 (14... Bxe2 $6 15. Qxe2 f5 (15... Nxc3 16. Qe3 Ne4 17. f3 $18) 16. f3 Ng5 17. Bxg5 Qxg5 18. a5 {with a clear positional advantage.}) 15. f3 Ng5 16. Rf2 c5 17. Bxg5 Qxg5 18. f4 Qe7 19. f5 cxd4 20. cxd4 Qh4 21. Nf4 {looks dangerous for Black as well.}) 14. f3 Ng5 15. Bxg5 fxg5 16. f4 Qd7 $6 {I don't think Black can survive with two white pawns on e5 and f5.} (16... Bb5 17. f5 g4 18. Rf2 {doesn't change so much}) (16... gxf4 {this should be played} 17. Nxf4 Qg5 18. Ne6 Rxf1+ 19. Rxf1 Qg4 20. Nf4 (20. Nxc7 $2 {is not advisable} Rc8 21. e6 $1 {White can still draw by finding some good moves} Rxc7 22. Qf2 h6 23. Qf8+ Kh7 24. Qd8 Bb5 25. Qxc7 Bxf1 26. Kxf1 Qf5+ 27. Kg1 Qxe6 $11) 20... Rf8 21. h3 Qg5 22. Qd2 {White has a better knight and a passed pawn, but Black can still fight at least.}) 17. f5 Ba4 18. Qb1 Bb5 19. e6 (19. Rf2 Bxe2 20. Rxe2 Qxf5 21. Qxb7 {is also good for White}) 19... Qe7 20. Rf2 h5 21. g4 $1 h4 (21... hxg4 {gives a nice place for the knight} 22. Ng3 c5 23. Qd1 cxd4 24. cxd4 Rac8 25. Qxg4 {and Black is in trouble.}) 22. Nc1 Bc4 23. Nd3 Bxd3 24. Qxd3 a5 25. Rb1 b6 26. Re2 Rfd8 27. Rf1 (27. Re5 $1 {would be enough for the win} Rd6 28. Rb5 Rad8 29. a4 Qe8 30. Qf3 Qc6 31. Kg2 $18) 27... Kh8 28. Qf3 c6 29. Re5 Rd6 30. f6 {Opening the position. White is still better, but now the endgame requires precision and a lot of effort.} gxf6 31. Qxf6+ Qxf6 32. Rxf6 Re8 33. Kg2 Kg7 34. Rff5 Rdxe6 35. Rxg5+ Kh6 36. Rh5+ Kg6 37. Kh3 Rxe5 38. dxe5 Rf8 39. Kxh4 Rf2 40. Rg5+ Kh6 41. h3 Rc2 42. Rg8 Rxc3 43. g5+ Kh7 44. Rd8 Re3 45. Rd6 Rxe5 46. Rxc6 d4 47. Rd6 Re2 48. a4 d3 49. Rxd3 Re4+ 50. Kh5 Rxa4 51. g6+ Kg7 52. Rd7+ Kg8 53. Rb7 Rb4 54. h4 a4 55. Kg5 a3 56. h5 Rb5+ 57. Kf6 1-0


