{This year many top players didn't play the Chinese Championship and Wei Yi was the main favourite. He played solidly and even won the title with one round to go.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Qc7 {The Paulsen is very common nowadays.} 6. Be2 a6 7. O-O Nf6 8. Be3 Be7 9. f4 d6 10. Kh1 O-O 11. Qe1 Bd7 (11... Nxd4 12. Bxd4 b5 13. Qg3 Bb7 14. a3 Bc6) 12. Qg3 Nxd4 13. Bxd4 Bc6 14. Rae1 b5 15. a3 {This is the critical position of the 6.Be2 line. My database still has more than 500 games here. [#] is the usual way to reach the position of the game.} Rae8 {!? A very subtle move, directed against the logical continuation Bd3.} 16. Bf3 {Not the best square but there is nothing better.} (16. Bd3 {is met by} e5 {!} 17. fxe5 Nh5 {and Black is fine:} 18. Qh3 dxe5 19. Nd5 Bxd5 20. exd5 exd4 21. Qxh5 g6) 16... Rd8 {The rook deviated the bishop and eventually goes to support the d5 push.} 17. Re3 {!? 17.Nd1 or 17.Re2 are mostly played.} (17. Nd5 {is far from being deadly, as after} exd5 18. exd5 Ba8 19. Rxe7 Qxe7 20. Re1 Qxe1+ 21. Qxe1 Nxd5 {the position seems around equal.}) 17... Qb7 $146 {?!} ({A previous game finished quickly after Black missed a couple of tactics:} 17... g6 {There is no reason to delay playing this move. The position is balanced as Black's d5 push is not easy to stop.} 18. e5 (18. Rfe1 d5 {!} 19. Be5 Qb7) 18... dxe5 (18... Nd7 {This position has to be carefully checked, but I don't think White has an advantage.}) 19. Bxe5 Qb6 20. Bxc6 Qxc6 21. Qh4 Nd5 22. Qxh7+ {1-0 (22) Bernadskiy,V (2358)-Fedoseev,V (2353) Lvov 2009}) 18. Rfe1 g6 19. Qh3 Rfe8 {The f8 square has to be freed for the bishop and the rook is well placed to support an eventual e5 push. [#]} 20. Qh6 {?! The next moves seem natural for White but might be parried. There was a very strong continuation that was not easy to see over the board:} (20. b4 {! With the usual idea of closing the queenside and later taking the c5 square.} Nd7 21. e5 {!} dxe5 (21... Bxf3 22. Rxf3 d5 23. Nd1 {! and soon White will break through on the kingside.}) 22. fxe5 Nb6 23. Bxc6 Qxc6 {looks fine at first but...} 24. Bc5 {! Exchanging bishops opens the f6 square for the knight.} Bxc5 25. bxc5 Qxc5 (25... Nd5 26. Rf3 {!} Nxc3 27. Rxf7 {!} h5 28. Rf6 {±}) 26. Rf3 {and Black has a tough time coping with both the Ne4 and Rxf7 threats.}) 20... Bf8 21. Qg5 Nd7 22. Nd5 {[#]} (22. e5 {doesn't seem very dangerous here but might still be the best move.}) 22... Qb8 {? I don't really understand this move, as the usual break seems to work perfectly:} (22... e5 {!} 23. fxe5 (23. Bc3 Bxd5 24. exd5 Bg7 25. f5 Rc8 {with a pleasant position.}) 23... dxe5 24. Bc3 Bxd5 25. exd5 Qc7 {Black's position is fine.}) 23. Nf6+ Nxf6 24. Bxf6 Rc8 25. Bg4 {Very direct play, which will work only thanks to Black's blunder. The best way to get an advantage was [#]} (25. h4 {!} Qc7 26. h5 Be7 27. hxg6 fxg6 28. Rd1 {⩲ with a small positional plus.}) 25... Ba8 $2 {?? A blunder that is hard to understand. Black should quickly exchange the dangerous bishop and it could easily be achieved: [#]Now Black's position collapses remarkably quickly.} ({After} 25... Qb7 26. c3 (26. Qh4 Bg7 27. Bxg7 Kxg7 28. Rh3 h5 {∞}) 26... Bg7 (26... Be7) 27. Bxg7 Kxg7 {the engines evaluate the position as equal.}) 26. Rh3 {Brutally simple. Black is helpless against the attack on the h-file.} Rc5 (26... Rxc2 27. Qh4 h6 28. Qxh6 {might be the easy sacrifice missed by Black?}) 27. Qh4 h5 28. b4 {There is nothing better than resigning. After 28...Rxc2 White plays 29.Bxh5 and Black's king won't survive long.} 1-0


