1. c4 g6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Qb3 dxc4 6. Qxc4 O-O 7. e4 a6 8. Be2 b5 9. Qb3 c5 10. dxc5 Nbd7 {A provocative move that has come back into fashion over the last couple of years or so.} ({In Delchev's new work (The Safest Grünfeld Reloaded, Chess Stars, 2019) he recommends} 10... Bb7 {which has been covered many times in ChessPublishing.com.}) 11. Be3 ({I examined both pawn pushes} 11. c6) ({and} 11. e5 {in Kaczmarczyk, D - Heimann, A Swiss league 2019. The latter might offer a nominal edge according to the engines, but a well-prepared Heimann had no problems to steer the game towards a draw.}) 11... Ng4 12. c6 Nxe3 13. cxd7 Nxg2+ 14. Kf1 Qxd7 15. Kxg2 Qh3+ 16. Kg1 Be6 17. Ng5 {When I was analyzing the Volkov, S - Riazantsev, A encounter from a couple of years ago I described this move "as possible, but evaluating the consequences isn't that evident". Now we have a proper OTB test to help us to better understand the complications..} ({I think that Black had enough practical compensation (and did go on to win) after} 17. Qc2 Rac8 18. Ng5 {, but White was still OK in Volkov, S - Riazantsev, A St.Petersburg 2017 (see the archives) .}) 17... Qh4 18. Nxe6 fxe6 19. Qxe6+ $6 ({I felt (and still feel!) that} 19. Nd1 {was more prudent i.e.} Rad8 20. Bf3 Rd6 {Quoting myself again: "White retains his extra piece, but can't unravel, so Black seems to be OK".} 21. Kg2 Qg5+ 22. Kf1 Qf4 23. Kg2 Qg5+ $11) 19... Kh8 20. Rf1 Rf4 $1 {I had already considered this position in my ChessPub analysis. I concluded that "Black's pressure is more important than the piece deficit". It looks like Wei Yi (and friends) came to the same conclusion in their prep.} 21. h3 Raf8 22. Rh2 {So f2 is well-defended, but not e2 it seems...} Bxc3 $1 23. bxc3 Rxe4 {Regaining the piece.} 24. Qxa6 Rxe2 25. Qxb5 Qe4 $1 {Centralizing the queen and thus keeping up the pressure. White can't hold onto all of his pawn islands.} ({If} 25... Rxa2 {then} 26. Qe5+ {virtually forces} Qf6 {with a likely draw.}) 26. Qb4 Qa8 27. c4 ({Or} 27. a4 Re4 ({or} 27... Rf3) 28. c4 Qc6 {and Black is not risking very much by building up the pressure on both wings.}) 27... Qxa2 28. Qc3+ Kg8 29. Ra1 Rc2 (29... Qc2 30. Qxc2 Rxc2 31. Re1 Kf7 32. Re4 {is similar.}) 30. Rxa2 Rxc3 31. Re2 Kf7 32. Re4 Rc8 {Black will win a pawn and thus have the better endgame, but Navara decides that it's the moment to improve his h2-rook.} 33. Kg2 R8xc4 34. Rxc4 Rxc4 35. Rh1 Kf6 36. Ra1 h5 37. Ra6+ Kf5 38. Ra5+ e5 39. Ra8 {Keeping as active and vigilant as possible to stop the opponent making progress. As to the broken pawns: Black's reduce his opportunities to hide and expand, whereas White's are actually quite good in keeping the opponent's pieces and pawns at bay.} Rc6 40. Rf8+ Rf6 41. Ra8 Kf4 42. Ra4+ Kg5 ({After} 42... e4 {there is} 43. f3 $1 Re6 44. fxe4 Rxe4 45. Ra2 {when it's hard to create any danger for the opponent.}) 43. Ra5 Rf5 44. Ra6 Rf4 45. Re6 Kf5 46. Re8 e4 47. Re7 Kf6 48. Re8 g5 49. Rh8 h4 50. f3 $5 {What an astonishing move!} ({I think most people would have settled for} 50. Re8) ({or} 50. Rf8+ {disrupting Black's attempts to 'do something constructive'.}) 50... exf3+ ({Otherwise} 50... Rxf3 51. Rf8+ Ke5 52. Rxf3 exf3+ 53. Kxf3 Kf5 54. Ke3 $1 $11 {is just a draw.}) (50... Kg7 51. Re8 {doesn't change very much.}) 51. Kf2 Ke7 52. Ra8 Rf5 53. Ra3 Kf6 54. Rxf3 g4 ({Or} 54... Rf4 55. Kg2 {(it's best not to capture and give Black a passed pawn)} Ke5 56. Ra3 {with a draw in sight.}) 55. hxg4 Rxf3+ 56. Kxf3 Kg5 57. Kg2 Kxg4 58. Kh2 h3 59. Kh1 h2 60. Kg2 h1=N 1/2-1/2


