1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 c5 8. Rb1 O-O 9. Be2 Nc6 10. d5 Ne5 11. Nxe5 Bxe5 12. O-O $6 {White really seems keen on giving up his c-pawn! The?! label indicates what I think of it in objective terms.} ({Although} 12. Qd2 {has been played a great deal (you can find a couple of Aronian, L - Vachier-Lagrave, M games from 2013 in the archives) other surprise weapons occasionally get played at this point.}) ({The most significant of these is} 12. Rb3 {see Ding Liren - Ni Hua, Jiangsu 2009, in the archives (where Black played the dubious-looking 12...Qd6). The critical line involves} c4 13. Bxc4 Qc7 {e.g.} 14. Bd3 (14. Be2 Bxc3+ 15. Bd2 Be5 16. Bh6 Rd8 17. Qd2 e6 18. O-O exd5 19. exd5 Bxh2+ 20. Kh1 Be5 {Kozul, Z - Areshchenko, A Plovdiv 2012}) 14... Bxc3+ 15. Bd2 Be5 $1 {(it's definitely a good idea to keep bishops on for now)} 16. Qc1 Qxc1+ 17. Bxc1 f5 (17... e6 $5 {is the other way to hit at the centre}) 18. exf5 gxf5 ({more precise is} 18... Bxf5 $1 19. Bxf5 Rxf5 20. Rxb7 Bd6 {and Black picks up the d-pawn with a fully satisfactory game}) 19. O-O b6 {Sokolov, I - Fier, A Dubai 2016, with near equality, but White keeps some nagging pressure with} 20. Ba3) 12... Bxc3 13. Bh6 ({The alternatives also come into the 'experimental' category:} 13. Rb3 Bg7 14. Rg3 {(is this rook really effective here?)} e6 15. Bc4 exd5 16. Bxd5 Qc7 17. h4 Be6 18. Bxe6 fxe6 19. h5 Qf7 20. hxg6 hxg6 21. Qg4 $13 {Pak, Y - Marin, Mi Almaty Blitz 2016}) (13. Be3 b6 14. f4 e6 $5 15. Bc4 Bb7 16. Qd3 (16. dxe6 Qxd1 17. Rbxd1 Bxe4 18. exf7+ $13) 16... exd5 17. exd5 Qf6 18. Bxc5 bxc5 19. Rxb7 Rfb8 {Drenchev, P - Erturan, Y Albena 2013, with easy equality.}) (13. Bc4 Qc7 14. f4 a6 15. a4 {(sure, White has a lead in development and some active intentions, but Black shouldn't be in too much danger)} Bd4+ 16. Kh1 Bd7 17. Bd2 Rab8 (17... b5 18. axb5 axb5 19. Bxb5 Bxb5 20. Rxb5 Ra1 $15 {with a very comfortable game}) 18. a5 b5 19. axb6 Rxb6 20. Qe2 Rxb1 21. Rxb1 a5 $17 {Pham Chuong - Lei Tingjie, Ho Chi Minh City 2017, and White lacks real compensation.}) 13... Bg7 ({Previously} 13... Re8 $5 {had been played:} 14. Qb3 Bd4 15. Be3 e5 $5 (15... Bxe3 16. Qxe3 b6 {is akin to the main game continuation}) 16. Bb5 Rf8 17. Bh6 a6 18. Bxf8 Qxf8 19. Be2 b5 {and a draw was agreed in Ferreira, J - Tomazini, A Albena 2011, but that wonderful bishop on d4 ensures more than enough compensation for the small material investment.}) 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. Qc2 b6 16. Qc3+ f6 17. f4 e6 $1 {I think that Black should aim for this counter, if at all reasonable, before White gets his attack underway.} 18. Rbd1 exd5 19. Rxd5 ({After} 19. exd5 $6 Qd6 {Black keeps everything under control.}) 19... Qe7 20. e5 Bb7 21. Rd6 Rad8 22. Rfd1 Rxd6 23. Rxd6 {Wei Yi has limited any problems associated with the d-file, but now needs to resolve the tension in the central arena.} Bc8 24. Bc4 fxe5 25. fxe5 Rf5 $6 ({The engine suggests the more ambitious} 25... Qh4 $1 $17) ({A superior rook move could be} 25... Rf4 {when the options of ...Re4 and ...Rd4 might offer some chances for a durable advantage.}) 26. Rc6 $1 {Maximizing his capacity to cause mischief.} Bb7 27. Rd6 Kh6 28. Qh3+ Rh5 29. Qe3+ Qg5 30. Qxg5+ $6 ({With Black's king being so draughty,} 30. Qf2 $5 {comes to mind e.g.} Qxe5 31. Qf8+ Kg5 32. Qd8+ {and I think that most humans would accept a repetition with} Kh6 {etc.}) 30... Rxg5 31. e6 Re5 32. Rd7 Bc6 33. Rc7 (33. Rxa7 $2 {allows Black the time for} b5 $1) 33... Be8 34. Rc8 Ba4 35. Rc7 a6 36. e7 Bb5 $1 {It all holds together!} 37. Bxb5 {There is nothing better.} axb5 38. a3 Kg5 39. Rb7 Kf4 $1 {Wei Yi hopes that a more active king will keep his winning chances alive.} 40. Rxb6 Rxe7 41. Rxb5 Rc7 {Thee rook is ideally placed behind the passed pawn.} 42. Kf2 Ke4 43. Ke2 Kd4 44. Rb3 ({Switching the king to the queenside doesn't solve all his problems:} 44. Kd2 Rd7 45. Kc2 Rf7 {and a rook invasion follows.}) 44... c4 45. Rh3 Rb7 {The rook will penetrate the white camp via the b-file.} 46. Kd1 c3 47. Kc2 Rb2+ 48. Kc1 Rxg2 49. Rxh7 g5 50. a4 g4 51. a5 Ra2 {There are only two pawns each remaining, but defending such a position requires precision.} 52. Rg7 Kd3 53. Rd7+ Ke3 54. Rg7 Kf3 55. Rf7+ ({I prefer} 55. Rc7 $1 {after which I believe that the draw becomes relatively straightforward:} Kg2 56. Rc4 Ra1+ (56... Kh3 57. Rxc3+ Kxh2 58. Rc2+ $11) 57. Kc2 Kh3 58. Rc5 Kxh2 59. Rh5+ Kg2 60. Kxc3 {etc.}) 55... Kg2 56. Rg7 Ra4 57. a6 $2 {Losing the plot. The h-pawn needs to be retained for now.} (57. Rh7 Rxa5 58. Rh4 Kf3 59. Kc2 Rc5 60. Rh8 $15 {and I don't see how Black makes progress.}) 57... Kxh2 58. a7 g3 59. Kc2 g2 60. Kb3 Ra1 61. Rh7+ Kg3 62. Rg7+ Kf3 63. Rf7+ Ke4 64. Re7+ Kf5 65. Rg7 c2 $1 {This fine move must have been what Esipenko had overlooked.} 66. Kxc2 Rxa7 $1 67. Rxa7 (67. Rxg2 Ra2+) 67... g1=Q 68. Rd7 Qc5+ 69. Kd1 Ke4 70. Rd2 Qc4 71. Rh2 Qf1+ 72. Kc2 Ke3 73. Rh6 Qf4 74. Rh3+ Ke2 75. Rc3 Qa4+ 76. Rb3 Qc4+ 77. Kb2 Kd2 {White resigned a little early, but he is about to be squeezed into the corner, at which point he runs out of acceptable defensive moves.} 0-1


