{The winner of the Wijk aan Zee Challengers is the 15-year old Chinese Wei Yi! He was simply crushing through the field. It is worth looking at his brilliant victory in the penultimate round.} 1. e4 {Ftacnik,L Arsovic,Goran} c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Qc7 {The recently very popular Sicilian Paulsen variation.} 6. Be3 a6 {Diagram} 7. Qf3 {<xml:en>A somewhat unexpected move that has been going through a surprising boom in last few months. White players are probably tired of the intricacies of the main line with 7.<sym>Q</sym>d2 and want something fresh and less well analysed.</:en/xml> A relatively new alternative to the main lines with Qd2 and 0-0-0. The idea is to castle queenside here again and White often intends to play Qg3, offering the trade of queens after which Qxg3 hxg3 improves his pawn structure, opens the h-file for the rook and it usually yields a better and more easy to play endgame. A somewhat unexpected move that has been going through a surprising boom in last few months. White players are probably tired of the intricacies of the main line with 7.d2 and want something fresh and less well analysed.} (7. Qd2 Nf6 8. O-O-O) 7... Ne5 {<xml:en>If you ever witnessed a true exception to the rules please prepare yourself for the repetition. Black will ignore the first rule of the opening strategy - "Develop the pieces" at his peril.</:en/xml> If you ever witnessed a true exception to the rules please prepare yourself for the repetition. Black will ignore the first rule of the opening strategy - "Develop the pieces" at his peril.} (7... Nf6 8. O-O-O (8. Be2 h5 9. Qg3 Ne5 10. f4 h4 11. Qh3 Nc4 12. e5 Nxb2 13. Bc1 Bb4 14. Bd2 Nc4 15. exf6 Nxd2 16. fxg7 Rg8 17. Kxd2 Qxf4+ 18. Kd3 e5 19. Qg4 Qxg4 20. Bxg4 exd4 21. Nd5 Rxg7 22. Nc7+ Kd8 23. Nxa8 Rxg4 24. Nb6 d5 25. Nxc8 Kxc8 $11 {1-0 (54) Durarbayli,V (2635)-Izzat,K (2424) Baku 2015 '=' Ftacnik,L: '='}) 8... Ne5 (8... Be7 9. Kb1 d6 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. g4 Rb8 12. g5 Nd7 13. Qg3 Qa5 14. Bc1 d5 15. h4 Qb4 16. h5 Bd6 17. f4 Nc5 18. Qe3 O-O 19. e5 Be7 20. Rh3 Na4 21. Nxa4 Qxa4 $11 {1-0 (34) Popov,I (2622)-Lazarev,V (2387) Chennai 2015 '=' Ftacnik,L: '='}) 9. Qg3 b5 10. f4 Neg4 11. Bg1 h5 12. e5 b4 13. Na4 Nd5 14. Nb3 Bb7 15. Nac5 Rc8 16. Bd3 a5 17. Kb1 Bc6 18. Na6 Qd8 19. Nd4 $14 {1/2 (109) Nepomniachtchi,I (2714)-Wang,Y (2720) Beijing 2014}) 8. Qg3 h5 {<xml:en>This move was probably invented by Giri and any idea prepared by one of the youngest and strongest GM in the world deserves serious attention.</:en/xml> The young Dutch lady follows the path of her countryman Anish Giri, who played two interesting games with good results in the same tournament, but in the A group. This move was probably invented by Giri and any idea prepared by one of the youngest and strongest GM in the world deserves serious attention.} (8... Nf6 9. f4 Nc4 10. e5 Nxb2 11. Bd2 Nd5 12. Nxd5 exd5 13. Nf5 g6 14. Nd6+ Bxd6 15. exd6 Qb6 16. Qb3 Qxd6 17. Qxb2 Qe6+ 18. Kf2 $18 {1-0 (18) Wei,Y (2641)-Lei,T (2421) Zhongshan 2014}) 9. O-O-O (9. Nf3 Bd6 10. Qg5 Ne7 11. Be2 b5 $11 {'=' Ftacnik,L: '='}) (9. f3 b5 10. O-O-O d6 11. f4 Ng4 12. e5 dxe5 13. fxe5 Nxe3 14. Qxe3 Bd7 15. Be2 g6 16. Qf3 Rc8 17. Rhf1 Rh7 18. Kb1 Bb4 19. Ne4 Qxe5 {1-0 (42) Karjakin,S (2767)-Giri,A (2768) Tashkent 2014} 20. Qd3 f5 21. Ng5 $14) (9. f4 Ng4 10. Bd2 b5 $11 {'=' Ftacnik,L: '='}) 9... h4 10. Qh3 {<xml:en>Both players in this game are repeating the moves from the game that was played in Wijk 2015 in group A. The white queen would be surprisingly lost after any other (reckless) retreat.</:en/xml> Both players in this game are repeating the moves from the game that was played in Wijk 2015 in group A. The white queen would be surprisingly lost after any other (reckless) retreat.} (10. Qf4 $2 g5 $1 11. Qxg5 f6 12. Qf4 Bh6 $19) 10... b5 {<xml:en>Personally I am a great fan of the plan of preventing main ideas of the opponent. The modest retreat of the knight to g6 would have been surprisingly efficient.</:en/xml> A standard Sicilian game. The black king stands in the center, therefore White launches a central attack with f4-f5 and Black looks for counterplay on the queenside. Personally I am a great fan of the plan of preventing main ideas of the opponent. The modest retreat of the knight to g6 would have been surprisingly efficient.} (10... Ng6 $5 11. Bd3 b5 12. Nde2 Ne5 $11 {'=' Ftacnik,L: '='}) 11. f4 Nc4 (11... Ng6 $6 12. e5 Bb7 13. Bd3 $14) (11... b4 {is a known counterattacking motif, but it makes no sense this time, because after} 12. Na4 {the b6 square becomes vulnerable!}) 12. Bxc4 Qxc4 (12... bxc4 $5 {<xml:en>Haast trusts the great predecessors, but she might have considered also recapturing with the pawn with a solid position with shared chances.</:en/xml> Haast trusts the great predecessors, but she might have considered also recapturing with the pawn with a solid position with shared chances.} 13. g4 Rb8 14. Nde2 Ne7 15. Rhf1 Nc6 $11 {'=' Ftacnik,L: '='}) 13. f5 {White has already arrived, but the e6 pawn is well protected at the moment, he still needs to increase the pressure to execute a blow. It is time to finish the development for Black...} Bb7 {! A typical move in some Sicilian lines. Black delays the development of his kingside and brings his bishop and the a8 rook into the game.} (13... b4 14. Na4 Qc7 (14... Qxa2 {loses too many tempi. Black gives up the b6 square and the queen alone cannot create any serious threats.} 15. Nb6 Rb8 16. Nb3 {! Trapping the queen and securing the b6 square for the knight! Black is in trouble...} Nf6 17. fxe6 dxe6 18. e5 {+⁠−}) 15. e5 $14) 14. Rhf1 e5 {<xml:en>The line with 14...<sym>R</sym>c8 that Giri chose against Radjabov is very interesting. White can open up the position and put Black under severe pressure with a rook sacrifice on f7.</:en/xml> ! Anne Haast follows Giri's improvement over his own game. The line with 14...c8 that Giri chose against Radjabov is very interesting. White can open up the position and put Black under severe pressure with a rook sacrifice on f7.} (14... b4 15. Na4 Qxa2 16. Nb6 Be7 (16... Rd8 17. Nb3 $18) 17. e5 $16) (14... Rc8 {and the game finished in a spectacular way:} 15. fxe6 (15. Nf3 {! The knight is heading to e5, from where it attacks the two most critical targets on d7 and f7. Probably the only move is 15...f6, but to weaken the e6 square cannot lead to anything good either.} Nf6 (15... b4 {is too slow} 16. Ne5 Qc7 17. fxe6 {+⁠− and White is coming faster!}) 16. Ne5 Qc7 17. Nxd7 {!} Nxd7 18. fxe6 {+⁠− Black collapses.}) 15... dxe6 {Diagram} 16. Rxf7 $5 (16. Nf3 Nf6 {is not the same anymore as in the 15.Nf3 line, because White cannot sacrifice on d7 followed by taking on e6!}) 16... Kxf7 17. b3 {Deflecting the queen from the e6 square. Fortunately for Black, he has} (17. Nf3 Rh5 $1 (17... Qc7 $2 18. Ng5+ Ke8 (18... Kg6 19. Qxe6+ Kh5 20. g4+ $18) 19. Qxe6+ Qe7 20. Qg6+ $18) 18. Rd7+ (18. g4 Ba3 19. Bd4 (19. gxh5 Bxb2+ 20. Kb1 Bxc3 $19) 19... Rhc5 20. Qxh4 Bxe4 21. Bxc5 Rxc5 22. Ng5+ Rxg5 23. Nxe4 $11 {'=' Ftacnik,L: '='}) 18... Be7 19. g4 Bxe4 20. gxh5 Bxf3 21. Qxf3+ Nf6 $11 {'=' Ftacnik,L: '='}) 17... Ba3+ {! Black frees the f8 square for the king with an intermediate check.} 18. Kb1 Qxc3 19. Qxe6+ Kf8 {Diagram White had nothing more than forcing a perpetual check with} 20. Rf1+ Nf6 21. Rxf6+ {!} gxf6 22. Qxf6+ Kg8 23. Qg6+ Kf8 24. Qf6+ Kg8 (24... Ke8 25. Qg6+ Kd7 26. Qe6+ Kc7 27. Bf4+ Kd8 28. Bg5+ $11 {'=' Ftacnik,L: '='}) 25. Qg6+ Kf8 26. Qf6+ {1/2 (26) Radjabov,T (2734)-Giri,A (2784) Wijk aan Zee 2015 1/2 Radjabov-Giri, Wijk aan Zee 2015}) 15. Nb3 Qc7 {Arsovic,Goran: '*' Black must cover the a5 square.} (15... Nf6 {Allowing Na5 leads to serious positional problems after} 16. Na5 Qc7 17. Nxb7 Qxb7 18. Bg5 {! White is going to take on f6 and install his knight to d5, which will dominate the entire game. Black is positionally lost there, while} Nxe4 {loses tactically to} 19. Nxe4 Qxe4 20. Rfe1 {+⁠− and the e5 falls.}) 16. Kb1 $146 {<xml:en>In case you had some problems believing the first part of the game do not despair. Your annotator has been equally amazed by the modern form of treating opening problems by Black. The king move in the game is the first independent idea of this battle.</:en/xml> This is Wei Yi's improvement over the Saric-Giri game. Quite a deep idea, which was missed by Black in this game. In case you had some problems believing the first part of the game do not despair. Your annotator has been equally amazed by the modern form of treating opening problems by Black. The king move in the game is the first independent idea of this battle.} (16. Bg5 {when Black had time to play} Rc8 17. Rf2 Be7 {!} 18. Bxe7 Kxe7 {! securing and excellent square for the knight on f6!} 19. Rfd2 Nf6 20. a3 Rh6 $11 {0-1 (47) Saric,I (2666)-Giri,A (2784) Wijk aan Zee 2015 '=' Ftacnik,L: '=' ! With the idea to drive the king into safety with Kf8-g8. He could not do it with the rook on h8 because White had g4-g5, using the fact that Black cannot take en passant on g3.} 21. Qe3 Kf8 {and Black was fine in Saric-Giri, Wijk aan Zee 2015.}) (16. f6 {fails right away, because of the hidden point...} Nxf6 17. Rxf6 gxf6 18. Bb6 {and Black has} Bh6+ {! freeing the f8 square for the king! This is the point of playing 16.Kb1!} 19. Kb1 Qxb6 20. Qxd7+ Kf8 {−⁠+}) 16... Rc8 $2 {<xml:en>My explanation for the disaster that will now befall the second player is connected with the symmetries on the board. Black has so far only used the pieces of the queenside and seriously breached the balance between both sides of the board.</:en/xml> ? Black fails to recognize the differences and falls into the prepared trap! Diagram My explanation for the disaster that will now befall the second player is connected with the symmetries on the board. Black has so far only used the pieces of the queenside and seriously breached the balance between both sides of the board.} (16... Nf6 $1 {! which was most probably Giri's preparation. He is already threatening to take on e4 and he seems to be doing well.} 17. Nd5 {It seems like White has nothing better than this, but I believe that if White cannot take with a piece on d5 and he is forced to change the structure with exd5, he cannot hope for an advantage.} Nxd5 (17... Bxd5 18. exd5 a5 (18... Rc8 {Arsovic,Goran} 19. c3 {with mutual chances. Black might go for a balanced endgame with Qc4-g4 for instance.} Rh5 $13) 19. Rfe1 $14) 18. exd5 Rc8 19. Rf2 Ba8 (19... f6 20. d6 Qc4 $11 {'=' Ftacnik,L: '='}) 20. f6 gxf6 21. Qf5 Qd6 22. Bc5 Rxc5 23. Nxc5 Qxc5 24. Qxf6 Bxd5 25. Qxh8 Qxf2 26. Qxe5+ Be6 27. Qb8+ Ke7 28. Qd6+ $11 {'=' Ftacnik,L: '='}) (16... b4 {was also wrong, because after} 17. Nd5 Bxd5 18. Rxd5 Nf6 19. Ra5 {! deprives B lack from his counterplay with a5-a4 and White wants to enter a good knight vs. bad bishop position with Bg5 and the d5 square is very weak!} Nxe4 {? tactically fails to} 20. Qf3 {!}) 17. f6 $1 {[%mdl 128] <xml:en>Introduction to a shockingly swift punishment centred around the weakness of the d7 spot.</:en/xml> !! Opening the h3-c8 diagonal! A series of sacrifices are coming and Black loses because he cannot defend the d7 square. Introduction to a shockingly swift punishment centred around the weakness of the d7 spot.} Nxf6 (17... d6 18. fxg7 Bxg7 19. Qg4 Bf8 20. a3 $16) 18. Rxf6 $1 {! Eliminating the defender of the d7 weakness!} gxf6 19. Bb6 {Arsovic,Goran: '!' ! Deflecting the other defender of the d7 pawn. Bh6 is not a check anymore thanks to 16.Kb1. Black has nothing better than} Qc6 (19... Qd6 20. Rxd6 Bxd6 21. Bf2 $18) (19... Qxb6 $2 20. Qxd7#) 20. Na5 {! The haunt of the queen continues! The d7 square is still the key!} Qe6 21. Nxb7 {White has won material. He gained two pieces for the sacrificed rook and all his pieces are standing very well. The knight is soon coming to d5 with decisive threats. Black must try to win back the material with Rb8, otherwise he is lost.} Rb8 $2 {<xml:en>The Dutch women's champion did not want to suffer in the ending with rook against the two mighty minor pieces for White. Her honest ambition to punish White for the excessive aggressivity will backfire in the most charming way.</:en/xml> Diagram The Dutch women's champion did not want to suffer in the ending with rook against the two mighty minor pieces for White. Her honest ambition to punish White for the excessive aggressivity will backfire in the most charming way.} (21... Qxh3 22. gxh3 Rb8 23. Nd6+ {! saves the piece and guarantees a winning endgame.} Bxd6 24. Rxd6 {+⁠−} Rc8 (24... Ke7 25. Bc7 $18) 25. Be3 Rc6 26. Rd2 f5 27. exf5 Rh5 28. Rf2 $16) 22. Nd5 $1 {! This is the only way to victory!} Rxb7 {<xml:en>A sad necessity as the exchange of the queens is not possible any more.</:en/xml> Diagram A sad necessity as the exchange of the queens is not possible any more.} (22... Qxh3 23. Nc7+ {!} Ke7 {White could give a perpetual check with Nd5-c7, but he can play for more with} 24. Bc5+ {!} d6 {Diagram} 25. Rxd6 $1 {Arsovic,Goran: '+-!' !! As simple as that! Black is more than a queen up, but he cannot avoid getting mated!} f5 {trying to open an escaping route to f6 does not change anything...} (25... Qe6 26. Rd8+ Qd6 27. Bxd6#) (25... Qd7 26. Re6#) (25... Qe3 26. Rd4#) (25... Rxb7 26. Rd1# {is quite a pretty mate!}) 26. Nd5+ Ke8 27. Rd8+ (27. Nf6+ Ke7 28. Rxa6# (28. Rc6# {Another awesome mate!})) 27... Rxd8 28. Nf6#) 23. Qc3 {! The only move to win again! White switches his queen to the queenside and creates the decisive threat of Qc8.} Qc6 {Other moves are also losing quickly:} (23... d6 24. Qc6+ Qd7 (24... Rd7 25. Qc8+ {+⁠−}) 25. Nxf6+ {+⁠−} Ke7 26. Nxd7 Rxd7 27. Ba5 $18) (23... Rb8 24. Nc7+ {+⁠−}) 24. Nxf6+ $1 {<xml:en>The spirit and energy of White's final attack are truly charming. Black will not get a single tempo to recover from the blows from every side and angle.</:en/xml> ! The firework continues! The spirit and energy of White's final attack are truly charming. Black will not get a single tempo to recover from the blows from every side and angle.} (24. Qxc6 $2 dxc6 25. Nc7+ Rxc7 26. Bxc7 Be7 $17) 24... Ke7 {Diagram} (24... Qxf6 25. Qc8+ Ke7 26. Bc5+ {Arsovic,Goran: '+-'} (26. Bd8+ Ke6 27. Bxf6 Kxf6 28. Qxb7 $18) 26... d6 (26... Ke6 27. Qe8+ Qe7 28. Rd6#) 27. Qxb7+ Ke6 (27... Ke8) 28. Qc8+ Ke7 29. Qc7+ Ke8 30. Qc6+ Kd8 31. Bb6+ $18) 25. Bd8+ $1 {! Not the only, but the most spectacular win!} (25. Rxd7+ Rxd7 26. Qxc6 Rd1#) (25. Qxe5+ Qe6 26. Nd5+ Ke8 27. Qxh8 $18) 25... Ke6 (25... Kxd8 26. Qxc6 $18 {+⁠−}) 26. Qh3# {Arsovic,Goran: '#' <xml:en>In a nice gesture Haast has decided to recreate the flavour of historical attacking games to the full - mate of the black king in the centre. Fascinating and to my understanding beautiful game!</:en/xml> ! Mate! What a game! It will be very interesting to see Wei Yi participating in the A-group next year! In a nice gesture Haast has decided to recreate the flavour of historical attacking games to the full - mate of the black king in the centre. Fascinating and to my understanding beautiful game!} 1-0


