{The following games were played as part of the speed-chess online match-up on 28 July 2019. Even though they were blitz games and the quality cannot be expected to be too high, these games featured two of the brightest young talents in the world. Additionally, in speed chess the intuition and easiness of play comes to the fore, thus giving us a better idea how it feels to play these positions with both colours.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. Nc3 Nxc3 6. dxc3 Be7 7. Be3 Nc6 8. Qd2 Be6 9. a3 {A peculiar move-order, but soon leading to what we analysed.} Qd7 10. O-O-O {Now we reach the position from the famous Karjakin-Caruana game from the Berlin Candidates, analysed in the theoretical section.} h6 {Wei Yi follows Caruana. The main alternative is the move 10...a6.} 11. Nd4 Nxd4 12. Bxd4 O-O {In case if 10... a6 this is the right way to play, but here the hook on h6 gives White something to latch onto. I criticised this move in the analytical section, but perhaps things are not that simple.} 13. c4 {This is a slower approach and it allows Black to consolidate.} (13. Rg1 {is the move I recommended, withouth going into more depth. White's play is simple: g4-g5.}) 13... Rae8 {Black's plan is to play ...f5 followed by ...Bf6, thus concentrating all his forces on the kingside.} 14. Qc3 (14. h4 f5 15. Be2 {Bh5 is what the engine suggests and then after ...Bf7 to return to f3.}) 14... f5 15. Kb1 (15. Bxg7 $4 Bg5+) (15. f4 $5 Bf6 16. c5 {is how the engine pushes forward and it does look annoying for Black with the uncomfortable pressure on the d-file.}) 15... Bf6 16. Bxf6 Rxf6 17. Bd3 {All three games reached this position.} Qc6 (17... b6 {was played in the third game and we can assume it should have been an improvement. Black doesn't waste time on ...Qc6 and then recapturing ...Qc6xe8.} 18. Rhe1 a5 19. Re2 (19. f3 Bf7 20. Rxe8+ Qxe8 21. Qd4 {looks around equal.}) (19. b3 {is the engine's suggestion, again with an equal position.}) 19... Bf7 20. Rxe8+ Qxe8 21. f3 Bg6 (21... Qe3 $1 {would have been more annoying for White.}) 22. Qd2 Qe7 23. b3 Kf8 24. h4 Re6 25. Rh1 (25. g4 $5 fxg4 26. Bxg6 Rxg6 27. h5 Rg5 28. fxg4 {is again around equal, though White's king is safer than Black's.}) 25... Qf6 26. h5 Bf7 27. Qf4 $2 (27. g4) 27... Re5 28. a4 Be6 $2 (28... Bxh5 $1 {wins a pawn in view of the back-rank problems White has.}) 29. Rd1 Qg5 30. Qxg5 hxg5 31. Rh1 {with an equal endgame that eventually Black won. 0-1 (50) Firouzja,A (2682)-Wei Yi (2736) chess.com INT 2019}) 18. f3 b6 19. Rhe1 a5 20. Re2 Bf7 21. Rxe8+ Qxe8 {We have the same structure with the same material balance in all 3 games. The position is equal, though playing White seems a tad easier.} 22. f4 (22. b3 Qe5 $2 {This attempt at immediate simplification is a blunder:} 23. Qxe5 dxe5 24. Re1 {wins a pawn} e4 25. fxe4 fxe4 26. Rxe4 Rf2 27. Re7 c5 28. Rb7 Rxg2 (28... Kf8 29. Rxb6 Rxg2 30. h3 Rg3 31. Bf5 $18) 29. Rb8+ {1-0 (29) Firouzja,A (2682)-Wei Yi (2736) chess.com INT 2019}) 22... Qe7 (22... Qe3 $1) 23. g3 Kf8 24. b3 Bh5 25. Rf1 Bg4 {This game is the most characteristic one, as in the maneuvering phase White manages to outplay Black from an equal position.} 26. Qd4 Re6 27. Qd5 Re1+ $2 {Impatience.} (27... Qf6 28. c5 $5 dxc5 29. Bc4 {poses some problems} Be2 (29... Re4 {looks scary to allow the check from g8, but Black is OK} 30. Qg8+ Ke7 31. Qc8 Qd6) 30. Qxe6 Qxe6 31. Bxe6 Bxf1 32. Bxf5 $11) 28. Rxe1 Qxe1+ 29. Ka2 $16 {The endgame is difficult for Black because of his more exposed king and weak queenside pawns.} Qf2 30. b4 {This is also possible.} (30. Qc6 Qc5 31. Qd7 {Black is paralysed to the defence of c7 and f7.} Bh3 32. a4 $1 {preventing ... a4 ideas.} Bg4 33. Qe6 Bh3 34. Be2 $1 {Bh5} Bg4 35. Bxg4 fxg4 36. Qxg4 {winning a pawn with what should be a winning endgame.}) 30... axb4 31. axb4 Qxh2 $2 {This leaves the queen offside. Even taking on g3 won't help Black much because his kingside pawns are more difficult to set in motion than White's on the queenside.} 32. Qa8+ (32. Qb7 $1 $18) 32... Ke7 33. Qc8 $6 (33. c5 $1) 33... c5 $1 34. Qc7+ Ke6 35. Qxb6 Qf2 36. b5 Be2 37. Qc6 Bxd3 38. Qd5+ Kd7 39. Qxd3 g6 {This should be around equal, but still easier for White with the protected passed pawn.} 40. Kb3 Qe1 41. c3 Qc1 42. Qc2 Qxc2+ $2 {Making things more complicated for himself.} (42... Qf1 $11) 43. Kxc2 Kc7 $4 (43... g5 $8 44. g4 $1 fxg4 45. fxg5 g3 46. gxh6 g2 47. h7 g1=Q 48. h8=Q Qf2+ 49. Kb3 Qf1 {with a probably drawn queen endgame.}) 44. Kd3 $18 Kb6 45. Ke3 Kc7 46. Kf3 {g4} g5 47. g4 $1 fxg4+ 48. Kxg4 gxf4 49. Kxf4 Kb6 50. Kf5 Kc7 51. Kg6 Kb6 52. Kxh6 1-0


