{Diagram [#] In this position most mere mortals would simply continue 22.Qe2 with a much better position, indeed (see variation 22.Qe2). But Wei Yi proves once more his exceptional calculation abilities with the stunning queen sacrifice:} 22. Rxe6 $3 (22. Qe2 Bf7 23. Bxf7+ Kxf7 24. Qe7+ Kg6 25. c3 {etc. should be winning for white with proper play.}) 22... Rxd1+ 23. Kxd1 Qd8+ 24. Ke2 Kf8 {Diagram [#] The point of queen sacrifice was that black queen and king are completely tied down to the 8th rank. But how does white improve his position in this symmetrical pawn structure? The answer is:} 25. Kf3 $1 {intending to march his king to h5, trade into the pawn endgame on e8, and invade g6 square. A brilliant concept!} Qd7 ({The check} 25... Qd1+ {does not change anything. The game could continue} 26. Kg3 Qd7 27. Re1 Qd8 28. Kh4 {with Kh5 regardless.}) 26. Re1 Qd8 27. Kg4 Qd7+ 28. Kh5 Qd8 {Diagram [#] White has achieved his ideal setup, but before he completes the last step of his plan, he makes sure to restrict black's pawn tempi in the upcoming pawn endgame with:} 29. a4 $1 ({However, direct} 29. Re8+ $5 Qxe8 30. Bxe8 Kxe8 31. Kg6 {was winning as well. For example:} Kf8 32. g4 Kg8 33. h4 b6 34. a4 a6 35. c3 b5 36. cxb5 cxb5 37. axb5 axb5 {Diagram [#]} 38. b3 $1 b4 39. c4 $18 {and black is in zugzwang.}) 29... a5 {Nothing could save black any more.} ({Two other possibilities were:} 29... b6 30. g4 Qd7 31. h4 Qd8 32. Re8+ Qxe8 33. Bxe8 Kxe8 34. Kg6 Kf8 35. Kh7 Kf7 36. g5 hxg5 37. hxg5 fxg5 38. fxg5 a6 39. b3 a5 40. c3 $18) ({and} 29... Qd7 30. a5 b6 31. a6 Qd8 32. g4 b5 33. Re8+ Qxe8 34. Bxe8 Kxe8 35. Kg6 Kf8 36. h3 Kg8 37. h4 Kf8 38. Kh7 Kf7 39. g5 fxg5 40. fxg5 hxg5 41. hxg5 bxc4 42. c3 $18 {In both cases black's fate is decided by the saved pawn tempo c2-c3.}) 30. g4 Qd7 31. h4 {White has all the time in the world to improve his position.} Qd8 {Diagram [#]} 32. Re8+ Qxe8 33. Bxe8 Kxe8 34. Kg6 Kf8 35. Kh7 $1 {King's invasion has been succesful.} Kf7 36. g5 {and black finally resigned.} ({The winning variations are a mirror image of the game Gledura-Anand:} 36. g5 fxg5 (36... hxg5 37. hxg5 f5 38. Kh8 $1 Kg6 (38... Kf8 39. g6 $18) 39. Kg8 $18) 37. fxg5 h5 (37... hxg5 38. hxg5 $18) 38. Kh8 b6 39. b3 Kg6 40. Kg8 $18 {Diagram [#]}) 1-0


