1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 {At the end of our series on Dragon, we are going to examine the move 6.Bc4 followed by 0-0.} 6. Bc4 Bg7 ({Black shoud avoid the move} 6... Nc6 {because of} 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. e5 {Diagram [#]  It's difficult to say that Black is in trouble here but there are is no point in studying additional information.}) 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 ({Sometimes, White gives preference to} 8. h3 {which leads to transposition to the main line after} Nc6 9. Re1 {Nevertheless, Black could have played 8...a6 with the idea "b7-b5" followed by Bb7 and Nbd7. In this case, Black's position is very flexible.}) 8... Nc6 (8... a6 {is possible here. Nevertheless, Black should take into consderation the fact that in the fight for the center, the move 8.Re1 is much more useful than 8.h3. Here is a fresh example:} 9. Bg5 Qc7 ({Black often plays} 9... b5 {but after} 10. Bb3 Bb7 11. a4 b4 12. Nd5 {Diagram [#] White's initiative shouldn't be underestimated. I bring to you attention two victories of the English grandmaster Emms:} Nbd7 13. Nxb4 Qb6 14. c3 Bxe4 (14... e5 15. a5 Qc7 16. Bxf6 Nxf6 17. Ndc2 Bxe4 18. Ne3 {Diagram [#]  Black's weakness on "a6" has decided the outcome of the game, Emms - Trent, 2002} Qc5 19. Ng4 Nxg4 20. Qxg4 Bb7 21. Red1 Ra7 22. Bd5 Bc8 23. Qf3 Qc7 24. Qe3 Kh8 25. Qb6 f5 26. Bf3 e4 27. Qxc7 Rxc7 28. Be2 Be5 29. Bxa6) 15. a5 Qc5 16. Qd2 Rfe8 17. Ba4 Bb7 18. Ndc6 e6 19. Be3 Ne4 20. Qc2 Qf5 21. Nd4 Bxd4 22. Bxd4 e5 23. Be3 Rec8 24. f3 Nec5 25. Qxf5 gxf5 26. Bxd7 Nxd7 27. Rad1 {White has a tremendous pressure, Emms - Mestel, 1997.}) 10. Bb3 e6 {A suspicious idea. Generally, we shoud avoid the combination "g7-g6" and "e7-e6".} 11. Qd2 Nc6 12. Nf3 b5 13. Rad1 Rd8 14. Qf4 {In addition to the weak pawn on "d6", White has managed to create an annoying pin along the "h2-b8" diagonal.} Qe7 15. Bd5 $1 Bb7 16. Bxc6 $1 Bxc6 17. e5 $1 dxe5 18. Nxe5 Bb7 19. Rxd8+ Qxd8 20. Rd1 Qe7 21. Rd7 $1 Nxd7 22. Bxe7 Bxe5 23. Qd2 {White has managed to convert his material advantage in the game Solodovnichenko - Hauge, Oslo, 2014.}) 9. h3 ({The alternative} 9. Nb3 {Diagram [#] illustrates one of the subtleties of White's move order. White is ready to play the standart Bf1 while the central break "d6-d5" is impossible. Maybe, Black should play} a5 $5 ({If} 9... a6 {then} 10. Bf1) 10. a4 $140 Be6 {In the game Zagratsky - Afek, White followed with} 11. Bxe6 fxe6 12. Nb5 {and here, insted of the anti-positional} e5 $6 {which takes the "e5" square from the knight and at the same time kills the bishop on "g7"} ({Black should have played} 12... Qc8 {overprotecting the "e6" pawn which controls the key "d5" square. Later, Black can go for a maneuver like Nh5-f4. The move} 13. N3d4 {is well met by} Nxd4 14. Nxd4 Ng4 $1 {With favourable for Black complications.})) ({The straightforward} 9. Bb3 {doesn't pose problems for Black. Good option is} Na5 {[%cal Gb7b6,Gc8b7] followed by b7-b6 and Bb7.}) 9... Nxd4 ({Like in the most of the cases in Dragon variation, Black tries to exchange a pair of knights. In the game Kveynis - Migo, 2014, he proceeded with normal developing moves but didn't manage to go out of the opening after:} 9... a6 10. Bb3 (10. Bf1 $5) 10... Bd7 (10... Na5 $142) 11. Bg5 Rc8 12. Nxc6 Bxc6 13. Qd2 Re8 14. Rad1 b5 15. Nd5 Nd7 16. Nxe7+ $1 Rxe7 17. Qxd6 Bf8 18. e5 $3 {A quite and beautiful continuation of the attack.} Re6 19. Qxe6 fxe6 20. Bxe6+ Kg7 21. Bxd8 Rxd8 22. Bxd7 Rxd7 23. Rxd7+ Bxd7 24. e6 {1-0}) 10. Qxd4 Qc7 11. Bb3 Be6 {Diagram [#]  Again, the bishop goes to it's normal position. As shows the game Grozpeter - Kan, 1999, this move is justified from a tactical point of view. The game followed with} 12. Bg5 h6 13. Bh4 g5 $1 14. Bg3 Nh5 15. Qd3 Nxg3 16. Qxg3 Rac8 {Diagram [#]  Black has very comfortable position. "d5" square is under control and Black's dark-squared bishop has no opponent along the long diagonal. With this nice position, we finish our series on Dragon. I wish you a lot of success in your own games!} 1-0


