1. c4 g6 2. g3 Bg7 3. Bg2 c5 4. Nc3 Nc6 5. Nf3 e6 6. h4 {David Cummings: 'One of White's many attempts to try and gain an edge against the 5...e6 Fischer system'} d5 {David Cummings: '!?' David Cummings: 'A typical move in the Fischer system, but a bold one to play before completing development. Wei Yi had played the same move in 2015, so presumably Adams was prepared for this. Instead'} (6... h6 {is another natural reply that leads to lines we have covered in the Archives:} 7. a3 (7. d3 Nge7 8. Bd2 b6 9. a3 (9. h5 g5 10. Nxg5 $6 {is the speculative piece sac which worked as a one game weapon in Radjabov-Ivanchuk}) 9... Bb7 10. O-O O-O 11. Rb1 d5 12. Qc1 Kh7 13. b4 {was Ipatov-Cmilyte}) 7... d5 8. b4 dxc4 9. O-O Nge7 10. bxc5 Qa5 11. Bb2 O-O 12. Qc2 e5 13. Ne4 {was Milov-Sermek}) 7. h5 Nge7 8. d3 {David Cummings: 'White has also played:'} (8. Qa4 Bd7 9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. Qc4 Nxc3 $6 {Hillarp Persson, T (2564) -Wiedenkeller, M (2479) Borlange 2014 1-0 (28), and here} (10... Na5 {is better, and Black should be fine}) 11. dxc3 {would give White an advantage}) (8. cxd5 exd5 9. d3 h6 10. hxg6 fxg6 11. Bd2 g5 12. Qa4 Bd7 13. O-O Nd4 14. Qd1 Be6 15. Rc1 O-O 16. a3 Qd7 17. b4 {was a quick draw in Ribli, Z (2610)-Sosonko, G (2545) Amsterdam 1980 1/2-1/2 (17)}) (8. h6 $5 {has not been tested, but may be White's best try. It keeps more tension in the position since after} Bf6 9. d3 {Black cannot simplify as in the main game with} dxc4 $6 {since} 10. Ne4 $1 Nf5 11. dxc4 {puts Black in a tough spot, for example} Qxd1+ {or} (11... O-O 12. Qxd8 Bxd8 13. Nxc5 {winning a pawn}) 12. Kxd1 Be7 13. Bg5 {penetrating on the dark squares}) 8... dxc4 9. dxc4 Qxd1+ 10. Nxd1 b6 11. h6 Bf6 12. Bg5 Bxg5 13. Nxg5 Bb7 {David Cummings: 'The first new move, varying from Wei Yi's earlier game, which continued'} (13... O-O 14. Nc3 f6 15. Nge4 Ba6 16. b3 Rad8 17. f4 Rd7 18. Kf2 Kf7 19. g4 Rfd8 {Zeng, C (2541)-Wei, Y (2706) China 2015 1/2-1/2 (33), and here} 20. g5 $1 {would give White a significant edge, for example} f5 21. Nf6 Rd4 22. Kg3 e5 23. Ncd5 Bb7 24. e3 Rd2 25. Rad1 {when Black's h7-pawn is terminally weak}) 14. Ne3 $1 {White has created a very unpleasant concrete threat - Ne3-g4-f6.} Nf5 {David Cummings: 'According to the official site, Wei Yi thought for almost an hour on this move!'} ({Black can also hold this position with the move} 14... Rd8 $5 15. Ng4 Nf5 16. Rc1 {(The attractive tactical strike} (16. Nxf7 Kxf7 17. Bxc6 Bxc6 18. Ne5+ Kf6 19. Nxc6 Rd7 20. e4 Ne7 21. e5+ Kf5 22. Nxe7+ Rxe7 {, would have led to a drawish endgame. The activity of Black's king compensates fully the pawn lost by him.}) 16... Nd6 17. Nf6+ Ke7 18. Ngxh7 Ne8 {This resource enables Black to regain quickly his pawn.} 19. Nxe8 Rxh7 20. Nc7 Rdh8 21. Nb5 a6 22. Nc3 Kd7 $1 {White cannot save his h6-pawn, so Black is not in a hurry to capture it and sends his king to protect the b6-pawn.} 23. Kd2 Kc7 24. b3 {, draw, Korogodski - Postupa, Email 2015.}) 15. Nxf5 $6 {After this exchange, it is White who is fighting for equality. David Cummings: 'This cedes some key squares to Black's control, and in the long term exposes White's advanced h-pawn to attack from the g6-square'} ({He had to play instead} 15. Ng4 Ke7 16. O-O-O (16. Nxf7 Kxf7 17. Bxc6 Bxc6 18. Ne5+ Kf6 19. Nxc6 Rhc8 $36 {Black regains his pawn and can hope to obtain an advantage thanks to the great activity of his king.}) 16... Raf8 17. Rd2 f6 18. Rhd1 {(White cannot break his opponent's position after} (18. Ne4 Ncd4 19. e3 Bxe4 20. Bxe4 Nd6 21. Bg2 N4f5) 18... Rd8 19. Rxd8 Nxd8 20. Bxb7 fxg5 21. Bg2 Nf7 22. Rh1 Rd8 {The weakness on h6 has been reliably protected.}) (15. O-O-O {is better, although Black is OK as long as he plays} Nfd4 {to keep the d-file closed}) 15... gxf5 16. O-O-O Rb8 $1 {David Cummings: 'Guarding the b7-bishop before activating the c6-knight'} 17. Rd2 ({White would not equalise with} 17. Bxc6+ $5 Bxc6 18. Nf3 Ke7 $15 {The main plus of Black's position is his more active king and it is headed to the h6-square in order to capture the weak enemy pawn there.}) 17... Ne5 18. Bxb7 Rxb7 19. b3 Ke7 {David Cummings: 'Any slight initiative that Adams had has gone and now it is White that needs to be careful'} 20. Rh4 Rd7 21. f4 $2 {David Cummings: '?!' David Cummings: 'Creating more weaknesses'} ({White would have had more chances of a successful defence after} 21. Rxd7+ Nxd7 22. Nh3 $15) (21. Nh3 Rxd2 22. Kxd2 Rd8+ 23. Kc2 {is preferable}) 21... Rxd2 22. Kxd2 Ng4 $2 {David Cummings: '?!'} ({Black was winning after} 22... Rd8+ 23. Kc2 (23. Ke1 Ng4 {gives Black a tangible advantage, since here the freeing move} 24. e4 {is not an option due to} f6 25. Nf3 Rd3 {and Black breaks through}) 23... Ng4 {, the pawn on h7 is untouchable due to f7-f6.}) 23. e4 {David Cummings: 'Relieving some of the pressure, though Black is still somewhat better'} f6 $6 ({Black's king had to go to the h6-pawn along another route -} 23... Kf6 24. exf5 exf5 25. Rh1 Kg6 26. Re1 Nf6 27. Nf3 {(The seemingly active line:} (27. Re7 Rd8+ 28. Kc2 Rd7 $17 {, would have enabled Black to protect all his weaknesses and to have real chances of winning the game.}) 27... Rd8+ 28. Kc1 Kxh6 $15 {Black's extra pawn is weak, but White's g3-pawn is also weak and after Black captures it, he will have a very serious trump - his outside passed h-pawn.}) 24. Nf3 $2 ({White could have made a draw with the not so obvious line:} 24. exf5 exf5 25. Ne4 $1 Rd8+ 26. Ke2 Kf7 27. Nc3 Kg6 28. Rh1 Nxh6 29. Nd5 {Black cannot capture the enemy pawn on g3 and White's powerful knight on d5 guarantees his survival in this position.}) 24... Kf7 ({It is preferable for Black to play here} 24... Nf2 25. exf5 Ne4+ 26. Kc2 Rg8 27. g4 exf5 28. gxf5 Nd6 $17 {White's king is too far from the fighting operations on the kingside.}) 25. Ke2 Rg8 ({Before the opening of the e-file, it would very strong for Black to choose} 25... Re8 $1 26. Nd2 Kg6 $17) 26. Nd2 Kg6 27. exf5+ exf5 28. Nf1 Re8+ 29. Kd2 Re4 30. Nh2 $2 {White had to try to bring his rook into the action here with the move - 30.Rh1 (=+)} Nxh6 $2 ({Following} 30... Ne3 31. Rh3 Kf7 {, White would be incapable of activating his stalemated kingside without material losses.}) 31. Nf3 {David Cummings: 'White's h6-pawn has dropped off, but he is now able to centralize his pieces and keep Black's advantages within bounds'} Nf7 32. Rh1 Nd6 33. Nh4+ Kg7 34. Rf1 $6 ({It was useful for White to fix his opponent's queenside pawns with} 34. a4 a5 35. Rh2 $15) 34... Kh6 35. Rh1 Kg7 36. Rf1 Re6 37. Kd3 Re8 38. Rh1 Kf7 39. Ng2 Kg6 40. Rh2 Re6 $6 ({Black could have improved his position with the line:} 40... h5 41. Nh4+ Kf7 42. Nf3 Rh8 $17) 41. Nh4+ {David Cummings: 'Black's weak f5-pawn makes it hard for him to improve his position'} Kg7 42. Ng2 Re8 43. Ne3 Kg6 44. Ke2 Re4 $6 ({That was the right time for Black to open a second front with} 44... b5 45. cxb5 Nxb5 $15) 45. Rh1 Rd4 46. Nc2 Re4+ 47. Kf3 Re6 48. Ne3 Re4 {David Cummings: 'Black has made no progress and he soon decides to call it a day'} 49. Nc2 Re6 50. Rd1 Ne4 51. Ne3 Rd6 52. Nd5 ({It was a simple draw after} 52. g4 Rxd1 53. gxf5+ Kf7 54. Nxd1 Nd6 55. Ne3 {Meanwhile, even here Black decided not to prolong the fight, draw.}) 1/2-1/2


