1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2 Nc6 9. O-O-O d5 {This central strike is widely considered to be Black's main response to 9.0-0-0, preempting White's kingside pawn storm. The drawback of this move is that White has a pleasant choice of lines here, and can either sharpen the struggle or play for a nagging positional edge. Moreover, Black won't always be able to attain thematic Dragon counterplay, and must be ready to patiently defend a slightly worse position in some lines, which is not to everyone's taste-especially not a Dragon player! After some review, we're big fans of:} 10. Qe1 $5 e5 {Black's most natural move, forcing White to trade on c6 and release the tension in the center.} ({The point of this move is to maintain the tension in the center-} 10... dxe4 {loses instantly to} 11. Nxc6 {, while}) (10... Nxd4 11. Bxd4 {leaves Black under a lot of pressure. Instead, Black has two serious options, the flexible 10...e6 and the forcing 10...e5, the latter of which is currently considered to be the main line. White's other alternatives include 10.Kb1, 10.Nxc6, and 10.exd5, all of which are serious attempts to fight for an advantage.}) ({But let's first cover the flexible} 10... e6 {:Black has strengthened his center and would like to play either Qc7 or Qe7 next, followed by Rd8. We consider both 11.g4?! and the much better 11.h4.} 11. g4 $6 {would be a good move if not for} ({White's most challenging response is the direct} 11. h4 {: a) Now,} Qe7 {is unsatisfactory for Black in view of} ({b) In case of} 11... Re8 {White has a strong response in} 12. Bb5 $1 $146 (12. h5 Nxd4 13. Bxd4 e5 $132) 12... Bd7 13. Bxc6 Bxc6 (13... bxc6 $2 14. e5) 14. h5 $1 {. White is very close to a decisive attack, for instance} e5 (14... Nxh5 15. g4 Nf6 16. Bg5) 15. Nxc6 bxc6 16. exd5 Nxd5 17. hxg6 hxg6 18. Ne4 {. The open h-file and threat of c2-c4 means White is close to the full point.}) ({c) Most common is} 11... Qc7 {and now} 12. Kb1 $1 {, which has only been played once, is astoundingly strong. c1) Firstly,} (12. h5 Nxh5 13. g4 Nxd4 14. Bxd4 Bxd4 15. Rxd4 Ng3 16. Rh3 Qe5 {White is still planning on playing h4-h5, but now the king isn't susceptible to potential checks-this will be an important detail in certain lines. This position is quite complex and play will be concrete in nature, but it appears that Black has no clear way to equalize. Let's take a look at four lines, 12...dxe4, 12...a6, 12...Nxd4, and 12...h5:}) 12... dxe4 {should be met with} ({c2) Next,} 12... a6 {seems like a useful move, but now} 13. h5 $1 {is even more dangerous with the king on b1.} Nxh5 14. exd5 $1 {c21) After} exd5 ({c22) More critical is} 14... Nxd4 15. Bxd4 Bxd4 16. Rxd4 Ng3 17. Ne4 $1 {With the king still on c1 Black could refute this idea with Qf4+, but here White is nearly winning, for instance} Nxh1 (17... Nxe4 18. Qh4 h5 19. fxe4 $16) 18. d6 Qd8 19. d7 $1 $16 {. After capturing the bishop White will eventually play Qh4, winning the knight on h1 and continuing the attack.}) 15. Nxd5 Qe5 16. Bc4 $1 {Black is in danger of losing a lot of material. c211) Now} Be6 {is strongly answered by} ({c212) Also bad is} 16... Re8 17. Qf2 {with the threat of either g2-g4 or Rhe1, depending on what Black plays.} Na5 {runs into the beautiful shot:} 18. Rxh5 $1 Qxh5 19. g4 Qh3 20. Bf1 Qh1 21. Nc7 {. After taking on a8 White can trap Black's queen with Re1 and Bg2.}) ({c213) The only way to stay alive is} 16... Nxd4 17. Bxd4 Qxe1 18. Rhxe1 Bxd4 19. Rxd4 b5 20. Bb3 $16 {. Black has managed not to lose any material but this endgame is fantastic for White, whose pieces could not be better placed.}) 17. f4 $1 Nxf4 18. Qh4 Nh5 19. Bf4 Qe4 20. Rhe1 {winning Black's queen.}) ({c3) Exchanging with} 12... Nxd4 13. Bxd4 dxe4 14. Nxe4 {allows Black to avoid immediate capitulation:But White still has a clear pull: c31) After} e5 ({c32) Or} 14... Nxe4 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. fxe4 e5 17. h5 h6 18. hxg6 fxg6 19. Rd3 $36 {.}) 15. Bc5 Rd8 16. Rxd8+ Qxd8 17. Bc4 $14 {it's doubtful that Black will be able to equalize anytime soon.}) ({c4) Lastly, in case Black panics and plays} 12... h5 {White can launch the thematic breakthrough} 13. g4 $5 (13. Ndb5 Qb8 14. exd5 Nxd5 15. Bf2 $14) 13... hxg4 14. h5 gxh5 (14... Nxh5 $6 15. fxg4 Ng3 16. Rh3 Nxf1 17. Qh4) 15. Be2 $1 $36 {:Obviously this position deserves further analysis, but it's clear that the kingside is about to open up, much to Black's dismay. It will take extreme precision for Black to avoid losing within the next several moves. Now back to our main game, after Black's :}) 13. Ndb5 $1 {And now: c11)} Qa5 ({c12) After} 13... Qb8 14. Bc5 {Black is forced to give up the exchange and will remain in a passive position.}) ({c13) If} 13... Qe7 {then} 14. Bf4 $1 {threatening Bd6. This time, Black should probably give up the exchange, since} e5 15. Bg5 Be6 16. Nxe4 Rfd8 17. Be2 $16 {leaves White in full control of the position.}) 14. h5 $1 {‚ looks very dangerous for Black.}) 12. h5 $1 dxe4 (12... Nxh5 13. g4 Nxd4 14. Bxd4 Bxd4 15. Rxd4 $16) 13. hxg6 fxg6 14. Nxc6 bxc6 15. Nxe4 $146 Nxe4 16. fxe4 $14 {. Next is c2-c4 and Bc4-White is clearly better.}) 11... e5 $1 {leading to an improved version for Black of the line 10...e5. Specifically, after} 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. exd5 cxd5 14. Bg5 Bb7 $1 15. Bc4 d4 $17 {as played in Dvoirys-Tolnai, Balatonbereny 1993, White would like to continue} 16. Qxe5 {, but the problem is that after} Nxg4 17. Qf4 Qa5 $17 {,} 18. fxg4 {hangs the rook on h1, and otherwise this line just doesn't work for White.}) 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. exd5 Nxd5 ({Recapturing with the knight is more popular and more dynamic than} 12... cxd5 {, where Black will struggle to maintain the center. Black's center may look quite menacing, but fortunately for White we have a series of precise moves that lead to an advantage, starting with} 13. Bg5 $1 {Black must now choose between 13... b7?! discussed here, and 13... e6 analyzed on . We answer} Bb7 $6 {with} ({More solid is} 13... Be6 14. Bc4 $1 {And now: a) In case of} Qb6 ({b) A theoretical is reached after} 14... Qc7 15. Bxf6 dxc4 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 {With the exchange of several pieces one might think that Black's position is relatively safe, but this is not the case after} 17. h4 $5 {b1) Let's examine some of Black's most natural options, starting with} (17. Nd5 Bxd5 18. Rxd5 Rfe8 19. Qc3 Kg8 20. Qa5 $1 $14) 17... Qa5 ({b2) GM Yangyi Yu demonstrated his class with a nice victory after} 17... Rab8 18. Ne4 (18. h5) 18... f6 19. g4 $1 {Now White can choose between attacking Black's structure with h4-h5-h6 or g4-g5.} Rb5 (19... Rfd8 20. Qc3 $1 $16) 20. h5 g5 21. h6+ Kg8 22. Rd6 Rb6 23. Qa5 $1 {threatening Rxe6, and Black's position soon collapsed, Y.Yu-Pham, Kazan 2013.}) ({b3) Finally, after} 17... h5 {the direct} 18. g4 $1 $146 {is very strong: And if} hxg4 {then} 19. h5 {. While this is a risky way for White to play, it is even riskier for Black, since one misstep could mean getting checkmated on the spot! For instance} gxf3 $6 {seems to lose in view of} 20. Qh4 $1 Qb6 21. Qg5 $1 {preventing Qe3+ and threatening hxg6, winning. Now} Bf5 {loses quite spectacularly:} 22. Nd5 f6 23. Qg3 Qe6 24. hxg6 Bxg6 25. Ne7 $1 {Simply opening up the d-file. After} Qxe7 26. Rhg1 Qf7 27. Rd7 {it's all over. Now we return to our main game, after :}) 18. h5 Rab8 {: Best is} 19. Rd6 $1 $146 {cutting off Black's queen-now Qe3 can't be met with Qb6.} (19. hxg6 hxg6 20. Qe3 Rh8 21. Rxh8 Rxh8 22. g4 $14 {Black is already in serious trouble, for after}) 19... Rfd8 20. Rxd8 Rxd8 21. Qh4 {White has threats of hxg6, as well as h5-h6+ followed by Qf6, with a decisive attack.}) 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 {Black doesn't get quite enough compensation after} 16. Bxd5 (16. Nxd5 Bxd5 17. Rxd5 e4 18. Rb5 Qc7 19. Qxe4 Rae8 20. Qd3 $14) 16... Rab8 17. Bb3 a5 18. Na4 $1 Qb5 19. Kb1 Rfc8 20. Rd6 $16 {. White can follow up with either Qe3 or Nc3-e4, and Black's counterplay should slowly fade out.}) 14. Bc4 $1 {Another precise move, otherwise Black would be able to consolidate his center. And now: a) The tactics work out for White after} d4 ({b) Instead, after} 14... Qc7 {White continues} 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 (15... dxc4 16. Nb5 $1 Qc5 17. Bxg7 Kxg7 18. Nd6 $16) 16. Bxd5 $16 {. It's difficult to believe Black has enough compensation for the lost pawn, Boudre-Rafiee, Bad Zwesten 2002.}) 15. Qxe5 $1 Ng4 16. Qf4 $1 {Analyzing the following lines over a physical chess board would not only be helpful, but entertaining as well!} Qa5 (16... Qb6 17. Na4 Qc6 18. Rxd4 $1) 17. fxg4 Rac8 (17... dxc3 18. Rd7 $1 cxb2+ 19. Kb1) 18. Bb3 dxc3 19. Be7 $1 cxb2+ 20. Kb1 {. Black must give up the exchange and afterwards will still be tied down to defending the f7 pawn.}) 13. Bc4 {The structure that has arisen is quite interesting. By capturing with the knight Black strives for active piece play in the center, while also looking to play f7-f5 and e5-e4 if possible. Meanwhile, White would like to secure a firm grip over the center and slowly exploit Black's weaknesses on the queenside. The moves Kb1, Ne4, and Bc5 are definitely part of White's plan. At some point advancing on the kingside would also be logical, not necessarily to launch a mating attack but rather to gain space and restrict Black's counterplay.} Be6 {Black defends the knight and puts the bishop on its most natural square.} 14. Kb1 $1 ({For the majority of this line's existence, the move} 14. Ne4 {has been played almost exclusively, aiming to setup a positional bind with Bc5, h2-h4, and g2-g4. While that remains a decent attempt of fighting for an opening advantage, in a few games in 2013 White opted to first secure the location of his king before carrying out this standard plan. This fresh approach to the position seems quite promising, and the king move is our wholehearted recommendation. But first, to provide a brief theoretical overview of the older move, we look at the position after} Qc7 15. Bc5 Rfd8 {Now White has a choice: Caruana tried} 16. Qh4 {and was able to quickly outplay his opponent:} ({White has also had success with} 16. h4 h6 17. g4 {:And now:} f5 $6 {This is generally too loose if White already has g2-g4 in.} (17... Nf4 18. Bxe6 Nxe6 $6 (18... Rxd1+ 19. Qxd1 Nxe6 20. Be3 $14) 19. Bd6 Qb6 20. g5 Nd4 $6 (20... h5 21. Nf6+ Bxf6 22. gxf6 $14) 21. h5 $1 {‚ and White soon had a decisive attack in Durik-Dobias, Trnava 1994.}) 18. gxf5 gxf5 19. Ng3 Qf7 20. Qa5 $1 Kh7 21. Bb3 Bf6 22. Qa6 Qc7 23. Nxf5 $1 Bxf5 24. Bxd5 cxd5 25. Qxf6 $16 {, Matsuura-Delgado Ramos, Havana 2008.}) 16... Qa5 $6 (16... h6 17. g4 Nf4) 17. Ba3 $1 h6 18. Nc5 Bf5 19. Bb3 g5 20. Qf2 Qb6 21. g4 Bg6 22. Rd2 Nc7 $6 23. Ne4 $1 Qxf2 24. Rxf2 $14 {. White's better structure and more active pieces was enough to press for a win, Caruana-Mamedov, Plovdiv 2012.}) 14... Rb8 {The main upside of 14.Kb1 is that it delays Black from achieving his optimal setup with Qc7 and Rfd8. Instead, Black has to make a different, less useful move and wait for White to play Ne4.} ({Black simply doesn't get enough for the pawn after} 14... Qc7 $6 15. Nxd5 cxd5 16. Bxd5 Rab8 17. b3 $16 {.}) ({Exchanging with} 14... Nxc3+ 15. Qxc3 {allows White to play for only two results-Black can only be worse with the weakened queenside.} Qe7 16. Bb3 $14 {, Pavlidis-Goumas, Porto Rio 2014.} (16. h4 $146 {was also a thought.})) ({Another game saw} 14... Re8 15. Ne4 a5 {a) White obtained a clear advantage after} (15... Qc7 16. Bc5 Nf4 17. Bxe6 Nxe6 18. Bd6 Qb6 19. g4 $14 {And now:}) 16. h4 ({b) White should usually start with} 16. g4 $1 {to discourage f7-f5, for instance after} Qc7 17. Bc5 f5 $6 18. gxf5 gxf5 19. Ng5 {White is nearly winning, the critical variation being} e4 20. fxe4 Nc3+ 21. Qxc3 $1 Bxc3 22. Nxe6 {, and Black is either losing material or just getting mated by White's pieces.}) 16... h6 $6 (16... Qc7 17. Bc5 f5 18. Ng5 e4) 17. Qd2 $1 Kh7 18. h5 $16 {, Popilsky-Polzin, Paleochora 2013.}) 15. Ne4 {Black was threatening e5-e4, so White cannot delay this move any longer.} Qc7 (15... f5 $5 {would be an interesting attempt at sharpening the struggle, although White seems to get the better of it after} 16. Ng5 Bc8 17. h4 h6 18. Ne4 $1 $14 {-a typical motif when there's a pin along the d-file.}) 16. Bc5 Rfd8 17. g4 {In this game the young Chinese GM Wei Yi is able to squeeze his opponent's position and nurse a small advantage. His last move controls the important f7-f5 advance, which is Black's main source of counterplay.} a5 (17... Nf4 $2 {allows} 18. Bxe6 Nxe6 19. Bd6 $16 {, winning the exchange.}) ({An earlier game of Wei Yi continued} 17... h6 18. h4 (18. Bb3 $14) 18... f5 19. gxf5 gxf5 20. Ng3 Qf7 21. Bb3 Rd7 22. Qa5 Rbd8 23. Rd3 Nf4 $6 {A bad misjudgment.} (23... Kh7 24. Rg1 Nf4 25. Rxd7 Rxd7) 24. Qxd8+ Rxd8 25. Rxd8+ Kh7 26. Rhd1 Bd5 27. Ra8 {. After Rxa7 and Rg1, White should be completely winning, Y.Wei-Gagare, Chongqing 2013.}) 18. h4 h6 19. g5 {A common advance, fixing the f6 square.} (19. h5 $6 {would be an error as after} f5 20. gxf5 gxf5 {, White cannot play Ng5 and will soon lose control over the position, since Black's next move will be e5-e4.}) ({However} 19. Bb3 $1 {might have been more testing, since} f5 20. gxf5 gxf5 21. Nc3 $1 Nxc3+ (21... Kh7 22. Na4 Nf4 23. Qf2 $14) 22. Qxc3 Bxb3 23. axb3 $14 {is certainly more pleasant for White, who has the safer king and a healthier structure.}) 19... h5 20. a4 Qb7 $6 ({Black would have had better chances to equalize with} 20... Bf8 $1 {trading off the problem dark-squared bishop, though after} 21. Qf2 {White would still retain a small edge.}) 21. b3 {It's clear that White is gearing up for a long, positional struggle.} Ra8 ({Now} 21... Bf8 $2 {is just a blunder due to} 22. Bxd5 cxd5 23. Nf6+ Kg7 24. Qxe5 {:}) 22. Kc1 Qc7 23. Qf2 Rd7 24. Rd2 Nf4 {Not exactly necessary, but it would be difficult for any player to just sit on the position.} 25. Bd6 Qd8 26. Bxe6 Nxe6 27. Rhd1 Nd4 28. Ba3 Rd5 29. f4 ({The immediate} 29. Nc3 $1 {was stronger, forcing the rook to an undefended square. After} Rd7 30. f4 $1 Qe8 (30... exf4 $2 31. Bc5) 31. Ne4 Rad8 32. Re1 $16 {, Black is under a lot of pressure.}) 29... exf4 30. Bb2 Ne6 31. Bf6 {Again missing the best way to put pressure on Black.} ({Better was} 31. Rxd5 cxd5 32. Nf6+ Bxf6 33. Bxf6 Qd6 34. Qf3 $14 {. After winning the d5 pawn, White will have a clear advantage thanks to his powerful bishop.}) 31... Qd7 32. Bxg7 Kxg7 33. Qf3 {The point of White's previous play, threatening Qc3+ and Nf6.} Qc7 {The only move, preparing to meet Qc3+ with Qe5.} 34. Rxd5 cxd5 35. Rxd5 Rd8 $1 {Correctly trading off White's more active rook.} 36. Rxd8 Qxd8 37. Qc3+ Kg8 {White has definitely let his advantage slip, and now Black is well within the drawing zone.} 38. Qe5 f3 39. Qc3 Nd4 40. Kb2 Nf5 $2 {Tragically, Black makes a losing blunder on the 40th move.} ({After} 40... Kg7 {White would find it difficult to make progress.}) 41. Qxf3 Nxh4 42. Qf6 $1 {Without the f3 pawn, any knight endgame is simply lost for Black.} Qxf6+ ({White answers} 42... Qc7 {with} 43. Qc3 $1 {, forcing a trade of queens due to the threat of Nf6+. After} Qxc3+ 44. Kxc3 Kf8 45. Kc4 {, White is winning, with his more active king.}) 43. gxf6 Nf3 44. b4 $1 axb4 45. Kb3 (45. a5 {was also good enough.}) 45... h4 46. a5 h3 47. a6 Nd4+ 48. Kxb4 h2 49. Nf2 {Black's knight can deal with the a-pawn, but once the c-pawn joins the action, it will all be over. Meanwhile, Black's king is too far away to support the h-pawn. Realizing the hopelessness of the situation, Black resigned.} 1-0


