1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Qb3 dxc4 6. Qxc4 O-O 7. e4 Be6 {A popular move in the last few years. As White has been unsuccessful with d4-d5, to challenge Black's idea, he has to move his queen again. So Black arguably gains time for development.} 8. Qd3 ({Instead} 8. Qb5 Bd7 9. Qb3 c5 10. d5 Qb6 ({best is the dynamic option:} 10... b5 $1 11. e5 Ng4 12. Bf4 Qb6 13. Qc2 Bf5 $11 {as in Checa, N-Mikhalevski, V Rockville 2015}) 11. Bc4 Bg4 12. Be3 Nbd7 13. Nd2 {occurred in Svidler, P-Wei Yi, Baku 2015, when White was somewhat better. Maybe the improvement on move ten (see the bracket) indicated to Wei Yi that .. .b5 is the right approach for Black in this line.}) 8... c5 9. d5 {There are differences with this advance compared to on the previous move. Now, with Black's c-pawn on c5, he doesn't have the ...c6 counter available to nibble at the centre.} Bg4 ({Instead going back with} 9... Bc8 {has been the most common here. Then} 10. Be2 e6 11. Bg5 h6 12. Be3 exd5 13. exd5 Na6 (13... Bf5 $1) 14. Rd1 Ng4 {was seen in Potkin, V-Nepomniachtchi, I Yaroslavl rapid 2014. This looks very much like a type of Prins Variation  (where Black plays with 7...Na6 and typically follows-up with ...c5).}) 10. Bg5 {This seems to be new.} ({Instead} 10. Be3 {'developing with a threat' looks normal:} Nbd7 11. Nd2 e6 12. d6 e5 $1 13. Be2 Be6 $6 ({with less space Black should not be afraid to trade pieces:} 13... Bxe2 $1 14. Qxe2 Qb6 15. Nc4 Qc6) 14. O-O Ne8 15. Rfd1 Rc8 16. Nc4 {Vidit, S-Khusnutdinov, R Al-Ain 2015, and Black was cramped.}) 10... b5 $5 {Time is an important factor in this variation. If White can 'settle things down' and hold onto his central preponderence he can count on a middlegame advantage. So Wei Yi aims to complicate matters with this pawn sacrifice.} ({Although the engines may suggest} 10... Bxf3 11. Qxf3 Nbd7 {to me this still looks more comfortable for White (although the engines give it as only 0.2). However there may be nothing better.}) ({Instead, after the routine} 10... Nbd7 {White removes the knight with} 11. Nd2 {and Black's bishop is in danger.}) 11. Qxb5 Nbd7 12. Bc1 $5 {A remarkable 'anti-development' move in order to hold onto his queenside.} Rb8 13. Qa6 $5 (13. Qd3 {is less greedy.}) 13... Rb6 14. Qxa7 {Wang Yue is really waving the red rag by going for the second pawn.} e6 $1 {Cracking open the centre just has to be good.} 15. d6 $5 Bxf3 16. gxf3 Ne8 {Wei Yi regains one pawn and has easier piece play, so it seems that he has enough compensation.} 17. f4 Nxd6 18. e5 Rb7 $6 ({There is no need to 'aid and abet' White to get his queen back to civilization. Instead} 18... Nf5 $1 {with ...Nd4 should yield excellent play. The engines even prefer Black.}) 19. Qa6 Rb6 20. Qd3 c4 21. Qd1 Nf5 {Not quite as effective now that the white queen is on d1 and when there is no access to d4.} 22. Bg2 Nh4 23. O-O Nxg2 24. Kxg2 f6 {Opening lines is still in Black's interest.} ({Instead} 24... g5 {undermining the e5-pawn, is another way for Black to get good play.}) 25. exf6 Bxf6 26. Qf3 Qa8 {Trading queens may come as a surprise to many, but exchanging White's best placed piece is certainly a reasonable idea.} ({As an alternative, improving the knight with} 26... Nc5 $5 {would have been the choice of many.}) 27. Rd1 Qxf3+ 28. Kxf3 Rb7 ({Again} 28... Nc5 {comes into consideration, when the following moves give Black somewhat the worst of a draw:} 29. Be3 Rc6 30. Bxc5 Rxc5 31. Ne4 Rf5 32. Nxf6+ R5xf6 33. Rd4 c3 34. bxc3 e5 35. Re4 Rxf4+ 36. Rxf4 Rxf4+ 37. Ke3 Ra4) 29. Ne4 Be7 {White's extra pawn may not look that thrilling, but Black also has weaknesses.} 30. Kg2 Nf6 $2 ({Now I'm sure that} 30... Nc5 {would be a better choice, avoiding the game continuation.}) 31. Ng5 Rb6 32. Re1 {Here e6 is doomed. White now has an undisputed, if not decisive, advantage.} Nd5 33. Nxe6 Rc8 34. a4 Bf6 35. a5 Ra6 36. Ra4 {From Black's point of view, it looks like a Benko gone wrong. Note that the bishop is actually quite happy on c1!} c3 {Activity, or simply frustration?} 37. b4 c2 38. Nc5 Rac6 39. Ne4 {Wang Yue is ready for b4-b5.} Bb2 {Definitely desperate stuff!} 40. Bxb2 Nxf4+ 41. Kf1 Nd3 42. Bc1 Re6 43. b5 Rd8 44. Be3 Nxe1 45. Kxe1 {The queenside pawns constitute a decisive advantage.} ({e.g.} 45. Kxe1 Rd3 46. Bd2 Rc3 47. b6 c1=Q+ 48. Bxc1 Rxc1+ 49. Kd2 Rc8 50. b7 Rd8+ 51. Ke3 Ra6 52. Rc4 Rxa5 53. Rc8) 1-0


