1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nb6 7. Ne2 c5 8. d5 O-O 9. O-O e6 10. Nec3 Na6 11. Na3 ({Previous updates have been mainly concerned with} 11. a4 {(see the archives).}) 11... exd5 12. exd5 Bf5 13. Be3 ({The rather flamboyant} 13. g4 $6 {soon rebounded on White in the following:} Bd7 14. h3 f5 $1 15. d6 fxg4 16. Bxb7 Qh4 17. Ne4 Rae8 {Jobava, B-Bacrot, E Spanish league 2011, and Black was better.}) 13... Qd7 14. Qb3 ({Although} 14. Qd2 {has been played a few times, White has been unable to obtain any advantage with it. Here is a recent example:} Bh3 15. Bh6 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 Bxh6 17. Qxh6 Rae8 18. Qd2 Nb4 19. Rfd1 Re5 {Gemy, J-Huerga Leache, M Barcelona 2014, and Black had the initiative.}) 14... Rfe8 {A sensible developing move, but there is more than one way to obtain an acceptable game:} (14... Bd3 15. Rfd1 c4 16. Qb5 Rfd8 17. d6 Qxd6 18. Bxb6 Qxb6 19. Bxb7 {Luch, M-Zakhartsov, V Leiden 2012, would be about equal following} Qxb5 $5 20. Naxb5 Rab8 21. Bxa6 Rb6) (14... Rac8 15. Nab5 Nb4 16. Bxc5 $5 {(winning a pawn at the cost of the bishop pair)} Rxc5 17. Qxb4 Rc4 18. Qa3 Ra8 19. d6 a6 20. Nc7 Rd8 21. Rad1 Bc2 {Navara, D-Grandelius, N Reykjavik 2013, with enough counterplay.}) 15. Rad1 (15. Rfd1 Rxe3 $5 {(a bit optimistic, but maybe OK)} (15... Rac8 {looks normal}) 16. fxe3 Nb4 17. Ne4 N4xd5 $2 ({Black could justify his exchange 'sac' with} 17... Bxe4 $1 18. Bxe4 Na4 19. Rd2 a5 {with ...b5 and ...c4 in mind}) 18. Nxc5 Qe7 19. Bxd5 Qxc5 20. Bxf7+ Kh8 21. Nc4 {Lenderman, A-Robson, R St.Louis 2014, with a big advantage.}) 15... Rac8 16. d6 Nb4 $5 {The threat of coming into d3 forces White into action.} 17. Bxc5 $1 Nxa2 $1 18. Bxb6 Nxc3 19. bxc3 axb6 ({Alternatively} 19... Rxc3 {seems OK e.g.} 20. Qb4 axb6 21. Nc4 Bd3 22. Nxb6 Qb5 $11) 20. c4 Be4 $6 ({The dynamic} 20... Re2 21. Qxb6 Rb2 {is another, and possibly better, way of handling the position. Then Black's active pieces fully compensate for the pawn minus.}) 21. Qxb6 $6 {Taking the pawn only leads to a balanced game.} ({Instead} 21. Rfe1 $1 Bxg2 22. Rxe8+ Rxe8 23. Kxg2 {is interesting (the d-pawn is a handy trump), and after} Qc6+ 24. Kg1 Bd4 $1 25. Nb5 $1 {I prefer White.}) 21... Rc6 22. Qb4 (22. Qb5 Bxg2 23. Kxg2 Re5 {eventually leads to Black picking off the passed pawn e.g.} 24. Qa4 Bf8 25. Rd3 b6 $1 26. Nb5 Rxd6 $1 27. Rxd6 Bxd6 28. Rd1 Qc6+ $11) 22... Bxg2 23. Kxg2 Bf8 24. Qb5 Re6 {What a pile-up on the d6-pawn!} 25. Nc2 Rexd6 26. Ne3 Rc7 27. Qxd7 Rcxd7 28. Rxd6 Rxd6 29. Rb1 Rd7 $11 {Wang Yue now tries to win, perhaps the match situation dictated this course of action.} 30. Rf1 $6 {I really don't understand this, and suspect that another move was played in the game.} Rd6 ({This position may not have occurred, but nevertheless, the standard way of reducing White's chances is} 30... h5 $1 {when Black has less risk of being cramped.}) 31. Rb1 Rd7 32. Nd5 Kg7 33. g4 $1 h6 34. Rb5 Be7 35. Kf3 Bh4 36. Ke3 {White's pieces are well-placed, but I'm not sure he can really make progress if Black sits tight.} f5 $5 {This avoids being squeezed for space, at the risk of weakening his structure.} 37. gxf5 gxf5 38. f4 Kg6 39. Rb6+ Kg7 40. Kf3 Bd8 41. Rb5 Kg6 42. Ne3 Rd3 $5 {Wei Yi again decides to go active.} ({After the passive} 42... Rf7 {Black looks as if he is close to being in Zugzwang. However I can't see White 'pulling it off' as Black has ...Bh4-d8 to temporize. If White places his king on g3 (stopping ...Bh4) then ...Be7 holds for tactical reasons. If White instead places his king on h3...} 43. Kg2 (43. Kg3 Be7 44. Kh3 Bf8 45. Ng2 Rc7 46. Nh4+ Kh7 47. Rxf5 Be7 48. Rb5 Bxh4 49. Kxh4 Rxc4 {should be drawn}) {or} 43... Bh4 ({even} 43... Bc7 {might be OK:} 44. Rxb7 Bxf4 45. Rxf7 Kxf7 46. Nxf5 Ke6 47. Ng3 Kd6 48. Kf3 Ke5 {is fairly drawish despite White winning a pawn}) 44. Kh3 Bf2 {and the pressure on Black's position is released.}) 43. Ke2 Rd4 44. Kf3 Rd3 45. Rxb7 Ba5 {Having the initiative is handy, but is it worth a pawn?} 46. c5 Rc3 47. Rb5 Bc7 48. h3 Kh5 49. c6 {Wang Yue wants to trade the sickly c-pawn for Black's f-pawn. With all the play then on one wing the knight will be at least equal to the bishop.} Kg6 50. h4 Bd6 51. Ke2 Rxc6 52. Rxf5 Rc2+ 53. Kf3 Rh2 54. Kg4 Re2 55. h5+ Kg7 56. Kf3 Ra2 {The extra pawn is consolidated, so it's now a question of whether he can break Black's defences.} 57. Rd5 Bf8 58. Rd7+ Kf6 59. Rc7 Ra3 60. Rc6+ Kf7 61. Ke4 Ra4+ 62. Nc4 Bg7 63. Kf5 Ra1 64. Nd6+ Kg8 65. Rc8+ Bf8 (65... Kh7 66. Ne8 Bb2 67. Rc7+ Kg8 68. Nf6+ Bxf6 69. Kxf6 Ra6+ 70. Kf5 Ra5+ 71. Kg4 {is probably a draw, but White has some practical winning chances.}) 66. Ne4 Kf7 67. Rc7+ Be7 68. Nc3 $6 (68. Nd6+ $1 Kf8 69. Nc4 {looks stronger with Ne5 to follow. This looks like serious progress and might even be winning.}) 68... Ra5+ 69. Ke4 Ke6 70. Rc6+ Bd6 71. Rb6 Kd7 72. Nd5 Ra4+ 73. Ke3 $2 Bc5+ {Whoops! Fortunately for White this didn't change the result.} 74. Kf3 Ra3+ 75. Kg4 Bxb6 76. Nxb6+ Ke6 77. Nc4 Ra1 78. Ne3 Rg1+ 79. Kf3 Rh1 80. Kg4 Ra1 81. Nf5 1/2-1/2


