1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bg5 Ne4 6. Bf4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 dxc4 8. e3 ({For} 8. Qa4+ {, as in Sokolov, I-Aronian, L Wijk aan Zee 2013, see the archives.}) 8... Be6 {Wei Yi decides to hold onto the c4-pawn for now.} ({The alternative way to attempt to keep the booty involves} 8... b5 {. Here is a recent example:} 9. a4 c6 10. Qb1 Bf5 11. e4 Bd7 12. Bxc4 bxc4 13. Qb7 Na6 14. Qxa6 c5 15. Qxc4 cxd4 16. cxd4 Rc8 17. Qa6 Be6 18. Qb5+ Bd7 19. Qa6 {Andreikin, D-Vachier Lagrave, M Tashkent 2014, with a repetition.}) 9. Qb1 {Although 'hitting' the bishop with Ng5 is typically part of White's plans, there are several ways of implementing the knight leap.} ({If} 9. Ng5 Bd5 10. e4 h6 11. exd5 ({after} 11. Nf3 Bxe4 12. Bxc4 Nd7 13. O-O Nb6 {I don't think that White has full compensation}) 11... hxg5 12. Qa4+ Qd7 13. Qxd7+ Nxd7 14. Bxc7 (14. Bxg5 Nb6 {Bryzgalin, K-Khismatullin, D Ulan Ude 2009, and Black was more than comfortable, as he was soon able to capture on d5, without the loss of the c4-pawn}) 14... Rc8 15. d6 (15. Bg3 f5 $5 {with good play for Black}) 15... exd6 $6 ({instead} 15... Nf6 $1 16. Bxc4 exd6 17. Bb5+ Ke7 18. Ba5 b6 19. Bb4 a5 {favours Black}) 16. Bxd6 Nb6 17. Be2 Kd7 18. Ba3 Nd5 19. Kd2 {Matko, O-Zufic, M Zagreb 2012, with a tense and fairly balanced middlegame in prospect.}) ({Another way is} 9. Rb1 b6 10. Be2 (10. Ng5 Bd5 11. e4 h6 12. exd5 hxg5 13. Qa4+ Kf8 14. Bxg5 Qxd5 15. Be3 Qe4 {(gaining a tempo against the rook, thus demonstrating the downside of 9.Rb1)} 16. Rd1 Bh6 {Plachetka, J-Piesina, G Eger 1984, is promising for Black}) 10... O-O 11. O-O Nc6 ({hitting back at the centre with} 11... Nd7 12. e4 c5 {looks acceptable when} 13. Ng5 cxd4 14. cxd4 Nf6 15. Nxe6 fxe6 16. Bxc4 Nxe4 {is double-edged}) 12. Ng5 Bd7 ({better than} 12... Bd5 $2 13. e4 h6 {Aguettaz, M-Lokander, M Pardubice 2011, and then} 14. exd5 $1 hxg5 15. Bc1 $1 Qxd5 16. Bf3 Qd6 17. Qa4 {enables White to gain material and the advantage}) 13. Bxc4 e5 14. dxe5 Nxe5 $11) 9... b6 10. Ng5 Bd5 11. e4 h6 ({Keeping the bishop with} 11... Bb7 {has also been played. Here's a recent example...} 12. Bxc4 O-O 13. Qb3 e6 14. Bxe6 $5 fxe6 15. Qxe6+ Kh8 16. Nf7+ Rxf7 17. Qxf7 Nd7 18. f3 Ba6 {Lizak, P-Garcia Roman, D Budapest 2013, which wasn't clear.}) 12. Nf3 ({Capturing on d5 is also a serious option:} 12. exd5 hxg5 13. Qb5+ Qd7 14. Qxd7+ Nxd7 15. Bxg5 {(here, compared to the immediate 9. Ng5 variation, Black has the extra move ...b7-b6. This is a negative feature from his point of view, as he is denied access to b6 for the knight, and furthermore his queenside light-squares could become targets)} b5 16. a4 Nb6 17. axb5 O-O-O 18. Kd2 Rhe8 19. Kc2 Rxd5 20. Be3 Kb8 {0.5-0.5 Knezevic, M-Ftacnik, L Trencianske Teplice 1985. Although the draw is reasonable, White's bishop pair offers him the slightly better options.}) 12... Be6 13. Be5 f6 ({Solid, but perhaps less ambitious, is} 13... O-O 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. d5 Bc8 16. Bxc4 c6 17. O-O Bb7 18. Bb3 cxd5 19. exd5 Nd7 ({more to the point is} 19... e6 $5 20. dxe6 Bxf3 21. gxf3 fxe6 $11) 20. c4 Nc5 {Frog, I-Baikov, V Moscow 1995, when Black is solid but White has a small pull due to his centre.}) 14. Bg3 ({Or perhaps} 14. d5 {e.g.} Bf7 15. Bg3 O-O (15... f5 $1 16. Be5 Bxe5 17. Nxe5 O-O 18. Bxc4 Qd6 {transposes to the main game}) 16. Bxc4 c5 17. O-O Nc6 18. Qd3 Na5 {Maris, Iv-Leenhouts, K Vlissingen 2014, and now White keeps a central bind by retaining his bishop with} 19. Ba6 $1) 14... O-O 15. d5 f5 $1 16. Be5 ({Instead after} 16. dxe6 $2 {Black has} Bxc3+ {when White is gummed-up and soon hopelessly down on material e.g.} 17. Ke2 f4 18. Bh4 g5 19. e5 Qd3+ 20. Qxd3 cxd3+ 21. Kxd3 Bxa1) 16... Bf7 17. Bxc4 Bxe5 18. Nxe5 Qd6 {White has regained his gambited pawn, but his centre comes under pressure.} 19. f4 Nd7 20. Nxd7 ({If instead} 20. Nxf7 Rxf7 21. e5 {Black has an interesting piece offer available:} Nxe5 $5 (21... Qc5 22. Qd3 Rff8 {also looks playable}) 22. fxe5 Qxe5+ 23. Be2 Qxc3+ {with enough compensation.}) 20... Qxd7 21. exf5 $2 {An oversight?} ({Or} 21. O-O c6 $1 {and the centre will soon be dissolved. Nevertheless, this was White's best option, whereupon} 22. exf5 gxf5 23. dxc6 Qxc6 24. Bxf7+ Rxf7 25. Qd3 {would be more or less equal.}) 21... Bxd5 $1 22. Qe4 Rxf5 {Defending everything whilst snatching a pawn.} 23. O-O-O e6 24. Rhe1 Qf7 {White's threats have come to nought and Timman is reduced to fiddling about looking for swindling opportunities.} 25. Qd3 Rd8 26. Qg3 $2 (26. g3 {limits the damage to only one pawn.}) 26... Rxf4 27. Bd3 g5 28. c4 {Desperate stuff.} Bxc4 ({Another strong move is} 28... Qf6 {as} 29. cxd5 Qc3+ 30. Bc2 Qa1+ 31. Bb1 Rc4+ {gives Black a winning attack.}) 29. Bh7+ Kxh7 30. Rxd8 {Black has given up the exchange in order to concentrate his efforts on cashing-in on White's exposed king.} Qf6 31. Rd7+ Kg6 32. Rxc7 Qa1+ 33. Kc2 Qxa2+ 34. Kc1 Qa1+ 35. Kc2 Rf2+ $1 ({After} 35... Rf2+ 36. Qxf2 Qa2+ 37. Kd1 Qxf2 38. Rxc4 Qxg2 {the queen, plus a fistful of pawns, will beat the two rooks.}) 0-1


