1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5 4. d5 b5 5. Nc3 $5 {Sagar,Shah/CB Website: 'Glenn Flear: '!?' '!?''} b4 {The natural move 'punishing' White for having dared place his knight on c3. Sagar,Shah/CB Website: 'Glenn Flear: 'The natural move 'punishing' White for having dared place his knight on c3.''} ({Instead} 5... bxc4 {somehow misses the point, as White then obtains easy development. Nevertheless, it is sometimes tried e.g.} 6. e4 d6 7. Bxc4 e5 {(Black has a solid albeit passive Benoni)} 8. O-O Be7 9. Ne1 O-O 10. Nd3 Nbd7 11. b3 {Rubene, I-Palos, O Tuzla 1991, with a manoeuvring game in prospect where White has more space.}) 6. Na4 ({The main problem with} 6. Nb1 {is that it is too slow. Two lost tempi in the opening is a serious issue, and consequently White can't maintain his centre:} Bb7 7. dxe6 (7. Bg5 h6 8. Bxf6 Qxf6 {Vigo Allepuz, D-Vocaturo, D Barcelona 2013, leaves Black with all the trumps}) 7... fxe6 8. g3 Be7 9. Bg2 O-O 10. O-O Nc6 11. Qc2 Qc7 12. Nbd2 Rae8 13. b3 d5 {Bauer, A-Lako, L Hungarian league 1999, and Black has a lead in development.}) 6... Bb7 ({Releasing the tension by} 6... exd5 {has been played:} 7. cxd5 d6 8. a3 a5 9. Bg5 Be7 10. e3 O-O 11. Bc4 Nbd7 12. h3 Nh5 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. O-O Nhf6 {Kekki, P-Postny, E Gibraltar 2005, and White's c4-outpost is useful, but the knight on a4 would be happier elsewhere.}) ({Another sensible move is} 6... d6 {in order to meet} 7. Bg5 {with} Be7 {(when ...Nxd5 is a theme) and the knight on a4 starts to look seriously misplaced.}) 7. Bg5 h6 8. Bxf6 Qxf6 9. e4 {White has a fine centre Sagar,Shah/CB Website: 'Glenn Flear: 'White has a fine centre''} d6 10. a3 $1 {This move creates tension on the queenside which in turn gives the offside knight on a4 a certain relevance. Sagar,Shah/CB Website: 'Glenn Flear: '!' '!' Glenn Flear: 'This move creates tension on the queenside which in turn gives the offside knight on a4 a certain relevance.''} ({Delaying this move can have negative consequences:} 10. Bd3 Nd7 11. O-O g5 $1 12. Re1 g4 13. Nd2 Ne5 14. Bf1 h5 15. a3 h4 $1 {Mona, K-Adly, A Chania 2014, and Black had already generated a strong attack. In the game continuation, the sidelined knight on a4 was a mere spectator as White was duly mated.}) 10... Nd7 ({Previously} 10... Na6 {(to perhaps recapture on b4 with the knight) has been tried:} 11. Bd3 e5 12. O-O Be7 13. Nd2 O-O 14. Be2 bxa3 15. bxa3 Qg5 {Lombardy, W-Wilder, M Lone Pine 1981, with a fairly balanced game, but White's space advantage shouldn't be underestimated and may well be more relevant than Black's bishop pair.}) 11. axb4 cxb4 12. Qd2 Rb8 $5 {Sagar,Shah/CB Website: 'Glenn Flear: '!?' '!?''} ({The natural} 12... a5 {provoked a violent reaction in the following:} 13. c5 $5 dxc5 14. Bb5 exd5 15. O-O O-O-O 16. exd5 Nb6 {Boensch, U-Votava, J Bad Woerishofen 1993, with chances for both sides.}) 13. Be2 Be7 14. O-O O-O 15. Nd4 Rfc8 16. b3 {White consolidates his centre and even gives the wayward knight a route towards the centre via b2. You may notice however that the knight actually holds it's ground on a4 until it is captured late in the game. Sagar,Shah/CB Website: 'Glenn Flear: 'White consolidates his centre and even gives the wayward knight a route towards the centre via b2. You may notice however that the knight actually holds it's ground on a4 until it is captured late in the game.''} Bf8 17. Rae1 Re8 18. Bd1 g6 19. Nc2 a5 {Finally Wei Yi accepts that he has to play this move. Black's bishop pair are not able to do much about White's central grip. Sagar,Shah/CB Website: 'Glenn Flear: 'Finally Wei Yi accepts that he has to play this move. Black's bishop pair are not able to do much about White's central grip.''} 20. Nd4 h5 21. g3 Rbc8 22. f4 $1 {A sign of confidence. Sagar,Shah/CB Website: 'Glenn Flear: '!' '!' Glenn Flear: 'A sign of confidence.''} e5 $1 {A necessary reaction. Sagar,Shah/CB Website: 'Glenn Flear: '!' '!' Glenn Flear: 'A necessary reaction.''} 23. Nb5 exf4 24. gxf4 Ba6 $6 {Provocative, but maybe too much so. Sagar,Shah/CB Website: 'Glenn Flear: '?!' '?!' Glenn Flear: 'Provocative, but maybe too much so.''} ({Possibly} 24... Bh6 {when any exchanges (such as)} 25. Qd4 Qxd4+ 26. Nxd4 Bg7 {make Black's position easier to handle.}) 25. Na7 ({The engines cry out in unison for} 25. e5 $1 {when the pawns expand to great effect. After the plausible continuation} dxe5 26. fxe5 Qg7 27. Nd6 Bxd6 28. exd6 {White is better.}) 25... Rc7 26. Nc6 {A fine outpost from where the noble steed can pick off the a-pawn at leisure. Sagar,Shah/CB Website: 'Glenn Flear: 'A fine outpost from where the noble steed can pick off the a-pawn at leisure.''} Bh6 27. Qf2 Bc8 28. Kh1 Qg7 29. Qg3 ({It's perhaps the best moment to capture on a5, as then the knight can come back into play via c6. So} 29. Nxa5 $1 {is best.}) 29... Bb7 30. Nxa5 {Finally! The 'doubled knights' on the a-file are a strange sight, but White doesn't suffer from their lack of presence elsewhere. Sagar,Shah/CB Website: 'Glenn Flear: 'Finally! The 'doubled knights' on the a-file are a strange sight, but White doesn't suffer from their lack of presence elsewhere.''} Ba8 {With the bishop here it will take some preparation before White can play Nc6 under favourable circumstances. Sagar,Shah/CB Website: 'Glenn Flear: 'With the bishop here it will take some preparation before White can play Nc6 under favourable circumstances.''} 31. Bf3 Kh8 32. Bg2 Qd4 {There is nothing to hit here. Sagar,Shah/CB Website: 'Glenn Flear: 'There is nothing to hit here.''} 33. Rd1 Qa7 34. Nc6 Bxc6 35. dxc6 Rxc6 36. e5 {Hence the reason for placing the bishop on the long light-squared diagonal. Sagar,Shah/CB Website: 'Glenn Flear: 'Hence the reason for placing the bishop on the long light-squared diagonal.''} Ra6 37. exd6 Re3 {Finally some counterplay, but the passed pawns in the centre still give White a big advantage. Sagar,Shah/CB Website: 'Glenn Flear: 'Finally some counterplay, but the passed pawns in the centre still give White a big advantage.''} 38. Qf2 ({Or attacking mode with} 38. Qh4 $1 Rxb3 39. f5 {should see White home.}) 38... Rxb3 39. Qxa7 Rxa7 40. Bc6 (40. c5 $1 Rxa4 41. c6 {wins material.}) 40... Nb8 41. Bb5 Ra3 42. Rfe1 ({Again} 42. c5 $1 {is direct and strong.}) 42... Kg7 43. Re8 Rb7 44. Re7 $2 {Letting things slip rather too far. Sagar,Shah/CB Website: 'Glenn Flear: '?' '?' Glenn Flear: 'Letting things slip rather too far.''} (44. Nc5 Rb6 45. d7 Nxd7 46. Nxd7 {is strong, but there are technical difficulties.}) ({More sophisticated is} 44. f5 $1 {(exposing Black's king!)} gxf5 (44... Re3 45. fxg6 fxg6 46. Rxe3 Bxe3 47. Kg2 Kf6 48. d7 Nxd7 49. Bxd7 {and the knight on a4 is ideally-placed (!) to support the advance of the c-pawn while restraining the black b-pawn}) 45. Rg1+ Kf6 46. Nc5 Rb6 47. d7 {winning easily.}) 44... Rxb5 $1 {Sagar,Shah/CB Website: 'Glenn Flear: '!' '!''} 45. cxb5 Rxa4 46. Rb7 Ra8 47. d7 Nxd7 48. Rbxd7 ({Maybe Gagare saw too late that} 48. Rdxd7 $2 {is strongly met by} b3 $1) 48... Rb8 49. R7d5 {Now Black has realistic drawing chances. Sagar,Shah/CB Website: 'Glenn Flear: 'Now Black has realistic drawing chances.''} Kf6 ({Possibly} 49... Bxf4 50. R1d4 g5 51. Rxb4 Kf6 {when there is still an ongoing fight.}) 50. R1d4 Bf8 $6 {Sagar,Shah/CB Website: 'Glenn Flear: '?!' '?!''} ({Again I can't be sure that White is able to win after} 50... b3 51. Rb4 b2 52. Rd2 Kf5 53. Rdxb2 Rb6) 51. Rd8 $1 {Sagar,Shah/CB Website: 'Glenn Flear: '!' '!''} Bc5 52. Rxb8 Bxd4 53. Rd8 {Black resigned, but was it premature?} ({After Sagar,Shah/CB Website: 'Glenn Flear: 'After''} 53. Rd8 {Life isn't so easy after the astonishing Sagar,Shah/CB Website: 'Glenn Flear: 'Black resigned, but was it premature?' Glenn Flear: 'Life isn't so easy after the astonishing'' Sagar Shah/CB Website: 'Wei Yi resigned the game at this point seeing that his bishop is attacked, and if he moves it, b6 followed by b7-b8 is threatened. After b6 he cannot play ...xb6, as then d6+ will pick up the piece. Yet, here Black has a miraculous defence which was overlooked by the Chinese grandmaster.' Sagar,Shah/CB Website: 'Wei Yi resigned the game at this point seeing that his bishop is attacked, and if he moves it, b6 followed by b7-b8 is threatened. After b6 he cannot play ...xb6, as then d6+ will pick up the piece. Yet, here Black has a miraculous defence which was overlooked by the Chinese grandmaster. Wei Yi resigned the game at this point seeing that his bishop is attacked, and if he moves it, b6 followed by b7-b8 is threatened. After b6 he cannot play ...xb6, as then d6+ will pick up the piece. Yet, here Black has a miraculous defence which was overlooked by the Chinese grandmaster. Glenn Flear: 'Sagar Shah/CB Website: 'Wei Yi resigned the game at this point seeing that his bishop is attacked, and if he moves it, b6 followed by b7-b8 is threatened. After b6 he cannot play ...xb6, as then d6+ will pick up the piece. Yet, here Black has a miraculous defence which was overlooked by the Chinese grandmaster.'''} Bb6 $3 {(what a move!) Sagar,Shah/CB Website: 'Glenn Flear: '(what a move!)'' Sagar Shah/CB Website: 'Can you believe this! This is the only way in which Black can fight on, although most probably even this is objectively lost. But it is not so easy to prove it.' Sagar,Shah/CB Website: 'Can you believe this! This is the only way in which Black can fight on, although most probably even this is objectively lost. But it is not so easy to prove it. Can you believe this! This is the only way in which Black can fight on, although most probably even this is objectively lost. But it is not so easy to prove it. Glenn Flear: 'Sagar Shah/CB Website: 'Can you believe this! This is the only way in which Black can fight on, although most probably even this is objectively lost. But it is not so easy to prove it.'''} ({the normal-looking Sagar,Shah/CB Website: 'Glenn Flear: 'the normal-looking''} 53... Be3 {Sagar Shah/CB Website: '?' Sagar,Shah/CB Website: '?' '?' '?' '?' Sagar,Shah/CB Website: 'Glenn Flear: 'Sagar Shah/CB Website: '?'''} 54. b6 {Sagar Shah/CB Website: '!' Sagar,Shah/CB Website: '!' '!' '!' '!' Sagar,Shah/CB Website: 'Glenn Flear: 'Sagar Shah/CB Website: '!'''} Bxf4 (54... Bxb6 55. Rd6+ {Sagar Shah/CB Website: '+-' Sagar,Shah/CB Website: '+-' '+-' '+-' '+-' Sagar,Shah/CB Website: 'Glenn Flear: 'Sagar Shah/CB Website: '+-'''}) (54... b3 55. b7 b2 56. b8=Q $18) 55. b7 Kg7 56. b8=Q Bxb8 57. Rxb8 {is a straightforward win for White}) (53... Z0) (53... b3 $2 54. Rxd4 b2 55. Rb4 $18) 54. Rd6+ Ke7 {and now Sagar,Shah/CB Website: 'Glenn Flear: 'and now''} 55. Rxb6 $2 {is not good because of Sagar,Shah/CB Website: 'Glenn Flear: 'is not good because of''} ({Necessary is} 55. Rd3 $1 Ke6 56. Kg2 {followed by bringing the king into play. White would probably still be able to win with best play.}) (55. Rd2 Ke6 56. Kg2 {Slowly White should win this as he will activate his king and break the fortress. However, this sequence starting with ...b6 was definitely worth trying over the board by Wei Yi.}) 55... b3 {and White cannot come back to stop the b-pawn, and would have to give perpetual check with Sagar Shah/CB Website: '!' Sagar,Shah/CB Website: '!' '!' '!' '!' Sagar,Shah/CB Website: 'Glenn Flear: 'and White cannot come back to stop the b-pawn, and would have to give perpetual check with' Glenn Flear: 'and White cannot come back to stop the b-pawn, and would have to give perpetual check with Sagar Shah/CB Website: '!''' Sagar Shah/CB Website: 'The a- and c-files are useless as a1 and c1 will be covered after b2. And there are no other squares available.' Sagar,Shah/CB Website: 'The a- and c-files are useless as a1 and c1 will be covered after b2. And there are no other squares available. The a- and c-files are useless as a1 and c1 will be covered after b2. And there are no other squares available. Glenn Flear: 'Sagar Shah/CB Website: 'The a- and c-files are useless as a1 and c1 will be covered after b2. And there are no other squares available.'''} 56. Rb7+ Kd8 (56... Ke8 57. Rb8+ Ke7 $11) 57. Rb8+ Kd7 58. Rb7+ Kd8 $11) 1-0


