[EventCountry "RUS"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bf4 Bg7 5. e3 O-O 6. Nf3 c5 7. dxc5 Ne4 8. Rc1 Nd7 9. cxd5 Qa5 10. Be2 $5 (10. Nd4 {is better known, especially since the following high-level encounter:} Nxc3 11. bxc3 Qxa2 12. c6 Nc5 13. Be2 Qxd5 14. Bf3 Qc4 15. Be2 {and a draw with repetition followed in Ivanchuk, V-Gelfand, B London Candidates 2013.}) 10... Nxc3 ({I can't see any advantage in allowing White to castle into safety, so} 10... Ndxc5 $6 11. O-O Nxc3 12. bxc3 Ne4 13. c4 Qxa2 {isn't really a great idea. Black offered a draw which was accepted in Purnama, T-Vakhidov, T Penang 2015, but White's centre should be of a higher value than Black's queenside.}) 11. bxc3 Bxc3+ 12. Kf1 Nxc5 13. h4 ({Trading bishops doesn't seem to be worrisome for Black:} 13. Be5 Bxe5 14. Nxe5 Ne4 15. Qd4 Nd6 16. h4 Bf5 {(Black is already equal according to the engines)} 17. g4 $6 (17. f3 Rac8 18. Kf2 $11 {is safer}) 17... Rac8 $6 ({Speculative. Instead, Black has the more comfortable game after} 17... Be4 18. Bf3 Bxf3 19. Nxf3 Rac8 20. Kg2 Qa3 $1 {competing for the c-file}) 18. Rxc8 Rxc8 19. gxf5 Rc1+ 20. Bd1 Nxf5 {Golod, V-Charochkina, D Yerevan 2014. Objectively Black's compensation is a little unconvincing, but in a practical game White will have his work cut out to untangle. Black went on to win.}) 13... Bd7 ({Retreating with the bishop is a shade too slow:} 13... Bg7 14. h5 Bd7 (14... Ne4 {to come over to the kingside to bolster the defences might be better}) 15. hxg6 hxg6 16. Be5 (16. d6 $1) 16... Ne4 17. Qd4 Nf6 18. d6 $1 {Riazantsev, A-Sychev, K Moscow Blitz 2015, with a big advantage for White.}) 14. Kg1 Rac8 ({Another recent game varied with} 14... Ba4 15. Qf1 {(an unusual use of f1 in the Grünfeld!)} f6 (15... h5 $5) 16. g4 (16. Nd4 $5) 16... Rae8 ({why this square? Surely} 16... Rac8 {looks more natural?}) 17. g5 $1 Rf7 18. h5 gxh5 19. Rxh5 Rg7 20. Kh2 {Szabo, G-Shishkin, Va Alba Iulia 2016, and White's kingside play was starting to look dangerous.}) 15. h5 {The principled move leading to an exciting struggle.} Ne4 16. hxg6 fxg6 $5 ({The engines prefer} 16... hxg6 {and, if White isn't causing any mischief on the h-file, might be objectively best, but opening the f-file has its merits and certainly 'feels' more comfortable for the king.}) 17. Bd3 Nf6 ({Now, grabbing the d-pawn comes into consideration:} 17... Ba4 18. Qe2 Qxd5 {but then White can win two pieces for a rook with} 19. Bh6 Rfd8 20. Bxe4 Qxe4 21. Rh4 Qc6 22. Rxc3 Qxc3 23. Rxa4 {and must then be favourite.}) 18. Ng5 {Wei Yi has to react to the threat of Nxh7 which looks dangerous.} Bd2 $1 19. Rb1 Qc3 $5 ({Here} 19... Bg4 {gives White a difficult choice:} 20. Qb3 (20. f3 Bf5 $5) (20. Nf3 Bxf3 21. gxf3 Nxd5 $13) 20... Qxd5 21. Nxh7 Qxb3 22. Nxf6+ Rxf6 23. Rxb3 b6 $11) 20. Qe2 Bg4 21. Qf1 Nxd5 $2 {This definitely hands the initiative (and advantage!) to White.} ({The complications after} 21... Rfd8 22. Rh4 {are difficult to judge, but Black seems to be OK following} Rxd5 $1) 22. Ne4 Qa5 23. Bc4 Be6 ({Or} 23... e6 24. Rb5 Qxb5 25. Bxb5 Rc1 26. Nxd2 {and White picks off a piece.}) 24. Rb5 $2 {Missing a golden opportunity to beat the rising star of the East.} ({Here} 24. Bh6 $1 Rfd8 25. Nxd2 Qxd2 26. e4 {would be clearly winning.}) 24... Qa4 25. Bxd5 Bxd5 26. Rxd5 Rc1 27. Nxd2 Rxf1+ 28. Nxf1 Rc8 {Over the years, I have come across so many examples where the queen (plus a couple of pawns) can stave off the combined forces of a rook and a couple of minor pieces. It takes time for the multi-piece army to get organized and sometimes one just can't find it...} 29. Rd2 Rc1 30. Rd8+ $6 (30. f3 {keeps everything solid.}) 30... Kg7 31. Kh2 $4 {Suddenly the tactics work for Black...} Qa5 $1 {With threats against both rooks!} 32. Rd7 Qh5+ 33. Kg1 Rxf1+ 34. Kxf1 Qb5+ {Wei Yi naturally prefers to capture the most active white rook. Now Black is winning at a canter.} 35. Ke1 Qxd7 36. Be5+ Kg8 37. Rh4 Qd5 {Another handy fork.} 38. Bc3 Qxg2 39. a4 h5 40. Be5 g5 {If White captures on h5 he loses at least a piece, whereas if not, the h-pawn will keep going.} 0-1


