e than Black's queenside.} (14. b3 O-O 15. Re3 Bb4) 14... O-O {is better known, especially since the following high-level encounter:} 15. Re1 Be6 16. Re3) 12. f4 g6 (12... Bf6 {and must then be favourite.} {The engines prefer} 13. f5 {and, if White isn't causing any mischief on the h-file, might be objectively best, but opening the f-file has its merits and certainly 'feels' more comfortable for the king.}) ({Another recent game varied with} 12... Qd7 13. Nc3 {(an unusual use of f1 in the Grünfeld!)} g6 (13... Bg4 14. Qe3) 14. f5 gxf5 15. Bf4 $1) 13. Nc3 a3 14. b3 (14. bxa3 Bd6 15. f5 gxf5 $13 {Now, grabbing the d-pawn comes into consideration:} 16. Bf4 Bxe5 17. Qxe5 {but then White can win two pieces for a rook with} Rg8 18. Re1 Qd6 19. Nxd5 O-O-O 20. Qxd6 cxd6 21. Ne7+) 14... Bb4 (14... Bd6 15. f5 gxf5 16. Bf4 ({The complications after} 16. Rxf5 Qh4 {are difficult to judge, but Black seems to be OK following}) 16... Bxe5 {If White captures on h5 he loses at least a piece, whereas if not, the h-pawn will keep going.} 17. Qxe5 {keeps everything solid.} {Here} Rg8 $1 18. Re1 Qd6 (18... c6 19. Na4 {and White picks off a piece.}) 19. Nxd5 (19. Qxd5) 19... O-O-O {would be clearly winning.} {Or} 20. Qxd6 cxd6 21. Ne7+) (14... O-O $1 {Here} 15. f5 {gives White a difficult choice:} gxf5 16. Bf4 Bd6 17. Rf1 Kh8 18. Re3 Rg8 19. Qf2 $11 Bxf4 20. Qxf4 $5) 15. Na4 {The principled move leading to an exciting struggle.} O-O 16. Bd2 (16. c3 Bd6 17. Nc5 Bxe5 (17... Bf5 {Another handy fork.} 18. Rxd5) 18. fxe5) 16... Bd6 $5 17. Nc5 Bf5 18. Bb4 {Wei Yi has to react to the threat of Nxh7 which looks dangerous.} (18. Rxd5 Bxc2 {Wei Yi naturally prefers to capture the most active white rook. Now Black is winning at a canter.}) 18... Bxe5 $1 19. fxe5 Qh4 $5 20. c3 a5 21. Bxa3 Rfe8 $2 {This definitely hands the initiative (and advantage!) to White.} 22. Rf1 f6 23. e6 a4 (23... Re7) 24. bxa4 $2 {Missing a golden opportunity to beat the rising star of the East.} Qg4 25. Qe1 Be4 26. Qf2 Bf5 