{This game was played in the sixth round of the World junior. I was doing about ok here and was pitted against one of the top stars.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Be7 5. Bf4 (5. Bg5) 5... c5 (5... O-O 6. e3 c5 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. a3 Nc6 9. cxd5 (9. Qc2 Qa5 10. Nd2 Bb4 11. cxd5 exd5 12. Bd3 d4 13. O-O Bxc3 14. Nc4 Qh5 15. bxc3 Nd5 16. Bg3 dxe3 17. Rae1 Be6 18. fxe3 Nde7 19. Nd6 b6 20. Rb1) 9... Nxd5 10. Nxd5 exd5 11. Bd3 Bb6 12. O-O d4 13. e4 Bc7 14. Bxc7 Qxc7 15. h3 Qb6 16. b4 Be6 17. Rc1 h6 18. Qd2) 6. dxc5 Na6 {A relatively newer idea, it's seldom played and quite effective for 1 game purposes.} 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Nxd5 exd5 9. e4 $1 {I think bxd4 is more obvious, but White doesn't achieve much there.} (9. e3 Nxc5 10. Bb5+ Bd7 11. Bxd7+ Qxd7 12. O-O O-O) 9... O-O {Black needs to be precise here.} 10. exd5 Bxc5 11. Be2 (11. Bxa6 Qa5+ 12. Nd2 Qxa6 13. Qe2 b6) (11. Bc4 Re8+) 11... Bb4+ (11... Nc7 12. Bxc7 (12. d6 Ne6 13. Bg3 Qa5+ 14. Nd2 Qb4) 12... Bb4+ 13. Nd2 Qxc7 14. O-O) (11... Qb6 12. O-O Qxb2 13. Be5) (11... Qa5+ 12. Bd2 Qb6 13. O-O Qxb2 14. Rc1) (11... Nb4 12. d6 Be6 13. Ng5 Qf6) 12. Kf1 $5 Bd6 13. Bg5 (13. Be3 Bf5) 13... Qa5 (13... Qb6 14. Nd2 Qxb2 15. Nc4 Qb4 16. Rc1) (13... f6) (13... Qd7) 14. a3 Nc7 (14... Bd7 15. b4 Qa4 16. Nd2) 15. Bc4 b5 16. b4 $5 {This was a new move, but it transposed to what I had prepared, White's main threat is to take on e6 now.} Qb6 17. Bb3 a5 18. Be3 (18. Rc1 Bb7 19. Be3 Qa6 20. Ng5 h6 21. h4) 18... Qb7 19. Bc5 {I had this position at home with my king on g8, here I thought for a while if I should go for it via f5, but after a long thought I decided to go with what I had already seen.} (19. Ng5 Bf5 20. g4 Bg6 21. h4 Rfe8 22. h5 Be4 23. Nxe4 Rxe4 24. Qf3 Nxd5 25. Qxe4 Nxe3+) 19... Bxc5 (19... Rd8 20. Ng5 $1 {The whole point behind delaying ...f6, since now White doesn't have tricks like playing g5-xf6, or f3-e5, I think Black is very happy here.} Bf5 21. Nxf7 Kxf7 22. Qf3 g6 23. g4 Bxc5 24. d6+) (19... Ra6 20. Qd3 h6 21. h4 axb4 22. Ng5 f5 23. Bxb4 Bxb4 24. d6+ Kh8 25. d7 Bxd7 26. Qxd7 Qc8) 20. bxc5 a4 21. Ba2 b4 22. axb4 Qxb4 23. Qd4 Na6 {This was where my preparation ended. I had concluded that this position was about equal. White is a pawn up, but I think Black's pawn structure is just too solid, so it should just be a draw.} 24. c6 Qxd4 25. Nxd4 Nb4 26. Ke2 (26. d6 Rd8 27. d7 Bxd7 28. cxd7 Rxd7 29. Nf3 Nxa2 {and although this endgame looks very dynamic, Black should be able to hold the fort together.} 30. Rxa2 $2 Rd1+ 31. Ne1 Re8 32. Re2 Ra8 33. f3 Ra1 34. Kf2 a3 {and White can generate an attack on the kingside.} 35. Rf1 a2 36. Nc2 Rxf1+ $1 37. Kxf1 a1=Q+) 26... Nxa2 27. Rxa2 Ba6+ 28. Kd2 {Not much can go wrong for Black now.} Bc4 29. Ra3 Bxd5 30. c7 Be6 (30... Bxg2) 31. Nb5 Bd7 {It was not difficult to find a couple of correct moves here.} (31... Ra5 32. Rb1 Bd7 33. Nd6 Ra6) 32. Nd6 g6 (32... Ra6 33. Rd3 a3 34. Nc4 Be6 35. Nxa3) 33. Rc1 Kg7 34. Rc4 (34. Ke3 Kf6 35. Kd4 Ke7 36. Kc5 Ra6 $11 {Black is active enough here.} 37. Re1+ {is also playable I think, but somehow I wasn't so sure about this}) 34... Ra6 35. Rd4 (35. c8=N Rd8) 35... Ra7 {I offered him a draw here, he accepted, as neither one of us had any improvement.} 36. Ne8+ Rxe8 37. Rxd7 Raa8 (37... Rc8 38. Rf3 a3 39. Rdxf7+ $1 $19 Kh6 (39... Kg8 40. Rf8+ $11 {Usually in such structures White's light-coloured bishop poses a lot of problems. with it having been traded-off, Black's completely fine here.}) 40. Rh3+ Kg5 $5 41. f4+ Kg4 42. Rg3+) 38. Kc3 Kf6 39. Kb4 Ke6 40. Rd4 (40. Rad3 a3 41. Rd8 $11 {and because of the d4 invasion, Black probably survives.} a2 $2 42. Rxe8+ Rxe8 43. Re3+ Kf6 44. Rxe8 $19 a1=Q $2 45. c8=Q) 40... Ke5 (40... Rec8 41. Re3+ Kf6 $11 {Had I seen one more move, I would have played} 42. Rf4+ {as it's precise} Kg7 43. Re7 a3 (43... Rf8 44. Ka3 $1 $11) 44. Rfxf7+ $11 Kg8 (44... Kh6 45. Rxh7+ Kg5 46. h4+ Kg4 47. Re4+ Kf5 48. Rhe7) 45. Rg7+ Kf8 46. Rxh7 Kg8 47. Reg7+ Kf8 48. Rd7 Kg8 49. Rhe7 a2 50. Re1 $11) (40... f5 $5 41. Re3+ $1 Kf7 42. Rd7+ Kf8 43. Rxe8+ Kxe8 44. Rxh7) 41. Rc4 Rec8 (41... Ke6 42. Kc5 Kd7 43. Kb6 Kc8 44. Re3) 42. Kb5 Kd5 $11 43. Rc2 1/2-1/2


