{This game was played in the sixth round of the World junior. I was doing about ok here and was pitted against one of the top stars.} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. Ngf3 cxd4 6. Bc4 Qd8 {A relatively newer idea, it's seldom played and quite effective for 1 game purposes.} 7. O-O a6 8. Nb3 Nc6 9. Qe2 $1 {I think bxd4 is more obvious, but White doesn't achieve much there.} (9. Nbxd4 Nxd4 10. Nxd4 Qc7 $1 11. Qe2 Bd6 12. g3 Ne7 $1 {The whole point behind delaying ...f6, since now White doesn't have tricks like playing g5-xf6, or f3-e5, I think Black is very happy here.}) 9... b5 {Black needs to be precise here.} (9... Nf6 $2 10. Rd1 b5 11. Nbxd4 Nxd4 12. Rxd4 Qc7 13. Bd3 Bc5 14. Rh4 {and White can generate an attack on the kingside.}) 10. Bd3 Nf6 (10... Bb7 {is also playable I think, but somehow I wasn't so sure about this} 11. Rd1 Qc7 12. Nbxd4 Nxd4 13. Nxd4 Nf6 14. Bf4 Qxf4 15. Bxb5+ Ke7 16. Bc6 Ng4 17. g3 Qxf2+ 18. Qxf2 Nxf2 19. Kxf2 Bxc6 20. Nxc6+ Ke8 {and although this endgame looks very dynamic, Black should be able to hold the fort together.}) 11. Rd1 Bd6 12. a4 $5 (12. Bg5 Bb7 13. Be4 $5 O-O 14. Bxc6 Bxc6 15. Nbxd4 Bd5 $11 {Usually in such structures White's light-coloured bishop poses a lot of problems. with it having been traded-off, Black's completely fine here.}) (12. Nbxd4 Nxd4 13. Nxd4 O-O 14. c3 Bb7 15. a4 b4 $11 {Black is active enough here.}) 12... b4 13. Bg5 Bb7 14. Nfxd4 Nxd4 15. Nxd4 O-O 16. Bh4 $5 {This was a new move, but it transposed to what I had prepared, White's main threat is to take on e6 now.} (16. Nxe6 $2 fxe6 17. Qxe6+ Kh8 18. Bf1 Qa5 $1 $19) 16... Kh8 17. Nf3 Qc7 18. Bxf6 gxf6 19. Bxh7 {I had this position at home with my king on g8, here I thought for a while if I should go for it via f5, but after a long thought I decided to go with what I had already seen.} Kxh7 (19... f5 $5 20. Rd4 $1 (20. Ng5 $2 Qc6 21. f3 Bf4 22. Nh3 Bh6 $19) 20... Kxh7 21. Qd2 Be7 22. Rd7 Qb6 23. Rxe7 Bxf3 24. gxf3 Rad8 $11 {and because of the d4 invasion, Black probably survives.}) 20. Qd3+ f5 21. Qxd6 Qxd6 22. Rxd6 Bxf3 23. gxf3 a5 {This was where my preparation ended. I had concluded that this position was about equal. White is a pawn up, but I think Black's pawn structure is just too solid, so it should just be a draw.} 24. Rc1 Rfc8 ({Had I seen one more move, I would have played} 24... Rg8+ {as it's precise} 25. Kh1 (25. Kf1 Kg6 26. c4 (26. Rd4 Rh8 27. h4 Rad8 28. Rxd8 Rxd8 29. Ke2 Rd4 30. Rh1 b3 $1 $11) 26... bxc3 27. bxc3 Rh8 28. Kg2 Kf6 29. c4 Rag8+ 30. Kh1 Rh4 $11) 25... Rad8 26. Rxd8 Rxd8 $11) 25. Rd3 (25. c4 bxc3 26. Rxc3 Rxc3 27. bxc3 Rc8 28. Ra6 Rxc3 29. Rxa5 Rxf3 $11) 25... Rc4 26. b3 Rh4 27. c4 bxc3 28. Rcxc3 {Not much can go wrong for Black now.} (28. Rdxc3 Rb4 29. Rd3 Kg6 30. Rc7 Kf6 $11) 28... Rg8+ 29. Kf1 Rxh2 30. Rd7 Kg6 31. Ke2 f4 {It was not difficult to find a couple of correct moves here.} 32. Rc5 Rb8 33. Rd3 (33. Rb5 Rxb5 34. axb5 Rh5 35. Rb7 Rd5 36. b6 Kf6) 33... Rh5 34. Rxh5 Kxh5 35. Rc3 Kh4 {I offered him a draw here, he accepted, as neither one of us had any improvement.} 1/2-1/2


