{The final match between USA and China was a thriller with Fabiano Caruana defeating Wei Yi and Yu Yangyi defeating Wesley So. Since China had more points in the round robin stage, 2 : 2 was enough for them to win the title. Fabiano played important role in brining USA to the finals and scoring important point for the team. In this game he outplayed Wei Yi who opted for the Scandinavian! It would have been a really brave decision if he had managed to draw the game.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 {Black has four other queen moves apart from the move in the game.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 e5 7. Nf3 Be7 8. Bc4 {I like this move as White stops Black from playing Bg4 and exchanging the f3 knight.} O-O 9. O-O Qc7 $6 $146 {Diagram [#]} 10. Bb3 $1 Be6 11. Nh4 {White intends to play b4. White intends to play b4. [ b4]} g6 12. Bh6 Re8 13. Qd2 Ng4 14. Nf3 Nd7 {Diagram [#]} 15. Bg5 $1 {This move forces Black to retreat to c6.} Ngf6 16. a4 Rab8 {Diagram [#]} 17. Qe2 $1 {Black must have overlooked this move.} Bxb3 18. cxb3 b5 19. axb5 axb5 20. Bxf6 Nxf6 21. Rfd1 Rec8 22. Ne1 b4 23. Nd5 $2 {This is a rather greedy move. White throws away large advantage.} Nxd5 24. Rxd5 Rb6 25. g3 Bf8 26. Qe3 Rb7 27. Nd3 {Diagram [#]} Rcb8 28. Rc1 Qe7 29. Rc4 f5 30. Kg2 fxe4 31. Qxe4 Qf7 32. Qf3 {Diagram [#]} Be7 $2 {The final mistake in already very difficult position. Black has no chances to save the game. Fabiano plays the rest of it accurately, and takes home the crucial point for Team USA.} 33. Ra5 $18 Qxf3+ 34. Kxf3 Bd8 35. Rd5 Rb6 36. Ke4 Kf7 37. g4 Ke6 38. f4 exf4 39. Nxf4+ Kd7 40. Rd3 Rb5 41. Nd5 Ba5 42. Kf4 h6 43. Re4 Bd8 $145 44. Kg3 h5 (44... h5 $16 45. h4) 1-0


