1. Nf3 {Havasi,Gergo Havasi,G} d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8. cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Bc4 Nd7 (11... Nc6 {was played by Lysyj and it was annotated by Shagar Shah in CBM 168} 12. O-O b6 13. Rad1 Na5 14. Bd3 Bb7 15. h4 Rc8 16. h5 h6 17. Rfe1 Qe7 18. d5 Nc4 19. Bxc4 Rxc4 20. Ne5 Rc5 21. d6 Qd8 22. Qf4 f6 23. Ng6 Rf7 24. e5 $36 {1-0 (40) Tomashevsky,E (2747)-Lysyj,I (2673) Chita 2015 CBM 168 [Sagar Shah]}) 12. O-O b6 13. Rfe1 (13. a4 {and}) (13. Rad1 {are the main alternatives.}) 13... Bb7 14. a4 (14. Rad1 Rc8 15. Bb3 Qf6 16. Qe3 Rfd8 17. h3 h6 $13 {1/2 (33) Ponomariov,R (2714)-Wang,Y (2720) Beijing 2014}) 14... Rc8 15. Bb5 (15. Bd3 {is the other line.}) 15... Nf6 16. Bd3 h6 17. a5 b5 $146 {This is a novelty.} (17... Qc7 18. axb6 axb6 19. Rac1 Qb8 20. Rb1 Nd7 21. Qb4 $14 {1-0 (41) Janssen,R (2498)-Levin,F (2484) Netherlands 2011}) 18. a6 $1 {This is an important move to prevent a6, because it would stabilise Black's position.} Bc6 19. Qb4 {Overprotecting the d4-pawn, to free the knight and make it possible to move it.} Qb6 $1 {Protecting b5 and pushing the d4-pawn.} 20. Nd2 {The logical move, because the  will be good on b3.} Rfd8 21. Nb3 e5 (21... Be8 {is also possible, just a waiting move as it is hard to make progress for both sides.}) 22. d5 Bd7 23. Na5 $1 {An active move, getting the knight to b7.} Rc7 $1 {And a good reaction, because Black chooses the strategy of putting the s on the c-file.} 24. Nb7 (24. d6 {seems to be better to prevent Black from playing dc8:} Rcc8 25. Nb7 Re8 26. Reb1) 24... Rdc8 25. h3 {Good move, preventing g4.} (25. Nd6 Ng4 $1 26. Rf1 Rc1 $1 $36) 25... Rc3 $1 {d6 was threatening and Black neutralises this plan, because now d6 won't be dangerous} 26. Red1 R8c7 $1 {Havasi,G: '=' Havasi,Gergo: '=' This move may look like a simple position-improving, waiting move, but it has the point of preventing d6 or e7, because of d6 xb7 or e7 xh3} (26... Bg4 $5 {is a spectacular move, but it's likely, that it is hard to make progress after} 27. Rd2 $1 (27. hxg4 Nxg4 $36 28. Ra2 Rxd3 $1)) 27. Nd6 ({Maybe} 27. Na5 {is more accurate, when Black should repeat with} R7c5 28. Nb7 Rc7 $11) 27... Nh5 $1 {Now Black starts to get some initiative.} 28. Nf5 $1 {But White also finds this important defensive move to close the diagonal of the .} Nf4 29. Bf1 Rc2 (29... R7c5 {is also good, as the move played in the game lost a tempo because of e3.}) 30. Ne3 R2c3 31. d6 ({One of the suggestions of the computer is} 31. Kh2 {and it seems, that it's equal.}) 31... Rc8 32. Ra2 (32. Kh2 {is a bit more accurate.}) 32... Rxe3 $1 {A brave attacking sacrifice.} 33. fxe3 Qxe3+ 34. Rf2 $6 {This move overlooks the next move.} ({In the event of} 34. Kh2 $1 Ne6 {Black would have enough compensation.}) 34... Qg3 $1 35. Rf3 (35. Rxf4 Qxf4 $17) 35... Nxh3+ 36. Kh1 Qg4 $1 {And Black continues the attack. There was the possibility of a repetition with f2.} 37. Bxb5 (37. Qe1 {was better to hold the position, but Black has a good attack after} Ng5 38. Rg3 Qf4 $40) 37... Bxb5 38. Qxb5 Nf2+ 39. Kh2 {White wants to try a last practical chance, but Black exploits his advantage accurately.} ({Of course} 39. Rxf2 Qxd1+ 40. Kh2 Qxd6 41. Qb7 Qc7 $17 {is also winning.}) 39... Nxd1 40. Qxe5 Qh4+ 41. Rh3 Qg5 42. Qxg5 hxg5 43. Rb3 Nf2 44. Rb7 Nxe4 45. d7 Rd8 46. Rxa7 Nc5 47. Rc7 Nxd7 48. a7 Nf8 0-1


