1. e4 {Hillarp Persson,Tiger Hillarp Persson,Tiger Hillarp Persson,Tiger Hillarp Persson,Tiger Hillarp Persson,Tiger Hillarp Persson,Tiger Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'Hillarp Persson,T' Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'Arsovic,Goran'} c5 {Already at this stage I felt inclined to comment on this game. It's nice to see that there are some who still seek asymmetry.} 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 {Finally someone who is prepared to play a principled move.} ({Karjakin came up with} 6. a3 {in the first round against Giri. I guess this move is inspired by a kind of psychic prophylaxis: "I'll stop you from playing b5-b4 because the cards say that you will play b7-b5." Then Carlsen followed suit in round 2, and won. "Principled" is so yesterday.}) 6... e6 7. f4 h6 {This line has ascended from obscurity into the limelight in only a few years. Compared to the normal poisoned pawn lines (without h6 and h4) I can only find one small difference (but possibly I've missed something).} (7... Qb6 8. Qd2 (8. Qd3 $5) (8. a3 Nc6 {is much better for Black now that there is no f2.}) 8... Qxb2 9. Rb1 Qa3 10. e5 (10. f5 {is one option that is unique to this move order.}) 10... h6 {leads to the same position described after 9.d2. I'm still not much wiser as to why Black prefers h6 to the direct ...b6.}) 8. Bh4 Qb6 {This move is played in many Sicilian scenarios, with the idea of luring White to place d4 on a more passive square. White is not in the habit of cooperating.} 9. a3 {This is the latest fashion.} (9. Qd2 Qxb2 10. Rb1 Qa3 11. e5 dxe5 12. fxe5 {If you go down the rabbit hole, you will be likely to meet something like} Nfd7 13. Ne4 Qxa2 14. Rd1 Qd5 15. Qe3 Qxe5 16. Be2 Bc5 17. Bg3 Qd5 18. c4 Bxd4 19. Rxd4 Qa5+ 20. Rd2 O-O 21. Bd6 f5 22. Bxf8 Nxf8 23. Nd6 Nbd7 {where Black is currently doing all right. Wei Yi has tried this twice with White, with no success.}) ({After} 9. Qd3 Qxb2 10. Rb1 Qa3 {I get the feeling that ...h6/h4 favours Black somewhat.}) ({Without ...h6/h4, White could consider} 9. Nb3 {, although it would be a terribly passive move. Here it is just bad because of} Qe3+ {winning a pawn.}) 9... Nbd7 {This is a first step off the most trodden paths, and a step that I like.} ({The normal} 9... Be7 {almost forces White to play} 10. Bf2 {, when} Qc7 11. Qf3 Nbd7 12. O-O-O b5 13. g4 {featured in three absolute top games in 2016. The last game saw:} Bb7 14. Bg2 Rc8 15. Kb1 g5 16. Qh3 Nc5 17. Rhe1 h5 18. Nf5 $1 Ncxe4 19. Bxe4 Nxe4 20. Bd4 {Nakamura,H (2775)-Vachier Lagrave,M (2800) 8th London Classic 2016, with a huge attack for White. It has been clear since then that Black needed to find an improvement.}) (9... Nc6 10. Bf2 {with splendid chances for White, is the main difference to the usual poisoned pawn lines (7...b6).}) (9... Qxb2 10. Na4 {and as we all know; the knight on the rim is dim.}) 10. Be2 {This move doesn't quite fit with the usual narrative of "queen goes to f3, long castle, g4, bam!", but it isn't obviously wrong. I'm very curious as to how far Wei Yi's preparation stretched. When I read his comments, I get the feeling that he has an exceptional "feeling" for what goes on in the Najdorf and that his preparations are more conceptual than they are detailed.} ({After} 10. Bf2 Qc7 11. Qf3 {, hoping for 11...e7, Black can instead play} b5 {, which seems a bit more active.}) (10. Bc4 {Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'Arsovic,Goran: '- 117/79''} e5 $5) 10... e5 {Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'Arsovic,Goran: 'N'' As far as I can tell, this is a novelty.} ({However, now that the queen's route to f3 is obstructed, it is again possible to play} 10... Be7 11. Bf2 Qc7 {White should continue with} 12. Bf3 {and then either} g6 ({or} 12... Nb6 {, intending e6-e5, seems possible.})) 11. Nf5 $1 {White's minor pieces start swarming and the knight is on the road towards d5. Still, Black cannot tolerate the knight on f5 and has to kick it towards its goal.} g6 12. Bf2 $5 {This means either a) that Wei Yi has prepared the position deeply and seen that the 12.e3 is less clear than the engines indicate, or b) that he didn't prepare the position and played f2 on instinct. Considering how the game continues and the fact that he spent quite a lot of time on this move, it seems more likely that b) was the case.} ({The engine likes} 12. Ne3 {Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'Arsovic,Goran: '!'' better, intending} Qxe3 (12... Be7 {(Hillarp Persson,Tiger) Arsovic,Goran} 13. Bf2 $1 Qc6 (13... exf4 14. Ned5 Qd8 15. Qd2 Nxd5 (15... g5 16. O-O-O $16) 16. Nxd5 Bh4 17. Qxf4 Bxf2+ 18. Qxf2 Ne5 19. O-O-O $16) 14. Bf3 $14) 13. Bf2 {At first sight it seems that} Ng4 (13... Qxf4 14. g3 {Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'Arsovic,Goran: '+-''} Qxe4 15. Nxe4 Nxe4 16. Bf3 Nxf2 17. Kxf2 h5 {is another possibility, but the bishop on f3 looks strong here.}) 14. Bxe3 Nxe3 15. Qd2 Nxg2+ 16. Kd1 Nxf4 {is fine for Black, but when you evaluate this kind of line you must first of all look for forced lines. Indeed, in this case there is such a one:} 17. Rf1 $1 {Intending xf4. If Black is allowed to solidify his position then the sacrifice will be less effective.} (17. Bc4 $16 {(Hillarp Persson,Tiger) Arsovic,Goran}) 17... Be7 (17... g5 18. Nd5) 18. Rxf4 exf4 19. Nd5 Bd8 20. Qxf4 Ne5 21. c4 {and Black is definitely under pressure. I wonder if Wei Yi considered this line and chose not to enter it?}) 12... Nc5 {Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'Arsovic,Goran: 'Diagram [#]'' After this move we seem to be on a one way road, so if Black is to find an improvement (apart from 10...e7), then this is the place to look for it.} (12... Qc7 $6 13. Ne3 exf4 14. Ned5 $36) (12... Qc6 $5 13. fxe5 dxe5 14. Ne3 Bc5 15. O-O {Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'Arsovic,Goran: '''}) 13. b4 $1 {Being ahead in development, it's the initiative, not the pawns, that count.} gxf5 14. O-O $5 ({There was nothing wrong with} 14. bxc5 {Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'Arsovic,Goran: ''' and it is far from clear that Wei Yi's move is the better one. It keeps things simple and allows for Black to be a bit surprised.} Qc7 {(Hillarp Persson,Tiger) Arsovic,Goran}) 14... Nfxe4 (14... Qc7 {leads to the same position as after 16...c7.} 15. bxc5 {(Hillarp Persson,Tiger) (Arsovic,Goran) - 14.bc5} Nxe4 {Arsovic,Goran} 16. Nxe4) 15. Nxe4 fxe4 16. bxc5 dxc5 (16... Qc7 $1 {Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'Arsovic,Goran: '' Arsovic,Goran: '- 14.bc5''} 17. Qd5 (17. Rb1 $5 Be6 18. Bg4) 17... Qc6 18. Bc4 Be6 19. Qxc6+ bxc6 20. Bxe6 fxe6 21. cxd6 exf4 22. Bd4 Rg8 23. Rxf4 Bxd6 24. Rxe4 {leads to a slightly better endgame for White, but there are other promising alternatives on move 17.} Rg6 {(Hillarp Persson,Tiger) Arsovic,Goran} 25. Be3 $14) 17. fxe5 $6 ({Here} 17. Qd5 {Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'Arsovic,Goran: '!'' was the strongest move. After something like} Bg7 (17... Qe6 {(Hillarp Persson,Tiger) Arsovic,Goran} 18. Qxe4 exf4 19. Qxf4 $1 Bd6 20. Qh4 Be7 21. Qh5 Rg8 22. Rae1 $16) 18. Rad1 Be6 19. Qxe4 exf4 20. Qa4+ Qc6 21. Qxc6+ bxc6 22. Bxc5 {White has good winning chances.} Bf8 {(Hillarp Persson,Tiger) Arsovic,Goran} 23. Bxf8 Rxf8 24. Rxf4 $14) (17. Bh4 Rg8 {is less clear.}) 17... Be6 18. Rb1 Qc6 19. Bg4 {The bishop on e6 is the linchpin of Black's position, so White must challenge it.} b5 ({Black can also consider} 19... Rd8 20. Qe2 Be7 21. Bxe6 fxe6 22. a4 h5 $132) 20. Bh4 $1 {The most active place for the bishop that also opens the route for the rook to f6.} Rg8 $6 ({Black should keep the rook out of f6:} 20... Bg7 $1 21. Bf6 Bxf6 22. Rxf6 Rd8 {is unclear. The queenside structure gives Black some reasons to be optimistic.} 23. Qe2 {(Hillarp Persson,Tiger) Arsovic,Goran} Rg8 (23... h5 $5) 24. Bxe6 (24. Bh3 Rg6 25. Rxg6 fxg6 26. Bxe6 Qxe6 27. Qxe4 Rd4 28. Qa8+ Rd8 $11) 24... fxe6 25. g3 Rd7 26. Rxh6 Kd8 $1 $13) 21. Bxe6 Qxe6 22. Rf6 $1 Qg4 $1 {Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'Arsovic,Goran: 'Diagram [#]''} (22... Qxe5 23. Rxa6 $1 Rc8 24. Rc6 $1 Ra8 25. Qe2 c4 26. a4 {Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'Arsovic,Goran: '!''} Rg6 27. Bf6 {Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'Arsovic,Goran: '!''} Rxf6 28. Rxf6 Rxa4 (28... Qxf6 29. Qxe4+) 29. Rbf1 {is close to winning for White.} (29. Rff1 $16 {(Hillarp Persson,Tiger) Arsovic,Goran})) 23. Qd2 {Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'Arsovic,Goran: '!''} Be7 (23... Qxh4 $2 {(Hillarp Persson,Tiger) Arsovic,Goran} 24. Qd5 Ra7 25. Rd1 $18) 24. Rf4 Qd7 ({Black seeks salvation in exchanges, falls into a trap. A better move was} 24... Qe6 25. Bxe7 Qxe7 26. Rxe4 {Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'Arsovic,Goran: '''} Rg6 {, when White is better, but no more.}) 25. Qxd7+ Kxd7 {Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'Arsovic,Goran: 'Diagram [#]''} 26. e6+ $1 {There's the trap.} ({After} 26. Rxf7 Rae8 {Black is doing very well. For instance:} (26... Rge8 {(Hillarp Persson,Tiger) Arsovic,Goran} 27. Re1 Ke6 28. Rxe7+ Rxe7 29. Bxe7 Kxe7 30. Rxe4 Ke6 $11) 27. c4 e3 28. cxb5 axb5 29. Rxe7+ (29. Rxb5 $2 Kc6 $19) 29... Rxe7 30. Bxe7 Kxe7 31. Rxb5 e2 32. Kf2 (32. Rb1 Ke6) 32... Rxg2+ 33. Ke1 Rxh2 {with equality. With a c-pawn and such a centralised king, Black is happy to enter almost any rook endgame.}) 26... fxe6 (26... Kxe6 $2 27. Rxe4+) 27. Rf7 Rg5 ({A neccessity since} 27... Rae8 28. Rd1+ {loses a piece.}) 28. Rd1+ Ke8 29. Rh7 {Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'Arsovic,Goran: '''} b4 ({Black gets some more chances with} 29... c4 {aiming to pick up the a-pawn for nothing. Still, after} 30. Bxg5 hxg5 31. Kf2 (31. Rh8+ {(Hillarp Persson,Tiger) Arsovic,Goran} Bf8 32. Rf1 Ke7 33. Rg8 $16 e3 34. Rf3 a5 35. Rxe3 $16) 31... Bxa3 32. Ke3 a5 33. Kxe4 a4 34. c3 {Black is struggling to survive but White's advantage is not a comfortable one. Black's pawns look menacing and a small mistake might cost the game.}) 30. a4 (30. Bxg5 $1 {(Hillarp Persson,Tiger) Arsovic,Goran} hxg5 31. Rh6 bxa3 32. Rxe6 $16) 30... c4 31. Bxg5 hxg5 32. Rh8+ Bf8 33. Rf1 Ke7 34. Rh7+ Kd6 35. Rh8 Ke7 36. Rh7+ {White's next few moves are anything but random. The point is that he gets a rook to the c-file, which makes it easier to handle Black's queenside pawns.} Kd6 37. Rhf7 Bh6 38. Rd1+ Ke5 39. Rc7 c3 {Black hopes to be able to make b4-b3 work at some point. The downside is that Black's queenside pawns are robbed of most of their dynamism.} ({Perhaps Nepomniachtchi didn't have enough time to calculate the consequences of} 39... b3 $5 40. Rc5+ Kf4 {After} 41. Rxc4 b2 42. Re1 {Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'Arsovic,Goran: '''} Ke5 43. Rexe4+ Kd6 44. Rcd4+ Ke7 45. Rb4 Bg7) 40. Kf2 g4 (40... Rb8 $5 41. Rc5+ Kf6 42. Ke3 (42. Rb1 $2 Rd8) 42... g4+ 43. Kxe4 b3 44. cxb3 Rxb3 45. g3 {and the engine assures me that White is winning. Still not a problem free situation.}) 41. Rc5+ Kf6 42. Ke2 {Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'Arsovic,Goran: '?!''} (42. Rd4 {(Hillarp Persson,Tiger) Arsovic,Goran} Rb8 43. Rxe4 $16) 42... Rb8 {Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'would again lead to the position where White needs to play' Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'Hillarp Persson,T: 'would again lead to the position where White needs to play''} 43. Rb1 $6 (43. Rd4 {Hillarp Persson,Tiger: '!' '!' '!' '!' '!' '!' Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'Hillarp Persson,T: '!'' Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'Arsovic,Goran: '!' '' Arsovic,Goran: '- 43.Rd4'' was better, although I can symphatise with Wei Yi's handling of the situation. He doesn't risk anything by taking it easy.} a5 {(Hillarp Persson,Tiger) Arsovic,Goran} (43... b3 {(Hillarp Persson,Tiger) Arsovic,Goran} 44. cxb3 Rxb3 45. Rxe4 $16) 44. Rxe4 Rd8 45. Kf2 $16) 43... Rd8 44. Rf1+ Ke7 45. Rc7+ Kd6 46. Rc4 Ke7 $6 (46... Ke5 $1 47. Rd1 Rb8 48. Rc5+ (48. Rb1 {(Hillarp Persson,Tiger) Arsovic,Goran} Rd8 49. Rbxb4 Rd2+ 50. Ke1 Rxc2 51. Rxe4+ Kf5 $13) 48... Kf6 {would again lead to the position where White needs to play} 49. Rd4 $1) 47. Rd1 Rb8 48. Rdd4 b3 49. cxb3 Rxb3 50. Rc7+ (50. Rxe4 {(Hillarp Persson,Tiger) Arsovic,Goran} Rb2+ 51. Kd3 Rxg2 52. Rc6 $16) 50... Kf6 51. Rxe4 Rb2+ 52. Kd3 {White's dream comes true. All of Black's active pawns gets liquidated within the next few moves. In the resulting endgame, the e-pawn is of little consequence, whereas the a4-pawn becomes a hero.} Rd2+ 53. Kxc3 Kf5 54. Re1 Rxg2 55. Rc5+ Kf6 56. Re4 Rxh2 57. Rxg4 a5 {Black is able to save the a-pawn by tactical means, but now he is left with two weaknesses: the a-pawn and the e-pawn.} 58. Kd3 Rd2+ (58... Rh3+ 59. Kc4 Bd2 60. Re4 (60. Kb5 e5) 60... Rc3+ 61. Kb5 Rxc5+ 62. Kxc5 Bb4+ 63. Kc6 Kf5 64. Re2 Bc3 65. Kd6 Bb4+ 66. Kd7 e5 67. Kc6 Ke6 68. Re4 Bd2 69. Kc5 Bb4+ 70. Kc4 Be7 71. Re3 Bb4 72. Rh3 {and the e-pawn will fall.}) 59. Ke4 Re2+ 60. Kf3 Re3+ 61. Kf2 Re5 $2 {This makes matters simple for White.} (61... Ra3 {(Hillarp Persson,Tiger) Arsovic,Goran} 62. Rxa5 Bd2 63. Rb5 $16) 62. Rg6+ {Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'Arsovic,Goran: '!''} Kxg6 63. Rxe5 Bd2 64. Rxe6+ Kf7 65. Re4 {Hillarp Persson,Tiger: 'Arsovic,Goran: '+-''} Kf6 66. Ke2 Bc3 67. Rc4 Be5 (67... Bb4 68. Rxb4 axb4 69. a5) 68. Rc5 Ke6 69. Rxa5 Bc7 70. Rb5 Kd6 71. Kd3 Kc6 72. Kc4 Bb6 73. a5 Ba7 74. a6 Bb6 75. Rb3 1-0


