{It's a tough call whether to cover this game, as by ECO code it falls under 1. d4 d5 territory, but it's been covered in the 'Flank Openings' section previously and also often arises from a Symmetrical English move order. Still I consider it trendy enough to deserve an update.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nb6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Be3 Nc6 {This is definitely Black's best line.} 8. d5 Ne5 9. Bd4 (9. f4 $11 {and Black was entirely safe in 1/2-1/2 (90) Rakhmanov, A (2620) -Dominguez Perez, L (2736) Linares 2015} Ng4 10. Bb5+ Bd7 11. Qxg4 {followed by advancing the queenside pawns holds pretty comfortably.} (11. Bxd7+ Qxd7 12. Bd4) {It's also fine to play} 11... Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 Bxb5) 9... O-O (9... g5 10. h4 h6 11. hxg5 hxg5 12. Bb5+ Kf8 13. Rxh8+ Bxh8 14. f4 Bg4 (14... gxf4 15. Qh5) 15. Be2 (15. Qd2 Nbc4 $11 {is also fine for Black.} {or} 16. Qc2 gxf4 17. Bxc4 Nxc4 18. Bxh8 Ne3 19. Qf2 f6 20. Kd2) 15... Bxe2 16. Ngxe2 gxf4 17. Nxf4 Qd6 18. Qh5 Nd3+ $11 {with a drawn endgame, 1/2-1/2 (35) Wang, Y (2724) -Radjabov, T (2738) Skopje 2015} 19. Nxd3 Bxd4) 10. f4 Ng4 11. Bxg7 {This position has arises in several super-GM games this year. It's obvious that only White can be better, however players such as Leko, Dominguez, Wei and others have been using this system to hold a draw with Black. Here we'll consider White's recent and best attempts to complicate Black's task.} (11. Nf3 c6 (11... Nf6 12. Qd2 (12. a4) 12... e6 13. dxe6 $14 {gives White a stable advantage as he managed to make full use of his kingside majority and avoid the exchange of light-squared bishops.} Bxe6 $5 {also seems reasonable as played in two 2012 games.} 14. O-O-O {is the most popular continuation by a wide margin, but White has failed to make real headway in this line.} c5 15. Be5 Qxd2+ 16. Rxd2 Rfd8 $1 {This is an important move to stop the cramping e5 break:} 17. Bd3 Ng4 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. Re1 Bc4) 12. Bxg7 Kxg7 13. h3 $11 {is just a worse version of the 11...Bb4 line for White.} {The most direct approach is} Nf6 14. dxc6 bxc6 15. Qxd8 Rxd8 {, however Anand showed already that Black is fine by means of the standard} 16. Kf2 $1 c5 {and in 0-1 (50) Van Wely, L (2647)-Anand, V (2792) Monte Carlo 2006 Black could have even refined his move order with} 17. Be2 $1 Bb7 18. Ke3 $11 {, preventing a full penetration down the c-file and just equalising on the spot.} (18. e5) 18... Bxe4 {1/2-1/2 (25) L'Ami, E (2614)-Hera, I (2599) Netherlands 2015} 19. Nxe4 $1 Nbd5+) 11... Kxg7 12. Nf3 $1 {Previously castling was considered almost automatic, but this new wrinkle by the Chinese seems to give White a more durable advantage as now the ...b6/... Bb7 plan (used so effectively after 12.0-0) is prevented.} e6 {Black should play this, as after} ({A couple of days before this game, the quieter} 12... c6 {was tried, but after} 13. Qd4+ (13. h3 $6 {1/2-1/2 (29) Meins, G (2436)-Heimann, A (2557) Biel 2015}) 13... Nf6 14. dxc6 Qxd4 15. Nxd4 bxc6 16. Be2 (16. Nxc6 Bb7 {it's hard to see what Black does other than ...Rb8.}) 16... c5 17. Nb3 c4 18. Na5 (18. Nd2 $11 {the game was quickly drawn, 1/2-1/2 (24) Ni, H  (2696)-Wei, Y (2737) Shenzhen 2015}) 18... Be6 19. O-O-O Rac8) 13. Qd4+ $1 Nf6 {This position has occurred in three 2015 games and is definitely the critical one for the whole variation.} (13... Qf6 14. e5 Qd8 15. d6 (15. h3 Nh6 16. g4 exd5 $11 {and I don't see a way to break down Black's position or even attack his weaknesses.} 17. Bd3) 15... Bd7 16. h3 Nh6 {and drawn, 1/2-1/2 (23) Ponomariov, R (2713)-Dominguez Perez, L (2729) Tsaghkadzor 2015} 17. g4 {also allows} Bc6 18. Be2 Nd5 19. O-O cxd6 20. exd6+ f6 $11 {and Black can hold easily with only one weakness, 1/2-1/2 (31) Deac, B (2460) -Parligras, M (2581) Albena 2015} 21. Nxd5 {is the most obvious move but it hasn't been played yet.} Bxd5 22. Rad1 $5 Qxd6) (13... Kg8 14. h3 Nf6 15. O-O-O exd5 16. exd5 c5 $11 {is pretty robust for the second player.}) 14. O-O-O $5 $146 {The idea of this novelty is to prepare d5 before Black can complete his development.} exd5 15. e5 {Now at least Black's queenside structure is fixed, although it requires some inventive play to exploit that fact.} (15. exd5 Qd6 16. Be2 $11 {is just fine for Black.} (16. g3 Bg4 17. Bg2 Rad8 18. h3) 16... Rd8 17. Rd2 Nbxd5 18. Nxd5 Qc6+ 19. Qc3 $1 $36 {is a very computerish idea to stop ...Rfc8, but it seems extremely effective.} Rxd5 {is again too slow:} 20. Qxc6 bxc6 21. Rc2 Rd6 22. Rd1 $5 {(a very practical continuation, to trade the queenside pawns)} Nd5) 15... Nh5 (15... Ng8 16. h4 $14 {and White retains some pressure, although the endgame can probably be held on Black's part if he is very accurate.} Be6 (16... h5) (16... Bg4 17. h5 gxh5 {and ...Bb5 will be a draw. Even in the worst case scenario of Black losing the a6-pawn, Black should still be able to draw the pawn down endgame of 4v3.} 18. Bd3) 17. Bd3 Nh6 18. h5 Qe7 19. hxg6 $36 {followed by f4, Kf2 and Rb1 also favours White.} hxg6 20. Rxh6 Kxh6 21. f5 gxf5 22. Qf4+) 16. f5 Bxf5 {The most natural move, blocking the b-file.} (16... gxf5 $1 17. Rg1 Qe7 18. g4 fxg4 19. e6+ Qf6 20. Qxg4+ Kh6) 17. g4 c5 $6 {Now Black faces quite real pressure, however it wasn't too late to stop White's main idea and equalise with} 18. Qg1 $1 {A very nice positional continuation, which cements White's advantage as now the b7-pawn will become weak.} Bxg4 19. Qxg4 d4 20. Rg1 Kh8 21. Ne4 Nd5 $6 22. Qg5 $16 {Now White's advantage is unquestionable, and he went on to convert in the game.} (22. Nfg5 Qe7 $11 {and White can't count on more than a symbolic plus here.} 23. Re1 {is another try, to simplify the position down with} h6 24. Bc4 Ne3 25. Rxe3 dxe3 26. Nf3) 22... Qxg5+ 23. Nfxg5 Ne3 24. Rd2 Rae8 25. Nd6 Re7 26. Rf2 Kg7 27. Be2 f6 (27... Rxe5 28. Bxh5) 28. Ngf7 (28. Bxh5 $1 $11 fxg5 $1 29. Rxf8 Kxf8 {is the computer's recommendation, to prevent the Be4-d3 idea played in the game, and only then go ...Bb5. Indeed this completely neutralises White's edge, e.g.}) 28... fxe5 29. Bxh5 e4 30. Bd1 Rexf7 (30... Rd7 31. Re2 Rdxf7 32. Nxf7 $16 {retains a big edge for White, though again Black is probably within the drawing margin objectively.} {or} Rxf7 33. Rxe3 dxe3 34. Re1 Rf2 35. Rxe3 Rxh2 {, although this rook ending looks like a draw after} 36. Rxe4 $1 $14) 31. Nxf7 Rxf7 32. Rxf7+ Kxf7 33. Bc2 Nxc2 34. Kxc2 Kf6 35. Rf1+ Ke6 36. Rf8 h5 37. a4 g5 38. a5 Ke5 {I really like this g3 Semi-Tarrasch for White as the first player takes no real risk yet obtains very real chances for an advantage. I think we'll see more tests of Ding's idea, however with correct play Black can neutralise White's pressure and achieve his goal of holding the draw from a slightly worse ending.} 39. Rf7 {is preferable, but it isn't everyone's first reaction to give up a pawn as such.} e3 40. Rxb7 Ke4 41. Rxa7 1-0


