{It's a tough call whether to cover this game, as by ECO code it falls under 1. d4 d5 territory, but it's been covered in the 'Flank Openings' section previously and also often arises from a Symmetrical English move order. Still I consider it trendy enough to deserve an update.} 1. c4 (1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. g3 {would be a possible move order for 1.d4 and how this system is classified by the ECO codes. Of course} (6. e4 {(which we'll see in two games of this update) is the main move from this move order.})) 1... c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. g3 d5 5. d4 e6 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. Bg2 cxd4 {This is definitely Black's best line.} (7... Be7 8. O-O O-O {gives White a small edge with} 9. e4 $1 (9. Nxd5 exd5 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. Bg5 {is a risk-free option, but} Qd7 12. Rc1 ({or} 12. Ne1 Re8 $1 13. Nd3 Bb6 14. Re1 Qf5 15. Bf4 Be6 16. Rc1 d4 $1 $11 {when ...Bd5 will give Black sufficient counterplay.}) 12... Bb6 13. Bd2 Qg4 14. e3 Qh5 15. Nh4 Bg4 16. Bf3 Bxf3 17. Qxf3 Qxf3 18. Nxf3 d4 $1 {allowed Black to equalise in 1/2-1/2 (47) Aronian, L (2815) -Radjabov, T (2724) Dubai 2014}) 9... Nb6 (9... Ndb4 $6 {is virtually refuted by} 10. d5 $1 exd5 11. exd5 Nd4 12. Nxd4 cxd4 13. a3 $1 dxc3 14. axb4 Bxb4 15. Qd4 Bd6 16. bxc3 b6 17. Ba3 $1 $16) 10. dxc5 {For some reason this has been the main move in recent practice, but I prefer 10.d5.} ({A simpler route to an advantage is} 10. d5 exd5 11. exd5 Nb4 12. Ne1 c4 $5 13. a3 Na6 14. a4 Nc5 15. a5 Nb3 16. Ra2 Nxc1 17. Qxc1 Nd7 18. Qf4 $14 {as played in an engine game.}) 10... Bxc5 (10... Qxd1 11. Rxd1 Bxc5 12. e5 {transposes.}) 11. e5 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 Be7 $1 (12... Nc4 {is well met by} 13. Na4 $1 Be7 14. Bf4 f6 15. Rac1 N4xe5 16. Nxe5 Nxe5 17. Bxe5 fxe5 18. Nc5 Rd8 19. Rxd8+ Bxd8 20. Bxb7 Bxb7 21. Nxb7 Bb6 22. Nd6 $16 {with a permanent endgame advantage in 1-0 (50) De Carlos Arregui, I (2402) -Sedlacek, P (2478) ICCF email 2004}) 13. b3 (13. Bf4 $5 Bd7 14. Rac1 h6 15. Ne4 Nd5 16. Be3 {with the idea of Bc5 is a direct and very interesting alternative that might give White a tiny edge after} b6 $1 17. Nc3 Rac8 18. Nxd5 exd5 19. Rxd5 Be6 20. Rd3 Nb4 21. Rdd1 Bxa2 22. Nd4 $14) 13... Bd7 14. Bb2 ({Vuckovic gives} 14. Ne4 Rfd8 15. Nd6 Bxd6 16. exd6 Nd5 17. a4 $11 {as the best try, though I can't really see how White can realistically hope to break Black's light-squared blockade.}) 14... Rfd8 15. Rac1 Be8 16. h4 h6 17. Nb5 {and in 1/2-1/2 (34) Huzman, A (2580)-Almasi, Z (2689) Berlin 2015,} Rxd1+ 18. Rxd1 Nd5 $11 {was the easiest way to maintain equality.}) 8. Nxd4 Nxc3 9. bxc3 Nxd4 10. Qxd4 Qxd4 11. cxd4 {This position has arises in several super-GM games this year. It's obvious that only White can be better, however players such as Leko, Dominguez, Wei and others have been using this system to hold a draw with Black. Here we'll consider White's recent and best attempts to complicate Black's task.} Bd6 (11... Bb4+ {is not so trendy any more, because of} 12. Bd2 Bxd2+ 13. Kxd2 Ke7 14. Rhc1 Rd8 15. Rc7+ $1 (15. Rc4 {gives Black time to hold his position with} Rd6 16. Rac1 Kd8 17. e3 ({or} 17. Ke3 Rb8 18. g4 h6 19. h4 f6 20. g5 Bd7 21. gxh6 gxh6 $11 {1/2-1/2 (24) Rapport, R (2547) -Teske, H (2547) Germany 2012}) 17... Rb8 18. Rc7 Rd7 19. Rxd7+ Bxd7 20. f4 b6 21. Be4 h6 22. h4 Rc8 23. Rxc8+ Bxc8 $11 {and with no weaknesses to speak of, Black drew effortlessly in 1/2-1/2 (31) Salgado Lopez, I (2622)-Hansen, E  (2577) Doha 2014}) 15... Rd7 16. Rac1 Kd8 17. Rxd7+ Kxd7 18. g4 $1 {This is an important move to fix Black's kingside pawns, otherwise Black would draw without much difficulty.} (18. Rc5 Rb8 19. Ra5 a6 20. Rh5 h6 21. g4 {transposes to 18.g4.}) 18... h6 19. h4 $1 (19. Rc5 Rb8 20. Ra5 a6 21. Rh5 Kd6 {is completely safe for Black as demonstrated in two elite games:} 22. g5 hxg5 23. Rh7 ({or} 23. Rh8 g4 24. Rg8 g6 25. f3 gxf3 26. Bxf3 b5 $11 {1/2-1/2 (39) Gelfand, B (2773)-Leko, P (2737) Beijing 2013}) 23... Bd7 24. Rxg7 f6 25. e4 Bc6 26. Rf7 Rh8 27. Rxf6 Rxh2 $11 {and this was hard to be anything other than a draw, 1/2-1/2 (52) Fridman, D (2629) -Meier, G (2610) Dortmund 2013}) 19... Rb8 20. f4 b6 21. Bc6+ {Black is really suffering in such a position, with no space and passive pieces.} Kd8 (21... Ke7 $5 22. e4 Bd7 23. h5 f6 24. Bxd7 Kxd7 {was an attempted improvement in 1/2-1/2 (39) Fressinet, L (2712)-Radjabov, T  (2717) Bilbao 2014, but here} 25. Ke3 $1 b5 26. f5 exf5 27. gxf5 $16 {with the idea of e5 to follow would be very tough for Black to defend (although perhaps he can do so with best play).}) 22. e4 Bd7 23. Bxd7 $1 (23. h5 b5 $6 ({It was later determined that} 23... Rc8 $1 {allows Black to barely scrape a draw with} 24. Bxd7 Rxc1 25. Kxc1 Kxd7 26. e5 Ke7 27. Kd2 f6 28. Kc3 fxe5 29. dxe5 Kf7 30. f5 Ke7 31. Kd4 a6 32. Ke4 Kf7 33. Kf4 Ke7 34. g5 exf5 35. Kxf5 b5 36. gxh6 gxh6 37. Kg6 a5 38. Kxh6 b4 39. Kg7 a4 40. h6 b3 41. axb3 axb3 42. h7 b2 43. h8=Q b1=Q $11 {with a theoretically drawn endgame. However, who would volunteer to go for this?}) 24. Bxd7 Kxd7 25. Rc5 $1 Rb6 26. Kc3 a5 27. e5 $16 g6 $2 {A blunder, but if Black sat and waited White would play f5 and the squeeze would continue, with good chances for success in practice.} 28. hxg6 fxg6 {and in 1-0 (37) Gelfand, B (2759)-Leko, P (2731) Moscow 2014, White could have just won with} 29. d5 b4+ 30. Kd4 $18 {ignoring Black's counterplay.}) 23... Kxd7 24. h5 Rb7 $6 ({Black needs to hurry with} 24... a5 25. a3 g6 26. hxg6 fxg6 $14 {when he should be able to defend.}) (24... Rc8 $2 {doesn't work now because of} 25. Rxc8 Kxc8 26. f5 Kd8 27. e5 Ke7 28. Ke3 f6 29. Kf4 fxe5+ 30. Kxe5 $1 exf5 31. gxf5 Kd7 32. Kd5 a6 33. a3 b5 34. Kc5 Kc7 35. d5 Kd7 36. Kb6 $18) 25. f5 Rb8 26. e5 b5 27. Rc5 Rb6 28. Kd3 $16 {1-0 (33) Ribli, Z (2560) -Szabo, B (2414) Hungary 2014}) 12. a4 $1 {Previously castling was considered almost automatic, but this new wrinkle by the Chinese seems to give White a more durable advantage as now the ...b6/... Bb7 plan (used so effectively after 12.0-0) is prevented.} (12. Bf4 $6 {1/2-1/2 (29) Meins, G (2436)-Heimann, A (2557) Biel 2015} Bxf4 13. gxf4 Rb8 14. Kd2 b6 $11 {is just a worse version of the 11...Bb4 line for White.}) ({The most direct approach is} 12. e4 Rb8 (12... e5 $5 {also seems reasonable as played in two 2012 games.}) 13. e5 Be7 14. Be3 {, however Anand showed already that Black is fine by means of the standard} b6 $1 (14... Bd7 {1/2-1/2 (25) L'Ami, E (2614)-Hera, I (2599) Netherlands 2015} 15. Rb1 $1 b6 16. Rc1 Kd8 17. O-O Rc8 18. d5 $14 {gives White a stable advantage as he managed to make full use of his kingside majority and avoid the exchange of light-squared bishops.}) 15. Rc1 {and in 0-1 (50) Van Wely, L (2647)-Anand, V (2792) Monte Carlo 2006 Black could have even refined his move order with} Kd8 $1 16. O-O Bb7 $11 {, preventing a full penetration down the c-file and just equalising on the spot.}) (12. O-O {is the most popular continuation by a wide margin, but White has failed to make real headway in this line.} Rb8 13. e4 b6 ({Even the} 13... Bd7 $5 {of 0-1 (53) Diermair, A (2494)-Korpa, B (2432) Zillertal 2015 is quite reasonable, as} 14. e5 Bc7 15. Rb1 Bc6 16. Bxc6+ bxc6 17. Rxb8+ Bxb8 $11 {followed by ...Bc7-b6 and ...Kd7 proves virtually impregnable.}) 14. Bb2 f6 $1 {This is an important move to stop the cramping e5 break:} (14... O-O 15. e5 $1 Bb4 16. Rfc1 Bb7 $2 (16... b5 {was necessary, but White retains some winning chances with} 17. a3 Ba5 18. d5 $1 exd5 19. Bd4 Be6 20. Bxa7 Rbc8 21. Rd1 $14) 17. Rc7 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 Ra8 19. Rac1 Rfe8 20. Kf3 Bf8 21. Rb7 Re7 22. Rxe7 Bxe7 23. Rc7 Bf8 24. a4 a5 25. Ke4 Rb8 26. Bc3 $16 {and Black was totally tied up in 1-0 (48) Bu, X (2695)-Vitiugov, N (2734) Ningbo 2015, a model game from White's perspective.}) (14... Bb7 15. Rfc1 $1 f6 {as played in 1-0 (33) Radjabov, T (2734)-Leko, P (2723) Beijing 2014 is a less accurate move order as it permits} 16. e5 Bxg2 17. exd6 Bd5 18. Rc7 O-O 19. Rac1 Rbd8 20. Rxa7 Rf7 21. Rxf7 Kxf7 22. Rc7+ Kg6 23. Ba3 $14 {and while the opposite-coloured bishops should give Black a draw with best play, Black suffers a long defence for the half point.}) 15. Rac1 (15. f4 Bb7 16. e5 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Be7 18. Rac1 Kd7 19. d5 $5 {was an earlier try to make use of White's temporary initiative, but Black held it off with} exd5 20. e6+ Kxe6 21. Rc7 Bc5 22. Re1+ Kd6 23. Ree7 d4 24. Bxd4 Bxd4 25. Red7+ Ke6 26. Rxd4 Rbd8 $11 {1/2-1/2 (40) Bu, X (2675) -Edouard, R (2587) Biel 2011}) 15... Bb7 16. Rfd1 ({A model game from Black's perspective was} 16. f4 $6 Kd7 17. e5 Be7 18. Rfd1 Bxg2 19. Kxg2 Rhc8 20. d5 Rxc1 21. dxe6+ Kxe6 22. Rxc1 Bc5 23. exf6 gxf6 $11 {with an equal endgame in 0-1 (60) Svane, R (2543)-Svidler, P (2727) Skopje 2015, although White continued to play over-aggressively and even lost.}) 16... Kd7 ({It's also fine to play} 16... Ke7 17. f4 Rhc8 18. e5 fxe5 19. fxe5 Bb4 20. Rxc8 Bxc8 21. Be4 g6 $11 {when White was unable to make a hint of progress in 1/2-1/2 (85) Karjakin, S (2753) -Caruana, F (2803) Khanty-Mansiysk 2015}) 17. d5 ({or} 17. e5 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 Be7 19. d5 Rhc8 20. exf6 (20. d6 Bd8 21. f4 b5 {followed by advancing the queenside pawns holds pretty comfortably.}) 20... gxf6 21. dxe6+ Kxe6 22. Re1+ Kf7 $11 {and Black was entirely safe in 1/2-1/2 (90) Rakhmanov, A (2620) -Dominguez Perez, L (2736) Linares 2015}) 17... exd5 18. exd5 Ke7 19. Rc3 (19. Rc4 Rhc8 20. Ra4 a5 $11 {is also fine for Black.}) 19... Rhd8 20. Ba3 Rbc8 21. Re1+ Kf8 22. Rxc8 Bxc8 23. Bxd6+ Rxd6 24. Rc1 Bb7 25. Rc7 Bxd5 26. Bxd5 Rxd5 27. Rxa7 b5 $11 {with a drawn endgame, 1/2-1/2 (35) Wang, Y (2724) -Radjabov, T (2738) Skopje 2015}) 12... Rb8 {Black should play this, as after} (12... Ke7 13. a5 {it's hard to see what Black does other than ...Rb8.}) 13. a5 $1 ({A couple of days before this game, the quieter} 13. Ba3 {was tried, but after} Ke7 14. Bxd6+ Kxd6 15. Kd2 Bd7 16. Rhb1 b6 17. e4 f6 18. a5 bxa5 19. Rxb8 Rxb8 20. Rxa5 Rb2+ $11 {the game was quickly drawn, 1/2-1/2 (24) Ni, H  (2696)-Wei, Y (2737) Shenzhen 2015}) 13... Bd7 {This position has occurred in three 2015 games and is definitely the critical one for the whole variation.} 14. Be3 $5 $146 {The idea of this novelty is to prepare d5 before Black can complete his development.} (14. Ba3 {is again too slow:} Ke7 15. Kd2 Rhc8 16. Rhb1 b5 $5 {(a very practical continuation, to trade the queenside pawns)} 17. axb6 Rxb6 18. Be4 Rxb1 19. Bxb1 Rc4 20. Bxd6+ Kxd6 21. Rxa7 Rxd4+ 22. Ke3 Rd5 23. Be4 {and drawn, 1/2-1/2 (23) Ponomariov, R (2713)-Dominguez Perez, L (2729) Tsaghkadzor 2015}) (14. Rb1 {also allows} b5 15. axb6 Rxb6 16. Rxb6 axb6 17. Bd2 Ke7 $11 {and Black can hold easily with only one weakness, 1/2-1/2 (31) Deac, B (2460) -Parligras, M (2581) Albena 2015}) (14. O-O {is the most obvious move but it hasn't been played yet.} Bb5 15. d5 $5 (15. Re1 O-O 16. Be3 a6 17. d5 exd5 18. Bxd5 Rfe8 $11 {is pretty robust for the second player.}) 15... e5 16. Ra2 Rc8 17. Be3 a6 $11 {and I don't see a way to break down Black's position or even attack his weaknesses.}) 14... a6 (14... b5 15. axb6 axb6 16. Ra7 Ke7 17. Bb7 $1 $36 {is a very computerish idea to stop ...Rfc8, but it seems extremely effective.}) 15. d5 {Now at least Black's queenside structure is fixed, although it requires some inventive play to exploit that fact.} (15. O-O Bb5 16. Ra2 O-O $11 {is just fine for Black.}) 15... e5 (15... Bb4+ {is another try, to simplify the position down with} 16. Kf1 Bc3 17. Ra3 (17. Rb1 exd5 18. Bxd5 Bxa5 19. Bf4 Rd8 20. Bxb7 Bh3+ 21. Bg2 Bd7 {and ...Bb5 will be a draw. Even in the worst case scenario of Black losing the a6-pawn, Black should still be able to draw the pawn down endgame of 4v3.}) 17... Bb4 18. Ra2 O-O (18... exd5 19. Bxd5 Bh3+ 20. Bg2 Be6 21. Ra4 $36 {followed by f4, Kf2 and Rb1 also favours White.}) 19. f4 $1 exd5 20. Bxd5 Bc6 21. Bxc6 bxc6 22. Bb6 Rfc8 23. Kg2 c5 24. Rc1 $14 {and White retains some pressure, although the endgame can probably be held on Black's part if he is very accurate.}) 16. Rb1 Bb5 {The most natural move, blocking the b-file.} (16... f5 $1 17. Kd2 g6 {is the computer's recommendation, to prevent the Be4-d3 idea played in the game, and only then go ...Bb5. Indeed this completely neutralises White's edge, e.g.} 18. Bb6 Rc8 19. e4 Rf8 $11 {and White can't count on more than a symbolic plus here.}) 17. Kd2 Ke7 $6 {Now Black faces quite real pressure, however it wasn't too late to stop White's main idea and equalise with} (17... f5 $1 $11) 18. Be4 $1 {A very nice positional continuation, which cements White's advantage as now the b7-pawn will become weak.} Bc7 (18... Rhc8 19. Bd3 Bc7 20. Bc5+ Kd8 21. Bb4 ({or} 21. Bxb5 Bxa5+ 22. Bb4 Bxb4+ 23. Rxb4 axb5 24. Rxb5 {, although this rook ending looks like a draw after} Rc4 $1 $14) 21... Bxd3 22. Kxd3 $16 {retains a big edge for White, though again Black is probably within the drawing margin objectively.}) 19. Bc5+ Bd6 20. Bb6 Rbc8 21. Bd3 Bxd3 $6 (21... Bc5 {is preferable, but it isn't everyone's first reaction to give up a pawn as such.}) 22. Kxd3 $16 {Now White's advantage is unquestionable, and he went on to convert in the game.} f5 23. f3 Rhf8 24. Rb3 Rf7 25. Rhb1 Ke8 26. Ba7 Rcc7 27. Bb8 Rc5 28. Bxd6 Rxd5+ 29. Kc4 Rxd6 30. Rxb7 Rd2 31. Rb8+ Ke7 32. R1b6 Rf6 33. R8b7+ Kf8 34. Ra7 Rc2+ 35. Kb3 Rfc6 36. Rb8+ Rc8 37. Rxc8+ Rxc8 38. Rxa6 Ke7 {I really like this g3 Semi-Tarrasch for White as the first player takes no real risk yet obtains very real chances for an advantage. I think we'll see more tests of Ding's idea, however with correct play Black can neutralise White's pressure and achieve his goal of holding the draw from a slightly worse ending.} 1-0


