1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 Be7 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O Nbd7 8. Qc2 c6 9. Bg5 {Not a very common move, but of course it is quite natural to develop like this, even if trading the bishop for the knight somehow doesn't appeal to my positional instincts.} (9. Rd1 {is the normal line, and I also covered Carlsen's}) (9. a4 {recently.}) 9... b6 (9... h6 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. Nbd2 b6 (11... a5 $6 12. e4 b5 13. c5 $14) 12. e4 Bb7 13. e5 Be7 {transposes to the 12.e5 note in the game.}) 10. Nbd2 h6 (10... Bb7 11. e4 dxe4 (11... c5 $5 12. exd5 exd5 13. Rad1 Rc8 14. dxc5 Nxc5 $11 {followed by ...Ne6 provides quite straightforward equality.}) 12. Nxe4 c5 13. Nxf6+ Nxf6 $1 (13... Bxf6 14. Bxf6 Nxf6 15. dxc5 bxc5 {Black should not be fooled by the engine's assessment of equality - such positions with the extra pawn island are a lot easier for White to play and in principle I would rather avoid them.} 16. Ne5 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Qc7 18. Qe2 Rfd8 19. Rfd1 $14 {The quoted game is a nice example of how to grind out a win from such positions in practice.} h6 20. Nf3 Rab8 21. Rxd8+ Rxd8 22. Rd1 Rxd1 23. Qxd1 Nd7 24. b3 Ne5 25. Nxe5 Qxe5 26. Qd8+ Kh7 27. Qa8 Qc7 28. Qe4+ g6 29. h4 Kg7 30. a3 a5 31. Kf3 Qb6 32. Qe5+ f6 33. Qe3 h5 34. Ke2 e5 35. Qd3 f5 36. Qd7+ Kh6 37. Qe8 Qf6 38. Qa8 g5 39. hxg5+ Kxg5 40. Qxa5 f4 41. Qxc5 h4 42. gxh4+ Kxh4 43. Qd5 Qf5 44. Qd8+ Kh5 45. Qd3 Qe6 46. b4 Kh4 47. b5 e4 48. Qd4 Qg4+ 49. Kd2 Qf3 50. b6 Kh3 51. b7 e3+ 52. fxe3 Qxb7 53. exf4 Kg4 54. Kc3 Qa6 55. f5+ Kxf5 56. Qd5+ Kf4 57. Kb4 Qb6+ 58. Qb5 Qd6+ {1-0 (58) Baburin,A (2598)-Orr,M (2315) Belfast 2001})) 11. Bxf6 Nxf6 12. Ne5 $5 {This is quite a valid attempt, considering that White didn't do too well with e4-e5 ideas previously.} (12. e4 Bb7 13. e5 Nd7 14. cxd5 cxd5 {This position has been seen a lot, with Black scoring very well as compared to the standard Closed Catalan line, Black has one less minor piece bottled in and the bishop pair to boot.} 15. Rfc1 (15. Rfe1 b5 $5 {I would have been a simpleton and played ...Rc8, but this is good too.} 16. Bf1 Qb6 17. Bd3 Rfc8 18. Qb3 b4 19. Rad1 a5 20. Bb1 a4 $15 {By this point it is obvious who possesses the initiative.} 21. Qd3 Nf8 {In such positions, White really needs the dark-squared bishop for Bxh6 breakthroughs.} 22. h4 a3 23. b3 Rc3 24. Qf1 Rac8 25. g4 Ba6 26. Qg2 Bd3 27. h5 Bxb1 28. Nxb1 Rc2 29. g5 hxg5 30. Nxg5 Bxg5 31. Qxg5 Qd8 32. Qg4 Nh7 33. f4 Rxa2 34. Rd3 Rac2 35. Rg3 Qf8 36. f5 exf5 37. Qxf5 Rc1 38. Qf1 a2 39. Rxc1 Rxc1 40. Qxc1 a1=Q 41. Rg4 Qa6 42. Qc2 Qfc8 43. Qg2 Qc1+ 44. Kh2 Qah6 45. Rh4 Qxb1 46. Qxd5 Qd2+ {0-1 (46) Li,C (2751)-Tomashevsky, E (2728) Huaian 2016}) 15... Rc8 16. Qa4 a6 17. Qd1 Bc6 18. a3 b5 19. Ne1 a5 20. Nd3 a4 21. Rc2 Nb6 22. Rac1 Nc4 $15 {Black was better as he simply has control on the queenside and, being a correspondence game, he went on to win a model game.} 23. Nf3 Qa5 24. Qe2 b4 25. axb4 Bxb4 26. Bf1 Be7 27. Qe1 Qb6 28. Bg2 Rb8 29. Bf1 Bb5 30. Qc3 Na5 31. Nc5 Qa7 32. Bxb5 Rxb5 33. Nd3 Nb3 34. Rd1 Rfb8 35. Kg2 Bd8 36. Nf4 Qb7 37. Nd3 g5 38. h3 Ba5 39. Qc6 Qxc6 40. Rxc6 Bb6 41. g4 Ra8 42. h4 gxh4 43. Nxh4 Nxd4 44. Rc3 Rb3 45. Rxb3 Nxb3 46. Nf3 Kg7 47. Kg3 Rc8 48. Nfe1 Bd4 49. Rb1 Rb8 50. Rd1 Nc5 51. Nxc5 Bxc5 52. Ra1 Rxb2 53. Nd3 Rb3 54. Rd1 a3 {0-1 (54) Johnsen,K (2470)-Kuosa,N (2573) ICCF email 2008}) 12... Bb7 13. Rfd1 (13. cxd5 cxd5 14. Rfc1 $11 {is a rather meek play for equality, but White would probably succeed in such a modest goal here.}) 13... Rc8 14. c5 $6 (14. Rac1 c5 {is completely fine for Black, but it was probably a better choice.}) 14... bxc5 15. dxc5 Qc7 (15... h5 {is the engine's suggestion, going for ...Ng4. I believe it when it claims Black is better, but it's a very strange idea!}) 16. f4 {This position makes a nice puzzle from Black's perspective.} a5 $1 {Black is stopping the advance of White's queenside majority, and also preparing ...Ba6 to activate his b7-bishop in certain positions.} (16... Rfd8 17. b4 $11) 17. Nb3 a4 {Black is going for forcing play, but he has the central majority and bishop pair, so he can and probably should have been more patient.} (17... Rfd8 18. Rab1 Nd7 19. Nxd7 Rxd7 $15) 18. Nd4 Nd7 19. Nxd7 Qxd7 20. e4 Ra8 21. Qc3 Qc7 22. b4 axb3 23. axb3 Rxa1 24. Rxa1 dxe4 25. Ra7 $2 (25. Bxe4 Bf6 26. Ra4 Rd8 27. Qe3 e5 28. Nf5 (28. fxe5 Qxe5 $17) 28... exf4 29. Qxf4 Be5 $15) 25... Qd7 $1 $19 26. Qc4 Rd8 27. Bxe4 Qxd4+ 28. Qxd4 Rxd4 29. Rxb7 Bxc5 30. Rb8+ Rd8+ 0-1


