1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 d6 5. O-O Be7 6. c3 O-O 7. Nbd2 (7. Re1 {will be examined in the next game.}) (7. h3 $5 {is an interesting attempt to keep White's options open.} Bd7 ({Those with both 3...Nf6 and 3...a6 in their repertoire might opt for} 7... a6 8. Ba4 {, transposing to the 3...a6 4.a4 f6 5.0-0 e7 6.d3 d6 7.c3 0-0 variation where White should play 8.e1 instead of 8.h3. Black can exploit this by proceeding} b5 9. Bc2 d5 10. Nbd2 dxe4 11. dxe4 Be6 12. Ng5 Bd7 13. Qe2 Bd6 14. Rd1 Ne7 15. Nf1 h6 16. Nf3 Ng6 17. Ng3 Re8 $11 {; naturally a deeper analysis would be outside the scope of this article.}) 8. Be3 $5 {This move, first played in 1882 (!) has been seen in various engine games, with the point that bd2 will no longer block in the bishop.} ({White tried an original approach with} 8. Ba4 Re8 9. Nbd2 Bf8 10. Nc4 $5 h6 11. Re1 Ne7 12. Bc2 Ng6 13. a4 c6 $11 {in ½-½ (32) Rozentalis,E (2622)-Babula,V (2584) Austria 2013, but without disrupting the equilibrium.}) 8... a6 (8... h6 9. Nbd2 Nh7 10. Ba4 Ng5 11. d4 $14 {is good for White because of his space advantage.}) 9. Ba4 b5 ({After} 9... Qe8 10. Nbd2 Nd4 11. cxd4 Bxa4 12. Qc1 exd4 13. Nxd4 c5 14. Nf5 Bd7 15. Nxe7+ Qxe7 16. a4 $14 {[%csl Ye3] White has a small edge because of his central majority and slightly better bishop.}) (9... h6 10. Nbd2 Re8 11. a3 Bf8 12. b4 Ne7 13. Bc2 Ng6 14. d4 {also gives White chances for an advantage due to his extra space in the centre.}) 10. Bc2 d5 11. Nbd2 Be6 (11... h6 $6 12. d4 $1 exd4 13. cxd4 dxe4 14. Nxe4 Nd5 15. Rc1 $14 {[%csl Rc5,Rc6,Rc7] favours White due to Black's hugely weakening ...b5.}) 12. Rc1 (12. d4 exd4 13. cxd4 dxe4 14. Nxe4 Bd5 $11 {is now fine for Black as his pieces are very active compared to the 11...h6 variation.}) 12... h6 (12... dxe4 13. dxe4 Qc8 14. Nh4 g6 15. Qe2 Rd8 16. Rfd1 Rb8 17. Nhf3 $14 {[%csl Rc5,Rd5] gives White some pressure based on g5/b3 and the weakness of the d5 and c5 squares.}) 13. d4 exd4 14. Nxd4 ({Less effective is} 14. cxd4 dxe4 15. Nxe4 Nb4 $11 {[%csl Ra2]}) 14... Nxd4 15. cxd4 dxe4 16. Nxe4 {White has some chances for an edge here based on Black's weak queenside, but} Re8 $1 (16... Nd5 17. Bd2 Nb4 18. Bxb4 Bxb4 19. Qd3 Bf5 20. Rfd1 {might objectively be OK for Black, but White's position feels very harmonious and a lot easier to play.}) 17. Nxf6+ Bxf6 18. Qd3 g6 19. Bb3 Bxb3 20. Qxb3 Qd7 21. Rfd1 Rad8 22. Qc2 Qe6 $1 $11 {more or less neutralises White's pressure. Even so, I would not be surprised if we see 8.e3 in subsequent high-level practice.}) 7... Bd7 (7... a6 8. Ba4 {again transposes to the Morphy Ruy Lopez lines with d3, which however are not our subject.}) (7... Nd7 8. d4 Bf6 {has been a trendy alternative, exerting pressure on White's centre as such.} 9. Nb3 (9. Nc4 exd4 10. cxd4 d5 11. exd5 Nb4 12. Nce5 Nxd5 13. Bd3 Re8 {was demonstrably robust after the possible continuation} 14. Re1 c6 15. Bd2 Nf8 16. Qc2 Be6 17. b4 Nc7 18. a4 a6 19. h3 $11 {½-½ (19) Smirin,I (2670)-Howell,D (2633) Porto Carras 2011}) 9... a6 10. Be2 (10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. Na5 Qe8 $1 12. Re1 c5 13. d5 Nb6 {[%cal Yf6d8,Yf7f5] followed by ...d8 and ...f5 is quite harmonious for Black.}) (10. Bd3 $5 {might be the best try, but then Black can play} a5 $5 11. Be3 a4 12. Nbd2 a3 13. b3 exd4 14. Nxd4 Re8 15. Rc1 Nde5 16. Nxc6 bxc6 17. Be2 c5 18. f4 Ng6 $132 {[%cal Yc8b7] with persistent counterplay against White's centre, though the engine does give a marginal preference to White.}) 10... exd4 11. cxd4 (11. Nfxd4 $142 $11) 11... Re8 12. Qc2 {0-1 (56) Kotronias,V (2564)-Harikrishna,P (2726) Porto Rio 2014} Nb4 13. Qb1 Qe7 {[%cal Yc7c5] would be quite promising for Black, intending} 14. Re1 Qxe4 $5 15. Bf1 Qxe1 16. Nxe1 Rxe1 17. a3 Nc6 18. Qd3 Nb6 $44 {with very interesting compensation for the queen.}) 8. Ba4 {We're already familiar with this move in the other variations, and indeed it's an important move here as well to prepare d4 (which would otherwise run into the familiar ...xd4 tactic)} (8. Re1 {will be the feature of the next game.}) (8. a4 {is legal but not overly dangerous; for instance} a6 9. Bc4 Na5 10. Ba2 c5 11. Re1 b5 $11 {is quite a good answer.}) 8... Rb8 $5 {I'm quite drawn to this original approach, although it doesn't fully equalise.} (8... Re8 9. Re1 Bf8 10. Nf1 {would be the standard continuation, and indeed transposes to the next game after} h6 11. Ng3 {.}) 9. Re1 (9. Bc2 $5 {would be interesting to give White more options if Black is consistent with} b5 {. Indeed, something like} 10. d4 {would be a sensible continuation as} exd4 ({or} 10... b4 11. a3 bxc3 12. bxc3 Bg4 13. h3 Bh5 {when the position is somewhere between equal and slightly better for White.}) 11. cxd4 Nb4 12. Bb1 c5 13. e5 $1 dxe5 14. dxe5 Nfd5 15. a3 Nc6 16. Nb3 Nb6 17. Nxc5 $1 {[%cal Rd1c2]} Bg4 18. Nd3 $14 {looks a little better for White based on his extra pawn.}) 9... b5 10. Bc2 b4 ({It's also possible to adopt a waiting strategy with} 10... Re8 11. h3 Bf8 12. Nf1 h6 {, however in this case} 13. d4 $14 {will favour White.}) 11. d4 $1 {The consistent move, meeting flank play with central action.} bxc3 12. bxc3 Re8 (12... exd4 13. cxd4 Nb4 14. Bb1 {illustrates a disadvantage of trading the b-pawns, in that ...c5 is no longer positionally well founded, and after the tricky} Bb5 15. Nf1 c5 16. a3 Nc6 17. Ne3 $14 {consolidates, with advantage.}) 13. d5 $6 {Closing the centre doesn't feel right when Black obtains the c5-square for his pieces.} (13. Nc4 exd4 14. cxd4 d5 15. exd5 Nb4 16. Bb3 Nbxd5 17. Nfe5 Bb4 18. Bd2 Bxd2 19. Qxd2 $16 {with complete positional domination was called for.}) 13... Na5 14. c4 c6 {[%cal Rd2c4] Now Black is not at all worse, as the a5-knight is quite useful in pressuring c4 and stopping the active deployment of the c1-bishop.} 15. Ba3 Bf8 16. Ba4 Qc8 17. Rc1 Qa6 18. c5 dxc5 19. Bxc5 Rbd8 20. Bxf8 Kxf8 21. d6 Bg4 22. h3 Bxf3 23. Nxf3 Nc4 24. Qc2 Nxd6 25. Bxc6 Rc8 26. Qc5 Nfxe4 27. Qd5 Qa3 28. Nxe5 Nf6 29. Qd2 Re6 30. Nd7+ Kg8 31. Rxe6 fxe6 32. Nxf6+ gxf6 33. Rc3 Ne4 34. Qd7 Nxc3 35. Qxc8+ Kg7 36. Qc7+ Kf8 37. Qd8+ Kg7 38. Qc7+ Kf8 39. Qc8+ Kg7 40. Qd7+ Kf8 41. Qd8+ Kg7 42. Kh2 Qc5 43. Qd7+ Kf8 44. Qxe6 Qxf2 45. Qd6+ Kg7 46. Qe7+ Kg8 47. Qe6+ Kg7 48. Qe7+ Kg8 49. Qe6+ Kg7 50. Qd7+ Kh6 51. Qd6 Ne2 52. Qf8+ Kg6 53. Be4+ f5 54. Bxf5+ Kg5 55. Qe7+ Kf4 56. Qd6+ Kg5 57. Qd8+ Kf4 58. Qc7+ Kg5 59. Qg7+ Kf4 60. Qc7+ Kg5 61. Qd8+ Kf4 62. Qd6+ Kg5 63. Qe7+ Kf4 64. Qb4+ Kg5 65. h4+ Qxh4+ 66. Qxh4+ Kxh4 67. Bxh7 Nc3 68. Bg8 a5 69. Be6 a4 70. a3 Nb5 71. Bc4 Nxa3 72. Bd3 Kg4 1/2-1/2


