1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 {This is the main trend against the Nimzo as White hasn't made any headway in the Capablanca, Rubinstein or Kmoch lines.} O-O 5. Bg5 d5 {In general it's not considered the most accurate to castle immediately in the Ragozin.} (5... h6 {falls outside the scope of my column.}) 6. cxd5 (6. e3 c5 7. cxd5 exd5 {may be the most accurate move order, to avoid the next note.} (7... Qxd5 8. Bxf6 gxf6 9. a3 Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 b6 $1 11. Bd3 Bb7 12. O-O Kh8 13. e4 Qd6 14. Qd2 Rg8 15. Qh6 Qe7 16. Rfd1 $14 (16. g3 $5 {also looks promising.}))) 6... exd5 7. e3 c5 (7... h6 8. Bh4 c5 (8... Bf5 $5 {This is probably the best way to justify the early castling. It transposes to the 7...Bf5 Ragozin lines I've covered before, but note that 6.e3 first would have avoided this option.}) 9. dxc5 Nbd7 10. Rc1 Qa5 11. Nd2 {is better for White, who managed to used the tempo spent on ...0-0 to consolidate his position. A recent game went} Qxc5 12. a3 (12. Nb3 $142 Qd6 13. Bd3 $14) 12... Bxc3 13. Rxc3 Qb6 14. Qb3 d4 $1 {A thematic strike for the opening.} 15. Qxb6 Nxb6 16. exd4 Nfd5 17. Rc5 Re8+ 18. Kd1 Bg4+ 19. f3 Ne3+ 20. Kc1 Bd7 $44 (20... Be6 $11) 21. Ne4 Na4 22. Re5 Rac8+ 23. Kd2 Nxf1+ 24. Rxf1 Rxe5 25. dxe5 Nxb2 26. Nd6 Nc4+ 27. Nxc4 Rxc4 28. Be7 Bc6 {1/2-1/2 (28) Wagner,D (2575)-Tari,A  (2521) Berlin 2015}) 8. dxc5 Nbd7 9. Rc1 Qa5 (9... h6 $6 {is too late now:} 10. Bxf6 (10. Bh4 Qa5 11. Nd2 $14 {- see 7...h6.}) 10... Nxf6 11. a3 Bxc3+ 12. Rxc3 Ne4 13. Rc1 Qa5+ 14. Nd2 Bf5 15. Be2 Rfe8 16. f3 Nxc5 17. b4 Qxa3 18. bxc5 Rxe3 19. O-O Rc3 $14) 10. a3 (10. Nd2 $5 Qxc5 11. Nb3 (11. a3 Bxc3 12. Rxc3 Qb6 13. Rb3 Qe6 14. Be2 {also looks good for a tiny edge.}) 11... Qb6 12. Bd3 Ne4 13. Bxe4 dxe4 14. O-O Qg6 15. Bf4 $14) 10... Bxc3+ 11. Rxc3 Ne4 12. b4 Nxc3 13. Qa1 Qa4 14. Qxc3 a5 15. b5 $14 {This line is known to be stupendous for White, so I have no idea why strong players continue to enter it.} Nxc5 (15... h6 16. Bf4 Nf6 17. Nd4 Ne4 18. Qc1 g5 (18... Bd7 19. f3 Ng5 20. Bxg5 hxg5 21. Be2 $16) 19. Bc7 Re8 20. Be2 Bd7 21. O-O $18 Rac8 22. b6 f5 23. Qb2 f4 24. Rc1 Nxf2 25. Kxf2 fxe3+ 26. Ke1 Re4 27. Be5 Be8 28. c6 Rxc6 29. Nxc6 Bxc6 30. Rc5 Rh4 31. Bd1 Qe4 32. Rxc6 d4 33. Qb3+ {1-0 (33) Ding,L (2755)-Liu,Q (2510) China 2015}) 16. Qxc5 Bf5 $2 (16... Bd7 $1 {But this line is a little tricky.} 17. Be2 $5 (17. Qxd5 Be6 18. Qd1 Qxa3 19. Bd3 h6 20. Bf4 Bb3 21. Bd6 Qa4 22. Qb1 Rfd8 23. Bc7 Ba2 24. Qc2 Bb3 25. Qc3 Rxd3 26. Qxd3 Qa1+ 27. Ke2 Qxh1 28. Qxb3 Qc1 $1 $11) (17. Qc1 $1 Rac8 18. Qa1 Bxb5 19. Nd4 Bxf1 20. Rxf1 Rfe8 21. Bf4 Rc4 22. Kd2 Rec8 23. Qb2 $36 {White has full control over the position.}) 17... Rfc8 18. Qxd5 Rc1+ 19. Bd1 Qxb5 20. Qxb5 Bxb5 21. Nd4 Ba4 22. Ke2 Ra1 23. Rf1 Rxa3 24. Bxa4 Rxa4 25. Rb1 $14) 17. Qc3 Rac8 (17... Rfc8 18. Qa1 Qc2 19. Nd4 Qc1+ 20. Qxc1 Rxc1+ 21. Kd2 $18 {It is quite surprising that Nakamura would enter this, clearly he mixed up something in his opening (for instance, the lines with ... h6/Bh4 inserted).} Rac8 22. Nxf5 R8c2+ 23. Kd3 Rxf2 24. Ne7+ Kh8 25. g3 Ra1 26. Kd4 Rc1 27. Bg2 Rd2+ 28. Ke5 f6+ 29. Kd6 Rc3 30. Rf1 h6 31. Rxf6 hxg5 32. Rf8+ Kh7 33. Bh3 g4 34. Bxg4 Rxe3 35. Bf5+ g6 36. Bxg6+ Kg7 37. Rg8+ {1-0 (37) Aronian,L (2792)-Nakamura,H (2787) Leuven 2016}) 18. Qa1 Rc2 {This looks scary but isn't anything.} 19. Nd4 Rfc8 20. Nxc2 Rxc2 21. Be2 $1 $18 Qb3 (21... Rxe2+ 22. Kxe2 Qg4+ 23. Kd2 Qxg5 24. Qe5 $18) 22. Bd1 Bd3 $1 23. e4 {The best of many good moves.} Bxb5 24. Qe5 {Black could have resigned here.} h6 25. Qxd5 Qb1 26. Bd2 $1 Ra2 27. f3 Qb2 28. Bb3 Ra1+ 29. Kf2 Rxh1 30. Qxf7+ Kh7 31. Qf5+ g6 32. Qd5 1-0


