1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 ({The Nimzo-Indian move order is} 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 d5) 3... d5 4. Bg2 Bb4+ 5. Nc3 {In the 4...Bb4+ Catalan, 5 Bd2 is normal and 5 Nbd2 is also played. Transposing to the Nimzo-Indian with 5 Nc3 is relatively rare.} O-O 6. a3 {This move has been played by Mamedyarov on a few occasions, as well as Nakamura, Topalov and Wei Yi on a previous occasion.} ({White's most popular choice here has been} 6. Nf3 {, which offers a Catalan-style gambit. See the notes to Sambuev,B-Wei Yi/ Tbilisi 2017.}) 6... Bxc3+ (6... Be7 {is equally playable.}) 7. bxc3 c6 {A typical idea which allows ...cxd5, a more desirable recapture on d5 if White plays cxd5. Black aims to follow up by putting pressure on the c4-pawn to induce White into the pawn swap.} (7... dxc4 {is the main alternative and is covered in Sadorra, J-Wang Hao/Chengdu 2017.}) 8. Nf3 b6 9. Bg5 Nbd7 {The first new move.} (9... Ba6 10. Bxf6 $5 (10. Ne5) 10... Qxf6 11. Ne5 Bxc4 12. Nxc4 dxc4 13. O-O {with decent compensation for White, Gozzoli,Y-Fressinet,L/ Agen 2016.}) 10. Ne5 Qc7 11. Nxd7 Nxd7 12. Bf4 $1 Qd8 13. cxd5 cxd5 14. c4 $1 {A key move.} ({Delaying the push in favour of} 14. O-O {allows} Ba6 $1 {Black prevents c4 and is fine.}) 14... Bb7 ({Perhaps Black has better options here with} 14... Nf6 $5 {and on the 16th move with ...Bc4.}) 15. cxd5 Bxd5 16. e4 Bb7 (16... Bc4 $5) 17. O-O Nf6 18. Re1 $14 {The bishop pair and the pawn centre give White a pleasant edge.} Qd7 19. g4 $5 {Wei Yi goes for the most aggressive approach, although objectively it might not be the best.} (19. a4 {intending a5}) ({or} 19. Be5 {are logical alternatives to keep the advantage.}) 19... Rfd8 $1 20. g5 Ne8 21. Be5 Nd6 22. Qg4 Kh8 23. Re3 (23. Rac1 Rac8 24. d5 $1 {is still better for White.}) 23... Nc4 $1 24. Rh3 Nxe5 25. Qh5 h6 26. dxe5 Qe7 $1 {Planning to meet 27 gxh6 with 27...g6! when White's h-pawn acts as a useful shield for Black's king. By going 'all in' White has lost his advantage, Black has counterplay and the position is unclear.} 27. Qh4 Rd7 (27... Kg8 $5) 28. Qf4 Rad8 29. Bf3 Rd3 $1 30. Rc1 R8d7 $2 {Zhao misses a chance.} (30... Bxe4 $1 {is strong here. I guess that Wei Yi's intention was} 31. gxh6 (31. Qxe4 $2 Qxg5+) 31... g6 32. Rc7 $1 {but Black has} g5 $1) 31. gxh6 g6 32. Rg3 $1 {Now White has the plan of h4-h5, and the position becomes difficult for Black to defend.} Kh7 (32... Rxa3 $1 33. h4 Kh7 34. h5 Rad3 $1 35. Kh2 Rd8 $1 {intending} 36. Rcg1 Rg8 {and Black is just about hanging on.}) 33. h4 Qf8 $2 {Going after the wrong pawn.} (33... Rxa3 $1 34. h5 Rad3 {as in the previous note, was Black's best chance.}) 34. Kg2 $1 Qxh6 $2 35. Rg5 $1 {Now White's attack will be decisive.} Kg7 36. h5 Rxf3 37. Kxf3 Rd3+ 38. Ke2 Ba6 39. Ke1 Rf3 40. Qxf3 Qxg5 41. Qf6+ 1-0


[Event "FIDE Grand Prix"]
