1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 O-O 5. e3 d5 6. Bd2 {We can now add Wei Yi to the list of 2700+ grandmasters who have been persuaded by Bd2 against the Nimzo.} b6 7. cxd5 exd5 8. Bd3 Bb7 9. Ne5 $5 {Wei Yei plays an early Ne5, which allows White to meet ...Nbd7 with f2-f4 and recapture on e5 with the f-pawn.} (9. O-O) ({and} 9. Rc1 {are the most popular choices.}) 9... Bd6 $1 {Karjakin exploits the delay in Rc1. With a rook on c1, Black would have to prepare ...Bd6 with ...a6 to prevent Nb5, but doesn't need to here.} 10. O-O c5 11. Rc1 (11. Nb5 {doesn't achieve anything. After} Be7 12. Rc1 a6 (12... Nbd7 {also looks okay}) 13. Nc3 Nc6 {we reach a position very similar to one we've previously covered (Ponomariov,R-Yilmaz,M/Douglas 2019), except that Black has gained a useful move in ...a6.}) 11... Nc6 12. Ng4 $1 {The most challenging.} (12. f4 cxd4 $1 13. Nxc6 Bxc6 14. exd4 Re8 {looks fine for Black.} ({or} 14... Qd7)) 12... Nd7 $5 {Engines initially don't like this move because of the tactical possibility chosen by Wei Yi, but in fact the assessment is far from clear.} (12... cxd4 13. exd4 Nxd4 14. Bg5 $1 Be7 15. Bxh7+ $1 Kxh7 16. Qxd4 Nxg4 17. Bxe7 Qxe7 18. Qxg4 {looks a little more comfortable for White.}) ({An earlier high-level encounter continued} 12... Nxg4 13. Qxg4 c4 14. Bb1 Ne7 15. Nb5 ({maybe} 15. Qh3 f5 16. f3 {intending e3-e4 is better}) 15... f5 $1 16. Qe2 a6 (16... Bb8 $5) 17. Nxd6 Qxd6 18. f3 b5 19. Be1 Ng6 {and now a slightly odd repetition ended the game:} 20. Ba5 Ne7 21. Be1 Ng6 (21... a5) (21... b4) 22. Ba5 Ne7 23. Be1 {1/2-1/2 Nakamura,H-Giri,A/ Saint Louis 2019.}) 13. Nh6+ $1 {Not forced (13 Qf3 and 13 f4 are alternatives) but tempting nevertheless. The next few moves are forced.} gxh6 (13... Kh8 14. Qh5 $1) 14. Qg4+ Kh8 15. Qf5 Nf6 16. Nxd5 $1 Nxd4 $1 17. Qxf6+ (17. exd4 $2 Bxd5 18. dxc5 {fails to} Rg8 $1 ({not} 18... Bxc5 $4 19. Bc3 {and White wins}) 19. g3 Be6 $1 $19) 17... Qxf6 18. Nxf6 Nf3+ $1 {Both players continue accurately.} (18... Be5 19. exd4 Bxf6 20. dxc5 {is better for White, as} Rfd8 21. Bc3 $1 {avoids losing a bishop.}) 19. gxf3 Rg8+ $1 20. Ng4 Be5 $1 (20... Bxf3 $4 21. Bc3+) 21. Be2 $1 Bxb2 (21... h5 {is close to equal. After} 22. b4 hxg4 23. fxg4 cxb4 24. Bxb4 {Black has the resource} Ba6 $1) 22. Rxc5 $1 {An excellent choice by Wei Yi.} ({After} 22. Rb1 Bf6 $1 {Black will regain his piece with ...h5 and his queenside pawn majority looks more dangerous than White's on the other side.}) 22... bxc5 23. Rb1 Bg7 24. Rxb7 h5 25. Rxf7 {Wei Yi understandably grabs a second pawn for the exchange, and the resulting position is equal.} ({White could also consider keeping his rook with} 25. Bc4 $5 hxg4 26. fxg4) 25... hxg4 26. fxg4 Rgf8 27. Rxf8+ Rxf8 28. Kf1 (28. Kg2 $5) 28... Rb8 29. Bc4 Rb1+ 30. Ke2 $1 {Wei Yi gives up the h-pawn to centralise his king and sideline the rook.} ({White has to avoid} 30. Kg2 $2 Rd1 31. Ba5 Rc1 $17 {followed by ...c4.}) 30... Rh1 31. Bd5 Rxh2 32. g5 Rh5 33. e4 Bd4 34. Bf4 Kg7 35. e5 Kf8 36. Bf3 Rh4 37. Bg3 Rh3 38. Bg2 Rxg3 {Liquidating to a draw.} (38... Rh5 {keeps the game going, but Black isn't better. After, for example,} 39. f4 c4 40. Be4 c3 41. Kf3 Rh1 42. f5 Rc1 43. Ke2 {it's Black who needs to be careful.}) 39. fxg3 Bxe5 40. Be4 {An early Ne5 is an interesting option for White. Karjakin reacted logically with 9...Bd6 and 10...c5, but 12 Ng4! ensures that Black doesn't get an easy equality. Karjakin's 12...Nbd7!?, allowing 13 Nh6+, is certainly provocative but, as analysis shows, not necessarily bad!} 1/2-1/2


