1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. Nf3 dxc4 7. Bxc4 c5 8. O-O cxd4 9. exd4 b6 10. Bg5 Bb7 11. Rc1 Nc6 ({As mentioned before, it's possible that if Black is going to play ...h6, this might be the best time to do so, because it means that Bf4 may be met by ...Bd6 without losing time with ...Be7:} 11... h6 12. Bh4 (12. Bf4 Nc6 13. a3 Bd6 $1 {is the point}) 12... Nc6 13. a3 ({for} 13. Bd3 {see the notes to Sokolov,I-Leko,P/Wijk aan Zee 2013}) 13... Be7 {transposes to Vachier Lagrave,M-So,W/Leuven 2018, where we saw that} 14. Re1 (14. Ba2) ({or} 14. Qd3 {might be wiser}) 14... Nh5 $1 15. Bg3 Nxg3 16. hxg3 Bf6 $1 17. d5 Na5 $1 {was more than fine for Black.}) 12. a3 Be7 (12... Bxc3 $5 {has scored well for Black - see the notes to Brunner, N-Alekseev,E/Skopje 2015.}) 13. Ba2 {Both players are following the game Flores,D-Shankland,S/ Montevideo 2018, which was previously covered here.} (13. Re1 $1 h6 14. Bf4 $1 (14. Bh4 Nh5 $1 {would transpose to Vachier Lagrave-So, above}) 14... Bd6 15. Ne5 {is challenging for Black - see the notes to Repka, C-Levin,E/Krakow 2018.}) 13... Rc8 14. Re1 h6 15. Bh4 Nh5 16. Bg3 Nxg3 17. hxg3 Bf6 18. d5 $1 Bxc3 {Finally the game varies, and it's Wei Yi who is the first to deviate.} ({The Flores-Shankland game went} 18... exd5 19. Nxd5 $1 Bxb2 20. Rc2 Bxa3 21. Rd2 $1 {when Black was under considerable pressure - see the notes to that game. Instead Wei Yi declines the pawns and tries to neutralise White's pressure with an exchange of minor pieces.}) 19. Rxc3 exd5 20. Bxd5 Rc7 $1 {A good move, defending the second rank and preparing ...Rd7. Despite the simplification, Black has to tread carefully here.} ({For example, the plausible} 20... Re8 $2 {runs into the combination} 21. Bxf7+ $1 Kxf7 22. Rd3 $1 Rxe1+ 23. Nxe1 {followed by Rd7+ and Rxb7.}) (20... Na5 {is another option, but after} 21. Rd3 Qf6 22. Ne5 $1 Bxd5 23. Rxd5 {White still has a slight initiative.}) 21. Ree3 {Planning Red3. Wang Yue chooses to put his rooks on the c- and d-files rather than the e- and d-files.} (21. Rd3 Rd7 22. Rd2 {To prevent the idea of ...Nb4.} (22. b4 $2 Nxb4 $1) 22... Na5 ({or} 22... Qf6) 23. Bxb7 Rxd2 24. Qxd2 Nxb7 {and Black has equalised. If} 25. Qxd8 Rxd8 $1 26. Re7 Nc5 27. Rxa7 Rd1+ 28. Kh2 Nd3 {and Black regains the pawn.}) 21... Re7 $1 (21... Rd7 22. Red3 $1 Nb4 $6 {doesn't work here.} (22... Re8 $4 23. Bxf7+ $1) (22... Qe8 $1) 23. Bxf7+ $1 Rfxf7 24. axb4 {and White is a pawn ahead.}) 22. Red3 Qe8 $1 {Initially this looks awkward for Black, but in fact White can do nothing to prevent Black's next move.} (22... Rd7 $2 {makes no sense given that the rook has just moved to e7. Furthermore,} 23. Bxc6 Bxc6 24. Rxd7 Qxd7 (24... Bxd7 25. Rd3) 25. Qxd7 Bxd7 26. Rc7 {wins the a7-pawn.}) 23. b4 Ne5 $1 {Liquidating the minor pieces and solving all of Black's problems.} 24. Bxb7 Rxb7 25. Re3 Qd8 $1 26. Qxd8 Nxf3+ 27. gxf3 Rxd8 28. f4 Kf8 29. Kg2 Re7 30. Kf3 g6 {Although Black has to display some accuracy, Wei Yi's 18...Bxc3 eventually equalises. Black should consider playing ...h6 earlier, which might lead to more favourable lines.} 1/2-1/2


