1. d4 ({Giving Black the IQP seems to be a general trend at the moment. For example, the Semi-Tarrasch line} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. e3 e6 5. d4 d5 6. cxd5 exd5 7. Bb5 {(followed by dxc5, or ...cxd4 and Nxd4) has been played by numerous elite GMs including Carlsen, Kramnik and Aronian. This is very similar to the Nimzo line here.}) 1... Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 c5 6. Nf3 d5 7. cxd5 {If anyone gets the IQP in this line, it's usually White, the obvious example being the Karpov Variation. However, in recent years some GMs have preferred an early cxd5 to give Black the IQP.} (7. O-O Nc6 ({although anti-IQPers can get in first with} 7... dxc4 8. Bxc4 cxd4 9. exd4) 8. cxd5 exd5 9. dxc5 {is a similar line we've also looked at, and we actually transpose to it after 9 0-0.}) 7... exd5 8. dxc5 Nc6 ({Black's most popular choice has been} 8... Nbd7 {intending ...Nxc5 - see the notes to Harikrishna, P-Topalov,V/Stavanger 2016.}) ({Another option is} 8... Bg4 9. O-O Nbd7 {which is covered in Carlsen,M-So,W/Leuven 2017.}) 9. O-O Bg4 $5 {A rare choice.} ({Black nearly always recaptures with} 9... Bxc5 {- see Aleksandrov, A-Levin, E/St Petersburg 2011.}) 10. Na4 $1 {This is certainly not the only move, but it does seem logical to force Black to work to regain the pawn. Moreover, any minor piece swap on c5 should slightly favour White.} Ne4 (10... Qe7 11. b3 Ne4 12. Be2 Nc3 13. Nxc3 Bxc3 14. Rb1 Qxc5 15. Bb2 Bxb2 16. Rxb2 Rfd8 17. Rd2 a5 18. h3 Be6 19. Nd4 $14 {was very slightly better for White, Shankland,S-Negi,P/ San Francisco 2017.}) 11. a3 (11. Be2 $1 {might be stronger:} Rc8 (11... Nxc5 $6 12. a3 $1 Nxa4 13. Qxa4 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 Bc5 15. Rd1 $16) 12. a3 Bxc5 13. Nxc5 Nxc5 14. b4 Qf6 $1 (14... Ne4 15. Bb2) 15. Ra2 Ne4 16. Bb2 Nc3 (16... Qd6 $14) 17. Bxc3 Qxc3 18. Qd2 (18. Qxd5 $1 Be6 19. Qd2 $1) 18... Ne7 19. h3 Bd7 20. Nd4 Qxd2 21. Rxd2 Rc3 22. Ra1 $14 {(Sargissian,G-Ghaem Maghami, E/Khanty-Mansiysk 2013) reaches another typical position. Black's control of the c-file is close to neutralising White's edge due to the IQP.}) 11... Bxc5 12. h3 ({The knight on a4 needs to be exchanged, so White should probably play} 12. Nxc5 Nxc5 13. Be2 {although Black is active enough after} Ne4 $1) 12... Bxf3 13. gxf3 $6 {Extremely risky!} (13. Qxf3 Ne5 14. Qe2 Bd6 {is still roughly level.}) 13... Qg5+ 14. Kh1 (14. Kh2 Bd6+) 14... Qh4 $1 15. fxe4 $2 {Now Black has a winning position.} ({White has to defend with} 15. Kg2 $1 Ng5 16. Rh1) 15... Qxh3+ 16. Kg1 Ne5 ({This is good, but} 16... Rad8 $1 {intending ...Rd6 is even stronger.} 17. exd5 (17. f4 Bxe3+ 18. Bxe3 Qxe3+ 19. Kg2 dxe4 $19) 17... Rd6 18. Re1 (18. Be4 f5 $1) 18... f5 $1 {and ...Rg6 is coming. No doubt Wei Yi would have seen this in a game with a slower time limit, but then So wouldn't have played 13 gxf3!}) 17. f3 $2 (17. f4 {is a better defence. If} Bxe3+ 18. Bxe3 Qxe3+ 19. Kh2 Nxd3 {White can win the knight with} 20. Rf3 {although Black still keeps an advantage after} Qxe4 21. Rxd3 Qxf4+) 17... Qg3+ 18. Kh1 Qh3+ $2 (18... Rac8 $1 {intending ... Rc6 is decisive.}) 19. Kg1 Qg3+ 20. Kh1 Bd6 (20... Rac8 $1) 21. f4 Qh3+ {Wei Yi settles for perpetual check.} ({Black is still winning, although now it's much more difficult to find:} 21... f5 $1 22. fxe5 Qh4+ 23. Kg2 Qg5+ 24. Kh1 (24. Kf2 fxe4+ 25. Ke1 exd3 26. Qxd3 Rxf1+ 27. Qxf1 Rf8 28. Qh1 Qg3+ 29. Kd2 Rf2+ 30. Kd3 Qg6+ 31. Kd4 Bxe5+ 32. Kxe5 Qf6+ 33. Kxd5 Qc6+) 24... Rf6 25. exf6 Qh4+ 26. Kg2 Qg3+ 27. Kh1 Qh2#) 22. Kg1 Qg3+ 23. Kh1 Qh3+ 24. Kg1 Qg3+ 25. Kh1 {Wesley's So's 10 Na4! is a good move, and White should be able to keep a small edge after it.} 1/2-1/2


