1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 c5 ({The other main option for Black against the Saemisch.} 5... b6 6. f3 Ba6 7. e4 Nc6 {- see games in the archives.}) 6. e3 ({After} 6. f3 {Black may either transpose to the 4 f3 Nimzo with 6...d5 or play in more classical Nimzo fashion with} Nc6 7. e4 d6 8. Be3 b6 {- see the notes to Murali Krishnan, B-Prasad,D/Nagpur 2002.}) 6... Nc6 7. Bd3 O-O 8. Ne2 (8. e4 {is met by} d5 $1 {- see Georgiev,V-Efimenko,Z/Isle of Man 2007.}) 8... b6 9. e4 Ne8 $1 {A key move in the Saemisch, sidestepping the Bg5 pin.} 10. O-O Ba6 11. f4 f5 12. Ng3 (12. exf5 exf5 13. dxc5 bxc5 14. Be3 d6 15. Ng3 g6 {transposes to Pedersen, N-Schandorff,L/Horsens 2003 - see below.}) (12. d5 {was popular for a while but Peter Leko found a convincing antidote:} exd5 $1 (12... Na5 13. e5 Bxc4 14. Bxc4 Nxc4 15. d6 $1 {, with good compensation for the pawn, is White's idea - see the notes to Milov,V-Polgar,J/ Moscow 2001}) 13. cxd5 Bxd3 14. Qxd3 fxe4 15. Qxe4 Nd6 $1 16. Qd3 Na5 {with advantage to Black - see Radjabov,T-Leko,P/Monte Carlo 2007.}) 12... g6 13. Be3 ({The alternative is for White to break the tension:} 13. exf5 exf5 14. dxc5 bxc5 15. Be3 d6 {- see Pedersen,N-Schandorff, L/Horsens 2003.}) 13... cxd4 $1 {The start of a simplifying procedure which was worked out by Anatoly Karpov many years ago, and it's still recognised as perfectly sufficient. White is allowed to get rid of his doubled c-pawns, but in return Black gains some light-squared control.} 14. cxd4 d5 $1 15. cxd5 Bxd3 16. Qxd3 fxe4 17. Nxe4 $5 ({The stem game with 13...cxd4 continued} 17. Qxe4 Qxd5 18. Qxd5 exd5 {- see the notes to Yusupov,A-Karpov,A/Linares 1993. Radovanovic prefers to battle with the queens on the board, and the chances remain roughly level.}) 17... Qxd5 18. Rad1 (18. Nc3 Qf5 $1 19. Qxf5 Rxf5 20. g4 Ra5 {with an edge for Black, Toth, C-De Souza,M/Aracatuba 1998.}) 18... Rd8 19. Rfe1 {The first new move, and a logical one.} (19. g4 $6 {(Hamilton,D-Rej, T/Parramatta 2008) looks premature in view of} Nf6 $1 20. Nxf6+ Rxf6 $15 {Here} 21. f5 $2 {fails to} gxf5 22. Bg5 Rg6 $1 23. Bxd8 Rxg4+) 19... Ng7 20. Ng5 e5 $1 {Not the only move, but this allows Black to get rid of the weak e6-pawn and get his knight to c4.} ({Another way to reach c4 would be with} 20... Na5 {but after} 21. g4 Nc4 22. Bc1 $1 {White intends Qh3 and suddenly Black is feeling under pressure.}) 21. fxe5 Nxe5 22. Qe4 Nc4 $1 (22... Qxe4 $6 23. Nxe4 Nc4 $2 24. Bg5 $1 $16) 23. Bc1 (23. Qh4 h5 (23... Nh5) 24. Nf3 Nxe3 25. Rxe3 Nf5 {forks the queen and rook, but White can force a draw with} 26. Qg5 Nxe3 27. Qxg6+ Kh8 28. Qh6+) 23... Nf5 (23... Rfe8 $11 {is safer.}) 24. Qe6+ $1 Kh8 25. Re4 (25. Rf1 $5) 25... h6 26. Qxg6 $1 {The beginning of a forcing sequence.} hxg5 27. Rd3 $1 Qxe4 $1 28. Rh3+ Qh4 29. Rxh4+ gxh4 30. Qh5+ Kg7 31. Qg5+ Kh7 32. Qh5+ Kg8 33. Qg6+ Kh8 34. Qh5+ Kg8 35. Qg6+ Ng7 $5 {After repeating the position once, Wei Yi chooses to give up a piece and continue the game.} (35... Kh8 36. Qh5+ {is perpetual check.}) 36. Bh6 $1 Rd7 37. Bxg7 Rxg7 38. Qe6+ Kh8 39. Qh6+ (39. Qxc4 Rfg8 {is similar to the game, but with 39 Qh6+ Radovanovic is still trying to force a draw.}) 39... Kg8 40. Qe6+ Kh7 $1 {Wei Yi plays on, and is soon to be rewarded.} 41. Qxc4 Rfg8 42. Qd3+ Kh8 43. Qe4 Rxg2+ 44. Qxg2 $2 {Radovanovic errs at a critical moment.} ({After} 44. Kf1 $1 R2g4 45. Qe5+ R8g7 46. Ke2 {a draw is the most likely result. With Black's king so exposed, White certainly isn't worse.}) 44... b5 $1 {A star move. Black is winning the resulting pawn ending.} (44... Rxg2+ $2 45. Kxg2 {is a draw, e.g.} Kg7 46. Kf3 Kf6 47. Ke4 Ke6 (47... b5 $2 48. Kd5 $1) 48. a4 $1 h3 49. d5+ Kd6 50. Kd4 a6 51. Kc4 Ke5 $5 52. a5 $1 bxa5 53. Kc5 a4 54. d6 Ke6 55. Kc6 a3 56. d7 a2 57. d8=Q a1=Q 58. Qc8+) 45. Qxg8+ (45. d5 $1 {is more testing, and here} h3 $1 {is the only move to win.} (45... Rxg2+ $2 46. Kxg2 Kg7 47. Kf3 Kf6 48. Ke4 Ke7 49. Ke5 a5 50. d6+ Kd7 51. Kd5 b4 52. axb4 axb4 53. Kc4 Kxd6 54. Kxb4 $11) 46. Qg3 $5 {is a good try:} (46. Qxg8+ Kxg8 47. Kf2 Kf7 48. Ke3 Ke7 49. Kd3 Kd6 50. Kd4 a6 $1 {Reciprocal zugzwang.} (50... a5 $2 51. Ke4 b4 52. axb4 axb4 53. Kd4 b3 54. Kc3 Kxd5 55. Kxb3 Ke4 56. Kc3 $11 {is a draw}) 51. Ke4 a5 52. Kd4 a4 $1 53. Ke4 b4 {and Black wins.}) 46... Rxg3+ 47. hxg3 Kg7 $1 48. g4 Kf6 $1 (48... a5 $4 {even loses:} 49. d6 Kf8 50. g5 b4 51. axb4 axb4 52. g6 b3 53. d7 Ke7 54. g7 b2 55. d8=Q+ $1 Kxd8 56. g8=Q+) 49. Kh2 (49. d6 Ke6 50. g5 Kxd6 {and Black's king is in the g-pawn's square}) 49... a5 50. Kxh3 b4 51. axb4 axb4 52. Kh4 b3 53. g5+ Ke5 $1 54. g6 b2 55. g7 b1=Q 56. g8=Q Qh1+ 57. Kg5 Qg1+ {and Black wins!}) 45... Kxg8 46. Kg2 a5 ({Black also wins with} 46... Kf7 47. Kf3 Ke6 48. Ke4 Kd6 49. d5 h3 50. Kd4 a6 $1 51. Ke4 a5 52. Kd4 a4 $1 53. Ke4 b4 $1) 47. Kf3 a4 $1 ({But not} 47... b4 $4 48. axb4 a4 49. b5) (47... a4 48. Ke3 b4 49. Kd2 b3 (49... bxa3 {also wins}) 50. h3 Kf7 51. Kd3 Ke6 52. Kd2 Kd5 53. Kd3 (53. Kc3 Ke4) 53... b2 54. Kc2 Kxd4 55. Kxb2 Kd3 56. Kb1 Kc3 57. Ka2 Kc2 58. Ka1 Kb3 59. Kb1 Kxa3 60. Ka1 Kb3 61. Kb1 Kc3 62. Ka2 Kd3 {and Black wins.}) 0-1


