1. e4 {Gawain Jones} c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 a6 7. f3 b5 {Time to look at another Accelerated Dragadorf game. The advantage behind this move order is that White is unable to play Bf1-c4 which is considered a critical test of Black's opening. Gawain Jones: 'Time to look at another Accelerated Dragadorf game. The advantage behind this move order is that White is unable to play Bf1-c4 which is considered a critical test of Black's opening.'} 8. Qd2 Bb7 9. O-O-O ({I examined 9.a4 in Haznedaroglu-Gunnarsson last year, which I believe to be the critical test of an early ...b5. A couple of recent games continued: Gawain Jones: 'I examined 9.a4 in Haznedaroglu-Gunnarsson last year, which I believe to be the critical test of an early ...b5. A couple of recent games continued:'} 9. a4 e5 10. Nb3 b4 11. Nd5 (11. Na2 d5 12. Bg5 Nbd7 13. exd5 h6 (13... Bxd5 14. Nxb4 Bxb3 15. cxb3 Qb6 16. Nd5 Nxd5 17. Qxd5 Bb4+ {is the line I gave from Simon's book where Black has good compensation for the pawn as White's king is exposed. Gawain Jones: 'is the line I gave from Simon's book where Black has good compensation for the pawn as White's king is exposed.'}) ({The computer suggests Gawain Jones: 'The computer suggests'} 13... Qb6 $5 {which could be playable although I would be anxious playing with my king in the centre Gawain Jones: 'which could be playable although I would be anxious playing with my king in the centre'}) 14. Bxf6 Nxf6 15. Nxb4 Nxd5 {This position is given as "with compensation" by Simon but in truth I'm afraid I don't see it. Maslak evidently agrees and following: Gawain Jones: 'This position is given as "with compensation" by Simon but in truth I'm afraid I don't see it. Maslak evidently agrees and following:'} 16. Nxd5 Bxd5 17. O-O-O Bxb3 18. Qxd8+ Rxd8 19. cxb3 Rxd1+ 20. Kxd1 a5 21. Bb5+ Kd8 22. Ke2 {he eventually converted his extra pawn. Maslak, K-Fedorovsky, M Pardubice 2010. Gawain Jones: 'he eventually converted his extra pawn. Maslak, K-Fedorovsky, M Pardubice 2010.'}) 11... Nxd5 12. exd5 Nd7 13. O-O-O Rb8 14. Kb1 {This looks like a nuance.} (14. f4 {was played in the aforementioned game when perhaps I was too dismissive of Black's chances. The game continued Gawain Jones: 'was played in the aforementioned game when perhaps I was too dismissive of Black's chances. The game continued'} Be7 (14... Bh6 15. fxe5 Bxe3 16. Qxe3 Nxe5 17. Qh6 Qc7 18. Kb1 Rc8 19. Rd2 f5 {was a line I gave in which I fancied White's chances although I think Black's play can be improved upon. Gawain Jones: 'was a line I gave in which I fancied White's chances although I think Black's play can be improved upon.'}) (14... Bg7 {is a logical move which I failed to investigate as I saw mentioned on the forum and indeed this position seems fully adequate for the second player, e.g. Gawain Jones: 'is a logical move which I failed to investigate as I saw mentioned on the forum and indeed this position seems fully adequate for the second player, e.g.'} 15. Qxb4 O-O $1 16. Ba7 (16. Qxd6 Re8 {gives White a few problems to extricate his queen. He could try Gawain Jones: 'gives White a few problems to extricate his queen. He could try'} 17. Qa3 {when a plausible line could continue Gawain Jones: 'when a plausible line could continue'} (17. Nc5 exf4 18. Qxf4 Nxc5 19. Bxc5 Bxd5 {looks promising for Black.}) 17... Bf8 18. d6 exf4 19. Bxf4 Re4 20. Bg3 Qg5+ 21. Kb1 Qg4 22. Bd3 Rxa4 23. h3 Rxa3 24. hxg4 Ra4 25. Rh4 Bxg2 {when Black has no problems and indeed could probably have kept the initiative rather than winning back the couple of pawns. Gawain Jones: 'when Black has no problems and indeed could probably have kept the initiative rather than winning back the couple of pawns.'}) 16... Qf6 17. Bxb8 Rxb8 {when Black has the better practical chances with his queenside attack whilst White will have to defend well before hoping to convert his extra material. Gawain Jones: 'when Black has the better practical chances with his queenside attack whilst White will have to defend well before hoping to convert his extra material.'}) 15. h4 $5 {Haznedaroglu-Gunnarsson 2009, annotated in the archives. Gawain Jones: 'Haznedaroglu-Gunnarsson 2009, annotated in the archives.'}) 14... Nf6 (14... Bg7 {is no longer so effective as following Gawain Jones: 'is no longer so effective as following'} 15. Qxb4 O-O 16. Qxd6 Re8 {White has} 17. Nc5) (14... Nb6 15. a5 Nxd5 16. Bxa6 Bxa6 17. Qxd5 {is messy but White has started to take control of the position. Gawain Jones: 'is messy but White has started to take control of the position.'}) (14... Be7 $5) 15. Bg5 (15. f4 $5 {looks like a critical try now that Black's knight is no longer covering the e5 square. The pawn is taboo as Gawain Jones: 'looks like a critical try now that Black's knight is no longer covering the e5 square. The pawn is taboo as'} Nxd5 (15... Bxd5 16. fxe5 dxe5 17. Bg5 Ne4 18. Qxd5 Qxd5 19. Rxd5 Nxg5 20. Rxe5+ Ne6 21. Bxa6 {would leave Black in a lost position.}) 16. Bxa6 Nxe3 17. Bb5+ Ke7 18. Qxe3 {is pretty rotten for Black.}) 15... Be7 16. Qxb4 O-O 17. Qa5 Qc8 18. h4 Bd8 19. Qd2 Nxd5 (19... Qd7 {is probably a better bet.}) 20. Bxa6 Bxa6 21. Qxd5 Bxg5 $6 22. hxg5 {and Black was suffering. Ashwin, J-Fernandez, D Ho Chi Minh City 2009. Gawain Jones: 'and Black was suffering. Ashwin, J-Fernandez, D Ho Chi Minh City 2009.'}) (9. Be2 {was the quiet choice of a high rated Indian GM in a game from earlier this year. Gawain Jones: 'was the quiet choice of a high rated Indian GM in a game from earlier this year.'} Nbd7 10. O-O b4 (10... Bg7 11. a4 b4 12. Na2 a5 13. c3 {was probably White's intention, claiming the advantage with his control over b5 but the position doesn't look so clear to me.) Gawain Jones: 'was probably White's intention, claiming the advantage with his control over b5 but the position doesn't look so clear to me.)'}) 11. Nd5 $1 Nxd5 12. exd5 Bxd5 13. a3 $1 ({Stronger than} 13. Qxb4 Bg7 14. c4 Rb8 15. Qd2 Ba8 {which is fully adequate for Black.}) 13... bxa3 14. Rxa3 Bb7 (14... Bg7 15. Rxa6 Rxa6 16. Bxa6 Ba8 {would reach a complex middlegame where White will battle to prove the passed pawn more relevant than the central control. Gawain Jones: 'would reach a complex middlegame where White will battle to prove the passed pawn more relevant than the central control.'}) 15. Rfa1 Qc8 ({The critical test of White's plan is} 15... e5 $5 {but} 16. Nb3 d5 17. Na5 $1 Bxa3 18. Nxb7 Qc7 19. Qxd5 Rb8 20. Bxa6 Be7 21. Rd1 {gives White a dangerous initiative.}) 16. Rc3 $1 Qb8 {Geetha Narayanan Gopal-Carlsson, P Caleta 2010 and here Gawain Jones: 'Geetha Narayanan Gopal-Carlsson, P Caleta 2010 and here'} 17. Nc6 Bxc6 18. Rxc6 Bg7 19. Raxa6 Rxa6 20. Bxa6 O-O 21. b4 {is very promising for White.}) 9... h5 {This is Kudrin's choice. Gawain Jones: 'This is Kudrin's choice.'} (9... Nbd7 {has been the main move in the past and Simon Williams concentrates on this in his book. This has been played a couple of times in 2010 thus far: Gawain Jones: 'has been the main move in the past and Simon Williams concentrates on this in his book. This has been played a couple of times in 2010 thus far:'} 10. Kb1 {given as dubious by Simon this move doesn't really help White's position and thus is basically a tempo loss. Gawain Jones: 'given as dubious by Simon this move doesn't really help White's position and thus is basically a tempo loss.'} (10. g4 h6 $5 {given as a possibility. Black doesn't allow g4-g5 or the bishop trade on h6.} 11. Be2 {I think it's here that White needs to come up with a better plan as the previous two moves don't coordinate well. Gawain Jones: 'I think it's here that White needs to come up with a better plan as the previous two moves don't coordinate well.'} b4 (11... e5 12. Nb3 b4 {also looks fully playable.}) 12. Nd5 (12. Na4 Qa5 13. b3 e5 $1 {picks up the stranded knight. Gawain Jones: 'picks up the stranded knight.'}) (12. Nb1 e5 13. Nb3 a5 {looks promising for Black.}) 12... Nxd5 13. exd5 Bxd5 14. Qxb4 (14. Nb3 Bxb3 (14... Bc6 $5) 15. axb3 Qa5 16. Qd4 Qe5 {is rather unclear.}) 14... Bg7 15. Nb3 Bxb3 $6 {I don't like giving up the bishop pair so easily. Gawain Jones: 'I don't like giving up the bishop pair so easily.'} (15... Rb8 16. Qd2 Ba8 {looks satisfactory for Black. Gawain Jones: 'looks satisfactory for Black.'}) 16. cxb3 a5 17. Qe4 O-O 18. Kb1 Rc8 19. f4 {was unclear but in the end Black triumphed. Rubil, M-Feletar, D Pula 2010. Gawain Jones: 'was unclear but in the end Black triumphed. Rubil, M-Feletar, D Pula 2010.'}) 10... Rc8 11. Nb3 {Not covered in Simon's book but this move hardly looks threatening. Indeed White has just played two moves which fail to contribute to any kingside attack. Gawain Jones: 'Not covered in Simon's book but this move hardly looks threatening. Indeed White has just played two moves which fail to contribute to any kingside attack.'} Ne5 12. Nd5 Nxd5 13. exd5 Bg7 14. Bd4 O-O 15. f4 Nc4 16. Bxc4 Bxd4 17. Nxd4 Rxc4 {and Black could be happy with his opening and caused an upset. Kanovsky, D-Otte, M Pardubice 2010. Gawain Jones: 'and Black could be happy with his opening and caused an upset. Kanovsky, D-Otte, M Pardubice 2010.'}) 10. Kb1 ({Previously Chris annotated the game Uribe, M-Kudrin, S Sao Paulo 2009 which continued: Gawain Jones: 'Previously Chris annotated the game Uribe, M-Kudrin, S Sao Paulo 2009 which continued:'} 10. Bd3 Nbd7 11. f4 Ng4 12. Kb1 Nxe3 13. Qxe3 e5 14. fxe5 Nxe5 15. Nd5 Bg7 16. h3 Rc8 17. Nf3 O-O 18. Nxe5 Bxe5 19. g4 h4 {and Black had a pleasant position.}) 10... Nbd7 11. Nb3 (11. Bd3 {was played in the first game with 9...h5 and was more threatening than Wei Yi's attempt. Gawain Jones: 'was played in the first game with 9...h5 and was more threatening than Wei Yi's attempt.'} Bg7 12. h3 Rc8 13. g4 Ne5 14. g5 Nfd7 15. f4 Nc4 (15... Nxd3 {would probably be my choice here.} 16. cxd3 e5 17. Nc2 (17. fxe5 Nxe5 {would leave a very happy knight on e5.}) 17... exf4 18. Bxf4 Bxc3 $5 19. bxc3 Ne5 {looks interesting and I sincerely doubt that Black's worse here.}) 16. Bxc4 Rxc4 17. f5 O-O (17... gxf5 {is probably too risky after} 18. g6 $1 (18. Nxf5 Bxc3 19. bxc3 Bxe4 {isn't anything to worry about.}) (18. exf5 b4 19. Nce2 Bxh1 20. f6 $5 Be4 21. fxg7 Rg8 {is chaotic but seems good for Black.}) (18. Rhf1 $5) 18... Bxd4 19. Bxd4 e5 20. Bf2 {leaves an absolutely crazy position on the board. Gawain Jones: 'leaves an absolutely crazy position on the board.'}) 18. fxg6 fxg6 19. Ne6 Bxc3 20. bxc3 {Homa, S-Kudrin, S Philadelphia 2009 when Gawain Jones: 'Homa, S-Kudrin, S Philadelphia 2009 when'} Qc8 21. Nxf8 Nxf8 {would have left Black with fantastic compensation for the exchange. Gawain Jones: 'would have left Black with fantastic compensation for the exchange.'}) 11... Rc8 (11... Bg7 {would make sense now that White can no longer exchange on h6 but the Chinese number one prefers to delay touching his kingside and instead puts pressure on White's king. Gawain Jones: 'would make sense now that White can no longer exchange on h6 but the Chinese number one prefers to delay touching his kingside and instead puts pressure on White's king.'} 12. a4 {here isn't as threatening as Black can react with} b4 13. Na2 a5 14. Bb5 O-O {when White has no time for e5.}) 12. Bd4 {I have to confess I'm at a bit of a loss as to what this move hopes to achieve. Gawain Jones: 'I have to confess I'm at a bit of a loss as to what this move hopes to achieve.'} (12. a4 $1 {is critical, and the only way to try and exploit Black's delayed kingside development. Gawain Jones: 'is critical, and the only way to try and exploit Black's delayed kingside development.'} bxa4 (12... b4 13. Na2 (13. Nd5 Nxd5 14. exd5 Qc7 {is ok for Black. Gawain Jones: 'is ok for Black.'}) 13... a5 14. Bb5 Bc6 (14... Bg7 15. e5 $1 {would be extremely awkward to deal with. Gawain Jones: 'would be extremely awkward to deal with.'}) 15. Qe2 Bxb5 16. Qxb5 Ra8 17. e5 dxe5 18. Nc5 {is very dangerous for Black. Gawain Jones: 'is very dangerous for Black.'}) 13. Nxa4 Bg7 14. Na5 Bc6 15. Qb4 O-O {is unclear. My computer insists on a small White edge but Black has good attacking chances and I'm sure Wang Hao would have been confident to outplay someone rated over 450 points below him here. Gawain Jones: 'is unclear. My computer insists on a small White edge but Black has good attacking chances and I'm sure Wang Hao would have been confident to outplay someone rated over 450 points below him here.'}) 12... Qc7 13. Qf2 {An obvious sign that White has failed to come up with a plan. Gawain Jones: 'An obvious sign that White has failed to come up with a plan.'} (13. Nd5 {may have been his intention but} Bxd5 14. exd5 Bh6 15. Qe2 O-O $1 {would leave a fully coordinated Black camp.}) 13... e5 $1 {Wang Hao doesn't miss the chance to take over the initiative.} 14. Be3 b4 15. Nd5 (15. Na4 Bxe4 $1 {is a pretty trick that I'm sure Wang Hao spotted. The idea is that Gawain Jones: 'is a pretty trick that I'm sure Wang Hao spotted. The idea is that'} 16. fxe4 Ng4 17. Qd2 Nxe3 {and the White queen is overworked and thus cannot recapture on e3. Gawain Jones: 'and the White queen is overworked and thus cannot recapture on e3.'} 18. Bxa6 Ra8 19. Bb5 Nxd1 20. Rxd1 Be7 21. Qxb4 O-O {leaves White with some compensation but it's clear Black has the upper hand. Gawain Jones: 'leaves White with some compensation but it's clear Black has the upper hand.'}) 15... Nxd5 16. exd5 Bg7 17. Bd3 O-O 18. Rd2 Ra8 $5 {Black changes tack and decides on the simply plan of pushing the a pawn. White, meanwhile, still fails to come up with any plan to challenge Black and just meanders around with his pieces. Gawain Jones: 'Black changes tack and decides on the simply plan of pushing the a pawn. White, meanwhile, still fails to come up with any plan to challenge Black and just meanders around with his pieces.'} (18... Nf6 19. Be4 Nxe4 20. fxe4 f5 {looks like some sort of super Kings Indian but perhaps then at least White could get an ounce of play of his own. Gawain Jones: 'looks like some sort of super Kings Indian but perhaps then at least White could get an ounce of play of his own.'}) 19. Be2 a5 {Charge!} 20. Nc1 a4 21. Nd3 Qa5 (21... a3 $1 {would have left Black with an overwhelming advantage, for example:} 22. Nxb4 axb2 23. c4 Qa5 24. Rxb2 Rfb8 25. Rd1 (25. Ka1 Bxd5 $1 $19) 25... Bc8 26. Qe1 Nc5 27. g4 e4 28. Bd4 Bxd4 29. Rxd4 Qa3 30. fxe4 Ra4 {picking up the knight and the game is a typical continuation of the attack for Black. Gawain Jones: 'picking up the knight and the game is a typical continuation of the attack for Black.'}) 22. Rhd1 Rfc8 23. Qh4 b3 {Breaking open White's defences.} 24. Qb4 bxa2+ 25. Kxa2 (25. Ka1 {wouldn't save White as} a3 $1 {would open up the White monarch with decisive effect. Gawain Jones: 'would open up the White monarch with decisive effect.'}) 25... Bxd5+ 26. Kb1 Qc7 27. Ne1 Rcb8 28. Qa3 Be6 29. Qxd6 Qc3 {A comfortable win for Black as White failed to find a plan. White must be happy to go into the critical lines against the Dragadorf or, as we've seen here, he'll just drift into a worse position. Gawain Jones: 'A comfortable win for Black as White failed to find a plan. White must be happy to go into the critical lines against the Dragadorf or, as we've seen here, he'll just drift into a worse position.'} 0-1


