1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Nc3 g6 4. d4 Bg7 5. h3 dxe4 6. Nxe4 Nf6 7. Nxf6+ exf6 $5 {This idea was suggested to me by a subscriber. We reach a position similar to those arising from 1 e4 c6 2 d4 d5 3 Nc3 dxe4 4 Nxe4 Nf6 5 Nxf6 exf6. The engines always give White an edge in such positions, however in reality I think this is a little misleading - White's plans are not so easy meanwhile this game illustrates how Black may increase the pressure if White lets him.} 8. Bc4 (8. Bd3 O-O 9. O-O Re8 {.} (9... Na6 $6 10. c3 (10. Bxa6 bxa6 11. c4 {is better for White.}) 10... Nc7 11. Re1 b6 12. a4 a5 13. Bf4 Nd5 14. Qd2 Be6 15. Re2 Nxf4 16. Qxf4 Qb8 17. Qxb8 Raxb8 18. Nd2 Bh6 19. Bc4 Bxd2 20. Bxe6 fxe6 21. Rxd2 Rfd8 22. Kf1 Kf7 $11 {1/2-1/2 (25) Kollars,D (2542)-Howell,D (2697) Germany 2019}) 10. Bf4 Na6 11. c3 Nc7 12. Re1 Rxe1+ 13. Qxe1 {1/2-1/2 (36) Zelbel,P (2452)-Larino Nieto,D (2495) Leiria 2017} a5 14. a4 (14. Qd2 a4 15. a3 Nd5 16. Bh2 b5 $13) 14... Be6 15. c4 Na6 $132) 8... O-O 9. O-O a5 10. a4 Na6 {The most flexible route.} ({The following was a blitz game, so it's merely illustrative.} 10... Nd7 11. Bf4 (11. Re1 {is the strongest reaction, when White is a bit better - here was an excellent example:} Nb6 12. Bb3 Nd5 13. c4 $1 Nb4 14. Bd2 b6 15. Bc3 Ra7 {Black allowed his opponent to gain far too much control over the position.} 16. Qd2 Qd6 17. Qe3 Bf5 18. Re2 c5 19. Rd1 Qc7 20. Nh2 Na6 21. d5 Qd6 22. Ng4 Bxg4 23. hxg4 Rd7 24. Rde1 $18 {1-0 (47) Beim,V  (2527)-Mahdy,K (2352) Aschach 2001}) 11... Nb6 12. Bb3 Nd5 13. Bh2 Be6 14. Re1 Re8 15. Nd2 f5 16. Nc4 f4 $1 17. c3 g5 18. Ne5 {0-1 (42) Lu,S (2630)-Wei,Y  (2734) Tianjin 2018} Bxe5 $5 19. dxe5 (19. Rxe5 f6 20. Re1 Qd7 $15 {is awkward for White, mostly due to the hemmed in dark-squared bishop.}) 19... Nb6 20. Bxe6 Qxd1 21. Bxf7+ Kxf7 22. Rexd1 Rad8 23. b3 Rxd1+ 24. Rxd1 Rxe5 25. g3 Rd5 $15 {Commonly, the endings give Black good winning chances.}) 11. c3 Nc7 12. Bf4 (12. Re1 Nd5 13. Bd2 Be6 14. Bf1 Qd6 15. Qc1 Qd7 16. Bh6 b5 17. Bxg7 Kxg7 18. Nd2 Nb6 19. axb5 cxb5 20. Ne4 Bc4 21. Bxc4 bxc4 22. Qf4 Qc6 23. Qd6 Rfc8 24. Qxc6 Rxc6 25. Nc5 Nd5 26. Ra4 Nb6 27. Ra2 Nd5 28. g3 Rb6 29. Re2 Rb5 30. Kg2 Rab8 31. Kf3 h5 $13 {0-1 (93) Stripunsky,A (2536)-Gonzalez,R (2451) chess. com INT 2017}) 12... Nd5 13. Bh2 Be6 14. Nd2 f5 (14... Bh6 15. Re1 Re8 16. Ba2 {1/2-1/2 (90) Sindarov,J (2287)-Bai,J (2443) Hamedan 2018} f5 17. Nf3 f6 $5 $132 {Black plays some useful moves next, for instance Qd7, Kg7 and takes stock. Either Bh6-f4 which would generally lead to equality or to keep the position more complicated: g6-g5, f5-f4, Bf7-h5 - a snazzy development (!), prioritising the light-squared bishop's scope over that of the dark-squared bishop, which should eventually reroute via f8. Incidentally, this is exactly what occurred in our game continuation, it is the most effective way to play for the win.}) 15. Bb3 (15. Qb3 Qd7 16. Rfe1 Rfe8 17. Re2 Re7 18. Rae1 Rae8 19. Qa3 {1-0 (60) Savic,M (2511)-Jovanovic,Z (2540) Hungary 2018} f4 $1 {justified by the tactic} 20. Bxd5 Qxd5 {[%cal Gg6g5]} 21. Bxf4 $4 Bxh3 $19) 15... h5 $5 16. Re1 Bh6 17. Be5 {This move, which plays into Black's hands, somewhat shows that White was unaccustomed to this obscure structure.} (17. Nf3 Re8 18. Ne5 {(else f7-f6 might actually come voluntarily).} Bf4 (18... Kh7 19. Qf3 f6 20. Nd3 Bf7 {is now riskier and less effective, not only because the c5-square isn't covered but also because} 21. g4 {is possible.} fxg4 22. hxg4 hxg4 23. Qxg4 $36 {This was perhaps a drawback of the h7-h5 plan.})) 17... Re8 18. Nc4 f6 19. Bh2 {With his next few moves, Wei Yi affirms his class by seizing the initiative.} f4 20. Qf3 Kg7 21. Nd2 Qc7 22. Re2 Bf7 23. Rae1 Rxe2 24. Rxe2 g5 25. Bc2 Qd7 26. Qd3 Rh8 {Black has covered all the concrete issues that White has posed.} 27. Qf5 $6 Qxf5 28. Bxf5 Bg6 $1 29. Bxg6 Kxg6 {The ending is fantastic for Black.} 30. Nb3 b6 31. Re6 Rc8 32. c4 Nb4 33. c5 Kf5 34. Re2 bxc5 35. dxc5 Rd8 36. Re1 Rd5 37. Kf1 Bf8 38. Nxa5 Bxc5 39. Nc4 Rd4 40. b3 Rd3 41. Rb1 g4 42. hxg4+ hxg4 43. Bg1 Rc3 44. a5 f3 45. Bh2 Rc2 46. Bg3 Nd3 47. gxf3 gxf3 48. Rd1 Nxf2 49. Re1 Ne4 50. Bh4 Rxc4 {An absolute model game for this variation, note White's light squared bishop was completely restricted even up to the final position!} 0-1


