{[%evp 0,44,58,-6,-6,-39,-3,-39,27,-57,-49,0,22,22,45,1,16,21,6,-63,99,-14,-63,-85,-107,-120,-89,-199,-190,-176,-116,-199,-213,-229,-194,-194,-172,-178,-249,-208,-165,-294,-279,-379,-379,-627,-649]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 $6 {[#] A rather provocative move which is punished emphatically by the Chinese prodigy. Wei Yi shows us that we shouldn't be afraid of any ghosts and that h5 by White is not necessarily connected with an attack against the black king.} a6 $1 5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7 7. a3 b6 8. Be3 Bb7 9. f3 {[#]} Nc6 $17 {Black has developed properly getting a serious space advantage while White's attack is destined to fail since his pieces are not well coordinated.} 10. Rc1 Bc5 $1 {It makes a lot of sense for Black to open the f-file in order to use it for attacking purposes.} (10... Ne5) 11. Na4 (11. b4 {I don't find it necessary for Black to respond to the "threat" of h5. By playing h5 Black weakens the g5-square which can be used by the white knight.} Bxd4 12. Bxd4 Nxd4 13. Qxd4 e5 (13... d6 14. Rd1 Ke7 (14... Rd8 15. Na4) 15. Be2) (13... O-O 14. e5 $13 {1-0 (37) Jobava,B (2706)-Dubov,D (2614) Minsk BLR 2014} Ne8 15. Rd1 f6 (15... Bc6 16. Bd3 f6 $14 17. exf6 Nxf6 18. O-O) 16. Qxd7 Qxe5+ 17. Kf2 $13 Nc7 18. Qd4 (18. Be2 $6) 18... Qxd4+ 19. Rxd4 $14 {1/2 (43) Lagarde,M (2610)-Van der Lende,I (2334) Cappelle la Grande FRA 2019}) 14. Qe3 d6 $13 {1-0 (60) Rakhmanov,A (2636)-Zhukova,N (2470) Doha QAT 2014} 15. Be2 O-O 16. O-O) 11... Nxd4 12. Bxd4 Bxd4 (12... e5 $5 $13 {[%cal Yd7d6,Yf7f5]} 13. Nxc5 bxc5 $15 14. Be3 a5 15. b3 O-O {[%cal Yc8e6,Yd8d7,Ye8c8]}) 13. Qxd4 {[#]} b5 $1 14. Nb6 (14. Nc5 $5 e5 15. Qe3 Qb6 $13 (15... d6 16. Nxb7 Qxb7 $5 $17 17. b4 {1-0 (39) Lagarde,M (2657)-Roselle,T (2161) Montagne FRA 2019} O-O $5 18. Be2) 16. Kf2 O-O 17. Nxb7 Qxb7 18. c5 Rfd8 19. Be2 d5 20. cxd6 $13 Rxd6 $6) 14... Rb8 15. e5 (15. c5 e5 $15 {[%cal Yc8f5,Yd8d7,Ye8c8] Black is already in control since he has developed faster than White.} 16. Qe3 O-O 17. b4 d5 18. exd5 Bxd5 (18... Nxd5 19. Nxd5 Bxd5 $15 20. Bd3 {1-0 (51) Gabuzyan,H (2614)-Shahinyan,D (2442) Yerevan ARM 2016}) 19. Bd3 Bc6 20. O-O Rbd8) 15... Nd5 $19 {[%csl Re1] With the white king trapped on e1 it is only a matter of time for black to deliver the killing punch.} 16. Nxd5 Bxd5 17. Kd2 (17. Rc3 Bc6 (17... bxc4 18. Bxc4 Bxc4 {[%cal Yc7c5,Yd7d5] is equally good.} 19. Rxc4 $5 Qd8 20. O-O O-O 21. Rfc1) 18. b4 {is very comfortable for Black.} O-O 19. Bd3 f6 20. exf6 Rxf6 21. O-O $13) 17... Rc8 18. c5 f6 (18... O-O 19. Bd3 f6 20. Rhe1 fxe5 $19 21. Qxe5 (21. Rxe5 d6 22. Rg5 h6 23. Rg4) 21... Qd8) 19. Bd3 {[#]} (19. exf6 gxf6 (19... O-O 20. fxg7 Rf4 $19 21. Qe3) 20. Qxf6 Rg8 $17 {[%cal Yc8f5,Yc8g4]} 21. b4 $2 d6 22. Rg1) 19... fxe5 $1 20. Qh4 e4 21. fxe4 Bc4 22. Rhf1 (22. Bxc4 bxc4 23. Rxc4 $19 {Black has control of the centre and White has issues with the lack of space.} Qe5 $5) 22... Qe5 23. b4 Qb2+ 24. Rc2 Qxa3 25. Bxc4 bxc4 26. Rxc4 (26. Qh5+ g6 27. Qe5 Qd3+ 28. Ke1 Qe3+ $17 {0-1 (24) Bartel,M (2600)-Paravyan,D (2627) Prague CZE 2019} 29. Kd1 $5 {Planning on playing f5, e7 and castling long.} Qd3+) 26... Qb2+ $19 27. Kd3 $5 a5 $5 (27... Qb3+ 28. Rc3 Qxb4 29. Qh5+ Kd8 30. Qg5+ Kc7 31. Qe5+ Kb7 $15 {0-1 (31) Jobava,B (2690)-Le Quang Liem (2737) Riyadh KSA 2017} 32. Rf7 $5 $15 Qb1+ $5 33. Rc2 Qb3+ $1 {Black shouldn't avoid pushing his pawn to e4 harassing the white knight.} 34. Kd2 $6 Qb4+) 28. Rd4 (28. Qf4 axb4 29. c6 Qf6 30. cxd7+ Kxd7 $17 31. Rd4+ Ke8 32. Qxf6 gxf6 33. Rxf6 Ke7) 28... axb4 $40 29. Qh5+ $2 g6 $19 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Yc7c6,Yb4c2] emphasises White's lack of space.} 30. Qe5 Qc3+ 31. Ke2 Qb2+ $1 32. Ke3 Qc3+ $19 {[%cal Ya8d8,Yd5d4,Yc6e5,Yf6e4] White will not be able to put his king is safety.} 33. Ke2 $4 Qb2+ 34. Ke3 Qc3+ $18 {[%cal Yd5f6,Yh1h7]} 35. Ke2 Qb2+ $17 {[%cal Yc7c6,Yd7d5]} 36. Ke3 Qc3+ 37. Ke2 Qb2+ 38. Ke3 Qc3+ 39. Ke2 Qb2+ 40. Ke3 Qc3+ $15 0-1


