{[%evp 0,97,16,-14,-19,-14,-3,-3,38,-3,26,10,10,-39,-12,-29,-17,-4,-16,-2,-2,38,63,81,74,74,95,66,66,47,58,42,35,50,50,4,78,60,89,89,109,73,62,54,69,104,158,151,160,129,152,94,106,88,79,42,111,111,120,86,342,329,329,62,109,63,68,62,65,40,56,40,54,58,34,44,50,35,37,37,29,32,41,20,39,44,62,104,107,107,112,112,112,98,111,111,141,129,121,121]} 1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. e4 d5 4. e5 d4 5. exf6 dxc3 {[#]} 6. fxg7 $5 {A rare sideline in a well known position. An interesting/good decision by Yu Yangyi for the most important game ( both players were tied for first 2 rounds before the end of the championship) of the tournament. Wei Yi's couldn't have expected this line and his reaction was not the optimum.} (6. bxc3 {is by far the main line}) 6... cxd2+ 7. Bxd2 (7. Qxd2 Qxd2+ 8. Bxd2 Bxg7 9. O-O-O Nc6 10. Nf3 {with a balanced queenless middlegame.}) 7... Bxg7 8. Nf3 (8. Qb3) (8. Qc2 {will likely lead to the game without having to worry about the b2 pawn.}) 8... Nc6 (8... Bxb2 $5 {Go pawn-grabbing in the early stages of the game is usually wrong. In this case white gets some compensation but things are not entirely clear. Of course Wei Yi's decision to refrain from taking on b2 is totally understandable.} 9. Rb1 Bg7 10. c5 O-O 11. Bc4 $44 {[%cal Ye1g1,Yd1c2,Yf3g5]}) 9. Qc2 (9. Qb3 $5 {is an interesting alternative. By placing the queen on b3 white makes it more difficult for black to develop Bc8. On the other hand black has the additional option of a5-a4 creating counterplay.} a5 $5 (9... O-O 10. Bd3 a5 11. O-O f5 12. Rad1 Qe7 13. c5 $1 $14 {[%cal Yd3c4,Yf1e1]}) (9... Qe7 10. Bd3 O-O 11. Be4 $5 $14 (11. O-O-O a5 12. a3 e5 13. Bc3 f5 14. c5+ Kh8 15. Bb5 Be6 $15 {1/2 (32) Carlsen,M (2861)-Nakamura,H (2761) Abidjan CIV 2019})) 10. O-O-O (10. Bd3 Qe7 (10... a4 11. Qa3 Qe7 12. c5 $14) 11. Be4 a4 12. Qb5 O-O (12... Ra6 $2 13. Qh5 $1 a3 14. b4 $1 Bxa1 15. O-O Bb2 16. b5 $16) 13. O-O $13) 10... a4 11. Qc2 Qe7 12. a3 Bd7 13. Bd3 Na5 14. Kb1 Nb3 15. Bc3 Bxc3 16. Qxc3 O-O-O $13 {0-1 (58) Gukesh,D (2547)-Zarnicki,P (2514) Moscow RUS 2019}) 9... Qf6 (9... Qe7 {looks more natural than Qf6.} 10. Bd3 (10. O-O-O Bd7) (10. Bc3 Bxc3+ (10... f5 $5) 11. Qxc3 Qb4 $13 {1-0 (41) Iturrizaga,E (2635)-Nowak,L (2257) Suwalki POL 2019}) 10... Bd7 11. O-O Nb4 (11... O-O-O) 12. Bxb4 Qxb4 13. Rab1 O-O-O $13) 10. O-O-O (10. Bc3 Qf5 (10... e5 11. Bd3 $14 {[%cal Yd3e4]}) 11. Bd3 Bxc3+ 12. Qxc3 Qa5 13. Qxa5 Nxa5 14. O-O-O {white's superior pawn structure gives him some slim chances of an advantage.}) 10... Bd7 (10... e5 $5 11. Bd3 (11. Bg5 $6 Qg6 $15) 11... Bg4 12. Bg5 (12. Be4 O-O-O $15) 12... Bh6 $13) 11. Bg5 $1 Bh6 12. h4 O-O-O 13. Qd2 Bxg5 14. hxg5 Qe7 {[#]} 15. Qe3 $14 {White's superior pawn structure gives him a slight advantage.} e5 (15... f6 {Exchanging the annoying g5 pawn as soon as possible might have been a better idea} 16. gxf6 Qxf6 17. Bd3 h5 18. Be4 e5 19. g3 $14) 16. Bd3 Bg4 17. Be4 Qb4 $6 {[#]} (17... Bxf3 $1 18. gxf3 (18. Bxf3 Nd4) 18... Rxd1+ 19. Rxd1 Rd8 $1 20. Rxd8+ Kxd8 21. Bxh7 $14) 18. Kb1 $1 {The best way to deal with the threat Qxc4.} (18. Bd5 $14) (18. Bxc6 $6 Qxc4+ 19. Kb1 Qxc6 20. Nxe5 Bf5+ $13) 18... Rxd1+ 19. Rxd1 Qxc4 20. Rc1 Qa6 21. Bxc6 bxc6 22. Nxe5 $16 Be6 23. b3 (23. a3 $5) 23... Bd5 {[#]} 24. Qf4 $2 (24. Nd3 $1 {By transfering their knight to c5 white would have secured a winning advantage.} Bxg2 $2 (24... Rd8 25. Nc5 Qa3 26. g3 $16 {[%cal Ye3e5,Ye3e7]}) 25. Nc5 Qa3 (25... Qb6 26. Qd4 $18 {[%cal Yd4h8,Yd4g4]}) 26. Rc4 $1 $18 {[%cal Yc4a4]} (26. Qd4 $2 {[%cal Yd4h8,Yd4g4]} Rd8 $1 27. Qg4+ Kb8 28. Qe2 $13 (28. Qxg2 $2 Rd2 $19))) 24... Re8 $1 {Practically pinning Ne5 since any move by the white knight will allow Re2.} 25. f3 Kb7 $2 {[#]} (25... Qb5 26. Ka1 Qb6 {and it is difficult for white to make progress.}) 26. Nd7 $1 {Black's last careless move allows the rerouting of the white knight to c5.} Qd3+ (26... Qa3 27. Nc5+ Kb8 28. Qd4 $16) 27. Rc2 Qb5 28. Nc5+ Kb8 29. a4 (29. Qf5 $5 $16 {[%cal Yf5h7]}) 29... Re1+ 30. Kb2 Qf1 31. Qf6 (31. Qb4+ $1 Kc8 32. Qb7+ Kd8 33. Qb8+ (33. Qxa7 Rb1+ 34. Ka3 Ra1+ 35. Kb4 Qb5+ 36. Kc3 $18) 33... Ke7 34. Qxa7 (34. Qxc7+ $2 Kf8 35. Qxa7 Kg7 {Black's counterplay is enough to secure the draw.}) 34... Rb1+ 35. Ka3 Qe1 36. Qxc7+ Kf8 37. Qd8+ Kg7 38. Qf6+ Kg8 39. Qc3 $18) 31... Re8 (31... Be6 32. Nxe6 fxe6 33. Qf8+ $1 Kb7 34. Qc5 Rb1+ 35. Ka3 Ra1+ 36. Kb4 Qa6 37. Rc4 $18) 32. Qc3 Ka8 33. Qd2 (33. Rd2 $5) 33... Qe1 34. Qxe1 Rxe1 35. a5 $16 Kb8 36. Kc3 Kc8 37. Kd3 (37. Kd4 Kd8 38. b4 h6 39. gxh6 Rh1 40. Nd3 $16) 37... Kd8 38. Re2 {[#]} Rd1+ (38... Rb1 $5) (38... Rh1 $5 {with the idea of exchanging pawns with h6 is a better defensive plan} 39. Kd4 h6 40. gxh6 Rxh6 {is still unpleasant but playable}) 39. Kc3 Rc1+ 40. Kd4 Ra1 41. a6 Rd1+ 42. Ke5 $18 Ke7 43. Kf5+ Be6+ (43... Kd6 44. Nb7+ Kd7 45. Kf6 $18 {[%cal Ye2e7]}) 44. Nxe6 Rd5+ 45. Kg4 fxe6 46. g3 (46. Rc2 c5 47. Kh5 $18 {[%cal Yh5h6]}) 46... Kf7 47. f4 Ra5 48. Rh2 Kg7 49. Rh6 1-0


