{[%evp 0,60,26,34,73,52,55,33,82,29,66,2,8,8,36,28,35,1,-14,-1,18,18,31,23,27,-8,57,36,49,20,59,16,21,21,33,24,12,-3,5,-41,-33,-33,-60,-6,-3,-3,-22,-227,-238,-227,-227,-227,-227,-228,-8,-8,130,0,0,0,0,0,-48]} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4 c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Be3 a6 {[#]} 8. Ne2 $5 {A side line which has been in fashion lately. White's main idea is to play c3 and strengthen his center even further. On the downside white will develop in a much slower pace than usual.} (8. Qd2 {is by far the main line}) 8... Qb6 (8... Be7 9. c3 O-O (9... cxd4 10. Nexd4 Nc5 11. Nb3 b6 12. Be2 O-O 13. O-O $14 {1-0 (29) Shankland,S (2679)-Stojanovic,M (2496) Budva MNE 2019}) 10. g3 (10. dxc5 $5) 10... b5 11. dxc5 Nxc5 12. Ned4 Bd7 13. Nxc6 Bxc6 14. Nd4 Bd7 15. Bg2 $13 {1-0 (37) Sasikiran,K (2647)-Gurevich,M (2577) chess.com INT 2020}) (8... b5 9. c3 b4 10. cxb4 $1 cxd4 11. Nexd4 Bxb4+ 12. Kf2 $1 (12. Bd2 Bxd2+ 13. Qxd2 $13 {0-1 (58) Ivanchuk,V (2698)-Akobian,V (2625) Saint Louis USA 2019}) 12... Nxd4 13. Bxd4 $14 {1-0 (27) Sasikiran,K (2674)-Svane,R (2570) Moscow RUS 2017}) 9. Qc1 (9. Rb1 cxd4 (9... Qa5+ 10. Bd2 Qc7 11. c3 b5 12. f5 $5 $40 {1-0 (39) Robson,R (2667)-Akobian,V (2625) Saint Louis USA 2019} (12. g4 $5)) (9... Be7 {[%cal Yf7f6]}) 10. Nexd4 Nc5 11. c3 Nxd4 12. Bxd4 $14 {1-0 (40) Van Foreest,J (2612)-Barua,D (2393) Pardubice CZE 2019}) 9... f6 (9... cxd4 10. Nexd4 Nxd4 11. Bxd4 Bc5 12. c3 $14 {1-0 (34) Najer,E (2648)-Greet,A (2417) Tornelo INT 2021}) (9... Be7 10. c3 O-O 11. g3 (11. h4 $5) 11... cxd4 (11... a5 12. Qc2 cxd4 13. Nexd4 Nc5 14. Rb1 (14. h4 $1 $40 {[%cal Yf3g5]}) 14... Bd7 15. Be2 Rac8 $13 {1/2 (53) So,W (2770)-Nepomniachtchi,I (2792) chess24.com INT 2021}) 12. cxd4 (12. Nexd4 $5) 12... f6 13. Bh3 (13. Bg2 $13) 13... fxe5 14. Bxe6+ Kh8 15. Bxd7 Bxd7 16. dxe5 d4 $17 {1-0 (45) Motylev,A (2640)-Bluebaum,M (2644) Moscow RUS 2019}) (9... g5 {This typical advance fails to equalize for black} 10. fxg5 (10. c3 $5) 10... cxd4 11. Nexd4 Ncxe5 12. Be2 $14 {1-0 (52) Yu Yangyi (2754)-Li Shilong (2525) China CHN 2018}) 10. c3 Be7 {[#]} 11. h4 $5 {White expands on the kingside and prepares the development of the white rook through the h3 square.} (11. exf6 {Surrendering the center in order to play against black's hanging pawns is another option for white.} Nxf6 12. dxc5 Bxc5 13. Bxc5 Qxc5 14. Ned4 Bd7 15. Bd3 O-O 16. O-O Ng4 $1 17. Qd2 (17. h3 $6 e5 $1 18. fxe5 Ngxe5 $13 (18... Rxf3 $5 19. Rxf3 Nxd4 20. cxd4 Qxd4+ 21. Kh1 Nxe5 22. Bf5 $13)) 17... e5 18. fxe5 Ngxe5 19. Nxe5 Nxe5 20. Bc2 {is slightly more pleasant for white but objectively close to equal.}) 11... O-O 12. h5 {[#]} Qa5 (12... h6 $5 {A few days later, in the same tournament, Xu Yinglun decided to deviate from the current game and play ...h6 which was the move chosen by French's expert Bluebaum.} 13. Rh3 $1 Qa5 $5 (13... Rf7 14. Kf2 fxe5 15. fxe5 Bg5 $1 16. Kg1 Bxe3+ 17. Qxe3 Qxb2 18. Re1 {1-0 (53) Xu,Y (2527)-Xu,Y (2554) Xinghua CHN 2021 White got a strong attack and won a nice game}) 14. Bd2 (14. Kf2 cxd4 $1 15. cxd4 fxe5 16. fxe5 Ndxe5 $1 17. dxe5 Nxe5 18. Kg1 Ng4 $44 {[%cal Ye6e5] 0-1 (79) Aronian,L (2781)-Bluebaum,M (2670) chess24.com INT 2021}) 14... Qd8 15. Qc2 {[%cal Ye1c1] In my opinion, white's position is slightly preferable.}) 13. h6 (13. Kf2 $5 {[%cal Yf2g1] Transfering the king to the relative safety of g1 could have been an interesting alternative.}) 13... g6 (13... g5 $5 {Would have made the position even sharper.} 14. exf6 (14. Qc2 gxf4 15. Nxf4 fxe5 16. dxe5 Ndxe5 17. Rh5 $1 Nd4 $1 18. Bxd4 Nxf3+ 19. gxf3 cxd4 {is a mess}) (14. a3 $5 fxe5 15. b4 Qd8 $13) 14... Nxf6 15. Nxg5 Ng4 $44 {[%cal Yc5d4] with a complicated battle ahead.}) 14. a3 (14. Kf2 $5) 14... cxd4 (14... Qc7 {keeping the tension in the center was possible and probably preferable.} 15. Ng3 $14 {[%cal Yf1d3]} (15. g3 {[%cal Yf1g2]})) 15. Nexd4 $1 (15. b4 Qc7 16. cxd4 b5 $1 $13 {[%cal Yd7b6,Yb6c4]}) 15... Nxd4 {[#]} 16. Bxd4 {Stabilizing the position in the center looks like the most sensible choice.} (16. Nxd4 $5 {The position becomes more complicated but white still keeps a sizable advantage.} fxe5 (16... Nb8 17. exf6 Bxf6 18. Qd2 (18. Be2 $16 {[%cal Ye1g1]}) 18... Nc6 19. O-O-O $16) 17. Nxe6 Rf7 18. Qc2 $1 $16) 16... fxe5 17. Nxe5 Nxe5 18. Bxe5 Qb6 {[#]} 19. c4 $2 {Opening the center is a very strange decision by Wei Yi. Completing his development with long castle looks very natural and would have given white a nice advantage.} (19. Qd2 Bc5 (19... Bf6 20. Bxf6 Rxf6 21. O-O-O $16 {[%cal Yg2g3,Yf1h3]}) 20. Rh3 $16 {[%cal Ye1c1]}) 19... Bc5 20. Bd3 {[%cal Yd3g6]} Bd4 $1 {[#]} (20... dxc4 $5 21. Qxc4 (21. Bxc4 Bd4 $13) 21... Bf2+ 22. Kd2 Bd7 23. Rh3 $1 $13 {White's king is safe for the moment and position remains sharp and balanced.}) (20... Bf2+ $6 21. Ke2 {helps white.}) 21. c5 $1 {Excellent resource! White gives up a pawn to win some time and get the pawn on g6.} (21. Rf1 dxc4 22. Bxd4 Qxd4 23. Bxc4 b5 24. Be2 $13) (21. Qd2 Bxe5 22. fxe5 Bd7 23. O-O-O Rf2 {Black is by no means worse}) 21... Bxc5 (21... Qxc5 $2 22. Qxc5 Bxc5 23. Bxg6 $1 $18 {[%csl Rg8] White's king is out of danger while the black king is in serious trouble.}) 22. Bxg6 Bd4 $1 23. Bd3 Bxe5 24. fxe5 Qf2+ 25. Kd1 Qxg2 26. Rh5 Kh8 {[#]} 27. Qc7 $2 {White overpresses and he could have gotten into very serious trouble.} (27. Qg5 Rf1+ $1 {Forces the draw.} (27... Qxg5 $2 28. Rxg5 Rg8 $2 (28... Bd7 29. Rg7 Bb5 30. Rxh7+ Kg8 31. Rg7+ Kh8 32. Bxb5 axb5 33. Kc2 $16) 29. Rxg8+ Kxg8 30. Kd2 $18 {[%cal Ya1g1]}) (27... Qf3+ 28. Kd2 $18) 28. Bxf1 Qxf1+ 29. Kc2 Qe2+ 30. Kc3 Qf3+ $1 31. Kd4 Qf2+ $11) 27... Bd7 $1 (27... Qf3+ 28. Kd2 Bd7 $1 (28... Rf7 $2 29. Qd8+ Rf8 30. Qg5 Rg8 {[#]} 31. Qxg8+ $1 Kxg8 32. Rg5+ Kh8 33. Rf1 $18)) 28. Qxd7 Rf1+ $2 $11 (28... Qf3+ $1 {Black fails to see the winning motif} 29. Kd2 (29. Be2 Qb3+ 30. Kd2 Qxb2+ 31. Kd3 Rg8 $19 {White's king is finally busted}) 29... Rf7 $1 {Black defends against both mate threats and collects the hanging rook on h5.} 30. Qxe6 Qxh5 $19) 29. Bxf1 Qxf1+ 30. Kd2 Qf4+ 1/2-1/2


