{After losing in the first round with White against Nakamura in rather upsetting fashion, one might have expected that Carlsen would try to play it safe with Black against Chinese prodigy Wei Yi... But no! Carlsen played the Modern Defence, showing from the very start of the game that he was in a fighting mood and intending to go for a win with the Black pieces. Wei Yi’s reaction to Carlsen’s opening surprise wasn’t very convincing so the world champion got what he had hoped for: a playable position where all three results were on the table. We will catch up with the game at the 29th move and see how Carlsen poses problems for Wei Yi in an almost equal ending and eventually breaches the defenses of his young opponent. Diagram [#]} 29... Rd8 $1 {Carlsen activates his rook, creating mating threats against White’s king, whilst keeping the game alive.} ({Perhaps most people would have played} 29... Nxa2+ 30. Kb2 Nb4 31. Bxc7 Kxc7 32. Rf6 Rf8 33. Ng5 $11 {when the game would have ended in a draw soon afterwards.}) ({Also} 29... b4 30. Kb2 Nd1+ 31. Kc1 Nc3 {is equal.}) {Diagram [#]} 30. Kb2 $1 {Wei Yi reacts in the best possible way.} ({Not} 30. Bxc7 $2 Kxc7 31. Rxa6 Rd1+ 32. Kb2 b4 $19 {when White is forced to give up his knight to save his king from mate.}) 30... Nd5 $1 ({Carlsen sacrifices a pawn to keep the game alive instead of forcing a draw by playing} 30... Nd1+ 31. Kc1 Nc3 $11) 31. Bxc7 Kxc7 32. Rxa6 Kb7 33. Ra3 Ne3 {Carlsen has full compensation since White’s rook on a3 looks silly and his king might be threatened with a mating attack from Black’s remaining pieces.} 34. c4 $1 {Wei Yi correctly decides to give back the pawn.} ({Not} 34. g3 $2 Nd1+ 35. Kc1 Nc3 $19) 34... bxc4 {Diagram [#]} 35. Ne5 $2 {Finally Wei Yi cracks under the pressure and allows Carlsen to obtain a very dangerous passed c-pawn. Time pressure was surely one of the reasons for Wei Yi’s mistake.} (35. b4 $1 {, activating the rook, was the right way to continue:} Nd5 (35... Nxg2 36. Rc3 $13) 36. Ra5 $1 $13 {keeps the position unclear and balanced.}) 35... Rd2+ 36. Kc3 Rc2+ {Diagram [#]} 37. Kd4 ({Upon} 37. Kb4 Nd5+ 38. Kb5 (38. Kc5 c3 $1 39. Nc6 Rd2 $1 $19 {and White cannot prevent the promotion of the black pawn.}) {White’s pieces are not in a position to weave a mating net around the black king so} 38... c3 {will gain the full point for Black.}) 37... Nf5+ 38. Kd5 (38. Ke4 Re2+ 39. Kf4 c3 40. b4 c2 41. Rc3 Nd4 42. Nd3 g5+ $1 43. Kxg5 Re3 $19) 38... c3 39. Kc5 Nd6 $1 {Carlsen shows some excellent calculating skills and nips White’s counterplay in the bud.} ({Not} 39... Rd2 $2 40. Nc6 Kc8 41. Ra7 $1 Ng7 42. Re7 $1 {[%cal Yc6a7] with the idea of 43.Na7. Then} Ne6+ 43. Kc4 Nd8 44. Na7+ Kb8 45. Kxc3 $11) 40. Nc6 {Diagram [#]} (40. Kxd6 Rd2+ {is hopeless}) 40... Ne4+ $6 {This is quite good but not the best.} (40... Kc7 $1 $19 {followed by Rd2, Nb7 and c2 was the simplest road to victory.}) ({But not} 40... Rd2 $4 41. Ra7+ Kc8 42. Kb6 {and suddenly it is Black who must resign.}) 41. Kb5 Kc7 42. Ra7+ Kd6 {Diagram [#]} 43. Ra4 (43. Nb4 Rxg2 ({After} 43... Rf2 44. Ra6+ Kd7 45. Ra7+ Ke6 46. Rc7 Rxg2 47. a4 Rxh2 48. a5 Rh5+ 49. Kb6 Nd6 {Black has a great advantage but the game is not over yet}) 44. Rxf7 c2 45. Rf1 (45. Nxc2 Rxc2 46. Rxh7 Rxa2 $19) 45... Nc3+ 46. Kc4 Nb1 $1 47. Rc1 (47. Re1 Rg4+ $19) 47... Rg4+ 48. Kb5 Nc3+ 49. Ka5 Rxb4 $19) 43... f5 44. Kb6 Rxg2 45. Rd4+ Ke6 46. a4 {Diagram [#]} Ra2 $6 {(A strange move by Carlsen and one which doesn’t make much sense to me. It might have been a slight mistake due to the fact that the position is completely winning anyway.)} ({Correct is} 46... Rb2 $1 47. b4 (47. Kc7 Kf6 $19 (47... Rxb3 $2 48. Rxe4+ fxe4 49. Nd4+ Kd5 50. Nxb3 e3 51. Nc1 Ke4 52. a5 Kf3 $11)) 47... Rd2 $1 48. a5 (48. Rc4 Kd5 $1 {and the rook is trapped!}) 48... Nd6 $19 {[%cal Yc3c2]}) 47. a5 Rb2 {Diagram [#]} 48. Kc7 (48. b4 Rd2 $1 (48... c2 $2 49. Rc4 Kd5 50. Rd4+ $11) (48... Nd6 49. Rd3 $1 c2 50. Rc3 Kf6 51. a6 f4 $17) 49. a6 Nd6 50. a7 Nc8+ 51. Kb7 Nxa7 52. Kxa7 Rxd4 53. Nxd4+ Kd5 54. Ne2 Kc4 55. Nxc3 Kxb4 56. Nd1 Kc4 $19 {is hopeless for White.}) 48... Nc5 $1 {Another point in the game where Carlsen displays excellent calculation. The black knight must deal with White’s passed pawn.} 49. Rc4 {Diagram [#]} Na6+ $1 (49... Nxb3 $4 50. a6 $16 {and suddenly Black is in a world of trouble since his pieces will not be able to halt the advance of the a6 pawn.}) 50. Kb6 Rxb3+ $1 51. Kxa6 Kd5 {(When he played 48...Nc5, Carlsen had calculated up to this position. Black is totally winning.)} 52. Rb4 c2 $19 53. Ne7+ Kc5 54. Rxb3 c1=Q 55. Rb6 Qc4+ 56. Kb7 Qe4+ 57. Nc6 Qd5 $1 58. Kc7 Qd6+ 59. Kb7 Qd7+ 60. Kb8 f4 {An excellent endgame performance by Carlsen who was rewarded for his persistence.} 0-1


