{Going into the seventh round, Carlsen had a clear lead over the rest of the field. Moreover, having the white pieces against Wei Yi must have seemed a good opportunity for him to extend his lead in the tournament. Diagram [#] After a quiet opening we have reached a typical Grunfeld middlegame where White has more space and the two bishops, while Black has good control of the dark squares and a strong knight on d6. Though my preference is for White, as Black’s position is slightly passive, breaching Black’s fortress is not at all easy.} 18. b3 {Carlsen correctly tries to restrict Black’s knights by denying them access to the important c4 square.} Rc8 19. Qd2 Nd7 {Wei Yi tries to improve his worst placed piece, whilst at the same time making way for his queen to go to the a5 square.} 20. Na4 $146 {Carlsen prevents ...Qa5 but this comes at a price, since he is forced to exchange a pair of rooks.} ({After} 20. g4 $5 Qa5 21. Nb1 Qxd2 22. Nxd2 Rxc1 23. Rxc1 Bd4 $14 {White is marginally better but Black’s fortress will be a tough nut to break.}) (20. Ne4 Be5 $13 (20... Nxe4 $145 {Matveeva,Svetlana 2454 - Huang,Qian 2380, Russia vs. China (m) 2006})) 20... Rxc1 21. Qxc1 (21. Rxc1 Be5 22. Bxe5 Nxe5 23. Bg2 Nd7 24. b4 $14) 21... Bd4 22. Qd2 Bg7 23. h4 (23. g4 $5 $14 {, grabbing more space on the kingside, was an interesting alternative.}) 23... h5 24. Nb2 (24. Bg2 $5 {, slightly improving the bishop before deciding what to do with the knight on a4, could be a possible improvement.}) 24... Nb5 25. Re3 Nd4 26. Bg2 {Diagram [#]} e5 $5 {Wei Yi decides that no longer wants to wait and therefore opens the position. His calculation proves to be accurate and he equalises the game completely.} (26... Nf5 27. Re1 Nf6 {followed by ...Ng4 was another reasonable setup for Black.}) 27. dxe6 Nxe6 28. Nc4 (28. Rd3 $5 {had to be calculated precisely by Wei Yi.} Nxf4 29. Rxd7 Ne2+ 30. Kh2 Qf6 31. Nd1 b5 32. Bd5 Re7 33. Rd6 $1 Qf5 34. Rxa6 Kh7 $1 {leaves Black with good enough compensation and he does not stand worse.}) (28. Bxb7 $4 Ndc5 $19) 28... Nxf4 29. Rxe8+ Qxe8 30. Qxf4 b5 (30... Qe1+ $5 31. Bf1 b5 32. Ne3 Ne5 $11) 31. Ne3 Qe5 (31... Qe7 $11) 32. Qxe5 {Diagram [#]} Bxe5 $6 {Probably feeling that he had easily equalised, Wei Yi made a couple of rather hasty moves which have handed Carlsen a tiny edge and prompted him to play on.} (32... Nxe5 $11) 33. b4 $1 {Carlsen fixes a weakness on a6 but his opponent will defend stubbornly and never allow him any real winning chances.} Bd6 34. Bb7 Nb8 35. Nd5 Kf8 36. Kg2 Ke8 37. f3 f5 $1 {(Black correctly prevents g4.) Diagram [#]} 38. Kf2 (38. Kh3 Kd7 39. g4 Ke6 (39... hxg4+ 40. fxg4 Ke6 41. g5 {and Black hasn’t fully equalised yet.}) 40. gxh5 gxh5 41. f4 Nd7 42. Kg3 Nf8 43. Ne3 Bxb4 44. Bc8+ Kd6 45. Bxa6 (45. Nxf5+ Kc7 $11) 45... Kc5 46. Bc8 Be1+ 47. Kh3 Bf2 48. Nd1 Be1 49. Bxf5 Kd4 {should end in a draw.}) 38... Kd7 39. Nf4 Kc7 40. Bd5 Bxf4 $1 41. gxf4 Kd6 42. Bf7 Nc6 43. a3 Ne7 $11 {Diagram [#] Carlsen tries hard to breach Wei Yi’s fortress but to no avail.} 44. Ke1 Kd7 45. Kd1 Kd6 46. Kd2 Kd7 47. Kd3 Kd6 48. Kc2 Kd7 49. Kb3 Kd6 50. a4 Nc6 51. axb5 axb5 52. Kc3 (52. Bxg6 Nd4+ 53. Kc3 Nxf3 54. Bxh5 Nxh4 $11) 52... Ne7 53. Kd2 Nd5 54. Bxg6 Nxb4 55. Bxh5 Nd5 56. Be8 Nxf4 57. Bxb5 Ke5 58. Bf1 Ng6 59. h5 Nh4 60. Ke2 Nxf3 1/2-1/2


