{Going into the seventh round, Carlsen had a clear lead over the rest of the field. Moreover, having the white pieces against Wei Yi must have seemed a good opportunity for him to extend his lead in the tournament. Diagram [#] After a quiet opening we have reached a typical Grunfeld middlegame where White has more space and the two bishops, while Black has good control of the dark squares and a strong knight on d6. Though my preference is for White, as Black’s position is slightly passive, breaching Black’s fortress is not at all easy.} 1. e4 {Carlsen correctly tries to restrict Black’s knights by denying them access to the important c4 square.} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 {Wei Yi tries to improve his worst placed piece, whilst at the same time making way for his queen to go to the a5 square.} 3. Bc4 $146 {Carlsen prevents ...Qa5 but this comes at a price, since he is forced to exchange a pair of rooks.} Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d3 d6 6. O-O h6 7. Re1 O-O 8. Nbd2 a5 9. Nf1 {Diagram [#]} Be6 $5 {Wei Yi decides that no longer wants to wait and therefore opens the position. His calculation proves to be accurate and he equalises the game completely.} 10. Bb5 Ne7 11. d4 exd4 12. cxd4 Bb6 13. Ng3 d5 14. e5 Ne4 15. Be3 {Diagram [#]} Nf5 $6 {Probably feeling that he had easily equalised, Wei Yi made a couple of rather hasty moves which have handed Carlsen a tiny edge and prompted him to play on.} (15... Nxg3 $11 16. fxg3) 16. Nxf5 $1 {Carlsen fixes a weakness on a6 but his opponent will defend stubbornly and never allow him any real winning chances.} Bxf5 17. Nd2 (17. Qc2 c6 18. Bd3 f6) 17... Nxd2 18. Qxd2 a4 19. b4 (19. Qd1) 19... axb3 20. axb3 c6 $1 {(Black correctly prevents g4.) Diagram [#]} 21. Be2 Qe7 22. h3 Ra3 23. b4 Rfa8 $1 24. Rxa3 Rxa3 25. Rc1 Rb3 26. b5 Qb4 $11 {Diagram [#] Carlsen tries hard to breach Wei Yi’s fortress but to no avail.} 27. Qd1 Rb1 28. Rxb1 Qxb1 29. Qxb1 Bxb1 30. bxc6 bxc6 31. Bd1 Bd3 32. f4 f6 33. Kf2 Kf7 34. Ba4 fxe5 35. fxe5 Bb5 36. Bc2 Ba5 37. g4 Bc3 38. Bf5 c5 