1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O Nf6 5. c4 O-O 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. d4 {Glenn Flear: 'After an offbeat move order, we arrive at one of the main lines of the Neo-Grünfeld.'} Nb6 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. d5 Na5 10. e4 c6 11. Bf4 {Glenn Flear: 'White has scored well with this active development of the bishop.'} Nac4 12. Qe2 cxd5 13. exd5 Bg4 ({Instead} 13... Nxb2 {was played in Game 6.}) ({I quite like} 13... Bf5 {where the bishop can dodge any efforts by the knight on f3 to trade it off:} 14. Rac1 Rc8 {after} 15. Nh4 $5 (15. b3 Nd6 16. Ne5 Nd7 17. Rfe1 Re8 {(Black has built up a solid defensive set-up without making any concessions)} 18. h4 Qa5 19. Na4 Nxe5 20. Bxe5 Bh6 {Valsecchi, A - Cheparinov, I Skopje 2013}) 15... Bd7 {the knight on h4 doesn't look great to me but, going further...} 16. b3 Nd6 17. Be5 Bh6 18. Rcd1 Re8 19. Rfe1 {Black couldn't find anything better than} Nf5 {in a fairly recent encounter. Then White correctly aimed to increase his grip with} 20. Nxf5 Bxf5 21. g4 Nd7 $5 ({resourceful, as} 21... Bd7 22. Ne4 {would leave the first player with nagging pressure}) {This tense game continued with} 22. Bd4 e5 $1 23. dxe6 Rxe6 24. Qf3 Bc2 25. Ra1 {(Khismatullin, D - Duzhakov, I Moscow 2015) and now} Nc5 $1 {would have been fine for Black.}) ({The remaining (reasonable) square for the bishop is d7:} 13... Bd7 14. Rac1 Rc8 15. Rfe1 Re8 16. b3 Nd6 {(Black digs in. He has good squares for his pieces, but lacks space)} 17. Ne5 h6 ({it's too late for} 17... Bf5 {because of} 18. g4 $1 {pushing the bishop back}) 18. Qd2 g5 19. Nxd7 Nxd7 20. Bxd6 (20. Be3 {is simpler, keeping more space and retaining some hopes of exploiting Black's loose kingside}) 20... Rxc3 ({trading the dark-squared bishops with} 20... Bxc3 $1 21. Rxc3 exd6 {looks like a better idea. Black has to be careful on the kingside, but should still be OK.}) 21. Bb4 Rxc1 22. Qxc1 Ne5 {Kunte, A - Sengupta, D Aurangabad 2011, and you have to surely prefer the side with the bishop pair.}) 14. h3 Bxf3 15. Bxf3 Nd6 ({Glenn Flear: 'Similar is'} 15... Rc8 {- 59/(491)} 16. Rac1 Nd6 17. Rfe1 Re8 {but then} 18. Nb5 Rxc1 19. Rxc1 Qd7 20. Nxd6 (20. Nxa7 Ra8 $11) 20... exd6 21. Qd2 Be5 $11 {had simplified to equality in Lipka, J - Tuncer, U Austrian league 2014.}) 16. Rfe1 ({White employed an enterprising plan in the following:} 16. Rac1 a6 17. h4 Rc8 ({as usual in such cases, it's a tough call, but} 17... h5 {would avoid getting squeezed too badly at the risk of presenting the opponent with some kingside targets}) 18. h5 Rc4 19. h6 Bh8 20. Rfe1 {Almada, E - Rogers, I Luzern 1999, when the h-pawn has a cramping effect.}) 16... Re8 17. Rac1 a6 18. b3 Rc8 19. Qd2 Nd7 20. Na4 $146 (20. g4 $5 Qa5 21. Nb1 Qxd2 22. Nxd2 Rxc1 23. Rxc1 Bd4 $14) ({Glenn Flear: 'Only now do we vary from known territory. Previously'} 20. Ne4 Nxe4 21. Bxe4 Qb6 22. Bg2 Rxc1 23. Rxc1 Be5 24. Be3 Qd6 {was seen in Matveeva, S - Huang Qian, Ergun 2006, when the bishop pair yields a small but enduring pull.}) 20... Rxc1 21. Qxc1 (21. Rxc1 Be5 22. Bxe5 Nxe5 23. Bg2 Nd7 24. b4 $14) 21... Bd4 22. Qd2 Bg7 {Glenn Flear: 'Just biding his time.'} 23. h4 (23. g4 $5 $14) 23... h5 {Glenn Flear: 'This is generally sensible, that is when White is unlikely to be able to get any sacrifices in to open Black's king.'} 24. Nb2 (24. Bg2 $5) 24... Nb5 25. Re3 Nd4 26. Bg2 {Diagram  Diagram [#]} e5 $5 {Glenn Flear: '!' '!' Glenn Flear: 'Wei Yi goes for freedom over passivity.'} (26... Nf5 27. Re1 Nf6 $132) 27. dxe6 Nxe6 28. Nc4 (28. Bxb7 $4 Ndc5 $19) (28. Rd3 Nxf4 29. Rxd7 Ne2+ 30. Kh2 Qf6 31. Nd1 b5 32. Bd5 Re7 33. Rd6 $1 Qf5 34. Rxa6 Kh7 $1 $44) ({Here, retaining the bishop with} 28. Bd6 $6 {may seem more natural, but then} Ne5 $1 29. Qd5 $6 Ng4 $1 30. Re2 Bd4 {leaves Black on top. So self-pinning down the d-file isn't a good idea.}) 28... Nxf4 29. Rxe8+ Qxe8 30. Qxf4 b5 {Glenn Flear: 'It must be a nice feeling to have equalized against Carlsen!'} (30... Qe1+ $5 31. Bf1 b5 32. Ne3 Ne5 $11) 31. Ne3 Qe5 (31... Qe7 $11) 32. Qxe5 Bxe5 $6 {Glenn Flear: 'The endgame is drawish, but how many times have Carlsen's opponents thought that in the past and yet ultimately been ground down?'} (32... Nxe5 $11) 33. b4 $1 Bd6 34. Bb7 Nb8 35. Nd5 Kf8 36. Kg2 Ke8 37. f3 {Glenn Flear: 'Maybe g4 is a half-threat, hence Black's reply.'} f5 $1 {Glenn Flear: '!?' '!?'} 38. Kf2 (38. Kh3 Kd7 39. g4 Ke6 (39... hxg4+ 40. fxg4 Ke6 41. g5 $14) 40. gxh5 gxh5 41. f4 Nd7 42. Kg3 Nf8 43. Ne3 Bxb4 44. Bc8+ Kd6 45. Bxa6 (45. Nxf5+ Kc7 $11) 45... Kc5 46. Bc8 Be1+ 47. Kh3 Bf2 48. Nd1 Be1 49. Bxf5 Kd4 $11) 38... Kd7 {Glenn Flear: '!' '!' Glenn Flear: 'This needed calculating!'} 39. Nf4 Kc7 40. Bd5 {Diagram  Diagram [#]} Bxf4 $1 41. gxf4 Kd6 (41... Nd7 42. Bf7 Nf8 {would have been passive. It might nevertheless hold, but Wei Yi prefers placing the knight on e7.}) 42. Bf7 Nc6 43. a3 (43. Bxg6 Nxb4 {won't favour White if he loses his a-pawn.}) 43... Ne7 $11 44. Ke1 Kd7 45. Kd1 Kd6 46. Kd2 Kd7 47. Kd3 Kd6 {Glenn Flear: 'White's only try is the a4-break, but it shouldn't lead anywhere against a 'responsible' defence.'} 48. Kc2 Kd7 49. Kb3 Kd6 50. a4 Nc6 {Glenn Flear: '!?' '!?'} 51. axb5 axb5 52. Kc3 ({Glenn Flear: 'Or'} 52. Bxg6 Nd4+ 53. Kc3 Nxf3 54. Bxh5 (54. Bxf5 Nxh4 55. Be4 Ke6 56. Kd4 Nf5+ $11) 54... Nxh4 $11) 52... Ne7 53. Kd2 Nd5 {Glenn Flear: 'Not the only way, but sufficient to earn half-a-point.'} 54. Bxg6 Nxb4 55. Bxh5 Nd5 56. Be8 Nxf4 57. Bxb5 Ke5 58. Bf1 Ng6 59. h5 Nh4 60. Ke2 Nxf3 {Glenn Flear: 'The black king heads to the h8-square with a book draw.'} 1/2-1/2


