1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. h3 O-O 6. Nf3 e5 7. d5 a5 8. Bg5 Na6 9. Be2 {Vigorito,D: 'Now we are technically in a Petrosian Variation.'} Qe8 10. g4 (10. Nd2 Nd7 11. a3 h6 $6 {see Movsesian, S (2698) -Grischuk, A (2763) Istanbul 2012.}) 10... Kh8 {Vigorito,D: 'Generally I do not like to play this move unless White has played Rg1, but Black has done well here in the past.'} ({Instead} 10... Nc5 {see Varga, P (2475)-Efimenko, Z (2435) Master Open, Lausanne 2001.}) ({I have expressed preference for} 10... Nd7 $1 {and only after} 11. Rg1 (11. Nd2 Ndc5 {intending ...f5}) (11. a3 Nb6 $1 {is another typical idea}) 11... Kh8 ({or just} 11... Ndc5)) 11. Nd2 {Not the most accurate move order.} ({Korobov's} 11. Be3 {is more appropriate here (see my "Opening trends" article in CBM 182).} Ng8 12. g5 $5 {see Korobov,A (2705)-Smirin,I  (2638) Eilat 2012} ({This turns out to be very effective. White can also play more slowly with} 12. Nd2)) 11... Ng8 $1 {Vigorito,D: 'Preparing ...f5 and possibly ...Bh6.'} 12. h4 f5 {Vigorito,D: 'this has scored very well for Black'} ({It makes no sense to insert} 12... f6 {since White's bishop is not placed well on g5. Here is an example:} 13. Be3 f5 14. gxf5 (14. f3 $1 f4 15. Bf2 {is better for White, because all the play will shift to the queenside, where White has a significant space advantage.}) 14... gxf5 15. exf5 Bxf5 (15... Nh6 16. Bh5 Qd7 17. f6 Rxf6 18. Nde4 Rf8 {0-1 (44) Polivanov,A (2421)-Vovk,A (2339) Lvov 2005} 19. Qd2 Nf5 20. O-O-O $14) (15... Bh6 16. Bg5 Bxg5 17. hxg5 Bxf5 18. Nde4 $14 {1/2 (18) Giddins,S (2290)-Gullaksen,E (2365) Skei 1995}) 16. Nde4 Nf6 17. Ng3 Qd7 {(Black's bishop has no h7-square)} 18. h5 Rf7 19. h6 Bf8 20. Bd3 Bxd3 21. Qxd3 Ng4 22. Nce4 Nxe3 23. fxe3 Qg4 24. Kd2 $14 {0-1 (36) Polak,T (2544)-Novikov,S (2562) Pardubice 2007}) (12... h6 $5 13. Be3 f5 {is possible, transposing to the position from my game against Spirin, examined in the same article.}) 13. gxf5 ({Vigorito,D: 'After'} 13. f3 fxg4 $5 (13... f4 {Vigorito,D: 'Black threatens to win the g5-bishop, and'} 14. h5 Bf6 {Vigorito,D: 'allows Black to both trade his bad bishop and keep some open lines on the kingside.'} 15. hxg6 Qxg6 16. Bxf6+ Nxf6 17. Nb3 b6 18. Qd2 Bd7 19. O-O-O $14 {0-1 (40) Lazarev,V (2500)-Cebalo,M (2465) Estensi 2001} Kg7 20. Rdg1 h6 {with chances for both sides in Lazarev,V (2500)-Cebalo,M (2465) Lido degli Estensi 2001, 0-1 (40)}) 14. fxg4 Nf6 $132) 13... gxf5 14. Bh5 {Vigorito,D: '!?' '!?'} (14. exf5 Bxf5 15. Nde4 Nf6 16. Ng3 Qd7 {Vigorito,D: '!' '!'} 17. Rg1 Nb4 {Vigorito,D: '' '' Vigorito,D: 'Georgiadis,I (2449)-Simeonidis,I (2238) Rethymno 2013, 1/2-1/2 (45)'} 18. Rc1 e4 $132 {1/2 (45) Georgiadis,I (2449)-Simeonidis,I (2238) Rethymno 2013}) (14. Qc2 {has been played in some correspondence games.} Nf6 (14... Nb4 15. Qb3 Nf6 16. O-O-O Nd7 17. Qa3 Nc5 $132 {Sidenko,A (2286) -Mancuso,A (2244) Lechenicher SchachServer 2010}) 15. a3 Nc5 16. exf5 e4 (16... Qd7 $5 $146) 17. h5 Bxf5 {led to a mess. Make of it what you will, with engines running.} 18. h6 Nd3+ 19. Kf1 Nxf2 $1 20. hxg7+ Kxg7 21. Rg1 Kh8 22. Nb5 Nd3 23. Rg3 Bg4 24. Bxd3 Nh5+ 25. Kg1 Nxg3 26. Nxe4 Qh5 $1 $19 27. Qh2 Nxe4 28. Bxe4 Bh3 29. Bg2 Qxg5 30. Qxh3 Rf6 31. Nxc7 Rg8 32. Ne6 Qd2 33. Rf1 Rxg2+ 34. Qxg2 Qe3+ 35. Rf2 Rg6 36. b3 Rxg2+ 37. Kxg2 h5 38. Rf3 Qe2+ 39. Kg3 h4+ 40. Kf4 a4 {0-1 (40) Malkov,A (2233)-Ulasevich,S (2319) ICCF 2012}) 14... Qd7 {Vigorito,D: 'Now both the Bh5 and Qd7 are somewhat misplaced.'} 15. Qe2 {Vigorito,D: 'N' 'N'} (15. exf5 {Vigorito,D: '?!' '?!'} Qxf5 16. Nde4 Nc5 {Vigorito,D: '!' '!' Vigorito,D: 'is already looking good for Black.'} 17. Qe2 Nxe4 18. Nxe4 Nf6 19. Ng3 Qd7 20. Rg1 {Vigorito,D: 'Solomon,K (2350)-Popovic,D (2553) Cappelle-la-Grande 2014'} c6 $132 {0-1 (32) Solomon,K (2350)-Popovic,D (2553) Cappelle-la-Grande 2014} (20... b5 $1 {with excellent play.})) 15... Nf6 16. Bf3 fxe4 $6 {[%mdl 32] Vigorito,D: 'A concrete move.'} (16... Nc5 {is a normal continuation. If} 17. O-O-O {then} fxe4 (17... Qf7 $5) 18. Ndxe4 Nfxe4 19. Nxe4 Qf5 $1 20. Bg2 Nxe4 21. Bxe4 Qxf2 22. Qh5 (22. Qxf2 Rxf2 23. Rdf1 Rxf1+ 24. Rxf1 Bg4 25. Rf7 Rc8 {[%cal Yh8g8]}) 22... Bf5 23. Rhf1 Bxe4 $1 24. Rxf2 Rxf2 $44) (16... Qf7 {was also possible.}) 17. Ndxe4 Nxe4 18. Nxe4 Nb4 {Alas, sending Black's knight to c5 is not so easy now:} (18... Nc5 $6 19. Nxc5 dxc5 {[%csl Re5]} 20. Rg1 $16) (18... b6 19. Rg1 Nc5 20. Nxc5 bxc5 21. Be4 Qf7 22. f3 $14) 19. Bg2 ({Of course not} 19. a3 $2 Nc2+ 20. Qxc2 Rxf3) 19... Qa4 {Vigorito,D: 'Always aggressive, but White's 21st move will give him a sizable advantage.'} (19... c6 $5 {was probably a better way to create counterplay.}) (19... Qg4 $5 20. Bh3 Qxe2+ 21. Kxe2 Bxh3 22. Rxh3 b5 $5) 20. Nc3 (20. b3 Qe8 {leaves the queenside softened up.}) 20... Qc2 21. Be4 {Vigorito,D: '!' '!' Vigorito,D: 'The only move, but strong.'} Qxe2+ 22. Kxe2 $14 {After the exchange of queens White's king is safe, and he keeps the better prospects due to Black's passive g7 bishop.} Bg4+ {Vigorito,D: '?!' '?!'} ({A better try was} 22... Bf5) 23. f3 Bh5 24. Rag1 Rf7 $6 (24... Na6 $5 {[%cal Ya6c5]} 25. Be3 Bf6 {[%cal Yf8g8]}) 25. Be3 Bf6 $2 ({It was better to "take the last move back":} 25... Rff8) (25... Raf8 26. Rh3 $16) 26. Rg5 {[%mdl 64] Vigorito,D: '!' '!' This is what Black missed. He can't take the rook so material losses are inevitable.} ({Vigorito,D: 'Even more accurate was' But} 26. a3 $1 Na6 27. Rg5 $1 {was even more accurate. Black had no ideas with ...b4-c2 in that case.}) 26... Bg6 (26... Bxg5 27. hxg5 $18) 27. Bxg6 hxg6 28. Rxg6 {Vigorito,D: '+-' '+-' Vigorito,D: 'It's a bit of a mop-up now.'} Nc2 29. Ne4 Be7 30. Ng5 Rf6 31. Rxf6 Bxf6 32. Ne6 {White easily converts his material and positional advantage.} Nxe3 33. Kxe3 Rg8 34. Ke4 c6 35. Kf5 Be7 36. Ng5 Re8 37. Ne4 Kg7 38. Ke6 Bf8+ 39. Kd7 Re7+ 40. Kxd6 Kf7 41. Rg1 cxd5 42. cxd5 Ke8 43. Nf6+ Kd8 (43... Kf7 44. Nd7 $5) 44. Rg8 Re8+ 45. Rxf8 Rxf8 46. Ke6 {[%csl Rf8]} Rh8 47. h5 b5 48. d6 {Black's king and rook are completely paralysed.} 1-0


