1. d4 {Krasenkow,M} Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Bg2 Bg7 6. e4 Nb6 7. Ne2 c5 8. d5 O-O 9. O-O e6 10. Nec3 Na6 11. a3 $5 {A rare continuation in this well-known theoretical position. Its idea is to restrict Black's a6-knight. The c5-square will be controlled by the bishop (from e3).} (11. a4 {[%cal Ya4a5] and}) (11. Na3 {are main lines here.}) 11... c4 {[%cal Ya6c5]} ({White successfully outplayed Black in the following game:} 11... exd5 12. exd5 Nc4 13. Nd2 Nd6 14. Nde4 Nxe4 15. Nxe4 Qb6 16. Rb1 Rd8 17. Bg5 f6 18. Be3 $16 Qa5 $2 19. Nxc5 $1 {1-0 (57) Pustovoitova,D (2315)-Gluszko,M (2077) Albena 2011}) 12. Be3 exd5 13. exd5 Bf5 {OK, the a6-knight is cut off but other pieces can be developed.} 14. d6 Rb8 15. Re1 Re8 (15... Bd3 $5 {needs analysis. Generally, the 11.a3 line is likely to become an object of study and practice in the near future.}) 16. Nd2 {The only but good way for White to develop his queenside.} Qxd6 17. Bf4 Be5 18. Rxe5 $1 Rxe5 19. Nde4 Qxd1+ (19... Qe6 $2 20. Qd4 Re8 21. Bxe5 Qxe5 22. Nf6+) (19... Qe7 20. Bg5 $40) 20. Rxd1 Bxe4 21. Nxe4 Rbe8 22. Nf6+ Kg7 23. Nxe8+ Rxe8 24. Be3 $1 (24. Bxb7 $143 Nc5) 24... Re7 25. Rd6 Nc7 26. Bd4+ Kh6 27. Bxb6 Ne8 28. Rd4 axb6 29. Rxc4 {[%mdl 4096] As a result, White has a clear pull in the endgame: his bishop is stronger than Black's knight as the position is open and pawns are on both flanks; besides, Black's pawn structure is damaged.} Re1+ 30. Bf1 Nd6 31. Rb4 Nc8 32. Kg2 f5 33. Rd4 Re7 34. h4 Rc7 35. Kf3 Kg7 36. Ke3 Ne7 37. Bg2 Kf7 38. Rd6 f4+ {This tactical trick reduces the number of pawns.} 39. Kd3 (39. Kxf4 $5 Rc2 40. b4 Rxf2+ 41. Bf3) 39... fxg3 40. fxg3 Nc8 41. Rd8 Ke7 42. Rh8 Kf6 43. Bxb7 Nd6 44. Bg2 Nf5 45. Rf8+ Kg7 46. Rb8 Rd7+ 47. Kc3 Rd6 48. Rb7+ Kh6 49. a4 Nxg3 {Black has recaptured the pawn but the position is now asymmetric, with potential passed pawns on both sides; the bishop is much more powerful than the knight in such cases. However, Black retains fair drawing chances as there are too few pawns on the board!} 50. b4 Ne2+ 51. Kc2 Nd4+ 52. Kb2 Nf5 53. Be4 $2 {After this move Black liquidates into the ending "+ vs " and saves the game.} (53. Bf1 $142 $1 {[%cal Ya4a5]} Ne3 (53... Nxh4 54. a5) 54. Ba6 {Perhaps, though, it was not enough for a victory either.}) 53... Nxh4 54. a5 bxa5 55. bxa5 Nf5 $5 56. Bxf5 (56. Rb6 Rxb6+ 57. axb6 Nd6 58. Bd5 Kg5 59. Kc3 h5 60. Kd4 Kf6 $11) 56... Rd5 57. Be6 Rxa5 58. Bg8 Kg5 59. Rxh7 Kf4 60. Kc3 g5 61. Be6 g4 62. Rf7+ Kg3 63. Rg7 Ra4 64. Kd3 Kf3 65. Bd5+ Kf2 66. Rf7+ Kg3 67. Rg7 Kf2 68. Rf7+ Kg3 69. Ke3 Ra3+ 70. Ke2 Ra4 71. Rf1 Ra5 72. Rg1+ Kf4 73. Rd1 Kg3 74. Rd4 Rc5 75. Rd3+ Kh2 76. Ke3 Ra5 77. Kf4 Ra4+ 78. Kg5 g3 79. Rd1 g2 80. Rd2 Rd4 81. Rxg2+ Kh3 82. Bf3 Rd8 83. Kf4 Rf8+ {A so-called "defence on the 3rd rank" (the f-file plays that role here).} 84. Ke3 Rb8 85. Rg7 Kh4 86. Rg4+ Kh3 87. Rg6 Kh4 88. Be4 (88. Kf2 Rb4 {is the so-called "Szen position".}) 88... Rf8 89. Bf3 Rf5 90. Rg7 Rg5 91. Rb7 Kg3 {"Defence on the 2nd rank" (here - g-file).} 92. Rb2 Re5+ 93. Be4 Rg5 94. Rb1 Kg4 95. Bf3+ Kg3 96. Rh1 Re5+ 97. Be4 Rg5 98. Rf1 Kg4 99. Rf4+ Kg3 100. Bf5 Rg7 101. Rf3+ Kh4 102. Kf4 Rg4+ {A well-known stalemate trick.} 103. Ke5 Rg3 104. Rf1 Kg5 105. Rh1 Re3+ 106. Be4 Rg3 107. Rh8 Kg4 108. Rf8 Kg5 109. Rh8 Kg4 110. Bf5+ Kg5 111. Bg6 Re3+ 112. Be4 Rg3 113. Rh7 Kg4 114. Rf7 Kg5 115. Bf3 Kh4 116. Ke4 (116. Kf4 Rg4+ $1) 116... Rg5 $6 {After this move White destroys Black's front line of defence.} (116... Kg5 $142) 117. Rh7+ Kg3 118. Rh1 Rb5 {Of course, the position remains drawish anyway but Black must now use other methods.} 119. Rg1+ Kf2 120. Rg2+ Ke1 121. Kf4 Rb8 122. Ra2 Rc8 123. Re2+ Kf1 124. Rb2 Ke1 125. Kg3 Rg8+ 126. Bg4 Re8 {The Szen position again.} 127. Kf4 Rf8+ 128. Bf5 Kf1 129. Ra2 Rf7 130. Ke4 Kg1 1/2-1/2


