{[%evp 0,89,28,28,65,65,73,42,53,58,60,6,6,9,0,-14,-4,-4,-13,-37,-53,-13,-13,-4,1,16,19,8,3,17,22,22,5,-18,-8,-18,1,1,19,14,35,-23,-10,0,-14,-1,-1,0,0,-8,-4,-6,25,-23,17,45,88,95,84,91,82,88,101,98,99,102,102,111,114,81,108,114,119,117,119,119,143,145,144,148,141,151,151,151,159,156,156,168,194,214,560,690]} 1. e4 {Milanovic,Danilo} c5 2. Nc3 d6 3. f4 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bc4 Nc6 6. O-O e6 7. d4 $5 {This is a completely different approach to the Grand Prix Attack compared to the usual build-up with d3, e1, etc., leading into more of Open Sicilian types of positions. Recently, an increasing number of strong players, most notably Alexander Grischuk, have been using it to good effect. As practice has shown, this variation is ideal for shorter time controls because just one mistake in the opening can quickly land Black in serious trouble. Even if Black plays the opening accurately, White typically gets at least a decent version of the Dragon since the black pawn structure has been compromised by the move 6...e6. The Grand Prix f4-f5 charge remains the central attacking theme in the resulting positions.} cxd4 ({In today's online-chess world, an unaware opponent could take 7.d4 as a mouse-slip (instead of the more common 7.d3) and just grab the 'free' pawn with} 7... Nxd4 $6 {However, this is already a dubious decision because White takes the initiative with} 8. Be3 $1 Nf6 {Black needs to return the pawn to complete his development, otherwise he gets in trouble.} (8... Nxf3+ $6 9. Qxf3 $40 {already gives White too much activity for the pawn. With 10.f5 coming, Black is bound to come under a strong attack.} Ne7 10. Rad1 ({A more clinical way was} 10. f5 $1 exf5 11. exf5 Nxf5 12. g4 $18) 10... O-O 11. Bxc5 Qc7 12. Bxd6 Qxc4 13. Bxe7 $18 {1-0 (24) Grischuk,A (2750)-Vachier Lagrave,M (2795) chess.com INT 2017}) ({Another important variation is} 8... Qb6 9. e5 $1 Nxf3+ 10. Qxf3 d5 11. Bb5+ Kf8 12. b4 $1 {Keeping the initiative.} d4 13. bxc5 Qxc5 14. Rad1 $1 {A powerful move, setting up back-rank checkmate ideas.} Qxc3 15. Bxd4 Qc7 {0-1 (84) Narayanan,S (2618)-Muradli,M (2449) lichess.org INT 2020} {and here White could have obtained a winning position with a surprisingly strong} 16. Qc3 $1 Qxc3 17. Bxc3 $18 {The rook is coming to the 8th rank with devastating threats.}) ({It is possible to force an endgame with} 8... Bd7 9. Nxd4 cxd4 10. Bxd4 Bxd4+ 11. Qxd4 Qb6 {but in the game below, Black duly suffered due to the weakness of d6 and other queenside pawns.} 12. Rad1 Ke7 13. Qxb6 axb6 14. Rd4 Bc6 15. Rfd1 $16 Nf6 ({if} 15... Rd8 {then} 16. b4 $1 $18 {with b4-b5 and a4 to follow, winning the b6-pawn.}) 16. Rxd6 b5 17. Bxb5 Nxe4 18. Nxe4 Bxe4 19. Rd7+ Kf6 20. R1d4 Bxc2 {½-½ (29) Darini,P (2475)-Idani,P (2611) Bushehr 2019} 21. a3 $16) 9. Nxd4 cxd4 10. Bxd4 O-O 11. Bb3 $5 $146 {I find this bishop retreat to be more in the spirit of the variation} ({than} 11. Be2 Bd7 12. Qd2 Bc6 13. Qe3 Qa5 $13 {0-1 (32) Manukyan,A (2148)-Abdusattorov,N (2627) Chess.com INT 2020}) 11... Bd7 ({As usual in such positions, Black also has a} 11... b5 $5 {diversion. After the forced sequence:} 12. Nxb5 Ba6 13. c4 Bxb5 14. cxb5 Nxe4 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. Qd4+ Nf6 17. Rac1 $14 {White has a nice positional plus thanks to his powerful queen and the queenside majority. In the event of} Qa5 {there is} 18. g4 $1 $36) 12. Qe2 Re8 ({The bishop on b3 is always a nuisance for Black as it strengthens the f5-break. Here,} 12... Bc6 {would be met by} 13. f5 $36) 13. Rad1 Bc6 14. h3 $14 {White prepares f2 with e4-e5 or f4-f5, depending on Black's actions.}) 8. Nb5 Nge7 {The most popular move, although by no means the only playable option for Black here.} ({The main alternative is} 8... a6 9. Nbxd4 {Here, too, Black have many options besides the most straightforward} Nge7 (9... d5 {looks slightly suspicious with the king on e8, but might well be playable.} 10. Nxc6 ({In the event of} 10. exd5 exd5 11. Bb3 {Black can solve the issues on the e-file with} Nf6 $1 (11... Nge7 {on the other hand, is met by the thematic pawn sacrifice:} 12. f5 $1 Nxf5 13. Re1+ Kf8 14. Nxf5 Bxf5 15. c3 $36) 12. Re1+ Ne4 $11) 10... bxc6 11. Bd3 Ne7 {Too passive.} ({Black should be doing well with the more active} 11... dxe4 $1 12. Bxe4 Qb6+ 13. Kh1 Nf6 14. Bd3 O-O 15. Ne5 c5 $132) 12. Qe2 O-O 13. c4 Bb7 14. Be3 $14 {1-0 (35) Gabuzyan,H (2620)-Preotu,R (2512) New York 2019}) (9... Nxd4 10. Nxd4 Nf6 {should deserve serious attention as a more active way to develop the knight.} (10... b5 {is not a helpful inclusion, as seen in the game below:} 11. Bb3 Nf6 12. f5 O-O 13. fxe6 ({but} 13. Bg5 $1 {was clearly stronger, and if} h6 {then} 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. c3 $36) 13... fxe6 14. Nxe6 $6 Bxe6 15. Bxe6+ Kh8 $132 {[%csl Re4] 0-1 (27) Sunilduth Lyna,N (2928)-Ruiz,J (2737) Chess.com INT 2020}) 11. f5 e5 ({The move order} 11... gxf5 12. exf5 e5 {has the benefit of avoiding the tricky 12.g5 option, most likely transposing into the game continuation.}) 12. Nf3 (12. Bg5 $5 {is a dangerous idea.} exd4 (12... Qc7 13. Qe2 Nxe4 14. Qxe4 Qxc4 15. Rad1 $36) 13. fxg6 hxg6 14. Qxd4 Ng4 $1 {The only way for Black to stay afloat.} 15. Bxf7+ Kd7 16. e5 $1 {White can keep attacking thanks to this move.} ({Of course, there is also the less ambitious} 16. Be6+ Ke8 17. Bf7+ $11) 16... Nxe5 17. Qe3 Qa5 18. Rad1 {The position is double-edged, but Black is clearly under more pressure. Here is a sample line:} Kc7 19. Be7 Bf8 20. Rd5 Nc4 $1 21. Bd8+ $1 Kb8 22. Qe8 $36) 12... gxf5 13. Ng5 $6 ({The critical continuation is} 13. exf5 Qc7 14. Bb3 Bd7 15. Bg5 Bc6 $13 {Black is preparing to castle queenside, with an original and complicated position.}) 13... O-O (13... d5 $1 {would have extinguished White's attacking hopes.} 14. Bxd5 Nxd5 15. exd5 f4 $17) 14. exf5 d5 $15 15. Bb3 Bd7 16. Qe1 Bb5 $6 17. Rf3 e4 18. Rg3 Bd7 19. Qf2 Qc8 20. Nh3 Bxf5 21. Rxg7+ Kxg7 22. Qh4 Ng8 23. Nf4 $16 {1-0 (32) Lazov,T (2405)-Baenziger,F (2409) chess.com INT 2020}) (9... b5 $5 $146 10. Bb3 Na5 {has not been tried yet in this position, but winning the bishop pair like this is a typical idea for Black. The principled continuation would be} 11. f5 Nxb3 12. axb3 e5 13. Ne2 {which bears some resemblance to Fischer's games in the Sozin Attack, at least looking from the White side. Both sides would have chances, as the sample variations below suggest:} Nf6 (13... gxf5 14. exf5 Bb7 15. Ng3 h5 16. f6 $1 Qb6+ 17. Kh1 Bxf6 18. Nf5 O-O-O 19. c4 $13) 14. Ng3 O-O 15. Bg5 Bb7 16. Qe2 d5 $5 17. Nxe5 Qc7 $1 18. Bxf6 Bxf6 19. Ng4 Bxb2 $13) 10. Bb3 O-O (10... Na5 {is somewhat risky now, in the view of the pawn sac} 11. f5 $1 Nxb3 12. axb3 exf5 13. exf5 Bxf5 14. Nxf5 Nxf5 15. Re1+ Kf8 16. g4 Ne7 (16... Nh4 17. Ra4 $1) 17. Bf4 $44 {Practically, this position seems easier to play for White.}) ({Here is a fun (blitz game) miniature that shows exactly how quickly things can go south for Black if he mishandles the opening in this variation:} 10... Nxd4 11. Nxd4 Nc6 12. c3 Bd7 13. Be3 b5 $2 14. f5 $40 Qe7 15. fxe6 fxe6 16. Nxc6 Bxc6 17. Qg4 Kd7 18. Bxe6+ {1-0 (18) Sunilduth Lyna,N (2898)-Yoo,C (2607) Chess.com INT 2020}) 11. c3 Nxd4 {While this move was played in two top-GM games, on closer inspection the alternatives seem better.} (11... Na5 {was a recent choice of a strong theoretician, GM Cheparinov.} 12. Bc2 e5 13. Ne2 ({However,} 13. Nb3 $5 $146 {looks like an improvement for White, trying to force favourable exchanges in the centre.} Nc4 14. fxe5 Nxe5 (14... dxe5 15. Qxd8 Rxd8 16. Nc5 b6 17. Bb3 $14) 15. Nxe5 Bxe5 16. Bg5 $14) 13... b5 14. Qe1 f5 $13 {This looks quite good for Black and he went on to prove his case.} 15. fxe5 dxe5 16. exf5 $6 Bxf5 17. Bxf5 Nxf5 18. Ng3 Qb6+ 19. Rf2 Nxg3 20. hxg3 Nc4 $15 {0-1 (41) Cornette,M (2558)-Cheparinov,I (2660) Sitges ESP 2020}) ({Another recent game saw} 11... Bd7 $5 {and there seems to be nothing wrong with this simple developing approach.} 12. Be3 ({Perhaps, White could try to take advantage of the weak d6-pawn with} 12. Nxc6 $5 {in order to force} Bxc6 {and then continue} 13. Bc2 {preparing 14.d4. Here, Black would need to be more accurate than in the game:} Qd7 (13... b5 14. Nd4 Bb7 15. f5 $36) 14. Nd4 f5 $1 $11) 12... Rc8 13. Qe1 Na5 14. Qh4 Nc4 15. Bxc4 Rxc4 $11 {0-1 (47) Piliposyan,R (2161)-Yilmaz,M (2630) lichess.org INT 2021}) 12. Nxd4 $14 {White has a very comfortable position that can be improved with moves like e3, d2, etc. Meanwhile, Black finds it difficult to complete his development satisfactorily due to the permanent f4-f5 threat. MVL and Nepo have tried to solve these issues by pushing ...e6-e5, but this only created new weaknesses.} b5 (12... e5 13. Nf3 Qc7 $2 {A blunder, although the black position was already clearly worse.} 14. fxe5 dxe5 15. Ng5 $18 Qb6+ 16. Kh1 Be6 17. Nxe6 fxe6 18. Bg5 Rxf1+ 19. Qxf1 Re8 20. Rd1 h6 21. Bh4 Kh7 22. Qf7 {1-0 (22) Nepomniachtchi,I (2775)-Vachier Lagrave,M (2775) Paris 2019}) 13. Be3 Qc7 (13... Bb7 14. f5 $40) 14. Qd2 e5 15. fxe5 dxe5 16. Nf3 Be6 {This has to be played, giving White a long-term positional advantage.} 17. Bxe6 fxe6 18. Rfd1 Rad8 19. Qc2 h6 20. a4 $16 {½-½ (50) Grischuk,A (2767)-Nepomniachtchi,I (2751) Moscow 2018}) ({Black has another interesting option in} 8... d5 $5 9. exd5 exd5 10. Bxd5 Nge7 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 {This pawn sacrifice is more natural than the alternative.} (11... Nxc6 {is playable, although I doubt that many Black players would be excited about their position after} 12. Qe1+ $1 Kf8 (12... Be6 $2 13. f5 $1 gxf5 14. Qg3 $40 {is why we gave the check on e1 and not e2.}) {Here, White has a couple of good options to keep the initiative:} 13. c3 (13. f5 $5 Bxf5 14. Qg3 $36 {preparing 15.d6.}) (13. b3 Kg8 14. Ba3 a6 15. Nc7 Rb8 16. Qe8+ Qxe8 17. Nxe8 Bf5 18. Nxg7 Kxg7 $11) 13... dxc3 14. Nxc3 Kg8 15. Be3 h6 16. Rd1 $36) 12. Nbxd4 O-O $44 {In return for the pawn, Black has comfortably completed his development and will try to utilise his bishop pair in the middlegame.} 13. c3 ({Perhaps it was more accurate to immediately shut down the dark-squared bishop with} 13. Ne5 $5 {while also preparing to develop the queen to f3 at some point.} c5 14. Nb3 Qc7 $44) 13... Rb8 (13... c5 $5 14. Nb3 Qc7 $44) 14. Kh1 Qc7 15. Re1 Nd5 16. Ne5 Bb7 17. Qa4 $2 (17. c4 $14 {with e3 to follow, would have allowed White to consolidate his control of the centre.}) 17... c5 18. Nb5 Qb6 $15 {0-1 (30) Piliposyan,R (2151)-Ter Sahakyan,S (2617) Yerevan 2020}) (8... Na5 {is a rather risky approach. Black chases away the bishop from the a2-g8 diagonal in order to protect the extra pawn with 9...e5.} 9. Be2 ({A reasonable alternative is} 9. Bd3 e5 {½-½ (33) Nepomniachtchi,I (2775)-Giri,A (2779) Paris 2019} {and now an improvement over the game is} 10. fxe5 $5 $146 dxe5 11. Qe1 {preparing the unpleasant 12.b4.} Nc6 (11... a6 {is strongly met by} 12. Bg5 f6 13. Nxe5 $1 axb5 14. Bxb5+ $40) 12. Bc4 f6 13. a4 a6 14. Na3 $44 {Having provoked the weakening ...f6, White has good chances to keep the initiative against the unsafe black king. The next step would be to open the centre with c2-c3.}) 9... e5 $6 {This stubborn attempt to hold onto the pawn does not work tactically.} ({It is more sensible to 'admit the mistake' with} 9... Nc6 $5 {and if} 10. Nbxd4 Nxd4 11. Nxd4 Nf6 {does not look that bad for Black at all.}) 10. fxe5 dxe5 11. Nfxd4 $1 {A nice tactical refutation.} Nf6 (11... exd4 12. Bf4 $18) 12. Nb3 Qb6+ 13. Kh1 O-O {½-½ (69) Chukavin,K (2355)-Kulaots,K (2529) Tallinn 2020} {Here, White could have obtained a nice edge simply with} 14. Nc3 Nxb3 15. axb3 $16) ({One of the first games in this variation saw} 8... Nf6 $6 9. e5 Ne4 {0-1 (14) Kovalev,V (2546)-Kochetkov,G (2338) Minsk 2015} {and here White had a cool, though not so obvious tactical sequence} 10. Ng5 $1 $146 Nxg5 11. Nxd6+ Kf8 12. h4 $1 (12. fxg5 $2 Nxe5 $19) 12... Nh3+ 13. gxh3 Qxh4 14. Qf3 $16) 9. Bb3 {Necessary prophylaxis against ...d6-d5. The d4-pawn won't run away.} (9. Nbxd4 $6 {is too hasty because it allows Black to break free with} d5 10. exd5 {1-0 (61) Sindarov,J (2537)-Drygalov,S (2477) Moscow 2020} {and even get a more promising position by playing} Nxd4 $146 11. Nxd4 O-O $1 12. c3 Nxd5 $15 {without the e4-pawn, the positional weaknesses incurred by the f-pawn push become apparent.}) 9... O-O ({I believe that the best approach for Black is} 9... Na5 $5 {either on this, or on the next move.} 10. Nbxd4 {GM Abhijeet Gupta, an experienced Sicilian player, tried to clarify the situation in the centre straight away with the following sequence:} Nxb3 ({a more flexible move is} 10... O-O $5 {transposing directly into the line 9...0-0 10.bxd4 a5}) 11. axb3 e5 12. Ne2 O-O 13. Nc3 b5 {Besides this dynamic, yet arguably slightly weakening move, Black had a couple of reasonable alternatives:} ({1)} 13... f5 14. fxe5 Qb6+ (14... fxe4 15. Bg5 $1 Qb6+ 16. Rf2 $1 $36) 15. Kh1 dxe5 16. Bg5 Qe6 17. Nb5 $36) ({and 2)} 13... Qb6+ $5 14. Kh1 Qc6 $13 {preparing the ...f5-break in better circumstances}) 14. fxe5 Qb6+ 15. Qd4 ({A stronger try was} 15. Rf2 $1 dxe5 16. Qd3 {preparing c1-e3} b4 17. Be3 Qc6 18. Nd5 Nxd5 19. exd5 $14) 15... Qxd4+ 16. Nxd4 b4 17. Nd5 Nxd5 18. exd5 Bb7 19. Nc6 Bxc6 20. dxc6 Bxe5 $11 {0-1 (68) Prithu,G (2478)-Gupta,A (2602) Reykjavik 2019}) 10. Nbxd4 Nxd4 {Milanovic,Danilo: '?!' From Black's perspective, it makes sense to exchange a pair of knights to provide the c6-square for a rather passive e7-knight.} ({Yet, the alternative a more flexible move is} 10... Na5 $5 {deserves serious consideration. transposing directly into the line 9...0-0 10.bxd4 a5} 11. Be3 a6 {And while this is the most typical way to prepare queenside fianchetto in the Sicilian,} ({a more modest} 11... b6 $5 {might even be more accurate for Black. Interestingly, this was played in the very first game in 7.d4!? variation, between Gajewski and Mikrut way back in 2003! I wonder if the Polish GM deserves to get the honour of naming this variation after him? After all, we already have the Polugaevsky variation in the Sicilian, so why not name this one ''Gajewski variation''!?} 12. Qd3 {Stopping ...a6 and covering the e4-pawn, but as it turns out, d3 is not such a great square for the queen in this particular position.} ({A possible improvement is} 12. c3 $5 Ba6 (12... Nxb3 13. axb3 Bb7 {would be met by the standard GP break} 14. f5 $1 {and if} e5 (14... Qd7 15. fxe6 fxe6 16. Ng5 $36) {then} 15. Bg5 $1 exd4 16. f6 $36) 13. Rf2 e5 {and now White can initiate some wild complications with} 14. Bxf7+ $1 Rxf7 15. Ne6 Qd7 16. Nxg7 Nc4 $1 (16... Rxg7 17. fxe5 Nc4 18. Bh6 $18) 17. Bc1 exf4 (17... Rxg7 18. b3 $16) 18. Ne6 $1 Ne3 $1 19. Qd4 Qxe6 {The simplest.} (19... Ng4 20. Nfg5 Nxf2 21. Kxf2 $13 {is a mess.}) 20. Ng5 Nc6 21. Nxe6 Nxd4 22. cxd4 $11) 12... Bd7 13. Bd2 Nb7 $1 {A somewhat unexpected and strong manoeuvre.} 14. Qe3 Nc5 $132 {1-0 (49) Gajewski,G (2456)-Mikrut,D (2390) Lubniewice 2003. The knight assumed a strong outpost on c5 and Black was doing well in this complex middlegame. Congratulations to the Black player for playing the opening so well when faced not only with a new move, but a completely new and (as the future would show) sound opening concept.}) ({Another decent alternative is} 11... Bd7 12. Qe2 ({Though, now White could play the more active} 12. Qd3 $5 {preparing to exert the pressure on the d6-pawn with Rad1, etc.}) 12... Qc7 13. e5 $5 dxe5 14. fxe5 Nf5 {1-0 (30) Mikaelyan,A (2467)-Tran,T (2529) Rome 2019} 15. Bf4 $13) 12. c4 {This creates a bind against Black's ...b5 and ...d5 breaks.} ({Additionally, the typical GP attack queen manoeuvre} 12. Qe1 $5 b5 13. Qh4 $13 {also deserves attention.}) 12... b6 13. Qd2 Qc7 14. Rac1 Nxb3 15. axb3 $13 {½-½ (30) Narayanan,S (2525)-Amonatov,F (2608) Kolkata 2018, with an interesting Hedgehog-type of middlegame.}) (10... b6 {is not such a great idea in connection with ...b7, as played in the two GM-games below, considering the ease with which White carries out the f5-break.} 11. c3 (11. Kh1 Nxd4 12. Nxd4 Bb7 13. f5 exf5 14. exf5 Nxf5 15. Nxf5 gxf5 16. Rxf5 $14 {1-0 (25) Sindarov,J (2544)-Shipov,S (2541) lichess.org INT 2020}) 11... Bb7 $2 (11... Na5 12. Bc2 $14) 12. Nxe6 $5 {An inspired sacrifice, though perhaps not even necessary.} (12. f5 $5 $40 {was simple and strong}) 12... fxe6 13. Ng5 d5 14. Nxe6 Qd6 15. c4 $1 $40 {1-0 (51) Nasuta,G (2518)-Donchenko,A (2618) Maastricht 2019}) 11. Nxd4 e5 {Milanovic,Danilo: '?!' This was the choice of strong GMs Wei Yi and Korobov, though White should probably be happy to see this move as it opens up the diagonal for his bishop and leaves the backward d6-pawn. So far, Black has not yet shown a clear path to equality in this position, although I will mention an important novelty that could change this verdict in the notes below. But first, let us take a look at the two other continuations seen in practice.} ({Firstly, there is the natural} 11... Nc6 12. Be3 a6 13. c3 $14 {White has a pleasant position in the center and easy development. Meanwhile, Black's development is troubled by the latent threat of f4-f5.} Na5 ({Firouzja played} 13... Bd7 14. Qd2 Na5 {which also allowed White to launch the kingside attack with} 15. f5 $1 Nxb3 16. axb3 e5 17. Ne2 Bc6 18. Ng3 {This looks like a dream attacking position for White, so Black had to seek counterplay with} d5 {but after} 19. f6 $1 Bh8 {0-1 (34) Sunilduth Lyna,N (2940)-Firouzja,A (3149) Chess.com INT 2020} 20. Qf2 $1 {would have lead to a winning position for White, in the view of} dxe4 21. Nf5 $1 Bxf6 22. Rad1 $18) 14. Qd2 ({As usual, the direct} 14. f5 {was more to the point.} Nxb3 15. Qxb3 exf5 16. exf5 Re8 17. Rae1 $40) 14... b5 $6 {Too slow.} (14... e5 {would have been clearly better now that the dangerous b3 can be eliminated.} 15. Ne2 Nxb3 16. axb3 Be6 17. c4 f5 $11) 15. f5 e5 16. Ne2 {This would be a normal continuation, leading to a similar position to that in Sunilduth-Firouzja above.} ({The game saw} 16. Bd5 $4 {which looks like a mouse-slip. What is even more strange about this game, if the scoresheet is to be trusted, is that Black lost (!) it in only a couple of moves after himself leaving a rook hanging...} exd4 17. Bxd4 Nc4 18. Qf4 Ra7 $4 19. f6 Bh8 20. Bxa7 {1-0 (20) Sunilduth Lyna,N (2618)-Timofeev,A (2580) chess.com INT 2020}) 16... Nxb3 17. axb3 Bb7 18. Ng3 d5 {Here, the strongest continuation is} 19. Rad1 dxe4 20. f6 $1 Qxd2 21. Rxd2 $16 {locking in the bishop on h8.}) ({Another game went} 11... d5 12. e5 $14 {when we have a French-like structure. This version seems pleasantly better for White as he controls the d4-square well and has a simple plan of advancing his kingside pawns.} Nc6 13. Be3 Nxd4 14. Bxd4 Bd7 15. Qf3 Bb5 ({Probably} 15... f6 $14 {here, or at some later point was called for.}) 16. Rf2 Qc7 17. c3 Rfc8 18. g4 $40 {½-½ (54) Shahinyan,D (2456)-Livaic,L (2507) chess.com INT 2020}) ({A new direction in this position is} 11... b5 $5 $146 {looking for counterplay on the queenside. According to the analysis below, it seems to be the most promising continuation for Black of all that we have seen in this position.} 12. Be3 ({In the event of} 12. a3 a5 13. c3 {Black prepares the ...b4 break with} d5 $1 (13... Ba6 $2 14. f5 $40) 14. e5 Ba6 $132 {followed by 15...b4 and a nice position for Black.}) 12... b4 ({Another playable option is} 12... a5 13. a3 Bb7 {and if} 14. f5 exf5 15. exf5 {then} Nd5 16. Bxd5 Bxd5 17. Qd2 $13) 13. a3 bxa3 14. Rxa3 a5 15. Qd2 Bd7 {The bishop remains on the c8-h3 diagonal to keep the f4-f5 break in check. Black plans to go ...c7 and connect his rooks, with a reasonable position.} 16. Ba4 Qc7 $11) 12. Nf3 {Milanovic,Danilo: ''} (12. f5 exd4 13. f6 {looks attractive at the first sight, but after} Bh8 14. fxe7 Qxe7 15. Bh6 Bd7 16. Bxf8 Rxf8 $44 {Black achieves full positional compensation for the exchange.}) 12... Nc6 {Milanovic,Danilo: 'N?!'} ({Objectively best is} 12... exf4 {Milanovic,Danilo: '?!' Milanovic,Danilo: '- 147/(30)'} 13. Bxf4 Be6 ({Black quickly went down after} 13... Bxb2 $2 14. Rb1 Bg7 15. Bxd6 $18 {in a blitz game 1-0 (23) Saydaliev,S (2384)-Korobov,A (2688) chess.com INT 2020}) 14. Bxe6 Qb6+ 15. Kh1 fxe6 16. Qxd6 Nc8 $1 {The key move to keep Black alive, although after} 17. Qd2 Qxb2 18. Ng5 $36 {he still has problems.}) 13. Kh1 $6 {It is very tempting to remove the king from possible checks on the g1-a7 diagonal, yet this move lets a large portion of White's advantage slip.} ({Instead,} 13. c3 {would have kept White in charge since} Be6 {would be strongly met by} 14. f5 $1 $16 {when} gxf5 15. exf5 Bxf5 {would allow White to obtain very good chances with either} 16. Ng5 ({or} 16. Nxe5 dxe5 17. Rxf5 Qxd1+ 18. Bxd1 $16) 16... Bg6 17. h4 $40) (13. Ng5 $5 {Milanovic,Danilo} h6 {Diagram [#]} (13... Qe7 $4 14. f5 $1 Bf6 15. Nxf7 Rxf7 16. fxg6 hxg6 17. Bxf7+ Qxf7 18. Qf3 $18) 14. Nxf7 $1 Rxf7 15. fxe5 Nxe5 16. Qd5 Qb6+ (16... Qe7 $2 17. Bf4 $18) 17. Kh1 Kh7 18. Rxf7 Nxf7 19. Qxf7 Be6 $5 (19... Bg4 20. Bxh6 $1 Kxh6 21. Qf4+ Kh7 (21... Kh5 $4 22. h3 Bf3 (22... Bxh3 23. g4+ $1 Bxg4 (23... Kh4 24. g5+ Kh5 25. Bc4 $18) 24. Kg2 Bh3+ 25. Kxh3 Qd8 26. Rg1 Qf6 27. Qg4+ Kh6 28. Kg2 Kh7 29. Rf1 $18) 23. gxf3 $18) 22. Qxg4 $16) 20. Qxe6 (20. Bxe6 $2 Rf8 $19) 20... Qf2 21. Bxh6 $1 Rf8 $1 22. Be3 Qxe3 23. Qxd6 Qxe4 24. Qd2 $14 (24. c3 $6 Qe2 $132)) 13... Be6 {Milanovic,Danilo: ''} 14. c3 {Milanovic,Danilo: 'Diagram [#]'} Qe7 $2 {An unfortunate choice of square for the queen.} (14... Qd7 $11 {would keep the f5-square under control.} 15. Be3 {Milanovic,Danilo} exf4 16. Bxf4 Rad8 17. Qd2 Rfe8 18. Rae1 $13) 15. fxe5 $2 {Somehow both top GMs underestimated the thematic attacking continuation.} ({It would be a dream of every GP Attack player to make} 15. f5 $1 $16 {Milanovic,Danilo: '!' work. If Black accepts the pawn sacrifice with} gxf5 (15... Bxb3 {Milanovic,Danilo} 16. axb3 Rad8 17. Ng5 $5 h6 18. Nh3 Qh4 {Diagram [#]} 19. Nf2 $1 d5 $140 (19... gxf5 20. exf5 d5 21. g3 Qe7 22. Ng4 $18) 20. g3 Qe7 21. exd5 gxf5 22. Qf3 $18) 16. exf5 Bxf5 {then White would have a very strong move} 17. Nh4 $1 $40 {Milanovic,Danilo: '!?' securing absolute domination on the light squares. It was probably this resource that was missed by the players.} Bg6 {Milanovic,Danilo} (17... Qxh4 {Milanovic,Danilo} 18. Rxf5 h6 19. Be3 Ne7 20. Rh5 Qf6 21. Qg4 Qg6 22. Qh3 Kh7 23. Rg5 Qf6 24. Bc2+ Ng6 25. Rf5 Qe6 26. Raf1 $18) 18. Qg4 d5 (18... Kh8 19. Bg5 Qc7 20. Rf6 $1 e4 21. Raf1 $18) 19. Bxd5 Rad8 20. Nxg6 hxg6 21. Bc4 (21. Bg5 Qd7 22. Qxd7 Rxd7 23. Rad1 $16) 21... Na5 22. Be2 $16) 15... dxe5 16. Bg5 f6 17. Be3 Rad8 $11 {Now the position is roughly equal, but in the remainder of the game Grischuk kept pressing and eventually managed to obtain a winning endgame.} 18. Qe2 Bxb3 $6 (18... b6 $11 19. Rad1 {Milanovic,Danilo} Na5 20. Bxe6+ Qxe6 21. b3 $13) 19. axb3 Qe6 20. Qc4 {Milanovic,Danilo: '?!' White will have a very slight risk-free plus in the endgame.} (20. b4 $5 {Milanovic,Danilo: ''} a6 21. Nd2 $14 {was another approach.}) 20... Qxc4 21. bxc4 a6 22. Bb6 Rd7 23. Rfd1 Rxd1+ 24. Rxd1 f5 25. b4 Rc8 {Milanovic,Danilo: '?!' Here, and on a couple of later occasions, Wei Yi failed to achieve counterplay by capturing the e4-pawn.} (25... fxe4 26. Ng5 e3 $1 27. Bxe3 Bh6 $11 {Milanovic,Danilo: '!?'} 28. h4 {Milanovic,Danilo} e4 $132) 26. h4 {Milanovic,Danilo: '?!'} (26. Rd7 {Milanovic,Danilo} fxe4 27. Ng1 (27. Ng5 e3 28. Bxe3 (28. Kg1 e4 $132) 28... e4 $132) 27... e3 28. Rxb7 e4 $132) (26. Nd2 $5 $14 {(Milanovic,Danilo)  Nf1-e3-d5,  c5,  ef5}) 26... Bf6 {Milanovic,Danilo: '?!'} (26... fxe4 27. Ng5 e3 28. Bxe3 e4 $11 {Milanovic,Danilo: ''}) 27. Rd7 Bd8 $2 {A strange decision as White simply forces a winning pawn-up knight endgame.} ({This was the last chance for} 27... fxe4 28. Ng5 {Milanovic,Danilo} (28. Nd2 {Milanovic,Danilo} Bd8 29. Bxd8 (29. Rxb7 $2 Bxb6 30. Rxb6 e3 31. Nf3 e2 32. Rxa6 Rf8 $19) 29... Rxd8 30. Rxd8+ Nxd8 31. Nxe4 a5 $1 32. bxa5 Nc6 $13) 28... Bxg5 29. hxg5 Rf8 30. Rxb7 (30. Kg1 $6 Rf7 $13) 30... Nd4 $1 31. b5 $5 (31. cxd4 e3 32. b5 axb5 33. cxb5 Rf1+ 34. Kh2 e2 $11 {- 31.b5!?}) 31... e3 32. cxd4 {Diagram [#]} axb5 $1 (32... Rf1+ $2 33. Kh2 e2 34. Ba5 Ra1 35. Kg3 Rxa5 36. Kf2 axb5 37. c5 $1 exd4 38. Kxe2 Ra6 39. Kd3 $18) 33. cxb5 Rf1+ 34. Kh2 e2 $11 {Milanovic,Danilo: '=' Milanovic,Danilo: '- 31.b5!?'} 35. Ba5 Ra1 36. Kg3 exd4 37. Kf2 Rxa5 $8 38. Kxe2 Ra3 $1 39. b6 Rb3 40. Rb8+ (40. Kd2 d3 41. g3 Kf8 42. Rb8+ (42. Rxh7 Rxb6 $11) 42... Kf7 43. b7 Kg7 $11) 40... Kf7 41. b7 Kg7 42. Kd1 d3 43. Kd2 Rb5 44. Kxd3 Rb1 $11) 28. Bxd8 Rxd8 29. Rxd8+ Nxd8 30. exf5 gxf5 31. Nxe5 $18 Kg7 32. Kh2 Kf6 33. Nd7+ Ke7 34. Nb6 Ne6 35. Kg3 Kd6 36. Kf3 Kc6 37. Nd5 b6 (37... Kd6 {Milanovic,Danilo} 38. Nf6 b6 39. Nxh7 a5 40. c5+ Kc6 41. Ng5 $1 Nxg5+ 42. hxg5 a4 43. g6 a3 44. g7 a2 45. g8=Q a1=Q 46. Qe6+ Kb5 47. Qxb6+ Kc4 48. Qe6+ Kb5 49. Qd7+ Kc4 50. Qd4+ Kb5) 38. Ne7+ Kd7 39. Nxf5 a5 40. Ne3 a4 41. Nc2 Kd6 42. Ke4 Nf8 43. g4 Ng6 44. h5 Ne5 45. c5+ 1-0


