1. Nf3 {Marin,M Marin,M Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail Marin,Mihail: 'Marin,M''} d5 2. e3 Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. Bxc4 a6 6. b3 $5 {Marin,M: 'An extremely rare way of avoiding the Queen's Gambit Accepted.' An extremely rare way of avoiding the Queen's Gambit Accepted. Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'An extremely rare way of avoiding the Queen's Gambit Accepted.''} c5 ({Marin,M: 'In the only other game played at grandmaster level Black played more carelessly:' In the only other game played at grandmaster level Black played more carelessly: Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'In the only other game played at grandmaster level Black played more carelessly:''} 6... Be7 7. Bb2 O-O 8. Be2 c5 9. Rg1 {Marin,M: 'White does more or less the same as in our main game.' White does more or less the same as in our main game. Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'White does more or less the same as in our main game.''} b5 10. g4 b4 $6 {Marin,M: 'an unnecessary weakening.' an unnecessary weakening. Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'an unnecessary weakening.''} 11. Na4 Bb7 12. g5 Nd5 13. Qc2 Nd7 {Khismatullin,D (2628)-Grachev,B (2645) Sochi 2017 (0-1, 99)} 14. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5]} N5b6 15. Nxb6 Qxb6 16. Nh2 $16) 7. Bb2 Nc6 8. Qc2 Be7 9. a3 b6 {Marin,M: 'A hyper cautious move.' A hyper cautious move. Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'A hyper cautious move.''} ({Marin,M: 'But Black could have played the natural' But Black could have played the natural Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'But Black could have played the natural''} 9... b5 10. Be2 Bb7 {Marin,M: 'for instance:' for instance: Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'for instance:''} 11. a4 Nb4 (11... b4 12. Nb1 O-O 13. d3 Nd5 14. Nbd2 Nc3 15. Rc1 Rc8 16. Bxc3 bxc3 17. Qxc3 Nb4 18. Rd1 Bf6 19. Qc4 {Marin,M: 'offers Black active play, but probably not entirely adequate compensation for the pawn. The fact is that White is quite solid on the light squares.' offers Black active play, but probably not entirely adequate compensation for the pawn. The fact is that White is quite solid on the light squares. Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'offers Black active play, but probably not entirely adequate compensation for the pawn. The fact is that White is quite solid on the light squares.''}) 12. Qb1 bxa4 13. Rxa4 O-O {Marin,M: 'with satisfactory play.' with satisfactory play. Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'with satisfactory play.''}) 10. g4 {Marin,M: 'Trying to speed up the attack.' Trying to speed up the attack. Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'Trying to speed up the attack.''} (10. Rg1 {Marin,M: 'may simply transpose.' may simply transpose. Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'may simply transpose.''}) 10... h6 {Marin,M: 'Again a solid approach.' Again a solid approach. Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'Again a solid approach.''} (10... Nxg4 {Marin,M: 'deserves mentioning.' deserves mentioning. Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'deserves mentioning.''} 11. Rg1 (11. Qe4 Nf6 12. Qxc6+ Bd7 13. Qb7 Rb8 14. Qxa6 Ra8 $11 {Marin,M: 'with perpetual harassing of the queen.' with perpetual harassing of the queen. Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'with perpetual harassing of the queen.''}) 11... f5 12. h3 Nce5 13. Nxe5 Nxe5 14. Rxg7 Bf6 15. Rg3 b5 16. Be2 Bb7 17. O-O-O {Marin,M: 'Black is active and has more space, but his king is a bit unsafe. Whit's play may be just easier in the least of the cases.' Black is active and has more space, but his king is a bit unsafe. Whit's play may be just easier in the least of the cases. Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'Black is active and has more space, but his king is a bit unsafe. Whit's play may be just easier in the least of the cases.''}) 11. Rg1 b5 ({Marin,M: 'Basically losing a tempo. Black might have feared leaving the bishop on c4 due to' Basically losing a tempo. Black might have feared leaving the bishop on c4 due to Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'Basically losing a tempo. Black might have feared leaving the bishop on c4 due to''} 11... Bb7 12. g5 hxg5 13. Nxg5 Rh6 14. Bxe6 $5 fxe6 15. Nxe6 {Marin,M: 'but things are not entirely clear as the king can run away from the dangerous area:' but things are not entirely clear as the king can run away from the dangerous area: Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'but things are not entirely clear as the king can run away from the dangerous area:''} Qd7 16. Nxg7+ Kd8) 12. Be2 Bb7 13. g5 hxg5 14. Nxg5 Rh6 (14... Rxh2 {Marin,M: 'is too risky:' is too risky: Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'is too risky:''} 15. Nxf7 $1 Kxf7 16. Qg6+ Kf8 17. Ne4 Ne8 18. Bxg7+ Nxg7 19. Rc1 $5 $16 {Marin,M: 'The g7-knight is not running anywhere so White opens a new front along the c-file. The c5-pawn is in danger.' The g7-knight is not running anywhere so White opens a new front along the c-file. The c5-pawn is in danger. Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'The g7-knight is not running anywhere so White opens a new front along the c-file. The c5-pawn is in danger.''} Nd4 $5 20. Qxg7+ Ke8 21. Qg6+ Kd7 22. exd4 {[%cal Ge2g4,Ge4c5]} Qg8 (22... Qf8 23. Qg3 $1 $18) 23. Qxg8 Rxg8 24. Rxg8 Rh1+ 25. Bf1 Bxe4 26. f3 Bxf3 27. Kf2 Be4 28. dxc5 {Marin,M: 'and White should win.' and White should win. Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'and White should win.''}) 15. Nce4 (15. Bf3 Rc8) 15... Nxe4 {Marin,M: 'This slightly helps White developing the initiative.' This slightly helps White developing the initiative. Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'This slightly helps White developing the initiative.''} (15... Na5 $5 {[%cal Gb7d5,Ga8c8]} 16. d3 {[%cal Gb7d5,Ge4d2]} (16. b4 cxb4 17. axb4 Nc6 18. Nxf6+ gxf6 19. Ne4 Kf8 {Marin,M: 'leaves White's pawns hanging while the black king is relatively safe.' leaves White's pawns hanging while the black king is relatively safe. Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'leaves White's pawns hanging while the black king is relatively safe.''}) 16... Rc8 {Marin,M: 'with certain counterplay.' with certain counterplay. Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'with certain counterplay.''}) 16. Nxe4 g6 $6 {Marin,M: 'Too passive.' Too passive. Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'Too passive.''} (16... Qd5 $5 17. Bxg7 Rxh2 18. Nf6+ Bxf6 19. Bxf6 Rc8 {Marin,M: 'With his king facing problems allowing the rook connection (one ould not think of castling long) White cannot make use of his bishop pair at its best.' With his king facing problems allowing the rook connection (one ould not think of castling long) White cannot make use of his bishop pair at its best. Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'With his king facing problems allowing the rook connection (one ould not think of castling long) White cannot make use of his bishop pair at its best.''}) 17. Nxc5 Bxc5 18. Qxc5 Rxh2 19. a4 $36 {Marin,M: 'Instead of counterplay, Black only has queenside problems now.' Instead of counterplay, Black only has queenside problems now. Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'Instead of counterplay, Black only has queenside problems now.''} Qh4 $2 {Marin,M: 'A desperate counterattack, which mainly weakens his own king's defence.' A desperate counterattack, which mainly weakens his own king's defence. Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'A desperate counterattack, which mainly weakens his own king's defence.''} (19... Rc8 $5 20. Bg7 Qe7 (20... Ne7 21. Qe5 $16) 21. Qxe7+ Kxe7 {[%cal Gf7f6]} 22. Bb2 (22. axb5 axb5 23. Bf3 {[%csl Gh1]} f6 24. Rxg6 Kf7 25. Rh6 Rxh6 26. Bxh6 Rh8 27. Rc1 Rxh6 28. Bxc6 Bxc6 29. Rxc6 Rh1+ 30. Ke2 Rb1 31. Rc3 b4 $11) 22... b4 23. Rc1 {Marin,M: 'with some vague hopes for an encgame advantage due to his bishops. The problem is that Black is active and the b3-pawn causes some worries.' with some vague hopes for an encgame advantage due to his bishops. The problem is that Black is active and the b3-pawn causes some worries. Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'with some vague hopes for an encgame advantage due to his bishops. The problem is that Black is active and the b3-pawn causes some worries.''}) 20. Rf1 Rc8 21. Qb6 {Marin,M: 'At this point White's initiative should be decisive.' At this point White's initiative should be decisive. Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'At this point White's initiative should be decisive.''} Nd8 22. axb5 Bg2 23. Ra4 Qh3 24. Ba3 {Marin,M: 'White starts missing simple wins.' White starts missing simple wins. Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'White starts missing simple wins.''} (24. bxa6 Bxf1 25. Bxf1 Rh1 26. Qb5+ Nc6 27. a7 $18) 24... Rh1 25. bxa6 Qh8 (25... Bxf1 26. Qb5+ Nc6 27. Bxf1 $18) 26. Rd4 $2 {Marin,M: 'Throwing away the win by just one stroke.' Throwing away the win by just one stroke. Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'Throwing away the win by just one stroke.''} (26. d4 $18) (26. Qb5+ Nc6 27. d4 $18) 26... Bxf1 27. Qb5+ $2 {Marin,M: 'White could have still forced a draw in at least two ways.' White could have still forced a draw in at least two ways. Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'White could have still forced a draw in at least two ways.''} (27. Rxd8+ Rxd8 28. Qc6+ Rd7 29. Qc8+ Rd8 $11) (27. Bxf1 Nc6 28. a7 Nxd4 29. exd4 Rxf1+ 30. Kxf1 Qh1+ 31. Ke2 Qe4+ 32. Kd1 Qd3 33. Bc5 Qb1+ {Marin,M: 'and this time it is Black who has the perpetual.' and this time it is Black who has the perpetual. Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'and this time it is Black who has the perpetual.''}) 27... Nc6 28. Bxf1 Rxf1+ $1 {Marin,M: 'The start of a simple combination winning material.' The start of a simple combination winning material. Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'The start of a simple combination winning material.''} 29. Kxf1 Qh1+ 30. Ke2 Qh5+ 31. Qxh5 Nxd4+ $1 32. exd4 gxh5 {Marin,M: 'The position is not easy to assess but White's connected pawns are not dangerous so Black can hope stopping them and winning one of them, with reasonable winnin chances.' The position is not easy to assess but White's connected pawns are not dangerous so Black can hope stopping them and winning one of them, with reasonable winnin chances. Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'The position is not easy to assess but White's connected pawns are not dangerous so Black can hope stopping them and winning one of them, with reasonable winnin chances.''} 33. b4 (33. a7 Kd7 34. Bc5 Kc6 35. Kf1 Rg8 $1 $19 {Marin,M: 'followed by the advance of the h-pawn.' followed by the advance of the h-pawn. Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'followed by the advance of the h-pawn.''}) 33... Rb8 34. Kf3 Kd7 35. Kg3 Kc6 ({Marin,M: 'It would have been better to activate the rook with' It would have been better to activate the rook with Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'It would have been better to activate the rook with''} 35... Rb6 $1 36. b5 Rxb5 37. Bc5 Kc6 38. a7 Kb7 {Marin,M: 'with similar play as in the final phase of the game.' with similar play as in the final phase of the game. Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'with similar play as in the final phase of the game.''}) 36. b5+ $2 ({Marin,M: 'Black in vain forces Black into activating his rook. The best defence was' Black in vain forces Black into activating his rook. The best defence was Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'Black in vain forces Black into activating his rook. The best defence was''} 36. a7 Ra8 37. b5+ Kxb5 38. Bc5 Rh8 39. Kh4 Kc6 40. Be7 Kb7 41. Bc5 Rh6 42. Kg5 Rh7 43. Kh4 Rh8 {Marin,M: 'White will soon land in zugzwang so he should change the defensive system before advancing his pawns from the second rank.' White will soon land in zugzwang so he should change the defensive system before advancing his pawns from the second rank. Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'White will soon land in zugzwang so he should change the defensive system before advancing his pawns from the second rank.''} 44. d5 exd5 45. f4 ({Marin,M: 'Probably the only saving setup. If' Probably the only saving setup. If Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'Probably the only saving setup. If''} 45. Bd4 Re8 46. Kxh5 Re4 47. Bc5 Rc4 48. Bb6 d4 49. Kg5 Ra4 {Marin,M: 'or' or Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'or''}) (45. Be3 Rd8 46. Kxh5 d4 47. Bg5 Rd6 48. Kg4 Kxa7 {Marin,M: 'Black should win.' Black should win. Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'Black should win.''}) 45... Rc8 46. Be3 Rc4 47. Kxh5 d4 48. Bf2 d3 49. Kg4 Re4 50. Kf3 Re2 51. Be3 {[%cal Gf3e4] Marin,M: 'This defensive system seems reliable enough.' This defensive system seems reliable enough. Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'This defensive system seems reliable enough.''} f5 52. Bd4 Rxd2 53. Ke3 Rd1 54. Bc5 Ka8 55. Bd4 {Marin,M: 'with a draw since' with a draw since Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'with a draw since''} Rf1 56. Kxd3 Rxf4 {Marin,M: 'does not offer Black any constructive idea.' does not offer Black any constructive idea. Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'does not offer Black any constructive idea.''}) 36... Rxb5 37. Bc5 Rb2 38. a7 Kb7 39. d5 {Marin,M: 'Too late.' Too late. Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'Too late.''} exd5 40. Be3 Rb4 {[%cal Gd5d4]} 41. d4 (41. Bc5 Rb3+ 42. f3 Rd3 43. Be3 d4 $19) 41... Rb1 {Marin,M: 'White cannot win the h-pawn but will lose his a-pawn so he resigned.' White cannot win the h-pawn but will lose his a-pawn so he resigned. Marin,M: 'Marin,Mihail: 'White cannot win the h-pawn but will lose his a-pawn so he resigned.''} 0-1


