1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. exd5 exd5 5. Ngf3 Nc6 6. Bb5 Qe7+ 7. Qe2 Qxe2+ 8. Kxe2 cxd4 9. Nxd4 Bd7 10. N2f3 Bd6 11. Re1 $1 {The critical continuation, preventing Black from completing his development in the most desirable way.} Nge7 {This is the most popular continuation, which is the only reason why I took is as the main line.} ({Since sooner or later Black's best plan is based on Uhlmann's ...f7-f6, it makes sense to play it as soon as possible, in order to keep the king close to the centre with ...f7.} 11... f6 12. Kf1+ Kf7 13. Be3 Nge7 {looks like the right choice to me, basically transposing to Kasparov,S (2493)-Vysochin,S (2533) Wroclaw 2012 (½-½, 52) above.} 14. Rad1 Rhd8 15. c3 a6 16. Bd3 Ne5 17. h3 Rac8 18. Bc2 Nc4 19. Bc1 g6 20. Bd3 Ne5 21. Bc2 Nc4 22. Re2 Re8 23. Rde1 Nc6 $11 {Kasparov,S (2493)-Vysochin,S (2533) Wroclaw 2012 (½-½, 52)}) 12. Be3 (12. c3 O-O 13. Kf1 Ng6 14. h3 Rfd8 15. Be3 a6 16. Bd3 Nce5 17. Nxe5 Nxe5 18. Rad1 {Parligras,M (2511)-Vysochin,S (2531) Predeal 2006 (½-½, 30)} Nxd3 19. Rxd3 Re8 20. Kg1 Re4 21. Nc2 Bc6 $11 {[%cal Ga8e8]}) (12. Kf1 a6 13. Bd3 O-O 14. c3 Rfe8 ({This may be not the best moment to switch to} 14... f6 15. Be3 Ne5 16. Bf4 Nxd3 17. Bxd6 Nxe1 18. Rxe1 {In this position we can notice that with the king on f7 Black would have simply kept the extra exchange!} Nc6 19. Bxf8 Kxf8 {White has chances to exert some pressure, but with his kingside pawns placed on the right squares and with an additional knight on each side, Black should not fear too much the bad bishop ending.}) 15. h3 Nxd4 ({But now was a good moment for} 15... f6 16. Be3 Ne5) 16. Nxd4 Nc6 17. Rxe8+ Rxe8 18. Nxc6 Bxc6 19. Be3 Be5 20. Rd1 g6 21. Be2 Kg7 22. Bf3 $14 {Akopian,V (2660)-Lputian,S (2585) Yerevan 1997 (1-0, 54). In the absence of knights, the d5-pawn starts looking like a real weakness.}) 12... O-O (12... f6 $1 13. Kf1 Kf7 {looks like the right choice to me, basically transposing to Kasparov,S (2493)-Vysochin,S (2533) Wroclaw 2012 (½-½, 52) above.}) 13. Kf1 Rfc8 $6 {Transferring the rook to the queenside does not make too much sense. Once again choosing this game as the main one needs some explaining: I just wanted to check which is the perception of this variation at the height of the year 2014 among strong grandmasters.} (13... a6 14. Bd3 f6 15. c3 Rfe8 {more or less transposes to a line from Akopian,V (2660)-Lputian,S (2585) Yerevan 1997 (1-0, 54) above.}) 14. c3 a6 15. Bd3 f6 16. Rad1 Ne5 17. Bc2 ({Due to Black's chaotic coordination, White could have tried to set up some pressure on the central pawns with} 17. Nxe5 fxe5 18. Nc2 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Ge3g5,Gc2e3]} h6 19. f3 Kf7 20. Rd2) 17... Nc4 18. Bf4 $1 {With the rook on e8 or the king on f7 this reaource would not have been available.} (18. Bc1 Re8 19. Kg1 b5 20. Bd3 g6 {looks like a typical Kortschnoj fortress.}) 18... Kf7 (18... Bxf4 $6 19. Rxe7 Rc7 20. Ne6 Bxe6 21. Rxe6 Nxb2 22. Rxd5 Rxc3 23. Bb3 Kh8 24. Re7 b6 25. Rdd7 $40) 19. Bxd6 Nxd6 20. Re2 Re8 {Even though White has managed to exchange the dark-squared bishops, Black is well regrouped and the relative weakness of the d5-pawn alone is not enough to cause him big problems.} 21. h3 g6 22. Rde1 Rac8 23. Bb3 Nc4 $11 {Making the best out of the isolani. The pressure against the b2-pawn restricts White's possibilities.} 24. Ne6 $6 {A bit too optimistic, but otherwise White does not have obvious ways of making progress.} Bxe6 25. Rxe6 Nxb2 26. Rb6 Nd3 27. Ree6 Rc6 $11 (27... Rxc3 $5 28. Ba4 Rh8 $3 {[%csl Gh7]} (28... Rb8 $6 29. Rxf6+ Kg8 (29... Kg7 30. Ng5 Nc8 31. Rf7+ Kh6 32. h4 $18) 30. Ng5 Nc5 31. Ne6 $44 Nxa4 32. Rxb7 $1 Rc1+ 33. Ke2 Rc2+ 34. Kf3 Rc3+ 35. Kf4 Rc4+ 36. Kg3 (36. Kg5 $2 h6+ $1 37. Kxh6 Rh4+ 38. Kg5 Rh5+ 39. Kf4 Rxb7 $18) 36... Nf5+ 37. Rxf5 gxf5 38. Rxb8+ Kf7 39. Ng5+ Kg7 40. Rb7+ Kg6 41. Nf3 $14) 29. Rxf6+ Kg7 $15 30. Ng5 $2 Nc8 $1 31. Rbe6 Nc5 32. Rf7+ Kh6 $19) 28. Rexc6 bxc6 29. Rxa6 Nc5 (29... c5 $11) 30. Ra5 Nxb3 31. axb3 Rc8 32. b4 $14 Ke6 33. Nd4+ Kd6 34. Ra6 Kd7 35. Ke2 c5 36. Ra7+ Ke8 37. Nb5 Rc6 38. bxc5 Rxc5 39. Nd6+ Kf8 40. Ra8+ Kg7 41. Ra7 Kf8 42. Kd3 Rc6 43. Rd7 Ra6 44. Rd8+ Kg7 45. Rd7 Kf8 46. Rd8+ Kg7 47. Re8 Nc6 48. Re6 Kf8 49. g4 Ra4 50. Ke3 Ne5 51. Re8+ Kg7 52. Re7+ Kf8 53. Rxh7 Nc4+ 54. Nxc4 Rxc4 55. Kd3 Rf4 1/2-1/2


