1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O 8. c3 {I might be subjective, but my feeling is that Carlsen is allowed more frequently to play the genuine Marshall than any other of his colleagues. If this is true, the natural question is whether his opponents trust that despite his phenomenal positional feeling Carlsen may be less strong in concrete opening variations or on the contrary they want to play safe, keeping a draw in their pocket. Be it as it may, the present game contradicts both points of view as White got a slightly worse position out of the opening.} d5 9. exd5 Nxd5 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 11. Rxe5 c6 12. d3 Bd6 13. Re1 Bf5 (13... Qh4 {is slightly more popular. Here is just a recent example:} 14. g3 Qh3 15. Re4 Nf6 16. Rh4 Qf5 17. Bc2 Re8 18. d4 Qe6 19. Nd2 Qe1+ 20. Qxe1 Rxe1+ 21. Kg2 Bb7 22. f3 Rae8 23. Bd3 c5 24. Kf2 c4 $6 (24... cxd4 25. Ne4 R1xe4 26. fxe4 dxc3 27. bxc3 Bxe4 $44) 25. Be4 Nxe4+ 26. Nxe4 Bxe4 27. Kxe1 Bd3+ 28. Re4 Bxe4 29. fxe4 Rxe4+ 30. Kf2 $14 {1-0 (62) Ivanov,O (2513)-Balashov,Y (2418) Moscow 2015}) 14. Qf3 Qh4 ({Deviating from a game of his own:} 14... Bg6 15. Bxd5 cxd5 16. Bf4 {Anand,V (2791)-Carlsen,M (2863) Shamkir 2015 CBM 166 [Pavlovic,M] (½-½, 53), in which he had to struggle hard to reach a draw.}) 15. g3 Qh3 16. Be3 ({It is the Chinese player's turn to deviate from an earlier game between the same players as above, but with reversed colours:} 16. Bxd5 cxd5 17. Be3 Bxd3 18. Qxd5 Rad8 19. Qf3 Rfe8 20. Nd2 Qf5 21. Qxf5 Bxf5 {Carlsen,M (2548)-Anand,V (2785) Leon 2005 (½-½, 30)}) 16... Bxd3 17. Nd2 {White has returned the extra pawn for the sake of completing the development. Even though the structure is more or less symmetrical, the position is not dull at all. Black's minor pieces seem more active, but they can easily be exposed depending how things turn out. The same applies to Black's queenside space advantage: due to the permanent threats c3-c4 and a2-a4 Black's pawns may become weak.} Qf5 {Since Black has no attacking chances anymore, the queen returns to the centre.} 18. Bd4 {For the time being both players maintain the tension.} (18. Qxf5 Bxf5 19. Bd4 Rfd8 20. a4 Bf8 {½-½ (27) Ivanchuk,V (2751)-Aronian,L (2739) Nice 2008}) (18. Rad1 Rfe8 19. Qxf5 Bxf5 20. Bxd5 cxd5 21. Nb3 {Polgar,J (2707)-Leko,P (2753) Wijk aan Zee 2008 (½-½, 35)}) 18... Rae8 {In view of the next rook lift to e6, it looks logical to keep the other rook on f8,} ({but} 18... Rfe8 {is also played as in Leko,P (2708)-Svidler,P (2745) Reykjavik 2015 (½-½, 41)}) 19. Kg2 {Mikhalevski, V: 'Theory's last word.'} Qxf3+ $146 {Mikhalevski, V: 'A novelty from the world champion.' Preparing the rook lift without losing more time.} ({Mikhalevski, V: 'In the only preceding game Black played'} 19... h6 {- 125/106 - 125/106 Mikhalevski, V: 'Vachier Lagrave, M (2731)-Adams, M (2740)/Biel SUI 2015/ [Mikhalevski, V].'} 20. a4 Qxf3+ 21. Kxf3 Re6 22. axb5 axb5 23. Kg2 {Vachier Lagrave,M (2731)-Adams,M (2740) Biel 2015 CBM 168 [Sagar Shah] (1-0, 42)}) 20. Kxf3 Re6 $5 21. Rac1 {Mikhalevski, V: '!?' '!?' Mikhalevski, V: 'White is supporting an advance of the c-pawn.' With the obvious idea of finding a good moment to play c3-c4.} ({One of the points behind Carlsen's novelty is that} 21. a4 {can be answered with} bxa4 $5 {The e1-rook is hanging and the intermediate exchange on e6 loses a piece after ...fxe6 check!} 22. Bxa4 c5 $132 23. Be3 Nxe3 24. Rxe3 c4 {[%csl Gd3,Gd6]}) (21. Rxe6 {Mikhalevski, V: '?!' '?!' Mikhalevski, V: 'is dubious.'} fxe6+ 22. Kg2 {can lead to interesting play:} c5 {Mikhalevski, V: '!' '!'} 23. Re1 {Diagram  Diagram [#] Mikhalevski, V: '!' '!'} Bf4 $3 {Mikhalevski, V: '!'} (23... cxd4 24. Rxe6 $16) (23... Kf7 24. Be5 $14 {with a pleasant blockade.}) 24. Bxc5 (24. gxf4 cxd4 $13) (24. Rxe6 $2 {is bad due to} c4 $1 $17 {Mikhalevski, V: '!'}) (24. Bxd5 exd5 25. gxf4 cxd4 26. cxd4 Rxf4 {and White still has to equalise.}) 24... Bxd2 25. Rxe6 Rd8 26. Rxa6 $44 {[%cal Ga6a8]} Bc4 $8 {White's three pawns compensate for the missing knight, but possibly not more.}) (21. Kg2 {with the idea of 22.Rxe6 is an important alternative, although Black seems to equalise.} Rfe8 22. Rxe6 Rxe6 23. c4 bxc4 24. Nxc4 Bxc4 25. Bxc4 Re4 26. Bxd5 (26. Rd1 Bc5 $1 27. Bxd5 Rxd4 {is equal.}) 26... Rxd4 27. Bxc6 ({or} 27. Bb3 c5 28. Rc1 Rd2 29. Rc2 Rxc2 30. Bxc2 c4 $11) 27... Rd2 $11 {with sufficient counterplay.}) 21... h6 $5 {Diagram  Diagram [#] Mikhalevski, V: 'A waiting move. Black keeps the rook on f8 in order to recapture on e6 with check.' This move and White's reply show that both sides have problems making progress. The position is in some sort of dynamic balance, or, exaggerating a bit, mutual zugzwang. Still, I am not sure about the merits of Black's last move.} ({Mikhalevski, V: 'Now in case of' True,} 21... Rfe8 $2 {Mikhalevski, V: 'White doesn't have to wasted time on Kg2 any more and plays'} 22. Rxe6 Rxe6 23. c4 $16 {Mikhalevski, V: 'with a serious edge.' causes Black problems.}) ({But I would consider} 21... a5 {Black's main candidate, aiming to put Black's queenside space advantage to work.} 22. c4 ({White could renew the pseudo-zugzwang with the neutral} 22. a3 $5 a4 23. Ba2) (22. a4 bxa4 23. Bxa4 c5 $132) 22... bxc4 23. Bxc4 (23. Nxc4 $4 a4 $19 {wins a piece.}) 23... Bb4 24. Red1 Bxd2 25. Rxd2 Be4+ 26. Ke2 Bg2+ 27. Kd1 a4 $5 $13 {[%cal Gf8d8] Black's superior activity and the slight exposure of the white king compensate for the bishop pair.}) (21... Bg6 $5 {deserved serious attention.} 22. Kg2 Rd8 $1 23. a3 h6 24. Rxe6 fxe6 25. Nf3 c5 26. Be5 c4 27. Bc2 Bxc2 28. Rxc2 Bxe5 29. Nxe5 Nb6 {and Black equalises thanks to the open d-file.}) 22. Kg2 {White avoids the check in case of a later exchange on e6, but taking the king away from the centre looks a bit like a counter-developing move.} (22. c4 $5 {Mikhalevski, V: '!' '!' Mikhalevski, V: 'would set some problems.'} c5 {White has to permanently count with this counter-blow.} (22... Nb4 $6 23. Rxe6 fxe6+ 24. Ke3 $16) (22... Rxe1 23. Rxe1 Nb4 (23... Nf6 $11 24. c5 Bb8 25. Re7 $14) (23... c5) 24. c5 Bb8 25. Bc3 (25. Re7 $14) 25... a5 26. Kg2 $1 $14 {[%csl Rc6,Rf7][%cal Gd2f3,Gf3e5] Now is a good moment for this retreat!}) 23. cxd5 Rxe1 24. Rxe1 cxd4 25. Ne4 Bxe4+ 26. Rxe4 Bc5 27. Ke2 Rc8 (27... Rd8 28. Kd3 Kf8 29. Re1 $14) 28. Kd3 Kf8 29. Re2 $14 {In principle the position should be drawn, but while there are rooks on the board White can try exerting some pressure.. His king is perfectly placed and the black queenside is weakened.}) (22. a3 a5 ({What else? If} 22... g5 23. Kg2 $5 $14 {Black does not have the plan based on ...g6 followed by ...f4 anymore.}) 23. c4 {leads to a similar ending as above:} c5 (23... Rxe1 24. Rxe1 Nf6 25. c5 Bb8 26. Re7 $14) 24. cxd5 Rxe1 25. Rxe1 cxd4 26. Ne4 Bxe4+ 27. Rxe4 Bc5 28. Ke2 a4 29. Ba2 Rc8 30. Kd3 $14 {with the same evaluation.}) ({By the way, with his king on f3 White cannot try playing against the Isolani with} 22. Bxd5 $6 cxd5 23. Nb3 $2 {due to} Be4+ 24. Ke2 Bb1+ 25. Kd2 Bxa2 $15) 22... Rg6 {Mikhalevski, V: '!?' '!?' Mikhalevski, V: 'Carlsen chooses an active defence. He prepares 23...Nf4.' Finally exiting the tension along the e-file.} (22... a5 23. Rxe6 (23. c4 Rxe1 24. Rxe1 Nb4 $13) (23. a3 a4 24. Ba2 Rfe8 25. Rxe6 Rxe6 26. c4 bxc4 27. Bxc4 Re2 28. Nf1 Be4+ 29. Kg1 Rc2 30. Rxc2 Bxc2 $11) 23... fxe6 24. c4 a4 $1 25. Bd1 c5 26. cxd5 cxd4 27. dxe6 Bb4 28. Bf3 Bxd2 29. Rd1 Bc4 30. Rxd2 Bxe6 $11) (22... Ree8 $1 {deserved attention, with the idea to meet} 23. c4 {with} Nf6 {With the rook on e8 Black doesn't have to trade rooks.} 24. cxb5 cxb5 25. Rxe8 Rxe8 26. Rc6 Bb4 27. Rc7 Re7 28. Rxe7 Bxe7 {and Black is close to equalising.}) 23. Ne4 {Mikhalevski, V: 'A slight inaccuracy, which allows Black to solve his problems.' This leads to lively play with entirely adequate counterplay for Black.} ({Now was a good moment to settle for a slightly better ending against the Isolani with} 23. Bxd5 $5 {Mikhalevski, V: '!' '!' Mikhalevski, V: 'is an important alternative.'} cxd5 24. Be5 {Mikhalevski, V: 'or'} Bc5 (24... Bxe5 25. Rxe5 d4 $1 {An important resource. Otherwise White obtains a stable edge.} 26. Rd5 (26. cxd4 Rd6 27. d5 Rfd8 28. Rc5 R6d7 $11 {with the idea of 29...f6 is equal.}) 26... dxc3 27. Rxc3 Be2 28. f3 {Black's only problem is his bishop, but it's not easy to solve this without creating weaknesses.} b4 29. Rc2 Bb5 30. Rd4 Re6 31. Ne4 $1 Rb8 32. Kf2 $14 {and Black still has some problems to solve.}) 25. Nb3 Bb6 (25... Ba7 26. Bd4 Bb8 27. Nc5 $14) 26. Bd4 $14) 23... Nf4+ 24. Kf3 {As we see the king didn't find peace on g2. After returning to f3, it will soon allow Black to gain another tempo with a knight move.} Bxe4+ 25. Rxe4 (25. Kxe4 c5 $1 26. Bxc5 (26. gxf4 cxd4 27. cxd4 Rg4 $15) 26... Bxc5 27. Kxf4 Rf6+ 28. Kg4 Rxf2 $11) 25... Nd3 (25... c5 26. gxf4 cxd4 27. cxd4 $16 {[%csl Gf4]}) 26. Rd1 {Mikhalevski, V: 'White sacrifices a pawn, but lures the knight to a bad position.' The principled move, fighting for the initiative at the cost of a temporary pawn sacrifice.} ({Mikhalevski, V: 'In case of'} 26. Rb1 {Mikhalevski, V: 'Black would play'} c5 27. Be3 Rd8 {[%cal Gd6f8]} (27... Kh8 $1 {preparing 28...f5. For example,} 28. Ke2 f5 29. Re6 Rxe6 30. Bxe6 c4 31. Bd5 (31. b3 f4 $1 32. gxf4 Nxf4+ 33. Bxf4 Rxf4 $11) 31... Bc5 32. Bxc5 Nxc5 {and Black equalises.}) 28. Bc2 f5 $1 29. Rh4 Bf8 $13 {h4 Rh4 with better coordination for Black, compensating for White's bishop pair.}) 26... Nxb2 27. Rd2 Ba3 $11 {Mikhalevski, V: '!' '!'} (27... Nc4 $6 28. Bxc4 bxc4 29. Be3 $14 {yields White better chances.}) 28. Bb6 {Mikhalevski, V: 'White prepares 29.Ree2.'} (28. Ree2 c5 29. Bxc5 Rf6+ 30. Kg2 Bxc5 31. Rxb2 {is completely equal.}) 28... Rd6 {Mikhalevski, V: '!' '!'} 29. Rxd6 Bxd6 30. Re2 ({After} 30. Rd4 Be5 31. Rd7 $1 {with the idea of 32.Bc5.} Nc4 $1 32. Bxc4 bxc4 33. Ra7 Bxc3 34. Rxa6 ({or} 34. Bc5 Rb8 35. Rxa6 Rb2 36. Be3 Bd2 $11) 34... c5 $1 35. Bxc5 Rc8 36. Be3 Bb2 37. Rb6 c3 38. a4 Ba3 39. Rb3 Be7 40. Ke2 c2 41. Bc1 Ra8 $11 {The position remain equal.}) 30... Nd3 $5 {The knight is heading for c4 to neutralise the bishop's pressure against f7, but on the way it will drive the enemy king away from the centre for the second time in this game.} (30... Nc4 $11) 31. Rd2 Ne5+ 32. Kg2 Be7 {Mikhalevski, V: 'Black has kept an extra pawn, but White's activity and bishop pair promise him at least equal chances.'} 33. f4 {Mikhalevski, V: '!' '!'} Nc4 34. Bxc4 bxc4 35. Rd7 (35. Rd4 $6 {would be wrong in view of} Rb8 36. Bc7 Rb7 $1 37. Bd8 Rb2+) 35... Bf6 36. Rc7 Bxc3 37. Rxc6 Rb8 {Mikhalevski, V: '!' '!' More or less forced play has resulted in an ending where White needs some caution to make a draw. In principle, due to his activity many roads lead to Rome, but the problem is finding just one of them (and not a false path) and sticking to it.} 38. a4 {Mikhalevski, V: '!?' '!?'} ({There is no need to simplify to an ending with a pawn down, even though it should be drawn.} 38. Rxc4 Rxb6 39. Rxc3 Rb2+ 40. Kf3 Rxa2 41. Rc8+ Kh7 42. Ra8 $15 h5 {This type of ending is heavily analysed with the standard pawn positioning on f2, g3, h4, but the present structure is less usual. In principle it looks less favourable for White, as his king is exposed and the pawns more vulnerable, but it should not suffice for a win. I have found a game to which we will transpose after just a few (some of them dumb) moves:} 43. Ke4 (43. h3 $6 Ra3+ 44. Kf2 {forces the king to stay passive.}) 43... g6 44. Kf3 Kg7 45. Ra7 a5 ({This is necessary only for... transposing. But Black does not get much if he keeps the sixth rank defended for a while:} 45... Kf6 46. Ke4 Ke6 47. Kf3) 46. Ra6 a4 47. h3 $6 {This puts White on the edge.} (47. Ke3) 47... a3 48. Ra5 Ra1 49. Kg2 Kf6 50. Ra6+ Ke7 51. g4 h4 52. g5 a2 53. Kh2 {In order to win, Black needs to create a passed pawn on the f-file, but this is not achievable. A g-pawn or a h-pawn would not suffice.} Kd7 54. Kg2 Kc7 55. Ra8 Kb7 56. Ra3 Kc6 57. Ra6+ Kd5 58. Ra7 Ke6 59. Ra6+ Ke7 60. Ra7+ Ke6 61. Ra6+ Kd5 62. Ra7 Ke4 63. Re7+ ({Actually even} 63. Kh2 Kf3 64. Ra3+ Kxf4 65. Ra5 {is drawn.} Ke4 66. Kg2 Ke3 {[%cal Ga1d1,Gd1d2]} 67. Ra3+ $1) 63... Kxf4 64. Rxf7+ Kxg5 65. Ra7 Kh6 66. Ra4 g5 67. Ra6+ Kg7 68. Ra7+ Kg6 {½-½ Fominyh,A (2518)-Deepan Chakkravarthy,J (2428) Hyderabad 2006}) 38... Bb2 ({During the game I thought} 38... a5 {was more consistent, but it is just an illusion.} 39. Kf3 ({I had in view} 39. Rxc4 $6 Rxb6 40. Rxc3 Rb4 41. Ra3 $15 {when Black has more space than in the game, with increased chances to outplay his opponent.}) 39... Bb4 40. Bd4 c3 41. Ke4 $11) 39. Ba5 (39. Kf3 $5 c3 40. a5 $11 {is also good for equality.}) 39... c3 40. Bxc3 Bxc3 41. Rxc3 Rb4 42. a5 Rb5 43. Ra3 {Mikhalevski, V: 'Here Black is marginally better thanks to his more active rook, but White shouldn't have problems holding a draw.' The white rook is passive, but White does not have weaknesses on the kingside, making the draw quite obvious. In the worst case he can transpose to the previous ending, of course, but he can choose the circumstances under which to do it.} Rb2+ 44. Kh3 f5 45. Rc3 Rb5 46. Ra3 g5 (46... Kf7 47. Kh4 $11) 47. fxg5 hxg5 48. Kg2 Kg7 49. h4 g4 50. Rc3 $1 {Mikhalevski, V: '!' Mikhalevski, V: 'White finds the right moment to create counterplay.'} Rxa5 51. Rc6 Ra2+ 52. Kg1 a5 53. Ra6 a4 54. Kh1 Kf7 55. Kg1 Ra1+ 56. Kg2 Ra3 57. Kh2 Ra2+ 58. Kg1 Ke7 59. Kh1 a3 60. Kg1 {Mikhalevski, V: 'and a draw was agreed as Black can't make progress. 19...Qxf3 is a reasonable alternative to 19...h6, but one should then continue with 21...Bg6.'} (60. Kg1 Kd7 61. Kh1 (61. Rf6 $4 Rb2 $19) 61... Kc7 62. Kg1 Kb7 63. Ra4 Kb6 64. h5 $11) 1/2-1/2


