1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 Bc5 5. Nxe5 $5 {It is well established that in order to obtain some kind of advantage against 4...Bc5, White has to capture the e5-pawn, either now or after castling. Against all other tries, Black at least equalizes immediately. Since Wei Yi chose this move on two occasions, it's definitely one of the most critical moves, but Eljanov found an idea which I think puts this line under a cloud.} ({In my opinion, White should be looking at} 5. O-O O-O 6. Nxe5 {in his search for an advantage.}) 5... Nxe5 ({I always have a feeling of nausea whenever I see a move like} 5... Bxf2+ {. White is clearly better after} 6. Kxf2 Nxe5 7. d4 {.}) 6. d4 a6 $1 {This move has been played just 14 times out of 314 games in my database. Nevertheless, it was a wonderful discovery by Eljanov and it's notable that after this game Wei Yi switched to 5 0-0 0-0 6 Nxe5.} (6... Bd6 {is the main move and it looks like Black is doing fine here as well after} 7. f4 Nc6 (7... Neg4 {is a favourite of my engine, but Wei Yi is usually incredibly well prepared:} 8. e5 Bb4 9. h3 Ne4 10. Qxg4 Nxc3 11. bxc3 Bxc3+ 12. Bd2 Bxd2+ 13. Kxd2 O-O 14. Qg5 Qxg5 15. fxg5 d5 16. exd6 cxd6 17. Bd3 {and White enjoyed the better endgame in Wei Yi-I.Salgado Lopez, Leon (rapid) 2014, although Black managed to draw}) 8. e5 Bb4 9. exf6 Qxf6 {. Now the critical line seems to be} 10. a3 Ba5 (10... Bxc3+ {is generally a desirable structure, but} 11. bxc3 O-O 12. O-O d5 {allows} 13. g4 $1 {, preventing the activation of the c8-bishop; Black runs the risk of being heavily squeezed on the kingside}) 11. Be3 O-O 12. O-O Bxc3 13. bxc3 d5 14. Qf3 (14. g4 $2 Qe6 $1 {wins material}) 14... Ne7 {and Black's position looks playable, although to be honest I'd rather play White. He has the clear plan of going Bd3 and g4 followed by a slow but clear squeeze on the kingside.}) 7. Be2 ({The main reason why this ...a6 trick works here and not with 5 0-0 0-0 inserted is shown after} 7. dxe5 axb5 8. exf6 Qxf6 {. Now since Black threatens mate on f2, White is obliged to go} 9. O-O {, but Black doesn't have to castle just yet. He has time to include} c6 $1 {, protecting a valuable pawn first. Here Black has the bishop-pair, an open a-file and certainly can't complain.}) 7... Bd6 8. f4 {A standard resource.} ({To be fair, White can play} 8. dxe5 Bxe5 {when his bishop is more useful on e2 than on b5. This means that White has a slightly improved version of Game 41, but this is far from enough to claim any advantage. White has some ideas with 0-0 and f4, but the accurate} 9. Bg5 h6 10. Bh4 c6 11. O-O Qc7 {definitely solves all of Black's problems. White has nothing better than the beautiful} 12. f4 $1 Bxf4 13. Rxf4 $1 Qxf4 14. Bg3 Qe3+ 15. Bf2 Qf4 16. Bg3 {with a draw.}) 8... Nc6 9. e5 Bb4 $1 {I think the 4...Bc5 line has obtained a bad reputation simply because White's central pawn's look scary to play against, but if Black returns the piece in this manner the pawn on f4 could easily just become misplaced. White always has to watch out for the e4-square, as we will see in the game Berbatov-Hammer.} 10. exf6 Qxf6 {This is a key position, and one where Black is better off having included ...a6 and Be2.} 11. Be3 {A common move, but not critical in my opinion.} ({White's biggest test is} 11. a3 $1 {, when Black definitely should play} Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 d5 $1 13. O-O Bf5 $1 {when his gets his bishop to a great square before castling and he will establish an advantage based on the e4-square. Had Black not inserted ...a6 and Be2, White would have had Re1+ at this point, disturbing Black's king.}) ({Instead,} 11. a3 Ba5 $2 {is my recommendation with the bishop on b5, but here White can play the disturbing} 12. b4 Bb6 13. Nd5 $1 {, putting pressure on f6, c7 and b6 simultaneously. Had the bishop been on b5, Black would have had the move} Qe6 {with check.}) 11... d5 12. O-O Bxc3 13. bxc3 Bf5 {Black has managed to obtain his dream position. The bishop on f5 is very well placed and he would love to follow up with ...0-0-0, ...h5, doubling the rooks on the e-file and manoeuvring the c6-knight to a better square, preferably d6.} 14. c4 $1 {White, who has a statically worse position, tries to play dynamically with the bishop-pair, but it's difficult to break the light-square blockade.} O-O-O 15. c3 (15. cxd5 Nb4 $1 {was Black's main point.}) 15... Qe6 16. Bf2 dxc4 17. Re1 Be4 $1 {This bishop is a monster. Black has grabbed a pawn on c4 which White might be able to win back, but it won't break Black's terrific light-square blockade.} 18. Qa4 Qg6 19. g3 Ne7 20. Bxc4 Nd5 $1 {This is light-square domination in a picture. In fact, less than 10 moves later Wei Yi throws in the towel.} 21. Bxd5 Rxd5 22. Qd1 Re8 23. c4 Rh5 24. g4 Rh3 25. Bg3 {White has finally managed to get some air, but his kingside is left in tatters.} h5 $1 26. f5 Qg5 27. Qc1 Qxg4 28. Qf4 Qxf4 29. Bxf4 Rh4 {. An incredibly well-played game by Eljanov, who employed a theoretically important idea and then executed a strategical masterpiece worthy of any book.} 0-1


