1. d4 {Stamenkovic,Zoran} Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 {Meier,G: 'The Bishops's Opening or Italian Game reminds me of the London System (1.d4 followed by Bf4 on move 2 or 3) that has also had a resurgence of late, not least due to Magnus's efforts. You can of course find fresh ideas everywhere, but the main point of these openings - at least to me - is to keep a lot of pieces on the board and beat your opponent by a better understanding of positional play and pawn structures.' The Bishops's Opening or Italian Game reminds me of the London System (1.d4 followed by f4 on move 2 or 3) that has also had a resurgence of late, not least due to Magnus's efforts. You can of course find fresh ideas everywhere, but the main point of these openings - at least to me - is to keep a lot of pieces on the board and beat your opponent by a better understanding of positional play and pawn structures.} Bb4 4. Nf3 b6 {Meier,G: 'A bit tame. But it was played after almost 6 minutes of contemplation, indicating that Yi had not made up his mind about this opening beforehand.' A bit tame. But it was played after almost 6 minutes of contemplation, indicating that Yi had not made up his mind about this opening beforehand.} (4... d5 5. Bg5 Nbd7 6. cxd5 exd5 7. Nd2 c6 8. e3 Nf8 9. Bd3 Ng6 10. O-O O-O 11. f4 h6 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. f5 Ne7 (13... Qg5) 14. Nde4 dxe4 15. Nxe4 Qh4 16. g3 Qh3 17. Nf2 Qxf1+ 18. Kxf1) (4... c5 5. g3 Nc6 6. Bg2 Ne4 7. Bd2 Bxc3 8. bxc3 O-O 9. O-O f5 10. Be3 Nxc3 11. Qd3 cxd4 12. Nxd4 Ne4 13. c5) (4... O-O 5. Bg5 c5 6. Rc1 cxd4 7. Nxd4 h6 8. Bh4 d5 9. e3 e5 10. Nf3 g5 11. Bg3 d4 12. exd4 exd4 13. Nxd4 Qb6 14. a3 Bxc3+ 15. bxc3 Rd8) 5. Qc2 Bb7 6. a3 Bxc3+ {Meier,G: 'Both sides are free as concerns further development, so we get an impression of where both players feel their pieces belong.' Both sides are free as concerns further development, so we get an impression of where both players feel their pieces belong.} 7. Qxc3 Ne4 (7... O-O 8. e3 (8. Bg5)) 8. Qc2 f5 9. g3 {Meier,G: '* pawn center'} (9. e3 O-O 10. Be2 d6 11. O-O Nd7 12. b4 Rf6 13. d5 Rg6 (13... exd5 14. Bb2 Rg6 15. cxd5 Bxd5 16. Bc4) 14. Nd4 Qg5 15. g3 exd5 (15... Ne5 16. Nxe6 Rxe6 17. dxe6 Qg6) 16. cxd5 Bxd5 17. Bc4 Bxc4 18. Qxc4+ Kh8 19. Qc6 Rd8 20. Qxc7 Ne5 21. Ra2 Rf8 22. f4 Qg4 23. Qe7 Rg8 24. Rg2) 9... Nf6 10. Bh3 {Meier,G: '* limiting counterplay'} O-O 11. O-O a5 (11... Qe8 12. d5 Qh5 13. Bg2 exd5 14. Rd1) 12. Rd1 (12. d5) 12... Qe8 $1 {Stamenkovic,Zoran: 'Diagram [#]' Meier,G: 'This is important in connection with ...Bg4: Black must be ready to take on f3 and then he should soon halve White's bishop pair with Bg5.' This is important in connection with ...g4: Black must be ready to take on f3 and then he should soon halve White's bishop pair with g5.} (12... Be4 13. Qc3 Qe8 14. Bf4 Qh5 15. Bf1 d6 16. Ng5 Re8 17. Nxe4 fxe4) 13. d5 $5 {Meier,G: '* a trade-off: giving up f4-square to sideline black bishop'} Na6 14. Bf4 {Meier,G: 'The bishop on g6 will be passive for a long time, but White has also created a hole on f4.' The bishop on g6 will be passive for a long time, but White has also created a hole on f4.} exd5 {Meier,G: '*exchanging passive pieces' Being a bit cramped, Black wants to exchange pieces.} (14... Qh5 15. Bg2 exd5 16. Nd4 Rae8 17. cxd5 Nxd5 18. Qc4 Re4 19. Bf3 Qg6 20. Bxe4 fxe4 21. Be3 c6) 15. Bxf5 {Stamenkovic,Zoran: 'N' Meier,G: 'After 20 minutes thought! I don't think Magnus was too thrilled with his position at this point.' After 20 minutes thought! I don't think Magnus was too thrilled with his position at this point.} dxc4 (15... Ne4 16. Bh3 {Meier,G: 'would be the modern way to play.' would be the modern way to play.} Qh5 17. Bg2 a4 {Meier,G: 'sophisticated!' sophisticated!} 18. cxd5 (18. Qxa4 Nac5 19. Qc2 dxc4 20. Qxc4+ d5 21. Qc2 Ne6 22. Be3 c5) 18... Nac5 {Meier,G: 'is a popular line for Black' is a popular line for Black} 19. d6 cxd6 {Meier,G: 'would force Black to eventually release the tension in the centre.' would force Black to eventually release the tension in the centre.} 20. Bxd6 Rf7 21. Bf4 Nb3 22. Qc7 d6 23. Qxb6 Nxa1 24. Rxa1) 16. Ng5 Qh5 {Meier,G: 'From here on it looks very much like Black was looking for active ideas, when all he had to do is patiently improve his position.' From here on it looks very much like Black was looking for active ideas, when all he had to do is patiently improve his position.} (16... g6 17. Bxd7 {Meier,G: 'keeping the Ng3 at bay and with Bg5 soon following.' keeping the g3 at bay and with g5 soon following.} Nxd7 {Stamenkovic,Zoran} 18. Qxc4+ Kg7 19. Ne6+ $11 Kh8 20. Rxd7 Qxd7 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4] a slight advantage for White in the center.} 21. Nxf8 {Stamenkovic,Zoran} Qd5 $11 {- 60/292} (21... Rxf8 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc6c5,Gd6d5]} 22. Be5+) 22. Qxd5 Bxd5 23. Nd7) 17. Rxd7 (17. Bxd7 Nc5 18. Bf5 Kh8 {[%csl Rf4] * f4-pawn turns out to be weak} {Meier,G: 'The normal move would be' The normal move would be} 19. f3 Rae8) 17... Kh8 (17... Nxd7 18. Bxh7+ {Stamenkovic,Zoran: '=' Meier,G: 'with a good position for Black was mentioned by Carlsen.' with a good position for Black was mentioned by Carlsen.} Kh8 19. Bg6 Qg4 20. f3) 18. Re7 (18. Rd4 {Stamenkovic,Zoran: '=' Meier,G: 'is completely satisfactory for Black.' is completely satisfactory for Black.} Nc5 19. Rxc4 Bd5 20. Rc3) 18... Nd5 $2 {Stamenkovic,Zoran: '?!' Meier,G: '"An absolute gift" (Carlsen). Black is giving up the centre for no reason.' "An absolute gift" (Carlsen). Black is giving up the centre for no reason.} 19. Bg4 {Meier,G: '* backward pawn on d6'} (19. Re5 Nxf4 $1 {Meier,G: 'A smart waiting move, opening the d7-f8-e6 route for the knight.' A smart waiting move, opening the d7-f8-e6 route for the knight.} 20. gxf4 Rae8 21. Rxe8 Rxe8 22. f3) 19... Qg6 20. Nf7+ Kg8 (20... Rxf7 {[%csl Gd4,Rd6,Ge4,Gf5] * looks ever so slightly better for White, but Black is probably just fine} 21. Qxg6 {Meier,G: 'getting the rook into play and vacating f8 for the knight; good value for a tempo.' getting the rook into play and vacating f8 for the knight; good value for a tempo.} hxg6 22. Rxf7) 21. Bf5 {Meier,G: '* limiting counterplay, isolating the bishop on g6. king is safe on g2' Now White has a straightforward plan: Get rid of the queen on f4 and push his kingside pawns. At this point Black had to look for ways to limit the damage, and quickly.} Qxf5 $6 {Meier,G: 'Further drifting...' Further drifting...} (21... Qh5 22. g4 Qh4 $13 {Stamenkovic,Zoran} 23. Bg3 Qh3 $1 24. Ng5 Qh6 25. Re5 Nc5 {[%csl Re4]} 26. Qxc4 {Stamenkovic,Zoran: ''} Kh8 27. h4 Rad8 28. e4 Nf6 29. Nf7+ $11 Rxf7 30. Qxf7) 22. Qxf5 {Meier,G: '* trading Black's strongest piece'} Nxe7 23. Nh6+ {Meier,G: ''} gxh6 {Meier,G: '?!'} 24. Qg4+ {Meier,G: '* superior understanding of pawn structures - White's pawn majority is more potent'} Ng6 25. Bxh6 Rf7 26. Rd1 {Meier,G: 'Black must have underestimated the dangers of this endgame. Clearly, digging in and holding the fort does not come easy to the Chinese prodigy. He proceeds to lose in no time.' Black must have underestimated the dangers of this endgame. Clearly, digging in and holding the fort does not come easy to the Chinese prodigy. He proceeds to lose in no time.} Re8 {Meier,G: '* e4-outpost'} 27. h4 Nc5 (27... Kh8 $14 {Stamenkovic,Zoran} 28. h5 Nf8 29. Qxc4 Rfe7 $1 {Stamenkovic,Zoran: '!' Meier,G: 'leaves White with the superior minor piece forever.' leaves White with the superior minor piece forever.} 30. Qd4+ $5 Kg8 31. Qg4+ Kh8 32. Bd2 h6 33. Bc3+ Kh7 {Meier,G: 'looks tempting, but Black still holds on with' looks tempting, but Black still holds on with} 34. Qd4 Nd7 35. Qd3+) 28. h5 {Meier,G: '* centralization'} Bc8 29. Qxc4 $16 {Meier,G: '!' Meier,G: '* fixing the pawn structure; white has a space advantage.' The black knight has no way back, and White is ready to saddle Black with a weakness by c3-c4xd5 and decisively open the c-file.} (29. Qg5 Rf5 30. Qg4 (30. Qc1 Rxh5 31. Qxc4+ Be6) 30... Rf4 {[%cal Ga4a3,Gb6c4]} 31. Qg5 {[%csl Ra4]} Rf5 {Meier,G: 'would guarantee that Black does not run out of space. The isolated pawn would remain his only worry after' would guarantee that Black does not run out of space. The isolated pawn would remain his only worry after}) 29... Ne5 $2 {Stamenkovic,Zoran: 'Diagram [#]' Meier,G: 'Only creating more weaknesses.' Only creating more weaknesses.} 30. Qh4 {Stamenkovic,Zoran: '+-!' Meier,G: '* White undermines opponent's pawn chain first!'} Nc6 31. Rd5 {Meier,G: '* now the e4-knight has lost its footing'} Ne6 (31... Rxe2 {[%csl Ge5,Gf5][%cal Gf3f4,Rd5d4]} 32. Qd8+ $142) 32. Qc4 (32. Qa4 Bb7 {Stamenkovic,Zoran: ''} 33. Qg4+ Ng7 34. Rg5 Ree7 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Gf5d6]} 35. f4 Nd4 36. f5 Ndxf5 37. Rxf5 Rxf5 $16 38. Bxg7) 32... Ncd8 (32... Ne7 33. Qa4 Ref8 34. Rd2 Ng7 35. e4 {Stamenkovic,Zoran: '' Meier,G: 'with a large advantage, but exchanges will ease some of the pressure.' with a large advantage, but exchanges will ease some of the pressure.} Bg4 36. f4 {Meier,G: 'looks like a decent blockade still' looks like a decent blockade still} Bxh5 $36 {Stamenkovic,Zoran} 37. Rd7 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gf8e7,Rc3c4]} {Meier,G: 'To put up a line of defence Black should take f5 under control, grab space with a5 to somewhat secure c5 for his knight and then centralise his king. A reasonable sequence would be:' To put up a line of defence Black should take f5 under control, grab space with a5 to somewhat secure c5 for his knight and then centralise his king. A reasonable sequence would be:} c5 38. Qb3 Re8 39. Qxb6 Bf3 40. Bxg7 {Stamenkovic,Zoran: ''} Kxg7 41. Qxc5) 33. Qg4+ {Meier,G: 'This game clearly showed Wei not being comfortable with a quiet manoeuvring struggle. And obviously Carlsen is aware of this shortcoming. Given a strategically superior position out of nowhere he converted with ease.' This game clearly showed Wei not being comfortable with a quiet manoeuvring struggle. And obviously Carlsen is aware of this shortcoming. Given a strategically superior position out of nowhere he converted with ease.} Ng7 (33... 