{The finish. Black's play was very easy. Rc8 , Na7 and the pieces just coming towards White's King. White's play, on the other hand, was not at all easy. The finish. Black's play was very easy. Rc8 , Na7 and the pieces just coming towards White's King. White's play, on the other hand, was not at all easy. The finish. Black's play was very easy. Rc8 , Na7 and the pieces just coming towards White's King. White's play, on the other hand, was not at all easy. B69: Sicilian: Richter-Rauzer: 7...a6 8 0-0-0 Bd7 9 f4 Be7 10 Nf3 b5 Bxf6} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 d6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nf6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 a6 8. O-O-O Be7 9. f4 Bd7 10. Nf3 b5 11. Bxf6 gxf6 12. Kb1 Qb6 13. g3 b4 $146 (13... O-O-O 14. Bh3 (14. Bg2 Kb8 15. Ne2 Na5 16. b3 Nb7 17. Nfd4 Rc8 18. c3 Rhd8 19. Nc2 Rc7 20. f5 Rdc8 21. Rhf1 Bf8 22. b4 a5 23. a3 Qa6 24. fxe6 Bxe6 25. Ncd4 axb4 26. axb4 Bh6 27. Qb2 Bc4 28. Rf5 Nc5 {Chapter B50-Game 11 Game 11 (48)}) 14... Kb8 15. f5 Rhe8 16. fxe6 fxe6 17. Qh6 Qc5 18. Ne2 Rc8 19. Nf4 Qc4 20. Nd2 Qa4 21. c3 b4 22. b3 Qb5 23. c4 Qg5 24. Qh5 Nd4 25. Rhf1 Qxh5 26. Nxh5 Rc5 27. Nxf6 Bxf6 28. Rxf6 {Exam Time!-Chigaev,M (52)}) (13... Na5 14. f5 b4 15. fxe6 fxe6 16. Ne2 Nc4 17. Qd4 Qxd4 18. Rxd4 Ne5 19. Bg2 a5 20. Re1 Rc8 21. Rdd1 Kf7 22. Nf4 Ng6 23. Nxg6 hxg6 24. e5 d5 25. exf6 Bxf6 26. h4 Rh5 27. Bh3 Rc4 28. Re3 {6.dc5___ (2640) -Krueger,A (2675) Maribor 2016 Telechess CBM 89 [Harding/Busemann] 0-1 (61)}) 14. Ne2 a5 {The trainable ends here. It is instructive to see how a former prodigy rated 2742 loses control of the position pretty quickly. The trainable ends here. It is instructive to see how a former prodigy rated 2742 loses control of the position pretty quickly. The trainable ends here. It is instructive to see how a former prodigy rated 2742 loses control of the position pretty quickly. The position is equal.} 15. f5 e5 {With the center closed like this, it is not easy for White in practical play unless their minor pieces can use the d5 -square. With the center closed like this, it is not easy for White in practical play unless their minor pieces can use the d5 -square. With the center closed like this, it is not easy for White in practical play unless their minor pieces can use the d5 -square. Against Ne2-f4} 16. Nc1 (16. g4 $5 {[%cal Rh2h4]}) 16... Rc8 17. Qd5 {[%eval -31,20]} (17. Qh6 $11 {[%eval 6,19]}) 17... Na7 {An instructive way of improving the Knight.} 18. Nd2 Bc6 {[#]} ({But not} 18... Qc7 19. Ba6 $14) 19. Qd3 {[%eval -32,22]} (19. Nc4 $1 $11 {[%eval 1,24] is more appropriate.} Qc7 20. Qd3) 19... a4 $15 20. Nc4 Qc5 21. Qf3 Nb5 {All the Black pieces are moving towards White's King, while White's pieces themselves are going nowhere. All the Black pieces are moving towards White's King, while White's pieces themselves are going nowhere. All the Black pieces are moving towards White's King, while White's pieces themselves are going nowhere.} 22. Qe3 {[%eval -148,22]} ({Better is} 22. Ne3 {[%eval -83,21]}) 22... Nd4 $17 {Threatens to win with ...d6-d5.} 23. Bd3 {[%eval -238,24]} (23. b3 $17 {[%eval -154,22]}) 23... d5 $19 24. Nd2 a3 25. exd5 Bxd5 26. Ne4 Qc6 {Strongly threatening ...a3xb2.} 27. Nb3 O-O {White's King is beyond salvage so Black can spend one move towards King safety before going for the finish. White's King is beyond salvage so Black can spend one move towards King safety before going for the finish. White's King is beyond salvage so Black can spend one move towards King safety before going for the finish.} ({Inferior is} 27... Nxc2 28. Qe2 Bxb3 29. Bb5 Bxa2+ 30. Kxa2 b3+ 31. Kxb3 $11) 28. Rhe1 $2 {[%eval -851,23]} (28. bxa3 {[%eval -265,23]} Nxc2 29. Qe2 Nxa3+ 30. Ka1) 28... Nxc2 29. Qh6 Bxb3 {A strong pair of Bishops.} 30. Ng5 {[#]} Bxa2+ $1 31. Kc1 (31. Kxa2 b3+) 31... Nxe1+ {[%eval -1443,5]} (31... Nd4+ $142 {[%eval -32759,10]} 32. Kd2 Nb3+ 33. Ke3 Bc5+ 34. Ke2 Qg2#) 32. Kd2 Nf3+ {Weighted Error Value: White=0.86/Black=0.35} *


