1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. Qe2 {White's idea is to play 7.e5 when Black won't be able to pin the e-pawn by means of...Qe7.} Bc5 7. e5 ({In the previous update I considered} 7. g3 $2 {Nepomniachtchi, I  (2705)-Kramnik, V (2777)/Berlin GER 2015/[Mikhalevski, V].}) 7... Nd5 8. c4 Ne7 {Usually this square is occupied by the black queen. Here, thanks to White's move order, it's available and Black takes advantage of that fact.} (8... Nb6 {was tested just once.} 9. Qg4 g6 10. Bg5 Be7 (10... d5 $5 {is also an option.}) 11. Bh6 d5 12. Qf3 (12. Qg3 {is better.}) 12... Bg5 $1 13. Bg7 Rg8 14. Bf6 Bxf6 15. exf6 Bf5 $15 {with some edge for Black in Das, A (2439) -Pruijssers, R  (2517)/Dieren 2014.}) 9. Be3 {A logical exchange of Black's strong dark-squared bishop, which also helps to develop White's kingside.} (9. Bg5 {doesn't make much sense as Black can easily unpin the knight and then the bishop on g5 will be misplaced.} O-O 10. Nc3 Qe8 11. O-O-O Ng6 $15 {with a slight edge for Black.}) 9... Bxe3 10. Qxe3 d6 $5 {The first novelty from the young Chinese star, though it transposed to a preceding game, which saw 10... d5 before 11.exd6.} ({Earlier Black tried} 10... Rb8 11. Nd2 (11. b3 $5) 11... Rxb2 $2 (11... Nf5 12. Qe4 g6 {was better.}) 12. Nb3 O-O 13. Qc3 $16 {1/2-1/2 Chernyshov, K (2450)-Sulskis, S (2525)/Swidnica 1997.}) 11. exd6 Qxd6 {And the second novelty. Wey Yi hopes to compensate the defects of his pawn structure by the activity of his pieces. The game will show if he was right.} ({In the only preceding game Black recaptured with the pawn, which looks more natural.} 11... cxd6 12. Bd3 Qb6 13. b3 (13. Nd2 $5 {is worth attention.}) 13... Be6 14. Nd2 Qxe3+ 15. fxe3 O-O (15... Ng6 $5 $11 {bringing the knight to e5 looks better.}) 16. O-O Rfd8 17. Nf3 {with a slight edge for White in Nijboer, F  (2559) -Wiedenkeller, M (2453)/Skopje MKD 2015.}) 12. Bd3 {An inaccurate move order.} (12. Nc3 $1 {was critical. Now after} O-O 13. Rd1 $1 Qb4 14. Rd2 Re8 15. Be2 Bg4 16. Qe4 $1 {White seems to obtain some edge thanks to his better pawn structure, while Black can't take advantage of the position of White's king.}) 12... O-O 13. Nc3 {White wants to meet 13...Nf5 with long castles.} ({After} 13. O-O {Black would play} Bf5 14. Be4 Rfe8 15. Nc3 Qb4 16. b3 Nd5 $1 17. cxd5 Bxe4 18. Rae1 cxd5 19. Nxd5 Qd6 20. Nc3 Bc6 $11 {with equal chances.}) 13... Nf5 $1 (13... Bf5 $6 14. O-O-O $14 {is better for White.}) 14. Bxf5 Bxf5 15. O-O Rfe8 $1 {An important move. If Black doesn't play it White takes both the d- and e-files with his rooks.} 16. Qf3 {Now White has to consolidate in order to claim an advantage, though it's easier to say than to do.} Bg6 ({It's not obvious, but} 16... Re5 {doubling the rooks was more precise.} 17. Rae1 ({or} 17. Rad1 Qe6) 17... Rae8 18. Rxe5 Rxe5 19. Qd1 ({After} 19. h3 Bc2 $1 {is strong, covering the d1-square.}) ({The immediate} 19. Rd1 {is strongly answered by} Bc2 $1 $11) 19... h5 20. Qxd6 cxd6 21. Rd1 Kf8 {and Black shouldn't have big problems to hold.}) 17. b3 {Yu Yangyi decides to stabilize his position on the queenside.} (17. h4 {is an interesting alternative.}) 17... h6 {Wei Yi makes a useful move as well.} ({Black could have started with} 17... Re6 $5 {in order to meet} 18. Rad1 {with} Qe7 {when the queen is behind the rook.}) 18. h3 Re6 19. Rad1 Qe5 (19... Qe7 {looks safer.}) 20. Qg3 $1 {White is offering a favourable exchange of queens.} ({Another interesting option would be} 20. Rfe1 {sacrificing two rooks for a queen.} Qxe1+ {Black has to accept the offer.} 21. Rxe1 Rxe1+ 22. Kh2 {Now White can hope to exploit the weak pawns on the queenside, though Black seems to be solid enough after} Re6) 20... Qa5 $1 {Correctly avoiding the trade.} ({After} 20... Qxg3 21. fxg3 $14 {Black's queenside pawns allow White to claim a slight edge.}) 21. Rfe1 Rxe1+ {I would call this move inaccurate.} ({The natural} 21... Rae8 22. Rxe6 Rxe6 {is more accurate as it avoids the exchange of queens, which occurred in the game.}) 22. Rxe1 Rd8 {Black prefers to take the d-file, as this way he creates a threat of 23...Rd3.} 23. Qe5 $1 $14 ({White could also build up his advantage with queens on the board.} 23. Re3 Rd2 24. Qf3 Rc2 25. g3 $14) 23... Qxe5 {If Black avoided the trade it would lead to a passive position.} 24. Rxe5 Rd2 (24... Rd3 $1 {is the best defence. For example,} 25. Na4 Rd1+ 26. Kh2 Rd2 27. Nc5 Rxa2 28. f4 Ra5 29. f5 f6 30. Re6 Bxf5 31. Rxc6 Ra3 32. Rxc7 a5 {and White's chances to win are not too big.}) 25. Re8+ ({The straightforward} 25. Ra5 $1 Rc2 26. Na4 Rxa2 27. Rxa7 Bc2 28. Rxc7 Bxb3 29. Nb6 $14 {leads to an extra pawn for White.}) 25... Kh7 26. Re2 {An evaluation of this move depends on the assessment of the exchange on e2.} ({Instead White could have attacked Black's weaknesses.} 26. Rc8 $5 Rc2 27. Na4 Rxa2 28. Rxc7 Ra1+ 29. Kh2 Ra2 30. Rxa7 Rxf2 31. Nc5 $14) 26... Rd3 $6 ({I believe} 26... Rxe2 $1 {was better, and promised Black a rather simple equality.} 27. Nxe2 Bd3 28. Nc3 g5 $1 29. f3 f5 $1 30. Kf2 f4 $11) 27. Na4 $16 {Now Black is under pressure.} Rd1+ 28. Kh2 h5 {Black wants to keep White's king in a cage by means of 29... h4.} 29. Kg3 ({White could have ignored the idea of 29...h4.} 29. Nc5 $1 h4 30. a4 $1 {and Black has to defend passively.} Rd8 31. Re7 Rc8 32. g4 hxg3+ 33. fxg3 $16 {with a clear edge.}) 29... Rd4 30. f3 h4+ 31. Kf2 Rd1 32. Nc5 Kh6 (32... Bd3 $1 $14 {is a tougher defence.}) 33. f4 $2 {It's clear that Yu wanted to prevent the activation of the black king, but missed Black's reply.} ({After the correct} 33. Re7 Rd2+ 34. Kg1 Rxa2 35. Rxc7 Kg5 36. Rxc6 Kf4 37. Kh2 $1 Ke3 38. Rd6 $14 {White retains winning chances, though the activity of the black king yields Black certain counterplay.}) 33... Bh5 $1 $11 {Now the position is equal.} 34. Re7 ({In case of} 34. Rc2 {Black can activate the king.} Kg6 $11) 34... Rd2+ 35. Kg1 ({or} 35. Kf1 Rd1+ 36. Re1 Rd4 37. Re4 Rd1+ $11) 35... Rd1+ 36. Kf2 Rd2+ 37. Kg1 Rd1+ 38. Kf2 {The line with 6.Qe2 is not as innocent as I thought and Black has to be careful to retain the balance. I prefer 11...cxd6 to the 11...Qxd6 which occurred in the game.} 1/2-1/2


