1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. O-O ({Earlier we considered the following alternatives: the main line} 6. Nbd2 {Yu Yangyi (2705) -Kramnik, V (2760)/Doha QAT 2014/[Mikhalevski, V].}) (6. Be3 {Andreikin, D  (2709)-Anand, V (2770)/Khanty-Mansiysk RUS 2014/[Mikhalevski, V].}) ({and} 6. h3 {, which prevents 6...Bg4 in Anand, V (2773)-Nakamura, H (2789)/Zurich SUI 2014/ [Mikhalevski, V].}) 6... Bg4 $5 ({In a few recent games Black preferred} 6... Bd6) (6... Nd7 {is also a reasonable option.}) 7. h3 Bh5 {A very aggressive idea, which is connected with a piece sacrifice. If the sacrifice yields Black sufficient counterplay than the text should be preferred over 7... Bxf3.} (7... Bxf3 {was much more common recently.}) 8. g4 $5 {White accepts the challenge.} (8. Nbd2 {avoiding the sacrifice occurred in a couple of games. Here is an example:} Qe7 ({I prefer} 8... Nd7) 9. Nc4 O-O-O ({Once again} 9... Nd7 {looks better.}) 10. Qe2 b5 $6 11. Ne3 {and White obtained a clear edge in Bedia, M (2513)-Bondarev, B (2112)/Armavir 2011.}) 8... Nxg4 {This is obviously the most critical continuation.} (8... Bg6 9. Nxe5 Qe7 10. Nf3 O-O-O 11. Qe1 h5 12. g5 Nd7 {is playable despite White's extra pawn. Cabral, P (2066) -Almeida Junior, C (2066)/Rio de Janeiro 2013.}) 9. hxg4 Bxg4 10. Be3 $1 {The best defence.} ({In case of} 10. Re1 $2 {Black plays} f5 $1 11. exf5 O-O $1 12. Rxe5 Bd6 13. Re4 Bh5 14. Nbd2 Rxf5 $17 {and White is in trouble.}) 10... Bd6 $5 {Black saves his dark-squared bishop from exchange in order to keep the f-file closed.} (10... Qf6 {also yields Black compensation.} 11. Kg2 Bxe3 12. fxe3 Qe6 13. Rf2 (13. Ng5 $2 {is met by} Qd7 $1) 13... h5 14. Qe1 h4 15. Kh1 Bh5 16. Nbd2 f6 {with compensation for the sacrificed material.}) 11. Nbd2 $6 {This natural move turns out to be a mistake.} ({White should have got ready for the 11...f5 break.} 11. Kh1 $1 Qd7 $1 ({Now after} 11... f5 12. Rg1 Qd7 13. exf5 h5 (13... Qxf5 $2 {is strongly met by} 14. Nh4 $1 Bxd1 15. Nxf5 Bxc2 16. Rxg7 $16) 14. Nbd2 Qxf5 15. Nh4 Qf6 16. Ndf3 O-O-O $1 (16... O-O $2 {is bad because of} 17. Rxg4 $1 hxg4 18. Ng5 $18) ({or} 16... Rf8 $2 17. Rxg4 $1 hxg4 18. Ng5 $18) 17. Bg5 Qf7 18. Bxd8 Rxd8 19. Qe2 Rf8 20. Raf1 $1 g5 21. Nxg5 Bxe2 22. Nxf7 Rxf7 23. Re1 Rxf2 24. Rg2 $14 {Black's compensation seems to be insufficient.}) 12. Rg1 Bh5 $1 13. Rg3 f5 $1 14. Rg5 g6 15. exf5 {Now Black has two interesting options:} Rf8 (15... Be7 $5 16. Rxh5 gxh5 17. Nfd2 Qxf5 18. Qf3 Qg4 $1 19. Qxg4 hxg4 20. Nc3 $14 {with slightly better chances for White.}) 16. Nbd2 $1 (16. Rxh5 gxh5 17. Nh4 Qf7 18. Nd2 Be7 19. f6 (19. Ndf3 $6 O-O-O {is fine for Black.}) 19... Bxf6 20. Nf5 O-O-O 21. Ne4 Bg5 $1 {with serious counterplay.}) 16... Rxf5 17. Rg3 O-O-O 18. Qg1 e4 19. dxe4 Bxf3+ 20. Rxf3 Rh5+ 21. Kg2 Bc5 22. Bxc5 Rxc5 23. Nf1 Qg4+ 24. Ng3 h5 25. Rd1 Re8 {with compensation.}) 11... f5 $1 {Now Black's initiative is sufficient for at least equality.} 12. exf5 O-O $1 13. Qe1 $1 {The best defence. White is unpinning the f3-knight before it was attacked by the black rook.} Bxf3 {One of a few possible options here.} (13... Bxf5 $5 14. Kg2 Qf6 {was also interesting.}) 14. Nxf3 Rxf5 15. Qe2 $1 ({One inaccurate move, such as} 15. Nh2 $2 {may lead to problems.} e4 $1 16. f3 (16. dxe4 {loses to} Bxh2+ 17. Kg2 Rh5 $19) 16... exf3 17. Nxf3 Qf6 $17 {and Black is clearly better.}) 15... Qf6 $1 16. Nh2 $1 {The best defence again.} (16. Ne1 $6 Qh4 17. Ng2 Qh3 {is dangerous for White.}) 16... e4 $1 {Both sides have to make the very best moves to retain equal chances.} 17. Qg4 $5 (17. dxe4 {leads to a forced draw after} Bxh2+ 18. Kxh2 Qh4+ 19. Kg2 Qxe4+ 20. f3 Rg5+ 21. Kh1 Rh5+ 22. Kg1 Rg5+ {with a repetition.}) 17... exd3 $1 18. cxd3 Re8 $1 {With two pawns for a piece and a vulnerable white king Black's chances are at least not worse.} 19. Rae1 $1 (19. Rfe1 $6 {would be inaccurate in view of} Rxe3 $1 20. Qc4+ Rd5 21. Rxe3 Bxh2+ 22. Kf1 Bd6 $15) 19... Re6 $5 {Black's time to deviate from a forced draw. He has been preparing 20...Qf7 followed by 21...Rg6.} ({He could force a draw by means of} 19... Bxh2+ 20. Kxh2 Rxe3 21. Rxe3 Rxf2+ 22. Kg3 Rxf1 23. Qc8+ Qf8 24. Re8 Rf3+ 25. Kg4 Rf4+ {and Black checks along the f-file.}) 20. f4 $5 {Wei Yi is blocking the dark-squared bishop.} (20. Bd2 $5 {is a reasonable alternative.} Qg6 $1 {Black is threatening to play 21...Bxh2. So,} 21. Re4 $1 {The only defence.} Ref6 $1 22. f3 Qf7 $1 23. Qh3 Rg6+ 24. Kh1 Rg3 25. Qh4 h6 $11 {with sufficient compensation for a piece.}) 20... Qf7 $1 21. Kh1 Rg6 22. Qf3 Qxa2 $5 {Black restores the material balance.} 23. Re2 $1 (23. Ra1 Qxb2 24. Rxa7 (24. Rab1 Qc2 25. Rxb7 Rh6 26. Rf2 Qxd3 27. Rd2 Qc4 $15) 24... Rh5 25. Rf2 Qb1+ 26. Rf1 Qb5 {looks promising for Black.}) 23... Qd5 24. Bd2 $5 {White is opening the e-file for his rook.} ({Since White couldn't avoid this exchange it made sense to exchange the queens right away.} 24. Qxd5+ $5 Rxd5 25. d4 $11) 24... Rg3 $5 {Black is forcing an exchange of queens in order to win the d3-pawn.} (24... Rh5 {also makes sense.}) 25. Qxd5+ Rxd5 26. f5 $6 {The first inaccuracy after a long series of strong and sometimes only moves.} (26. Nf3 $5 {deserved attention, with the idea to meet} Rxd3 {with} (26... Rh5+ $5 27. Rh2 Rf5 $11 {is more accurate.}) 27. Ng5 {and White has been developing an initiative.}) 26... Rh3 ({It would be better to start with} 26... Rgxd3 $1 {and only after} 27. Bc3 Rh3 $15 {with slightly better chances.}) 27. f6 {White is trying to open up Black's king, but the move is slightly inaccurate again.} (27. Bc3 $1 {was better.}) 27... Rxh2+ $2 {Black returns the favour with a serious mistake.} ({Instead he should have played} 27... Re5 $1 28. Rg2 g6 29. d4 Re6 30. Bc3 Kf7 31. Kg1 Rxf6 32. Ra1 a6 33. Ng4 Rf5 {with the slightly better chances for Black.}) 28. Rxh2 Bxh2 29. f7+ $1 {An important intermediate move, which saves the d-pawn.} Kf8 30. Kxh2 $16 {Suddenly Black has to fight for his life, as White's f-pawn is very strong.} c5 $5 {Xiu Deshun is covering the a3-f8 diagonal.} 31. Bc3 $1 {With an obvious threat of 32.Bxg7. So,} Rg5 32. Kh3 $1 b6 33. Rf3 a5 (33... h6 $5 {was worth a try.}) 34. b3 $5 ({After the correct} 34. Kh4 $1 Rg6 ({Now} 34... h6 $2 {is bad because of} 35. b3 $1 $18 {and soon Black will find himself in zugzwang.}) 35. Rf5 Rh6+ 36. Kg3 Rg6+ 37. Kf3 Rg1 38. Kf2 Rg6 39. Be5 $18 {Black shouldn't survive.}) 34... Rg6 35. Be5 $5 (35. Rf5 $5 $18 {was also strong.}) 35... b5 36. Bxc7 $18 a4 37. bxa4 bxa4 38. Be5 $1 {Now Black is lost.} a3 39. Kh4 $2 {A mistake, which makes White's win difficult, if possible at all.} (39. d4 $1 {was strong, as after} cxd4 40. Bxd4 {Black can't stop an appearance of the white bishop on either the a3-f8 or f8-h6 diagonals.} Rh6+ 41. Kg3 Rg6+ 42. Kf2 Rg5 43. Rf4 $1 a2 44. Bc3 $1 Rb5 45. Bxg7+ $1 $18) 39... a2 40. Rf2 Rh6+ 41. Kg3 Rg6+ 42. Kh3 Rh6+ 43. Kg2 Rg6+ 44. Kf1 {The king escaped the checks, but Black starts advancing his h-pawn.} h5 $1 45. Rxa2 {White can't do without this move.} Kxf7 $2 {A losing move.} ({Black should have started with} 45... Rg5 $1 46. Bc3 {and then} Kxf7 47. Ra7+ Kg8 {with some chances to hold thanks to the reduced material.}) 46. Ra7+ Ke6 ({or} 46... Kg8 47. Rc7 $18 {White wins the c5-pawn and obtains good winning chances.}) 47. Rxg7 Rxg7 48. Bxg7 Kd5 49. Bc3 $1 $18 {White's idea is to answer 49...c4 with 50.d4.} Ke6 50. Kf2 {and Black resigned as he loses one of his pawns. A well-played game by both players despite some mistakes towards the end. Black's piece sacrifice is extremely interesting and requires more practical tests.} 1-0


