he g-pawn, although it could have been played even without the rook move.} (13. g4 {could have been played even here, as} Bxg4 $2 {is just bad due to} (13... f6 14. Rdg1 Nc6 {transposes to the game.}) 14. Rdg1 $18 {with a decisive attack along the g-file.}) 13... Nc6 $2 {Black doesn't take his chance to prevent 14.g4 and gets into trouble. Black doesn't take his chance to prevent 14.g4 and gets into trouble. Black doesn't take his chance to prevent 14.g4 and gets into trouble.} (13... Bg4 $5 14. Ne3 Qc8 $1 {would delay White's attack.} 15. Nxg4 (15. Rh4 Be6 16. g4 f6 17. Nf5 Nc6 {also looks playable for Black.}) 15... Qxg4 16. Nd4 Qxe2 17. Nxe2 Nc6 18. c3 $14 {and though White is better in the endgame the immediate danger has gone. and though White is better in the endgame the immediate danger has gone. and though White is better in the endgame the immediate danger has gone.}) 14. g4 f6 {www.rules-chess-strategies.com: 'Diagram #' transposes to the game.} 15. g5 $1 {David has definitely underestimated this move. The direct attack turns out to be too strong. David has definitely underestimated this move. The direct attack turns out to be too strong. David has definitely underestimated this move. The direct attack turns out to be too strong. www.rules-chess-strategies.com: '!!'} fxg5 (15... hxg5 16. h6 gxh6 (16... g6 17. Nxg5 fxg5 18. Bxg5 $40) 17. Nxg5 $1 hxg5 18. Qh5 $40) 16. Nxg5 $1 {The point of the previous move. The point of the previous move. The point of the previous move.} Nd4 (16... hxg5 17. h6 $1 {www.rules-chess-strategies.com: '→'} g4 18. hxg7 $1 Nd4 19. Qe3 Qf6 20. Rh8+ Kxg7 21. Rxe8 $18 {is winning for White.}) 17. Qd1 hxg5 (17... b5 18. Nxd6 cxd6 19. Nf3 Re6 20. Nxd4 cxd4 21. f4 $16 {is also very unpleasant.}) 18. Bxg5 Be7 19. Be3 $1 $18 {This cold-blooded move emphasizes Black's helplessness. 20. h6 opening the g and h-files can't be stopped. This cold-blooded move emphasizes Black's helplessness. 20. h6 opening the g and h-files can't be stopped. This cold-blooded move emphasizes Black's helplessness. 20. h6 opening the g and h-files can't be stopped.} Bf6 20. h6 Re7 (20... g5 21. Bxg5 $1 Bxg5+ 22. f4 $1 Ne6 $1 {The best practical chance.} ({or} 22... exf4 23. Qh5 $1 Kh8 24. Rxg5 $18 {and Black can't stop 25.h5 with the subsequent 26.Rg8. and Black can't stop 25.h5 with the subsequent 26.Rg8. and Black can't stop 25.h5 with the subsequent 26.Rg8.}) 23. fxg5 Nf4 24. h7+ Kg7 (24... Kh8 25. g6 Kg7 26. Qd2 $18 {isn't better.}) 25. Qd2 $1 Nh3 (25... Be6 26. Qh2 Qe7 27. Nxe5 Nh3 28. Ng4 $1 $18 {is also hopeless.}) 26. Rg3 Kxh7 27. Ne3 Kg7 28. Rgxh3 $1 Bxh3 29. Qh2 $1 Qd7 30. Nf5+ $1 Kf7 31. Qxh3 Rh8 32. g6+ Kf6 33. Qg2 $18 {with a decisive attack. However, it wouldn't be easy for White to find all these precise moves and so 20...g5 should have been played. with a decisive attack. However, it wouldn't be easy for White to find all these precise moves and so 20...g5 should have been played. with a decisive attack. However, it wouldn't be easy for White to find all these precise moves and so 20...g5 should have been played.}) 21. hxg7 {Now the attack develops all by itself. Now the attack develops all by itself. Now the attack develops all by itself.} Rxg7 22. Qh5 Be6 23. Bh6 $5 {A simple practical solution, which doesn't require any calculation. A simple practical solution, which doesn't require any calculation. A simple practical solution, which doesn't require any calculation.} ({The computer's way of winning is} 23. Qh8+ Kf7 24. Rxg7+ Bxg7 25. Nxe5+ Bxe5 26. Rh7+ Kg6 27. Rh6+ Kf7 28. Qxe5 $18) 23... Bf7 {www.rules-chess-strategies.com: 'Diagram #'} (23... Qe8 {leads to a winning rook endgame.} 24. Bxg7 Qxh5 25. Bxf6+ Kf7 26. Rxh5 Ne2+ 27. Kd2 Nxg1 28. Bxe5 Bxc4 29. dxc4 Nf3+ 30. Ke3 Nxe5 31. Rxe5 $18) 24. Bxg7 Bxh5 25. Bxf6+ Kf8 26. Bxd8 Ne2+ ({After} 26... Rxd8 27. Rg5 $18 {Black is completely helpless.}) 27. Kb1 Nxg1 28. Bxc7 {White wins a piece and so Black resigned. A well conducted attack by the Chinese superstar. 9.Bd2 seems to set some problems and so the ball is now in Black's court. White wins a piece and so Black resigned. A well conducted attack by the Chinese superstar. 9.Bd2 seems to set some problems and so the ball is now in Black's court. White wins a piece and so Black resigned. A well conducted attack by the Chinese superstar. 9.Bd2 seems to set some problems and so the ball is now in Black's court.} 1-0


