1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 Bb4 5. O-O O-O 6. d3 d6 7. Bg5 Ne7 {This old line is gaining popularity and it was already tested by some top players, including Aronian and Ponomariov. In fact, the latter turned out to be a driving force behind its rediscovery in the last few years after his crushing victory over Nisipeanu.} 8. Nh4 {The main line.} ({After} 8. Bxf6 {in Vallejo Pons, F (2722)-Granda Zuniga, J (2614) Bahia Feliz ESP 2011  [Mikhalevski, V] Black slowly but surely outplayed his opponent.}) 8... c6 9. Bc4 d5 10. Bb3 {This line was played by Caruana in the game given below.} Qd6 {Mamedyarov is following Aronian.} ({In a few recent games Black experimented with} 10... a5 $5 {and achieved good results. Here is how the games developed:} 11. a4 ({In case of} 11. Bxf6 $5 gxf6 12. a4 {Black can play} dxe4 13. dxe4 Qxd1 14. Rfxd1 b6 $1 15. Bc4 Be6 $11 {with equal chances.}) (11. a3 Bxc3 12. bxc3 a4 13. Ba2 Qd6 14. f4 (14. Qf3 $5 h6 15. Bxf6 Qxf6 16. Qxf6 gxf6 17. f4 Ra5 $1 {and Black seems to maintain the balance.}) 14... dxe4 15. Qe1 $2 (15. fxe5 Qxe5 16. Bxf6 gxf6 17. dxe4 Qxc3 {is good for Black too.}) 15... Ned5 $1 16. Bxd5 Nxd5 17. Qxe4 exf4 $17 {and in this much better position for Black a draw was agreed in Haslinger, S (2524)-Harika, D (2503) Vlissingen 2012} (17... Qc5+ $1 18. d4 exd4 19. cxd4 Qc3 $17 {is even better.})) 11... Qd6 (11... Bg4 $5 {A decent alternative to 11...Qd6.} 12. f3 (12. Qc1 $5 Qd6 {looks ok for Black.}) 12... Be6 13. f4 exf4 14. Bxf6 $1 (14. Rxf4 $6 Nd7 15. Rf1 {and a draw was agreed in Brkic, A (2575)-Kuljasevic, D (2577) Split CRO 2013, while Black could have continued with} Nc5 16. exd5 (16. e5 Nxb3 17. cxb3 h6 18. Bc1 Ng6 19. Nxg6 Qb6+ $1 20. d4 fxg6 $17 {is clearly better for Black.}) 16... Nxb3 17. cxb3 Bxd5 $17 {and Black's advantage is beyond question thanks to his better pawn structure.}) 14... gxf6 15. exd5 cxd5 16. Ne2 Bd6 (16... Ng6 17. Nxg6 hxg6 18. Nxf4 {looks more pleasant for White.}) 17. Nxf4 Bxf4 18. Rxf4 Ng6 19. Nxg6 hxg6 20. Qe1 Kg7 {with roughly equal chances in Wei Yi (2530)-Ni Hua  (2646) Danzhou CHN 2013}) 12. Qf3 h6 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. Qxf6 gxf6 15. f4 Be6 16. f5 (16. exd5 cxd5 17. Nb5 Rad8 18. Kh1 e4 $1 19. c3 Bc5 {with a good position for Black in Yu, R (2431) -Harikrishna, P (2666) Mashhad 2011}) 16... Bd7 17. Ne2 (17. exd5 Bxc3 18. bxc3 cxd5 {is fine for Black.}) 17... dxe4 $2 ({Black should have played} 17... Bc5+ 18. Kh1 Rad8 $11 {with equal chances.}) 18. dxe4 $14 {Kotsur, P (2558) -Pashikian, A (2616) Khanty-Mansiysk 2011} (18. Ng3 $1 {is much stronger.} exd3 19. Ne4 $1 Kg7 20. c3 $1 {is clearly better for White.})) 11. f4 $1 {This principled move has been known for 100 years!} Bxc3 $1 {The most accurate.} ({As I have already mentioned in my annotations to Caruana-Aronian} 11... Bc5+ $6 {, which was played by Yates in 1912(!) is dubious.}) ({In a few recent games Black played} 11... Qc5+ {which may seem to be a reasonable alternative of the Aronian's 11...Bxc3. However after} 12. Kh1 Ng4 {This way Black virtually forces} 13. fxe5 Nf2+ 14. Rxf2 Qxf2 15. Nf3 $1 {White sets problems and I don't see a clear way to equality.} (15. exd5 $6 Bxc3 $1 16. Bxe7 $1 Re8 17. d6 {Kadric, D (2420)-Nestorovic, N (2436) Paracin 2012. Now Black had to play} (17. bxc3 $5 {is better.} Rxe7 18. Qf3 $1 Qxf3 $1 (18... Qxh4 19. d6 $1 Bg4 20. Qe4 Ree8 21. Rf1 Rf8 22. h3 {with good compensation for the sacrificed material.}) 19. Nxf3 cxd5 20. Bxd5 Be6 {with slightly better chances for Black.}) 17... Bxe5 $15 {with Black's superiority.}) 15... d4 (15... Re8 $5 16. d4 Bxc3 17. bxc3 Bg4 18. Qd3 $1 dxe4 19. Qxe4 Bf5 20. Qf4 Bg6 21. Bh4 Qe2 22. Re1 Qa6 23. Bxe7 Rxe7 24. h4 $1 $14 {White's chances are higher.}) 16. Bh4 Qe3 17. Bg5 Qf2 18. Ne2 $1 $14 {and White obtained an advantage in Perunovic, M (2614) -Strikovic, A (2539) Valjevo 2012}) 12. bxc3 dxe4 $1 13. fxe5 Qxe5 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. dxe4 Qxc3 $1 $146 {I offered this novelty in my annotations to Aronian's game.} ({In the aforementioned game Black played} 15... Ng6 $6 {Caruana, F (2709)-Aronian, L (2801) Moscow RUS 2010 [Mikhalevski, V], which after} 16. Qe1 $1 {promises White some edge.}) 16. Qd6 {This move looks rather toothless.} ({I checked the critical} 16. Kh1 $5 Qe5 {, but missed} 17. Nf3 $1 Qxe4 18. Qd6 {Nevertheless, Black seems to be able to maintain the balance with} Nd5 19. Bxd5 cxd5 20. Rae1 Qg6 21. Nd4 Be6 $1 {However, the line with 16.Kh1 requires practical tests.}) 16... Ng6 $1 {The following exchanges lead to an equal endgame.} 17. Nxg6 hxg6 18. Qxf6 Qxf6 19. Rxf6 Kg7 20. Raf1 Bf5 $1 21. Rxf7+ ({or} 21. Rd6 Bxe4 22. Rd7 Kh6 $1 23. Rdxf7 Rxf7 24. Rxf7 c5 $11) 21... Rxf7 22. Bxf7 Bxe4 23. Bb3 b5 {and in this roughly equal position a draw was agreed. A short but important game, which indicates in which direction the theory of this line has been developing.} (23... Rf8 $5 {is equal too.}) 1/2-1/2


