anned on Marin,M: 'The traditional move order is' Marin,Mihail: 'The traditional move order is'} 10... O-O {as Marin,M: 'Beside 11.Nbd2, transposing to one of the main lines, White tried' Marin,Mihail: 'Beside 11.bd2, transposing to one of the main lines, White tried'} 11. Nbd2 {transposes into the main line.} (11. Qe2 {is another option. Marin,M: 'in a few historic games:' Marin,Mihail: 'in a few historic games:'} Qd7 $1 {Marin,M: 'Since White has deviated from the natural course of development, Black can ignore the threat on e4.' Since White has deviated from the natural course of development, Black can ignore the threat on e4.} ({Marin,M: 'Curiously, a few years ago the player who can be considered the greatest Open Spanish specialist ever did not react too well in two games against the same opponent:' Curiously, a few years ago the player who can be considered the greatest Open Spanish specialist ever did not react too well in two games against the same opponent:} 11... f5 12. exf6 Bxf6 13. Nbd2 Bf5 14. Nxe4 Bxe4 15. Bxe4 dxe4 16. Qxe4 Qd7 17. Bf4 Rae8 18. Qc2 $16 {Bronstein,D-Kortschnoj,V Leningrad 1962 (1-0, 39) Marin,M: 'Bronstein, D-Kortschnoj,V Leningrad 1962 (1-0, 39)'}) (11... Nc5 12. Nd4 Qd7 13. Nd2 Nxd4 14. cxd4 Nb7 15. Nf3 $14 {Bronstein,D-Kortschnoj,V Leningrad 1962 (½-½, 24) Marin,M: 'Bronstein,D-Kortschnoj,V Leningrad 1962 (1/2-1/2, 24)'}) 12. Rd1 (12. Bxe4 dxe4 13. Qxe4 Bf5 14. Qf4 f6 $36 {[%csl Ge7,Gf5]}) 12... f5 13. Nbd2 Kh8 14. Nb3 (14. Nxe4 $2 fxe4 15. Bxe4 dxe4 16. Rxd7 exf3 17. Qd3 Bxd7 18. Qxd7 Rad8 $19) 14... Bf7 15. Nbd4 Bh5 $13 16. Nxf5 $2 Qxf5 17. Rxd5 Bg6 $17 {Tal,M-Keres,P Moscow 1967 MCL [Dolmatov] (0-1, 30)})) 11. h3 {This is the move White played in the most recent human games. Marin,Mihail: 'Mikhalevski, V: 'This is the move White played in the most recent human games.''} ({Two recent computer games continued} 11. a4 b4 {and only then} 12. h3 Bxf3 13. Qxf3 Nxe5 14. Qf5 Bd6 ({Equinox played} 14... f6 15. cxb4 g6 16. Qf4 Ng5 17. Nc