1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Be7 6. Qe2 Nd6 7. Bxc6 bxc6 8. dxe5 Nb7 9. Nc3 O-O 10. Nd4 Bc5 {It has been a while we last considered this line. In fact, the entire 5...Be7 complex is out of fashion, although Carlsen played it on a couple of occasions in 2017.} 11. Rd1 Re8 12. Qh5 {This move hasn't been seen for nine years! White takes the h4-square away from the black queen and creates a threat of 13.Nxc6. I want to remind you that the immediate 12.Nxc6 runs into 12...Qh4.} ({Earlier we considered.} 12. Bf4 {Grischuk,A  (2717)-Malakhov,V (2679) Elista RUS 2007 [TonyK]}) 12... Qe7 {This move has been known since 1958! Even Smyslov tried it in one of his games. Black removes the queen from the d-file and attacks the e5-pawn.} (12... Bxd4 $5 {is a reasonable alternative. Black exchanges one of his bishops in order to play...d5.} 13. Rxd4 d5 14. Bd2 (14. Rh4 $2 {is strongly met by} Bf5 $1 $17) 14... Qd7 15. Rf4 (15. Re1 $5 Qf5 16. Qxf5 Bxf5 17. g4 Be6 $11) 15... Qe6 16. Re1 Qg6 17. Qxg6 {and in this slightly better position for Black a draw was agreed in Naiditsch,A (2686)-Motylev,A (2704) Poikovsky 2010}) 13. Bf4 Bxd4 14. Rxd4 d5 {This move is possible, since en passant leads to checkmate.} 15. Re1 (15. exd6 $4 Qe1+) 15... Nc5 {The knight comes to e6.} 16. Bd2 {A clever move. The rook will stay on the fourth rank.} (16. Rdd1 $5 {is a logical alternative.} Ne6 17. Bc1 Nf8 18. h3 $1 {with some pressure.}) 16... Qe6 {Black plans on trading queens.} ({After} 16... Ne6 17. Rg4 {White can set some problems.}) (16... a5 $1 {would take control of the b4-square and was more accurate.}) 17. b4 $5 (17. Na4 $5 {fighting for the c5-square was interesting. For example,} Nxa4 18. Rxa4 c5 19. Ra5 Qb6 20. Qf3 $14) 17... Nd7 18. b5 {This direct attack doesn't achieve its goal.} c5 {An interesting tactical trick.} (18... Bb7 $1 19. bxc6 Qxc6 $1 {was strong.} 20. Rxd5 (20. Nxd5 $2 Qc5 $1 $17) 20... f6 $1 21. e6 Ne5 {with the slightly better chances for Black.}) 19. Nxd5 $6 {A risky move.} (19. Rxd5 $2 {loses to} Nf6 $1) (19. Rg4 $1 {was more precise, although after} d4 $1 (19... Nxe5) 20. Ne4 Bb7 21. h3 g6 (21... Qxe5 $2 {runs into} 22. Rg5 $16 {with the subsequent 23.Nxc5.}) 22. Qg5 Qxe5 23. Qxe5 Rxe5 24. Nf6+ Nxf6 25. Rxe5 Nxg4 26. hxg4 c4 {Black should be able to hold.}) 19... cxd4 20. Nxc7 Qe7 21. e6 $1 {An important intermediate move.} ({The immediate} 21. Nxa8 $2 {would be wrong in view of} Qc5 $1 $17) 21... Nf6 22. exf7+ Qxf7 23. Qxf7+ Kxf7 24. Nxa8 {White has won two pawns, but his knight on a8 will be stuck after Black's next move.} Nd5 $1 25. Rxe8 Kxe8 26. Ba5 $1 {White had to prepare for 26...Bb7.} Kd7 $1 27. b6 $1 Kc6 $1 {Rapport wins back one of the pawns.} 28. Nc7 (28. bxa7 $2 Bb7 $1 {wins a piece.}) 28... Nxb6 {White's knight is still misplaced.} 29. Bxb6 (29. Ne8 $5 {deserved attention.} Nc4 30. Be1 Bf5 31. Nxg7 Bxc2 32. Ne6 Kd5 33. Ng5 Bb1 34. a4 Bc2 35. a5 d3 36. Nf3 Bd1 37. Nd2 Nxa5 38. Nf1 Nc4 39. Ne3+ Nxe3 40. fxe3 {and White probably survives the endgame with opposite-coloured bishops.}) 29... axb6 $6 {An inaccuracy, which allows White to escape with a draw. Black should have kept the pawn on the a-file, as it would be a potential passed pawn.} (29... Kxb6 $1 {was correct, with the idea to meet} 30. Ne8 {with} Kc5 $1 31. Nxg7 Kb4 32. f4 Kc3 33. f5 Kxc2 34. f6 d3 35. f7 d2 36. f8=Q d1=Q+ 37. Kf2 (37. Qf1 Qxf1+ 38. Kxf1 Kb1 $1 $19) 37... Qd2+ 38. Kg3 Qg5+ 39. Kf2 Qh4+ $1 $17 {with a clear edge for Black.}) 30. Ne8 g5 ({After} 30... Kc5 {White survives by means of} 31. Kf1 $1 Bd7 32. Nxg7 Kc4 33. Ke1 Kc3 34. Nh5 Kxc2 35. Ng3) 31. Kf1 Bf5 32. Ng7 $1 Bxc2 33. Ne6 Bd3+ 34. Ke1 h6 35. Kd2 Bb1 36. Nxd4+ Kc5 37. Kc3 Bxa2 38. Nf5 $1 h5 39. Ng3 Bd5 40. Nxh5 Bxg2 $11 {Now the chances are equal.} 41. Nf6 Kd6 42. Nh7 g4 43. Nf6 Bf3 44. Kb4 Ke6 45. Nxg4 Bxg4 46. f3 {The players found a fast way to exchange all the pieces.} ({or} 46. Kb5 $11) 46... Kf5 47. fxg4+ Kxg4 48. Kb5 Kh3 49. Kxb6 Kxh2 {The line with 5...Be7 is a reasonable alternative to the Berlin endgame, while, after 12.Qh5, 12...Bxd4 looks slightly more accurate than 12...Qe7.} 1/2-1/2


