{Krysa, Leandro: 'La apertura del centro en la Elite mundial. En el Gran Prix de la Fide del 2019 (Torneo Lento), el GM chino Wei Yi empleó la idea de 4...Dc4!? ante Sergey Karjakin, obteniendo una posición razonable y luego la victoria.''La apertura del centro en la Elite mundial. En el Gran Prix de la Fide del 2019 (Torneo Lento), el GM chino Wei Yi empleó la idea de 4...Dc4!? ante Sergey Karjakin, obteniendo una posición razonable y luego la victoria. Mikhalevski,V: 'Krysa, Leandro: 'La apertura del centro en la Elite mundial. En el Gran Prix de la Fide del 2019 (Torneo Lento), el GM chino Wei Yi empleó la idea de 4...Dc4!? ante Sergey Karjakin, obteniendo una posición razonable y luego la victoria.'''} 1. e4 {Krysa, Leandro Krysa, Leandro Krysa, Leandro: 'Mikhalevski,V Mikhalevski,V: 'Krysa, Leandro Krysa, Leandro''} e5 2. d4 {A rare guest at top level events. Mostly we see it in games with faster time controls. The current game is also a rapid game. Krysa, Leandro: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'A rare guest at top level events. Mostly we see it in games with faster time controls. The current game is also a rapid game.''} exd4 3. Qxd4 Nc6 4. Qc4 {A side line, which scored extremely well recently. After the current game it was played by another Chinese player, Xu Xianzhi, who scored 6 out of 6(!) with it. It has to be said that the text has been known since 1837 and was played by world-class players of the past, such as Gunsberg and Mieses at the end of the 19th century and first quarter of the 20th century respectively. Krysa, Leandro: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'A side line, which scored extremely well recently. After the current game it was played by another Chinese player, Xu Xianzhi, who scored 6 out of 6(!) with it. It has to be said that the text has been known since 1837 and was played by world-class players of the past, such as Gunsberg and Mieses at the end of the 19th century and first quarter of the 20th century respectively.''} (4. Qe3 {is the main line. See Taichman,O (2291) -Mikhalevski,V (2503) Tiberias 2016 [Mikhalevski,V] Krysa, Leandro: '(Mikhalevski,V) is the main line. See Taichman,O (2291) -Mikhalevski,V (2503) Tiberias 2016 [Mikhalevski,V]'}) 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 Bb4 {The most logical. Krysa, Leandro: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'The most logical.''} 6. Bd2 {White applies the same setup as in the 4.Qe3 line. Krysa, Leandro: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'White applies the same setup as in the 4.Qe3 line.''} O-O 7. O-O-O {White has obtained a theoretical position with the queen on c4 instead of e3, which seems to be in White's favour as after 7...Re8 the queen doesn't get x-rayed by the rook. Krysa, Leandro: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'White has obtained a theoretical position with the queen on c4 instead of e3, which seems to be in White's favour as after 7...Re8 the queen doesn't get x-rayed by the rook.''} d6 {This natural move was played by almost everyone who faced this line. However, it seems that Black has a stronger alternative. Krysa, Leandro: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'This natural move was played by almost everyone who faced this line. However, it seems that Black has a stronger alternative.''} (7... a5 $5 {The idea behind the move is to protect the bishop so that Black can play ...Ne5 with tempo. Krysa, Leandro: '(Mikhalevski,V) The idea behind the move is to protect the bishop so that Black can play ...Ne5 with tempo.'} 8. Nh3 (8. f3 Ne5 9. Qd4 d6 10. Bf4 (10. Qf2 c6 $17) 10... Qe7) 8... d6 9. Qe2 Re8 10. f3 Ne5 $15) 8. f3 Re8 {Krysa, Leandro: '[#]''[#] Mikhalevski,V: 'Krysa, Leandro: '[#]'''} 9. Qe2 {Krysa, Leandro: 'No es de mi agrado regresar con la dama directamente. Prefiero esperar el ataque negro con Ae6.''No es de mi agrado regresar con la dama directamente. Prefiero esperar el ataque negro con Ae6. Mikhalevski,V: 'Krysa, Leandro: 'No es de mi agrado regresar con la dama directamente. Prefiero esperar el ataque negro con Ae6.'''} (9. g4 {(Krysa, Leandro) Es mi sugerencia Krysa, Leandro: 'Es mi sugerencia Mikhalevski,V: '(Krysa, Leandro) Es mi sugerencia''}) 9... Be6 {Karjakin makes the most natural moves. Krysa, Leandro: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'Karjakin makes the most natural moves.''} ({Black played} 9... a5 $5 {in a blitz game which was played roughly two weeks later Krysa, Leandro: '(Mikhalevski,V) in a blitz game which was played roughly two weeks later'} 10. a3 Ne5 11. g4 (11. Qe1 $5) 11... Be6 12. Qg2 Nc4 (12... d5 $5 {deserved attention.} 13. g5 Nh5 14. exd5 Bxd5 {with the idea} 15. Nxd5 $2 Qxd5 16. Bxb4 Qa2 $1 $19) 13. Bxc4 Bxc4 14. g5 Nd7 15. h4 b5 {with a strong attack for Black in Ponkratov,P (2632)-Matlakov,M (2699) Moscow 2019}) (9... Ne5 $5 {is worth attention too. Krysa, Leandro: '(Mikhalevski,V) is worth attention too.'}) 10. Qf2 {Krysa, Leandro: 'Wei Yi opta en esta partida por un juego más posicional. Libera la casilla e2 para el caballo de g1 e intentar aprovechar su ventaja de espacio.''Wei Yi opta en esta partida por un juego más posicional. Libera la casilla e2 para el caballo de g1 e intentar aprovechar su ventaja de espacio. Mikhalevski,V: 'Krysa, Leandro: 'Wei Yi opta en esta partida por un juego más posicional. Libera la casilla e2 para el caballo de g1 e intentar aprovechar su ventaja de espacio.'''} ({It's unclear who is favoured by the inclusion of the moves a3 and ...a5.} 10. a3 {Krysa, Leandro: 'Mikhalevski,V'} a5 11. Nh3 d5 12. Be1 Qc8 13. Ng5 dxe4 14. Ngxe4 Nxe4 15. Nxe4 Bxe1 16. Qxe1 {with roughly equal chances.}) 10... a5 (10... Ne5 $5 {deserved attention, preparing to advance the queenside pawns. For example, Krysa, Leandro: '(Mikhalevski,V) deserved attention, preparing to advance the queenside pawns. For example,'} 11. g4 ({or} 11. Nge2 c6 12. Nd4 b5) 11... Nfd7 12. h4 c6 13. a3 a5 14. Qg3 Nc5 15. h5 b5 16. h6 g5 {with a complex position.}) (10... Bxc3 {Krysa, Leandro Krysa, Leandro: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'Krysa, Leandro''} 11. Bxc3 Bxa2 12. b3 a5 13. Kb2 a4 14. Kxa2 axb3+ 15. Kb1 {Es caótico, con chances mutuas.}) 11. Nge2 Qe7 $2 {This move is an important waste of time. Krysa, Leandro: '[#]''[#] Mikhalevski,V: '?' Mikhalevski,V: 'This move is an important waste of time. Krysa, Leandro: '[#]'''} ({Black still had to play} 11... Ne5 $1 {Krysa, Leandro: 'Mikhalevski,V'} 12. Nd4 c6 13. g4 b5 {with counterplay.}) 12. Nf4 $2 {Wei Yi misses a chance to set serious problems. Krysa, Leandro: 'Era importante mantener el caballo en e2, para respaldar a su par de c3. Tras esta imprecisión, el negro se hizo de la ventaja.''Era importante mantener el caballo en e2, para respaldar a su par de c3. Tras esta imprecisión, el negro se hizo de la ventaja. Mikhalevski,V: 'Wei Yi misses a chance to set serious problems. Krysa, Leandro: 'Era importante mantener el caballo en e2, para respaldar a su par de c3. Tras esta imprecisión, el negro se hizo de la ventaja.'''} (12. g4 $1 {was strong, preparing 13.Ng3 followed by 14. g5. Krysa, Leandro: 'Hubiese sido mejor, con ventaja blanca.''Hubiese sido mejor, con ventaja blanca. Mikhalevski,V: '!' Mikhalevski,V: 'was strong, preparing 13.Ng3 followed by 14. g5. Krysa, Leandro: 'Hubiese sido mejor, con ventaja blanca.'''} Bc5 {Krysa, Leandro: 'Mikhalevski,V'} (12... Ne5 {Krysa, Leandro: 'Mikhalevski,V'} 13. Ng3) 13. Qg3 a4 14. Nf4 a3 15. b3 Nd4 (15... Bd4 16. g5 Nd7 17. Nfe2 $1 $16) 16. g5 Nd7 17. Nxe6 Nxe6 18. f4 c6 19. Bg2 {with a clear edge for White.}) 12... Bxc3 $1 13. Bxc3 Nb4 $1 {Now White is the one who experiences problems. Krysa, Leandro: '[#] Y aquí las negras obtuvieron la iniciativa, aunque luego Wei Yi terminaría imponiéndose.''[#] Y aquí las negras obtuvieron la iniciativa, aunque luego Wei Yi terminaría imponiéndose. Mikhalevski,V: 'Now White is the one who experiences problems. Krysa, Leandro: '[#] Y aquí las negras obtuvieron la iniciativa, aunque luego Wei Yi terminaría imponiéndose.'''} 14. a3 $2 {This mistake could cost White the game. Krysa, Leandro: 'Mikhalevski,V: '?' Mikhalevski,V: 'This mistake could cost White the game.''} (14. Bxf6 $1 {was necessary. Krysa, Leandro: '(Mikhalevski,V) was necessary.'} Qxf6 (14... Nxa2+ 15. Kb1 Qxf6 16. Nxe6 Qxe6 17. c3 Nxc3+ 18. bxc3 Qb3+ 19. Kc1 Qxc3+ 20. Qc2 {with roughly equal chances.}) 15. Nxe6 Nxa2+ (15... Rxe6 {is also equal.}) 16. Kb1 Qxe6 17. c3 {transposing to 14...Nxa2.}) 14... Na2+ 15. Kd2 (15. Kb1 {Krysa, Leandro: 'Mikhalevski,V'} Nxc3+ 16. bxc3 b5 $1 $19 {is bad for White.}) 15... d5 $5 {It looks very logical to open the d-file against White's king. Krysa, Leandro: 'Mikhalevski,V: '!?' Mikhalevski,V: 'It looks very logical to open the d-file against White's king.''} ({However,} 15... Nxc3 $1 {Krysa, Leandro: 'Mikhalevski,V'} 16. Kxc3 Bg4 $1 {was even stronger.} 17. Kd2 Qe5 18. Ne2 Qxb2 19. Qd4 Qxd4+ (19... Nxe4+ $5 20. fxe4 Qxd4+ 21. Nxd4 Bxd1 22. Kxd1 Rxe4 {is also clearly better for Black.}) 20. Nxd4 Bd7 $17 {with a healthy extra pawn.}) 16. Bxf6 {It makes a lot of sense to move the bishop away from an attack from the a2-knight, trying to leave Black with a misplaced piece. Krysa, Leandro: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'It makes a lot of sense to move the bishop away from an attack from the a2-knight, trying to leave Black with a misplaced piece.''} ({Nevertheless,} 16. exd5 $5 {deserved attention. Krysa, Leandro: '(Mikhalevski,V) deserved attention.'} Nxd5 17. Nxd5 Bxd5 18. Bd4 Rad8 19. Bd3 Be6 20. Rhe1 b6 21. Ke2 c5 22. Be5 f6 23. Qh4 g5 24. Bxh7+ Qxh7 25. Qxh7+ Kxh7 26. Rxd8 Rxd8 27. Bxf6 $15 {with a worse, but playable position.}) 16... Qxf6 17. Nd3 dxe4 18. fxe4 Qg6 $17 {The material on the board is equal, but the white king is in the centre, so Black's chances are better. Krysa, Leandro: 'Mikhalevski,V: '' Mikhalevski,V: 'The material on the board is equal, but the white king is in the centre, so Black's chances are better.''} 19. Be2 $1 {Time to finish development, even at the cost of a pawn. Krysa, Leandro: 'Mikhalevski,V: '!' Mikhalevski,V: 'Time to finish development, even at the cost of a pawn.''} b5 $2 {This inaccurate move throws away all the advantage. Karjakin's idea was to free his knight from a2. Instead, he had to think how to create problems for White's king. Krysa, Leandro: 'Mikhalevski,V: '?' Mikhalevski,V: 'This inaccurate move throws away all the advantage. Karjakin's idea was to free his knight from a2. Instead, he had to think how to create problems for White's king.''} (19... Rad8 $1 {What could be better than this simple move? Krysa, Leandro: '(Mikhalevski,V) What could be better than this simple move?'} 20. Bf3 Bc4 21. Rhe1 Qa6 22. Re3 {and only now, when White is tied to defence, Black plays} b5 $1 23. Ke1 b4 24. Kf1 bxa3 25. bxa3 Qd6 $17 {and wins the a-pawn.}) 20. Qg3 $1 {It's clear that an exchange of queens favours White and so Wei Yi offers it. Krysa, Leandro: 'Mikhalevski,V: '!' Mikhalevski,V: 'It's clear that an exchange of queens favours White and so Wei Yi offers it.''} Qf6 $1 {Sergey also understands that it has to be avoided. Krysa, Leandro: 'Mikhalevski,V: '!' Mikhalevski,V: 'Sergey also understands that it has to be avoided.''} 21. Qe5 ({After} 21. Rhf1 $5 {Krysa, Leandro: 'Mikhalevski,V'} Qe7 22. Ke1 $11 {the king on e1 is pretty safe and so White's chances are not worse.}) 21... Qe7 $6 {An inaccuracy. Krysa, Leandro: 'Mikhalevski,V: '?!' Mikhalevski,V: 'An inaccuracy.''} (21... Qd8 $5 {Krysa, Leandro: 'Mikhalevski,V'} 22. Qc5 b4 {was worth a try, although after} 23. Bf3 bxa3 24. bxa3 Rb8 25. Ke3 $1 {White seems to equalise.}) 22. Qxb5 (22. Qc5 $1 {is an important tempo White could win. Krysa, Leandro: '(Mikhalevski,V) is an important tempo White could win.'} Qh4 23. Ke3 $1 $14 {and it turns out that White consolidates while the knight on a2 remains out of play.}) 22... Rab8 $2 {A mistake. White's queen is well placed on c5 and so Black had to prevent it, instead of forcing the queen to this square. Krysa, Leandro: 'Mikhalevski,V: '?' Mikhalevski,V: 'A mistake. White's queen is well placed on c5 and so Black had to prevent it, instead of forcing the queen to this square.''} (22... Rad8 $1 {Krysa, Leandro: 'Mikhalevski,V'} 23. Bf3 c5 24. Ke3 c4 25. Nf4 Qa7+ 26. Ke2 Rb8 27. Qe5 c3 28. Nxe6 Rxe6 29. Qd5 Qa6+ 30. Rd3 Ree8 $1 {and Black creates enough counterplay.}) 23. Qc5 $16 {Now White is better due to the bad position of the knight on a2, while White's king is getting to safety. Krysa, Leandro: 'Mikhalevski,V: '' Mikhalevski,V: 'Now White is better due to the bad position of the knight on a2, while White's king is getting to safety.''} Qh4 24. Bf3 ({The immediate} 24. Ke3 $1 $18 {was also strong. Krysa, Leandro: '(Mikhalevski,V) was also strong.'}) 24... g6 {Krysa, Leandro: '[#]''[#] Mikhalevski,V: 'Krysa, Leandro: '[#]'''} (24... c6 $5 {Krysa, Leandro: 'Mikhalevski,V'} 25. Ke3 Rb5 26. Qxc6 Qg5+ 27. Kf2 $18 {is also winning for White.}) 25. g3 {Krysa, Leandro: '!' '!''Mikhalevski,V: 'Krysa, Leandro: '!' '!'''} Qh6+ 26. Ke2 Qg7 27. Kf2 $18 {The position has changed drastically during the last ten moves. Now White has a healthy extra pawn and Black's knight on a2 is in trouble. So, Black decides to sacrifice an exchange and free the knight. Krysa, Leandro: 'Mikhalevski,V: '+-' Mikhalevski,V: 'The position has changed drastically during the last ten moves. Now White has a healthy extra pawn and Black's knight on a2 is in trouble. So, Black decides to sacrifice an exchange and free the knight.''} Rxb2 28. Nxb2 Qxb2 29. Rb1 Qc3 30. Qxc3 Nxc3 31. Rb7 {The endgame is clearly winning. Krysa, Leandro: 'Mikhalevski,V: 'The endgame is clearly winning.''} c5 32. Re1 (32. a4 $5 $18 {fixing the a-pawn on a5 was also strong. Krysa, Leandro: '(Mikhalevski,V) fixing the a-pawn on a5 was also strong.'}) 32... Rd8 33. Ke3 Rd4 34. Ra1 Kg7 35. Ra7 Ra4 36. Rb7 Rd4 37. Rb6 Rc4 $2 {A blunder in a lost position. Krysa, Leandro: 'Mikhalevski,V: '?' Mikhalevski,V: 'A blunder in a lost position.''} (37... Na4 {could prolong the fight, but it wouldn't change the outcome. Krysa, Leandro: '(Mikhalevski,V) could prolong the fight, but it wouldn't change the outcome.'} 38. Rb5 Rc4 39. Kd2 Rd4+ 40. Ke1 Rc4 41. Rxa5 $18) 38. Rxe6 $1 {Black loses the knight on c3 and so he resigned. The Centre game is a semi-correct opening, although in order to prove it Black needs time. So, it makes sense to try it once in a while in games with fast time controls. Both 7. .a5 and 9...a5 look like possible improvements on Black's play in this game. Krysa, Leandro: 'Mikhalevski,V: '!' Mikhalevski,V: 'Black loses the knight on c3 and so he resigned. The Centre game is a semi-correct opening, although in order to prove it Black needs time. So, it makes sense to try it once in a while in games with fast time controls. Both 7. .a5 and 9...a5 look like possible improvements on Black's play in this game.''} 1-0


