[EventCountry "RUS"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5 Be6 9. Nbd2 Be7 10. c3 O-O 11. Bc2 f5 12. exf6 {An old line, which is completely out of fashion these days. Nevertheless, I was surprised to see that we had not yet considered it on our pages. Time to fill the gap.} (12. Nb3 {can be found in the current update see Svidler,P (2739)-Vitiugov,N (2734) Moscow RUS 2019 [Mikhalevski,V]}) 12... Nxf6 13. Re1 $5 {A pretty rare continuation. White's idea is to exploit the weakness of the queenside and the e6-square.} (13. Nb3 {is still the most popular continuation.}) 13... Qd7 (13... Bg4 $5 {is a possible alternative.}) 14. a4 $1 {An interesting novelty in a very uncommon position. White is trying to create a target on b5.} ({Earlier White played} 14. Nf1 Rae8 $6 (14... Bd6 $1 {was more accurate.}) 15. Ng5 {Baramidze, D (2542)-L'Ami,E (2541) Germany 2006} ({White could set problems by means of} 15. Bg5 $1 Bc5 16. b4 Bb6 17. Bb3 $14) 15... Bg4 $1 16. f3 Bf5 $11) 14... Bf5 $6 {An exchange of the light-squared bishops in such a position is double-edged. On one side Black exchanges his "bad" bishop for White's "good" bishop. On the other it weakens the light squares in Black's camp.} (14... b4 $1 {keeping the a-file closed was better.} 15. a5 $1 {White is preparing 16.Ba4.} bxc3 16. bxc3 Bc5 17. Ba3 $1 Bxa3 18. Rxa3 Bf7 19. Qc1 Qd6 $14 {with just a slight edge for White.}) 15. Bxf5 Qxf5 16. axb5 $1 axb5 17. Rxa8 Rxa8 18. Nf1 $1 $16 {Suddenly Black starts to experience problems, as his b5 and d5-pawns are weak and the knight on c6 is misplaced. The latter prevents Black from playing ...c6 and consolidating his position.} Qd7 ({An attempt to get rid of the b-pawn by means of} 18... b4 {doesn't solve all the problems.} 19. Bg5 $1 bxc3 20. bxc3 Qd7 21. Ne3 Rd8 22. c4 $1 dxc4 23. Qc2 $16 {and despite the limited material Black still has problems to solve.}) 19. Bg5 $1 {White is going to exchange an important defender of the d5-pawn and the kingside.} Rd8 {Wei Yi strengthens the d5-pawn.} (19... b4 $5 {was still reasonable.}) 20. Ng3 $1 {Ian is preparing 21.Qd3 followed by 22.Nf5.} h6 21. Bxf6 Bxf6 22. Nh5 $1 $16 {An annoying move, which distracts Black from protecting his queenside pawns.} Qf5 $5 (22... Rf8 $5 {deserved attention. For example,} 23. Nf4 Bxc3 $1 24. Nxd5 Bd4 $1 25. Qb3 $1 Qf7 26. Qxb5 Ne5 27. Ne7+ Qxe7 28. Nxd4 c5 29. Qb3+ Qf7 30. Qxf7+ Rxf7 31. Rxe5 cxd4 32. Re2 Rb7 {with good chances to survive. Probably White can deviate from this line.}) 23. Nxf6+ Qxf6 24. Qb3 b4 $1 {An important resource. The Chinese player gives up a pawn, but creates doubled pawns on the b-file and a passed pawn on the d-file.} 25. cxb4 Nd4 26. Nxd4 Qxd4 27. Rd1 Qe5 {Now Black's goal to trade the queenside pawns and queens reaching a drawish rook endgame of 3 vs 2 on one side.} 28. g3 $16 Kh8 $1 29. Qc3 d4 $1 30. Qd3 (30. Qc5 $5 Rd5 31. Qc4 $16 {was interesting.}) 30... c6 $1 {Black fixes the b-pawn on b4 in order to attack it with his heavy pieces.} 31. b3 Qd6 $1 32. Rc1 Rb8 $1 33. h4 $1 Rxb4 ({Black could also wait on the d-file.} 33... Qd7 34. Rc4 Rd8 $14) 34. Qa6 $1 {White's idea behind the pawn sacrifice.} Rb8 35. Rxc6 Qd5 36. Rc8+ Rxc8 37. Qxc8+ Kh7 38. Qc4 Qf3 $1 39. Qxd4 Qxb3 {This endgame with the queens is more dangerous than the one with rooks, but probably still defendable, as Black showed in the game.} 40. Qe4+ Kh8 41. Kg2 Qf7 42. g4 Qf6 43. Kg3 g5 44. hxg5 hxg5 45. Qf5 Qe7 46. Kf3 Kg7 47. Qe4 Qf6+ 48. Qf5 Qe7 49. Qd5 Qf6+ 50. Ke2 Qb2+ 51. Qd2 Qb5+ 52. Qd3 Qb2+ 53. Kf1 Qc1+ 54. Kg2 Qc6+ 55. f3 Qe6 56. Qd4+ Qf6 57. Qb4 Qe5 58. Kf2 Kf7 59. Qe4 Qb2+ 60. Ke3 Qc3+ 61. Ke2 Qb2+ 62. Kd3 Qb3+ 63. Kd4 Qb4+ 64. Ke5 Qb2+ 65. Qd4 Qe2+ 66. Qe4 Qb2+ 67. Qd4 Qe2+ 68. Qe4 {This game demonstrated that the line with 12.exf6 is not without venom and I'm expecting more practical tests at the top level.} 1/2-1/2


