1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5 Be6 9. Nbd2 Be7 10. c3 Nc5 11. Bc2 d4 12. Nb3 d3 13. Bb1 Nxb3 14. axb3 Bf5 15. b4 O-O 16. Re1 Qd7 17. Bf4 {A new move in a well-known position.} ({Earlier we considered} 17. Bg5 {in Safarli,E (2660)-Nakamura,H (2772)/Tromso NOR 2013/  [Mikhalevski,V]}) ({and the main line} 17. h3 {in Caruana,F (2805)-Giri,A  (2773)/Stavanger NOR 2015/[Mikhalevski,V] and some other games.}) 17... Rfd8 {Wei Yi is offering a transposition into the main line.} ({An old correspondence game saw the typical} 17... a5 $2 {, which is premature here because of} 18. bxa5 Nxa5 19. Nd4 {and White won a pawn in Hauptmann, G-Allermann,H/Germany 1989/Corr 2000.}) 18. h4 {A surprising and slightly dubious idea, as the pawn on h4 may become vulnerable.} (18. h3 {would transpose back into 17.h3 Svidler, P (2745)-Mamedyarov,S (2743)/Reykjavik ISL 2015/[Mikhalevski,V].}) 18... h6 $1 {The most accurate reaction. Black takes control of the g5-square and makes a luft. Black is also making a waiting move before playing ...a5 in order to provoke White's rook to e3.} ({I also checked out the immediate} 18... a5 19. bxa5 Rxa5 20. Rxa5 Nxa5 21. Nd4 c5 22. e6 $1 Bxe6 23. Qxd3 g6 24. Nxe6 Qxd3 25. Bxd3 Rxd3 26. Nc7 Bxh4 27. Re8+ Kg7 28. g3 Bd8 29. Nxb5 {is a little bit more pleasant for White, but Black shouldn't have problems to hold here.}) 19. Re3 (19. Ba2 $5 $11 {supporting an advance of the e-pawn deserved attention.}) 19... a5 $1 20. bxa5 Rxa5 (20... Bc5 {leads to some complications after} 21. Re1 b4 $1 22. a6 Ne7 {when Black still has to prove his compensation for the sacrificed pawn is sufficient.}) (20... Nxa5 {is also sufficient for equality.} 21. e6 (21. Nd4 $6 Nc4 22. Rxa8 Rxa8 {is a better version of the game for Black.}) 21... fxe6 22. Nd4 Nc4 23. Rxa8 Rxa8 24. Nxf5 exf5 25. Rxd3 Qe6 26. b3 Nb2 27. Re3 Nxd1 28. Rxe6 Ra1 29. Bd3 Nxc3+ 30. Kh2 Nd5 31. Bxf5 Bxh4 32. Be5 Ra2 33. Bg6 Rxf2 34. Re8+ Rf8 35. Bh7+ Kf7 36. Bg6+ Kg8) 21. Rxa5 Nxa5 22. Nd4 (22. e6 fxe6 23. Nd4 Nc4 24. Nxf5 Nxe3 25. Nxe3 c5 {leads to the game with the moves e6 and ...fxe6 included. It's not easy to say who is favoured by this inclusion.}) 22... Nc4 {This is why the rook was provoked to e3.} 23. Nxf5 $5 {The most ambitious option.} (23. Rg3 {is interesting, but insufficient for an advantage.} Bxh4 24. Rxg7+ $1 Kxg7 25. Qh5 Bg5 26. Bxg5 hxg5 27. Qxg5+ Bg6 28. Bxd3 {Black is a full rook up, but White's attack is very strong and Black should return some material.} Nxe5 $1 29. Qxe5+ Kg8 30. Bxb5 Qd6 {with a roughly equal endgame.}) 23... Nxe3 24. Nxe3 {A complex position with two minor pieces versus rook has occurred. Black's main trump here is obviously his passed d-pawn and so Black is going to support it with his c-pawn.} c5 25. b3 {Kasimdzhanov is preventing an advance of the c-pawn to c4.} (25. c4 $5 {disconnecting the pawns deserved serious attention..} Bxh4 26. g3 Bg5 27. Bxg5 hxg5 28. Ba2 $1 {White's idea is to block the d-file by means of 29. Nd5.} b4 (28... Qd4 $2 29. cxb5 Qxb2 30. Bd5 $18 {favours White.}) 29. Nd5 {White wins the d-pawn, but Black is going to win the e-pawn.} Qe6 30. Bb1 Qxe5 31. Bxd3 g6 $1 {and the chances are roughly equal.} (31... Qxb2 32. Qh5 g6 33. Qxg5 {is more risky for Black.})) (25. h5 c4 {is not something a human player is happy about, but my computer still considers the position to be equal.}) 25... Bxh4 26. c4 {Once again White is trying to win the d-pawn by means of 27. Nd5, which explains Black's reaction.} (26. Qf3 Qe6 27. Qd1 Qd7 $11 {is a possible repetition of moves.}) 26... Qd4 $1 27. g3 bxc4 28. bxc4 Bg5 {Black is trying to win the e5-pawn and keep his d-pawn at the same time.} 29. Nf5 $1 {An important intermediate move.} (29. Bxg5 $6 hxg5 {is a little risky for White.}) 29... Qc3 30. Bxg5 hxg5 31. Ne3 {Probably Rustam wanted to preserve winning chances.} ({It would be safer not to retreat his knight from an active position. Instead,} 31. Qf3 $1 {would force a draw.} Qxc4 (31... Qe1+ 32. Kg2 Qxb1 33. Ne7+ Kf8 34. Ng6+ Kg8 (34... Ke8 $2 35. Qc6+ Rd7 36. e6 $1 $18 {wins for White.}) 35. Ne7+ {leads to a repetition.}) ({but not} 31... Kf8 $4 32. Nd6 $18) 32. Ne7+ Kf8 33. Ng6+) 31... g6 $1 32. Kg2 Kg7 33. e6 $5 {An attempt to open up the position of the black king.} fxe6 34. Qa4 $6 {This is already risky.} ({White should have created an attack from the other side, when White's queen is supported by the knight.} 34. Qf3 $1 Qd4 35. Ng4 $1 Rd7 (35... d2 36. Bc2 Rf8 37. Qe2 $11 {leads to a fortress position.}) 36. Bxd3 $1 Qxd3 37. Qf6+ Kh7 (37... Kg8 38. Qxe6+ Kf8 39. Qf6+ {is also equal.}) 38. Qe5 $1 {White vacates the f6-square and forces a draw.} Rf7 39. Nf6+ Kh6 ({or} 39... Kh8 40. Ng4+ Rg7 41. Qb8+ Rg8 42. Qe5+ $11) 40. Ng4+ Kh7 41. Nf6+ {with a draw.}) 34... Qd4 $1 35. Qc6 Rd6 (35... e5 $5 {was probably a better try, but it's difficult to evaluate which move is better than the other.} 36. Qe6 (36. Bxd3 Qxd3 37. Qc7+ Qd7 38. Qxe5+ Kh6 39. Qxc5 Qb7+ 40. Nd5 Re8 {is slightly better for Black, though I'm not sure he can win.}) 36... Rd7 37. Bxd3 Qxd3 38. Qxe5+ Kf7 39. Qxc5 Qe4+ 40. Kg1 Rb7 41. Kh2 Rb1 42. Qc7+ Qe7 43. Qa5 Kg8 {with some winning chances.}) 36. Qb7+ $6 {I wonder if Kasimdzhanov was still trying to play for a win.} (36. Qe8 $1 {is still ok for White.} Qf6 37. Qc8 $1 Qe7 38. Qxc5 Qb7+ 39. Kh2 Rd8 40. Qe5+ Kh7 41. Qxe6 Rh8 $1 42. Qd5 Kg7+ 43. Kg2 Qxb1 44. Qd7+ Kg8 45. Qd8+ {with a draw by perpetual.}) 36... Rd7 37. Qc6 $6 {An inaccuracy again.} (37. Qb8 $1 g4 38. Bxd3 $1 Qxd3 39. Qe5+ Kf8 40. Qxc5+ Qd6 41. Qb5 ({The endgame} 41. Qxd6+ Rxd6 42. Nxg4 {also yields White reasonable drawing chances.}) 41... Qc7 42. Nxg4 Qb7+ 43. Qxb7 Rxb7 44. Kf3 {and White might be able to hold.}) 37... e5 38. Qe6 e4 $6 {Black returns the favour. Probably both players were already short of time.} (38... Rf7 $5 {is a better chance.} 39. Bxd3 $1 Qxd3 40. Qxe5+ Kh7 41. Qxg5 (41. Qxc5 Qe2 42. Nf1 {is a little passive.}) 41... Qd2 42. Qh4+ Kg8 43. Ng4 Kg7 $15) 39. Qg4 $2 {Only this move is losing.} ({After the correct} 39. Ng4 $1 Rf7 40. Qe8 $1 {White holds on.}) 39... Rb7 $5 (39... Rf7 $1 40. Qe6 Qf6 $1 41. Qxe4 Qxf2+ 42. Kh3 Qf3 $1 43. Qxf3 Rxf3 44. Nd5 d2 45. Bc2 Rf1 46. Ne3 Re1 47. Nd1 Kf7 $1 48. Kg4 Kf6 $19 {and Black converts his positional advantage into a win.}) 40. Qc8 (40. Qe6 $1 {is a better defence, though it may not save the game.}) 40... Rf7 $1 $19 {Now White either loses the f2-pawn or exchanges queens. In both cases his position is lost.} 41. Qe6 Qf6 $1 42. Qxe4 (42. Qxf6+ Kxf6 {is hopeless.}) 42... Qxf2+ 43. Kh3 Qf3 $1 {Offering another favourable exchange of queens.} 44. Qe5+ (44. Bxd3 {fails to} Qxe4 45. Bxe4 Re7 $19) 44... Kg8 (44... Kh7 $19 {is equally strong.}) 45. Qe8+ Kh7 46. Ng2 {A sad necessity due to the threat of mate in one.} Qh5+ 47. Nh4 Rg7 {A safe way to win.} (47... Rf3 $5 $19 {is what computers prefer.}) 48. Bxd3 gxh4 {A very interesting game, though I still don't understand the hidden idea behind the advance of the h-pawn to h4. Nevertheless, the line with 13.Bb1 remains a critical test of Black's opening system with 10...Be7 and 11...d4.} 0-1


