1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nxd4 Bb4 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. Bd3 d5 8. exd5 O-O $5 9. O-O {White is intending to transpose to the main line, 8...cxd5.} (9. dxc6 Bg4 10. f3 (10. Be2 Qe8 $1 $17 {with the idea of 11...Rd8 is dangerous for White.}) (10. Qd2 Re8+ 11. Kf1 Be6 $1 $11 {yields Black good compensation for two sacrificed pawns.}) 10... Re8+ 11. Kf1 Be6 $1 $11 {with good compensation, since White lost his right to castle.}) 9... Bg4 $1 {An interesting and aggressive approach, which hasn't been considered on our site yet, as this is the first time it has occured in over the board play. In fact, it had only one predecessor, which can be found below.} (9... cxd5 {has been seen many times before. The most recent example is Morozevich,A (2724) -Karjakin,S (2770) Kazan RUS 2014 [Mikhalevski,V]}) 10. f3 Bh5 11. dxc6 ({The aforementioned correspondence game saw} 11. g4 Bg6 12. Bxg6 hxg6 13. dxc6 Qe7 $6 (13... Bxc3 $5 {equalises.} 14. bxc3 ({or} 14. Qxd8 Rfxd8 15. bxc3 Rd6 $11) 14... Qe8 $1 15. g5 Nh5 16. Qd5 Qe2 $1 17. Qd3 Rfe8 18. Qxe2 Rxe2 19. Rf2 Re1+ 20. Rf1 Re2 $11 {and Black equalises.}) 14. Qe2 Rfe8 $2 (14... Qc5+ {was necessary.}) 15. Qxe7 Rxe7 16. Na4 Re2 17. Bf4 $1 Nd5 18. Bg3 $16 {and Black's compensation was insufficient in Ciklabakkal,M (2004)-Ikegami,O (1999) ICCF email 2012}) 11... Qd4+ 12. Kh1 Bxc3 13. bxc3 Qxc3 {Black won back one of the sacrificed pawns, while the other one is hanging} 14. Rb1 Bg6 $1 {It's important to trade a pair of bishops to take away the advantage of the bishop pair.} (14... Qxc6 {would yield White some chances of obtaining an edge thanks to the bishop pair. For example,} 15. Bb5 Qb6 16. Qe1 $1 Rfe8 17. Qc3 Re6 (17... Nd5 18. Qc6 Red8 19. Ba3 $14) 18. Ba3 {and Black still has some problems to solve.}) 15. Bb2 Qxc6 16. Bxf6 {Encountering a strong novelty Wei Yi decides to simplify into a draw.} Qxf6 17. Bxg6 hxg6 18. Qd7 Qc3 19. Qd3 {This is necessary and leads to massive exchanges.} Qxd3 ({Black can try to keep queens on the board, but his chances to win the game are very slim.} 19... Qc6 20. Rfd1 Rfe8 21. h3 $11) 20. cxd3 Rfd8 21. Rb3 Rab8 22. Rxb8 Rxb8 23. Rc1 Rb2 24. Kg1 Rxa2 25. Rxc7 Rd2 26. Rxa7 Rxd3 {A short, but highly important theoretical game. It seems that 9...Bg4! equalises easily and so the entire Scotch Four Knights is now in trouble.} 1/2-1/2


