1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5 Be6 9. Qe2 Be7 10. Rd1 O-O 11. c4 bxc4 12. Bxc4 Bc5 13. Be3 Bxe3 14. Qxe3 Qb8 15. Bb3 Na5 16. Nd4 c5 {An important alternative to 16...Qb6, which hasn't been considered on our pages yet and leads to the following sequence:} (16... Qb6 {Hansen,E (2574)-Mikhalevski,V (2550) Hoogeveen 2014 [Mikhalevski,V]}) 17. Nxe6 fxe6 18. f3 {White traps the knight on e4 and so Black's reply is rather forced.} c4 $1 19. fxe4 {White doesn't have any choice either.} (19. Bc2 $2 {runs into} Qxb2) 19... cxb3 20. exd5 bxa2 $1 {This improvement was introduced by Anish Giri in 2016.} ({In two early games Black started with} 20... Nc4 {and} 21. Qd4 Qa7 {is the correct move.} 22. Qxa7 Rxa7 23. axb3 (23. Nc3 $5 {is more challenging.}) 23... Ne3 24. Rc1 Raf7 $1 25. Nd2 Rf2 (25... exd5 $5) 26. Nc4 {Kosteniuk,A (2489)-Muzychuk,A (2594) Belgrade 2013, and now} Rxg2+ 27. Kh1 Re2 {led to equality.}) 21. Rxa2 Nc4 22. Qd4 $1 {The only square for the queen.} ({After} 22. Qc3 Qb6+ 23. Qd4 Qxd4+ 24. Rxd4 Ne3 25. Nd2 Rac8 26. Nf3 Rc2 27. dxe6 h6 $1 {Black develops an initiative.}) 22... Qb3 23. Nc3 Rac8 $1 {An important point behind Black's preceding play. He creates the threat of 24.. . Nxb2, which explains White's next move.} 24. Rb1 ({After} 24. dxe6 {Black played} Nxb2 25. e7 Rfe8 26. Qd5+ Qxd5 27. Rxd5 Rxc3 28. Rxb2 Rxe7 {with full equality.}) 24... Nd2 {This is only a formal novelty, as two moves later the players will transpose to the previously played 24...Ne3.} ({Giri played} 24... Ne3) 25. Qxd2 {Other moves make no sense.} Rxc3 26. Qxc3 Qxa2 27. Rd1 exd5 28. Qd4 {White is putting pressure on d5.} Qc4 {One of a few moves which lead to equality. Black offers a pawn to force a rook endgame.} ({In the preceding game Black played} 28... Re8 29. Rc1 h6 30. h3 Kh8 31. e6 Rxe6 $2 (31... Qb3 $1 {was necessary, with equal chances.}) 32. Rc8+ Kh7 33. Qd3+ Re4 34. Qf1 $1 Re5 {and after} 35. Qd3+ Re4 36. Qf1 $1 Re5 37. Qd3+ ({After the correct} 37. Qf7 $1 Qxb2 38. Qg8+ Kg6 39. Rc6+ Kf5 40. Qf7+ Ke4 41. Qf3+ Kd4 42. Qd1+ Ke4 43. Kh2 $1 $18 {Black would be in trouble.}) 37... Re4 38. Qf1 {a draw was agreed in Caruana,F (2804)-Giri,A (2790) Shamkir 2016}) 29. Qxd5+ {There is no alternative to play for a win.} Qxd5 30. Rxd5 Re8 $1 {Black ties White's rook to the defence of the e5-pawn, preparing 31...Kf7 or 31...Kf8 followed by 32... Rb8.} 31. Rd6 {White has nothing to wait for.} (31. Kf2 Rb8 32. Kf3 Rb3+ 33. Ke4 Rxb2 34. Rd8+ Kf7 35. Rd7+ Kf8 36. Kd5 a5 37. g4 h6 38. Ra7 Rxh2 39. Ke6 g5 40. Rxa5 h5 {and White's symbolic edge isn't sufficient for a win.}) 31... Rxe5 32. Rxa6 Re2 {This move shouldn't miss a draw, but 32...Rb5 was better.} (32... Rb5 {looks more accurate. For example,} 33. Ra2 Rb3 34. Kf2 h5 $1 35. Ke2 ({or} 35. h4 Kf7) 35... h4 36. Kd2 h3 37. g3 Rf3 38. Ke2 Rb3 $11 {and White can't make progress due to his bad rook on a2.}) 33. Rb6 h5 $1 34. h4 (34. Rb7 $1 {cutting off Black's king was a better practical chance.} h4 35. h3 Kf8 36. b4 Rb2 37. b5 g6 38. b6 Ke8 39. Rb8+ Kd7 40. b7 Kc6 41. Rc8+ (41. Rg8 Rxb7 42. Rxg6+ Kd5 43. Rg4 Rh7 {with a theoretically drawish position.}) 41... Kxb7 42. Rc4 g5 43. Rc5 Rb1+ (43... g4 $2 {loses to} 44. hxg4 Rb4 45. g5 Kb6 46. Rc8 Rg4 47. Rg8 Kc7 48. Kh2 Rg3 49. g6 Kb6 $1 (49... Kd7 $4 {loses to} 50. g7 Ke7 51. Ra8 $18) 50. g7 Kb7 51. Rh8 Rxg7 52. Rxh4 Kc6 53. Rd4 Kc5 54. Rd2 $18) 44. Kh2 Rb6 45. Rxg5 Kc7 46. Rg7+ Kd8 47. Kg1 Ke8 48. Kf2 Kf8 49. Rg4 Rh6 50. Kf3 Kf7 $11 {and White can't make progress.}) 34... Re4 35. g3 Re3 (35... Re2 $5 {is also fine.}) 36. Kf2 Rd3 37. Rb5 ({or} 37. Rb7 Kh7 $11) 37... Kf7 $1 (37... g6 $2 {would be wrong in view of} 38. Rb7 Kf8 39. b4 Rb3 40. b5 Kg8 41. b6 Kf8 42. Ke2 $1 {The king goes to c2 and then up to b5, while} Rxg3 $2 {loses instantly to} 43. Rc7 $18) 38. b4 Rb3 39. Rf5+ ({or} 39. Rb8 Kf6 40. b5 Kf5 41. b6 g6 42. b7 Kg4 43. Rg8 Rxb7 44. Rxg6+ Kh3 45. Rg5 Rb3 $11) 39... Ke6 ({White hopes for} 39... Kg6 $4 40. Rg5+ Kf6 41. b5 $18 {and White wins.}) 40. Rg5 Rxb4 41. Rxg7 Rb5 {with an easy draw. An important game for the theory, which confirms that the line with 16...c5 leads to equality.} 1/2-1/2


