1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. Nbd2 Nd7 7. Nc4 O-O 8. O-O Re8 9. Bd2 Bd6 ({Earlier we only considered} 9... Bf8 {See Anand,V (2775) -Kramnik,V (2795) London ENG 2012 [Mikhalevski,V]}) 10. Bc3 $5 {Wei Yi is putting pressure on e5 and thus preventing the 10...Nf8-g6 regrouping. In order to transfer the knight to g6 Black will have to play ...f6, which will give White the option of playing on the kingside with Nh4.} (10. b4 {trying to prevent 10...c5 and take some space on the queenside can be answered by} Nb6 $5 ({The only game after 10.b4 saw} 10... Nf8 {, which is also OK for Black..} 11. a4 Ng6 12. h3 b6 13. Re1 Be6 14. Ne3 c5 15. b5 a6 16. c4 Nf4 17. Bc3 Qf6 {with a slight edge for Black in Bologan,V (2670)-Melkumyan,H (2634) Germany 2014}) 11. Na5 (11. Nxd6 cxd6 12. a4 Bg4 {is fine for Black.}) 11... c5 12. b5 a6 13. a4 Qf6 $11 {with the idea of 14...Ra7 and Black can develop his light-squared bishop.}) 10... c5 {Grischuk prefers to eliminate the option of 11.d4.} ({In case of the immediate} 10... f6 {White can play} 11. d4 {, although after} ({White played only} 11. Nh4 Nf8 12. Kh1 Ng6 13. Qh5 Be6 (13... Nf4 $5 14. Qf3 Bf8 {looks good for Black.}) 14. Nf5 Qd7 15. Nce3 Bc5 16. g3 Ne7 17. g4 Ng6 18. Ng2 Bd6 {with roughly equal chances in Wei,Y (2706)-Balogh,C  (2655) Tsaghkadzor 2015}) 11... exd4 12. Nxd6 cxd6 13. Qxd4 Ne5 $1 {Black equalises.}) 11. a4 f6 {Alexander is planning on bringing the knight via f8 to g6 or e6.} ({Black also tried to delay 11...f6, but it didn't stop White from playing on the kingside.} 11... b6 12. g3 $1 f6 13. Nh4 Nb8 14. f4 Nc6 15. Qh5 (15. f5 $5) 15... Be6 16. fxe5 Bf7 17. Qg4 Bxe5 18. Nf5 Bg6 19. Nxe5 Nxe5 20. Qf4 Bxf5 21. Qxf5 {yielded White some pressure on the kingside. Alekseenko,K  (2539)-Sakaev,K (2594) St Petersburg 2015}) 12. Nh4 {Almost an automatic reaction to ...f6.} Nf8 13. g3 {The most natural. White is going for f4.} ({In two preceding games White tested two other options.} 13. Ne3 Ne6 14. g3 Kh8 $6 (14... b6 $5) 15. Qh5 Nd4 16. f4 Be6 $6 17. f5 Bd7 18. Rf2 Kg8 19. g4 $14 {was better for Black in Kokarev,D (2622)-Sharafiev,A (2435) Sochi 2016}) (13. Nf5 Be6 (13... Ne6 $5) 14. Qf3 Qd7 15. Nce3 Ng6 16. h4 $14 {with some pressure in Borisek,J (2565) -Mastrovasilis,A (2544) Reykjavik 2015}) 13... Bh3 $5 {It would be good to force the f1-rook away from the f-file, but White isn't obliged to do so.} ({In case of} 13... Ne6 {, which prevents the immediate 14. f4, White would play} 14. Qd2 Nd4 15. f4 Be6 16. f5 Bf7 17. g4 {with some chances for an attack.}) 14. Ng2 Qd7 $1 (14... Ng6 {would be inaccurate as Black can't stop an advance of the f-pawn, while the knight on g6 may turn out to be misplaced.} 15. Nce3 Qd7 16. b3 Rad8 17. Qh5 $14 {with the idea of 18.f4.}) 15. f4 exf4 16. gxf4 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 f5 $1 {White should be stopped from playing 18.f5.} 18. e5 Qc6+ $1 {It's important to take control of the a8-h1 diagonal before White plays 19. Qf3.} (18... Be7 $6 19. Qf3 $1 $14 {yields White the upper hand.}) 19. Qf3 {Sooner or later White would have to exchange the queen on c6.} Qxf3+ 20. Kxf3 Be7 {Now Black's plan includes blocking the position on the kingside by putting his pawns on g6 and h5, the knight will block the e5-pawn from e6 and White will have a hard time breaking through Black's fortress.} 21. Ne3 ({In case of the immediate} 21. Rh1 {Black would first block the e5-pawn with} Ne6 $1 {in order to prevent the e5-e6 option, which is strong after black places his pawns on h5 and g6.} 22. h4 h5 {and the position is similar to the one in the game.}) 21... g6 22. Rh1 (22. Nd5 {doesn't present a problem as Black can easily part with his bishop.} Ne6 23. Nxe7+ Rxe7 24. h4 h5 {with a solid position.}) 22... Red8 $5 ({Black could also put the other rook on d8.} 22... Rad8 {with a similar position, when the other rook can be used on the kingside protecting the g6-pawn after Black plays ...h5.}) 23. h4 h5 $1 {This move is a necessity. Otherwise, Black would come under an attack on the kingside.} 24. Kg3 {White protects the h4-pawn in order to free his h1-rook from defence.} Ne6 25. Nc4 b6 {A useful move. Now the idea of a5 can be always met by...b5.} 26. Nd2 Bf8 $5 {Black's idea is to meet 27.Nf3 with 27...Bh6!} 27. Rhf1 ({In case of} 27. Nf3 Bh6 {White would have to exchange his knight for Black's bishop, which favours Black.} 28. Ng5 Bxg5 29. hxg5 Kf7 {and Black is fine.}) 27... a6 28. Nf3 Kf7 {The king is coming closer to e6 in order to blockade the e5-pawn after an exchange of knights on g5.} 29. b3 (29. Ng5+ Nxg5 30. hxg5 Ke6 $11) 29... Rd5 30. Bd2 Rad8 {Now neither side can make progress and so after repeating the moves a few times the players agreed to a draw.} 31. Ra2 R5d7 32. Be3 Rd5 33. Bd2 R5d7 34. Be3 Rd5 35. Bd2 {A well-played game. Grischuk showed a good understanding of these type of positions and equalised comfortably. The ball is in White's court.} 1/2-1/2


