1. e4 {[%emt 0:00:00] Fernandez,Daniel Howard: 'Fernandez,D'} e5 {[%emt 0:00:05]} 2. Nf3 {[%emt 0:00:00]} Nc6 {[%emt 0:00:04]} 3. Nc3 {[%emt 0:00:53]} Nf6 {[%emt 0:00:09]} 4. Bb5 {[%emt 0:00:08]} Nd4 {[%emt 0:00:15] Fernandez,Daniel Howard: 'Black had no truly adventurous choices in any case, except the slightly odd 4...d6. Quite solid are the well-known 4...d6 and 4...b4.'} 5. Bc4 {[%emt 0:01:07]} (5. Ba4 $5 {is the main line, trying to prevent Black from playing ...d5 under favourable conditions. Play could continue:} Bc5 $5 (5... Nxf3+ 6. Qxf3 Bc5 $11 {is stable equality, though White has also tried the pawn recapture.}) 6. Nxe5 O-O 7. Nd3 Bb6 8. e5 Ne8 9. Nd5 {Now see, for instance, Morozevich-Svidler, Thessaloniki 2013, or Kasparov-Dominguez, Saint Louis 2017.}) 5... Bc5 {[%emt 0:00:11]} 6. d3 {[%emt 0:02:00]} (6. Nxe5 Qe7 $1 {is vaguely reminiscent of the Traxler Counter-Gambit and is in any case more dangerous for White than Black.}) 6... d6 {[%emt 0:00:12]} 7. Na4 {[%emt 0:02:00] This knight move can be considered the main line. Fernandez,Daniel Howard: 'Mikhalevski,Victor: 'This knight move can be considered the main line.'' Fernandez,Daniel Howard: 'Initiating large-scale exchanges in a tried and tested manner.'} (7. h3 {is most played, but seems a little slow, especially since Black can just respond to g5/d5 ideas with a laconic ...c6.}) 7... b5 {[%emt 0:01:29] Nowadays this is the most popular reply. Fernandez,Daniel Howard: 'Mikhalevski,Victor: 'Nowadays this is the most popular reply.''} ({Earlier we only considered} 7... Nxf3+ {in Svidler,P (2749) -Karjakin,S (2785) Moscow RUS 2012 [Mikhalevski,V]}) 8. Nxd4 {[%emt 0:00:39]} (8. Nxc5 $6 {is dubious due to} bxc4 9. Nxd4 exd4 $1 10. Na4 Bd7 11. b3 c3 $17 {with the better chances for Black as the knight on a4 is completely out of play, while Black may consider taking it at any time.}) 8... bxc4 {[%emt 0:00:13]} 9. Nf5 $1 {[%emt 0:00:52] The best retreat. Fernandez,Daniel Howard: 'Mikhalevski,Victor: '!' Mikhalevski,Victor: 'The best retreat.'' Fernandez,Daniel Howard: 'Mikhalevski,Victor: '!' '!' Mikhalevski,Victor: 'The best retreat.''} ({In a recent game Svidler tested} 9. Ne2 cxd3 (9... Bb6 {is also interesting.}) 10. Qxd3 Bb4+ ({There is also nothing wrong with} 10... Bb6 11. O-O O-O 12. Ng3 Qe8 13. Nxb6 axb6 $11 {Post,E-Flamberg,A Mannheim 1914}) 11. c3 Qd7 $6 (11... Ba5 $1 {was better, having in mind to meet} 12. Qb5+ {with} c6 13. Qxc6+ Bd7 14. Qxd6 Bc7 (14... Bxa4 15. Qxe5+ Kf8 {also looks fine for Black.}) 15. Qa6 Nxe4 16. O-O Nd6 17. c4 Bc8 18. Qc6+ Bd7 19. Qa6 {with a repetition.}) 12. b3 Ba5 13. O-O (13. Bg5 $1 $14 {was the only chance to fight for an opening advantage.}) 13... Bb7 14. f3 Bc6 15. Qa6 Bb6+ 16. Nxb6 axb6 17. Qd3 d5 {and Black at least equalised. Svidler,P (2768)-Giri,A (2752) Wijk aan Zee NED 2018}) (9. Nf3 Bb6 10. Bg5 cxd3 11. Qxd3 Qd7 (11... h6 $5 12. Bh4 O-O {is more comfortable for Black.}) 12. Nc3 Ng4 13. Bh4 f6 {and Black was fine in Artemiev,V (2621)-Babujian,L (2491) Yerevan 2014}) 9... Bxf5 {[%emt 0:00:39]} 10. exf5 {[%emt 0:00:18]} cxd3 {[%emt 0:00:37]} 11. Nxc5 {[%emt 0:05:41]} dxc5 {[%emt 0:00:50]} 12. cxd3 {[%emt 0:04:21] Fernandez,Daniel Howard: 'So far following a source game from 2 years ago. What seems likely is that central pawn exchanges will follow and then a draw.'} ({White also tested two alternatives.} 12. Bg5 e4 $1 13. cxd3 exd3 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 ({Black could try to set some problems with} 14... gxf6 $1 15. O-O Qd5 (15... O-O $5 16. Qg4+ Kh8 17. Qc4 Qd6 18. Rad1 Rad8 19. Rd2 Rfe8 $15) 16. Re1+ Kf8 17. Re3 Rg8 18. Qf3 Rd8 19. Rd1 c4 20. Qxd5 Rxd5 21. b3 cxb3 22. axb3 Rg5 23. Rexd3 Rxd3 24. Rxd3 Rxf5 {with an extra pawn for Black. although White retains good drawing chances.}) 15. Qxd3 O-O 16. O-O Qxb2 17. Qc4 Qe5 18. Rac1 Qxf5 {and a draw was agreed in Ivanchuk,V (2710)-Cheparinov,I (2687) Varadero 2016}) (12. Qxd3 O-O $6 (12... Qxd3 $1 13. cxd3 O-O-O 14. Ke2 Nd5 $11 {promises Black equal chances.}) 13. Be3 $14 {and White was better in Baenziger,F (2379)-Kranz,A (2054) Austria AUT 2018}) 12... Qd7 $5 {[%emt 0:08:38] Fernandez,Daniel Howard: 'Mikhalevski,Victor: '!?'' Fernandez,Daniel Howard: 'Mikhalevski,Victor: '!?' '!?''} ({Black could also start with} 12... O-O $5 13. Be3 Qd7 14. Rc1 Qxf5 15. Rxc5 Rfd8 16. O-O Rxd3 17. Qc2 h6 18. Rxc7 Nd5 19. Rxa7 Rxa7 20. Bxa7 Nf4 21. Be3 Nxg2 $1 22. Kxg2 Qg4+ {with a draw.}) 13. Qf3 {[%emt 0:02:45]} O-O {[%emt 0:02:25]} 14. O-O {[%emt 0:00:33]} (14. Bg5 {doesn't promise any advantage either. Fernandez,Daniel Howard: 'Mikhalevski,Victor: 'doesn't promise any advantage either.''} Nd5 (14... e4 15. dxe4 Nxe4 $11) 15. O-O f6 16. Be3 Nxe3 17. fxe3 Rad8 $1 18. Rac1 Qb5 $11) 14... Rfd8 {[%emt 0:08:39]} 15. Be3 {[%emt 0:00:57]} Qxd3 {[%emt 0:00:40]} 16. Rac1 {[%emt 0:00:28] Fernandez,Daniel Howard: 'To be honest with you, I doubt it makes much difference which rook White plays with here.'} (16. Rfc1 e4 17. Qg3 Qd5 18. Qxc7 Rac8 19. Qf4 $11 {Maze,S-Fressinet,L Agen 2016, was the source game, maybe marginally more pleasant for Black but still ultimately agreed drawn without much trouble.}) 16... c4 $1 {[%emt 0:03:13] Fernandez,Daniel Howard: 'Mikhalevski,Victor: '!'' Fernandez,Daniel Howard: 'Mikhalevski,Victor: '!' '!''} 17. h3 $1 {[%emt 0:09:03] A clever move. There is no rush in winning back the c4-pawn. Fernandez,Daniel Howard: 'Mikhalevski,Victor: '!' Mikhalevski,Victor: 'A clever move. There is no rush in winning back the c4-pawn.'' Fernandez,Daniel Howard: 'Mikhalevski,Victor: '!' '!' Mikhalevski,Victor: 'A clever move. There is no rush in winning back the c4-pawn.''} h6 $5 {[%emt 0:05:15] Caruana also prefers to make a luft. Fernandez,Daniel Howard: 'Mikhalevski,Victor: '!?' Mikhalevski,Victor: 'Caruana also prefers to make a luft.'' Fernandez,Daniel Howard: 'Mikhalevski,Victor: '!?' '!?' Mikhalevski,Victor: 'Caruana also prefers to make a luft.''} (17... a5 $5 {with the idea to bring the a8-rook into play deserved serious attention as well.} 18. Rc3 e4 $1 19. Qg3 (19. Rxd3 exf3 20. Rxd8+ Rxd8 21. Rc1 Ne4 22. gxf3 ({or} 22. Rxc4 Rd1+ 23. Kh2 Nd2 $1 24. Bxd2 Rxd2 25. Rxc7 g5 $1 $11) 22... Nd6 23. Bf4 Kf8 24. Bxd6+ Rxd6 25. Rxc4 Rd2 $11 {with equal chances.}) 19... Qd5 20. Bg5 Qxf5 21. Rxc4 Rd3 22. Qh4 Rad8 23. Rxc7 h6 24. Bxf6 Qxf6 25. Qxf6 gxf6 $11) (17... e4 $11 {kept equality more easily.}) 18. Rc3 {[%emt 0:16:53]} Qe4 {[%emt 0:08:35]} (18... Qd5 $1 19. Qxd5 Nxd5 20. Rxc4 a5 $11 {keeps everything watertight.}) 19. Qxe4 {[%emt 0:01:38]} Nxe4 {[%emt 0:00:05]} 20. Rxc4 {[%emt 0:00:11]} Nd2 $1 {[%emt 0:03:21] The point of the move 17...h6. In the coming rook endgame Black obtains good drawing chances. Fernandez,Daniel Howard: 'Mikhalevski,Victor: '!' Mikhalevski,Victor: 'The point of the move 17...h6. In the coming rook endgame Black obtains good drawing chances.'' Fernandez,Daniel Howard: 'Mikhalevski,Victor: '!' '!' Mikhalevski,Victor: 'The point of the move 17...h6. In the coming rook endgame Black obtains good drawing chances.''} 21. Bxd2 {[%emt 0:00:08]} Rxd2 {[%emt 0:00:05]} 22. Rb1 {[%emt 0:04:46]} ({Black has made a few very minor inaccuracies, and now} 22. Rxc7 $5 Rxb2 23. Re1 $1 Rxa2 24. Rxe5 $14 {might still make Black do a little bit of work in an unpleasant 4-v-3 rook endgame.}) 22... Rad8 $1 {[%emt 0:08:08] Fabiano activates his rooks. Fernandez,Daniel Howard: 'Mikhalevski,Victor: '!' Mikhalevski,Victor: 'Fabiano activates his rooks.'' Fernandez,Daniel Howard: 'Mikhalevski,Victor: '!' '!' Mikhalevski,Victor: 'Fabiano activates his rooks.''} 23. Rxc7 {[%emt 0:01:04]} Re2 $1 {[%emt 0:00:29] Now Rdd2 can't be stopped and Black fully equalises. Fernandez,Daniel Howard: 'Mikhalevski,Victor: 'Now Rdd2 can't be stopped and Black fully equalises.'' Fernandez,Daniel Howard: 'The sacrificed pawns will return home.'} 24. Rxa7 {[%emt 0:01:04]} Rdd2 {[%emt 0:00:08]} 25. Rf1 {[%emt 0:00:16]} Rxb2 {[%emt 0:00:06]} 26. g4 {[%emt 0:08:58]} (26. a4 e4 27. a5 e3 28. Ra8+ Kh7 29. g4 exf2+ 30. Kg2 Re3 31. Rxf2 Rbb3 $11 {and the activity of the black rooks yields Black enough counterplay.}) 26... Rxa2 {[%emt 0:00:58]} 27. Rxa2 {[%emt 0:00:05]} Rxa2 {[%emt 0:00:03]} 28. Re1 {[%emt 0:00:06] and in this completely equal position a draw was agreed. A short but well-played game, which proves that White doesn't have many winning chances in the line with 7.Na4. Fernandez,Daniel Howard: 'Mikhalevski,Victor: 'and in this completely equal position a draw was agreed. A short but well-played game, which proves that White doesn't have many winning chances in the line with 7.Na4.'' Fernandez,Daniel Howard: 'The draw was agreed here, none too soon.'} 1/2-1/2


