1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c4 c6 4. Nc3 a6 5. c5 Bf5 {A popular idea here.} 6. Qb3 Ra7 7. Nh4 Bg6 (7... Be6 $5 8. Bf4 Nh5 9. Bd2 g6 10. Nf3 Bg7 11. Qc2 f5 12. O-O-O $5 O-O {Unusual, but this is a very interesting position for both sides.} 13. Ne5 Nd7 14. f4 Nhf6 15. e3 Nxe5 16. fxe5 Ne4 17. Re1 Bh6 18. g3 b6 19. cxb6 Qxb6 20. Na4 Qc7 21. Bg2 a5 22. Bxe4 fxe4 23. Rhf1 Raa8 24. Nc5 Bh3 {With unclear play, Tan Zhongyi (2517)-Stefanova,A (2500) Huai'an CHN 2017 0-1 (66)}) 8. Bg5 {Developing a bishop is not the only choice here:} (8. Nxg6 hxg6 9. e3 Nbd7 10. Bd2 e6 11. Be2 Be7 12. O-O-O b6 13. cxb6 Qxb6 14. Qxb6 Nxb6 15. Kb1 Kd7 16. Rc1 Rb8 17. Rc2 {White has typical symbolic pressure here, which may become bigger if Black misplays it. Edouard,R (2621)-Malakhov,V (2691) Brest FRA 2018 1/2-1/2 (26)}) 8... Nbd7 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. e4 $1 dxe4 11. g3 e6 12. Bg2 Be7 13. O-O O-O ({Alternatively:} 13... Nd5 14. Bxe7 Nxe7 15. Nxe4 O-O 16. Rac1 Nf5 17. Rfd1 Nf6 18. Ng5 Qe7 19. Nf3 Rd8 20. Rd3 Raa8 21. Rcd1 {White has the slightly better chances, his main idea is to put pressure on the h1-a8 diagonal by pushing the a and b pawns, Grischuk,A (2785)-Malakhov,V (2691) Antalya TUR 2017 1/2-1/2 (100)}) 14. h4 {White has more space and Black's pieces are restricted.} b6 15. cxb6 Nxb6 16. Nxe4 Nxe4 17. Bxe7 Rxe7 18. Bxe4 Qxd4 19. Bxc6 {This particular bishop versus knight position slightly favors White.} Rc7 (19... Rb8 20. Rad1 Qe5 21. Qa3 Rc7 22. Bg2 a5 23. b3 {With some small advantage for White.}) 20. Rac1 Rb8 21. Rfd1 Qe5 22. Rc3 Nd7 $1 23. Qa3 (23. Qc2 Nf6 24. a3 a5 {Also gives Black enough play.}) 23... Nf6 {After this good manoeuvre Black equalizes.} 24. b4 Nd5 25. Rc5 Qe2 26. Rdc1 Rxb4 27. R5c2 Qe5 28. Qxa6 Rb2 29. Rxb2 $6 (29. Qa5 $1 Rxc2 30. Rxc2 Qa1+ 31. Kg2 Qd4 {With equal play.}) 29... Qxb2 30. Rf1 Nb4 31. Qa8+ Kh7 32. Be4 f5 ({An alternative could have created a problem for White...} 32... Qxa2 $1 33. Qxa2 Nxa2 34. h5 Kh6 35. hxg6 f5 {A pawn up and this is no easy task for White to defend this position.}) 33. Qb8 Rc1 34. Bg2 $1 {Now its equal again.} Ra1 35. Qb6 Rxa2 36. Qxe6 Ra1 37. Qc4 Nc2 38. Rxa1 Qxa1+ 39. Kh2 Nd4 40. Bd5 Qd1 41. Qc8 Nf3+ 42. Bxf3 Qxf3 43. Qc5 f4 44. Qd4 1/2-1/2


