1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 d5 4. d4 Bb4 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bxf6 Qxf6 {The popular Ragozin.} 7. e3 O-O 8. Rc1 dxc4 9. Bxc4 c5 10. O-O cxd4 11. Ne4 Qe7 12. a3 Ba5 13. Qxd4 Rd8 14. Qc5 $5 {This is a less played alternative.} (14. Qe5 {which is more complicated, was also seen recently:} Nc6 ({An interesting idea is} 14... Bc7 $5 15. Qh5 b6 16. Nd4 (16. Nfg5 $5 Nd7 17. Bxe6 Bxh2+ 18. Kxh2 fxe6 19. Nf3 (19. Rc7 $5 hxg5 20. Rd1 Qf7 21. Qxg5 Rf8 22. g4 $5 {Preventing the ... Qf5 idea.} Qf3 23. Rdxd7 Bxd7 24. Rxd7 Rf7 25. Rxf7 Kxf7 26. Qh5+ Kg8 {Black is OK.}) 19... Bb7 20. Qg4 Rac8 {Doesn't look bad for Black.}) 16... Bb7 17. Bd3 Rd5 18. Qe2 Be5 19. Nb5 a6 20. Nbc3 Rd8 21. Rfd1 Nd7 {Black is fine. Miknevicius,L (2150)-Capone,N (2392) Prague 2016 1/2-1/2 (50)}) 15. Qh5 Bd7 16. g4 f6 17. Rfd1 Bb6 18. Nd6 Na5 $5 {A new idea, but probably not that good.} 19. Ba2 $1 (19. Nf5 Qf7 20. Ba2 $5 (20. Qxf7+ Kxf7 21. Ba2 Kf8 {Black is OK here. Guo Qi (2359)- Nie,X (2233) Hangzhou CHN 2018 0-1 (67)}) 20... Qxh5 21. gxh5 Kh7 22. Ne7 Be8 23. Bxe6 Bxh5 24. Kg2 Rxd1 25. Rxd1 Rd8 26. Rxd8 Bxd8 27. Nc8 Nc6 28. Bd5 Bg4 29. Nd6 Bc7 30. Be4+ g6 31. Nxb7 Bxf3+ 32. Bxf3 Na5 {Leads to a draw.}) 19... Ba4 20. Nf5 Rxd1+ 21. Rxd1 Qe8 22. Bxe6+ $1 {This is easily missed.} Kf8 (22... Qxe6 23. Qg6 {White wins.}) 23. Rd6 Qxh5 24. gxh5 Be8 25. N3h4 Rd8 26. Ng6+ Bxg6 27. Rxd8+ Bxd8 28. hxg6 {White is better.}) 14... Qxc5 15. Nxc5 Nd7 16. Nb3 Bb6 17. a4 Nf6 $1 {A good move, Black doesn't weaken his structure.} 18. Be2 Ne8 $1 19. a5 Bc7 20. Rc2 Kf8 21. Rfc1 Bd6 22. Nc5 b6 23. axb6 axb6 24. Ne4 Bb7 {Black has easily reached equality.} 25. Nxd6 Nxd6 26. Nd2 Rac8 27. f3 Ke7 28. Kf2 e5 29. e4 Rxc2 30. Rxc2 Rc8 31. Rxc8 Bxc8 1/2-1/2


