1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 d6 4. f4 Nf6 5. Nf3 c5 6. Bb5+ Nc6 $5 {A really surprising move especially for someone whom only knows of the main line. At first it looks to simply be a blunder and White has multiple paths to an advantage however if he isn't careful Black can get alot of counterplay. He should play accurately to get an advantage here.} (6... Bd7 {Is of course the main line with thousands of games played and a large body of theory. There are many games in the archives already in this line.}) 7. e5 {Quite a natural response but here I'm not sure if it is correct since the White centre will soon break apart.} (7. dxc5 {GM Nigel Davies considered this to be the critical continuation being the only game analysed in the archives.} Qa5 8. Bd2 (8. O-O O-O 9. cxd6 exd6 10. Qe2 (10. Qe1 Nxe4 $5 11. Qxe4 Bxc3 12. Bxc6 Bg7 13. Bxb7 Qb6+ 14. Be3 Bxb7 $132) 10... Re8 11. Bd3 (11. Bd2 Qd8 {With some chances for Black to complicate matters.}) 11... Bf5 $13) 8... O-O 9. Qe2 (9. cxd6 exd6 10. Qe2 Re8 11. O-O-O Be6 12. Bc4 Rac8 13. Bxe6 Rxe6 14. Kb1 {When Black could have played} Nxe4 $1 15. Nxe4 Nb4 $1 16. a3 Rxc2 $40 {and get a big attack in Alsina Leal,D (2537)-Movsziszian,K (2484) Barcelona 2015}) 9... Bg4 10. Nd5 (10. cxd6 exd6 11. Bd3 Qh5 12. O-O $14) 10... Qd8 11. Nxf6+ Bxf6 12. c3 dxc5 13. O-O e5 $1 {Gave Black enough counterplay in the game: Alsina Leal,D (2535)-Peralta,F (2591) Catalunya 2012}) (7. d5 a6 8. Ba4 $1 {I believe this to be the most accurate way to an advantage.} (8. Be2 Na7 9. O-O O-O 10. a4 Rb8 11. f5 b5 {Gave Black sufficient counterplay in Cabrera Trujillo,J  (2357)-Del Rio de Angelis,S (2533) Las Palmas 2012}) 8... b5 9. dxc6 Qc7 10. e5 $1 {I like this variation for White since it is very concrete and almost by forces Black into the resulting position.} (10. Bb3 c4 11. a4 b4 12. Bxc4 bxc3 13. e5 dxe5 14. Nxe5 O-O $13) (10. O-O bxa4 11. e5 dxe5 12. fxe5 Ng4 13. h3 (13. Bf4 Qxc6 $11) (13. Qd5 Be6 14. Qxc5 Nxe5 15. Nd4 Rd8 $13) 13... Nxe5 14. Nd5 Qxc6 15. Bh6 $1 Nxf3+ 16. Qxf3 Bd4+ 17. Kh1 f5 {It looks as though White should simply be much better but it's not at all easy to prove.} 18. Nf6+ Qxf6 19. Qxa8 Kf7 $13) 10... dxe5 11. fxe5 Ng4 12. Bf4 bxa4 13. Qd5 a3 $5 14. Qxc5 axb2 15. Rb1 Qa7 16. Qxa7 Rxa7 17. Rxb2 $16 {Gave White a much better endgame in Vocaturo,D (2574)-Movsziszian,K (2458) Barcelona ESP 2016}) 7... Nd7 {Of the very few games I've found in this position, Black has gone on to win all of them. Clearly indicating that once the situation in the centre is resolved he usually stands to have the favourable outcome.} 8. d5 {This was also the move played previously, other moves do not help White's position.} (8. exd6 O-O $5 9. Be3 exd6 $11) (8. Be3 cxd4 9. Nxd4 Nxd4 10. Qxd4 (10. Bxd4 dxe5 11. Bxe5 O-O $11) 10... a6 {is the simplest way to equalise.} 11. Bxd7+ Bxd7) 8... Nd4 9. Nxd4 cxd4 10. Qxd4 O-O 11. Bxd7 Qxd7 $44 {After a series of semi-forced moves we reach this position whereby Black has nothing to worry about. He has enough compensation for the pawn and some decent chances with the bishop pair as the game goes on.} (11... Bxd7 12. O-O b5 $5 {is also fine for Black.}) 12. O-O Qf5 13. Qd1 {This retreat makes Black's life easier since it now takes longer to bring both rooks into the game.} (13. Be3 Qxc2 (13... dxe5 14. Qd2 (14. fxe5 Qxe5 15. Qd2 (15. Qxe5 Bxe5 $11) 15... Bf5 16. Rae1 Rfc8 $11) 14... exf4 15. Rxf4 Qd7 16. Re1 b6 17. Rf3 (17. Rf2 Bb7 18. Bh6 Bxh6 19. Qxh6 f6 20. Rd2 Rac8 21. Re4 {White has a very active position but Black is still very solid.}) 17... Re8 18. Bh6 Bh8 $13) 14. Rf2 Qf5 15. Qd2 b6 16. Bd4 Ba6 17. exd6 exd6 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. Qd4+ Qf6 20. Qb4 $14) 13... dxe5 14. fxe5 Qxe5 15. Kh1 {Sensible move to side step the queen trades.} (15. Bf4 Qd4+ 16. Qxd4 Bxd4+ 17. Kh1 Bf5 $15) 15... Qd6 {Other options such as ...Bf5 or ...Qc7 were also possible.} 16. Bf4 Qb6 (16... Qb4 17. Rb1 Bf5 18. d6 $5 e6 $13 {White will have trouble holding the d6-pawn forever and in the meantime the bishops remain a real force.}) 17. Rb1 Bf5 18. Qe2 (18. g4 $6 {is too weakening.} Bd7 $15) (18. Re1 Rfe8 19. Qd2 e6 $132) 18... Rfe8 19. Be3 Qa6 $1 20. Qd2 (20. Qxa6 bxa6 21. Rf2 Red8 $17) 20... Rad8 $17 {Now Black starts to get a serious advantage.} 21. Qf2 (21. Bh6 Be5 22. Rbe1 f6 $15) 21... e6 22. Bxa7 exd5 23. Bd4 Bxd4 24. Qxd4 Qc4 (24... Bxc2 25. Rbc1 Be4 $17) 25. Rbd1 Bxc2 26. Nxd5 $2 {The simplification will make it easier for Black to convert.} (26. Qf2 {Is the only move to stay in the game. Still a pawn down but White can hope to create a blockage on d4.} Bf5 27. Rd4 Qc6 28. Qd2) 26... Qxd4 27. Rxd4 Kg7 (27... Kf8 $1 $17 {is even stronger avoiding ideas auch as ...Nf6 later.}) 28. Nc7 Rxd4 29. Nxe8+ Kf8 30. Nc7 Rd2 $17 {White will soon lose material and with the active Black pieces there is little hope to comeback. We see the rest of the game is a matter of converting which Rapport does comfortably.} 31. Ne6+ Kg8 32. Ng5 Bd3 33. Re1 h6 34. Nf3 Rxb2 35. h3 Rxa2 36. Re8+ Kg7 37. Re7 Bf1 38. Nh4 g5 39. Kg1 Ra1 40. Nf3 Be2+ 41. Kf2 Bxf3 42. Kxf3 Rb1 43. Re8 b5 44. Rb8 Rb3+ 45. Kg4 Rb4+ 46. Kf3 Rf4+ 47. Ke3 b4 48. Rb6 h5 49. Kd3 Rf2 50. g4 Rf3+ 51. Ke4 hxg4 52. hxg4 Rf4+ 53. Ke5 f6+ 54. Ke6 Re4+ {The king is cut off from the pawn and that will end the game. All in all, 6...Nc6 I don't believe to be completely sound yet proves to again be an excellent surprise weapon. Since to gain a safe edge, White needs to know some concrete lines. Otherwise he may find Black's counterplay to be rather uncomfortable to deal with.} 0-1


[Event "Wei Yi - Rapport Match TB"]
[Site "Yancheng CHN"]
[Date "2016.12.23"]
