[EventRounds "2"]

1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 a6 $5 {I really like this move since Black does not commit to anything yet but as we have seen before ...a6 will always fit into our setup. Here we hold off on playing ...d6 to try and get ...d5 in with one move instead if available.} 4. f4 (4. Be3 {has been examined already by Gawain Jones and Neil McDonald in the archives.}) (4. h4 d5 $5 {Hitting right away at the centre seems the logical response if it works.} (4... h6 {was played a number of times also but I prefer the text move.}) 5. Nxd5 (5. e5 c5 $1 6. dxc5 d4 7. Ne4 (7. Na4 Qa5+ 8. c3 Bd7 9. Nb6 dxc3 $15) 7... Qd5 8. Bd3 Nd7 $13) (5. exd5 Nf6 6. Bc4 O-O $13) 5... c6 6. Ne3 (6. Nc3 Qxd4 7. Qxd4 Bxd4 8. Nf3 Ba7 9. h5 (9. Bf4 Nf6 10. Be2 Bg4 $11) (9. Bc4 Nf6 10. Ne5 Be6 $5 11. Bxe6 fxe6 12. f3 Nbd7 $11 {Soon the pawn will go to ...e5 and despite the doubled pawns Black should be okay. Holding all the key central square for now.}) 9... gxh5 10. Rxh5 Nf6 11. Rh4 Ng4 12. Nd1 h5 $13) 6... Qxd4 7. Bd3 (7. Qxd4 Bxd4 8. h5 (8. Nf3 Bg7 9. h5 Nd7 10. Nc4 gxh5 11. Rxh5 Ngf6 12. Rh4 h5 13. a4 (13. e5 $5 Nd5 14. e6 $5 fxe6 15. Be2 e5 $13) 13... Ng4 $13) 8... Nd7 9. Nf3 Bg7 10. a4 Ne5 (10... Nc5 11. e5 Be6 $5 12. b4 Nd7 13. Bb2 Nh6 14. Be2 $14) 11. Nxe5 Bxe5 12. Nc4 Bc7 13. Be3 Be6 14. hxg6 fxg6 15. O-O-O Nf6 16. Nb6 Rd8 $11) 7... Nd7 8. Nf3 Qd6 $13) (4. Bc4 b5 5. Bd5 c6 (5... Ra7 $6 {it's a big problem if the rook doesn't manage to find its way into the game later.}) 6. Bb3 d6 (6... d5 $5 7. exd5 (7. Nf3 Nf6 8. e5 Nfd7 9. h4 $5 $13) (7. Qf3 e6 8. Nge2 Bb7 {Followed by . ..Nd7 and ...Ne7 should help Black consolidate since the White bishop will be locked out for a long while yet.}) 7... Nf6 $1 8. dxc6 Nxc6 9. Nge2 O-O $11) 7. Bg5 Nf6 {Would have been fine for Black in the game: Royset,P (2234)-Tiller,B  (2374) Tromsoe 2008}) 4... d5 $5 {The key idea.} 5. Nxd5 (5. exd5 Nf6 $11) (5. e5 {This particular closed structure is fine for Black and he can continue in typical fashion} h5 {or} (5... Nh6 {would be normal ways to continue.})) 5... e6 6. Nc3 (6. Ne3 Qxd4 7. Qxd4 Bxd4 8. Nf3 Ba7 {I don't see any advantage to having the knight on e3 instead of c3.}) 6... Qxd4 7. Qxd4 (7. Qf3 $5 Nc6 8. Nge2 (8. Be3 Qb4 $15) (8. Bd2 $1 {is best aiming to castle long.} Qb6 (8... Bd7 9. O-O-O O-O-O 10. Kb1 Qb4 11. a3 Qf8 $14) (8... Qb4 9. O-O-O Bd7 10. e5 O-O-O 11. Ne4 $14 {White is preferred since the Black queen is somewhat misplaced.}) 9. O-O-O Nge7 (9... Nd4 10. Qd3 Nh6 11. h3 Bd7 12. Be3 $16) 10. Kb1 O-O $13) 8... Qb6 9. Bd2 Qxb2 $17 {Was a free pawn in the game Sveshnikov,V (2407) -Fedorchuk,S (2618) Presolana 2011}) 7... Bxd4 8. Nf3 (8. Bd2 {is another option.} Ne7 9. Nf3 Bg7 (9... Ba7 10. O-O-O Nd7 {Black is a little cramped but has no obvious weaknesses.}) 10. O-O-O b6 11. Bd3 Bb7 12. f5 $40 {Gave White some initiative in Powierski,E (2317)-Gharamian,T (2621) London ENG 2016}) 8... Ba7 9. Bd2 Nc6 10. h4 $6 {h5 is not a real threat since Black can easily cover it. The extra weaknesses on the kingside ensure Black is already fine here.} (10. Bd3 Nf6 11. h3 O-O 12. O-O-O Nd7 {Should be okay for Black whom will fight back for space.}) 10... Nf6 11. e5 Ng4 12. Ne4 h5 {Covering all the important light squares.} (12... Bd7 13. O-O-O O-O-O 14. h5 Ne7 $11) 13. c3 {Trying to stop ...Nd4 options.} (13. Nfg5 Kf8 14. O-O-O Kg7 $13) 13... Ne3 {Going for the bishop pair but this is perhaps not best in this situation.} (13... Ne7 14. Nh2 Nf5 $11) 14. Bxe3 Bxe3 15. g3 Bd7 16. Nf6+ Ke7 17. Ng5 $14 {In this position we can see the dark-squared bishop is not very effective and unable to stop the White knights from dominating key squares on the kingside.} Rhd8 18. Ke2 (18. Rd1 Be8 19. Bd3 {It is better to have the bishop positioned here as we shall see in the game.} Bb6 20. Ke2 $14 {When Black finds it difficult to come up with a useful plan.}) 18... Ba7 19. Bg2 Na5 20. b3 $6 (20. Nxd7 Rxd7 21. b3 $14 {With the Black knight stuck out of the game.}) 20... Bb5+ 21. c4 Nxc4 $1 {Forced therefore good. Anything else renders the pass few moves pointless.} 22. bxc4 Bxc4+ 23. Ke1 (23. Kf3 $4 {Walks into a mating net.} Rd3+ 24. Ke2 Rad8 $3 {The quiet but deadly method works well here, with imminent mate to follow soon.}) 23... Bb6 (23... Rd3 $1 24. Rd1 Re3+ 25. Kd2 Rd8+ 26. Kc1 Bd4 27. Nf3 Rc3+ 28. Kb2 Rb3+ 29. Kc1 Rc3+ $11 {Ending in a perpetual but Richard is perhaps looking to get more from the position.}) 24. Rd1 (24. Bf1 $1 Ba5+ 25. Kf2 Rd2+ 26. Kf3 Bxa2 27. Be2 $16 {The attack stops and White should be good to consolidate.}) 24... Ba5+ 25. Kf2 Bb6+ 26. Ke1 Ba5+ 27. Kf2 Bb6+ 28. Kf3 $5 {Avoiding the draw and trying to play for more.} Bxa2 {An interesting endgame arises with chances for both sides.} 29. g4 $1 hxg4+ (29... Bb3 $1 30. Rxd8 Rxd8 $13) 30. Kxg4 a5 31. Bxb7 Rab8 32. Bc6 {Now White is once again on top but doesn't manage to convert his advantage.} Bb3 33. Rb1 a4 34. h5 (34. Be4 {Stops the ...Bc2 as in the game proved a valuable defensive resource.} Bd4 35. Rbc1 c5 36. h5 gxh5+ 37. Rxh5 $14) 34... gxh5+ 35. Nxh5 Bc2 $1 $11 36. Ra1 (36. Rbc1 Bf5+ 37. Kg3 Rd3+ 38. Bf3 $13 {is still fine for both sides.}) 36... Bf5+ 37. Kg3 Rd3+ 38. Bf3 a3 39. Nf6 Bd4 $1 40. Rac1 {The key mistake after which Black gains the advantage for the first and last time in the game.} (40. Ra2 {was needed.}) 40... c5 $17 41. Rc4 Ra8 42. Ra4 $2 Rxa4 43. Rh8 Bxe5 $1 44. fxe5 Rd8 45. Ng8+ Kd7 46. Nxf7 Rxg8+ 47. Rxg8 a2 {In general 3...a6 is a good move order for Black players to have if they play the Modern Tiger systems regardless. It can also prove effective as a surprise weapon against players who employ the Austrian Attack. In terms of its soundness, if White chooses to keep queens on it will lead to some very unbalanced and unclear positions which I suppose is what players of the Black side who looking for. As the game showed, even when one side has an advantage, he can easily lose it again if he does not play accurately.} 0-1


