1. d4 {ChessBase: 'Kapnisis,Spyridon'} g6 {ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: 'When a world champion takes up the mantle of our opening, we take it as an article of faith in its inherent soundness. ''} 2. e4 Bg7 3. Nc3 d6 4. Be3 a6 {ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: 'So far we are transported back to Chapter One of the book, but this alters with White's next move, which transposes to the realm of the Austrian Attack. '' ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: 'So far we are transported back to Chapter One of the book, but this alters with White's next move, which transposes to the realm of the Austrian Attack. '' ChessBase: 'The Swedish GM Tiger Hillarp-Persson wrote a voluminous book on this opening which recently appeared in a new, revised edition.' ChessBase: 'The Swedish GM Tiger Hillarp-Persson wrote a voluminous book on this opening which recently appeared in a new, revised edition.'} 5. f4 b5 {is the most accurate move order. Magnus goes for a system popularised by GM Tiger Hillarp Persson in his book, "The Modern Tiger" to stir up some complications.} (5... Nd7 {allows the move} 6. a4 $1 b6 7. Nf3 Bb7 8. Bd3 {when White enjoys more space and a comfortable game.}) 6. Nf3 Nd7 (6... b4 {is another option that was examined in 1-0 Slobodjan, R - Azmaiparashvili, Z}) (6... Bb7 7. Bd3 Nf6 8. e5 Ng4 9. Bd2 c5 10. dxc5 dxe5 11. h3 Nf6 12. fxe5 Nfd7 13. e6 fxe6 14. Ng5 Nxc5 15. Qe2 Nc6 16. Nxe6 Nxe6 17. Qxe6 Ne5 18. O-O Qd7 $11 {ChessBase: '0-1 (50) Zelbel,P (2450)-Hillarp Persson,T (2541) Gothenburg 2015' 0-1 (50) Zelbel,P (2450)-Hillarp Persson,T (2541) Gothenburg 2015}) 7. e5 (7. Qe2 Bb7 8. a3 {is fine for Black.}) 7... Bb7 8. Bd3 c5 {ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: 'The dismantling of White's centre is top priority. We reach a crucial tabiya position of the Austrian Attack. ''} ({Cyrus Lakdawala: 'In 'The Modern Defence: Move by Move', I focused on'} 8... Nh6 {Cyrus Lakdawala: 'where Black played for a light-square strategy without opening the centre early.'} 9. Qe2 Nb6 10. O-O-O Qd7 11. h3 Nf5 12. Bf2 e6 13. Kb1 Ne7 14. Be3 Ned5 15. Nxd5 Bxd5 16. Rhf1 b4 17. g4 O-O 18. f5 Na4 {ChessBase: '0-1 (36) Byklum, B (2275)-Hillarp Persson,T (2557) Stockholm 2006' 0-1 (36) Byklum, B (2275)-Hillarp Persson,T (2557) Stockholm 2006} 19. f6 $5 $16) 9. Be4 {ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: 'White plays the familiar manoeuvre, depriving us of our best piece.''} (9. O-O {ChessBase: 'is known to give Black no trouble at all after '} cxd4 10. Bxd4 dxe5 (10... Nh6 {ChessBase: ', reaching dynamic equality. Don't fear '} 11. Be4 (11. Qe2 O-O 12. Rad1 Qc7) (11. e6 {which can be met with} Bxf3 $1 12. exd7+ Qxd7 13. Bxb5 axb5 14. Rxf3 O-O {and Black's extra central pawns should give him at least equality, if not a shade more.}) 11... Bxe4 12. Nxe4 dxe5 13. fxe5 Nf5 14. c3 O-O $11) 11. fxe5 Nxe5 12. Bxe5 Bxe5 13. Bxb5+ axb5 14. Nxe5 $14) 9... Bxe4 (9... Qc8 10. Bxb7 Qxb7 11. dxc5 dxe5 12. Qd5 Qxd5 13. Nxd5 Rc8 14. Nb6 Nxb6 15. cxb6 Nf6 16. O-O-O Ng4 {ChessBase: 'Kapnisis,Spyridon: '''} 17. Rhe1 Nxe3 18. Rxe3 Bh6 $11 {0-1 (53) Mortensen,E (2450)-Hillarp Persson,T (2461) Denmark 2003}) 10. Nxe4 Nh6 ({TIP: When defending the black side of Austrian Attack, it's crucial to avoid falling too far behind in development. Avoid non-developing/game opening moves like} 10... cxd4 $6 11. Bxd4 dxe5 12. fxe5 Nh6 13. e6 $1 Nf6 14. Neg5 {with a big advantage for White.}) 11. dxc5 {We are still following recommendation by Tiger.} ({ChessBase: 'After '} 11. Qe2 cxd4 12. Bxd4 Nf5 (12... dxe5 13. fxe5 Nf5 14. e6 Nxd4 15. Nxd4 Bxd4 16. O-O-O $1 Ne5 $1 17. exf7+ Nxf7 18. c3 O-O 19. Rxd4 Qb6 {Black's activity makes up for the slight weakness of his e-pawn isolani.}) 13. O-O-O Nxd4 14. Rxd4 O-O 15. Rhd1 Qa5 16. Kb1 Nb6 17. exd6 exd6) 11... dxe5 {is a new move for this site.} (11... Ng4 {is what was played in the Smeets,J - Siebrecht,S game and well looked at by Gawain Jones. ChessBase: 'Kapnisis,Spyridon: '!?' Kapnisis,Spyridon: '- 104/174''}) 12. c6 {is the most commonly played move and there follows a relatively forced sequence of moves. ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: 'White chases away a defender of e5.''} (12. Qe2 {seems like a plausible alternative.} Qc7 (12... Nf5 13. O-O-O Qc7 14. fxe5 $14) (12... Qa5+ 13. c3 Nf5 14. c6 Nf6 15. Nxf6+ exf6 16. Bc5 O-O-O (16... Qc7 17. O-O-O Qxc6 18. b4 $5 {Simply trying to anchor the bishop whilst preventing Black from castling. It is difficult for Black to find an adequate reply. For example:} Bh6 19. Kb1 Bxf4 20. Rhe1 $36 {followed by g3 and Nxe5 is strong.}) 17. b4 $36) 13. fxe5 Nxe5 14. O-O-O Nf5 (14... O-O 15. Bf4 Nd3+ 16. Qxd3 Qxf4+ 17. Kb1 Nf5 $11) 15. Bf2 (15. Bf4 Nd3+ 16. Rxd3 Qxf4+ 17. Kb1 O-O 18. Rhd1 $14 {was stronger.}) 15... O-O {Erdogdu,M (2419)-Yilmazyerli,M (2450) Kocaeli 2015 (1/2-1/2 in 24)}) 12... Nf6 ({Nobody has ever tried the contortionist theoretical novelty} 12... Nf8 $5 13. Qxd8+ Rxd8 14. fxe5 Rc8 {. Black's game looks just fine to me.}) 13. Qxd8+ Rxd8 14. Nxf6+ exf6 15. c7 (15. fxe5 fxe5 16. Bxh6 Bxh6 17. Nxe5 O-O 18. O-O Rd2) 15... Rc8 16. Bb6 {ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: 'This is scary stuff, since now White plans to transfer a rook to d8. ''} Kd7 {ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: '!' Cyrus Lakdawala: 'When we face an obstacle we have two choices: a) Issue a direct challenge and attempt to go through it. b) Save energy and go around it.  Carlsen's last move is an example of number two on the list. He utilizes the endgame principle which guides us to move our king out of the safety zone and put it to work in an ending. In fact in this game Carlsen's hardworking king moved a whopping total of 11 times, like a temporary labourer who is hired when demand for goods is high, and then laid off and discarded in the off season. '' ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: '!' '!' Cyrus Lakdawala: 'When we face an obstacle we have two choices: a) Issue a direct challenge and attempt to go through it. b) Save energy and go around it.  Carlsen's last move is an example of number two on the list. He utilizes the endgame principle which guides us to move our king out of the safety zone and put it to work in an ending. In fact in this game Carlsen's hardworking king moved a whopping total of 11 times, like a temporary labourer who is hired when demand for goods is high, and then laid off and discarded in the off season. '' ChessBase: 'This kind of position should suit Carlsen. After an early exchange of queens White's far advanced pawn on c7 is vulnerable.' Cyrus Lakdawala: 'When we face an obstacle we have two choices: a) Issue a direct challenge and attempt to go through it. --- b) Save energy and go around it. --- Carlsen's last move is an example of number two on the list. He utilizes the endgame principle which guides us to move our king out of the safety zone and put it to work in an ending. In fact in this game Carlsen's hardworking king moved a whopping total of 11 times, like a temporary labourer who is hired when demand for goods is high, and then laid off and discarded in the off season.' ChessBase: 'This kind of position should suit Carlsen. After an early exchange of queens White's far advanced pawn on c7 is vulnerable.'} 17. Ba5 (17. O-O-O+ Kc6 18. Ba5) 17... Nf5 ({This isn't the time to get greedy with} 17... exf4 $6 18. O-O-O+ Kc6 19. Rd8 {. Black must hand over the exchange. If he doesn't with} Nf5 $2 {then follows} 20. Rhd1 Kb7 21. R1d7 {with a winning bind for White.}) 18. O-O-O+ Kc6 {ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: 'transposes to the game.'' ChessBase: 'Kapnisis,Spyridon: 'Diagram '' ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: 'transposes to the game.'' ChessBase: 'Kapnisis,Spyridon: 'Diagram '' ChessBase: 'Kapnisis,Spyridon: 'Diagram [#]' All this has been played before.' ChessBase: 'All this has been played before.'} 19. Rd8 {At first it looks like the only move to maintain pressure. However, it turns out to be inaccurate and it seems Black is already doing more than fine. ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: 'EXERCISE (planning): White threatens to increase his choke hold with Rhd1. Carlsen found an efficient way to dismantle White's bind. What would you play here? ANSWER: Transfer the knight to either c4 or b7, which dislodges White's bishop, and therefore White's bind. '' ChessBase: 'Kapnisis,Spyridon: 'N'' At first it looks like the only move to maintain pressure. However, it turns out to be inaccurate and it seems Black is already doing more than fine. ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: 'EXERCISE (planning): White threatens to increase his choke hold with Rhd1. Carlsen found an efficient way to dismantle White's bind. What would you play here? ANSWER: Transfer the knight to either c4 or b7, which dislodges White's bishop, and therefore White's bind. '' ChessBase: 'Kapnisis,Spyridon: 'N'' Cyrus Lakdawala: 'EXERCISE (planning): White threatens to increase his choke hold with Rhd1. Carlsen found an efficient way to dismantle White's bind. What would you play here? --- ANSWER: Transfer the knight to either c4 or b7, which dislodges White's bishop, and therefore White's bind.'} (19. fxe5 {was from a game played between two young Australians when it shows that White's passed c-pawn is going nowhere. Whilst the black centre majority is a real threat. ChessBase: 'Kapnisis,Spyridon'} fxe5 20. Rhe1 f6 {ChessBase: '' ChessBase: '' ''} 21. g4 Nd6 22. g5 Rhe8 23. gxf6 Bxf6 24. b3 e4 {when Black had a already winning advantage in Li,Z (2349)-Cheng,B (2440) Melbourne 2013 (0-1 in 41)}) (19. Rd3 Nd6 {ChessBase: 'Kapnisis,Spyridon: '='' ChessBase: 'Kapnisis,Spyridon: '='' ChessBase: 'Kapnisis,Spyridon: '=' and now 1/2-1/2 (19) in Tan,J (2322)-Buchal,S (2296) Haarlem 2013 - a bit premature.' and now 1/2-1/2 (19) in Tan,J (2322)-Buchal,S (2296) Haarlem 2013 - a bit premature.}) 19... Nd6 $1 {Stopping White's attack and threatening Nc4 or Nb7 ideas. ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: '!''} 20. fxe5 fxe5 21. Rd1 (21. b3 $2 {keeps the knight out of c4, but not b7:} Nb7 22. Rxh8 Bxh8 23. Bc3 f6 {and the c7-pawn falls.}) 21... Nc4 {Now Black is in full control, The pawn on c7 can no longer be protected so White tries to win the e5 pawn instead.} 22. Bc3 Rxc7 {ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: 'With this move Black completely equalizes.''} ({Cyrus Lakdawala: 'Even stronger was '} 22... b4 {Cyrus Lakdawala: '!' Cyrus Lakdawala: '!' '!'} 23. Bxb4 (23. Rxh8 Bxh8 24. Bxb4 e4 {(simultaneously attacking f3 and b2)} 25. Nd4+ Kb7 26. Bc3 Rxc7 {when Black's majority and piece activity are more potent than their white counterparts.}) 23... e4 24. Nd4+ Kxc7 25. Rxh8 Bxh8 26. Bc3 Be5 $11) 23. b3 Ne3 (23... Rxd8 24. Rxd8 Ne3 25. Bxe5 Bxe5 26. Nxe5+ Kb7 27. Rd2 {was another possibility.} f5 {led to even chances in the ending, S.Vokhidov-A.Bodnaruk, Baku 2016.}) 24. Bxe5 (24. R1d6+ Kb7 25. R8d7 Kc8 26. Rxc7+ Kxc7 27. Rxa6 (27. Rd3 Ng4 {holds everything together, since} 28. h3 $6 {is met with} Nf2 29. Ba5+ Kc6 30. Rc3+ Kd6 {when it is Black who stands better due to his functional kingside pawn majority.}) 27... Rc8 28. Ba5+ Kb7 29. Rb6+ Ka7 30. Rd6 Nxc2 $15) 24... Nxd1 {ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: '!?' Cyrus Lakdawala: 'Any world champion's great weakness is that they know nothing but victory and success, the logical extension of which is that there is no place to go but down if they continue to play. When great players plunge into unfathomable complications, it falsely presupposes that they have a duty to entertain us with dazzling and risky ideas. The truth is their main objective is simply to win.'' ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: '!?' '!?' Cyrus Lakdawala: 'Any world champion's great weakness is that they know nothing but victory and success, the logical extension of which is that there is no place to go but down if they continue to play. When great players plunge into unfathomable complications, it falsely presupposes that they have a duty to entertain us with dazzling and risky ideas. The truth is their main objective is simply to win.''} ({In our electronic and wireless chess world, news of a new idea travels fast. A couple of months later} 24... Rxd8) 25