n one move, rather than two. '' ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: '?!' '?!' Cyrus Lakdawala: 'This represents the loss of a tempo, since he could have played to b2 in one move, rather than two. ''} 48. Kc7 {ChessBase: '!?' '!?' '!?' '!?' ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: '?!'' ChessBase: '!?' '!?' '!?' '!?' ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: '?!' '?!'' ChessBase: '!?' '!?' '!?' ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: '?!''} (48. a6 c2 49. Rc4 Rxb3+ 50. Ka7 Nc3 $19) (48. b4 Nd6 $17 (48... c2 $2 49. Rc4 Kd5 {Kapnisis,Spyridon} 50. Rd4+ $11) (48... Rd2 $1 {Kapnisis,Spyridon} 49. a6 Nd6 50. a7 Nc8+ 51. Kb7 Nxa7 52. Kxa7 Rxd4 53. Nxd4+ Kd5 54. Ne2 Kc4 55. Nxc3 Kxb4 56. Nd1 Kc4 $19) 49. Rd3 $1 {Kapnisis,Spyridon} c2 50. Rc3 Kf6 51. a6 f4 $17) 48... Nc5 {ChessBase: '!' '!' '!' '!' ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: 'Carlsen slows the advance of White's passed a-pawn. '' ChessBase: '!' '!' '!' '!' ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: '!' 'Carlsen slows the advance of White's passed a-pawn. '' ChessBase: '!' '!' '!' ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: 'Carlsen slows the advance of White's passed a-pawn. ''} (48... c2 $2 49. Rc4 $11) (48... Rxb3 $4 49. Rxe4+ fxe4 50. Nd4+ $16) 49. Rc4 {ChessBase: '[#]' ChessBase: '[#] Kapnisis,Spyridon: 'Diagram '' ChessBase: '[#]' ChessBase: '[#] Kapnisis,Spyridon: 'Diagram '' ChessBase: '[#] Kapnisis,Spyridon: 'Diagram [#]''} Na6+ {ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: '!'' ChessBase: 'Kapnisis,Spyridon: '!'' ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: '!' '!'' ChessBase: 'Kapnisis,Spyridon: '!''} (49... Nxb3 $4 {Kapnisis,Spyridon} 50. a6 $16) 50. Kb6 {ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: 'EXERCISE (combination alert): Find Carlsen's winning idea. ANSWER: Step 1: Force White's king in front of his passed pawn by giving up a piece. '' ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: 'EXERCISE (combination alert): Find Carlsen's winning idea. ANSWER: Step 1: Force White's king in front of his passed pawn by giving up a piece. '' Cyrus Lakdawala: 'EXERCISE (combination alert): Find Carlsen's winning idea. --- ANSWER: Step 1: Force White's king in front of his passed pawn by giving up a piece.'} Rxb3+ $1 {Correctly seeing that the knight can be indirectly guarded with tactics. ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: '!' Cyrus Lakdawala: 'This is his second knight offer in the ending. '' ChessBase: 'Kapnisis,Spyridon: '!''} 51. Kxa6 Kd5 {ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: '!' Cyrus Lakdawala: 'Step 2: Double attack.'' ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: '!' '!' Cyrus Lakdawala: 'Step 2: Double attack.'' ChessBase: 'The point. The white rook is once again in trouble.' ChessBase: 'The point. The white rook is once again in trouble.'} 52. Rb4 {ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: '!?' Cyrus Lakdawala: 'Clever tactics, but not good enough. '' ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: '!?' '!?' Cyrus Lakdawala: 'Clever tactics, but not good enough. ''} ({After} 52. Ne5 Kxe5 {Black wins easily, since his pawn can promote, while White's can't.}) 52... c2 {ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: '!' Cyrus Lakdawala: 'Step 3: Promote and win the queen versus rook and knight ending. '' ChessBase: 'Kapnisis,Spyridon: '-+'' ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: '!' '!' Cyrus Lakdawala: 'Step 3: Promote and win the queen versus rook and knight ending. '' ChessBase: 'Kapnisis,Spyridon: '-+''} 53. Ne7+ Kc5 54. Rxb3 c1=Q 55. Rb6 Qc4+ 56. Kb7 ({If} 56. Ka7 Qe4 57. Nc8 Qa4 58. a6 Qd7+ 59. Kb8 Qxc8+ $1 {(simplification)} 60. Kxc8 Kxb6 {and White's precious a-pawn falls as well.}) 56... Qe4+ 57. Nc6 Qd5 {ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: '!'' ChessBase: 'Kapnisis,Spyridon: '!'' ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: '!' '!'' ChessBase: 'Kapnisis,Spyridon: '!''} 58. Kc7 (58. a6 $4 Qd7+ 59. Kb8 Kxb6 {and mate in two moves.}) 58... Qd6+ 59. Kb7 {ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: 'This is the part of the movie where the contrite, cheating husband tells his aggrieved wife: "I realize I don't deserve your forgiveness, but I'm asking anyway." ''} Qd7+ 60. Kb8 f4 {This long variation after 12. c6 seems to give no problems thus far for Black. It is now up to White to show there is something there. ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: '!' '!' Cyrus Lakdawala: 'White's a-pawn is weirdly frozen on its square and so he resigned. '' This long variation after 12. c6 seems to give no problems thus far for Black. It is now up to White to show there is something there. ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: '!' '!' '!' '!' Cyrus Lakdawala: 'White's a-pawn is weirdly frozen on its square and so he resigned. ''} 61. Nb4 f3 62. Rb7 Qxb7+ $1 63. Kxb7 Kxb4 64. a6 f2 65. a7 f1=Q 66. a8=Q Qf3+ 67. Kb8 Qxa8+ 68. Kxa8 {would be totally hopeless. SUMMARY: The position after 8...c5 is probably the most critical for us in the entire Austrian Attack, so let's learn it thoroughly. 0-1 (68) Wei,Y (2696)-Carlsen,M (2855) Bilbao 2016 CBM 174 [ChessBase] would be totally hopeless. SUMMARY: The position after 8...c5 is probably the most critical for us in the entire Austrian Attack, so let's learn it thoroughly. 0-1 (68) Wei,Y (2696)-Carlsen,M (2855) Bilbao 2016 CBM 174 [ChessBase] Cyrus Lakdawala: 'would be totally hopeless. --- SUMMARY: The position after 8...c5 is probably the most critical for us in the entire Austrian Attack, so let's learn it thoroughly.'} 0-1


