{The next position is much deeper, and here the choice is not completely clear. With the rooks on the board White has more winning potential and without his rook Black is weak on the light squares, but objectivly both options should lead to a draw:  Diagram [#]} 62. Rg6+ $5 {a good winning try despite the reduced winning potential.} (62. Rb5 {is met by} Bd2 {and Black's rook is a good piece.} ({However, not simplification into a pawn endgame via} 62... Rxb5 $2 63. axb5 Bf8 64. Rf4+ Kg7 65. Rxf8 Kxf8 66. b6 $18)) 62... Kxg6 63. Rxe5 Bd2 64. Rxe6+ Kf7 65. Re4 Kf6 66. Ke2 {Diagram [#]  I had a deep look at this material constellation in Chess Informant 125. Here Black can draw by not allowing his king to be driven further away. The cut off along the e-file is not sufficient to win as White can not simplify to a winning pawn ending with Black's king so close.} Bc3 $2 {Black had only a narrow path to draw:} (66... Bc1 $1 67. Kd3 (67. Rc4 Ba3 68. Rh4 Ke6 69. Rh5 Bb4 $11) 67... Ba3 68. Kc4 Bb4 69. Kd5 Kf7 70. Re2 Bc3 71. Kd6 ({The try to go into a pawn ending with} 71. Kc6 Bb4 72. Kb6 {Diagram [#]  is met by} Kf6 $1 73. Re8 Kf5 (73... Kf7 $2 74. Re5 $18) 74. Ra8 Ke6 $1 75. Rxa5 Bxa5+ 76. Kxa5 Kd7 77. Kb6 Kc8 $1 $11) 71... Bb4+ 72. Kd7 {Diagram [#]  and now Black must play} Kf6 73. Re6+ Kf5 $11 {as found by B. Baranov in 1954.}) 67. Rc4 $1 {Now the bishop surprisingly is completely dominated.} Be5 ({After} 67... Bb4 {White has} 68. Rxb4 $1 axb4 69. a5 b3 70. Kd2 {when his king is inside the square of the enemy pawn and Black's king is not.}) 68. Rc5 Ke6 69. Rxa5 Bc7 70. Rb5 Kd6 71. Kd3 Kc6 72. Kc4 Bb6 73. a5 Ba7 74. a6 Bb6 75. Rb3 (75. Rb3 {and White wins easily} Kc7 (75... Bg1 76. Rb7 Bf2 77. Rf7 Bg1 78. a7 $18) 76. Kd5 Bf2 77. Rb7+ Kc8 78. Kc6 $18) 1-0


