1. e4 {Negi,P Negi,P} e5 2. Bc4 {Popularly used to avoid the Petroff, but Wei Yi seems to like switching between various non Spanish variations in order to avoid theoretical lines...} Nf6 3. d3 Nc6 (3... c6 {is the obvious extra option allowed by this move order, and while there is nothing objectively wrong with it, I felt more like developing my pieces:)}) 4. Nf3 {This was rather surprising - if he wanted to play the closed Italian then why not simply play from the 2.f3 move order?} (4. Nc3 {is what I was expecting since he has played it before as well. Now after} Na5 {Black manages to get the bishop pair, and we get a special type of structure after dxc4, and a long strategic fight.}) 4... Be7 5. O-O O-O 6. Re1 d6 7. a4 Kh8 $5 (7... Na5 8. Ba2 c5 {is a more stable alternative, but I was in the mood of something more enterprising. Besides, I wanted to test him in more forcing variations...}) 8. Nc3 ({The inclusion of} 8. a5 a6 {shouldn't make much difference.} 9. Nc3 {can still be met by} Bg4 10. h3 Bh5 11. Nd5 (11. g4 $2 Nxg4 $1 12. hxg4 Bxg4 13. Be3 Qd7 14. Nb1 f5 15. Bd5 fxe4 16. Bxe4 d5 17. Nbd2 dxe4 18. dxe4 Bxf3 19. Nxf3 Qg4+ 20. Kf1 Rxf3 {0-1 (20) Rendle,T (2400)-Tissir,M (2474) England 2011}) (11. Be3 Nd4 $1 {remains similar to my game}) 11... Nxd5 12. Bxd5 Nxa5 $1 13. g4 Bg6 14. d4 f6 {an interesting position. At first Black's position looks fine but perhaps White's play could be improved upon in the following game:} 15. Nh4 Be8 16. Nf5 Nc6 17. c3 Qd7 18. Be3 Nd8 19. Qd2 Bf7 20. c4 c6 21. Bxf7 Nxf7 $15 {½-½ (36) Womacka,M (2427)-Nemcova,K (2261) Teplice 2012}) (8. c3 Ng8 9. d4 f5 $1 10. dxe5 fxe4 11. Rxe4 Rxf3 $1 {is a rather famous line by now.} 12. gxf3 (12. Qxf3 d5 $1 $15) 12... Nxe5 13. Rxe5 dxe5 14. Qxd8 Bxd8 15. Nd2 Nf6 16. Ne4 Nxe4 17. fxe4 Bg4 $11 {½-½ (21) Fedorchuk,S (2635)-Giri,A (2722) Germany 2012}) 8... Bg4 $5 9. h3 Bh5 10. Be3 ({During the game, I thought} 10. Bg5 $5 {might be an interesting idea.} h6 (10... Nd7 11. Be3 $1 $14) 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. g4 Bg6 13. Nd5 Nb8 {but maybe Black is doing quite alright.}) 10... Nd4 $5 $146 {A very obvious novelty... my opponent responded rather quickly with} 11. g4 $2 {I can't imagine what he expected me to play - since this just forces me to sacrifice on g4.... after which he lapsed into nearly an hour's long period of thought.} (11. Bxd4 exd4 12. Nd5 (12. Nb1 Bxf3 13. Qxf3 c6 $5 $11 { d5...b4.}) 12... Nxd5 (12... Bxf3 13. Qxf3 Nd7 {seemed somewhat better during the game.} 14. Nxe7 (14. Qe2 Bg5 $11) 14... Qxe7 15. Qg3 (15. Ba2 a5 $11) 15... a5 (15... Rae8 16. f4 a5 17. Qf2 Qf6 18. g4 $14) 16. f4 {seems more pleasant for White.}) 13. Bxd5 {was interesting... somehow during the preparation I had under-estimated this, but I wasn't too sure about which setup to play here in the game:} c6 14. Bb3 Bxf3 (14... Bf6 15. g4 {seems scary for Black}) 15. Qxf3 Bf6 {and Black has a solid position, but it's easy to realise during the game that White's position is more pleasant.}) 11... Nxg4 $1 12. Nxd4 $5 {Of course it's not a great move... but it's easier to play than the scary looking positions after hxg4, especially against a prepared opponent.} (12. hxg4 Bxg4 13. Bxd4 exd4 {is of course the critical line, but it only begins to look dangerous for White.} 14. Nb5 {basically, every move gives Black excellent compensation.} (14. Nd5 Bg5 $1 $17) 14... d5 $5 (14... c5 $44) 15. exd5 Bc5 $36) 12... Nxe3 13. Qxh5 Nxc4 (13... g6 {was a possible intermediate move, but I didn't see the point.}) 14. dxc4 exd4 15. Ne2 Bf6 16. Rad1 Qe8 $5 (16... c5 {I became worried that after} 17. Nf4 {and d5, White might suddenly get excellent compensation.}) 17. Nxd4 Bxd4 {I thought getting rid of the knight removes any chance of counterplay from his position... at the same time it gives him better drawing chances with a passive setup as well. Objectively perhaps ...xa4 was better, but it wasn't an easy decision in my opinion:} (17... Qxa4 18. b3 Qd7 (18... Qa2 $5) 19. Nf3 g6 20. Qh6 $17) 18. Rxd4 Qxa4 19. b3 Qa2 20. Qd5 $1 {White manages to get excellent counterplay with this and create a mess.} ({I had expected} 20. Rd2 Rae8 21. Qd5 b6 {when I have an excellent position.}) 20... Qxc2 21. Qxb7 Qc3 $1 {The computer isn't very impressed, but practically, of course I had to go for the h3-pawn...} 22. Red1 Qxh3 23. Qxc7 Qg4+ {An annoying move in time pressure. Otherwise White would have defended with 1d3-g3...} 24. Kf1 ({Amazingly enough, White could actually defend with} 24. Kh1 $1 {since} f5 {there are better moves according to the computer, but it doesn't seem as easy as I thought at all.} 25. Qxd6 {doesn't promise Black all that much since it's impossible to lift the rook to the kingside on time.}) 24... f5 $1 {Now this is strong. I felt White's position wass absolutely collapsing... but it seems I under-estimated his chances after the sacrifice of another pawn:} 25. e5 Qh3+ 26. Ke2 dxe5 27. Rd8 (27. Rg1 $1 {Amazingly, I didn't realise that the position is still insanely complicated - rather than me being on the verge of winning:} Qh5+ 28. Ke1 Rg8 29. Rd7 Qh6 (29... Rac8 30. Rdxg7 $1 $16) 30. Kd1 {and even though Black is of course better... it's a strangely complicated position.}) 27... Qg4+ (27... Qxb3 {somehow I forgot about this move, but I am not sure if Black can win after} 28. Rxf8+ Rxf8 29. Rd8 Qc2+ 30. Kf1 Qc1+ 31. Ke2 Kg8 32. Rxf8+ Kxf8 33. c5 {and the perpetual checks are always hanging in the air...}) 28. Kf1 (28. Ke1 $5 {would have been a tougher defence. I wasn't yet sure of what to do since ...h5 doesn't work as well here due to the e1-king defending the d1-rook - thus allowing xa8.} Qe4+ (28... h5 29. Rxa8 Qe4+ 30. Kf1 Rxa8 31. Rd7 (31. Rd8+ Rxd8 32. Qxd8+ Kh7 33. Qg5 {not so easy to convert}) 31... Rg8 32. Rd5 {with excellent chances to draw.}) 29. Kf1 h6 $5 {was my plan eventually, and maybe it is even an excellent practical try since it's not easy to decide for Black.} 30. Rxa8 Rxa8 31. Rd5 (31. Rd8+ Rxd8 32. Qxd8+ Kh7) 31... Re8 $17) 28... h5 $1 {Since xa8 isn't possible.} 29. Rxf8+ Rxf8 30. Rd3 $1 {Amazingly he found this resource with almost no time on the clock.} (30. Rd8 Rxd8 31. Qxd8+ Kh7 32. c5 {will just run into a mating net after} h4 33. c6 h3 34. c7 h2 35. Qd5 e4 36. c8=Q h1=Q#) 30... f4 {The only way.} 31. Qxe5 f3 32. Rd6 $1 {Another amazing resource... at one point I had nearly an hour more, but my time was fast approaching the last minutes as well.} (32. Qe3 Rf4 $1 {would finish the game.}) 32... Kh7 {Again, the only way forward.} (32... Qg2+ 33. Ke1 Qg1+ 34. Kd2 Qxf2+ 35. Kc3 {Amazingly, there are no checks now, and it's impossible to avoid a perpetual check.}) 33. Rd4 $1 {These only moves were beginning to infuriate me... but after seeing my next moves I thought I had finally found a win to finish things off:} Qg2+ (33... Qg6 34. Qe4 {is very drawish.}) 34. Ke1 Qg6 $1 {Since e4 isn't possible here.} (34... Qg1+ 35. Kd2 Qxf2+ 36. Kc3 {is messy.}) 35. Rd7 {Another, seemingly, only move!} (35. Kd2 Re8 36. Qd5 Re2+ 37. Kc3 Rxf2 38. Rf4 $1 {is some insane computer defence, but I wouldn't imagine any human considering this playable for White.}) 35... h4 36. Kd2 h3 {Things began to look smooth for me now, I really couldn't see any counter for him...} 37. Rd6 Rf6 38. c5 $5 ({Unfortunately, I spent all my time calculating} 38. Rxf6 Qxf6 39. Qh2 Qe6 $5 {and Black should be able to win eventually.}) 38... Qh6+ 39. Kc2 {Now, with my clock running out, I panicked and did not play the natural h2.} Qg6+ (39... h2 $1 {Alas, just one more accurate move was required...the point is that after} 40. Rxf6 gxf6 41. Qc7+ Kg6 42. Qg3+ Kf5 43. Qxf3+ {White seems to get a lot of checks, but Black will find a safe haven on the queenside:} Qf4 44. Qh5+ Ke6 45. Qe8+ Kd5 46. Qd7+ Kxc5 47. Qc8+ Kb6 48. Qe6+ Kc7 49. Qf7+ Kd6 50. Qf8+ Kc6 $1 51. Qe8+ Kb7 $19) 40. Kd2 {He returns the favour.} (40. Kb2 $1 {I just couldn't find a way to continue.}) 40... Rf5 {I suddenly decided that I had excellent winning chances in the endgame... but that is of course very hard to figure out with no time left:} 41. Rxg6 Rxe5 42. Rg3 $1 Rh5 43. c6 h2 44. c7 Rc5 (44... h1=Q $1 {would have led to a very exciting line, but I was too tired to calculate it till the end:} 45. c8=Q Rd5+ 46. Ke3 Qe1+ 47. Kxf3 Qh1+ $1 {the move which I obviously missed.} 48. Ke3 (48. Rg2 Qd1+ $1 49. Kf4 g5+ $1 50. Rxg5 Qd2+ $19) 48... Re5+ $1 49. Kd4 $1 Qe4+ 50. Kc3 Qe1+ 51. Kd4 Qxf2+ 52. Kxe5 Qxg3+ 53. Ke4 Qxb3 {this should be practically winning...}) 45. Rh3+ Kg6 46. Rxh2 Rxc7 47. Rh3 Rf7 48. Kd3 $1 (48. Ke3 Rb7 $1 {would be suffering.}) 48... Rf4 49. Rh1 Rb4 50. Ra1 $1 {The simplest. It's impossible to win this position since my pieces are too passive. The rest of the game was quite uneventful:} (50. Kc3 Re4 51. Rh3 Rf4 {and I was hoping to gain a move like this, although the computer isn't impressed at all.}) 50... Rxb3+ 51. Ke4 Rb7 52. Kxf3 Kf5 53. Ra5+ Ke6 54. Kg4 Kd6 55. f4 Kc6 56. Ra1 Kb5 57. Rb1+ Kc6 58. Ra1 Kb6 59. Rb1+ Kc7 60. Ra1 Kb8 61. Kh5 Rb2 62. f5 Rg2 63. Ra6 Rh2+ 64. Kg5 Rg2+ 65. Kh5 Rf2 66. Kg5 Kb7 67. Rg6 Rg2+ 68. Kh5 Rh2+ 69. Kg5 Rg2+ 70. Kh5 Rh2+ 1/2-1/2


