{A wonderful game by Wei Yi. Nonetheless Black has only himself to blame for his troubles after his instructive strategical mistake at move 13.} 1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd6 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 g6 {In principle it's attractive to combine Qd6 with a kingside fianchetto. The question is whether Black can afford to leave the b5 square undefended. Alternatives examined on ChessPub are} (5... c6 {and}) (5... a6) 6. Nb5 {The most challenging reply.} Qb6 7. Na3 c6 8. Nc4 Qc7 {The solid alternative} (8... Qd8 {was endorsed by Caruana in his game with Leko on ChessPub.}) 9. Nce5 {Modern players know when to break Classical rules. Spurning the development of his other pieces, Wei Yi invests four straight moves in getting his knight from c3 to a fine post on e5.} Bg7 10. Bc4 Nd5 11. O-O O-O 12. Bb3 Nd7 13. Nd3 a5 $2 {The cause of a lot of misfortune for Black. Instead he should solidify his knight on d5 with} (13... b5 $1 {Then} 14. Re1 N7b6 15. c3 a5 16. a3 Bf5 {proved OK for Black in D. Solak- D.Milanovic, Vrnjacka Banja 2010.}) 14. Re1 N7f6 {Black would lose a pawn after} (14... a4 15. Bxd5 cxd5 16. Rxe7) 15. c4 $1 {Punishing Black's omission of 13...b5.} Nb6 16. a4 {Having chased the knight away from its wonderful base on d5 Wei Yi rules out any counterplay with 16... a4.} Bf5 17. Bf4 Qd8 18. h3 Nbd7 19. Nc1 $1 {The beginning of another extended manoeuvre with the knight. It heads for g3 in order to embarrass the bishop on f5. By retreating to c1 it takes away the option of Bxd3, this introducing the threat of 20.g4.} Nb8 {Having been deprived of the d5 post the knight wanders pathetically around the queenside.} 20. Ne2 Na6 21. Ng3 Bc8 22. Qd2 Nb4 23. Rac1 Re8 24. Re2 b6 25. Bg5 {Here the bishop deters the move e7-e6 as it would leave the knight on f6 in a pin. This becomes an important factor after White's next move.} Ba6 26. Ne5 Nd7 27. Ng4 Nf6 28. Nh6+ {The weakness of f7 allows Wei to force Black into the horrible exchange of his vital bishop for the knight.} Bxh6 29. Bxh6 b5 30. cxb5 cxb5 31. axb5 Bxb5 32. Re5 Bc6 33. Nf5 {Provoking a loosening of Black's kingside. In fact there was already a strong tactical solution with} (33. d5 $1 Bd7 ({The less evil is to give up the exchange with} 33... Bxd5 34. Ba4 {If}) (33... Nfxd5 34. Rxc6 Nxc6 35. Rxd5 {leaves White with two pieces for a rook plus a big attack.}) 34. Qd4 $1 {putting the queen on a line where she intersects with the mating square g7. The knight on f6 proves too flimsy a barrier.} Ra6 35. Ne4 {with the threat of 36.d6! undermining the knight on f6. Black has no good defence.}) 33... e6 34. Ng3 Nd7 35. Ree1 Rb8 36. h4 $1 {Utilising all his resources to attack the black king. The h-pawn will ram g6 in due course.} Nd5 {The queen is trapped after} (36... Qxh4 37. Bg5 Qg4 38. Bd1) 37. Bd1 Ne7 38. h5 Rb4 39. hxg6 hxg6 40. Bg5 Qb6 41. Bxe7 Rxe7 42. Qh6 Nf6 {After} (42... Rxd4 43. Rc3 {threats include 44. Nh5 gxh5 45.Rg3+.}) ({Or} 42... Bb7 43. Nf5 gxf5 44. Re3 {leaves the black king fatally exposed.}) 43. Nf5 $1 {Wei Yi's last piece of wizardry with his knights. The threat of mate on g7 wins the exchange.} exf5 {Too awful for Black is} (43... gxf5 44. Qxf6) 44. Rxe7 Qxd4 45. Bf3 Rb6 {Black is mated after} (45... Bxf3 46. Rc8+) 46. Rd1 {A decisive check on d8 follows if the queen saves herself.} 1-0


