1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 {A direct challenge to Black's Nimzo-Indian strategy which revolves around controlling the e4-square.} d5 {Style and temperament as well as knowledge of opening theory play a role in the choice of a pawn structure.} ({Here Yuffa opts for a space-gaining thrust in the centre. Instead he could pursue adventure by imbalancing things with} 4... c5 5. d5 O-O 6. e4 {. This would be more strategically risky as White has a big centre but it can be undermined, even immediately with the Benko Gambit-like} b5 $5 {.}) 5. a3 Be7 6. e4 dxe4 7. fxe4 e5 $1 {The strong point on d5 having been dissolved it is necessary to exert himself a second time in the centre or else he'll be overrun by 8 e5.} 8. d5 {So Wei Yi establishes a space advantage after all. On the other hand setting up a wedge of pawns on light squares has left some of his dark squares feeling a little exposed. As we shall see if Black responds precisely then White can be persuaded into castling queenside, when the pawn advances which the structure requires of him – namely b2-b4 and c4-c5 –become problematical.} O-O 9. Nf3 Nbd7 $2 {The cramped black position has too many minor pieces vying to use its narrow outlets.} ({He should ease the clutter with} 9... Bg4 $1 {. Then the exchange on f3 would allow his other bishop to get to a strong diagonal. For example,} 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 Nbd7 12. Bd3 Bc5 {(now White can only castle kingside if he agrees to the rather unappealing exchange of his 'good' bishop with 13 Be3)} 13. Bd2 a5 14. O-O-O {(as observed above with the king on the queenside rather than tucked away on h1 it is difficult to see how White can safely arrange b2-b4 which the pawn structure indicates is his natural plan)} Ne8 15. Kb1 Nd6 {and Black is well entrenched.}) 10. Bd3 Nc5 ({After} 10... a5 11. O-O {White's king is secure on the kingside and he can try to exploit his queenside space advantage by engineering b2-b4. However the game move doesn't solve Black's problems as his knight can eventually be kicked back by b2-b4.}) ({Perhaps he should speculate with the disruptive} 10... Bc5 $5 11. b4 Bd4 {.}) 11. Bc2 a5 12. O-O Bg4 {Too late as the white king is already on g1 and Black has the wrong piece on c5.} 13. Be3 Bh5 14. h3 Ra6 15. b3 $5 {A sensible consolidating/ waiting move.} ({Perhaps upon} 15. g4 {(objectively the best move)} {In any case, Black could also answer} Bg6 {when} ({Yuffa was intending the sacrifice} 15... Nxg4 16. hxg4 Bxg4 {. It's not very convincing, but after} 17. Qd2 Nd7 ({not} 17... Rg6 $2 18. Nxe5 {) he has certain attacking chances.})) 16. Nxe5 {gives White strong pressure as in the game but with White's kingside more airy as he has put a pawn on g4 rather than b3. Wei Yi decides to take no risks.}) 15... Bg6 $2 ({Black could have guarded e5 with} 15... Ncd7 {when White would have had to squeeze him slowly on the queenside as he has missed the chance for 15 g4 Bg6 16 Nxe5. But I suspect one reason why Wei Yi spurned 15 g4 was because he had anticipated that Yuffa would carrying on playing actively even when the position required careful defence.}) 16. Nxe5 Bxe4 17. Nxe4 Ncxe4 {when White would have had to squeeze him slowly on the queenside as he has missed the chance for 15 g4 Bg6 16 Nxe5. But I suspect one reason why Wei Yi spurned 15 g4 was because he had anticipated that Yuffa would carrying on playing actively even when the position required careful defence. QUESTION: Can you list White's positional advantages going into the middlegame? In a general way how should he try to exploit them? And what should be his first move? ANSWER: White has the bishop pair: a sure advantage when there are open diagonals in and around the centre. He has a well-placed knight on e5 which can be supported by the other pieces. He has the open f-file for his rook. And he has a significant space advantage in the centre due to the powerful pawn on d5. While allowing for the defensive solidity of Black's kingside, his 3-2-pawn majority there is of no dynamic value. In contrast, we can imagine White's 4-3 queenside majority becoming mobile. This evaluation gives us an outline of White's overall strategy: combine threats to the black king with edging the pawns forwards on the queenside. Then Black will be under pressure across the whole board. For the moment, Wei Yi is concerned with improving the layout of his own pieces and worsening the coordination of his opponent's pieces. Thus he brings his queen to an active square and forces the black knight to retreat from its centre post.} 18. Qf3 $1 Nc5 19. Bd4 {And now the white bishops are aligned for action against the black king on neighbouring diagonals. In this formation they are known as raking bishops.} Ncd7 {Driven from its own centre post the black knight won't let the white horse remain undisturbed.} 20. Nxd7 Nxd7 {QUESTION: How can we start using the 'sleeping giant' – that is, White's queenside pawns? ANSWER:} 21. b4 $1 {Have some sympathy for Black's bishop. If we compare him to a fireman, he was all geared up for 21...Bf6 to exchange off one of White's imposing bishops and stop any possible conflagration on the kingside. And now suddenly a blaze has erupted on a square on the queenside which is in his remit to extinguish.} axb4 ({White would have an imposing positional advantage after} 21... Bf6 22. Bxf6 Rxf6 23. Qe4 {(gaining vital time to seize control of the e-file by attacking h7)} g6 24. Rfe1 {. There would no longer be an assault on Black's king, but the pawn majority would be ready to advance with 25 c5 etc.}) 22. axb4 Bf6 ({After} 22... Rxa1 23. Bxa1 {Therefore the bishop elects to perform its role as defender of the king, rather than restrainer of the white queenside. If instead} Bf6 {then} (23... Bxb4 {the 'fireman' has been distracted and flames soon engulf the kingside:} 24. Qh5 $1 g6 25. Qh6 f6 {(forced as there's no ...Bf6 move to stop mate on g7)} 26. Bxg6 $1 {and the Black kingside falls apart as} hxg6 27. Qxg6+ Kh8 28. Rf5 {leads to mate on the h-file.} (28. Z0)) 24. Qf5 $1 {forces} g6 {, when} 25. Bxf6 gxf5 26. Bxd8 Rxd8 27. Bxf5 {wins a clean pawn for White.}) ({Similar is} 22... Bxb4 23. Rxa6 bxa6 24. Qh5 g6 25. Qh6) {QUESTION: White's bishop is about to drop with check on d4, but can you see Wei Yi's imaginative reply? ANSWER:} 23. Rxa6 $1 {Very nicely played.} ({Black would avoid the worst after} 23. Bxf6 Rxf6 {.}) 23... Bxd4+ 24. Kh1 bxa6 25. Qe4 {The point: the double attack on d4 and h7 means that White regains the piece. Technically speaking this isn't a very hard tactic, but leaving the bishop hanging with check is so against our instincts that it takes some pluck even to consider it.} Re8 {Objectively, Black's move is a blunder.} ({On the other hand,} 25... g6 26. Qxd4 {leaves him in dire straits: his pawn on a6 is sickly and easy to attack while White can readily create a passed pawn with 27 c5 and 28 d6. Note that White could continue to plan on a wide scale: the bishop, a superior piece to the knight, could either attack a6 (with Bd3 after c4-c5) or aim at f7 (with Bb3 after c4-c5 and d5-d6). It is very doubtful that Yuffa would have been able to hold this endgame against his higher rated opponent. So the game move might be worth the gamble. Perhaps Wei Yi won't rise to the occasion...}) ({If} 25... Nf6 26. Rxf6 {wins at once.}) {QUESTION: Before reading on, try to decide White's best option: should he take on d4 or on h7? ANSWER:} 26. Qxh7+ $1 {No such luck.} ({If White had settled for} 26. Qxd4 Nf6 {Black remains in deep trouble but he is much healthier than after 26...g6 27 Qxd4 as given in the last note. He has kept his pawn on g7 so his knight has a firm centre base where it shields the f7-pawn. He would be able to put up more of a fight. Instead a king hunt begins.}) 26... Kf8 27. Qh8+ Ke7 {QUESTION: White has to decide whether to play 28 Re1+ or 28 Qh4+ here. Can you find a reason why one of these is much stronger? ANSWER:} 28. Qh4+ $1 {A precise move which attacks the bishop and forces it to f6, after which it can't block the e-file.} ({If instead} 28. Re1+ Be5 $1 {uses the bishop as a bodyguard,} {when} 29. Qxg7 ({while} 29. Qh4+ $2 g5 $1 {(getting the bishop involved in the defence of g7 and h8)} 30. Qxg5+ Kf8 {is even good for him}) 29... Rg8 $1 {defends adequately for Black after} 30. Rxe5+ Nxe5 31. Qxe5+ Kf8 {.}) 28... Bf6 29. Re1+ Kd6 ({Instead} 29... Kf8 {allows mate in one.}) ({A pretty finish would be} 29... Ne5 30. Rxe5+ $1 Kd6 31. c5+ $1 {(the winning move and curiously the only way for White to be better)} Kxe5 32. Qe4# {.}) 30. c5+ {In variations above this pawn advance aimed to create a queen; here it is to catch a king.} Nxc5 ({White gradually hunts down his quarry after} 30... Kxd5 {, e.g.} 31. Rd1+ Kc6 32. Be4+ Kb5 33. Bd3+ Kc6 34. Qc4 {(removing the black king's access to the b5 and d5-squares and preparing to push him back to his doom on b8; threats include 35 Qxa6+ and 35 Be4+)} Kb7 35. Qxa6+ Kb8 36. Qb5+ Ka7 ({or} 36... Kc8 37. c6 Nb6 38. Qa6+ {and mates next move}) 37. Bf5 $1 {(the elimination of the black knight opens the way to mate)} Re7 38. Bxd7 {and Black has no good defence against 39 Qa5+ Kb8 40 c6 followed by a quick mate with the queen on b7.}) {QUESTION: Wei Yi still needs to be accurate. Decide if he should recapture with 31 bxc5+ or throw in a check with 31 Qf4+. ANSWER:} 31. Qf4+ $1 {Another precise move. Unless you have a massive material advantage it is never a good idea to relax and think the game will win itself.} ({Here for example White would suddenly be worse after} 31. bxc5+ Kxc5 {.}) 31... Kd7 ({If} 31... Kxd5 32. Rd1+ Kc6 {it would be cruel to give Black some false hope with} 33. Rxd8 ({but the zwischenzug} 33. Qf3+ $1 Kb5 34. Rxd8 {allows him to resign with no qualms}) 33... Re1+ $2 34. Kh2 Be5 {when he regains the queen and can linger on.}) ({Alternatively upon} 31... Be5 32. bxc5+ Kxd5 ({if} 32... Kxc5 33. Rxe5 {is a piece up for White}) {, there is a neat win of the queen:} 33. Rxe5+ $1 Rxe5 34. Qd2+ {.}) 32. Bf5+ {It seems the calculation of variations had taken its toll and White was in time pressure. With this check he allows the black king to slip back to the relative sanctuary of f8.} ({Instead it was possible to keep the fugitive in the centre or else drive him to destruction on the queenside with} 32. Qf5+ $1 Kd6 ({or} 32... Ne6 33. dxe6+ fxe6 34. Rd1+ Ke7 35. Qc5+ Kf7 36. Rxd8 {pockets the queen}) 33. bxc5+ Kxc5 34. d6+ $1 {opening all lines of attack} Kb6 ({or} 34... Kxd6 35. Rd1+ {again winning the queen}) 35. Rb1+ Kc6 ({if} 35... Ka7 36. Qc5+ {leads to mate}) 36. dxc7 Kxc7 37. Qc5+ Kd7 38. Ba4+ Ke6 39. Re1+ {and mate next move.}) 32... Ne6 33. dxe6+ Ke7 34. Qg4 Kf8 ({There was a fighting chance with} 34... Qd2 $1 35. Rd1 Qe3 36. exf7 Rd8 $1 {. The point is that} 37. Rxd8 {allows} Qe1+ 38. Kh2 Be5+ 39. g3 Qf2+ 40. Kh1 Qf1+ {with a draw by perpetual. White could keep an edge with the superior 37 Rg1! If Black was in time pressure as well it is no surprise he failed to seize his chance. It is also likely he had been made punch drunk by the endless threats and felt relieved to tuck the king back on f8. The idea of a counterattack never occurred to him.}) 35. Rd1 {Gaining time for his next move by breaking the pin on the e-file.} Qb8 36. exf7 Re5 ({If} 36... Kxf7 37. Bg6+ Kg8 38. Qh5 Rd8 39. Re1 {and there's no good way to stop 40 Qh7+ Kg8 41 Qh8 mate. Naturally grabbing the exchange with 38 Bxe8 in this sequence was also entirely winning.}) 37. Bg6 Rg5 ({Losing at once, but if he waits then amongst other winning methods White has the plan of queening his advanced pawn, for example} 37... Qa8 38. Qd7 Qb8 39. Qe8+ Rxe8 40. fxe8=Q+ Qxe8 41. Bxe8 Kxe8 42. g3 {when the endgame is a technical win.}) {QUESTION: Can you see the quickest win for White? ANSWER:} 38. Re1 $1 {A neat finish. After 38...Rxg4 39 Re8+ mates next move.} ({Also decisive but more laborious is} 38. Qh4 Ke7 ({or} 38... Rxg6 39. Qh8+ Kxf7 40. Qxb8 {winning the queen}) 39. Re1+ Kd7 40. Qe4 {etc. when having been ousted from f8 the black king will soon be mated.}) 1-0


