{China's biggest hope is the 15 years old Wei Yi, who indeed has all the chances to become a top GM, but this time he runs into a very nice defeat... Balogh Csaba: 'China's biggest hope is the 15 years old Wei Yi, who indeed has all the chances to become a top GM, but this time he runs into a very nice defeat... China's biggest hope is the 15 years old Wei Yi, who indeed has all the chances to become a top GM, but this time he runs into a very nice defeat...'} 1. e4 {Balogh Csaba} d5 {The Scandinavian defence. Wei Yi is very strong in the main lines, therefore it was a clever choice by Miroshnichenko to play something less explored. Balogh Csaba: 'The Scandinavian defence. Wei Yi is very strong in the main lines, therefore it was a clever choice by Miroshnichenko to play something less explored. The Scandinavian defence. Wei Yi is very strong in the main lines, therefore it was a clever choice by Miroshnichenko to play something less explored.'} 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd6 {The queen stays resolutely in the middle of the action. The question is whether White can gain anything worthwhile by harassing her with Nb5 or Bf4 in the future. The queen stays resolutely in the middle of the action. The question is whether White can gain anything worthwhile by harassing her with Nb5 or Bf4 in the future.} 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 g6 {A kind of Scandinavian-Pirc hybrid. You might like to examine Tiviakov- Fedorchuk in the archives for more details. A kind of Scandinavian-Pirc hybrid. You might like to examine Tiviakov- Fedorchuk in the archives for more details.} ({Balogh Csaba: 'One of the alternatives is'} 5... a6 {where White's strongest reply is Balogh Csaba: 'where White's strongest reply is where White's strongest reply is'} 6. g3 {Probably Wei Yi mixed up these lines...}) 6. g3 {A natural response as White's light squared bishop will exert pressure on the queenside on g2 and the black queen can be hunted by his other bishop with Bf4. However as we shall see Black can throw a spanner in the works when it comes to White castling kingside. A natural response as White's light squared bishop will exert pressure on the queenside on g2 and the black queen can be hunted by his other bishop with Bf4. However as we shall see Black can throw a spanner in the works when it comes to White castling kingside. It looks natural to fianchetto the bishop and also to prepare for the other bishop to develop with tempo to f4, but it turns out to be an inaccuracy... Balogh Csaba: 'It looks natural to fianchetto the bishop and also to prepare for the other bishop to develop with tempo to f4, but it turns out to be an inaccuracy... It looks natural to fianchetto the bishop and also to prepare for the other bishop to develop with tempo to f4, but it turns out to be an inaccuracy...'} ({Instead Instead Balogh Csaba: 'The best is'} 6. Nb5 {gains time for White to play the strategically desirable c2-c4 advance. For example gains time for White to play the strategically desirable c2-c4 advance. For example ! followed by c4, building a very strong center. Practice already shows that Black is unable to put enough pressure on it, therefore White claims an edge in the end. Balogh Csaba: '!' '!' Balogh Csaba: '! followed by c4, building a very strong center. Practice already shows that Black is unable to put enough pressure on it, therefore White claims an edge in the end. followed by c4, building a very strong center. Practice already shows that Black is unable to put enough pressure on it, therefore White claims an edge in the end.'} Qd8 7. c4 (7. Bf4 Na6 {Slightly awkward for Black is} (7... Nd5 8. Be5) 8. c4 {Slightly awkward for Black is} Bg7 9. Be5 O-O 10. Be2 Bh6 11. O-O c6 12. Nc3 Nc7 13. Qb3 Ne6 14. d5 Nf4 15. Rad1 {this sharp position was reached in Dastan, B (2432)-Mamedov, R (2659)/Kocaeli TUR 2014, and now I like this sharp position was reached in Dastan, B (2432)-Mamedov, R (2659)/Kocaeli TUR 2014, and now I like} Nd7 $5) 7... c6 8. Nc3 Bg7 9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O Bg4 11. Be3 Nbd7 12. Qb3 {White would have a small plus due to the bishop pair and his extra space after} (12. h3 Bxf3 13. Bxf3) 12... Qc7 13. Rfd1 Rfe8 14. d5 $6 {Evidently Wei Yi doesn't enjoy playing against Black's opening system. It's not too late to get a tiny edge with Evidently Wei Yi doesn't enjoy playing against Black's opening system. It's not too late to get a tiny edge with} (14. h3 Bxf3 15. Bxf3) 14... Bxf3 15. gxf3 {Not an aesthetic recapture. Perhaps White had missed that after Not an aesthetic recapture. Perhaps White had missed that after} (15. Bxf3 Ne5 16. Be2 Neg4 {the double attack on e3 and h2 is very pleasant for him.}) 15... b6 {So far this is Wei Yi (2638)-Benidze, D (2458)/Kocaeli TUR 2014 and here So far this is Wei Yi (2638)-Benidze, D (2458)/Kocaeli TUR 2014 and here} (15... Nh5 16. Rd2 Be5 {looks good for Black due to White's fractured kingside.})) 6... Bg7 7. Bg2 {Diagram} Qa6 $5 {The black queen slips away from attack by Bf4 and prevents White castling kingside. Instead The black queen slips away from attack by Bf4 and prevents White castling kingside. Instead ! This is the drawback of the g3-Bg2 plan and the point of avoiding playing a6 or c6 in the 5th move. White cannot castle kingside. Balogh Csaba: '!' '!' Balogh Csaba: '! This is the drawback of the g3-Bg2 plan and the point of avoiding playing a6 or c6 in the 5th move. White cannot castle kingside. This is the drawback of the g3-Bg2 plan and the point of avoiding playing a6 or c6 in the 5th move. White cannot castle kingside.'} (7... c6 {was preferred in the aforementioned Fedorchuk game. was preferred in the aforementioned Fedorchuk game.}) 8. Bf4 {Black looks comfortable after a queen exchange for example Black looks comfortable after a queen exchange for example} (8. Qe2 O-O 9. O-O Qxe2 10. Nxe2 Bf5 11. c3 Be4 {as in Malakhov, I (2441)-Kovalenko, I (2650)/St Petersburg RUS 2014. as in Malakhov, I (2441)-Kovalenko, I (2650)/St Petersburg RUS 2014.}) 8... c6 9. Qd2 {This is the ambitious continuation, keeping the queens on the board and castling queenside, but objectively I believe that it is a wrong idea because Black's attack comes too fast. Balogh Csaba: 'This is the ambitious continuation, keeping the queens on the board and castling queenside, but objectively I believe that it is a wrong idea because Black's attack comes too fast. This is the ambitious continuation, keeping the queens on the board and castling queenside, but objectively I believe that it is a wrong idea because Black's attack comes too fast.'} ({Balogh Csaba: 'It is more solid to play'} 9. Qe2 Qxe2+ 10. Nxe2 {but of course the probability for a draw has increased a lot. Balogh Csaba: 'but of course the probability for a draw has increased a lot. but of course the probability for a draw has increased a lot.'}) 9... O-O 10. O-O-O $2 {Leads to trouble. Black is comfortable but no more after} (10. Bh6 {but Black appears to be able to hold his own or more after} Bxh6 11. Qxh6 Bf5 12. O-O-O b5 {for example Sit back and enjoy the attack the attack after for example Sit back and enjoy the attack the attack after} 13. a3 ({Instead} 13. Nh4 {might lead to a sharp draw:} Be6 14. Rhe1 b4 15. Rxe6 bxc3 $1 ({Steering clear of} 15... fxe6 16. Bh3 bxc3 17. Bxe6+ Rf7 18. Nxg6 {when mate on f8 is threatened.}) 16. Nf5 cxb2+ 17. Kb1 gxf5 18. Qg5+ Kh8 19. Rxf6 exf6 20. Qxf6+ Kg8 21. Qg5+ Kh8 {draw!}) 13... b4 $1 14. axb4 Qa1+ 15. Nb1 Na6 16. Nh4 Bxc2 $1 17. Kxc2 Nxb4+ 18. Kd2 Rad8 19. Ke2 Qa6+ 20. Kf3 c5 21. g4 Rxd4 22. Rxd4 cxd4 23. Rd1 Nd3 24. Qd2 e5 25. Kg3 e4 26. f4 Rb8 27. Bf1 Qe6 28. h3 Rb3 {0-1 Berbatov, K (2481) -Chatalbashev, B (2555)/Albena 2010.}) ({Meanwhile} 10. Ne5 Be6 11. Nd3 Nbd7 {looked OK for Black in Akash, G (2404) -Sethuraman, S (2520)/ Kolkata 2012. looked OK for Black in Akash, G (2404) -Sethuraman, S (2520)/ Kolkata 2012.}) 10... b5 {! Black does not need to waste more time and he immediately launches his attack on the queenside. Even the queen is well placed now on a6. Balogh Csaba: '!' '!' Balogh Csaba: '! Black does not need to waste more time and he immediately launches his attack on the queenside. Even the queen is well placed now on a6. Black does not need to waste more time and he immediately launches his attack on the queenside. Even the queen is well placed now on a6.'} 11. a3 $2 {Leads to trouble. Black is comfortable but no more after Leads to trouble. Black is comfortable but no more after ? Another wrong decision to slow down the attack. It works with the opposite effect. Diagram Balogh Csaba: '? Another wrong decision to slow down the attack. It works with the opposite effect. Diagram Another wrong decision to slow down the attack. It works with the opposite effect. Diagram'} ({Balogh Csaba: 'White should have played'} 11. Kb1 b4 12. Ne2 {although after} Nd5 (12... Bf5 {followed by Nbd7 and Nd5 or Ne4 seems to be completely fine for Black. Balogh Csaba: 'followed by Nbd7 and Nd5 or Ne4 seems to be completely fine for Black. followed by Nbd7 and Nd5 or Ne4 seems to be completely fine for Black.'})) 11... b4 $1 {A move familiar from the Berbatov game in the notes above. Black gambits a pawn for a big initiative. A move familiar from the Berbatov game in the notes above. Black gambits a pawn for a big initiative. ! A perfect sacrifice, which was underestimated by the young Chinese. At first sight it does not look that dangerous indeed, but after some extremely strong energetic moves, all black pieces come into the attack. Balogh Csaba: '! A perfect sacrifice, which was underestimated by the young Chinese. At first sight it does not look that dangerous indeed, but after some extremely strong energetic moves, all black pieces come into the attack. A perfect sacrifice, which was underestimated by the young Chinese. At first sight it does not look that dangerous indeed, but after some extremely strong energetic moves, all black pieces come into the attack.'} 12. axb4 Qa1+ 13. Nb1 a5 $5 {! The most natural attacking move again! Black would like to open the a- and b-files in order to quickly attack the weakest point in White's camp, the b2 pawn! However, Black had to count with the next move beforehand: Balogh Csaba: '!' '!' Balogh Csaba: '! The most natural attacking move again! Black would like to open the a- and b-files in order to quickly attack the weakest point in White's camp, the b2 pawn! However, Black had to count with the next move beforehand: The most natural attacking move again! Black would like to open the a- and b-files in order to quickly attack the weakest point in White's camp, the b2 pawn! However, Black had to count with the next move beforehand:'} ({Black also had an attack after Black also had an attack after} 13... Nd5 14. Qd3 a5 15. b5 cxb5 16. Ne5 Be6 17. Qa3 Qxa3 18. Nxa3 b4 {in Juggernaut, R (2613) -Wikiman, R (2478)/ playchess.com INT 2007, but White can at least be pleased to have got the queens off! in Juggernaut, R (2613) -Wikiman, R (2478)/ playchess.com INT 2007, but White can at least be pleased to have got the queens off!}) 14. b5 {Wei Yi is relying on this move to keep the queenside blocked, but he meets with an unpleasant surprise. Wei Yi is relying on this move to keep the queenside blocked, but he meets with an unpleasant surprise. The critical test of the previous move. This pawn advance seems to paralyze the black pieces and White is threatening with Ne5. Accepting the pawn with cxb5 seems to drop a piece after Ne1 or g1, because White attacks the a8 rook and the b8 knight is also hanging. However, Black had something in mind... Balogh Csaba: 'The critical test of the previous move. This pawn advance seems to paralyze the black pieces and White is threatening with Ne5. Accepting the pawn with cxb5 seems to drop a piece after Ne1 or g1, because White attacks the a8 rook and the b8 knight is also hanging. However, Black had something in mind... The critical test of the previous move. This pawn advance seems to paralyze the black pieces and White is threatening with Ne5. Accepting the pawn with cxb5 seems to drop a piece after Ne1 or g1, because White attacks the a8 rook and the b8 knight is also hanging. However, Black had something in mind...'} cxb5 $3 {! Balogh Csaba: '!' '!'} 15. Ne1 {White decides to take the piece on offer. If he declines he is left in a horrible position as the black queenside pawns will run at his king. White decides to take the piece on offer. If he declines he is left in a horrible position as the black queenside pawns will run at his king. The most natural move again with the knight to open the diagonal. Of course on e5 it would have been more active, but it closes the f4 bishop and the knight is not under attack anymore on b8. On e1, it could become an important defender of the king. Diagram Balogh Csaba: 'The most natural move again with the knight to open the diagonal. Of course on e5 it would have been more active, but it closes the f4 bishop and the knight is not under attack anymore on b8. On e1, it could become an important defender of the king. Diagram The most natural move again with the knight to open the diagonal. Of course on e5 it would have been more active, but it closes the f4 bishop and the knight is not under attack anymore on b8. On e1, it could become an important defender of the king. Diagram'} Ra6 {! Balogh Csaba: '!' '!'} 16. Bxb8 Be6 {The bishop on b8 is now hanging and White has no good way to prevent Black's next move. The bishop on b8 is now hanging and White has no good way to prevent Black's next move. ! This was the point which Black had to foresee before playing 13...a5, or maybe even before 11...b4. Black creates the double threat of Rxb8 and Ba2 and White has no adequate defence against both of them, therefore Black wins back the piece and his attack continues to roll. Balogh Csaba: '!' '!' Balogh Csaba: '! This was the point which Black had to foresee before playing 13...a5, or maybe even before 11...b4. Black creates the double threat of Rxb8 and Ba2 and White has no adequate defence against both of them, therefore Black wins back the piece and his attack continues to roll. This was the point which Black had to foresee before playing 13...a5, or maybe even before 11...b4. Black creates the double threat of Rxb8 and Ba2 and White has no adequate defence against both of them, therefore Black wins back the piece and his attack continues to roll.'} 17. Be5 ({After} 17. d5 Ne4 {Black threatens both the white queen and mate on b2.}) 17... Ba2 18. Qc3 {Of course it is not over yet. In case of Qxb1 Kd2, the queen is trapped. Black finds a strong intermediate move before capturing the knight to send away the queen from the protection of the b2 pawn. Balogh Csaba: 'Of course it is not over yet. In case of Qxb1 Kd2, the queen is trapped. Black finds a strong intermediate move before capturing the knight to send away the queen from the protection of the b2 pawn. Of course it is not over yet. In case of Qxb1 Kd2, the queen is trapped. Black finds a strong intermediate move before capturing the knight to send away the queen from the protection of the b2 pawn.'} b4 {! Balogh Csaba: '!' '!'} 19. Qc7 ({Attacking the black rook doesn't help much as it slides to a better attacking square on the third rank. Attacking the black rook doesn't help much as it slides to a better attacking square on the third rank.} 19. Qd3 {also loses after} Re6 $1 20. Kd2 (20. c3 bxc3 {[%t Shrt] âˆ⇗â + Rc8 next, White cannot hold such an enormous attack. Balogh Csaba: '-+' '-+' Balogh Csaba: '[%t Shrt] âˆ⇗â + Rc8 next, White cannot hold such an enormous attack. Rc8 next, White cannot hold such an enormous attack.'}) 20... Qxb2 $1 {The knight on b1 can wait. Black keeps up the attack rather than falling into a pin after The knight on b1 can wait. Black keeps up the attack rather than falling into a pin after !} ({Balogh Csaba: 'But not'} 20... Bxb1 $2 {?} 21. Nf3 {when suddenly White is winning as 22.Rxb1 follows. when suddenly White is winning as 22.Rxb1 follows. and White wins.}) 21. f4 ({after} 21. Nf3 Rc8 {the threats include 22...Bh6+ 23.Ke1 Bc4, trapping the white queen. the threats include 22...Bh6+ 23.Ke1 Bc4, trapping the white queen. [%t Shrt] âˆ⇗â + with a crushing attack. Balogh Csaba: '-+' '-+'} 22. Ke1 Bxb1) 21... Rd8 22. Nf3 Ng4 $1 23. Bxg7 Nf2 24. Qb5 ({Or} 24. Qf1 Rc8 {and White's defences collapse on c2. and White's defences collapse on c2.}) 24... Ne4+ 25. Kd3 Bxb1 26. Rxb1 Qc3+ 27. Ke2 Qxc2+ {and White is soon mated. and White is soon mated.}) 19... Qxb1+ 20. Kd2 Qxb2 21. Nd3 Qa3 22. Ra1 {It appears that Wei Yi has fought back well as the black queen is in an awkward pin. But now comes a decisive strengthening of Black's attack. It appears that Wei Yi has fought back well as the black queen is in an awkward pin. But now comes a decisive strengthening of Black's attack. Diagram White still had realistic hopes to survive, as the black pieces are temporarily discoordinated. He intends to hide his king on the kingside with Ke2, Rhe1 and Kf1. However the next move destroys all the hopes. Balogh Csaba: 'Diagram White still had realistic hopes to survive, as the black pieces are temporarily discoordinated. He intends to hide his king on the kingside with Ke2, Rhe1 and Kf1. However the next move destroys all the hopes. Diagram White still had realistic hopes to survive, as the black pieces are temporarily discoordinated. He intends to hide his king on the kingside with Ke2, Rhe1 and Kf1. However the next move destroys all the hopes.'} Ne8 $1 {!! A brilliant retreat! The point is to send away the queen from the c-file in order to continue the attack with Qc3 and Bc4! The queen has no good square to leave. Balogh Csaba: '!!' '!!' Balogh Csaba: '!! A brilliant retreat! The point is to send away the queen from the c-file in order to continue the attack with Qc3 and Bc4! The queen has no good square to leave. A brilliant retreat! The point is to send away the queen from the c-file in order to continue the attack with Qc3 and Bc4! The queen has no good square to leave.'} 23. Qc5 {Other moves are also losing:} (23. Qb7 Qc3+ 24. Ke3 Bc4 {[%t Shrt] âˆ⇗â + Balogh Csaba: '-+' '-+'}) (23. Qxe7 Qc3+ 24. Ke3 {Black has several wins, one of them is Balogh Csaba: 'Black has several wins, one of them is Black has several wins, one of them is'} Nd6 25. Bxd6 Qxd4+ 26. Ke2 Rxd6 27. Rxa2 Re6+ {[%t Shrt] âˆ⇗â + Balogh Csaba: '-+' '-+'}) (23. Qc8 Re6 {[%t Shrt] âˆ⇗â + followed by Nd6 next with tempo and Rc8. Balogh Csaba: '-+' '-+' Balogh Csaba: '[%t Shrt] âˆ⇗â + followed by Nd6 next with tempo and Rc8. followed by Nd6 next with tempo and Rc8.'}) 23... Nd6 {A powerful rerouting of the black knight. It wins the c8 square for the rook after which White's defences finally crumble. A powerful rerouting of the black knight. It wins the c8 square for the rook after which White's defences finally crumble. ! This great regrouping of the knight allows Black to occupy the c-file with the rook, which decides the outcome of the game. Balogh Csaba: '!' '!' Balogh Csaba: '! This great regrouping of the knight allows Black to occupy the c-file with the rook, which decides the outcome of the game. This great regrouping of the knight allows Black to occupy the c-file with the rook, which decides the outcome of the game.'} 24. Bxg7 ({Or} 24. Bd5 Qc3+ 25. Qxc3 bxc3+ 26. Kxc3 Bxd5 {and Black has won a piece.}) 24... Rc8 {! Tempo! Balogh Csaba: '!' '!'} 25. Qg5 (25. Qe5 Nc4+ {[%t Shrt] âˆ⇗â + Balogh Csaba: '-+' '-+'}) 25... Kxg7 {The easiest and most human. Black has an extra pawn and leads a crushing attack. It is over now... Balogh Csaba: 'The easiest and most human. Black has an extra pawn and leads a crushing attack. It is over now... The easiest and most human. Black has an extra pawn and leads a crushing attack. It is over now...'} ({Balogh Csaba: 'However the machine shows that'} 25... Rxc2+ 26. Kxc2 Nc4 {[%t Shrt] âˆ⇗â + was even stronger, but there was no need for such a sacrifice. Balogh Csaba: '-+' '-+'}) 26. Rhc1 Qc3+ 27. Ke2 Bc4 28. Kf1 b3 $1 {The queenside pawns have the last word as White's knight is fatally undermined. The queenside pawns have the last word as White's knight is fatally undermined. ! Black wins further material.} 29. Kg1 Bxd3 30. cxb3 {Equal to resignation, as White is a piece down for nothing.} ({Unbearable for white is} 30. cxd3 {does not change anything:} b2 {! Balogh Csaba: '!' '!'} 31. Rxc3 bxa1=Q+ {[%t Shrt] âˆ⇗â + Balogh Csaba: '-+' '-+'}) 30... Qxd4 31. Qxe7 Rxc1+ {White remains a piece down. White remains a piece down. A very nice win by Miroshnichenko. The game does not show the real strength of Wei Yi... Balogh Csaba: 'A very nice win by Miroshnichenko. The game does not show the real strength of Wei Yi... A very nice win by Miroshnichenko. The game does not show the real strength of Wei Yi...'} 0-1


