1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd6 {The queen stays resolutely in the middle of the action. The question is whether White can gain anything worthwhile by harassing her with Nb5 or Bf4 in the future.} 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 g6 {A kind of Scandinavian-Pirc hybrid. You might like to examine Tiviakov- Fedorchuk in the archives for more details.} 6. g3 {A natural response as White's light squared bishop will exert pressure on the queenside on g2 and the black queen can be hunted by his other bishop with Bf4. However as we shall see Black can throw a spanner in the works when it comes to White castling kingside.} ({Instead} 6. Nb5 {gains time for White to play the strategically desirable c2-c4 advance. For example} Qd8 7. c4 (7. Bf4 Na6 {Slightly awkward for Black is} (7... Nd5 8. Be5) 8. c4 {Slightly awkward for Black is} Bg7 9. Be5 O-O 10. Be2 Bh6 11. O-O c6 12. Nc3 Nc7 13. Qb3 Ne6 14. d5 Nf4 15. Rad1 {this sharp position was reached in Dastan, B (2432)-Mamedov, R (2659)/Kocaeli TUR 2014, and now I like} Nd7 $5) 7... c6 8. Nc3 Bg7 9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O Bg4 11. Be3 Nbd7 12. Qb3 {White would have a small plus due to the bishop pair and his extra space after} (12. h3 Bxf3 13. Bxf3) 12... Qc7 13. Rfd1 Rfe8 14. d5 $6 {Evidently Wei Yi doesn't enjoy playing against Black's opening system. It's not too late to get a tiny edge with} (14. h3 Bxf3 15. Bxf3) 14... Bxf3 15. gxf3 {Not an aesthetic recapture. Perhaps White had missed that after} (15. Bxf3 Ne5 16. Be2 Neg4 {the double attack on e3 and h2 is very pleasant for him.}) 15... b6 {So far this is Wei Yi (2638)-Benidze, D (2458)/Kocaeli TUR 2014 and here} (15... Nh5 16. Rd2 Be5 {looks good for Black due to White's fractured kingside.})) 6... Bg7 7. Bg2 Qa6 $5 {The black queen slips away from attack by Bf4 and prevents White castling kingside. Instead} (7... c6 {was preferred in the aforementioned Fedorchuk game.}) 8. Bf4 {Black looks comfortable after a queen exchange for example} (8. Qe2 O-O 9. O-O Qxe2 10. Nxe2 Bf5 11. c3 Be4 {as in Malakhov, I (2441)-Kovalenko, I (2650)/St Petersburg RUS 2014.}) 8... c6 9. Qd2 O-O 10. O-O-O $2 {Leads to trouble. Black is comfortable but no more after} (10. Bh6 {but Black appears to be able to hold his own or more after} Bxh6 11. Qxh6 Bf5 12. O-O-O b5 {for example Sit back and enjoy the attack the attack after} 13. a3 ({Instead} 13. Nh4 {might lead to a sharp draw:} Be6 14. Rhe1 b4 15. Rxe6 bxc3 $1 ({Steering clear of} 15... fxe6 16. Bh3 bxc3 17. Bxe6+ Rf7 18. Nxg6 {when mate on f8 is threatened.}) 16. Nf5 cxb2+ 17. Kb1 gxf5 18. Qg5+ Kh8 19. Rxf6 exf6 20. Qxf6+ Kg8 21. Qg5+ Kh8 {draw!}) 13... b4 $1 14. axb4 Qa1+ 15. Nb1 Na6 16. Nh4 Bxc2 $1 17. Kxc2 Nxb4+ 18. Kd2 Rad8 19. Ke2 Qa6+ 20. Kf3 c5 21. g4 Rxd4 22. Rxd4 cxd4 23. Rd1 Nd3 24. Qd2 e5 25. Kg3 e4 26. f4 Rb8 27. Bf1 Qe6 28. h3 Rb3 {0-1 Berbatov, K (2481) -Chatalbashev, B (2555)/Albena 2010.}) ({Meanwhile} 10. Ne5 Be6 11. Nd3 Nbd7 {looked OK for Black in Akash, G (2404) -Sethuraman, S (2520)/ Kolkata 2012.}) 10... b5 11. a3 $2 {Leads to trouble. Black is comfortable but no more after} (11. Kb1 b4 12. Ne2 Nd5) 11... b4 $1 {A move familiar from the Berbatov game in the notes above. Black gambits a pawn for a big initiative.} 12. axb4 Qa1+ 13. Nb1 a5 $5 ({Black also had an attack after} 13... Nd5 14. Qd3 a5 15. b5 cxb5 16. Ne5 Be6 17. Qa3 Qxa3 18. Nxa3 b4 {in Juggernaut, R (2613) -Wikiman, R (2478)/ playchess.com INT 2007, but White can at least be pleased to have got the queens off!}) 14. b5 {Wei Yi is relying on this move to keep the queenside blocked, but he meets with an unpleasant surprise.} cxb5 $3 15. Ne1 {White decides to take the piece on offer. If he declines he is left in a horrible position as the black queenside pawns will run at his king.} Ra6 16. Bxb8 Be6 {The bishop on b8 is now hanging and White has no good way to prevent Black's next move.} 17. Be5 ({After} 17. d5 Ne4 {Black threatens both the white queen and mate on b2.}) 17... Ba2 18. Qc3 b4 19. Qc7 ({Attacking the black rook doesn't help much as it slides to a better attacking square on the third rank.} 19. Qd3 Re6 $1 20. Kd2 Qxb2 $1 {The knight on b1 can wait. Black keeps up the attack rather than falling into a pin after} (20... Bxb1 $2 21. Nf3 {when suddenly White is winning as 22.Rxb1 follows.}) 21. f4 ({after} 21. Nf3 Rc8 {the threats include 22...Bh6+ 23.Ke1 Bc4, trapping the white queen.} 22. Ke1 Bxb1) 21... Rd8 22. Nf3 Ng4 $1 23. Bxg7 Nf2 24. Qb5 ({Or} 24. Qf1 Rc8 {and White's defences collapse on c2.}) 24... Ne4+ 25. Kd3 Bxb1 26. Rxb1 Qc3+ 27. Ke2 Qxc2+ {and White is soon mated.}) 19... Qxb1+ 20. Kd2 Qxb2 21. Nd3 Qa3 22. Ra1 {It appears that Wei Yi has fought back well as the black queen is in an awkward pin. But now comes a decisive strengthening of Black's attack.} Ne8 $1 23. Qc5 Nd6 {A powerful rerouting of the black knight. It wins the c8 square for the rook after which White's defences finally crumble.} 24. Bxg7 ({Or} 24. Bd5 Qc3+ 25. Qxc3 bxc3+ 26. Kxc3 Bxd5 {and Black has won a piece.}) 24... Rc8 25. Qg5 Kxg7 26. Rhc1 Qc3+ 27. Ke2 Bc4 28. Kf1 b3 $1 {The queenside pawns have the last word as White's knight is fatally undermined.} 29. Kg1 Bxd3 30. cxb3 ({Unbearable for white is} 30. cxd3 b2 31. Rxc3 bxa1=Q+) 30... Qxd4 31. Qxe7 Rxc1+ {White remains a piece down.} 0-1


