1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 dxe5 {This has become a popular move, at least at top level. Black concedes a space advantage but his position is without weaknesses, his queenside pieces are easily developed, and there is no White e-pawn to cramp his kingside.} 5. Nxe5 c6 $1 {You can find many examples of Magnus Carlsen defending this position as Black in the archives. The games are mostly Blitz. But then again you can't be rated 2948 at any time control if your openings aren't at least OK!} 6. Be2 Bf5 7. O-O Nd7 8. c4 $5 {A new move for ChessPub. It's what White would like to play, but can he prove an edge after 8...Nb4, when his queenside looks vulnerable? You can find various other moves discussed in the archives. Compare the present game with} (8. Nf3 e6 9. c4 N5f6 $1 {The best retreat square for the knight in this variation is f6 as it won't be bothered by a white pawn on e5.}) (8. f4 Nxe5 9. fxe5 e6 10. a3 {to rule out Nb4 after the next move.} Be7 11. c4 Nb6 {here the knight falls back to the queenside away from attack by the pawn on e5.}) 8... N5f6 {It is a definite achievement for White if Black goes back with the knight. The critical test is} (8... Nb4 {after which White must not only deal with the threat of 9...Nc2, but also prevent Black from equalising or more with Nxe5 and answering d4xe5 with Qxd1. Another fly in the ointment is Bxb1 and, after Rxb1, the capture Nxa2. So play usually continues} 9. Ng4 e6 ({White gets the initiative upon} 9... Nc2 10. Ne3 $1 Nxe3 11. Bxe3 e6 12. d5 {etc.}) 10. Ne3 Bxb1 {More or less forced as if the bishop goes back to g6 White has 11.a3 chasing the black knight to a6 then 12.Nc3 etc. with a great build up.} 11. Rxb1 Nxa2 12. Bd2 Nb4 {Necessary before the knight is shut in. Now the untried Instead of 13. Bg4,} 13. d5 $2 {has been played at once in four games, but this seems less incisive as it concedes the c5 square to Black's bishop and  (unlike Bg4) doesn't clear the e-file for future action by the white queen or rooks, or put pressure on d7. Play has continued} (13. Bg4 $5 {looks interesting. Black faces a lot of dangers e.g.} Nb6 {the most solid reply, fighting for the d5 square and ruling out any Qa4+ in the future. But here also White can build up strong pressure:} ({If} 13... Nf6 14. d5 $1 Nxg4 {note that Black loses a piece upon} ({Black loses a piece after} 14... cxd5 $2 15. Bxb4 Bxb4 16. Qa4+) ({Or} 14... exd5 15. Qe2 $1 {and suddenly White is winning as Black has no good way to meet a discovered check on the e-file.} Nxg4 ({If} 15... Be7 16. Bxb4 Bxb4 17. Nxd5+ Be7 18. Nxf6+ gxf6 19. Rbd1 Qc7 20. Rd7 {and White wins.}) 16. Nxd5+ Be7 17. Bxb4 cxd5 18. Rfe1 O-O 19. Bxe7 {and Black loses the exchange.}) 15. Qxg4) (13... Be7 14. d5 cxd5 15. cxd5 Nxd5 $2 16. Nxd5 exd5 17. Qa4 $1 {and again White is unexpectedly winning because the pin on d7 means Black can't evacuate his king from the centre.}) 14. Bc3 Be7 15. d5 cxd5 16. Bxg7 Rg8 17. Bc3 dxc4 18. Qf3 {and Black king is in peril as if} N4d5 $2 19. Bh5 {leaves him no good way to defend f7 as if} Rf8 20. Bg7 {wins.}) 13... Bc5 $1 14. dxe6 fxe6 15. Bh5+ ({Or} 15. Bc3 O-O 16. Ng4 Qe7 {completing development with an extra pawn in Alekseenko,K (2317)-Bortnyk,O  (2327) Moscow 2011.}) 15... g6 16. Bg4 Qe7 {and Black was ready to castle queenside with the better chances in Korchmar,V (2214)-Bortnyk, O (2302) Batumi 2010.}) ({After} 8... N5b6 {White could choose between} 9. Nf3 {leaving the black knight worse on b6 than on f6, which is its usual square in the move order 8.Nf3 e6 9.c4 N5f6.} ({Or} 9. f4 {so that after} Nxe5 10. fxe5 e6 {compared to the 8.f4 line the black knight has already been pushed back to b6 so that White doesn't have to spend a move on a2-a3, as is the case after 8.f4 Nxe5 9.fxe5 e6 10.a3 (to stop Nb4 after his next move) 10...Be7 11.c4 Nb6.})) 9. f4 $1 {White plays 9. f4 with the black knight having been tricked to f6! Whereas the knight is on its best square if White continues} (9. Nf3 $6 {when} e6 {transposes to other games in the archives.}) 9... h5 {Black restrains the advance of the g-pawn and so stabilises both his bishop on f5 and his knight on f6 (the horse was liable to attack by g4-g5.)As his knight is on f6 rather than b6 he can't play} (9... Nxe5 $2 {as} 10. fxe5 Bxb1 11. Rxb1 {gives White overwhelming pressure along the f-file.}) ({If} 9... e6 10. g4 $1 {looks strong as after} Bxb1 ({Or} 10... Be4 11. Nc3) 11. Rxb1 {the mobile pawns and bishop pair give White a big initiative.}) 10. Nc3 e6 11. Be3 {White builds up his game step by step. He has kept his space advantage as well as the strong knight on e5. A problem for Black is that for now at least he can't castle kingside without dropping the pawn on h5.} Bd6 12. Bf3 Rc8 13. Qe2 a6 14. a3 {There's no need to hurry. The pawn move prevents any possible counterplay for Black based on} (14. h3 Bb4) 14... Ng4 $1 {Black is virtually in zugzwang. He has run out of constructive moves: every piece is on its optimum square and there are no pawns to push. If he castles he drops the h5 pawn. And so the young Iranian Grandmaster seeks to free his game by offering a pawn.} 15. h3 $5 {Maintaining his grip on the centre, though the exchange of pieces next move helps Black's cramped game. Instead after} (15. Nxg4 $5 hxg4 16. Bxg4 Qh4 17. h3 Bxg4 18. Qxg4 Qxg4 19. hxg4 Nf6 20. g5 Ng4 21. Bd2 Rd8 {it would be hard for White to exploit his extra pawn.}) 15... Nxe3 16. Qxe3 h4 {Fixing the kingside as a prelude to castling.} 17. b4 O-O 18. Rae1 Re8 19. Qf2 Be7 20. Rd1 a5 ({After} 20... Nxe5 21. dxe5 ({Or} 21. fxe5 $5) 21... Qc7 22. c5 Red8 {White has the strong exchange offer} 23. Rd6 $1 {dominating the d-file when} Bxd6 $2 24. cxd6 Qb8 25. Na4 {intending Qb6 and Nc5 looks crushing.}) 21. c5 axb4 22. axb4 Ra8 23. b5 {With Black's bishop on f5 shut off from the queenside the attack on c6 by White's own light squared bishop is potent.} Nxe5 24. fxe5 Ra3 ({After} 24... Qd7 25. Ne4 Bxe4 26. Bxe4 Bg5 27. Qf3 {Black remains in deep trouble due to the weakness of his light squares: c6, f7 and h7.}) 25. Ne4 {he can't stop the white knight getting to d6 as} cxb5 (25... Bxe4 26. Bxe4 Rf8 27. bxc6 bxc6 28. Bxc6 {is hopeless.}) 26. Nd6 Bxd6 27. exd6 {The game is positionally won for White due to the monster on d6. Black's last chance is tricks with his passed b-pawn.} b4 28. d5 e5 29. Bg4 {A faster way to win was} (29. Bh5 g6 30. Bg4 {when Black's bishop is denied the g6 square. For example} Qd7 31. Bxf5 gxf5 32. c6 bxc6 33. dxc6 Qxc6 34. Qxf5 {threatening to push the passed pawn or capture on f7.}) 29... Bg6 30. d7 Rf8 31. c6 f5 32. Qc5 $1 bxc6 {Or} (32... fxg4 33. Rxf8+ {and the d-pawn queens.}) 33. dxc6 Rc3 34. Qd6 {attacking the bishop.} Rf6 ({Or} 34... Bh7 35. Qxe5 {when} fxg4 ({If} 35... Rxc6 {loses the rook to} 36. Qd5+) 36. Qe6+ Kh8 37. Rxf8+ {forces through the d-pawn.}) 35. c7 Rxc7 36. Qxc7 $1 {Winning a rook. The game might have ended here, but we get to see some efficient technique.} Qxc7 37. d8=Q+ Qxd8 38. Rxd8+ Kh7 39. Bd1 Bf7 40. Rb8 e4 41. Rxb4 Kh6 42. Bb3 Bxb3 43. Rxb3 Kg5 44. Rfb1 Rd6 45. Kh2 g6 46. Rb6 {White aims at the g6 pawn, the underbelly of Black's structure.} Rd3 47. Re6 Kh6 48. Rb8 Rg3 49. Re7 Rd3 50. Rh8+ Kg5 51. Re6 e3 52. Rg8 Kf4 53. Rgxg6 Rd4 54. Rh6 1-0


