1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 O-O 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 d5 7. Bg5 dxc4 (7... c5 {is the main alternative - see Wang, H-Grischuk,A/Chess.com 2020.}) 8. Qxc4 b6 9. Rd1 (9. Nf3 {transposes to 7 Nf3.}) ({For} 9. Rc1 {see the notes to Eljanov,P-Lenderman,A/ Tbilisi 2017.}) 9... Ba6 10. Qa4 h6 11. Bh4 Qe7 ({Caruana went for the queen exchange with} 11... Qd7 12. Qc2 Qc6 {but after} 13. Qxc6 Nxc6 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. e3 Bxf1 16. Kxf1 {Carlsen gained an edge and eventually won - see the notes to Carlsen,M-Caruana,F/Stavanger 2020.}) 12. Nf3 Rd8 {*} 13. e3 ({Previously we considered} 13. g4 $5 {in Mamedyarov,S-Sargsyan,S/chess.com 2020, and it hasn't yet been repeated.}) ({On the same day, but two rounds later, Wang Hao tried} 13. Ne5 {- see the notes to Wang,H-Ding,L/Chess.com 2020.}) 13... Bxf1 14. Rxf1 c5 15. dxc5 Rxd1+ 16. Qxd1 g5 {Diagram [#]} ({Previously it was noted that} 16... bxc5 17. Ne5 $5 (17. Qc2 Nbd7 18. Ke2 Rc8 {was level in Mamedyarov,S-Caruana,F/Saint Louis 2018, although White eventually won}) 17... Qc7 18. Bxf6 gxf6 19. Qg4+ Kf8 20. Qe4 (20. Qf3) 20... Qa5+ 21. Kd1 Qd8+ 22. Kc1 Qd5 23. Qxd5 exd5 24. Nd3 $16 {was much better for White in Nechaeva, M-Kashlinskaya,A/ Sochi 2016, and I'd wondered if this was the reason Caruana avoided repeating 11...Qe7 against Carlsen.}) (16... Qxc5 $6 17. Qd8+ $1 {is good for White:} Kh7 18. Bxf6 gxf6 ({or} 18... Qc1+ 19. Ke2 Qc4+ 20. Qd3+ Qxd3+ 21. Kxd3 gxf6 22. Rc1 {with a favourable endgame for White, Volovich, J-Wilks,S/Chess.com 2020}) 19. Qxf6 Qc1+ 20. Ke2 Qc4+ 21. Kd2 $1 Qxf1 22. Qxf7+ Kh8 23. Nh4 {and White wins.}) 17. Nxg5 $146 (17. Bg3 {- 137/182 John Emms: 'is met by Paunovic,Tomislav: '- 137/182''} Qxc5 $1 {This is possible after the insertion of ...g5 and Bg3, as Black doesn't need to fear the queen check.} 18. Qd8+ Kg7 19. Be5 ({White is in danger of being worse after} 19. Bxb8 Qc1+ 20. Ke2 Qxb2+ 21. Nd2 Ne4 {for example,} 22. Be5+ $2 Qxe5 23. Qxa8 Qb5+ $1 24. Ke1 Nc3 $1) 19... Qc1+ 20. Ke2 Qc4+ 21. Ke1 ({White could play on with} 21. Qd3 Qxd3+ 22. Kxd3 Nbd7 {but it looks equal}) 21... Qc1+ 22. Ke2 Qc4+ 23. Ke1 Qc1+ 24. Ke2 {1/2-1/2 Mamedyarov,S-Nakamura,H/Stavanger 2018.}) 17... hxg5 18. Bxg5 {[ Qf3+-]} Nbd7 $8 19. Qf3 ({After} 19. c6 $6 Nf8 $1 {Black can relieve the problem with the pin by ...N8h7.}) 19... Rc8 (19... Rd8 {is also possible, and indeed White must play accurately here:} 20. Qg3 $1 (20. c6 $2 Qc5 $1 21. Bxf6 Nxf6 22. Qxf6 Qc1+ 23. Ke2 Rd2+ {wins for Black}) 20... Kf8 21. c6 Qc5 $1 22. cxd7 Qc1+ 23. Ke2 Qc4+ {John Emms: '=' '=' '=' '=' '=''Paunovic,Tomislav: '=' Paunovic,Tomislav: 'John Emms: '='''} (23... Qc2+ 24. Kf3 $11) 24. Kf3 (24. Ke1 Ne4 $1) 24... Qc6+ 25. Ke2 Ne4 $5 (25... Qc4+ $11) 26. Bh6+ Ke7 27. Bg5+ f6 28. Bxf6+ $1 Kxf6 29. Qh4+ Kg6 30. Qxd8 Qc2+ 31. Kf3 Nd2+ 32. Kg3 Nxf1+ 33. Kf3 $1 (33. Kh3 Qf5+ {mates}) 33... Nxh2+ 34. Kg3 Nf1+ 35. Kf3 $1 {and Black has to give perpetual check.}) 20. c6 Qc5 (20... Ne5 $1 {is another option, and again White has to be careful:} 21. Qxf6 Qc5 $1 22. e4 $1 {(preventing ...Qc1+)} Qd4 $1 23. f3 Rxc6 24. Qd8+ $1 Qxd8 25. Bxd8 Rc2 26. Kd1 Rxg2 27. Bf6 Nd3 {with a likely draw.}) 21. Bxf6 (21. cxd7 Nxd7 {is risky, although} 22. Bf4 $1 Qc1+ 23. Qd1 e5 24. Bg3 Qxb2 25. Qg4+ $1 {saves White, as} Kf8 {can be answered by} 26. Qb4+) 21... Qc1+ {John Emms: 'Wei Yi takes the perpetual check. There are other ways to reach a draw but nothing better.' John Emms: 'Wei Yi's 16...g5 looks stronger than Black's other choices and seems to equalise against 17 Bg3. Wang Hao's novelty 17 Nxg5 is an interesting attempt to imbalance the position, but it doesn't alter the assessment in White's favour. Many lines lead to perpetual checks and in some it feels like White is the one who is having to be more careful.'} 22. Ke2 Qc2+ $11 23. Ke1 Nxf6 (23... Rxc6 24. Qg3+ Kf8 25. Qg7+ Ke8 26. Qh8+ Nf8 27. Bg7 Kd7 28. Qxf8 Qc1+ 29. Ke2 Qc2+ 30. Kf3 Qf5+ $11) 24. Qxf6 Rxc6 25. Qg5+ $11 *


