1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 O-O 5. Bg5 {John Emms: '!?'} c5 {John Emms: '!' John Emms: 'The recommended solution for Black.'} 6. dxc5 {John Emms: 'This line isn't meant to give White anything at all, and Black scores incredibly well. However, nothing gets into Shankland's opening repertoire by chance, and it's often interesting to see what happens when an elite player enters a supposedly discredited line.'} (6. e3 {is covered in Sokolov, I-Ibrahimov,R/Baku 2008.}) 6... Na6 7. a3 Bxc3+ 8. Qxc3 Nxc5 9. Bxf6 {John Emms: '!' John Emms: 'This looks best. The problem for White is that there's no good way to keep the bishop pair, so he may as well exchange the bishop straightaway and at least inflict doubled pawns on Black.'} ({A key point is that} 9. f3 $6 {, typically a desirable way to combat the knight on c5, runs into the tactic} Nfe4 $1 10. Bxd8 Nxc3 11. Be7 Nb3 $1 12. Bxf8 Kxf8 $1 {regaining the exchange with a good position.}) (9. Nf3 Nfe4 $1 {is also at least equal for Black, and maybe more.}) 9... Qxf6 10. Qxf6 gxf6 11. Rd1 {John Emms: 'This is rare.'} (11. b4 {- 100/431} Na4 12. e3 b6 13. Nf3 Ba6 14. O-O-O $5 {(novelty)} (14. Nd2 Rfc8 15. Ne4 Kf8 16. Be2 Ke7 17. Nd2 Rc7 18. e4 Rac8 $17 {Mchedlishvili,M-Gelashvili,T/Tbilisi 2007}) 14... d5 15. cxd5 Rac8+ 16. Kd2 Bxf1 17. Rhxf1 Rfd8 18. Rc1 Rxd5+ 19. Nd4 Rxc1 20. Kxc1 $11) 11... a5 12. e3 {John Emms: 'transposes to the game.'} Na4 ({White's idea is N(g1) -e2-c3, and it's not unreasonable to think that something like} 12... b6 13. Ne2 $1 Bb7 14. Nc3 Rfd8 15. f3 Kf8 16. Kf2 Ke7 17. Be2 {could be a little more comfortable for White. Wei Yi's move interferes with the Ne2-c3 plan.}) ({Another option for Black is} 12... a4 {to fix the queenside.} 13. Ne2 Ra6 14. Nc3 Rb6 15. Rd2 d6 16. Be2 Bd7 17. Rc2 Rc8 18. f3 f5 19. Kf2 f6 20. Rd1 Kf7 21. h3 Be8 22. g4 fxg4 23. hxg4 Rd8 24. Rh1 Kg8 25. Kg3 Bg6 26. e4 Bf7 27. Bd1 Bg6 28. Re2 Rc8 29. Reh2 (29. f4) 29... Ra8 30. Rd2 Kg7 31. Rh4 Kf7 32. Rhh2 Kf8 33. Rh1 Kg7 34. Rh4 Kf7 35. Nb5 Rd8 36. Nc3 Ra8 37. Nb5 Rd8 38. Nc3 Ra8 {1/2-1/2 Keijzer, R-Grau Ribas,J/ICCF email 2016. White was definitely a touch better throughout, and perhaps it's not such a trivial task for Black to defend in an over-the-board game.}) 13. b3 $146 (13. Rb1 Rd8 14. Ne2 d5 15. cxd5 Rxd5 16. b3 Nc5 17. Nc3 Rd8 18. Bc4 Bd7 19. Ke2 Kg7 20. Rhc1 f5 $11 {was Hildebrand,G-Gunkel,W/ email 2009.}) ({Black's idea is to meet} 13. Rd2 {with} Ra6) 13... Nc5 14. b4 Na4 15. Rc1 {John Emms: '!'} ({White is still aiming for Ne2, and then Nf4. However, the immediate} 15. Ne2 $2 Nb2 $1 {is annoying, so Shankland takes prophylactic measures.}) 15... b6 16. Ne2 Bb7 (16... axb4 17. axb4 Ba6 $5 18. Rc2 Rfc8 19. Nd4 d5 20. cxd5 Bxf1 21. Rxf1 {Diagram  [#] Diagram  [#] Diagram [#] Diagram [#]} Nc3 $1 22. Kd2 Nxd5 $11) 17. Nf4 (17. Nd4 Rfc8 18. Be2 Kf8 $11) 17... Rfc8 {John Emms: '!'} 18. Be2 b5 {John Emms: '!' John Emms: 'This turns out to be a clean equaliser.'} (18... Kf8 $5) ({Slower play such as} 18... Rc7 19. Kd2 Rac8 20. Rc2 Kf8 21. Rhc1 {leaves White with a small edge. In some cases the knight on a4 may turn out to be a liability for Black.}) 19. c5 axb4 20. axb4 d6 {John Emms: '!'} 21. Bxb5 dxc5 22. bxc5 (22. Bxa4 Rxa4 23. bxc5 Ba6 $5 $11) 22... Rxc5 23. Rxc5 Nxc5 24. O-O f5 $11 25. h3 Nb3 26. Rd1 Ra1 27. Rxa1 Nxa1 28. Ba4 {John Emms: 'The knight is temporarily corralled by the bishop, but it's easily saved.'} Be4 {John Emms: '!'} 29. g4 (29. Kf1 Nc2 30. f3 $140 Nxe3+ 31. Kf2 Bc2 $15) 29... fxg4 30. hxg4 Bc2 31. Bc6 Nb3 32. Ba4 Na1 {John Emms: '!'} 33. Bc6 Nb3 {John Emms: 'Black certainly isn't in trouble in this line. Despite the poor results for White, however, 5 Bg5 / 6 dxc5 isn't quite as toothless as it looks.'} 1/2-1/2


