1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. Re1 Nd6 6. Nxe5 {Although at first sight it looks harmless, actually such a approach is very popular against Berlin. White enjoys an early lead in development and is trying to profit from that fact.} Be7 7. Bf1 Nxe5 {Another way of playing this line is was seen just few days previously:} (7... Nf5 8. Nf3 O-O 9. d4 d5 10. c3 Bd6 11. Bd3 Nce7 12. Nbd2 c6 13. Nf1 Ng6 14. Qc2 Nfh4 15. Nxh4 Qxh4 16. g3 Qh3 17. f4 Bg4 $6 (17... Ne7 $5 18. Ne3 Re8 19. Qf2 (19. Bd2 Bd7 20. f5 f6 $13) 19... Bf5 $1 $132) 18. f5 Ne7 19. Ne3 Bf3 20. Qf2 Qh5 21. Rf1 $18 {½-½ (36) Anand,V (2784)-Nakamura,H (2787) Zurich (blitz) 2016}) 8. Rxe5 O-O 9. Nc3 Ne8 10. Nd5 {This is a popular position for both sides. White will get the bishop pair but Black will have harmonius development.} Bd6 11. Re1 c6 12. Ne3 Be7 {This is a less common idea, usually the bishop goes to c7:} (12... Bc7 13. Nf5 d5 14. Ne7+ Kh8 15. Nxc8 Rxc8 16. d3 f5 17. Qf3 Nf6 18. Bf4 Bxf4 19. Qxf4 Qc7 20. Qxc7 Rxc7 21. d4 g6 22. Re6 Kg7 23. Rae1 Kf7 24. f3 Rd8 {½-½ (41) Yu Yangyi (2736)-Kramnik,V (2796) Doha 2015. Black is fine.}) 13. c4 Nc7 14. d4 d6 15. g3 Bf6 16. Bg2 g6 17. Qd3 (17. d5 c5 {Black gets a nice version of a Benoni, it is interesting how openings can be transpositional!}) 17... d5 {Black decides to stabilise the centre.} 18. cxd5 cxd5 19. b3 Be6 20. Bb2 {Actually we have seen Karjakin play this from both sides!} (20. a4 Be7 21. Ba3 Bxa3 22. Rxa3 Ne8 23. Rc1 Nf6 24. Ra2 Qd7 25. Rac2 Rfc8 26. h4 h5 27. Qd2 b6 28. Rc3 Qd6 $11 {½-½ (40) Karjakin,S (2762)-Aronian,L (2784) Skopje 2015}) 20... Qd7 21. Rac1 Rac8 22. f4 $1 {Now we have a game, the position gets a different dynamic approach, White is going for the dangereous f5 idea.} Bg7 23. Rc2 Na6 24. Rf2 Nb4 25. Qd1 {I think an alternative was more precise:} (25. Qd2 Nc6 26. f5 gxf5 27. Ref1 Kh8 (27... f4 28. Rxf4 $36) (27... Bh6 28. Nxd5 $1 $14) 28. Nxf5 Rg8 29. Ba3 $14) 25... Nc6 26. f5 gxf5 27. Ref1 Ne7 28. Ba3 Bh6 29. Qd3 Rfe8 30. Bxe7 Qxe7 $6 (30... Bxe3 31. Qxe3 Qxe7 32. Qf4 {Perhaps it is not so terrible for Black after all just a bit passive, White doesn't have an obvious breakthrough.}) 31. Nxf5 Bxf5 32. Rxf5 Qe2 33. Qf3 Qxf3 34. Bxf3 Re7 35. Kg2 Be3 36. Bxd5 Rcc7 {White is better and Black will have a difficult task to defend this.} 37. Rd1 Rc1 38. Rxc1 Bxc1 39. Bc4 Rd7 40. d5 Ba3 41. g4 Kg7 42. Rg5+ Kh8 43. Rh5 Kg7 44. Bd3 h6 45. g5 $1 hxg5 46. Rxg5+ Kh6 47. Rf5 Kg7 48. Kf3 {White somehow for a long time doesn't push his h-pawn which is his best asset to play for a win.} (48. h4 Re7 $1 49. h5 Re3 50. Bb5 f6 51. Bc4 Bc5 52. a4 a6 {Still not that much, but I feel it was better at least to run with the h-pawn.}) 48... Rd6 49. Rg5+ Kh6 50. Kg4 Bc1 51. Re5 Bb2 52. Rh5+ Kg7 53. Rg5+ Kf8 54. Rh5 Kg7 55. Kf4 Rf6+ 56. Ke3 Ba3 57. h4 Bc5+ 58. Ke4 Rf2 59. Ke5 {It looks nice to have the king in the centre, but doesn't really do much.} Rd2 60. Rg5+ (60. Bc4 Rd1 61. Rg5+ Kf8 62. Rf5 Re1+ 63. Kf4 Bd6+ 64. Kf3 Ra1 65. a4 Rh1 66. h5 Kg7 {Black can defend this position.}) 60... Kf8 61. Rg3 Rh2 62. Rg4 Ke7 63. a4 Rh3 64. Bc2 Bd6+ 65. Kf5 Rf3+ 66. Kg5 Be5 67. Rb4 b6 68. h5 Rh3 69. Rc4 Bf6+ 70. Kh6 Be5 71. Kg5 Bf6+ 72. Kh6 Be5 73. Kg5 1/2-1/2


