1. e4 {Stamenkovic,Zoran} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Nd6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {The Berlin endgame is so popular that it is now considered as one of the best defences for Black against 1.e4. Together with the Najdorf Sicilian and the Spanish Marshall Attack they build a trio that gives a serious challenge for White how to claim an advantage after the most dangerous and direct move 1.e4.} 9. h3 h5 10. Nc3 Be7 (10... Ke8 {(Stamenkovic,Zoran) - 129/121}) 11. Bf4 Be6 12. Rad1+ {Stamenkovic,Zoran: 'N'} (12. Ng5 {Stamenkovic,Zoran}) 12... Kc8 {Trying to profit from the fact that White gave a check on d1 one move later than usual.} ({The alternative is considered best, played by all including Anand and the world champion:} 12... Ke8 {I will give here one of the latest examples:} 13. Ng5 Rh6 14. Rfe1 Bb4 15. g4 hxg4 16. hxg4 Ne7 17. f3 Bxc3 18. bxc3 Bxa2 19. Ne4 Rh8 20. e6 Bxe6 21. Bxc7 Nd5 22. Be5 Kf8 {½-½ (65) Vachier Lagrave,M (2788)-Carlsen,M (2851) Stavanger 2016. The world champion got a good position.}) 13. Ng5 Bxg5 14. Bxg5 b6 {In my opinion the alternative looks more to the point.} (14... c5 $1 15. Ne2 b6 16. g4 (16. Rfe1 Kb7 17. a3 Rae8 $132) 16... Bc4 17. Rfe1 hxg4 18. hxg4 Bxe2 19. Rxe2 Nd4 20. Re3 Kb7 {This is fine for Black.}) 15. g4 $1 hxg4 16. hxg4 Nh4 17. Bxh4 Rxh4 18. f3 Kb7 19. Kg2 Rah8 20. Rh1 Rxh1 21. Rxh1 Rxh1 22. Kxh1 {Stamenkovic,Zoran: 'Diagram '} c5 {The alternative is interesting as Black wants to stop the Ne4 idea, it seems that it is possible to do just that.} (22... Bd5 23. Kg2 (23. Nxd5 cxd5 24. f4 Kc6 25. f5 a5 26. Kg2 (26. g5 Kd7 $17) 26... g5 $1 27. Kf3 Kd7 {would lead to an equal pawn endgame.}) 23... Kc8 24. Kg3 g5 {again with equal chances.}) 23. Kg2 Kc6 24. a4 a6 (24... f6 $5 {Stamenkovic,Zoran}) 25. Kg3 b5 26. axb5+ axb5 27. f4 b4 28. Ne4 {This endgame is clearly in White's favor.} Ba2 (28... Bd5 {Stamenkovic,Zoran} 29. Kf3 Ba2 30. f5 Bb1 31. c4 $16) 29. Nd2 (29. Kf3 $5 {(Stamenkovic,Zoran) } Kd5 30. Ke3 Bb1 31. c4+ $1 $16) 29... Kd5 (29... Be6 {Stamenkovic,Zoran} 30. f5 $16) 30. c3 bxc3 (30... g5 31. c4+ Kd4 32. e6 $1 $18) 31. bxc3 g5 {Stamenkovic,Zoran: '?!'} (31... c4 {Stamenkovic,Zoran} 32. Kf3 Bb3 $11) 32. Kf3 {White could have won with a nice idea...} (32. c4+ $1 Kd4 33. e6 $1 $18 {Exellent motiv!}) 32... Ke6 $2 {Stamenkovic,Zoran: 'Diagram ' The alternative would prolonge the game, but the outcome would be the same.} (32... c4 33. Ke3 Ke6 (33... Bb3 {Stamenkovic,Zoran} 34. Ne4 gxf4+ 35. Kxf4 Ba4 36. Ng3 $14) 34. Ne4 gxf4+ 35. Kxf4 Bb1 36. Nc5+ Ke7 37. Ke3 Bc2 38. Kd4 Bd1 39. g5 Be2 40. Kd5 Bf1 41. Kc6 Be2 42. Kxc7 Bf1 43. Kc6 {Coming back wih the king and then having the knight on e3 let's say will win for White.}) 33. c4 $18 {Stamenkovic,Zoran: '+-!' The bishop is trapped and the game is over.} gxf4 34. Kxf4 f6 35. exf6 Kxf6 36. g5+ Kg6 37. Kg4 Kh7 38. g6+ (38. Kh5 {Stamenkovic,Zoran} Kg7 39. g6 c6 40. Kg5 Kg8 {1-0 (41) Wei,Y (2696)-Giri,A (2785) Bilbao 129/120 2016 CI1-130 [Stamenkovic,Zoran]}) 38... Kg7 39. Kg5 c6 40. Kh5 Kg8 41. Kh6 Kh8 {Stamenkovic,Zoran} 42. g7+ Kg8 43. Ne4 Bxc4 44. Nf6+ Kf7 45. g8=Q+ 1-0


