{Jones,Gawain: 'WEI YI HOLDING HIS OWN IN TROMSØ I recently played in my first World Cup in Tromso. While enjoying the experience, I was disappointed to go out in the first round but only after a long match with the young Russian Aleksandr Shimanov. After five draws I lost the second 10+10s/m game. You need luck to go your way in such short matches in a knockout format. I've chosen to examine the following game for a couple of reasons. Wei Yi might not be a name familiar to many readers yet but I'm sure he'll be a star very soon. I was present in Reykjavik earlier this year when he got his final GM norm at the tender age of 13. In the World Cup he won the first two rounds against elite GMs and only got knocked out by Mamedyarov in rapid tiebreaks. Secondly, the Dragon is my beloved opening and so I had added interest following this game.'} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 Nc6 8. Bc4 {Jones,Gawain: 'Nepomniachtchi chooses the most aggressive and direct line, the Yugoslav Attack.'} (8. Qd2 O-O 9. O-O-O d5 {is probably the most topical line where the game is likely to be more positional in nature.}) 8... O-O 9. Qd2 Bd7 10. h4 {Chris Ward: 'White employs the Anti-Chinese variation move order, which of course leaves Black with an option of entering a normal 'Soltis' and that is what he does!'} Rc8 11. Bb3 h5 12. O-O-O Ne5 {Main Line Dragon. I can simply say: an always popular and entertaining opening, despite being extensively analysed for many decades still it has lots of possibilities waiting to be discovered. Main Line Dragon. I can simply say: an always popular and entertaining opening, despite being extensively analysed for many decades still it has lots of possibilities waiting to be discovered.} 13. Bh6 {Chris Ward: 'This move has the second highest appearances on this site behind 13 Bg5 with' not the main move but one of them; it used to be very popular in eighties not the main move but one of them; it used to be very popular in eighties Jones,Gawain: 'White's second most common move but relatively rare at the top level. However, White's approach is very logical and not without venom; he simply wants to get rid of Black's powerful Dragon bishop.' not the main move but one of them; it used to be very popular in eighties} (13. Bg5 Rc5 {this is tabiya. Now White has many moves but one has been most popular: this is tabiya. Now White has many moves but one has been most popular: Jones,Gawain: 'is the mainline of the Soltis Variation, with tons of theory' this is tabiya. Now White has many moves but one has been most popular:} 14. Kb1 {this was always considered critical and with couple of possibilities for Black, some of them used by the author of this text. Its evaluation is changing constantly, but the Dragon is like that. this was always considered critical and with couple of possibilities for Black, some of them used by the author of this text. Its evaluation is changing constantly, but the Dragon is like that.} Re8 (14... b5) (14... a6) (14... a5)) ({Jones,Gawain: 'while'} 13. Kb1 {this is yet another idea which has been played many times Chris Ward: 'closely behind in third. Regards that, hot off the press is' this is yet another idea which has been played many times Jones,Gawain: 'has also also tried but not with great success. Kasparov won an important game against Anand with Black in their World Championship match of 1995.' this is yet another idea which has been played many times} Nc4 14. Bxc4 Rxc4 {with couple of interesting possibilities like: with couple of interesting possibilities like:} 15. b3 (15. Nde2 b5 16. Bh6 {when Black deviated from the Anand-Kasparov World Championship match continuation of 16...Qa5 with} b4 17. Bxg7 Kxg7 18. Nd5 Nxd5 19. exd5 Qa5 20. b3 Rc5 21. g4 {Now} Rfc8 ({Instead} 21... Kg8 $1 {gets the king off a tricky diagonal and sets the clever trap} 22. gxh5 $2 Rxc2 $1 23. Qxc2 Rc8 {with ...Bf5 to follow.}) 22. Qd4+ Kg8 23. Rd2 {left White with the upper hand but} Rc3 $2 {simply didn't work i.e.} 24. Nxc3 bxc3 25. Rd3 Bb5 26. Re3 Be2 27. Ka1 {1-0 (27) Ortiz Suarez, I (2612)-Asis Gargatagli, H (2487) Barbera del Valles ESP 2013}) (15. Nb3) (15. g4 {all of them leading to unclear possibilities all of them leading to unclear possibilities})) 13... Nc4 {Chris Ward: 'The most common continuation aiming to facilitate a doubling of the rooks on the c-file and pressurising of the d4-knight.' Black has another typical idea with which to confront White: Black has another typical idea with which to confront White: Jones,Gawain: 'Wei Yi shows he's well prepared.' Black has another typical idea with which to confront White:} ({Chris Ward: 'You will find quite a bit in the archives on the tempting'} 13... Bxh6 14. Qxh6 Rxc3 15. bxc3 {Chris Ward: 'whilst'} Qa5 (15... Qc7 16. Kb1 a5 17. f4 Nfg4 18. Qg5 a4 19. fxe5 axb3 20. cxb3 Nxe5 21. Qd2 $16 {0-1 (53) Mendez Fortes,E (2316)-Cardenas Ballester,M (2114) Havana CUB 2011}) (15... Qc8 16. g4 $5 hxg4 17. f4 Qxc3 18. Kb1 Nc4 19. Bxc4 Qxc4 20. h5 Qb4+ $4 (20... Be6) ({or} 20... g5 {were necessary.}) 21. Nb3 Be8 22. e5 {1-0, Gonzalez Vidal-Delgado Ramos, Sabadell 2011.}) 16. Kb1 Rc8 17. g4 Qxc3 18. gxh5 Nc4 19. Bxc4 Rxc4 20. Rd3 Qb4+ 21. Nb3 (21. Rb3 Qc5 22. Ne2 Nxh5 23. Rxb7 Rb4+ 24. Rxb4 Qxb4+ 25. Ka1 Bb5 26. Rb1 Qc4 27. Nc1 Qc3+ 28. Rb2 a6 29. Qg5 Qxf3 30. Qxe7 Qd1 $1 (30... Qf4 31. Qg5 $16 {1-0 (60) Kovacevic,A (2548)-Ristic,N (2450) Vrnjacka Banja SCG 2005}) 31. Qd8+ Kg7 32. Qg5 Ng3 $1 $132) 21... Nxh5 22. Rg1 Qb6 23. Qe3 Qxe3 24. Rxe3 Nf4 {½-½ (45) Koskivirta,O (2410)-Volaks,B (2465) ICCF 2002. ½-½ (45) Koskivirta,O (2410)-Volaks,B (2465) ICCF 2002. There is compensation for Black but White is also not without chances to try to convert to the full point his exchange up. There is compensation for Black but White is also not without chances to try to convert to the full point his exchange up.}) (13... Qa5 $5 {awaits further tests.}) 14. Bxc4 Rxc4 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 {Jones,Gawain: 'Diagram [#]'} 16. Kb1 {Chris Ward: 'And this calm waiting move has also been seen a lot in practice although 3 others have also been featured on chesspublishing:' The alternative is very important: The alternative is very important: Jones,Gawain: 'A generic move in Open Sicilians but unlikely to refute the Dragon.' The alternative is very important:} ({Jones,Gawain: 'Last year another strong Russian GM played the critical'} 16. g4 {Chris Ward: 'Not beating about the bush with' Jones,Gawain: '. This pawn sacrifice is always dangerous to deal with. In the words of Bobby Fischer, the way to deal with the Dragon is to 'sac, sac, mate'. However, things aren't so straightforward!'} hxg4 17. h5 Rh8 18. hxg6 fxg6 {Chris Ward: 'well investigated in Anderson, R (2254)-Khachiyan, M (2473) Los Angeles 2003.'} 19. f4 e5 {Jones,Gawain: 'when, in Inarkiev-Yakovich, Vladivostok 2012, White kept the tension with'} 20. Nde2 {Jones,Gawain: 'and a complicated game ensued.'} ({Jones,Gawain: 'White can win the exchange with'} 20. fxe5 dxe5 21. Nde2 (21. Ne6+ Bxe6 22. Qxd8 Rxd8 23. Rxd8 {but following} Nxe4 {Black's passed pawns seem to grant him adequate counterplay.}) 21... Rh3 $1 $13) 20... Rxh1 21. Rxh1 Nxe4 22. Nxe4 Rxe4 23. fxe5 Rxe2 24. Qxe2 Qg5+ 25. Kb1 Qxe5 ({Another good move is: Another good move is:} 25... Bc6 26. Rg1 Bf3 27. Qf2 dxe5 28. Qxa7 g3 29. Qc5 $13 {½-½ (29) Hudák,D (2192)-Piccirilli,F ICCF 2006 ½-½ (29) Hudák,D (2192)-Piccirilli,F ICCF 2006}) 26. Qd2 {after a long sequence of moves that has been played before we come to an interesting type of position after a long sequence of moves that has been played before we come to an interesting type of position} Bc6 27. Qh6+ Kf6 28. Rg1 Bf3 29. Qf8+ Ke6 30. a4 a6 31. b3 Qe2 32. Kb2 Qe5+ 33. Ka2 Kd7 {and Black has enough play and Black has enough play} (33... Qe2 $4 34. Re1 $1 {1-0 (34) Inarkiev,E (2683)-Yakovich,Y (2525) Vladivostok RUS 2012})) (16. Rhe1 {seemingly abandoning a potential kingside attack in favour of focusing in the centre. See Salman, M (2105)-Pogonina, N (2402) Instanbul 2004.}) (16. Nd5 e5 $1 (16... Nxd5 17. exd5 {as in Milos, G (2605)-Hausrath, D (2440) Groningen 1997 leaves Black without a defensive knight and White with potential e-file pressure too.}) 17. Nb3 Nxd5 18. Qxd5 Rc6 {looks absolutely fine for Black as White's knight is on a bad track.}) 16... Qa5 {Chris Ward: 'Regular subscribers will know that the position after'} (16... a6 $5 {has also received a bit of air time on our site with arguably 17 g4!? most critical as seen in Solodovnichenko, Y (2615)-Smith, A (2478) Fagernes NOR 2012.}) 17. Rhe1 {Chris Ward: 'Again opting to focus on the centre with 3 obvious alternatives:' Jones,Gawain: 'Nepomniachtchi decides he's not going to mate Black down the h-file any more, and so centralises his rooks. Now Black has to watch out for e4-e5 breaks.'} (17. g4 {Chris Ward: '!?' '!?'} Rxc3 (17... hxg4 18. h5 {when the standard 18...Rh8 or perhaps 18...Rxc3 were to be recommended but} Nxh5 $2 {got flattened by} 19. Nf5+ $1 Bxf5 20. Rxh5 Rh8 21. Rxh8 Kxh8 22. Qh6+ Kg8 23. Nd5 {1-0 in Kuchatova, N-Vifleemskaia, S Elista RUS-ch (Women) 1996.}) 18. bxc3 Bxg4 $5 19. Rdg1 Bd7 20. Rg5 Qb6+ 21. Ka1 e6 $13) ({Jones,Gawain: 'Hitting White's queen with'} 17. Nb3 {Chris Ward: 'offers Black a number of queen options with' Jones,Gawain: 'is the alternative. After'} Qc7 {Chris Ward: 'being most popular. Then' Jones,Gawain: ','} 18. g4 {Chris Ward: 'looks most challenging with' Jones,Gawain: 'is again the most dangerous approach and has been played a couple of times recently by Ukrainian IM and WGM Inna Gaponenko. I believe Black should be OK but again this is a more dynamic approach.'} Rxc3 (18... hxg4 19. h5 Rxc3 (19... gxf3 20. hxg6 fxg6 21. Rdg1 {saw Black omit the exchange sac with} Kf7 {when} 22. Qg5 Ke8 23. Qxg6+ Kd8 {could also have gone either way but after} 24. Qg7 $6 Re8 25. Rf1 Rxc3 $1 26. bxc3 Qxc3 27. Qg3 Nxe4 28. Qxf3 Bc6 {Black was clearly better in Webb, R (2290)-Mah, K  (2365) Highgate 1997.}) 20. hxg6 fxg6 21. bxc3) 19. bxc3 hxg4 20. h5 gxf3 (20... Rc8 21. hxg6 fxg6 22. Qh6+ Kf7 23. Rd3 $1 Qb6 24. fxg4 Bxg4 {all in all probably favoured White in Stets, D (2390)-Brunner, N (2435) Chambery 2007.}) 21. hxg6 fxg6 {Chris Ward: 'offering chances for both sides in Gaponenko, I (2404)-Dolzhikova, K (2313) Kharkov 2012.'} 22. Rdg1 (22. Qh6+ Kf7 23. Rd3 Bg4 24. Nd4 Rg8 $5 (24... Qc4 25. Nxf3 Bxf3 26. Rxf3 Qxe4 27. Rff1 Rg8 28. Re1 Qc6 29. Rhf1 Qd7 30. c4 g5 $13 {½-½ (60) Ivanovic,Z (2241)-Elíson,K (2348) ICCF 2005 ½-½ (60) Ivanovic,Z (2241)-Elíson,K (2348) ICCF 2005}) 25. Nxf3 Ke8 26. Re1 Nd7 $13) 22... Kf7 $5 (22... Ng4 23. Rxg4 Bxg4 24. Qh6+ Kf7 25. Qf4+ Kg7 26. Qh6+ Kf7 27. Qh7+ Kf6 28. Qh4+ Kg7 29. Qh7+ Kf6 30. Qh4+ Kg7 31. Qxg4 Qxc3 32. Qh4 Kf7 33. Qg5 Ke8 $14 {1-0 (50) Gaponenko,I (2404)-Dolzhikova,K (2313) Kharkiv UKR 2012}) 23. Rg3 Bg4 24. Qg5 Bh5 25. Rxh5 gxh5 26. Qg6+ Ke6 27. Nd4+ (27. Qf5+ Kf7 $11) 27... Kd7 28. Qf5+ Ke8 29. Ne6 Qb6+ 30. Ka1 Rh8 31. Rg7 Rh6 $13) (17. Nd5 Qxd2 18. Rxd2 Nxd5 19. exd5 Rfc8) 17... Rfc8 18. Qe3 {Chris Ward: 'A novelty and frankly a difficult move to explain. Possibly White wants to move his c3-knight without trading queens, possibly he is looking to get in e4-e5 or possibly he is looking to bolster everything with Rd3. Whatever, it doesn't seem to cause Black many problems although then again the alternatives don't look that threatening either:' We came to a position where White doesn't go for an immediate attack, but simply tries to base his play on a more advanced and solid structure where the d5-square plays a key role in his seeking an advantage. We came to a position where White doesn't go for an immediate attack, but simply tries to base his play on a more advanced and solid structure where the d5-square plays a key role in his seeking an advantage.} (18. Nd5 Qxd2 $1 (18... Qd8 19. Nxf6 exf6 20. c3 $14 {1-0 (36) Zezulkin,J (2494)-Szefer,M (1980) Warsaw POL 2005}) 19. Rxd2 Nxd5 20. exd5 Kf8 $11 (20... Kf6 {which was about equal but Black went on to win in Kalod, R (2483)-Macieja, B (2536) Presov 2000.})) (18. Nb3 Qa6 19. e5 dxe5 20. Rxe5 b5 (20... e6 {was a solid alternative, but the text looks more interesting.}) 21. Rxe7 b4 22. Ne4 Rxc2 23. Qg5 Bf5 24. Nd4 R2c5 25. Nxf5+ Rxf5 26. Qe3 Rd5 {and as 27 Rxd5?? wasn't possible in view of 27...Qf1+, Black held a slight edge in Apicella, M (2465)-Alterman, B (2585) Cap d'Agde 1994.}) (18. Re3 a6 (18... Be6 19. Nce2 Qxd2 20. Nxe6+ fxe6 21. Rxd2 Nd7 22. b3 R4c5 23. Kb2 Kf6 {was pretty equal in Wegener, D (2344)-Doberitz, P (2220) Germany 2010.}) 19. Qe1 Qe5 20. Red3 b5 21. g3 b4 22. Nce2 d5 {with initiative Black in Grichkevitch, G (2275)-Komljenovic, D (2485) Las Palmas 1995.}) 18... a6 {Chris Ward: 'Nothing much going down and so Black is in no hurry.'} ({Jones,Gawain: 'As a Dragon player I'd be itching to play'} 18... Rxc3 {Jones,Gawain: 'but it seems White has some edge after'} 19. bxc3 Rxc3 20. Rd3 (20. Nb3 Qc7 21. Qxa7 Rxc2 22. Rc1) 20... Rc4 21. Nb3 Qc7 22. Qd2 $14) 19. Re2 {There was another way to conduct this position: There was another way to conduct this position: Jones,Gawain: 'A mysterious move but White is struggling for a plan.' There was another way to conduct this position:} (19. Rd3 $5 Qc5 20. Qd2 b5 21. Nd1 {[%cal Gd3d7]} e5 22. Nb3 Qc7 23. Ne3 d5 24. exd5 Rxh4 25. Rc3 Qd6 26. Rxc8 Bxc8 27. Rf1 {with interesting play ahead of us possibly in White's favour due to the slight;y clumsy position of the black rook. with interesting play ahead of us possibly in White's favour due to the slight;y clumsy position of the black rook.}) 19... Qc5 {Jones,Gawain: 'Black is keeping an eye on the e5 square while a g4 advance is hardly going to work with the rook on e2 rather than h1.'} (19... Qe5 {was equally a candidate, both queen moves equally getting her majesty more onside before deploying ...b5.}) (19... Rxc3 $5 {should again be considered but Wei Yi prefers to keep the tension and ask White exactly how he's going to continue.}) ({I think White's last was aimed against} 19... e5 {as then White can play} 20. Nb3 Qc7 21. Red2 {although Black is at least fine after} Rc6 {as White has no way to increase the pressure on the backward d-pawn. In fact, had Wei Yi been playing a lower-rated opponent, it's likely this is how he would have continued.}) 20. Qd2 Qa5 ({Or} 20... Qb4 {and upon} 21. a3 {then} Qa5 {, both sequences challenging White to try and make progress which in turn is a department that White is being far from convincing in.}) 21. Qd3 Qe5 22. Qe3 Qc5 {Chris Ward: 'All thrills and spills then-NOT!'} 23. Rdd2 {Chris Ward: 'So, White has well over-protected c2 and has vacated the d1-square for his knight but it doesn't look impressive.' Jones,Gawain: 'Declining the repetition but hardly riveting.'} b5 ({It seems} 23... e5 $1 {would be the better move order.}) 24. Nd1 $6 {Jones,Gawain: 'Diagram [#] The young Russian is trying to keep the game going but it's a bad practical decision as he has had to go so passive.'} ({Chris Ward: 'Surely White had to dabble in'} 24. Nd5 {Chris Ward: '!?' '!?' Chris Ward: 'but only if after' Jones,Gawain: '!' Jones,Gawain: 'was White's last chance to hold equality:'} e5 (24... Nxd5 25. exd5 Re8 (25... Qxd5 {he employs the typical computer style move} 26. Qg1 $1 {Yes, he can't take on e7 with the queen due to ...Rxd4 but the retreat would threaten to take that pawn with the rook whilst bringing into play discovered attacks against the black queen.}) 26. b3 (26. g4) 26... Rc3 27. Qg5 f6 (27... e5 28. dxe6 fxe6 29. Qxc5 Rxc5 {with a roughly level ending.}) 28. Qg3 $36) 25. Nb3 Qxe3 26. Nxe3 R4c6 27. Na5 Rb6 28. c3 Be6 29. Re1 Ne8 30. Nc2 {[%cal Gc2b4] with a still playable position with a still playable position}) 24... e5 $1 {Jones,Gawain: 'This is often a good move in the Dragon once the g7 bishop has been traded. Now the structure resembles a Najdorf. Some players might worry about the backward d-pawn but Black can defend it adequately. Grabbing central control is more than worth a temporary backward pawn.'} 25. Nb3 (25. Nf5+ {is nothing after is always the move you have to watch out for, but here} Bxf5 $1 (25... gxf5 $2 26. Qg5+) 26. exf5 Qxe3 27. Nxe3 Rxh4 {but now Black is starting to take over the initiative.} 28. Rxd6 e4 {gives Black a good endgame advantage.}) 25... Qc7 26. Qg5 {Chris Ward: 'An aggressive post for the white queen, but she is the only attacker. Meanwhile Black's pieces are far better coordinated.'} Be6 27. Qg3 ({Chris Ward: 'Observe'} 27. Ne3 {Chris Ward: '?' '?'} Rxe4 $1 $19 {Chris Ward: '!' '!' Chris Ward: 'as after'} 28. fxe4 Nxe4 {the white queen is trapped. That tactic explains the white queen withdrawal.}) 27... a5 {Chris Ward: 'Black though quite rightly continues with his queenside action.' Jones,Gawain: 'Black's position plays itself while White is still struggling for a plan.'} 28. Ne3 Rb4 {Risky as the black rook is slightly awkwardly placed. Risky as the black rook is slightly awkwardly placed. Jones,Gawain: 'This square for the black rook looks a bit strange to me.' Risky as the black rook is slightly awkwardly placed.} (28... Rc6 $1 29. Nc1 b4 $15) (28... a4 $1 {was a powerful alternative:} 29. Nc1 (29. Nxc4 bxc4 30. Nc1 c3 {and Black's attack crashes through.}) 29... a3 30. b3 (30. Nxc4 bxc4 {again gives Black a powerful initiative.}) 30... Rc3 {and Black is better but perhaps White is holding.}) 29. Qe1 $1 ({Black's last move carried with it a serious threat as highlighted by the variation} 29. Nf5+ Bxf5 30. exf5 a4 31. Nc1 a3 32. b3 $2 Qc3 33. Nd3 e4) 29... Qb6 {Jones,Gawain: 'Slight hesitancy.'} ({Again,} 29... a4 {looks more natural.}) 30. Nc1 (30. Qd1 $1 Rc6 31. c3 Ra4 32. Nc1 Nd7 33. b3 b4 34. c4 Ra3 35. Nc2 Bxc4 36. bxc4 Rc3 $13) ({After} 30. c3 {Wei Yi wouldn't have hesitated to give up the exchange with} Rxb3 31. axb3 Bxb3 {when Black dominates on the light squares. However, the game continuation loses control of yet another square.}) 30... Rd4 $5 {Escaping. Escaping. Jones,Gawain: 'Wei Yi is quick to exploit this.' Escaping.} 31. Rxd4 exd4 32. Nd1 b4 {Jones,Gawain: 'It's evident here that Black's attack is always going to be faster than White's. However, he does have to be careful the d4 pawn doesn't drop before he can get his attack to land.'} 33. Qf2 d5 {Chris Ward: '!' '!' Chris Ward: 'If the black knight gets in on the act then there is big trouble.' Jones,Gawain: '!' Jones,Gawain: 'There's a saying that if Black manages to play ...d5 in the Sicilian then he has at least equalised. Wei Yi must have seen the idea on move 36 while playing this.'} 34. e5 Nd7 {Chris Ward: 'Now the white e-pawn has advanced, one simple black plan is ...Bf5 followed by ...a4 and ...b3.'} 35. Nb3 Rc4 {Chris Ward: 'The d4-pawn is protected but this rook has other ambitions besides.'} 36. Rd2 {Jones,Gawain: 'Diagram [#] Now if White gets time to play Nxd4 then he'll suddenly have control of the position. However, Wei Yi finds'} d3 $1 37. cxd3 $6 (37. Qxb6 $1 {Jones,Gawain: 'was the alternative but Black has a pleasant endgame advantage after'} dxc2+ 38. Rxc2 Nxb6 39. Rxc4 Nxc4 40. Kc1 Bc8 41. f4 Bg4 42. Nf2 Bf5 $11) 37... Qxf2 38. Rxf2 {Jones,Gawain: '?' Jones,Gawain: 'Perhaps the players were in time trouble here but this is a big error.'} ({He had to play} 38. Nxf2 Rxh4 39. d4 a4 40. Na5 Bf5+ 41. Kc1 {when White seems to be just about holding.}) 38... Bf5 {Jones,Gawain: '!' Jones,Gawain: 'This intermezzo move must have come as an unpleasant surprise.'} 39. Rd2 a4 $17 (39... Rxh4 40. Ne3 (40. Nxa5 Nxe5 {would see Black bossing.})) 40. Ne3 Rxh4 {Chris Ward: 'would transpose.'} ({Of course not} 40... axb3 $2 41. Nxf5+ gxf5 42. dxc4) 41. Nc1 (41. Nxf5+ gxf5 {would see Black's pawn structure compromised but the white knight still has to retreat and} 42. Nc1 Nxe5 {would still leave Black a pawn up with by far the more active position.}) 41... Nxe5 42. Nxd5 {Jones,Gawain: 'Diagram [#] So material is still level but Black's activity coupled with White's weak pawns means that Black's advantage is decisive.'} b3 {Chris Ward: 'Black is doing very well and here both'} (42... Rd4 {pounding that d3-pawn and}) (42... Rh2 {seemingly pressurising g2 but also threatening ...Nxf3, look very convincing. , threatening to take on f3, is the computer's suggestion but Wei Yi prefers to trap White's king.}) 43. axb3 axb3 44. Ne3 ({The black b-pawn was out of bounds i.e.} 44. Nxb3 $2 Bxd3+ 45. Kc1 ({or} 45. Ka2 Ra4#) 45... Rh1+ 46. Rd1 Rxd1+ 47. Kxd1 Bc4 {forking the white knights.}) 44... Rh1 $19 {Chris Ward: 'But now White is in a world of pain!'} 45. Rd1 {Jones,Gawain: '?'} (45. Nxf5+ {is also very unpleasant but had to be tried.}) 45... Bxd3+ {Jones,Gawain: '!' Jones,Gawain: 'Now it's over.'} 46. Ka1 Rxd1 47. Nxd1 f5 {Chris Ward: 'A pawn up with the white king out of commission and Black is easily winning.'} 48. f4 Bc2 49. Ne3 Nd3 50. Ne2 h4 51. Nd4 Ne1 52. Ne6+ Kh6 53. Ng5 Be4 54. Nxe4 fxe4 55. Kb1 Kg7 {Jones,Gawain: 'With ...Nxg2 coming next move, White resigned. A good win from Wei Yi and I'm sure we'll hear more about him very soon.'} (55... Nxg2 56. Nxg2 h3 57. Ne3 {would actually have won but not immediately with} h2 $4 58. Ng4+ {.Instead the black king retreat takes that check out of the equation so that ...Nxg2 will be instantly decisive.}) 0-1


