1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 Be7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. O-O d5 6. b3 b6 7. Bb2 Bb7 8. e3 c5 (8... Nbd7 9. Nc3 ({Kasparov suggests} 9. Qe2 $5 {to avoid Black's next move}) 9... Ne4 $1 {(the exclamation mark is Kasparov's) is a rare but logical continuation, looking to trade a pair of knights and, possibly, dark-squared bishops. This position has been wonderfully analysed by Marin and Kasparov and rather than reproducing their notes here I would urge interested readers to consult the original sources. Lines are: Sam Collins: '(the exclamation mark is Kasparov's) is a rare but logical continuation, looking to trade a pair of knights and, possibly, dark-squared bishops. This position has been wonderfully analysed by Marin and Kasparov and rather than reproducing their notes here I would urge interested readers to consult the original sources. Lines are:'} 10. cxd5 {, M.Marin-Y.Kryvoruchko, Reykjavik 2015, is wonderfully analysed by Marin in Chessbase Magazine #170. Sam Collins: ', M.Marin-Y.Kryvoruchko, Reykjavik 2015, is wonderfully analysed by Marin in Chessbase Magazine #170.'} (10. Ne2 {was Kasparov's choice in the final, 24th game of his 1987 World Championship match against Karpov, as evocatively annotated in 'Garry Kasparov on Modern Chess Part Three: Kasparov vs. Karpov 1986-1987'. Karpov chose the unfortunate Sam Collins: 'was Kasparov's choice in the final, 24th game of his 1987 World Championship match against Karpov, as evocatively annotated in 'Garry Kasparov on Modern Chess Part Three: Kasparov vs. Karpov 1986-1987'. Karpov chose the unfortunate'} a5 $6 {and ended up losing a heartbreaking technical display.} ({Makarychev suggests} 10... Bf6 11. d4 c5 {“with an excellent game” Sam Collins: '"with an excellent game"'}) ({while Taimanov's} 10... c5 11. d3 Bf6 12. Qc2 Bxb2 13. Qxb2 Qf6 {also looks fully playable for Black. Sam Collins: 'also looks fully playable for Black.'}))) 9. Nc3 Nc6 {'Sam Collins: 'Black develops his pieces rapidly to their most active squares. Because of some small problems after White's next move, many black players have preferred alternative setups, although it is notable that Dominguez chose this line with Black in an important blitz game against Wesley So.''} 10. cxd5 {'Sam Collins: '!' Sam Collins: 'Black faces a choice on this and the next move, namely whether to endure some tactical discomfort on the long diagonal  (by taking with pieces) or a minor structural disadvantage by taking with the pawn. All options are playable and it's a matter of taste, but I believe White has the better chances in most lines.''} Nxd5 (10... exd5 {makes sense since in the arising structures (where Black has a potential isolated queen's pawn or hanging pawns), Black often relies on dynamic play and having more pieces on the board is consistent with this aim. Sam Collins: 'makes sense since in the arising structures (where Black has a potential isolated queen's pawn or hanging pawns), Black often relies on dynamic play and having more pieces on the board is consistent with this aim.'} 11. d4 Ne4 (11... Re8 12. Rc1 {was more pleasant for White in N.Vitiugov-D.Frolyanov, Olginka 2011 Sam Collins: 'was more pleasant for White in N.Vitiugov-D.Frolyanov, Olginka 2011'}) 12. dxc5 Nxc3 13. Bxc3 bxc5 14. Qe2 Re8 $2 (14... Qb6 {is a better try}) 15. Rfd1 Bf8 16. Qb5 Qb6 17. Qxb6 axb6 18. Rxd5 Nd4 19. Nxd4 Bxd5 20. Bxd5 cxd4 21. Bxd4 {White was better and went on to win a model game in V.Kramnik-G.Jones, London 2012. Sam Collins: 'White was better and went on to win a model game in V.Kramnik-G.Jones, London 2012.'}) 11. Nxd5 Qxd5 (11... exd5 12. d4 {(E.Cordova-Y.Quesada Perez, Merida 2013) leaves White with a better structure but Black has good development. In my book on the Tarrasch I recommended Sam Collins: '(E.Cordova-Y.Quesada Perez, Merida 2013) leaves White with a better structure but Black has good development. In my book on the Tarrasch I recommended'} a5 $5 {, which I tested against Gawain Jones in Bunratty 2016. After Sam Collins: ', which I tested against Gawain Jones in Bunratty 2016. After'} 13. dxc5 bxc5 14. Ne5 Nxe5 15. Bxe5 Ra6 $5 16. Qc2 Qa8 17. Rfd1 a4 18. Qf5 {, instead of my} axb3 {,} ({Jacob Aagaard recommended} 18... Rd8 {, when Black isn't worse.})) 12. d4 {*'Sam Collins: 'White's next move is likely to be Ne5, while dxc5 is also a significant idea. Black has a wide choice.''} Qf5 {'Sam Collins: 'This has come into fashion and is the simplest route to a sound position.''} ({Instead: a) Sam Collins: 'Instead: a)'} 12... Qd8 {is quite passive; e.g.} 13. dxc5 ({White hardly needs an improvement here but Sam Collins: 'White hardly needs an improvement here but'} 13. Ne5 {is another option, for example} Nxe5 14. Bxb7 Rb8 15. Bg2 cxd4 16. exd4 Nd7 17. d5 exd5 18. Qxd5 Bf6 19. Rad1 Bxb2 20. Qxd7 a5 21. Rfe1 Qxd7 22. Rxd7 {and White ground out a win after further adventures in V.Kramnik -T.Radjabov, Kazan 2011 Sam Collins: 'and White ground out a win after further adventures in V.Kramnik -T.Radjabov, Kazan 2011'}) 13... Bxc5 14. Ne5 Nxe5 15. Bxb7 Rb8 16. Be4 Nd7 17. b4 Be7 18. Qa4 {was much better for White in D.Reinderman-T.Gharamian, Belgium 2017, A.Moskalenko-A.Zabotin, Orsha 2019, and several other games. White has the bishop pair and a strong initiative for free. Sam Collins: 'was much better for White in D.Reinderman-T.Gharamian, Belgium 2017, A.Moskalenko-A.Zabotin, Orsha 2019, and several other games. White has the bishop pair and a strong initiative for free.'}) ({b)} 12... Rad8 {is the traditional main line, leaving Black a principled choice after Sam Collins: 'is the traditional main line, leaving Black a principled choice after'} 13. Ne5 {: Sam Collins: ': The most popular move is'} {The most popular move is} Qd6 (13... Qxg2+ $5 {is a remarkable queen sacrifice which has been used to gain draws against Kramnik and Ehlvest. After Sam Collins: 'is a remarkable queen sacrifice which has been used to gain draws against Kramnik and Ehlvest. After'} 14. Kxg2 Nxe5+ 15. f3 {and now} cxd4 {is the main try;} ({but} 15... Ng4 16. Qe2 cxd4 17. exd4 Nf6 {was tested in the stem game M.Andrijevic-M.Jovicic, Belgrade 1980. Since Black is trying to erect a fortress White's most principled approach is to open lines with Sam Collins: 'was tested in the stem game M.Andrijevic-M.Jovicic, Belgrade 1980. Since Black is trying to erect a fortress White's most principled approach is to open lines with'} 18. a4 Nd5 19. a5 {. This is assessed as winning by the engines, although admittedly not with a significantly higher evaluation than after 15...cxd4. However, White seems to have more prospects here than after 15...cxd4 and, in any event, 15...Ng4 has been completely abandoned. Sam Collins: '. This is assessed as winning by the engines, although admittedly not with a significantly higher evaluation than after 15...cxd4. However, White seems to have more prospects here than after 15...cxd4 and, in any event, 15...Ng4 has been completely abandoned.'}) {In his notes to Morozevich-Bologan, Marin gives one of his blitz games, which proceeded Sam Collins: 'In his notes to Morozevich-Bologan, Marin gives one of his blitz games, which proceeded'} 16. Bxd4 $5 (16. exd4 Nc6 {and your engine will assess this as totally winning for White, but in fact Black's positional compensation makes the position unclear (although the play is for two results) Sam Collins: 'and your engine will assess this as totally winning for White, but in fact Black's positional compensation makes the position unclear (although the play is for two results)'} 17. Rc1 {and now Black has tested several moves:} (17. Qe2 Rd5 18. Rac1 Rfd8 {was tried in J.Ehlvest-H.Nakamura, St Louis 2009; after} 19. Rc4 Ba6 20. Qe4 Bxc4 21. bxc4 R5d6 22. Rd1 Bf6 23. Ba3 Rxd4 24. Rxd4 Nxd4 {White was unable to break through Sam Collins: 'White was unable to break through'}) 17... Bf6 (17... Rd5 18. Rc4 b5 19. Rc2 Bd6 20. Qe2 Ne7 21. Rfc1 Rf5 {and now: Sam Collins: 'and now: Marin's suggestion'} {Marin's suggestion} 22. d5 $1 {is strong, e.g.} (22. Bc3 $6 {was A.Morozevich-V.Bologan, Poikovsky 2014. Now Marin suggests} Bxf3+ (22... h5) 23. Qxf3 Rxf3 24. Kxf3 h5 25. Ba5 g5 26. Bc7 Ba3 {. This is a more understandable material balance (a pawn for the exchange) where Black appears to have good drawing chances since he retains his rook for the moment and his knight will have a stable square on d5. Sam Collins: '. This is a more understandable material balance (a pawn for the exchange) where Black appears to have good drawing chances since he retains his rook for the moment and his knight will have a stable square on d5.'}) 22... Bxd5 (22... Nxd5 23. Kg1 $1) 23. Kg1 Bxf3 24. Qd3 {, for example} Bd5 ({more tenacious than Marin's} 24... Nd5 {, which loses immediately to} 25. Rc8) 25. Qxb5 Be4 26. Qa6 Rd5 27. Rf2 {(as given by Demuth) and the asymmetrical pawn majorities are inconsistent with Black's desired fortress. Sam Collins: '(as given by Demuth) and the asymmetrical pawn majorities are inconsistent with Black's desired fortress.'}) (17... Rd7 {seems less principled since White retains the option of sacrificing his d-pawn. Sam Collins: 'seems less principled since White retains the option of sacrificing his d-pawn.'} 18. a3 (18. d5 Rxd5 19. Qe2 Nb4 20. Rfd1 Ba6 21. Qe4 Bd3 $2 22. Qg4 g6 23. Qf4 {with a decisive attack in S.Azaladze-A.Nadanian, Batumi 2015}) 18... Rfd8 19. Qe2 Bf6 20. b4 e5 (20... Ne7 21. d5 Bxb2 22. Qxb2) 21. d5 Rxd5 22. Rfd1 Nd4 23. Bxd4 exd4 24. Rc7 Bc8 {was V.Kramnik-M.Ezat, Antalya 2013 and now Marin gives} 25. Qc4 Be6 26. Qa6 d3 27. Rd2 Bg5 28. f4 Bf6 29. Rxa7 Bf5 {(?)} 30. Ra8 Be4+ 31. Kf1 {as winning for White.}) 18. Rc4 Rd7 ({opening lines with} 18... Nxd4 {is rejected by Marin based on} 19. Qa1 e5 20. Rc7 Ba6 21. Rf2 {when the black queenside is vulnerable and, of the fortress variations, this one seems more brittle to me, although a lot of analysis would be required to definitively assess the position Sam Collins: 'when the black queenside is vulnerable and, of the fortress variations, this one seems more brittle to me, although a lot of analysis would be required to definitively assess the position'}) 19. Qc2 Ne7 20. Rc7 Rfd8 21. Rxd7 Rxd7 22. Kf2 Nd5 23. a3 h5 24. h4 g6 {and in A.Mikaelyan-A.Nadanian, Jermuk 2014 White won after a king march to the queenside (preparing the g4 break). Sam Collins: 'and in A.Mikaelyan-A.Nadanian, Jermuk 2014 White won after a king march to the queenside (preparing the g4 break).'}) 16... Nxf3 17. Rxf3 e5 18. Rc1 exd4 19. exd4 {and now: Sam Collins: 'and now: Demuth gives'} {Demuth gives} Bxf3+ (19... Bc5 20. dxc5 $5 Rxd1 21. Rxd1 bxc5 22. Rd7 Bxf3+ 23. Kxf3 {was M.Marin-T.Gelashvili, World Chess Network (blitz) 2003). As Marin notes, despite Black's (temporary) extra pawn, this endgame is difficult for him. Sam Collins: 'was M.Marin-T.Gelashvili, World Chess Network (blitz) 2003). As Marin notes, despite Black's (temporary) extra pawn, this endgame is difficult for him.'}) ({The analysts have differed in their suggested alternatives here. Marin gives Sam Collins: 'The analysts have differed in their suggested alternatives here. Marin gives'} 19... Bf6 20. Rc7 (20. Kh3 $1 Bxf3 21. Qxf3 Bxd4 {is stronger, when Black retains hopes of building a fortress Sam Collins: 'is stronger, when Black retains hopes of building a fortress'}) 20... Rxd4 21. Qc1 {as slightly better for White.}) 20. Kxf3 Rd7 {with prospects of a fortress. Compared to 19...Bf6, I don't know how to assess this variation, where White retains his d-pawn. This pawn blocks the d-file (for both sides) and its route to d8 is very well controlled by the black pieces, so it seems to me that White's winning chances are roughly equivalent in both lines. Sam Collins: 'with prospects of a fortress. Compared to 19...Bf6, I don't know how to assess this variation, where White retains his d-pawn. This pawn blocks the d-file  (for both sides) and its route to d8 is very well controlled by the black pieces, so it seems to me that White's winning chances are roughly equivalent in both lines.'}) 14. dxc5 $1 (14. Rc1 Nxe5 15. Bxb7 {, V.Ivanchuk-M.Carlsen, Cap d'Agde 2008, is less ambitious though Black still needs to be precise to equalise completely Sam Collins: ', V.Ivanchuk-M.Carlsen, Cap d'Agde 2008, is less ambitious though Black still needs to be precise to equalise completely'}) 14... Qxc5 15. Nd7 $1 {. This position is wholly unpromising for Black and, over 40+ games, White has scored very heavily. Marin gives a very detailed coverage but I have sought only to give the key variations since it's a bad line for Black and White has alternatives along the way. Sam Collins: '. This position is wholly unpromising for Black and, over 40+ games, White has scored very heavily. Marin gives a very detailed coverage but I have sought only to give the key variations since it's a bad line for Black and White has alternatives along the way.'} Qg5 $2 (15... Qf5 16. e4 Qg5 17. h4 Qh6 18. Bc1 g5 19. hxg5 {and now:} Bxg5 (19... Qg7 20. e5 Kh8 (20... Nb8 21. Nf6+ Bxf6 22. exf6 Rxd1 23. Rxd1 $1 Qg6 24. Bxb7 {with overwhelming compensation for the queen in B.Khotenashvili -Z.Tan, Jiangsu Wuxi 2012 Sam Collins: 'with overwhelming compensation for the queen in B.Khotenashvili -Z.Tan, Jiangsu Wuxi 2012'}) 21. Bf4 Bxg5 22. Bxg5 Qxg5 23. Nxf8 Rxd1 24. Raxd1 {and White went on to win in E.Miroshnichenko-G.Nakhbayeva, Al Ain 2014. He clearly has the better chances, though Black should try Sam Collins: 'and White went on to win in E.Miroshnichenko-G.Nakhbayeva, Al Ain 2014. He clearly has the better chances, though Black should try'} h5 $5 {to generate some kingside counterplay although, admittedly, the black king might feel uncomfortable after Sam Collins: 'to generate some kingside counterplay although, admittedly, the black king might feel uncomfortable after'} 25. Rfe1 $1 h4 26. Re3 {.}) 20. f4 Be7 (20... Qg7 21. fxg5 Qxa1 22. Nf6+ Qxf6 23. gxf6 Rxd1 24. Rxd1 {left Black with a very difficult endgame in O.Ruggieri-A.Kovacs, ICCF email 2013 Sam Collins: 'left Black with a very difficult endgame in O.Ruggieri-A.Kovacs, ICCF email 2013'}) 21. Qg4+ Qg6 22. Qxg6+ hxg6 23. Nxf8 {was clearly better for White in V.Malakhov-B.Savchenko, Konya 2012.}) 16. h4 $1 Qh6 17. Rc1 Na5 (17... e5 18. Qg4 {with a winning advantage in D.Flores-A.Hoffman, Buenos Aires 2017 Sam Collins: 'with a winning advantage in D.Flores-A.Hoffman, Buenos Aires 2017'}) 18. Rc7 Bxg2 19. Kxg2 {and White won easily in D.Howell-A.Neiksans, Tromsoe 2014. David Howell had a magnificent Olympiad in Tromsoe but here Neiksans fell into a known opening trap. Sam Collins: 'and White won easily in D.Howell-A.Neiksans, Tromsoe 2014. David Howell had a magnificent Olympiad in Tromsoe but here Neiksans fell into a known opening trap.'}) ({c)} 12... Rfd8 $6 {is a well-known error:} 13. Ne5 Qd6 ({Black should probably speculate with Sam Collins: 'Black should probably speculate with'} 13... Qxg2+ 14. Kxg2 Nxe5+ 15. f3 {, as in A.Mikaelyan-H.Hayrapetyan, Yerevan 2016, with comparable play to the 12...Rad8 13 Ne5 Qxg2+ line Sam Collins: ', as in A.Mikaelyan-H.Hayrapetyan, Yerevan 2016, with comparable play to the 12...Rad8 13 Ne5 Qxg2+ line'}) 14. Qf3 Nxe5 15. Qxb7 {with the bishop pair for free and a clear advantage (for example, S.Brunello-M.Brunello, Biella 2011). Sam Collins: 'with the bishop pair for free and a clear advantage (for example, S.Brunello-M.Brunello, Biella 2011).'}) ({d)} 12... Nb4 13. Nh4 Qd7 14. dxc5 Qxd1 15. Rfxd1 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 Bxc5 17. a3 Nd5 {and now Marin (and the engines) endorse Nogueiras' suggestion Sam Collins: 'and now Marin (and the engines) endorse Nogueiras' suggestion'} 18. b4 $1 (18. e4 Nf6 19. Bxf6 gxf6 20. b4 Be7 21. Rd7 Rfe8 {with a level endgame which has been tested in several games Sam Collins: 'with a level endgame which has been tested in several games'}) {, for example} 18... Be7 (18... Bxe3 19. Rxd5 exd5 20. fxe3 {is also better for White}) 19. Nf5 Bf6 (19... exf5 20. Rxd5 {and Black w