r 22...Nd3, since he has retained the better minor piece.''} Kf8 27. e4 $1 {'Sam Collins: '!''} Nf6 28. f3 {Restricting t'Sam Collins: 'Restricting the black knight and preparing to invade on the seventh rank.'' he black knight and preparing to invade on the seventh rank.} Ke7 29. Kf2 (29. Rc7+ Rd7 {leads nowhere.}) 29... Ne8 30. Bb5 Rd1 31. Ke2 (31. f4 {was a good alternative, with an edge.}) 31... Rb1 32. b4 Rh1 33. Rc8 Nd6 34. Rc7+ Kf6 35. Bd3 Rxh2+ 36. Ke3 g5 $2 {'Sam Collins: '?''} (36... e5 {was a sounder defence, although after Sam Collins: 'was a sounder defence, although after'} 37. Rxa7 Ra2 38. Ra6 Ke6 {White retains the better chances. Sam Collins: 'White retains the better chances.'}) 37. Rd7 Ne8 38. f4 $1 {Threatening t'Sam Collins: '!' Sam Collins: 'Threatening to win the knight after e5+ and Re7.'' o win the knight after e5+ and Re7.} Rh3 39. e5+ Kg7 40. Kf2 $2 {Now Black obt'Sam Collins: '?' Sam Collins: 'Now Black obtains counterplay along the third rank.'' ains counterplay along the third rank.} (40. Kf3 gxf4 41. Kxf4 {would leave Black in serious trouble.}) 40... gxf4 41. gxf4 Kf8 (41... a5 $5 {looks like a better defence, limiting White to an edge. Sam Collins: 'looks like a better defence, limiting White to an edge.'}) 42. f5 $1 {'Sam Collins: '!''} a5 43. b5 $1 {A very natura'Sam Collins: '!' Sam Collins: 'A very natural decision, keeping more pawns on the board and fixing the weakness on b6. White loses the option of Bb5 (after Re8) but Black's position remains grim.'' l decision, keeping more pawns on the board and fixing the weakness on b6. White loses the option of Bb5 (after Re8) but Black's position remains grim.} (43. f6 {locks out the black knight and threatens Re8 and Bb5. Perhaps Rapport was worried that all his pawns would be eliminated, but I don't see how Black could achieve this, for example Sam Collins: 'locks out the black knight and threatens Re8 and Bb5. Perhaps Rapport was worried that all his pawns would be eliminated, but I