{Sethuraman,SP: 'This battle is between the Chinese No 1 Liren Ding and the young and rapidly advancing Yi Wei, who is only 16(!) and considered by many to be a future challenger to World Champion Magnus Carlsen. It was very exciting for the spectators since it had many up and down moments. When asked before the match who I thought would win this game, I said I was rooting for Ding Liren since I thought he had more experience of playing in super tournaments and also because he had achieved the amazing feat of defeating Boris Gelfand in their World Cup match. Hence, as far as I was concerned, he was the favourite. However my prediction was proved wrong and Wei won the match in the rapid tiebreaks. The number of losing positions he saved in this match and also in his previous match against GM Yuri Vovk was simply astonishing, and showed just how cold-blooded he can be, Some call it luck, but as they say luck favours the brave!' Sethuraman,SP: 'Wagner,D: 'In Round 4 of the Fide World Cup in Baku a highly interesting encounter took place, as the two most promising players in China, who fared really well in this event, were paired against each other. ''} 1. d4 {Wagner,Dennis Sethuraman,SP Sethuraman,SP: 'Wagner,D'} Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 {Sethuraman,SP: 'Wei Yi mainly plays the Gruenfeld and Anti-Gruenfeld against Nf3/c4 systems, so it was no surprise either to Ding nor to the spectators.' Sethuraman,SP: 'Wagner,D: 'Most of the Grünfeld adherents have adopted 2...c5 as a counter to 1.f3, but Wei Yi is faithful to the more principled but also more risky Anti-Grünfeld, which can be seen often in his games. ''} 4. Nc3 Be7 5. Bf4 {David Cummings: 'This line of the Pseudo-Grunfeld should perhaps be re-named the anti-Wei Yi variation! This is the fourth game in the last few months where other leading Chinese players have chosen this approach against the 16-year old star.' Sethuraman,SP: '!?' Sethuraman,SP: 'Wagner,D: 'A trendy line that already featured in some of Wei Yi's games.''} O-O {Sethuraman,SP: 'Diagram [#]'} 6. e3 {David Cummings: 'White goes for the aggressive h-pawn push which typically leads to a sharp game with queens on the board and sometimes (as in this game) opposite side castling. In contrast, White can enter the queenless middlegame which we covered in the July 2015 Update with:' Sethuraman,SP: 'Wagner,D: 'A rather uncommon opening concept. White achieves a huge space advantage on the kingside but on the other hand fails to develop his pieces at the same time.''} Nbd7 7. c5 Ne4 8. Rc1 {David Cummings: 'Although White is by no means better by force here, the advanced h-pawn is a thorn in Black's side and brings up persistent tactical themes throughout the whole game'} f5 {David Cummings: 'In an earlier game, Wei Yi kept his dark-squared bishop with'} 9. h3 (9. Ne5 Bf6 $11 10. Nxd7 {(Sethuraman,SP) Wagner,D} Bxd7) 9... c6 {David Cummings: 'After the game, Ding Liren gave an interview on the live broadcast where he analyzed the game in great detail. I have quoted him liberally here as he gave some great insights into this exciting game and demonstrated the depth to which he was calculating throughout.'} 10. Be2 (10. b4 Bf6 {Sethuraman,SP: 'The only non-human-like move to save the position is'} 11. Bd3 {was called for Sethuraman,SP: 'but it can nevertheless be found by means of Dvoretsky’s favourite method ‘Elimination of possibilities’. Black has hardly any other possibility than ...Nb4, which is inferior since White has at least two options to achieve a decent advantage. The other knight moves don’t make any sense. So the only remaining possibility is to move the king away from any checks, since the black rook is doing a good job keeping an eye on the h6 pawn and hampering the movements of the white rook on h7. With both players having little time on clock and still only 33 moves played, it was even more difficult to find this move. Wagner,D: '!'' Wagner,Dennis: '!'} a5 {(Sethuraman,SP) Wagner,D} 12. a3 axb4 13. axb4 $1 {clearing the 6th rank for the rook.} b5 14. O-O Re8 15. Ne2 Bb7 16. Ra1) 10... Bf6 {Sethuraman,SP: 'Diagram [#]'} 11. O-O {David Cummings: 'A novelty, and Ding Liren's prepared improvement over Wei Yi's previous outing in this line, which continued:' Sethuraman,SP: 'N' Sethuraman,SP: 'Here comes the improvement on the game mentioned below with Qa4. In the press conference after the game, Ding mentioned that he only analysed this idea a day before the game at Baku. Perhaps it is the top choice of the computer engines. Wagner,D: '!'' Wagner,Dennis: '!' Sethuraman,SP: 'Wagner,D: 'White is still behind in development but anyway he starts concrete operations leading to a highly complicated situation.''} Qe8 12. Bh2 {David Cummings: '!?' David Cummings: 'A move Ding Liren found on the morning before the game, the computer suggested'} b6 $6 {Sethuraman,SP: 'Wagner,D: 'This leads by force to an endgame where White is holding the initiative.''} 13. Nxe4 $1 {David Cummings: 'the only move, as White can't go for' Sethuraman,SP: 'Diagram [#]' Sethuraman,SP: 'Wagner,D: 'forcing the exchange of queens, but the character of the game still remains extremely forcing and complicated.''} (13. b4 bxc5 14. bxc5 Ndxc5 15. Ne5 Nxc3 16. Rxc3 Ne4 17. Rc2 Bxe5 $18 (17... Bd7 18. Ba6 {is still not clear after}) {Surprisingly} 18. Bxe5 {Sethuraman,SP} a5 19. Qc1 Ba6 20. Bxa6 $1 Rxa6 21. Qa3) 13... fxe4 14. Ne5 {David Cummings: '!' David Cummings: 'Wei Yi spent about half an hour on this move, and before long Ding Liren was about an hour ahead on the clock, but the game now enters a demanding phase with tactics to be calculated on every move' Sethuraman,SP: '!' Wagner,Dennis: '!' Sethuraman,SP: 'Wagner,D: 'An energetic counter-attacking developing move! Now unclear complications arise which should lead to a balanced position if both sides act accurately.''} Bxe5 15. Bxe5 Nxe5 {David Cummings: '!' David Cummings: 'A very interesting move, sacrificing the exchange. The problem is that normal moves work out well for White, for example'} 16. dxe5 Bd7 17. Qd4 {David Cummings: 'Ding Liren also considered'} b5 18. f4 $1 {Sethuraman,SP: 'Diagram [#]' Sethuraman,SP: 'Wagner,D: 'A pretty way of activating the last piece.''} exf3 {David Cummings: '?' David Cummings: 'Ding Liren said he overlooked this possibility, although objectively it is not the best move. He mainly looked at' Sethuraman,SP: '?' Sethuraman,SP: 'Diagram [#]' Wagner,Dennis: '?'} 19. gxf3 $2 {David Cummings: 'Here White missed a big chance to gain an advantage with' Sethuraman,SP: 'Wagner,D: '?''} Qh5 $1 {David Cummings: 'An important in-between move' Sethuraman,SP: '' Sethuraman,SP: 'Diagram [#] Wagner,D: '!'' Sethuraman,SP: 'Wagner,D: 'Maybe Ding underestimated this strong intermediate move. ''} 20. Kh2 {David Cummings: 'The engine gives' Sethuraman,SP: '?' Sethuraman,SP: '[As the position becomes more complex, move by move, it is difficult for both sides to play very accurately. Indeed, after playing a series of good moves, Ding now makes an error.]'} Be8 21. Rg1 Bg6 $1 {David Cummings: 'Another critical finesse' Sethuraman,SP: 'Wagner,D: 'It's important to activate the rook with check in order to take away the important e6-square from the white knight.''} 22. Rg3 Bf5 23. Rcg1 {Sethuraman,SP: 'Diagram [#]'} Rf7 {David Cummings: '?!' Sethuraman,SP: 'Wagner,D: '?'' Wagner,Dennis: '?' Sethuraman,SP: 'Wagner,D: 'Unfortunately Wei Yi fails to exploit a golden opportunity to seize the initiative.''} 24. R1g2 {David Cummings: 'White is trying to open the c-file and extricate his knight' Sethuraman,SP: 'Diagram [#] Wagner,D: '!?'' Wagner,Dennis: '!?' Sethuraman,SP: 'Wagner,D: 'I really like this energetic idea to create some threats on the queenside.''} Qh6 {David Cummings: 'now the position is roughly balanced.. .'} 25. Kg1 {David Cummings: '!?' Sethuraman,SP: 'Wagner,D: '!'' Wagner,Dennis: '!' Sethuraman,SP: 'Wagner,D: 'Increasing the tension even further...''} a5 {David Cummings: '?' David Cummings: 'Now the advantage swings back to White. Instead' Sethuraman,SP: '?' Wagner,Dennis: '?' Sethuraman,SP: 'Wagner,D: 'It's too risky to decentralise the knight in this fashion, but Ding fails to exploit this:''} 26. h4 {David Cummings: '?!' Sethuraman,SP: '?!' Sethuraman,SP: 'Wagner,D: '?'' Wagner,Dennis: '?' Sethuraman,SP: 'Wagner,D: 'Now Ding Liren misses a big chance. The posititon is so complicated that it's impossible for both players to avoid serious mistakes.''} Rfa7 27. Rg5 {David Cummings: '?!' Sethuraman,SP: '[Threatening Rg6.] Diagram [#] Wagner,D: '?!'' Wagner,Dennis: '?!'} Rf8 {David Cummings: '?!' Sethuraman,SP: 'Wagner,D: '?!'' Wagner,Dennis: '?!'} 28. h5 {Sethuraman,SP: '!'} Bb1 29. a3 {Sethuraman,SP: 'Wagner,D: '!'' Wagner,Dennis: '!' Sethuraman,SP: 'Wagner,D: 'The h7-pawn is much more important than the immobile knight on d6!''} Rf5 30. f4 {Sethuraman,SP: 'Wagner,D: 'Like in most complicated posititons in chess the computer evaluates it 0.00 after dozens of moves. Still in a practical game it seems like Black has more problems to solve than White, so I would tend to evaluate this constellation as +=''} Be4 31. R2g3 {Sethuraman,SP: 'Finally, after severe pressure from his opponent, Wei embarks on a series of inaccurate moves. Diagram [#]'} g6 {David Cummings: '?!' David Cummings: 'Black should be holding after, for example' Sethuraman,SP: 'Wagner,D: '?'' Wagner,Dennis: '?' Sethuraman,SP: 'Wagner,D: 'It's not easy to decide how to arrange the pieces, but this construction with the rook on g6 is definietly a step in the wrong direction.''} 32. Bg4 {Sethuraman,SP: 'Wagner,D: '!'' Wagner,Dennis: '!' Sethuraman,SP: 'Wagner,D: 'After this exact rook move Black has difficult problems. But with precise moves he should still hold his position together.''} Rxg5 {Sethuraman,SP: '?!' Wagner,Dennis: '?!' Sethuraman,SP: 'Wagner,D: 'It was necessary to improve the position of the king. Strangely enough, its movement in both directions was still enough to save the game.''} 33. fxg5 {Sethuraman,SP: 'Diagram [#]'} Qg7 {David Cummings: '?' David Cummings: 'a final swing of the pendulum, and this time White does not let go of the win' Sethuraman,SP: 'Wagner,D: '?'' Wagner,Dennis: '?' Sethuraman,SP: 'Wagner,D: 'Only this move seems to be the decisive mistake! It was still necessary to evacuate the king, while the important knight, which cages the rook in on d6, had to be kept in the centre.''} 34. Bxe6+ Kf8 35. h6 {David Cummings: '!' David Cummings: 'Attacking both b4 and g4' Sethuraman,SP: '!' Sethuraman,SP: 'Precise play by Ding, avoiding the position with queen for two pieces in the variation discussed below.' Wagner,Dennis: '!' Sethuraman,SP: 'Wagner,D: 'Now it's all over, because both of White's rooks are active.''} Qc7 36. Bh3 {David Cummings: 'The h-pawn finally makes it one step further, 28 moves after 8 h6!'} Ke8 37. Kf2 Qf7+ 38. Ke1 Qc7 39. Rg1 {David Cummings: 'The h-pawn will queen and White's material advantage will prevail. It is amazing how much influence the h6-pawn had throughout the game.' Sethuraman,SP: 'A fighting game which ended in Ding’s favour. However Wei struck back with a win in the second game to level the score, and finally won the match in the rapid tiebreaks.' Sethuraman,SP: 'Wagner,D: 'A really complicated and nerve-racking game!''} Qb8 {(Sethuraman,SP) Wagner,D} 40. e6 1-0


