inal swing of the pendulum, and this time White does not let go of the win' Sethuraman,SP: 'Wagner,D: '?'' Wagner,Dennis: '?' '?' Sethuraman,SP: 'Wagner,D: 'Only this move seems to be the decisive mistake! It was still necessary to evacuate the king, while the important knight, which cages the rook in on d6, had to be kept in the centre.''} ({Sethuraman,SP: 'The only non-human-like move to save the position is' Sethuraman,SP: 'The only non-human-like move to save the position is'} 33... Kb8 {was called for Sethuraman,SP: 'but it can nevertheless be found by means of Dvoretsky’s favourite method ‘Elimination of possibilities’. Black has hardly any other possibility than ...Nb4, which is inferior since White has at least two options to achieve a decent advantage. The other knight moves don’t make any sense. So the only remaining possibility is to move the king away from any checks, since the black rook is doing a good job keeping an eye on the h6 pawn and hampering the movements of the white rook on h7. With both players having little time on clock and still only 33 moves played, it was even more difficult to find this move. Wagner,D: '!'' Wagner,Dennis: '!' Sethuraman,SP: 'but it can nevertheless be found by means of Dvoretsky’s favourite method ‘Elimination of possibilities’. Black has hardly any other possibility than ...Nb4, which is inferior since White has at least two options to achieve a decent advantage. The other knight moves don’t make any sense. So the only remaining possibility is to move the king away from any checks, since the black rook is doing a good job keeping an eye on the h6 pawn and hampering the movements of the white rook on h7. With both players having little time on clock and still only 33 moves played, it was even more difficult to find this move.' was called for Sethuraman,SP: '!' 'but it can nevertheless be found by means of Dvoretsky’s favourite method ‘Elimination of possibilities’. Black has hardly any other possibility than ...Nb4, wh