1. e4 {Mokal,P} c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {Saying no to Wei Yi's Sveshnikov/Pelikan.} g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. Nc3 Nf6 6. e5 Ng4 7. Bxc6 dxc6 8. Re1 O-O 9. d3 Nh6 10. h3 b6 11. Ne4 Nf5 12. c3 Ba6 13. g4 Nh6 14. d4 cxd4 15. cxd4 f5 16. exf6 exf6 17. Qa4 {An uncommon idea, to first push the  back and then return with b3.} (17. Qb3+ Kh8 18. Bf4 Nf7 19. Rad1 (19. Rac1 $5) 19... Qd7 20. Qa3 (20. d5 c5 $132) 20... Bc4 21. Nd6 Bd5 22. Re3 Nd8 23. Rde1 Ne6 $17 {½-½ Dolzhikova,K (2278)-Zontakh,A (2545)/Kiev 2007/CBM 119 ext (67)}) 17... Bb7 18. Qb3+ Nf7 19. Bf4 Qd5 20. Qxd5 cxd5 21. Nd6 (21. Nc3 Rfe8 {seems ok for Black.}) 21... Nxd6 22. Bxd6 Rf7 {Black has come out of the opening with no serious problems. He has 2s but the pawn structure is not optimal for them at the moment. One important point to note is that White's pawn has advanced to g4. He will always have to look out for ...f5 and ...h5 breaks which could open Black's s. White's control of the e and the d6-square is not permanent. All these factors make the position complex but dynamically equal. It is therefore interesting to see Wei Yi's approach to it. He wants to keep one  on the board to keep some fighting chances, rather than going for simplifications with a very tiny edge.} ({Both the s would have been exchanged after} 22... Rfe8 $5 23. Rxe8+ Rxe8 24. Rc1 Rc8 25. Rxc8+ Bxc8 {Black can still try but it is closer to equality.}) 23. Re6 (23. Rac1 Rd8 24. Re6 Rfd7 $132) 23... h6 (23... Rc8 24. Rae1 Bh6 $13 (24... Rd7 $6 25. Re7 $14) (24... h6 25. Nh4 Kh7 26. Re7 $14)) 24. Rae1 Rd8 25. Nh4 ({It was worth considering bringing up the  to bolster the  pawn mass with} 25. Kg2 Ba6 (25... Kh7 26. Kg3 Bc8 27. Re8 $11) 26. Kg3 $11) 25... Kh7 26. Bb4 ({The natural follow-up seemed to be} 26. f4 $142 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gf4f5] with the intention of closing the eyes of Black's dark squared .} Bc8 (26... f5 27. Be5 {[%cal Ge6g6]} (27. Nxg6 $2 $19 Bc8) 27... fxg4 28. Rxg6 gxh3 29. Rxg7+ Rxg7+ 30. Bxg7 Rg8 31. Kh2 Rxg7 32. Nf5 Rd7 33. Kxh3 $14) 27. Re7 (27. Re8 Rxd6 28. Rxc8 f5 29. Nf3 fxg4 30. hxg4 Rxf4 31. Re7 Rxf3 32. Rcc7 $11) 27... Rxe7 28. Bxe7 Re8 29. f5 (29. Kf2 $2 f5 $19) 29... gxf5 (29... Bf8 $2 30. Nxg6 $18) 30. Nxf5 Bxf5 31. gxf5 Bf8 32. Bb4 Rxe1+ 33. Bxe1 $11) 26... Bc8 27. Re8 {This loses some important tempi.} (27. Re7 {would be answered by} Rd7 (27... Rxe7 28. Rxe7 a5 29. Bd2 $11) 28. Rxf7 Rxf7 {[%cal Gf6f5]} 29. Nf3 h5 $15 (29... f5 $6 30. g5)) (27. Rc6 $5 {[%cal Gc6h6] was worth considering, maintaining an active position of the  to be ready for the  breaks.} Ba6 $13 (27... f5 $5 28. gxf5 (28. Rxg6 $2 fxg4 29. hxg4 Bxd4 $17) (28. Nxg6 Bb7 29. Rce6) 28... gxf5 29. Nf3 $11) (27... Bd7 28. Rc7 $16) 28. Re7 Rd7 29. Rxd7 Rxd7 30. Kg2 $11 {with good chances to hold.}) 27... Rxe8 28. Rxe8 Bd7 29. Ra8 a5 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Ga8b8,Gb8b6]} ({It was more precise to play} 29... f5 $142 {right away. For example} 30. gxf5 g5 31. Nf3 (31. Ng6 Bxf5 {is the same}) 31... Bxf5 32. Ne5 Bxe5 33. dxe5 Bxh3 $15) 30. Bc3 {The position seems to be getting difficult for White, especially with Black's ...f5 coming, but White does have a resource.} ({It would need some computer precision to find} 30. Bd6 $5 f5 31. g5 $1 {The machine wants to use the idea of trapping the Black  in a mating net to carry out some simplifications.} (31. Nf3 fxg4 32. Ne5 Bxe5 33. Bxe5 g5 34. hxg4 Bxg4 $15) 31... Bxd4 (31... hxg5 32. Nf3 Kh6 33. Ne5 Bxe5 34. dxe5 $13) 32. Nf3 Bxb2 33. Ne5 Rg7 (33... Bxe5 $2 34. Bxe5 $18 {[%cal Ga8h8]}) 34. gxh6 Kxh6 35. Nd3 Bf6 36. Bf8 $11 {[%cal Gd3f4,Ga8a7]}) 30... f5 31. gxf5 $6 ({Compared to 30.d6 f5 31.g5, the resource} 31. Nf3 $142 fxg4 32. Ne5 {was not out of human reach.} Bxe5 33. dxe5 g5 (33... gxh3 $4 34. e6 $18 {[%cal Ga8h8]}) 34. hxg4 Bxg4 35. Rb8 $11 {with good chances to hold.}) 31... g5 32. Ng2 $6 {The  would have been happier in the centre.} (32. Nf3 $142 Bxf5 33. Ne5 (33. Kh2 $2 Be4 $19 {[%csl Rf2]}) 33... Rb7 34. Kh2 Bf6 $132 {Although it is Black who has every reason to keep pushing, White's pieces are in the sort of position to create counterplay.}) 32... Bxf5 33. Ne3 (33. Kh2 Bb1 $19) 33... Be4 $15 {Black's 2s are now dominating. Wei Yi gives a fine demonstration of his technique now.} (33... Bxh3 $6 34. Nxd5 $11) 34. Rb8 Rf3 35. Rxb6 Rxh3 36. Kf1 h5 37. Rb7 h4 38. Bxa5 Kg6 $1 (38... Rh1+ 39. Ke2 h3 40. Bc7 $17 {invites unnecessary complications.}) 39. Ke2 Bxd4 40. Bb6 Bxb2 41. Bc5 Bc3 42. Rb6+ Kh5 43. Bf8 Bg6 44. Kf1 (44. Nxd5 Bd3+ 45. Kd1 Rh1#) 44... Bd4 45. Nxd5 Rf3 46. Rb4 Bd3+ 47. Kg2 Rxf2+ 48. Kg1 Rf1+ 49. Kg2 Rf2+ 50. Kg1 Ba7 51. Be7 (51. Ra4 Rxa2+ $19) (51. Rb7 Rf7+ $19) 51... Rb2+ 52. Kh1 Rxb4 53. Nxb4 Be4+ 54. Kh2 Bb8+ {After this game, Wei Yi drew the second one to advance to the 2nd round of the World Cup.} (54... Bb8+ 55. Kg1 (55. Kh3 g4#) 55... h3 {[%cal Gh3h2,Gh2h1]}) 0-1


