{White is slowly outplaying Black in this Advanced Caro-Kann opening position. White has the pair of bishops, a lot of space in the centre and queenside thanks to his e5- and a5-pawns. Diagram [#]} 17... Qg5 $5 {Black starts searching for some counterplay by bringing his queen to take aim at the white king.} (17... Qc7 {Black will try to put pressure on the e5-pawn and also possibly an exchange sacrifice on c3 if White plays b4 in the future.}) 18. Ra3 $2 (18. f3 $1 {simply taking the e4-square away from Black's minor pieces. Now White is threatening to play b4 and consolidate his space advantage on the queenside.}) 18... Qf5 $5 (18... Bf5 {with the idea to go ...Qg6 and...Bd3 and get better control on the light-squares.} 19. b4 Bh3 20. Bf3 Nd7 21. Kh1 $14) 19. b4 $6 {White is trying to force things on the board.} (19. f3 $1 h5 20. Qd2 $14) 19... Nd3 20. g4 {Keeping the initiative going.} Qg6 21. f4 Qe4 {The black queen has moved around quite a bit in the past few moves, and White has pushed his kingside pawns too much attacking her, making his own king weak in the process. White has to play accurately to keep his initiative going, and if not - the extended kingside pawns could become targets of attack. If you would want to get a calculation workout, I would highly suggest you spend at least 15-20 minutes in this position and calculate all the intricacies of the position.} 22. Bf3 $2 (22. Qd2 $1 {White plans to reroute the a3-rook to d1 and win the trapped d3-knight.} h5 $1 (22... Nxb4 $2 {Looks like White has blundered a pawn, but he has a very nice trick up his sleeve. Diagram [#]} 23. f5 $3 {Disrupting the coordination between the black pieces.} (23. cxb4 $4 Rc2 $17) 23... exf5 24. Bd1 $1 (24. Rb3 Nc2 25. Bf3 Nxd4 26. Bxe4 Nxb3 27. Qxd5 fxe4 28. Qxb3 Rc7 $44 {Black should be able to hold this position, as White pawns are very weak.}) 24... Rc4 (24... Nd3 25. Bf3 $18) (24... Qd3 25. Qb2 $18 {The black knight and queen are poorly placed.} fxg4 (25... Rc4 26. Be2 Qe4 27. Bxc4 $18) 26. cxb4) 25. Rb3 Qd3 26. Qxd3 Nxd3 27. gxf5 $16 {The black bishop on h7 is out of the game, and White can use that to his advantage.}) 23. Raa1 (23. Rf3 $5 Nxb4 $1 (23... Nc1 $1 24. Bd1 hxg4 25. Re3 Qb1 26. Re1 Rfc8 27. Ba4 Rc4 $1 28. Be3 (28. Rxc1 $4 Rxd4 $1 $19) 28... d4 29. Qxc1 Qd3 30. Bf2 dxc3 $44) 24. f5 hxg4 25. Rf4 Qc2 26. Qe3 exf5 27. cxb4 g5 28. Rf2 f4 $44 {I like Black's chances in this position.}) 23... Rc4 $1 (23... hxg4 24. Rad1 Nxb4 25. f5 $3 Bxf5 26. Rf4 Qc2 27. cxb4 $18) 24. Rad1 (24. gxh5 $2 Rxd4 25. cxd4 Qxd4+ 26. Kg2 Be4+ 27. Kg3 Rc8 $44) 24... Rxd4 25. cxd4 Qxd4+ 26. Kg2 Qe4+ 27. Kg3 Nxb4 28. gxh5 (28. Bf3 Qc4 29. Rc1 Qb3 $44) 28... Nc6 29. Bf3 $44) 22... Qxf4 (22... Qg6 $4 23. f5 exf5 24. Qxd3 $18) 23. Bxd5 exd5 24. Rxf4 Nxf4 {We have reached the position with the material imbalance as Black has a rook and knight for the queen. The compensation that Black has in this position: 1) Weak white king. 2) Weak light squares near the king. 3) Opposite coloured bishops giving good drawing chances. 4) Great outposts available for the pieces, as Black can place his bishop on e4, rook on g6, knight on e6 and so on.} 25. Be3 (25. Qf3 Ne6 26. Qxd5 Rd8 27. Qf3 Nxd4 28. cxd4 Rxd4 $11 {Technically equal, but White is the side that needs to be precise to hold a draw.}) 25... Nd3 $1 26. Bd4 Re8 27. Qf3 $2 (27. Ra2 $1 {White has to use all his pieces to defend his precarious position, so it becomes important to activate the passive rook on a3.} Nxe5 28. Bxe5 Rxe5 29. Re2 Be4 30. Re3 $44 {White has to be careful, as any minor error could make his position terrible.}) 27... Nxe5 28. Qxd5 $2 Nxg4 {The white king is terribly exposed now, and that will lead to his downfall.} 29. Ra1 {How can Black force matters in this position? Diagram [#]} Rg6 $1 {Going straight for the opponent's king!} 30. Qxb7 Ne3+ $6 (30... Ne5+ 31. Kh1 Nd3 $8 32. Rf1 Nf2+ $3 {- possibly Black did not spot this brilliant move in his calculation.} 33. Bxf2 Rg4 $19) 31. Kf2 Ng4+ 32. Kg1 {Do not box your king in a corner, if you are getting attacked as that would make it easier for the attacking side, as there would be no escape squares available.} (32. Kf3 $142 Nxh2+ 33. Kf2 Ng4+ 34. Kf3 Nf6 35. Qc7 (35. Qxa6 $4 Ne4 $19) 35... Nd5 36. Qd7 Rge6 $17) 32... Ne5+ 33. Kf1 $4 Rf6+ 34. Kg2 Rg6+ 35. Kf1 {Diagram [#]} Rg5 $1 {Allowing the h7-bishop to join the attack.} 36. Bxe5 Bd3+ 37. Kf2 Rexe5 (37... Rgxe5 $142 38. Qb6 Re2+ 39. Kg1 Rd2 $19) 38. Rd1 (38. Qc8+ Kh7 39. Rd1 Be4 40. Rd4 Rgf5+ 41. Kg1 Rf4 $19) 38... Re2+ 39. Kf3 Rf5+ 40. Kg4 h5+ 41. Kh4 Re4+ {One of the critical reasons why White lost this game was the fact that he had activated his Rook on a3 too late and by then Black had built a big attack against the white king. Losing the g4-pawn opened up all sorts of attacks on the white king, which could have been avoided had White defended that pawn.  Black played brilliantly with his minor pieces coordinating them in magnificent fashion, and they were also defending each other as they progressed forward, aiming at the white king. RR This game is published in Chess Informant 136/(45)} 0-1


