{[%evp 0,90,28,27,36,36,28,6,6,6,6,2,6,7,2,2,11,-19,-1,-9,-10,-24,5,-43,-1,-25,-13,-12,-4,-12,26,17,21,21,13,-7,-11,-17,-20,-19,1,-32,9,-5,-2,-12,-13,-42,-12,-41,-33,-34,4,0,30,-48,-10,-49,-63,-64,-41,-84,-94,-142,-173,-141,-188,-148,-165,-233,-216,-279,-282,-315,-274,-317,-317,-337,-184,-264,-164,-153,-136,-309,-249,-245,-285,-396,-301,-715,-841,-1142,-1178]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {The fashionable move!} Bc5 4. d3 Nf6 5. h3 d6 6. c3 a5 {One of the new ideas that have changed the landscape of the Giuoco Piano for black side.} 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 h6 9. Nbd2 Be6 10. b3 $5 {Tested heavily in the correspondence world, and then the novelty found its way to over-the-board games at the elite level.} ({The most popular continuation for White:} 10. Bb5 Qb8 {An important theoretical tabiya in the The Giuoco Piano.}) 10... Bb6 {A new idea for over-the-board games.} 11. Nf1 a4 (11... d5 12. exd5 Nxd5 13. Bd2 Qf6 14. N1h2 Rad8 $13) 12. Bd2 (12. Bxe6 fxe6 13. b4 Nh5 $13) 12... axb3 13. axb3 Rxa1 14. Qxa1 Qd7 {A quiet position, as there seems to be no weakness on either side and there seems to be no good pawn break on the board. It's time now for both sides to continuously manoeuvre the pieces and place them on best possible squares.} 15. Be3 (15. Ng3 d5 16. exd5 Bxd5 17. Qd1 Re8 $11) 15... Bxe3 16. Nxe3 Ne7 17. Bxe6 {White pieces seem to be bit clueless, so Wei Yi decides to swap a pair of knights on g4. Therefore he makes a preparatory move.} (17. Qa7 b6 18. Qb7 Ng6 19. Ra1 Nf4 20. Ra7 Bxc4 21. dxc4 Ne2+ 22. Kf1 Nxc3 23. Nd2 $13) 17... fxe6 $1 {Anton makes a practical decision to change the pawn structure and create some pressure on the f-file.} ({This recapture would have kept the symmetrical pawn structure intact increasing the chances of a draw.} 17... Qxe6 18. c4 $11) 18. Nh2 Ng6 {It's evident we are not going to see Na1 or Na8 in this game, so that means somewhere soon we will see Nh1 or Nh8 on the board!} 19. g3 Qb5 (19... Nh8 $5 {A bit early.} 20. b4 Nf7 21. h4 d5 $13) 20. Rd1 {Diagram [#]} Kh7 $1 {When you don't have a clear plan, improve your pieces!} (20... Qxb3 $4 21. Rb1 $18 {The queen is trapped!}) (20... d5 $5) 21. b4 $6 (21. Qa2 {This is a multi-tasking move, as it defends the f2 and b3 pawns, and keeps control of the a-file and at the same time puts some indirect pressure on the e6-pawn.} d5 22. Nhg4 $11) 21... d5 22. Nhg4 Nxg4 23. hxg4 dxe4 24. dxe4 Qe2 25. Rf1 Qf3 {White's treading on thin ice of equality now, and one slip here would give Black a significant advantage.} 26. Qa2 Rf6 27. Qc2 {Let's talk to the black pieces and see how they feel: Queen - I am in the most active square I can be on the board. Rook - I am multitasking as I am defending weakness on e6, and putting some pressure on the d-file. Knight - I need some purpose for my existence, and I am not doing much right now. King - I am safe, what else I need!? Diagram [#]} Nh8 $1 {Anton listened to his knight's whispers and made a great move} 28. Rd1 $4 (28. g5 $1 {A deep tactical idea to equalise!} hxg5 29. Qd1 Qxe4 {Two pawns have been sacrificed, so what's the idea?} 30. Ng4 {The point being - Black's extra pawns are too weak, so White can liquidate to a pawn down, but drawn endgame.} Rf5 31. Re1 Qf3 32. c4 $1 Nf7 33. Qxf3 Rxf3 34. Nxe5 Nxe5 35. Rxe5 Rc3 36. Rc5 c6 37. b5 cxb5 38. Rxb5 Rxc4 39. Rxb7 $11) 28... Nf7 29. Rd3 Rg6 $1 {Getting away from all the knight jump ideas, and also giving a cover for the king. A big threat for Black is now to play ...Ng5.} ({I believe Wei Yi considered this logical move for Black and missed the Black's 29...Rg6!} 29... Ng5 $2 30. Nd5 Nh3+ 31. Kh2 Qxf2+ 32. Qxf2 Rxf2+ 33. Kxh3 exd5 $11) (29... Qxe4 $2 30. Rd7 Qxc2 31. Nxc2 Ng5 32. Rxc7 Nh3+ 33. Kg2 Nxf2 34. Ne3 Ne4 35. Nd1 $11) 30. Qd1 Qxe4 $19 31. f3 Qc6 32. Ng2 e4 $1 {White's position is crumbling.} 33. Re3 exf3 34. Nf4 Rf6 35. Kf2 Ng5 {Mission accomplished. Now let's quickly look at the route taken by this knight which started its journey on b8. Nb8-c6-e7-g6-h8-f7-g5 and the knight arrived at its winning destination!} 36. Qd3+ Kg8 37. Nh5 Rf8 38. Qd4 e5 $5 {Diagram [#]} 39. Rxe5 (39. Qxe5 Nh3+ 40. Kf1 (40. Ke1 {A quick test for the viewers! Can you calculate the mate in 11 here?} f2+ 41. Kd2 Rd8+ 42. Kc1 (42. Kc2 Qa4+ 43. Kb2 Rd2+ 44. Kc1 Qc2# {#}) 42... Qh1+ 43. Kb2 Rd2+ 44. Kb3 Qb1+ 45. Kc4 Qa2+ 46. Kc5 Qa7+ 47. Kc4 f1=Q+ 48. Re2 Qxe2+ 49. Qxe2 Qa2+ 50. Kc5 Qd5# {# and that's how you do a checkmate in 11!}) 40... Qc4+ 41. Ke1 f2+) 39... Nh3+ 40. Kf1 (40. Ke3 f2 41. Rf5 Qe6+ 42. Kd2 Qa2+ 43. Kd3 Qb1+ 44. Kc4 f1=Q+ 45. Rxf1 Qxf1+) 40... f2 41. Re4 Qa6+ 42. c4 Qg6 43. Qa1 Rf7 44. Re8+ Kh7 45. Qd1 Rd7 {A game that seemed uneventful at the beginning ended up in sharp play after a series of manoeuvres. White made a bunch of minor inaccuracies and got himself in a tough spot and then through a series of clever manoeuvring starting with ...Kh7 and ...Rf6... and the key ...Nh8-f7-g5 Black won the game!} 0-1


