1. b3 e5 2. Bb2 Nc6 3. e3 Nf6 4. Bb5 {This is the main line, in which White intends to press immediately against Black's centre.} Bd6 {As paradoxical as it may look, this is a good way to protect the pawn.} (4... e4 {turns the pawn into a target on e4} 5. Ne2 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Ye2g3] some games continued} a6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. Ng3 h5 $5 {with chances for both sides, but Black is the one who should look for dynamic ideas, or the pawn will become a serious weakness}) (4... d6 {generally leaves White with a slightly better structure} 5. Ne2 Be7 (5... a6 6. Bxc6+ bxc6 7. d4 {doesn't change anything}) 6. d4 $1 exd4 7. Nxd4 Bd7 8. Bxc6 bxc6 {and White has ensured a small advantage due to Black's doubled pawns} 9. Qf3 $1 d5 10. Nf5 $1 {forcing exchanges, White is looking for better endgames} Bxf5 11. Qxf5 O-O 12. Nd2 Qd7 13. Qxd7 Nxd7 14. Nf3 Bf6 15. O-O-O {1-0 Hodgson,J (2575)-Parcerias,P (2255) EU-Cup sf Breda 1998 (1) and White managed to win the endgame in}) 5. Ne2 {The second most played idea, and Wey Yi's favorite. White intends to keeps his position flexible and explore ideas like g3-f5 or 0-0 followed by f4, in order to open both the d-file and the a1-h8 diagonal for his pieces.} (5. Na3 $5 {[%cal Ya3c4] looking for quick pressure against the e5-pawn, is the main line.}) 5... a6 {It makes sense to take the bishop pair if Black has the chance.} ({In 2016, I faced this position against the same Wey Yi in a blitz game and, after careless play, realised how unpleasant White's ideas can be. Although I had a decent position before starting to make bad moves, I think this game illustrates pretty well some dangers that Black can face if White manages to put all these ideas into practice} 5... O-O 6. O-O Re8 (6... a6 7. Bxc6 dxc6 {0-1 Wei,Y (2724)-Karjakin,S (2753) CHN-RUS Super Go 2015 (1.2)}) 7. Ng3 a6 (7... Bf8 8. f4 exf4 9. Rxf4 $36 {[%csl Yb2][%cal Yf4f8];1-0 Neiksans,A (2590)-Gumula,D (2218) European Blitz 2017 (11.64) it is not difficult to realise that White's position has great potential -}) 8. Be2 Bf8 {[%cal Yd7d5] Black is ready for d5} 9. c4 (9. f4 d5 10. fxe5 Nxe5 {is ok for Black}) 9... d5 10. cxd5 Nxd5 11. Nc3 Nxc3 (11... Be6 {0-1 Wei,Y (2734)-Svidler,P (2727) FIDE World Cup 2015 (5.6)}) 12. Bxc3 Be6 13. f4 exf4 14. Rxf4 Bd6 15. Re4 Qg5 16. Qe1 Rad8 (16... a5 $5 {[%cal Yd6b4]}) 17. Qf2 {Black has a totally aceptable position, but now I took a terribly wrong decision} Bxg3 $6 (17... Qg6 $1 {[%csl Ye4][%cal Yd6g3]} 18. Rf1 Bxg3 19. Qxg3 Qxg3 20. hxg3 Ne7 $11) 18. hxg3 Bf5 $2 (18... f6) 19. Rf4 Bg6 20. Rf1 {and now the defence was very bad} f6 $2 (20... Rd7 {would keep the position safe}) 21. Bc4+ {[%cal Yf4f6,Yc3f6] suddenly White is winning with thematic sacrifices on f6} Bf7 22. Bxf7+ Kxf7 23. Rf5 $1 Qg4 24. Rxf6+ $18 {1-0 Wei,Y (2707)-Quintiliano Pinto,R (2484) Wch Blitz Doha 2016 (1)}) 6. Bxc6 dxc6 {It is important to understand this change in pawn structure.} 7. d3 {Once Black has the bishop pair, White should be careful in opening the position, and start to place the pawns on light squares. This structure resembles some Anti-Berlin or Rossolimo positions, in which White plays b5 and takes on c6. In those positions, with the pawn already on e4, the plan is to look for initiative in kingside with f4, or d4 and play with the kingside majority. We can safely add that the bishop is well placed on b2 to support both plans. This is my guess as to why some players like this 5.e2 variation.} Qe7 {Leaving the king on e8 Black has an interesting idea.} (7... O-O {is the most played, and looks very decent. Some recent games show how the game can develop} 8. Nd2 Qe7 (8... Re8 9. h3 c5 10. g4 $5 {In a blitz game, White tried this hyper-aggressive idea} b5 11. Ng3 Bb7 12. Rg1 {[%cal Yg3f5] suddenly the position becomes very tense and risky for both sides} Re6 13. g5 Nd5 14. h4 a5 15. a4 bxa4 16. Rxa4 Nb6 17. Rg4 $5 $13 {½-½ Caruana,F (2823)-Anand,V (2779) Saint Louis Showdown Blitz 2016 (12)}) (8... Be6 9. O-O Re8 10. e4 a5 11. a4 Nd7 {1-0 Moussard,J (2576)-Dek,L (2288) PRO League Central rapid 2017 (3)} 12. Nc4 $5 f6 13. Ne3 {[%cal Yf2f4] Black is very solid, but White is always moving pieces around, preparaing f4 or f5 in good circumstances}) 9. O-O (9. a4 {probably played in order to avoid a3} Be6 10. O-O a5 11. Ng3 Rfe8 12. h3 Nd7 13. e4 b6 {1-0 Drozdowski,K (2490)-Miesbauer,J (2321) Ceske Budejovice 2016 (5)} 14. Nc4 Bxc4 15. Nf5 $1 Qf8 16. bxc4 {[%cal Yd1g4,Yf2f4]} g6 $6 17. Nxd6 Qxd6 18. f4 $1 exf4 19. Qg4 $14 {[%csl Yb2]}) 9... Bg4 10. h3 Bh5 11. Qe1 Nd5 12. Ng3 Bg6 13. e4 Nf4 14. Ne2 Ne6 15. Nc4 f6 {1-0 Drozdowski,K (2508)-Niemann,H (2273) Dallas UT Fall op 2016 (1)} 16. Nxd6 cxd6 (16... Qxd6 17. f4 exf4 18. Qc1 {[%cal Ye2f4]}) 17. f4 exf4 18. Nxf4 Nxf4 19. Rxf4 {[%cal Ye1f2,Ya1f1] Of course it is not much, but White can build up some pressure on the kingside.}) 8. Nd2 ({The point is if} 8. O-O {1-0 Wei,Y (2649)-Lupulescu,C (2643) Bazna Kings blitz 2014 (7)} h5 $1 $146 {then Black will be the one looking for the initiative on the kingside, for example} 9. Nd2 h4 10. h3 Be6 11. d4 exd4 12. Nxd4 O-O-O 13. Nxe6 Qxe6 14. Qe2 Rhg8 {[%cal Yg7g5,Yg5g4] and Black's coming attack looks annoying.}) 8... h5 $5 {Even if White doesn't play 0-0, this is an interesting way to seize space on the kingside, and now probably the best idea is put the king on the queenside.} (8... Ba3 {is also enough to equalise} 9. Bxa3 Qxa3 10. O-O Bg4 11. f3 Be6 12. d4 exd4 13. Nxd4 O-O-O $11 {0-1 Vaisser,A (2542)-Maze,S (2553) FRA-ch 83rd Pau 2008 (9)}) 9. e4 (9. h3 Be6 10. e4 O-O-O {actually White is already in trouble as to continuing the development, but now he played with fire} 11. f4 $2 exf4 12. O-O (12. e5 Nd5 {[%cal Re7h4,Gd5e3]}) 12... Ng4 $1 13. hxg4 hxg4 $19 {[%cal Re7h4,Gf4f3];0-1 Soffer,R (2508)-Kravtsiv,M (2653) EU-ch 18th Minsk 2017 (4) with a winning attack in}) 9... h4 $1 10. h3 c5 $6 {This allowed a strong continuation for White.} (10... Be6 $2 11. f4 $1) (10... Nh5 $5 {keeping an eye on f4 would be more careful} 11. Nc4 Bd7 12. Qd2 Bb4 $1 13. c3 (13. Bc3 Bxc3 14. Qxc3 f6 15. O-O-O O-O-O $11) 13... Bd6 14. O-O-O O-O-O $11) 11. Nc4 (11. f4 $1 exf4 12. Nc4 $1 {[%cal Ye4e5] would had put some unexpected problems for Black} f3 13. Nxd6+ (13. gxf3 Bg3+ $1) 13... cxd6 14. gxf3 Nh5 15. Qd2 Be6 16. O-O-O O-O-O 17. f4 $14 {White enjoys more space and can press the kingside pawns.}) 11... g5 $1 {Now Black stops f4-ideas at once.} 12. Qd2 Rg8 13. O-O-O b5 14. Ne3 (14. Nxd6+ cxd6 $11 {is harmless.}) 14... Be6 15. g4 {After the closing of kingside, it is difficult for both sides to make any progress, and the position is very equal.} (15. Ng1 O-O-O 16. Nf3 Nd7 17. Nh2 {[%cal Yh2g4]}) 15... O-O-O 16. c4 c6 17. f3 Nd7 18. Rhe1 f6 19. Nf5 Qf8 20. Kb1 Kb7 $11 {Neither side really wants to force an opening on the queenside where both kings are, and the likely result would be a draw but for it being a blitz game. Wey Yi eventually overpushed in the wrong moment and got an inferior position, then it was Deac's turn to blunder and be lost, but in the end Black won.} 21. Rc1 Bxf5 22. exf5 b4 23. Kc2 a5 24. a3 Nb6 25. Ra1 Bc7 26. Qe3 Qd6 27. Red1 Rge8 28. Bc1 Nd7 29. Qf2 Bb6 30. Be3 Ra8 31. Kb2 Ra7 32. Ra2 Rea8 33. a4 Re8 34. Kc2 Raa8 35. Bc1 Rad8 36. Qe3 Nf8 37. Rb2 Nd7 38. Kb1 Nb8 39. Rbd2 Na6 40. Bb2 Nc7 41. Nc1 Na6 42. Re2 Rf8 43. Qd2 Qc7 44. Re4 Qd7 45. Rde1 Bc7 46. Kc2 Rf7 47. Qf2 Qd6 48. f4 $2 gxf4 49. Qxh4 Qd7 50. Qf2 Rg7 51. Qf1 Rh8 {Black simply organises strong pressure against White's kingside.} 52. Qf3 Rgh7 $15 53. Rh1 Qg7 54. Ne2 Nb8 55. Ng1 Nd7 56. Qg2 Nf8 57. Nf3 {[%cal Yg4g5]} Rg8 58. Rhe1 Nd7 59. Rh1 Nf8 60. g5 fxg5 $2 (60... Rh5 61. Qe2 Rxg5 $1 62. Nxg5 Qxg5 $15 {[%csl Gf5]}) 61. Nxe5 Qh6 62. Ng4 $18 Qh4 63. Nf6 Rgg7 64. Nxh7 Rxh7 65. f6 g4 66. Re7 f3 67. Qd2 $2 (67. Qf1 $1 $18 {[%csl Yf3] keeps the f3-pawn under surveillance.}) 67... g3 $19 68. Rxh7 Nxh7 69. f7 g2 70. Rg1 Bh2 71. Rxg2 fxg2 72. Qxg2 Bd6 73. Qf3 Nf8 74. Qf5 Qg3 75. Kb1 Qg6 76. Qxg6 Nxg6 77. Bg7 Bf8 78. Bf6 Kc7 79. h4 Ne7 80. h5 Nf5 81. Kc2 Nh6 82. Be5+ Kd7 83. d4 Nxf7 84. Bf6 Ke6 85. Bh4 cxd4 86. Kd3 Be7 87. Bg3 Bd8 88. Ke4 Ng5+ 89. Kd3 Kf5 90. Bd6 Ne4 91. Bf8 Bb6 92. h6 Nf6 93. Be7 Kg6 94. h7 Nxh7 95. Ke4 Nf6+ 96. Ke5 d3 {Despite this being a blitz game with many understandable errors due to time trouble, the h5-idea displayed by Deac is very interesting and useful against the 5.e2 variation.} 0-1


