1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 b6 $5 8. Bg5 Nd5 $1 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. e4 $5 {Trying to take advantage of White's lead in development.} (10. Qxc4 Ba6 11. Qc2 Nd7 {[%cal Yc7c5];0-1 Studer,N (2493)-Bacrot,E (2715) Biel GM 50th 2017 (5) was just ok for Black -}) 10... Nb4 11. Qc3 c5 $1 {Black should contest White's center at the first chance.} (11... Ba6 {would be similar, but gives White more options} 12. a3 N4c6 13. Nbd2 (13. d5 $6 Na5 14. Nbd2 Nd7 15. Rfe1 Rad8 $15) 13... Na5 14. Rfe1 {[%cal Yg2f1]} (14. Ne5 c5 15. d5 Nd7 {transposes to the game}) 14... c5 (14... Nd7) 15. d5 $1 Nd7 16. Bf1 {Besides recapturing the pawn and keeping the f3, which is a better piece in this structure (see Gelfand-Hammer), White still has a subtle threat here, for example} Rad8 $6 17. b3 $1 $14 {[%cal Yb3c4]}) 12. a3 N4c6 13. d5 Na5 {This knight is having a lot of work!} 14. Nbd2 Ba6 {Black tries to solve his development problem while keeping the material advantage.} 15. Ne5 {There are two games with this move, but the position is very fresh, maybe White can to try other ideas in future.} ({For example} 15. Rfe1 $146 {[%cal Yg2f1]} Nd7 16. Bf1 {[%cal Yb2b3] reaching the position proposed in the notes to Black's 11th move} Rfe8 $1 {preparing a nice idea} (16... exd5 17. exd5 Qf6 18. Ne5 $1) 17. b4 (17. b3 exd5 18. exd5 Qf6 $1 {[%csl Ye5] Now e5 is avoided} 19. Qxf6 Nxf6 20. bxc4 Rxe1 21. Rxe1 Re8 $11 {[%csl Yc4] Black keeps up good pressure against c4}) 17... Nb7 18. Bxc4 Bxc4 19. Nxc4 exd5 20. exd5 Qf6 21. Qxf6 Nxf6 22. d6 Rxe1+ 23. Rxe1 cxb4 24. axb4 Kf8 $1 {and again Black is doing fine} (24... b5 25. Re7 $1) 25. Ra1 (25. Re7 $2 Nxd6 $1) 25... b5 26. Nb6 Rd8 27. Rxa7 Nxd6 $11) (15. Nh4 $5 $146 {also looks very interesting, with ideas of d6, e5 or even f4. It needs to be more deeply analysed and tested, but one illustrative variation could be} Nd7 16. e5 $1 (16. Rfe1 exd5 17. exd5 Qf6) (16. f4 Nf6 17. d6 Qd7 $1 $13) 16... exd5 17. Bxd5 Qxe5 $5 {maybe the best practical solution} 18. Bxa8 Rxa8 19. Rfe1 Qxc3 20. bxc3 g6 $44) 15... Nd7 {transposes to the game} 16. f4 {Keeping the tension.} (16. Nexc4 {was harmless for Black} exd5 17. exd5 Qf6 18. Rfc1 Nxc4 19. Nxc4 Qxc3 20. Rxc3 Bxc4 21. Rxc4 Rfe8 $11 {½-½ Gelfand,B (2737)-Hammer,J (2632) 21st European Teams 2017 (1.5)}) 16... Nf6 {The position remains tense and Black should be careful, but he has already finished his development and kept the pawn.} 17. Rae1 (17. Ndxc4 {wouldn't make sense} Nxc4 18. Nxc4 Bxc4 19. Qxc4 exd5 20. exd5 Qe3+ $1 21. Kh1 Rfe8 {Black has a pleasant position}) 17... Rfe8 {Deac has obtained an easier position.} 18. dxe6 $6 (18. Ndf3 $1 {was interesting and difficult to calculate} h6 (18... exd5 19. exd5 Nxd5 $2 20. Qc2 {[%cal Gf3g5]} Nf6 21. Ng5 Rad8 22. Ng4 $1 $18 {[%csl Rh7][%cal Gg4f6,Re1e7]}) 19. Ng5 $1 hxg5 20. fxg5 Nh7 21. Rxf7 Qxg5 (21... Qxf7 22. Nxf7 Kxf7 23. e5 $18 {[%cal Yd5e6]}) 22. h4 $1 Qh6 23. Ng4 Qg6 24. Ne5 Qh6 25. Ng4 {a funny draw :)}) 18... Qxe6 $15 19. Ndf3 h6 20. g4 Nh7 $2 {Now the game becomes very unclear and there are mistakes on both sides, probably due to time pressure on the players.} (20... Bb7 $1 {[%csl Ge4] would be very annoying for White}) 21. h4 (21. Nh4 $5 {[%cal Yh4f5]}) 21... Nb3 $1 {[%cal Yb3d4] The knight is coming back to the game.} 22. g5 Rad8 ({A more precise move was} 22... hxg5 23. hxg5 Nd4 $1 24. f5 (24. Nxd4 cxd4 25. Qxd4 Nxg5 $1) 24... Qe7 25. Nxf7 $1 Qxf7 26. g6 Qe7 27. gxh7+ Kh8 $1 $13) 23. f5 $40 {The attack looks very threatening now.} Qd6 24. f6 $2 {But the execution was wrong.} (24. Nxf7 $1 Kxf7 25. e5 $1 {[%csl Ye5,Yf5,Rf7,Yg5] The pawns rolling over Black's position give a good signal of what is coming} Qc7 (25... Qe7 26. g6+ Kg8 27. gxh7+ Kh8 28. f6 Qe6 29. h5 $1 $18 {[%cal Gf3h4,Gh4g6]}) 26. e6+ Kg8 27. f6 $1 {Black's position is crushed by the pawns} gxf6 28. gxf6 Nxf6 $8 29. Qxf6 Qg7 30. Ne5 $1 $18) 24... hxg5 25. Nxf7 Kxf7 26. e5 Qd7 $2 {In time pressure, both attack and defence are difficult to handle.} (26... Qe6 27. hxg5 g6 $1 $19) 27. e6+ $6 (27. hxg5 $1 Nd4 (27... g6 28. e6+ Rxe6 29. Bh3 $18) 28. g6+ $1 Kxg6 29. Nh4+ Kf7 30. Qg3 $40) 27... Rxe6 28. Rxe6 $2 (28. Bh3 $1 g4 $1 29. Bxg4 Rxe1 30. Bxd7 Rxf1+ 31. Kxf1 Nxf6 $1 32. Ng5+ Kg8 33. Be6+ Kf8 34. Ke1 $1 $14 {[%cal Ge6c4]}) 28... Qxe6 $19 29. Ne5+ Kg8 30. f7+ Kf8 31. Bh3 g4 $6 (31... Qd6 $19) 32. Bxg4 Qh6 $4 {Between time pressure and the many complications of a difficult position, suddenly White is winning again.} 33. Nd7+ (33. Qe1 $3 {[%cal Ge5d7,Ye1e8]} Nf6 (33... Bb5 34. Qe4 {[%cal Re5g6]} Nf6 35. Ng6+ Kxf7 36. Be6+ Ke8 37. Bxc4+ $3 Nxe4 38. Bxb5+ Rd7 39. Rf8# {A spectacular mate!}) 34. Nc6 $1 {[%csl Re7]} Rd7 35. Bxd7 $18) 33... Rxd7 34. Bxd7 {Now the emotion is over and Black is winning.} (34. Qe5 $1 {[%cal Ge5e8,Ge5b8]} Rd8 (34... Nf6 35. Rxf6) 35. Re1 Kxf7 36. Qe7+ Kg8 37. Qxd8+ Nf8 38. Be6+ Kh7 39. Qxf8 {[%cal Re6f5,Re6g8]} Qg6+ 40. Kf2 $1 $18) 34... Qg6+ 35. Kh2 Qd6+ 36. Qg3 Qxd7 37. Qe5 Nf6 {A tense and complicated game, in a short time control where neither player was able to find the best moves all the time. But it was theoretically interesting for this variation, showing some aggressive ideas for White and how to handle the position for Black.} 0-1


