{An important theoretical dispute in a recently popular line. Black reacted in the most principled way but White's trumps still turned out to be higher. It seems that Black has to work out his defence more precisely or choose some other earlier way...} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg5 Nbd7 7. e3 c5 8. Be2 {Recently this modest bishop's advance is becoming more popular than the approved 8. Bd3.} Qa5 9. O-O Bxc3 10. bxc3 c4 11. Qc2 Ne4 12. Rac1 {This position is being tested these days.} Nb6 {A typical manoeuvre. Black is heading his knight towards White's Q-side, at the same time opening a route for his light-squared bishop. However, his K-side might lack protection.} (12... O-O $2 {fails to} 13. Bxc4 $1) (12... b5 $6 13. Bf4 Bb7 14. Ne5 Nb6 15. f3 Nd6 16. Nc6 $1 Qa3 17. Na5 $1 Bc8 18. e4 {was favourable for White in the game Hammer - Aleksandrov, Dubai 2011}) (12... Nxg5 $5 {is playable:} 13. Nxg5 Nf6 (13... h6 14. Nf3 O-O 15. Nd2 $14 {was somewhat better for White in Edouard - Moor, Switzerland 2012}) 14. e4 h6 15. Nxf7 $5 (15. Nf3 $5 Nxe4 16. Bxc4 {is worth considering}) 15... Kxf7 16. e5 Ne8 $5 ({after} 16... Nh7 17. Bh5+ Kg8 18. Qg6 Nf8 19. Qf7+ Kh7 20. f4 Bd7 21. f5 {White has obtained excellent compensation for the piece, Douven - Ikonnikov, Sochi 1990}) 17. Bh5+ Ke7 18. f4 Kd8 19. f5 Bd7 {with a very unclear position, in which White keeps sufficient compensation for the piece thanks to his powerful central passers. The game Cheparinov - Alekseev, Moscow 2011, continued} 20. Rce1 Qa3 21. Qd2 (21. Qf2 $5 Qxc3 22. Bf7 $13) 21... Bc6 (21... Kc7 $5 22. Qf4 Kb6) 22. Qf4 Kc7 23. Qg3 Kb6 24. Rb1+ Ka6 {and here a draw was agreed though Black's chances are probably better.}) 13. Bf4 O-O (13... Qa4 14. Qb2 $14 {didn't improve Black's position much in Dambacher - Halkias, Netherlands 2007.}) 14. Ne5 $5 {White begins action in the center without delay.} ({Alexander already tried} 14. Rfe1 Re8 15. Ng5 Bf5 16. Nxe4 Bxe4 17. Qb2 Na4 18. Qa3 b5 {and Black has got acceptable play. The game Shimanov - Gajewski, Stockholm 2011 continued} 19. f3 Bg6 20. Bd1 Rac8 $2 (20... Bd3 $1 {was fine for Black}) 21. Re2 Re6 22. Rb2 $1 Ra6 23. Bxa4 Qxa4 24. Qxa4 Rxa4 25. Rxb5 Rxa2 26. Rxd5 {and White converted his extra pawn.}) (14. Nd2 Bf5 {is fine for Black:} 15. Nxe4 Bxe4 16. Qd2 Qa3 17. h4 Rfe8 18. h5 h6 {and Black has obtained some edge though she eventually lost, Zhao Xue - Koneru, Nalchik 2010}) (14. Ng5 {, which has been played in Zhao Xue - T.Kosintseva, Nalchik 2010, should have been met by the simple} Bf5) ({The rather unexpected} 14. Nh4 $5 {is worth considering:} f6 15. f3 Ng5 16. e4 Nf7 17. Nf5 Bxf5 18. exf5 Rae8 19. Rce1 Na4 20. Bd2 b5 21. Bd1 a6 22. g4 Nd8 23. h4 Nc6 24. Kg2 Nb6 25. g5 {and White has got the better chances, Tseng - Vetter, corr. 2010.}) 14... g5 $5 {A principled but very risky reply, which must be thoroughly prepared at home. Black also tried some other options, let's take a look at them.} ({An immediate} 14... f6 $2 {would not be too good - White simply grabs the pawn by} 15. Nxc4 $1) (14... Nd6 $6 {is a clear mistake due to} 15. Nc6 $1 bxc6 16. Bxd6 {, Kalinitschew - Tischbierek, Berlin East 1984}) (14... Qa4 $5 {is not so clear. Here White can think about} 15. f3 $5 (15. Qb2 f6 {looks acceptable for Black, who has successfully pushed the knight away, Izeta - Campos, Seville 1990}) 15... Qxc2 16. Rxc2 $14 {with somewhat better chances in the ending.}) ({Black did not equalise after} 14... Re8 15. f3 Nd6 16. e4 Be6 17. Ng4 Nb5 18. Ne3 $14 {, Ding Liren - Hou Yifan, Danzhou 2012}) (14... Bf5 15. g4 $1 Be6 16. f3 Nf6 {has been played in Douven - I.Rogers, Groningen 1988. White's chances look preferable but he should have probably thought about his e-pawn advance now, or later while in the game he played} 17. Bg3 Rfe8 18. Rf2 Qa3 19. h4 Na4 20. h5 a5 21. Bh4 (21. h6 $5) 21... Nd7 22. f4 $6 f6 23. f5 $6 fxe5 24. fxe6 Rxe6 25. Rcf1 Nxc3 26. Qf5 Nxe2+ 27. Rxe2 Qd6 {and found himself in a lost position.}) 15. f3 Nxc3 16. Bxg5 Nxe2+ 17. Qxe2 f6 18. Bh6 (18. f4 {did not create any problems:} fxg5 19. Qh5 Bf5 20. g4 $1 Qa3 21. Qxg5+ Kh8 22. gxf5 Qxe3+ {with a draw.}) 18... fxe5 19. Bxf8 Kxf8 20. f4 $1 exd4 $2 (20... e4 $1 {should have been played, keeping the center closed. The following brief analysis shows that Black still faces real problems, but he keeps chances to hold on:} 21. f5 (21. Qh5 Be6 $5) 21... Qa3 $1 22. Qh5 Qe7 (22... Qxe3+ 23. Kh1 h6 {does not help:} 24. Qg6 (24. h4 $5 {is also interesting:} Bd7 (24... Qg3 25. f6 Be6 26. Qxh6+ Ke8 27. f7+ $1 Bxf7 28. Rxf7 Kxf7 29. Rf1+ Kg8 30. Rf5 $18) 25. Qg6 Ke7 26. f6+ Kd6 27. Qg7 Qxd4 28. Qe7+ Kc7 29. f7 e3 30. f8=Q Rxf8 31. Rxf8 {though Black is still alive after} e2 $1 32. Qxe2 Qxh4+ 33. Kg1 Qd4+ 34. Kf1 Bg4 35. Qf2 Qxf2+ 36. Kxf2 Kd6 {and his passers keep White in tension}) 24... Qg5 25. Qd6+ Qe7 26. Qxh6+ Qg7 27. Qh4 $40 {with a strong attack.}) 23. Rf4 ({in case of} 23. f6 $2 Qf7 24. Qh6+ Kg8 {there was no way to transfer White's rook to the g-file}) 23... Kg8 (23... Bd7 24. Rg4 $1 Qa3 $1 25. Re1 Ke7 26. Qxh7+ Kd6 27. Qg7 Re8 28. Rg6+ Kc7 29. f6 c3 30. f7 Rf8 31. Qe5+ Kc8 32. Rg8 c2 33. h4 $16) 24. Rcf1 Bd7 25. a4 $3 {(otherwise White could hardly make progress)} c3 $1 (25... Nxa4 $6 26. f6 Qf7 27. Qg5+ Kh8 28. Qg7+ $1 Qxg7 29. fxg7+ Kxg7 30. Rf7+ Kg6 $2 31. R1f6+ Kg5 32. Rd6 $18) 26. a5 Nc4 27. f6 Qf7 28. Qg5+ Kh8 29. Qg7+ Qxg7 30. fxg7+ Kxg7 31. Rf7+ Kg6 32. Rxd7 ({or} 32. h4 Rg8 (32... Nxe3 $4 33. R1f6+ Kh5 34. Rxh7+ Kg4 35. Rg7+ Kh5 36. g3 $18) 33. Rxd7 (33. g4 Kh6 $1 (33... Bxg4 $4 34. R1f6+ Kh5 35. Rxh7#)) 33... Nxe3 34. Rc1 Kf5 $1 35. Kf2 Ng4+ 36. Ke1 Ne3 37. Rxc3 Nxg2+ {followed by ...Ng2xh4}) 32... b5 $1 33. Rxd5 Nxe3 34. Rd6+ Kg5 35. Rb1 a6 (35... c2 36. Rxb5+ Kg4 37. h3+ Kg3 38. Rg5+ Kh4 39. Rc5 Rf8 40. Rd7 $1 Rf1+ 41. Kh2 Ng4+ $1 42. hxg4 c1=Q 43. Rxc1 Rxc1 {with decent drawing chances}) 36. Rc6 Nc4 37. Rc1 e3 38. Rxc3 Kf5 {and Black keeps good drawing chances thanks to his active pieces and the e-passer.}) 21. f5 $1 (21. exd4 $2 {would be a waste of important time:} Bf5 (21... Bd7 $5) 22. Qe5 Be4 23. Rce1 Qa3 {and White had to force a draw by} 24. Rxe4 dxe4 25. Re1 Qe7 26. Qh8+ Kf7 27. Qxh7+ Kf8 28. Qh8+ $11) 21... Qc5 (21... Qa3 {did not help either:} 22. exd4 (22. f6 $4 Qxe3+) (22. Qh5 $5 Qe7 23. Rf3 $1 Qf7 24. Qh6+ Ke8 25. exd4 $40) 22... Qe7 23. Qh5 Qf6 24. Rce1 {with a decisive attack:} Bd7 25. Qxh7 c3 26. Re3 c2 27. Rg3 $18) 22. f6 $1 ({Surely not} 22. exd4 $2 Qxd4+ 23. Kh1 Qf6) ({but White could have begun with} 22. Qh5) 22... d3 ({Or} 22... dxe3 23. Qh5 $1 Be6 24. Qxh7 e2+ 25. Rf2 d4 26. Qg7+ Ke8 27. f7+ Bxf7 28. Rxe2+ $1 Kd8 29. Qf6+ Kc8 30. Re7 $18) 23. Qh5 Qxe3+ (23... Be6 24. Qxh7 $18) (23... Nd7 24. Rf3 $18) 24. Kh1 d2 {Black was probably hoping for this resource but...} 25. Rc3 $1 {The only way!} (25. Rcd1 $2 {was slow:} Bh3 $1 26. Qxh7 Bxg2+ 27. Kxg2 Qe4+ 28. Qxe4 dxe4 29. Rxd2 Kf7 $132 {and Black was fighting.}) 25... d1=Q ({The rook was untouchable:} 25... Qxc3 26. Qh6+ {White gets a second queen soon.}) 26. Rxd1 Qxc3 27. Qh6+ Kf7 (27... Ke8 28. Qg7) 28. Qg7+ Ke6 29. Qe7+ Kf5 30. Rf1+ Kg4 31. Qg7+ Kh5 32. Qxh7+ {and Black resigned in view of the quick mate.} 1-0


