{White's pawn sacrifice seems to be the most dangerous way to counter his opponent's set-up. White is gaining time by pursuing Black's queen but it is still not easy to convert certain pressure into something substantial...} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 b5 8. a4 b4 9. Nfd2 $5 {This somewhat unexpected retreat seems to be the most dangerous for Black.} c6 10. Nxc4 Qxd4 ({In the game Mikhalevski - Hess, Wheeling 2012, Black rejected the gift:} 10... Ba6 $5 11. Rd1 Nbd7 12. Nbd2 (12. Bxc6 $2 Rc8 13. Bb5 Bb7 14. Qd3 Be4 $5 (14... a6 15. Bxd7 Qxd7 $44) 15. Qd2 Nb8 $5 16. Ne5 Bc2 17. Re1 Ne4 18. Qe3 Nd6 $44 19. Bd3 Nf5 20. Bxf5 exf5 21. Nd2 Re8 $36) 12... Rc8 13. e4 Nb6 {but it should not be equal:} 14. a5 (14. Nxb6 $5 axb6 (14... Qxb6 15. Nb3) 15. Nc4 Bxc4 16. Qxc4 c5 17. Qe2 cxd4 18. e5 $14) (14. b3 $5 Qxd4 (14... c5 15. d5 exd5 16. Nxb6 axb6 17. exd5 $14) 15. Bb2 Qd8 16. Nf1 Qe8 17. Nd6 Bxd6 18. Rxd6 $44) 14... Nxc4 15. Nxc4 Qd7 16. b3 Rfd8 17. Be3 Nd5 $5 {An interesting trick, useful to remember.} 18. Bd2 (18. exd5 $2 cxd5 19. Bf1 dxc4 20. bxc4 Qc6 21. Rac1 Bb7 22. d5 exd5 23. Bg2 Qa6 $17) 18... Nf6 19. Bf4 Qb7 20. Rac1 Bb5 21. Bf3 $5 ({after} 21. h3 Qa6 22. Be3 Nd5 23. Bd2 Nf6 24. Be3 Nd5 25. Bd2 Nf6 {a draw was agreed}) 21... Qa6 22. Qb2 $14 {White intends to improve slowly by h2-h4, Kg1-g2... Then the thematic} c5 $6 {did not bring the desired effect:} 23. d5 exd5 24. exd5 $36 {with initiative.}) 11. Rd1 (11. Bf4 {is harmless:} Ba6 (11... Nd5 $5) 12. Nbd2 Qc5 13. Rac1 {and here in the game Bulski - Zeberski, Litomysl 2011, Black could have got excellent play by} Nd5 $13) ({The tricky} 11. b3 $5 {is interesting but the principled} Qxa1 $5 (11... Qc5 12. Bb2 Ba6 13. Nbd2 {gives White the better chances:} Nbd7 $1 (13... Qh5 $6 14. Rfd1 $1 {increases Black's problems:} Rc8 ({or} 14... Rd8 15. Bf3 Qg6 16. Ne4 Rxd1+ 17. Rxd1 $16 Nbd7 $2 18. Bxf6 $1 Nxf6 19. Ne5 Qf5 20. Nxc6 Bf8 21. Nd4 Rc8 22. Qxc8 {1-0 Ganguly - Thejkumar, Kolkata 2012}) 15. Nf3 (15. Rac1 $5) 15... Nbd7 16. Rac1 Nb6 17. Nce5 c5 18. a5 Nbd5 {and here, in the game Gordon - Medina, Jakarta 2012, in which White has actually played the line 11. Rd1 Qc5 12. Nbd2 (see Meier - Fridman/Baden-Baden 2013), he could have obtained a tangible advantage by} 19. h4 $1 $16 {with the idea Nf3-g5}) 14. Rfd1 Rfd8 15. Rac1 $14) 12. Bb2 Qa2 13. Nbd2 Ba6 14. Ra1 Qxa1+ 15. Bxa1 Nbd7 {is unclear and playable for Black.}) (11. Be3 {is the main alternative:} Qd8 (11... Qg4 12. Ne5 ({in the game Grigoryan - Olszewski/Shenzhen 2011, White played} 12. Nbd2 {, which had to be met by} Nd5 $5 $13 {with acceptable play for Black}) 12... Qh5 13. Bf4 (13. Nxc6 $2 Nxc6 14. Qxc6 Ng4 {favours Black:} 15. h3 Nxe3 16. fxe3 Rb8 17. Qc7 Qc5 $1 (17... Ba6 18. Qxe7 Qxe2 19. Qxa7 Ra8 20. Qb6 Rab8 21. Qa7 Ra8 22. Qb6 Rab8 {1/2 Golichenko - Vysochin, Kiev 2012}) 18. Qxc5 (18. Qxb8 $2 Bd6 19. Qa8 Qxe3+ 20. Kh1 Qxg3 21. Kg1 Qh2+ 22. Kf2 Bc5+ 23. e3 Qe5 24. Qf3 Qxb2+ $19) 18... Bxc5 19. Kf2 Rd8 $17 {with a big advantage}) 13... Bd6 14. Bf3 Qh3 15. Rd1 Bxe5 16. Bxe5 Ng4 17. Bxg4 Qxg4 18. Bd6 Re8 19. f3 Qf5 20. Qxf5 exf5 21. Bxb4 $14 {with a small advantage in the ending}) 12. Rd1 Nd5 13. Bd4 Nd7 $1 (13... Ba6 $6 {is dubious:} 14. e4 Bxc4 15. Qxc4 Nb6 16. Qe2 $36 Qc8 (16... Qc7 $5) 17. a5 N6d7 18. e5 $1 Na6 19. Nd2 Ndc5 20. Qe3 Qc7 21. Nc4 Rfd8 22. Rac1 $16 {Gagunashvili - Shanava, Tbilisi 2012.}) 14. e4 N5b6 $1 (14... b3 $6 15. Qxb3 Nb4 16. Qc3 {was better for White in the game Gleizerov - Paikidze, Alghero 2011}) 15. Na5 (15. Nxb6 $6 axb6 16. Qxc6 {would be met by the amazing} Bb7 $1 17. Qxb7 (17. Qc2 $5 $15) 17... Nc5 18. Qc6 Rc8 19. Qb5 Nb3 20. Nd2 Nxd4 $36) 15... c5 16. Nc6 Qe8 17. Be3 a5 {is okay for Black:} 18. e5 Nd5 (18... Ba6 $5 19. Nxe7+ Qxe7 20. Bxa8 Rxa8 21. Nd2 Rc8 $44) 19. Rxd5 $5 (19. Nd2 Bb7 20. Nxe7+ Qxe7) 19... exd5 20. Bxd5 Ba6 (20... Ra6 $6 21. Nd2 $36) 21. Nd2 Rc8 {with a complex play.}) 11... Qc5 12. Be3 Qh5 13. Nbd2 Ng4 {This is the only move Black has tried here, according to Megabase 2013. However, other moves have already been played.} (13... Ba6 $6 {is bad:} 14. Bf3 $1 ({not} 14. h3 $2 Nd5 15. Bd4 $2 c5 16. Be5 Nc6 $17 {Zanan - Sihite, Biel 2011}) 14... Ng4 15. Bxg4 Qxg4 16. f3 Qg6 17. Ne4 h5 18. Rac1 h4 19. Kg2 $16 {and Black cannot get his knight into play.}) ({Actually I prefer not to hurry with the knight's exchange:} 13... Nd5 $5 14. Nb3 (14. Bd4 $2 {favoured Black in the game Zanan - A.Dewi, Biel 2011:} c5 15. e4 Nc6 $1 16. Nb3 Nxd4 17. Nxd4 cxd4 18. exd5 exd5 19. Na5 Bf6 $17) ({but such options as} 14. Bf3 $5) ({or} 14. Ne4 $5 {are worth considering}) 14... Nxe3 $5 (14... Ba6 $6 15. Bc5) (14... Nd7 15. Nd4 (15. Bf3 $5 {deserves attention:} Qg6 (15... Qh3 16. Nba5 c5 17. Bf4 $1 Ba6 18. Nc6 Bf6 19. Bd6 Rfc8 20. N4a5 $16 { e2-e4}) 16. Qxg6 hxg6 17. Nba5 {and White restores the material balance and secures a small advantage}) 15... Bf6 16. Nxc6 Bb7 17. Bf3 Qh3 18. N4a5 (18. Nxa7 Nxe3 19. Nxe3 b3 $1 (19... Rxa7 20. Rxd7 Be4 21. Qxe4 Rxd7 22. Qxb4 $16 {Pa}) (19... Bxf3 20. Rxd7 $16) 20. Qxb3 Bxf3 21. Rxd7 Bxe2 22. Nc6 h5 $44) 18... Bxc6 (18... Nxe3 19. fxe3 Bxc6 20. Nxc6 Nb6 21. e4 e5 22. a5 Nd7 23. Qd2 Nc5 24. Qxb4 Ne6 25. Rd5 $16) 19. Nxc6 Rac8 20. Bf4 b3 $5 21. Qxb3 (21. Qc1 $5) 21... Rxc6 22. Bxd5 $1 Rb6 (22... exd5 23. Qxd5 Rc2 24. Qxd7 $16) 23. Bg2 $1 Rxb3 24. Bxh3 Nb6 $14 {and Black gets the pawn back though White is still somewhat better}) 15. Nxe3 a6 {followed by ...Ra8-a7 with acceptable play, though Black is still under pressure.}) 14. Nf3 Nxe3 (14... e5 $5 {is also worth considering but it doesn't completely solve the problems:} 15. Bd2 $1 b3 $5 16. Qxb3 Bc5 $5 (16... e4 {is well met by} 17. h3 $1 Nxf2 18. Kxf2 exf3 {and here in the game Edvardsson - Zumsande, Reykjavik 2012, White could have secured a stable advantage by the simple} 19. Qxf3 $1 $14) 17. Be1 e4 18. h3 exf3 19. hxg4 Qxg4 20. Ne3 $1 Bxe3 21. exf3 Qxg3 $1 22. fxe3 Qg6 23. Rac1 $44 {with more than sufficient compensation for the pawn.}) 15. Nxe3 a5 16. Nd4 $5 (16. Nc4 Ra7 ({after} 16... Ba6 17. Rac1 Ra7 18. Nfe5 Bxc4 19. Nxc4 {Black was under pressure in the game Gelfand - Ponomariov, RUS-chT Olginka 2011}) 17. Nd4 (17. Rac1 $44) 17... Ba6 {was fine for Black in H.Hernandez - Krysa, Montevideo 2011:} 18. Rac1 Bf6 (18... Rd7 $5) 19. Qe4 $2 (19. Ne3 $5 $44) 19... Rd7 20. Nb3 (20. Nxc6 Rxd1+ 21. Rxd1 Nxc6 22. Qxc6 Bxc4 23. Qxc4 Bxb2 $17) 20... Bxc4 21. Qxc4 Bxb2 $17 {with a big advantage.}) 16... Ra7 (16... Ba6 $5 {came to mind as well.}) 17. Rac1 ({Any capture of the c6-pawn made Black's play easier:} 17. Nxc6 $6 Nxc6 18. Qxc6 Qxe2) ({or} 17. Bxc6 $6 Rc7 18. Bf3 Rxc2 19. Bxh5 Rc7 (19... Rxb2 $5 20. Nc4 e5 $1 21. Nxb2 exd4 $44) 20. Nb3 Bf6 $13) 17... Ba6 (17... Rd7 18. Bf3 Qe5 (18... Qg5 $5 19. h4 Qe5) 19. Nc4 Qc7 20. Nb3 $14 {looked better for White.}) 18. Bf3 ({After} 18. f4 Rc8 ({or} 18... Bd8 $5 {with the idea ... Bd8-b6 Black was okay.})) 18... Qe5 19. Nxc6 $2 {This impatient capture helps Black to solve all the problems.} (19. Ng4 $1 {was much stronger:} Qc7 ({not} 19... Qg5 $2 20. Nxc6 Nxc6 21. h4 $1 (21. Qxc6 Bb7 22. Qb6 Bxf3 23. Qxa7 $2 Bxg4) 21... Nd4 $5 (21... Qf5 22. Qxc6 Rb8 (22... Bb7 $2 23. Qb6 Bxf3 24. Qxa7 $18) 23. Rd7 Rxd7 24. Qxd7 Bf8 25. Rc7 $18) 22. Rxd4 Qg6 23. Qd1 $16) 20. Bxc6 $1 (20. Nxc6 Nxc6 21. Qxc6 Rc8) 20... Qc8 (20... Rd8 21. Nb5 Bxb5 22. Bxb5 Qxc2 23. Rxd8+ Bxd8 24. Rxc2 Rc7 25. Rd2 $14) (20... Qb6 21. Bb5 $14) 21. Bb5 Qxc2 22. Rxc2 $14 {and White maintains a small advantage.}) 19... Nxc6 20. Qxc6 Qb8 21. Nc4 Rc8 (21... Bg5 $5 {deserved serious attention:} 22. Ne3 (22. e3 $4 Bb7) 22... Rc8 23. Qd6 Qxd6 24. Rxc8+ Qf8 25. Rxf8+ Kxf8 $15 {with better chances in the ending.}) 22. Qb6 Qxb6 23. Nxb6 Rxc1 (23... Rcc7 $5) 24. Rxc1 Bd8 25. Nc4 {White' strong knight on c4 does not give Black any chances for advantage.} Bxc4 ({Or} 25... Rc7 26. Rd1 $1 Rc8 27. Nd6 Rc2 28. Be4 $5 Rxe2 29. Bf3 Rc2 30. Be4 $11 {with a draw as} Rc7 $2 {fails to} 31. Nb5 Rc8 32. Na7 $18) 26. Rxc4 Rc7 27. Rxc7 Bxc7 28. e3 b3 29. Bd1 Be5 30. Bxb3 Bxb2 31. Kg2 {and the players signed the scoresheets.} 1/2-1/2


