{Wei Yi won many unclear matches in the World Cup and was stopped in the quarter finals by Svidler, losing the first game where he had some advantage after 5 difficult draws.} 1. b3 {The Chinese prodigy had problems in the openings in this match, so he correctly decided to change his first move.} e5 2. Bb2 Nc6 3. e3 Nf6 4. Bb5 Bd6 5. Ne2 (5. Na3 {is more popular but Black has many good weapons at his disposal.}) 5... O-O 6. O-O Re8 {Changing from the game Wei Yi-Karjakin, where Black played 6...a6.} 7. Ng3 {[#]} a6 {I don't think this is precise here.} (7... Bf8 {is more logical and if White wants to fight for an advantage, an interesting sequence is:} 8. f4 exf4 9. Rxf4 Ne5 {!} 10. Rf5 a6 {!} 11. Bxe5 Rxe5 12. Rxe5 axb5 { With full compensation thanks to the oddly placed rook.}) 8. Be2 Bf8 (8... b5 {!?}) 9. c4 {! The white pieces are nicely placed for this move.} d5 10. cxd5 Nxd5 11. Nc3 Be6 12. Rc1 Ndb4 {?! Not an easy position to play in a rapid time control. I would fight for the e4 square with:} (12... Nxc3 {!?} 13. Bxc3 f5 {∞}) 13. d3 Qd7 {Here it seems necessary to fight for the control of c5 by playing} (13... a5 {!?} 14. a3 Na6) 14. a3 Nd5 {[#]} 15. Nce4 {⩲ White simply takes the bishop pair after the loss of two tempi by his opponent.} a5 16. Ng5 Nb6 17. Nxe6 Qxe6 18. Bg4 Qd6 19. Qc2 Nd5 {This knight just moved too many times!} 20. Rfd1 {±} Red8 21. Bf3 g6 22. Ne4 Qe6 {[#]} 23. Nc5 {?! White should keep the pressure and not go for the second bishop. Some improving moves like Qc4, g3, Kg2, h4 and waiting for a good opportunity to open the position was better.} Bxc5 24. Qxc5 Ra6 {! This strong rook maneuver, putting some pressure on the b3 pawn as well as parrying the Qb5 threat was probably missed by White.} 25. Qc4 Rb6 26. g3 {?! A prophylactic move. Instead, 26.Ba1 followed by Rb1 was needed.} Nde7 {! [#]} 27. Qxe6 {Losing all the remaining edge, but the only way to keep an advantage was too difficult to find with little time on the clock.} (27. Rc3 {!! ⩲ and if Black tries to repeat moves with} Nd5 28. Rc2 Nde7 29. d4 {! is strong now that the bishop on b2 is protected by the rook.}) 27... fxe6 {∞} 28. b4 (28. Bxc6 Nxc6 29. Rc3 e4 {! is very ok for Black.}) 28... axb4 29. axb4 Nd5 30. Bc3 Rd7 31. d4 (31. Bxd5 {is the other way to play for equality.}) 31... exd4 (31... Nxc3 {!? It is maybe a good idea to swap one bishop.} 32. Rxc3 Nxb4 33. dxe5 Rxd1+ 34. Bxd1 Nd5 35. Rc1 c6 {The passed pawns should ensure Black's advantage.}) 32. Bxd4 Rxb4 33. Bc5 {?! The wrong diagonal. The bishop would be better placed on a1.} Ra4 34. Be2 Ra5 35. e4 Nf6 36. Rxd7 Nxd7 37. Be3 Kf7 {⩱} 38. Rb1 Nd8 {[#]} (38... b6 {immediately is more logical.}) 39. f4 {On the verge of collapsing, White chooses the right path and goes for opening the position.} b6 40. Rd1 Ke7 41. f5 {!} exf5 42. exf5 Nf7 43. Bf4 Nde5 44. Rc1 {White is provoking the pawns to advance. Much more natural is} (44. fxg6 hxg6 45. h4 {with good drawing chances.}) 44... c6 45. Be3 b5 46. Bc5+ Kf6 47. fxg6 hxg6 48. Rf1+ Ke6 49. Bd1 Ng5 {? The rook should be improved first. 49....Ra8 would have given Black a big advantage.} 50. Bb3+ Nc4 {[#]} 51. Kg2 {? Missing the chance:} (51. Bb4 {!} Ra8 52. Re1+ {Black has some problems now to stop the checks:} Kd5 53. Rd1+ Ke5 54. Re1+ Kd4 (54... Ne4 {?} 55. Bc2 {+⁠−}) 55. Rd1+ Ke4 56. Re1+ Ne3 {A try not to repeat moves.} 57. Kf2 {!} Nh3+ 58. Ke2 {and somehow the black pieces completely lost coordination.}) 51... Ra8 {More precise is} (51... Ne4 52. Re1 Kd5 {∓ is almost over.}) 52. Bb4 (52. Bc2 {!} Ra2 (52... Kd5 53. Bf2 {! was still a fight.}) 53. Rf2 Rxc2 $5 54. Rxc2 Kd5 55. Bf2 b4 56. Rc1 $1 {Looks risky but is holdable.}) 52... Ne4 $1 {∓ Now the black moves play themselves. The knights are doing an excellent job of controlling the bishops now.} 53. Re1 Kd5 54. Rd1+ Ke5 55. Re1 Kd4 56. Rd1+ Ke3 57. Rc1 {? Strange. If White had continued with checks Black would have needed to be precise to conclude the game: Black's made real progress, and now Svidler goes in for the kill.} (57. Re1+ Kd3 58. Rd1+ Ncd2 59. Bf7 c5 {!?} 60. Bxd2 Nxd2 61. Bxg6+ Ke2 62. Bh5+ Ke3 {∓ Black pawns should be faster than White's.}) 57... c5 {−⁠+ It is all over now.} 58. Re1+ Kd4 59. Rd1+ Ke5 60. Bxc4 bxc4 61. Be1 Ra3 62. Kf1 Ra2 63. Rc1 Kd4 64. Rd1+ Ke3 65. Rc1 Kd3 66. Rd1+ Nd2+ {Black is simply too active. The pawn rolls forward.} 67. Bxd2 Rxd2 68. Ke1 c3 {The junior is eliminated after a tense fight. Black threatens Ke3, Rxh2 and there is nothing White can do about it.} (68... Rxd1+ 69. Kxd1 Ke3 {is actually also winning.}) 0-1


