1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {Mikhalevski, V: 'Recently the young Chinese super GM switched from the Four Knights to the Spanish.'} Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Nd6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. h3 {Mikhalevski, V: 'This move is gaining more and more popularity. Earlier White preferred to start with 9.Nc3.'} Bd7 10. Rd1 Be7 11. g4 Nh4 12. Nxh4 Bxh4 13. Nd2 Kc8 14. Nf3 Be7 15. Rd3 h6 {Mikhalevski, V: 'As I had already mentioned before, Black's idea was to prevent 16.Bg5.'} (15... b5 {occurred in Kasimdzhanov, R (2706)-Radjabov, T (2726)/Baku AZE 2014/[Mikhalevski, V]. Find the game in our PGN archive for detailed information about the current line.}) ({I also considered} 15... c5 {in my annotations to the aforementioned game.}) 16. Nd4 {Mikhalevski, V: 'The knight is heading to f5. White has to make this move before Black plays ...c5.'} ({White also tested} 16. Bf4 {, but it looks inaccurate.} c5 $1 {Taking away the d4-square from the White's knight.} 17. Rad1 Be6 18. b3 b5 $15 {with a promising position for Black in Abdumalik, Z (2332)-Pashikian, A (2617) /Al-Ain UAE 2014.}) 16... b6 {Mikhalevski, V: '!?' '!?' Mikhalevski, V: 'An attempt to improve upon the only preceding game. As usual in the Berlin with the king on c8, Black uses the b7-square for the king.'} (16... Re8 $5 17. Bf4 c5 18. Nf5 Bf8 19. c4 a6 20. Ne3 b5 21. b3 g5 22. Bg3 Be6 23. Rad1 Kb7 $11 {with equal chances in Caruana, F (2782)-Grischuk, A (2785)/Warsaw 2013.}) 17. Rf3 Be8 18. Nf5 Bf8 19. b3 {Mikhalevski, V: '!?' '!?' Mikhalevski, V: 'The bishop will be well placed on the a1-h8 diagonal.'} Bd7 {Mikhalevski, V: 'Ding Liren brings the bishop to e6.'} (19... g6 $5 {deserved attention, driving the annoying knight away.} 20. Ng3 Kb7 ({or} 20... Bg7 21. Bb2 c5 22. Rd1 Kb7) 21. Bb2 Bg7 22. Rd1 c5 23. c4 Rf8 24. Rfd3 Bc6 25. f4 Rae8 $11 {and Black is fine.}) 20. Bb2 Be6 ({Black could have started with} 20... h5 21. g5 {and only then} Be6 22. Nd4 Bd5) 21. Nd4 {Mikhalevski, V: '!' '!' Mikhalevski, V: 'Forcing the bishop to d5 where it will be attacked by the c-pawn.'} Bd5 22. Re3 Bc5 {Mikhalevski, V: '!' '!'} 23. c4 Be6 24. f4 (24. Rd3 $5 {deserved attention. For example,} Bxd4 25. Bxd4 c5 26. Be3 h5 27. f3 Kb7 28. Kg2 Rae8 29. Kg3 {with some slight pressure, although Black should be able to hold a draw.}) 24... g6 {Mikhalevski, V: 'Black stops 25.f5 and the pin along the a7-g1-diagonal yields Black slightly better chances.'} 25. Rf1 {Mikhalevski, V: 'Renewing the idea of f5.'} Kb7 {Mikhalevski, V: '!' '!'} 26. Kg2 (26. f5 gxf5 27. gxf5 Bd7 28. Kh1 (28. e6 Rhg8+ 29. Kh1 fxe6 30. fxe6 Be8 $15 {turns out to be better for Black because of the bad position of White's king and Black's bishop pair.}) 28... Rae8 $15 {and the e-pawn is becoming vulnerable.}) 26... Rad8 (26... h5 $5 {deserved attention, trying to force an opening of the lines near White's king.} 27. f5 (27. Kg3 hxg4 28. hxg4 Rad8 29. Re4 Rh7 $17 {is dangerous for White as Black is going to double on the h-file.}) 27... gxf5 28. gxf5 Bd7 29. Rg3 h4 30. Rg4 Rhe8 31. Ne2 Rad8 32. Rxh4 Bc8 {with an initiative for the sacrificed pawn.}) 27. Rd3 $1 {This move is the start of an excellent concept. It seems as if White is pinning himself, but this is not the end of the story.} h5 {Mikhalevski, V: 'It seems that the highest rated Chinese player underestimated the coming exchange sacrifice.'} (27... Bxd4 28. Rxd4 Rdg8 $1 {Preventing the move f5, would have given Black excellent chances to draw the game. However, h5 seemed so tempting...}) (27... Bc8 $1 {is much safer, and only after} 28. Rfd1 h5 29. Ne6 Rxd3 30. Nxc5+ bxc5 31. Rxd3 hxg4 32. hxg4 Rh4 {with a minimal edge for Black, although White shouldn't have problems holding.}) 28. Nxe6 {Mikhalevski, V: '!' '!' The point:} Rxd3 29. Nxc5+ bxc5 30. e6 {Mikhalevski, V: '!' '!' Mikhalevski, V: 'White's moves are forced.' A simple attack on the rook, but it is not so easy to deal with.} Rhd8 {Mikhalevski, V: '!' '!'} (30... Rf8 $2 {Mikhalevski, V: '??' '??' Mikhalevski, V: 'would be a blunder because of'} 31. Bg7 {Mikhalevski, V: '+-' '+-' loses instantly.}) (30... Re8 $2 31. exf7) 31. exf7 {Mikhalevski, V: 'It turns out that Black's defence is not an easy task.' The pawn on f7 is still quite powerful. Black has a tough defense ahead of him.} Rd2+ $2 {Mikhalevski, V: 'This move is the decisive mistake.'} (31... Rf8 32. f5 $1 gxf5 33. g5 (33. Rxf5 hxg4 34. hxg4 Rd2+ 35. Kg3 Rxb2 36. g5 Re2 37. Rf6 Re1 38. Kg4 $14 {is dangerous for Black.}) 33... Rxf7 34. g6 Rf8 35. g7 Rg8 36. Be5 $1 {Still is unpleasant for Black.} (36. Rxf5 $6 Rd2+ 37. Rf2 Rxb2 38. Rxb2 Rxg7+ $11)) (31... h4 {Mikhalevski, V: '!' Mikhalevski, V: 'was necessary, with the idea to meet'} 32. Rf3 $1 {Mikhalevski, V: 'is stronger and promises some edge for White.'} (32. Bg7 Rg3+ 33. Kf2 Rd2+ 34. Ke1 Rgg2 {is a computer-like draw.}) (32. f5 {by} Rg3+ {once again Black uses his 31st move.} 33. Kf2 Rd2+ 34. Ke1 Rgg2 35. Rf3 Rxb2 36. Kf1 Rh2 37. Kg1 Rbg2+ 38. Kf1 Rxa2 39. Kg1 $11) 32... Rd2+ 33. Rf2 Rxf2+ 34. Kxf2 Rf8 35. f5 Rxf7 36. f6 (36. Kf3 gxf5 37. g5 Rd7 $1 {Black is just in time to create counterplay. The move 31...h4 is becoming very handy.} 38. g6 Rd3+ 39. Kf4 Rxh3 40. g7 Rg3 41. Be5 Rg2 42. Kxf5 h3 43. Kf6 Rf2+ 44. Ke6 Rg2 $11 {leads to a draw.}) 36... Kc8 37. Ke3 Kd7 38. Kf4 Ke6 39. Kg5 Rf8 40. Kxg6 Rg8+ 41. Kh7 Kf7 42. Bc1 Rg6 43. g5 Rg8 $11 {Black waits with the rook on g8 and g6 and holds a draw.}) 32. Rf2 {Mikhalevski, V: '+-' '+-' Mikhalevski, V: 'Now White's pawns on the kingside are unstoppable.'} Rxf2+ 33. Kxf2 Rf8 34. f5 $1 Rxf7 (34... gxf5 {doesn't help.} 35. g5 (35. gxh5 Rxf7 36. h6 Rh7 37. Bg7 Kc8 38. Kf3 Kd7 39. Kf4 Ke6 40. Kg5 Kf7 41. Kxf5 $18 {also wins.}) 35... Rxf7 36. g6 Rf8 37. g7 Rg8 38. Kf3 Kc8) 35. Kg3 $1 {Mikhalevski, V: 'White wins thanks to this clever move.' This is the point of the combination.} gxf5 (35... h4+ $1 {is a tougher defence.} 36. Kf4 $1 (36. Kxh4 $2 gxf5 37. g5 f4 $11 {is equal.}) 36... Kc8 37. f6 Kd7 38. Kg5 Ke6 39. Kxg6 Rd7 40. g5 Rd8 41. Bc3 Rg8+ 42. Kh5 Kf7 43. Kxh4 Kg6 44. Kg4 Re8 45. Bd2 Re2 46. Bf4 Rg2+ 47. Bg3 Rg1 48. h4 Rh1 49. Bxc7 Rg1+ 50. Bg3 Rh1 51. Bf2 Rh2 52. Bxc5 a6 53. a4 $18 {White creates a passed pawn on the queenside and wins.}) 36. g5 {Mikhalevski, V: '!' '!' '!' '!' Mikhalevski, V: 'and Black resigned as White advances his pawn to g7 and brings the king to support it. A very interesting fighting game, in which one mistake decided its outcome. From the theoretical point of view the line, which occurred in the game looks equal, but playable.' Despite Black's overwhelming material advantage, he is completely powerless against the simple g6-g7 followed by the forward king march. Black simply resigned before getting zugzwnaged to death.} (36. g5 Kc8 37. g6 Rf8 38. g7 Rg8 39. Kf4 Kd7 40. Kxf5 Ke7 41. Kg6 Ke6 {and White has many ways to win. He can play Ba3-xc5-f8 and then Kh7, trapping the rook and winning when Black runs out of moves, or taking on h5 and making way for the h-pawn.} 42. Ba3 $1 $18 {and White wins.}) ({But not} 36. gxh5 f4+ 37. Kf3 Rf5 $1 $11) 1-0


