1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Qb3 dxc4 6. Qxc4 O-O 7. e4 Be6 8. Qd3 ({In a later game from their match, Svidler opted for} 8. Qb5 {i.e.} Bd7 9. Qb3 c5 10. d5 Qb6 ({Black hasn't done very well with} 10... b5 $5 {but this looks more dynamic than the game move. After} 11. e5 {I suggest the unplayed} Ng4 12. Bf4 Qc7 {with double-edged play}) 11. Bc4 ({varying from the benign} 11. Qxb6 axb6 12. Bg5 e6 13. O-O-O exd5 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Nxd5 Bd8 $11 {Li Zuhao-Mu Ke, Canberra 2014}) 11... Bg4 12. Be3 Nbd7 13. Nd2 $1 Ne5 14. h3 Bc8 15. Be2 {with some pressure Svidler, P-Wei Yi, (fifth match game) Baku 2015.}) 8... c5 9. d5 Bg4 ({Facing this position (as Black!) a few years ago, Svidler preferred to retreat the whole way:} 9... Bc8 10. Be3 (10. Be2 e6 11. Bg5 h6 12. Be3 exd5 13. exd5 Na6 {Potkin, V-Nepomniachtchi, I Yaroslavl 2014. This definitely reminds one of the Prins Variation where the queen is odd on d3, but it could of course (if need be) drop back to d2 with a gain of tempo. Going further...} ({I suspect that} 13... Bf5 {is better than the 'natural' 13. ..Na6 e.g.} 14. Qd2 Ne4 15. Nxe4 Bxe4 $11) 14. Rd1 Ng4 15. Bf4 Bf5 16. Qd2 Nb4 17. O-O {turned out to favour White}) 10... b6 11. h3 e6 12. dxe6 Bxe6 13. Qxd8 Rxd8 14. Ng5 Nc6 15. Nxe6 fxe6 16. Bc4 Kf7 {Jakovenko, D-Svidler, P Moscow rapid 2012, doesn't seem to inconvenience Black too much (bishop pair and less pawn islands for White, but Black's knights are fine steeds).}) ({Going back to d7 may seem slightly odd (isn't it getting in the way?), but it worked well in the following:} 9... Bd7 10. Be3 Qa5 11. Nd2 Na6 12. Be2 b5 13. O-O c4 14. Qb1 Ng4 {Omar, Noa-Safarli, E Baku 2014.}) 10. Ng5 (10. Be3 Nbd7 11. Nd2 {(Black has to be careful about getting his minor pieces tangled, but he correctly and courageously continued in this example with...)} e6 $1 12. d6 (12. h3 exd5 $1 13. exd5 Bf5) 12... e5 13. Be2 Be6 $6 ({I prefer} 13... Bxe2 14. Qxe2 Qb6 15. Nc4 Qc6 {with an acceptable game}) 14. O-O Ne8 {(Black now lacks space)} 15. Rfd1 Rc8 16. Nc4 Rc6 17. Rd2 Qb8 18. a4 Bxc4 19. Qxc4 Nxd6 20. Qa2 {Vidit, S-Khusnutdinov, R Al-Ain 2015, with good compensation for the first player, as by winning the d-pawn Black has opened up lines for White's pieces.}) 10... h6 11. h3 Bc8 12. Nf3 e6 {Glenn Flear: 'Normally the addition of the moves h3 and ... h6 should be beneficial for White. However Black is quite active so Svidler makes the radical decision not to keep his d-pawn, as he must have judged it more 'isolated' than 'passed'!'} 13. dxe6 (13. Be2 exd5 14. exd5 Bf5 $11) (13. Be3 exd5 14. exd5 Bf5 15. Qd2 Ne4 {is at least equal.}) 13... Bxe6 14. Be3 Qe7 15. Rd1 Nc6 16. Qd6 {Glenn Flear: 'The idea is to leave Black with problems linked to the loose c-pawn.'} Qxd6 17. Rxd6 {A typical Grunfeld position. Black has some problems with his c5 pawn at the moment, but he is definitely better developed than White.} c4 (17... Na5 18. Bxc5 Rfc8 19. Be3 Rxc3 $1 {With strong counterplay.}) ({Also plausible is} 17... Nd7 {when the most challenging reply is} 18. Bb5 {. Here there is more than one way to obtain a correct position:} Nde5 (18... Rfc8 $5 19. Bxc6 Rxc6 20. Rxc6 bxc6 {leaves Black with doubled pawns, but not for long...} 21. Kd2 Rb8 22. b3 a5 {and ... c4 is coming}) 19. Bxc5 Nxf3+ 20. gxf3 Ne5 21. Be2 b6 22. Be3 Rfc8 {with adequate activity as compensation.}) 18. Rxe6 {Glenn Flear: '!?' Glenn Flear: 'A dynamic exchange sacrifice.' An obvious exchange sacrifice. White does get enough compensation for the lost material, but it is unlikely that it is any more than that.} fxe6 19. Bxc4 Rfe8 (19... Kf7 $1) 20. Nb5 {Glenn Flear: 'White has a pawn and good pieces for the exchange. He also has a superior pawn structure and threats of invading on c7 or d6.'} Na5 {Glenn Flear: '!' Glenn Flear: 'To deflect the annoying bishop.'} 21. Bd3 {Black has some issues since a7 is hanging and there is a fork that is being threatened on c7.} Rec8 22. Ke2 Nc4 $5 {The start of an unusual series of trades.} ({Glenn Flear: 'The more conventional'} 22... a6 {Glenn Flear: 'would have been many a player's choice.'} 23. Nd6 Rd8 24. e5 Nd7 25. Bxg6 $14) 23. Nxa7 $1 Nxe3 {Glenn Flear: 'Wei Yi gives back the exchange in order to obtain counterplay.'} 24. Nxc8 Nxg2 {Glenn Flear: 'The threat of ...Nf4+ is annoying, but Svidler finds a solution.'} 25. Ne7+ $1 (25. Rc1 Nf4+ 26. Ke3 Nxh3 $15) 25... Kf7 26. Nxg6 $1 {A nice detail. Because the knight covers f4, it cannot be ignored.} Kxg6 27. Rg1 Rxa2 (27... Nd7 28. Rxg2+ Kf7 {was probably better, gunning for the b2 pawn and taking control of e5.}) 28. Rxg2+ Kf7 {Glenn Flear: 'White temporarily has an extra pawn, but b2 is doomed. The only way forward is to create threats before Black gets sorted.'} 29. Ne5+ {White emergest upa a pawn and retains winning chances.} Kf8 ({Better than} 29... Kg8 $6 {as White would then obtain pressure with} 30. Bc4 Rxb2+ 31. Ke3 Rb6 32. f4 Kh7 33. Rd2) 30. Ng6+ Kf7 31. Nf4 Rxb2+ ({Black could also try} 31... b5 32. Kf3 ({the immediate} 32. Nxe6 {would be met with the tricky} Nh5 $1) 32... Rxb2 33. Nxe6 $1 Kxe6 34. Rxg7 Nd7 {with practical chances for the pawn.}) 32. Ke3 Bf8 33. Bc4 Rb6 {Black is just in time to defend his pawn, but even that endgame is unpleasant.} 34. Nxe6 {Glenn Flear: '!?'} (34. Rg6 $1 {is slightly awkward for Black who then needs a precise sequence to escape serious difficulties.} Ba3 $1 35. e5 Bc1+ 36. Kf3 Nh7 37. Rxh6 Ng5+ {and despite White's advantage being evident it may not be enough to win:} 38. Kg4 Rb4 $1) 34... Rxe6 35. e5 {Glenn Flear: '?!'} ({Glenn Flear: 'The best chance was offered by'} 35. f4 {Glenn Flear: '!'} Ke7 (35... b5 36. Ba2 Ke7 37. Bxe6 Kxe6 38. Kd4 {when the two connected passed pawns offer significant winning chances. In my experience Rook plus two supported connected passed pawns beat a bare Bishop and Knight. Here the presence of the b-pawn might not change very much.}) 36. Bxe6 Kxe6 37. Kd4 Nd7 $1 {seems close to a draw as well.}) 35... Nd7 36. f4 b5 $1 37. Bxe6+ Kxe6 38. Rd2 b4 $1 {Glenn Flear: 'White's problem with the pawns on e5 and f5 is that Black knows where the threat is coming from.'} 39. f5+ {Glenn Flear: 'Winning material, but not the game.'} Kxf5 {Glenn Flear: '!' Glenn Flear: 'Quite right, this should draw.'} 40. Rxd7 Kxe5 {White has an extra exchange, but because of the powerful passed b-pawn and the reduced number of pawns there is nothing Svidler can do to win.} 41. Kd3 Kf6 42. Rd5 Ke6 43. Rb5 Kf6 44. Ke4 Be7 45. Kf4 Bd6+ 46. Ke4 Be7 47. Kf4 Bd6+ 48. Kg4 Ke6 {Glenn Flear: '!' Glenn Flear: 'Active defence. It's always a key moment when the defender decides to come out of his shell.'} 49. Kh5 Kd7 {White captures the pawn on h6, but now the b-pawn is dangerous.} 50. Kxh6 Kc6 51. Rf5 b3 52. Rf1 Kc5 53. h4 b2 54. Rb1 Be5 55. Kg6 Kc4 {Glenn Flear: 'The race is an easy draw.'} 56. Rxb2 1/2-1/2


