1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nb6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Be3 O-O 8. Qd2 e5 9. d5 c6 10. h4 {Glenn Flear: 'The most popular choice.''The most popular choice. Ramirez Alvarez,Alejandro: 'Glenn Flear: 'The most popular choice.'''} ({Instead there are two alternatives worthy of note:} 10. Rd1 cxd5 11. exd5 Qh4+ ({for} 11... N8d7 12. Nh3 {see the archives}) 12. Bf2 Qb4 13. h4 N8d7 14. h5 Nf6 15. Rh4 e4 16. hxg6 hxg6 17. fxe4 Re8 {Wojtaszek, R-Dominguez Perez, L 2014, with double-edged play.}) (10. O-O-O cxd5 11. exd5 Na6 12. h4 h5 13. Be2 {(this proves to be too slow)} (13. Nh3 Bd7 14. Ng5 Rc8 15. Kb1 {is critical with complex play, Urkedal, F-Ostenstad, B Sandefjord 2012}) 13... Bd7 14. g4 Rc8 15. gxh5 Nb4 $1 16. Kb1 Nc4 17. Bxc4 Bf5+ 18. Ne4 Rxc4 {Pascua, H-Laylo, D Quezon City 2014, and Black's attack was already winning.}) 10... cxd5 11. exd5 N8d7 12. h5 Nf6 13. hxg6 fxg6 14. O-O-O Qd6 {Glenn Flear: '!?' '!?' '!?' '!?' '!?' Glenn Flear: 'Rarely played.''Rarely played. Ramirez Alvarez,Alejandro: 'Glenn Flear: '!?' Glenn Flear: 'Rarely played.'''} ({Instead} 14... Bd7 15. Kb1 Rc8 {has been tested at the highest level (check out the archives for games with both} 16. d6 ({and} 16. Ka1)) 15. Kb1 ({Developing the knight with} 15. Nh3 {comes into consideration:} Bxh3 16. Rxh3 Rac8 {(Black has rapid development, always handy)} 17. Kb1 (17. Rh4 {is given by Kaufman when} Qxd5 ({or perhaps} 17... Rfd8 $5) 18. Kb1 Qxd2 19. Rxd2 Rfe8 20. Bb5 Red8 {look like a reasonable line for Black}) 17... e4 $6 (17... Rfd8 $11 {is a more solid alternative}) 18. Bh6 (18. fxe4 Ng4 19. Bg1 {is given by the computer as better for White. So we can take it that it doesn't believe in Black's initiative then!}) 18... Bxh6 19. Rxh6 Qe5 20. Rh4 e3 {Gretarsson, Hj-Wei Yi, Reykjavik rapid 2013, with sharp play.}) 15... Bf5+ ({Alternatively} 15... Rd8 16. Ka1 Nbxd5 17. Nxd5 Qxd5 18. Bc4 Qxc4 19. Qxd8+ Bf8 20. Qd3 (20. Qxf6 $4 {fails to} Be6) 20... Qxd3 21. Rxd3 Bf5 22. Rd1 h5 23. a3 {is analyzed by Kaufman as being marginally better for White.}) 16. Ka1 h5 17. Nh3 e4 {Glenn Flear: '?!' '?!' '?!' '?!' '?!' Glenn Flear: 'As one can see in his game against Gretarsson (see above) Wei Yi likes this advance. Black wants, in principle, to open up the long dark-squared diagonal, but what can White do in reply?''As one can see in his game against Gretarsson (see above) Wei Yi likes this advance. Black wants, in principle, to open up the long dark-squared diagonal, but what can White do in reply? Ramirez Alvarez,Alejandro: 'Glenn Flear: '?!' Glenn Flear: 'As one can see in his game against Gretarsson (see above) Wei Yi likes this advance. Black wants, in principle, to open up the long dark-squared diagonal, but what can White do in reply?'''} ({After} 17... Rac8 18. Nf2 Nc4 19. Bxc4 Rxc4 {(this looks at first sight to be fine for Black, but Kaufman goes on to analyze a couple of ideas which he judges to be preferable for White...)} 20. Bh6 ({or} 20. Rc1 Rfc8 21. Bh6 Rd4 22. Qg5 $5) 20... Rd4 21. Qg5 {when White is (slightly) for preference e.g.} Nxd5 22. Bxg7 Kxg7 23. Rxd4 exd4 24. Nfe4 Qd8 25. Nxd5 Qxd5 26. Rxh5 Kg8 27. Rh6 $1) 18. Bh6 {Glenn Flear: '!' '!' '!' '!' '!''Ramirez Alvarez,Alejandro: 'Glenn Flear: '!'''} (18. Bd4 exf3 19. gxf3 Rac8 {looks fine for Black, so Sasikiran decides to eliminate Black's 'Indian' bishop.}) 18... Rad8 19. Bxg7 Kxg7 20. Nf4 {Glenn Flear: '!' '!' '!' '!' '!''Ramirez Alvarez,Alejandro: 'Glenn Flear: '!'''} ({After} 20. fxe4 Bxe4 $1 21. Nxe4 Nxe4 22. Qd4+ Nf6 {White hasn't achieved a great deal and d5 is weak, whereas g6 is less so.}) 20... Rfe8 ({If} 20... exf3 $6 21. gxf3 Rfe8 {then White would be happy to exploit the g-file with} 22. Rg1 {etc.} ({or} 22. Bb5 Re5 23. Rhg1)) 21. Bb5 e3 {Glenn Flear: '!?' '!?' '!?' '!?' '!?''Ramirez Alvarez,Alejandro: 'Glenn Flear: '!?'''} 22. Qd4 Re5 ({After} 22... Re7 {White has} 23. g4 $1 hxg4 24. fxg4 Bxg4 25. Nxg6 $1 Kxg6 26. Rdf1 {and Black's king is too exposed.}) 23. Bd3 ({Best is} 23. Be2 $1 {threatening both Nb5 and g4, and proves to be strong e.g.} a6 24. g4 $1 {with a dangerous attack.}) 23... Nbxd5 24. Nfxd5 $2 {Glenn Flear: 'Losing his way in this complicated struggle.''Losing his way in this complicated struggle. Ramirez Alvarez,Alejandro: 'Glenn Flear: 'Losing his way in this complicated struggle.''' Sasikirian underestimates his opponent's chances. Glenn Flear: 'Ramirez Alvarez,Alejandro: 'Sasikirian underestimates his opponent's chances.''} ({Glenn Flear: 'White keeps the advantage by including the preliminary''White keeps the advantage by including the preliminary Ramirez Alvarez,Alejandro: 'Glenn Flear: 'White keeps the advantage by including the preliminary'''} 24. Bxf5 $1 {Glenn Flear: 'as the following lines suggest:''as the following lines suggest: Ramirez Alvarez,Alejandro: 'Glenn Flear: 'as the following lines suggest:'''} gxf5 ({or} 24... Rxf5 25. Nfxd5 Re5 26. Rde1) 25. Ncxd5 e2 26. Rde1 Nxd5 (26... Kf7 27. a3 $1 {(the first rank is otherwise vulnerable to tricks)} Nxd5 28. Rxe2 Rxe2 29. Nxe2 {when the h-pawn will probably not survive for long.}) 27. Ne6+ $3 {Would have been a brilliant way to gain an advantage.} (27. Rxe2 {the far more normal move, also was good for a plus.}) 27... Qxe6 28. Rxe2 {and the rook on e5 will fall.}) 24... Bxd3 25. Rxd3 Nxd5 26. f4 {Glenn Flear: 'Unfortunately for Sasikiran this pin (surprisingly) doesn't yield an advantage.''Unfortunately for Sasikiran this pin (surprisingly) doesn't yield an advantage. Ramirez Alvarez,Alejandro: 'Glenn Flear: 'Unfortunately for Sasikiran this pin (surprisingly) doesn't yield an advantage.'''} Nxc3 {Glenn Flear: '!' '!' '!' '!' '!''Ramirez Alvarez,Alejandro: 'Glenn Flear: '!'''} 27. Qxd6 Rxd6 28. Rxd6 Rd5 $1 {Glenn Flear: 'Saving himself from further material loss. White may have won the exchange, but Black has held onto his big e-pawn.''Saving himself from further material loss. White may have won the exchange, but Black has held onto his big e-pawn. Ramirez Alvarez,Alejandro: 'Glenn Flear: 'Saving himself from further material loss. White may have won the exchange, but Black has held onto his big e-pawn.''' A beautiful sequence. Sasikirian has no choice but to take the rook, and although he is up the exchange, the powerful knight on d5, the passed pawn on e3 and the quickness with which the king can approach the center is enough to render his position hopeless. Glenn Flear: 'Ramirez Alvarez,Alejandro: 'A beautiful sequence. Sasikirian has no choice but to take the rook, and although he is up the exchange, the powerful knight on d5, the passed pawn on e3 and the quickness with which the king can approach the center is enough to render his position hopeless.''} 29. Rxd5 ({Rook endgames are often drawish, but after} 29. Re6 e2 30. bxc3 Rd1+ 31. Kb2 Rxh1 32. Rxe2 Kf6 {Black has winning chances due to the coming pressure against White's kingside.}) 29... Nxd5 30. g3 Kf6 {Glenn Flear: 'Black's combined forces of knight, passed pawn and more active king hold sway over a rook. Only Black can win.''Black's combined forces of knight, passed pawn and more active king hold sway over a rook. Only Black can win. Ramirez Alvarez,Alejandro: 'Glenn Flear: 'Black's combined forces of knight, passed pawn and more active king hold sway over a rook. Only Black can win.'''} 31. Rd1 Ke6 {Glenn Flear: '?!' '?!' '?!' '?!' '?!''Ramirez Alvarez,Alejandro: 'Glenn Flear: '?!'''} ({Not bad, but White should now be able to wriggle out. Instead the flashy} 31... h4 $1 {works for Black:} 32. Rxd5 (32. gxh4 e2 33. Re1 Nxf4 {is winning for Black, rather like in the game}) 32... hxg3 33. Rd1 Kf5 34. Kb1 Kxf4 {and White is struggling:} 35. Re1 Kf3 36. Kc2 g2 37. Kd1 a5 38. a3 e2+ 39. Kd2 a4 40. Rg1 Kf2 $19) 32. Kb1 h4 33. gxh4 {Glenn Flear: '?' '?' '?' '?' '?' Glenn Flear: 'Losing a key tempo and ultimately the game.''Losing a key tempo and ultimately the game. Ramirez Alvarez,Alejandro: 'Glenn Flear: '?' Glenn Flear: 'Losing a key tempo and ultimately the game.'''} ({Instead} 33. Kc2 $1 {(in endgames, 'when in doubt, bring up the king') should hold e.g.} hxg3 34. Rg1 e2 35. Kd2 Nxf4 36. Rxg3 Kf5 {and Black can't make progress.}) 33... e2 34. Re1 Nxf4 35. Kc2 Kf5 36. Kd2 Ke4 {Glenn Flear: 'Black's king glides into White's backyard and rules the roost.''Black's king glides into White's backyard and rules the roost. Ramirez Alvarez,Alejandro: 'Glenn Flear: 'Black's king glides into White's backyard and rules the roost.'''} 37. b4 Kf3 38. a4 Kf2 39. b5 b6 {Glenn Flear: 'Zugzwang. The rook is obliged to move.''Zugzwang. The rook is obliged to move. Ramirez Alvarez,Alejandro: 'Glenn Flear: 'Zugzwang. The rook is obliged to move.'''} 40. Rh1 Ng2 0-1


