1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Bd7 4. Bxd7+ Qxd7 5. c4 {The Grunfeld with 5.d2 seems to be more popular in the recent months. The idea are varied and Black has yet to fully equalize in some lines.} Nc6 (5... Nf6 6. Nc3 g6 7. O-O Bg7 8. d4 cxd4 9. Nxd4 O-O 10. f3 Rc8 11. b3 d5 12. exd5 Nxd5 13. Nxd5 e6) 6. Nc3 (6. d4 cxd4 7. Nxd4 g6 8. b3) 6... g6 7. d4 {This idea of preventing e5 at all costs has been seen at the top level a few times. Wang Hao has used it three times, Tomashevsky twice.} cxd4 8. Nxd4 Bg7 9. Be3 Nf6 10. f3 O-O 11. Rc1 {Black's bishops are not powerful yet - the central blockade is doing a good job of lessening the power of the fianchetto bishop while the one on e6 lacks targets. However, things change quickly - Black only needs to break through on c5..} Rfc8 (11... Nxd4 12. Bxd4 Rfc8) (11... a6 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. O-O Qb7 14. Rf2 Nd7 15. b3) 12. b3 a6 $1 {An excellent time for this break. Wei Yi ignores his structure and gives priority to the activity of his pieces.} 13. Nxc6 $6 (13. a4 e6 14. O-O d5 15. Nxc6 bxc6 16. a5 (16. e5 Ne8 17. f4 a5) 16... Qe7 17. Na4 (17. exd5 cxd5 18. Na4 Rc6 19. Qe2 Rd8 20. Bb6 Rdc8) 17... dxe4 18. Nb6 Rd8 19. Qe2 Rab8) (13. Nde2 Qd8 14. Qd2 Qa5 15. Na4 Qxd2+ 16. Kxd2 Nd7 17. Nec3 b5 18. cxb5 Bxc3+ 19. Rxc3 (19. Nxc3 axb5) 19... axb5 20. Rhc1 Nde5 21. f4 Nc4+ 22. bxc4 b4 23. Nb6 bxc3+ 24. Kd1 Rd8 25. Nxa8 Rxa8) (13. O-O Nxd4 14. Bxd4 b5) 13... Rxc6 $1 14. Qe2 (14. a4 e6 (14... Qd8 15. O-O Qa5 16. Nd5 Nxd5 17. exd5 Rc7 18. Qe1) 15. O-O Qd8 16. Kh1 Qa5 17. Bd2 Qc7 18. Qe2 Nd7) (14. Nd5 b5 15. c5 Qe6) 14... e6 {This simple maneuver gives White very unpleasant problems. The structure on the center is easily attacked, while the pawn on c5 will not survive for long. Notice the difference in power between the bishops now and a few moves ago.} 15. O-O Qc7 (15... d5 16. Rfd1) 16. a4 Nd7 17. Rc2 (17. Rfd1 Bxc3 18. Rxc3 b5 19. c5 Nxc5 20. Rdc1) 17... Bxc3 18. Rxc3 b5 $1 {Black has recovered his pawn and his pair of bishops gives him an advantage. It is uncomfortable to find moves for White, who simply does not have an answer to the bishop on g7.} 19. axb5 (19. c5 bxa4 20. cxd6 Qxd6 21. Rd1 Qc7 22. Rxc6 Qxc6 23. bxa4 Qxa4 24. Rd4 Qc6 (24... Qa1+ 25. Rd1 Qa4 26. Rd4) 25. Qd2 Nf6 26. Rd6 Qc4 27. h3 Ne8 28. Rd8 Rxd8 29. Qxd8 Qb5 30. Qe7 a5 31. Bc5 Qb1+ 32. Kf2 (32. Kh2 Qb8+ 33. Kg1 Ng7) 32... Qb2+ 33. Kg1) 19... axb5 20. Rfc1 b4 (20... bxc4 21. Rxc4 Rxc4 22. Qxc4 Qxc4 23. Rxc4) 21. Rd3 Nc5 22. Bxc5 dxc5 23. e5 Rca6 24. Qe3 Ra1 25. Rxa1 Rxa1+ 26. Kf2 Qe7 27. Qf4 Kg7 28. h4 h5 {Anton gives up in a position that is hopeless. He is down a pawn and Black's activity is overwhelming.} 29. Kg3 Rh1 30. Rd6 Rb1 $13 {and despite the weakness on e6, Black's superior activity gives him the easier play.} 31. Rd3 {was Moiseenko-Khusnutdinov from 2014.} Rh1 32. Rd6 0-1


