1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 e6 3. Nd2 ({The most trendy alternative to pushing the e-pawn two squares, although} 3. e3 {is, of course, also possible and after} c5 4. c3 cxd4 5. exd4 Be7 6. Bd3 a6 7. a4 b6 8. Nf3 Bb7 9. Nbd2 d6 10. O-O Nbd7 11. Re1 O-O 12. Nf1 Re8 13. Ng3 Qc7 {a very common sort of Torre struggle had arisen in Stopa-Richter, German Bundesliga 2016. Clamping down on b5 with a2-a4 was surely a reasonable call and White does have more space, but Black is typically compact and flexible. Play continued} 14. c4 $5 {when I suspect that Black should even consider breaking with his d-pawn, since} Bf8 15. a5 $1 {was quite annoying, White going on to exploit his edge after} bxa5 16. Bd2 a4 17. Qxa4 e5 $6 18. Ba5 Qc8 19. d5 Nc5 20. Qc2 Nxd3 21. Qxd3 g6 22. b4 {.}) 3... c5 ({In both the pure Torre and delayed Torre lines White must be ready for positions with and without ...h6. Indeed,} 3... h6 4. Bh4 d5 5. e3 Be7 6. Bd3 O-O 7. c3 b6 8. f4 $5 {should be compared with our main game. This feels like exactly the sort of early f4 White is trying to make work, partly because Black hasn't any tricks here. Following} Bb7 (8... Ba6 $1 {would be prudent}) 9. Bxf6 $1 ({avoiding} 9. Ngf3 Ne4 {, which should equalise}) 9... Bxf6 10. Qh5 Nd7 11. Ngf3 {I would certainly feel quite nervous in Black's shoes. However, the key question is: can White's aggressive play really be justified? Well, yes, here I believe it can:} Be7 12. g4 Nf6 13. Qh3 Ne4 14. Rg1 {. The attack simply runs on oiled wheels and after} c5 15. g5 hxg5 16. fxg5 g6 17. Rg4 $1 Nxg5 18. Nxg5 (18. Qh6 $1 {would have been an immediate game-ender, and if} Ne4 19. Bxe4 dxe4 20. Ne5) 18... Bxg5 19. Nf3 Bf6 20. O-O-O Kg7 21. Qg3 Rg8 22. Rf1 $1 Bc6 23. Ne5 {there was nothing much to be done about a devastating blow on g6 in Sengupta-Zarkovic, European Club Cup, Novi Sad 2016.}) 4. e3 d5 5. c3 Nc6 6. Bd3 (6. Ngf3 {might well be prudent and, moreover, takes play into a reasonable enough version of the Torre for White.}) 6... h6 7. Bh4 ({This time after} 7. Bxf6 $5 {Black can either recapture with the f-pawn or develop while hitting f4 with} Qxf6 8. f4 Bd6 9. Ne2 O-O 10. O-O Qd8 {.}) 7... Qb6 $5 ({In practice one can imagine many weaker players developing with} 7... Be7 {,}) ({but the text or} 7... e5 $1 {must be critical. Moreover, this central reaction just seems to equalise, as shown by} 8. Bxf6 Qxf6 9. e4 $5 (9. dxe5 Nxe5 10. Bb5+ Nc6 11. Ngf3 Be7 {is all too easy for Black}) 9... exd4 $1 10. exd5 Ne5 11. Qe2 Be7 12. Bb5+ Kf8 {and Black is at least OK in the resulting small mess.}) 8. Rb1 cxd4 9. exd4 e5 $5 {I'm not sure I would have opened the e-file before playing this, but even here White doesn't seem to have anything.} 10. Ne2 (10. Qe2 $5 Bg4 11. f3 {is the critical line, but after} Be6 12. dxe5 Nh5 13. Bf2 Nf4 {Black seems to equalise.}) ({Likewise,} 10. dxe5 Nxe5 11. Bc2 Bg4 12. Ne2 O-O-O $5 {isn't a position I'd want to give more than an unclear assessment to.}) 10... Be7 11. dxe5 Ne4 $1 {Equalising. White cannot allow an accident to happen on h4, so is forced to retreat after which the further exchanges are fairly favourable for Black.} 12. Bg3 Nxg3 13. hxg3 Nxe5 14. Nf3 Nxf3+ 15. gxf3 {At first I did wonder if White's firm grip on d4 might mean something, but unsurprisingly - no! The problem, as so often in IQP structures, is that White's kingside isn't entirely stable and that Black can continue actively.} O-O 16. O-O Bh3 17. Re1 Bc5 {Logical, and strong.} 18. Nd4 Rae8 19. Qd2 Qf6 20. Rxe8 ({After something like} 20. f4 $5 h5 21. Nf3 Bg4 22. Ne5 Be6 23. Bc2 {White would have been risking at least as much as Black. Yu Yangyi prefers to keep matters under control.}) 20... Rxe8 21. Re1 Rxe1+ 22. Qxe1 Bd7 23. Qe3 1/2-1/2


