h4 ({This time after} 7. Bxf6 $5 {Black can either recapture with the f-pawn or develop while hitting f4 with} Qxf6 8. f4 Bd6 9. Ne2 O-O 10. O-O Qd8 {.}) 7... Qb6 $5 ({In practice one can imagine many weaker players developing with} 7... Be7 {,}) ({but the text or} 7... e5 $1 {must be critical. Moreover, this central reaction just seems to equalise, as shown by} 8. Bxf6 Qxf6 9. e4 $5 (9. dxe5 Nxe5 10. Bb5+ Nc6 11. Ngf3 Be7 {is all too easy for Black}) 9... exd4 $1 10. exd5 Ne5 11. Qe2 Be7 12. Bb5+ Kf8 {and Black is at least OK in the resulting small mess.}) 8. Rb1 cxd4 9. exd4 e5 $5 {I'm not sure I would have opened the e-file before playing this, but even here White doesn't seem to have anything.} 10. Ne2 (10. Qe2 $5 Bg4 11. f3 {is the critical line, but after} Be6 12. dxe5 Nh5 13. Bf2 Nf4 {Black seems to equalise.}) ({Likewise,} 10. dxe5 Nxe5 11. Bc2 Bg4 12. Ne2 O-O-O $5 {isn't a position I'd want to give more than an unclear assessment to.}) 10... Be7 11. dxe5 Ne4 $1 {Equalising. White cannot allow an accident to happen on h4, so is forced to retreat after which the further exchanges are fairly favourable for Black.} 12. Bg3 Nxg3 13. hxg3 Nxe5 14. Nf3 Nxf3+ 15. gxf3 {At first I did wonder if White's firm grip on d4 might mean something, but unsurprisingly - no! The problem, as so often in IQP structures, is that White's kingside isn't entirely stable and that Black can continue actively.} O-O 16. O-O Bh3 17. Re1 Bc5 {Logical, and strong.} 18. Nd4 Rae8 19. Qd2 Qf6 20. Rxe8 ({After something like} 20. f4 $5 h5 21. Nf3 Bg4 22. Ne5 Be6 23. Bc2 {White would have been risking at least as much as Black. Yu Yangyi prefers to keep matters under control.}) 20... Rxe8 21. Re1 Rxe1+ 22. Qxe1 Bd7 23. Qe3 1/2-1/2


