1. d4 ({Yes, this is a d-pawn special, but do please note too the move order} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bf4 Bg4 7. Qb3 Qc8 8. Nd2 e6 9. Ngf3 {and we're back in our main game here.}) 1... d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 ({In the following blitz tournament Wei Yi also had to face} 3... e6 4. Nd2 Bd6 5. Bg3 b6 {. This must, of course, be quite respectable for Black, although one might label} 6. c3 Bb7 7. Bd3 Nbd7 8. Ngf3 Ne4 {as ambitious. In any case, I suspect that Black is OK here, but with} 9. Qc2 (9. Qe2 {was preferred in Nguyen Ngoc Truong Son-Grandelius, Doha (blitz) 2016, when} a6 10. Bc2 f5 11. Nxe4 fxe4 12. Ne5 Bxe5 13. dxe5 {would surely have been OK for Black after, say,} O-O 14. f3 Nc5 $5 {, and if} 15. b4 d4 $1) 9... f5 10. c4 O-O 11. cxd5 exd5 12. Rc1 Nxg3 $6 (12... Rc8 13. Bxd6 Nxd6 14. Ne5 c5 {can surely only favour Black}) 13. hxg3 g6 14. g4 $1 {the young Chinese star had already gained a powerful initiative in Wei Yi-Adly, Doha (blitz) 2016.}) 4. Nd2 cxd4 5. exd4 Bg4 $5 {This active development of the bishop in this precise position seems to be new for us, but cannot, of course, be terrible.} 6. Ngf3 Nc6 7. c3 e6 8. Qb3 {Just like in certain, closed-related types of Exchange Caro-Kann, unpinning while hitting b7 must be critical.} Qc8 ({Prudent, unlike} 8... Qd7 $2 9. Ne5 Qc8 10. f3 Bf5 11. g4 Bg6 12. h4 {when Black already finds himself in terrible trouble.}) 9. Bd3 ({Wei Yi sees no reason to kick Black's bishop so that Ne5 will come with tempo. In another recent game White preferred} 9. h3 {, but} Bf5 10. Be2 Be7 11. O-O O-O 12. a4 Bd8 $5 13. Qa3 Ne4 {was all too easy for Black in To-Becskei, Kecskemet 2016.}) 9... Be7 {Black's main move as we now follow arguably the main line of the Exchange Caro.} 10. O-O O-O 11. Ne5 {Thematic, although just as often White has been known to place a rook on e1.} Nxe5 ({This can hardly be terrible, but Black has more often gone} 11... Bh5 {(the retreat can also be played a move earlier), after which} 12. Qc2 Bg6 13. Nxg6 hxg6 14. Nf3 Nh5 15. Be3 Qc7 16. g3 Rac8 17. Qe2 a6 18. Rae1 Rfe8 19. Bc1 Nf6 20. Ng5 $1 Bd6 21. f4 {was a model demonstration of how to expand while maintaining control, White going on to win in Browne-Larsen, San Antonio 1972.}) 12. Bxe5 (12. dxe5 $5 Nd7 13. Qc2 {is also tempting, but it seems that Black should be OK after} h6 14. h3 Bh5 {, and if} 15. g4 Bg6 16. Bxg6 fxg6 17. Bxh6 Nxe5 $1 {.}) 12... Nd7 ({Once again} 12... Bh5 {would have been sensible, but Malakhov begins to drift.}) 13. Bf4 Nb6 $6 ({A strange choice, blocking any minority attack and provoking White's next. At the risk of sounding like a broken record, I would prefer} 13... Bh5 {, as played in the one previous test of the position I could find, where} 14. Rae1 ({even here} 14. a4 $5 {might be tried}) 14... Rd8 15. Re3 Nf8 16. Rh3 Bg6 17. Qc2 Qc6 18. Nf3 {was no more than a touch better for White in Znamensky-Nikolaev, St Petersburg 2005.}) 14. a4 $1 Bf5 $6 ({Possibly this was Malakhov's idea before his last, but his knight is a long way from e4. Instead,} 14... Nd7 15. a5 Nf6 {would have been retrograde, but was quite possibly best.}) 15. Bxf5 exf5 16. Rfe1 {Already White's pressure is quite something.} Qd7 (16... Re8 17. a5 Nc4 18. Nxc4 dxc4 19. Qa4 {also looks quite awkward,}) ({as does} 16... Bf6 17. a5 Nc4 18. Nxc4 dxc4 19. Qa4 Rd8 20. a6 $1 b6 21. Qb5 {.}) 17. a5 Nc8 18. Nf3 f6 {Fairly essential, if also another ugly pawn move. Now White might just double on the e-file, but Wei Yi prefers to seize the initiative.} 19. c4 $5 Rd8 $6 ({Black might prefer to go} 19... dxc4 20. Qxc4+ Kh8 (20... Rf7 $1 {followed by ...Nd6 would, however, be a better defence}) 21. Rac1 Bd6 {, but then} 22. Qd5 Rd8 23. Re6 {is a bit awkward. Still, better this than the game.}) 20. a6 b6 21. c5 $1 {Crashing through. Malakhov has been virtually unrecognisable and already must have been contemplating resignation.} g5 ({Black's main problem is} 21... bxc5 22. Qb7 {, and if} Nd6 23. Qxd7 Rxd7 24. Rxe7 $1 Rxe7 25. Bxd6 {.}) 22. c6 $1 {There's to be no let up as Wei Yi continues in vigorous vein.} Qxc6 23. Rac1 Qe8 24. Bc7 Rd7 25. Qb5 {Talk about tying the opponent up in knots. White is about to win serious material.} Nd6 26. Qxd5+ Kg7 $2 ({Scarcely any better would have been} 26... Nf7 27. Qxf5 Rc8 28. Bg3 Rxc1 29. Rxc1 Qd8 30. h4 {when Black is a pawn down and continues to struggle for a good move.}) 27. Bxd6 Rad8 ({A piece had gone west in any case, as if} 27... Rxd6 28. Rxe7+ $1 Qxe7 29. Qxa8 {.}) 28. Qe6 1-0


