1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bf4 Bg7 4. e3 O-O 5. Be2 d6 ({A popular choice with King's Indian players. Those who don't mind developing along classical lines may prefer} 5... c5 6. O-O d5 {, which is after} 7. c3 Nc6 {a reversed Catalan, albeit with the bishop outside the pawn chain. White has many moves here, as we've seen over the years, with} 8. Ne5 {a thematic leap and after} Bf5 $5 9. Qb3 (9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. Nd2 Qb6 11. Qb3 cxd4 12. cxd4 Nd7 $1 {should be fine for Black}) 9... Nd7 10. Nxd7 Qxd7 11. dxc5 e5 12. Bg3 d4 {Black already enjoyed decent counterplay and had at least enough for his pawn in Agrest-Efimenko, European Club Cup, Porto Carras 2018.}) 6. O-O c5 7. c3 ({In their earlier fifth game, which was played with a classical time control, Inarkiev had preferred} 7. h3 {, play continuing along similar lines with} cxd4 (7... b6 8. Nbd2 Bb7 9. c3 Nbd7 {remains a very flexible set-up for Black we're used to seeing Maxime Vachier-Lagrave countering the London so, but in Vachier-Lagrave-Grischuk, Saint Louis (rapid) 2018, he was on the other side of the board, with} 10. a4 a6 11. Bh2 Ne4 12. Nxe4 Bxe4 13. Bd3 Bxd3 14. Qxd3 Qc7 15. Rfd1 Rfc8 16. Qe2 Qb7 17. e4 cxd4 18. cxd4 Rc7 19. e5 $1 {giving White any slight pull that was going}) 8. exd4 Nc6 9. c3 Nd5 10. Bh2 {(possible thanks to White's seventh move, although Black can still hit back in the centre)} e5 $1 11. Na3 $5 (11. c4 {is even more critical, but perhaps asks too much of White's position now in Korneev-Wan Yunguo, Bruges 2018, I suspect that Black should have gone} Nde7 {, heading for f5 if needed, and if} 12. d5 e4 $1) 11... exd4 (11... Re8 {would have been a fairly useful semi-waiting move}) 12. Nc4 $1 Nb6 13. Nxd6 dxc3 14. bxc3 Bxc3 15. Rc1 Bb4 16. Bb5 {and by this stage White's activity gave him full compensation for the pawn, if no more than that.}) 7... cxd4 8. exd4 Nc6 9. Nbd2 Nd5 {Here we go again...} 10. Bg3 e5 $5 ({Wei Yi is consistent. We've previously focussed on} 10... Bf5 11. Qb3 Nb6 12. d5 $1 {- see Dreev-Zvjaginsev,V (2659) World Rapid Ch., Khanty-Mansiysk 2013, in the Archive.}) 11. Nc4 ({This central challenge must be fairly critical. Previously, I just noted that} 11. Re1 Bf5 ({and not} 11... exd4 12. Nxd4 $1 Nxd4 13. cxd4) 12. Qb3 Nb6 13. dxe5 dxe5 14. Rad1 Qe7 {must be OK for Black.}) 11... Re8 12. Qb3 $5 ({Very brave, for reasons we'll soon see. In the predecessor game,} 12. a4 Nf4 13. Bxf4 exf4 14. Re1 d5 15. Nce5 {surely shouldn't have given White anything (Palchun-Iljiushenok, Sochi (rapid) 2017),}) ({but maybe now is the moment for} 12. Re1 $5 {, with definite chances for an edge as} e4 $6 13. Nfd2 {just seems to leave Black rather overextended.}) 12... exd4 13. Nxd6 {The point behind White's last, but his bishop is hanging on e2 and queen about to be buffeted around.} Rxe2 14. Qxd5 Be6 15. Qb5 {At least this hits the rook and, whether or not it was all preparation from Inarkiev (I suspect the latter), it also tries to regain the initiative.} Rc2 ({This can't be terrible, but there was also} 15... d3 $5 {, angling to swap d3 for b2 and intending to cause trouble for the white queen after} 16. Qxb7 (16. Nxb7 $6 Qb6 {can only favour Black}) 16... Bd5 17. Rad1 a6 {, when} 18. Rxd3 Re7 19. Qxa8 Qxa8 20. Rxd5 Re2 {is hard to assess, but most likely roughly level.}) 16. Ng5 $6 ({This may well ask too much of White's position. Instead,} 16. Ne1 {would angle for a repetition with} Rd2 17. Nf3 {,}) ({while} 16. Qxb7 $5 dxc3 17. bxc3 Rxc3 18. Ng5 $1 Qb8 $1 19. Qxb8+ Rxb8 20. Nxe6 fxe6 {would most likely have resulted in a drawn ending.}) 16... Qb6 17. Qd3 (17. Nxe6 Qxb5 18. Nxb5 {was the alternative, but unfortunately for White after} fxe6 19. Nc7 Rc8 20. Nxe6 {Black has} dxc3 {, preparing a zwischenzug and obtaining an edge after} 21. bxc3 Bxc3 22. Rac1 Rxc1 23. Rxc1 Bf6 {.}) 17... Qxb2 $1 {Wei Yi is fearless as he bags a pawn.} 18. Nxe6 fxe6 19. c4 $6 ({This feels a bit desperate.} 19. Qc4 $1 {would have been more active, when White might yet be OK, in view of} Nd8 20. Qa4 {, and if} Qxc3 (20... Nc6 21. Qc4 {repeats}) 21. Qe8+ Bf8 22. Ne4 {with a dangerous initiative in return for the pawns.}) 19... Re2 (19... Rd2 $1 {might well have been a touch stronger, preparing to gain a tempo next move with either rook.}) 20. Rae1 Rxe1 21. Rxe1 Rf8 22. h4 $5 ({Perhaps not best, but creating luft and drumming up some play was a much better try than allowing} 22. Rxe6 $2 Ne5 $1 {. Moreover, by this stage I rather suspect that both players were beginning to run short of time after the early complications.}) 22... Ne5 23. Qb3 Qd2 $2 ({Overly ambitious. There was absolutely nothing wrong with} 23... Qxb3 24. axb3 Nd3 {, and if} 25. Rxe6 ({or} 25. Ra1 b6 26. Rxa7 Nc1) 25... Nc5 {, preserving a clear plus.}) 24. f3 $1 {It turns out that White didn't have to move his rook and now, as so often occurs, a second mistake follows hot on the heels of the first.} Nd3 $4 (24... Qc3 $1 {would still have been fine for Black, who regains his piece in the event of} 25. Qxc3 dxc3 26. Bxe5 Bxe5 27. Rxe5 Rd8 {,}) ({and even} 24... Nf7 {would have been OK.}) 25. Ne4 $1 {Backwards moves are never easy to spot.} 1-0


