1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 Nc6 8. Qd2 O-O 9. O-O-O d5 10. Qe1 e5 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. exd5 Nxd5 13. Bc4 Be6 14. Kb1 Rb8 15. Ne4 Qc7 (15... f5 {- Ganguly-Quintiliano Pinto.}) 16. Bc5 Rfd8 (16... Rfe8 $2 17. Bd6 {wins the exchange.}) 17. g4 (17. Bb3 $5) 17... h6 (17... f5 $2 {fails to} 18. gxf5 gxf5 19. Ng5 $18) (17... a5 18. h4 (18. Bb3 Ra8 19. a4 Nf4 20. Bd6 Qb6 21. Bxe6 Nxe6 22. Qc3 $16 {Ivanov,O-Kargin, Elets 2014}) 18... h6 19. g5 h5 20. a4 Qb7 21. b3 Ra8 {and now in Wei Yi-Yankovsky, Las Vegas 2013 White may have considered} 22. Rd3 $16 {In my opinion White has a fantastic grip on the position, thanks to Black's weak pawns on a5 and c6. Moreover, the c5-square is well controlled by the bishop and knight and Black is unable to push his kingside majority.}) 18. h4 ({Since White is unable to play g4-g5, I'm critical of this move and would prefer to play a more useful move.} 18. Rg1 $5 $146 {anticipating ...f7-f5 is probably better and worth investigating.} Kh7 (18... f5 $2 19. gxf5 gxf5 $2 (19... Bxf5 {is better, but can never be the idea of 18...f5.}) 20. Nf6+ Kh8 21. Nh5 $18) 19. Bb3 $1 {[%cal Yh2h4]} f5 20. gxf5 gxf5 21. Bd6 Rxd6 22. Nxd6 Qxd6 23. c4 {and White wins the exchange. Black will have some compensation thanks to the powerful centre and his pair of bishops, but I doubt it's sufficient. After all, White's king is safer than Black's.}) ({Starting with} 18. Bb3 {is sensible too.}) 18... f5 $1 (18... Rd7 $2 19. g5 $1 {and White nicely fixes the kingside, as in the game Wei Yi-Yankovsky.} h5 20. Bb3 Rbd8 21. Rd3 Nf4 22. Rxd7 Rxd7 23. Be3 Bxb3 24. axb3 Ng2 25. Qf2 Nxe3 26. Qxe3 Qb6 27. Qe2 Qb5 $2 (27... Rd5 $14 {There is still some work to be done.}) 28. Qxb5 cxb5 29. c4 bxc4 30. bxc4 Rc7 31. c5 Bf8 32. Rd1 Bxc5 33. Rd8+ Bf8 34. Nf6+ Kg7 35. Ne8+ {1-0 Ponomariov-Narva,R Tallinn rapid 2016.}) 19. gxf5 gxf5 20. Ng3 ({The following game nicely illustrates Black's attacking prospects thanks to the b-file, the bishop on g7 and the dynamic pawn centre:} 20. Nf2 a5 21. Bb3 a4 22. Bxa4 Rxb2+ 23. Kxb2 e4+ 24. Kc1 Qf4+ 25. Be3 Qd6 26. Bd4 Qa3+ 27. Kb1 Nb4 {Adamson-Gelashvili, Las Vegas 2016.}) 20... Qf7 (20... Kh7 $5 {makes sense too.}) 21. Bb3 Rd7 22. Qa5 Rbd8 23. Rd3 Nf4 $2 ({A shocking blunder.} 23... Kh7 $5 {Black's position is compact and difficult to breach.}) 24. Qxd8+ Rxd8 25. Rxd8+ Kh7 26. Rhd1 Bd5 27. Ra8 Qg6 28. Rxa7 Ne6 (28... Qxg3 29. Rg1 $18) 29. Bf2 e4 30. c4 $2 (30. Bxd5 $1 cxd5 31. Rg1 {gives White a decisive advantage.}) 30... e3 $1 31. Bxe3 (31. Be1 $1 $16) 31... Bxf3 $1 {And suddenly it becomes messy again.} 32. Rg1 Qf6 33. Rxg7+ Nxg7 34. Bc2 Bg4 35. Ne4 Qe5 36. Nf6+ Qxf6 37. Rxg4 Qe5 38. Bc1 Ne6 39. Rg2 Nd4 40. Bd3 Qe1 41. a4 Kh8 42. a5 Nb3 43. Rc2 Qxa5 44. Rc3 Qa1+ 45. Kc2 Qxc1+ 46. Kxb3 Qd1+ 47. Ka3 Qa1+ 48. Kb3 Qd1+ 49. Ka3 Qa1+ 50. Kb3 Qd1+ 51. Ka3 f4 52. Be4 c5 53. Bf3 Qe1 54. h5 Kg7 55. Ka4 Qa1+ 56. Kb3 Qb1 57. Rc2 Kf6 58. Rd2 Qc1 59. Rd3 Kg5 60. Bd1 Kh4 61. Bf3 Qe1 62. Kc2 Qf2+ 63. Kc3 Qe1+ 64. Kc2 Qe6 65. Kc3 Qe5+ 66. Kc2 Qb8 67. Bd1 Qb4 68. Rc3 Qa4+ 69. Kd2 Qa6 70. Kc2 Qb7 71. Kc1 Qe4 72. Bf3 Qe1+ 73. Bd1 Kg5 74. Kc2 Qe4+ 75. Kc1 Kf6 76. Bf3 Qe1+ 77. Kc2 Qf2+ 78. Kc1 Qd4 79. Kc2 Ke5 80. Kc1 Qg1+ 81. Kc2 Qf2+ 82. Kc1 Kd4 83. Bd1 Ke4 84. Bc2+ Ke5 85. Bd1 Qf1 86. Kd2 Kd4 87. Kc2 Ke4 88. Kd2 Qf2+ 89. Kc1 Kd4 90. Bf3 Qe1+ 91. Kc2 Qf1 92. Bd1 Qg2+ 93. Kc1 Qf2 94. Bf3 Qe1+ 95. Kc2 Ke5 96. Bd1 Qf2+ 97. Kc1 Qd4 98. Bf3 Kf5 99. Bd1 Kg5 100. Kc2 Kh4 101. Kc1 Qf2 102. Rf3 Qd4 103. Rc3 Qe4 104. Bf3 1/2-1/2


