{[%evp 0,43,35,24,43,48,43,44,49,33,31,30,61,37,37,11,11,7,11,-19,42,44,86,38,42,-2,-21,10,-16,-210,-251,-38,-31,-39,7,-18,-6,-13,-13,-3,-3,12,0,9,5,17] Dave Smerdon: 'There are many exciting things about future world champion Wei Yi, one of which is that he loves playing anti-Sicilians! This game is a good example that Yi can also come up with fresh opening ideas and excellent preparation as well.'} 1. e4 {Dave Smerdon Dave Smerdon Dave Smerdon Dave Smerdon} c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Bc4 Be7 5. d3 d6 6. O-O Nf6 7. Ng5 O-O 8. f4 Bg4 9. Qe1 (9. Nf3 {has been played here as well, but in that case Black has saved a tempo on ...h7-h6.} exf4 10. Bxf4 Nd4 $132 {[%cal Yd8d7]}) 9... exf4 10. Bxf4 (10. Rxf4 Bh5 (10... h6 11. Nf3 g5 $2 12. Rxg4 Nxg4 13. Nd5 $44 {is probably White's idea.}) (10... Ne5 $5 {[%csl Rc4,Rg5][%cal Yf6h5]}) 11. Nf3 a6 12. a4 Bxf3 13. Rxf3 Nd4 14. Rf2 Ng4 15. Rf4 Ne5 16. Qd1 Bg5 17. Rf2 Bxc1 18. Qxc1 Qh4 $132 {So-Topalov, Abidjan 2019.}) 10... Nd4 11. Qf2 {Dave Smerdon: '!?' '!?' '!?' '!?' Dave Smerdon: 'A very rare move in over-the-board chess, but it's been played a few times in correspondence. Like, well, everything in correspondence, it should lead to a draw with best play. But I wouldn't much like facing this preparation from the black side of things. Wei has a nice sacrifice in mind, but it should be noted that placing the queen on f2 also introduces another idea: taking on f7 with a view to reaching a favourable rook-and-pawns versus two minor pieces endgame.'} (11. Qh4 $6 h6 (11... Bh5 $2 12. Nxh7 Kxh7 13. Nd5 $18 {with a crushing attack for White.}) 12. Nxf7 Rxf7 13. Bxf7+ Kxf7 14. Bxh6 Be6 $1 ({More ambitious than} 14... gxh6 15. Qxg4 Nxc2 16. Rf3 Nxa1 17. Qh5+ Ke6 18. Qf5+ Kf7 19. Qh5+ $11) 15. Qh5+ Kg8 16. Qg6 Qf8 $15) (11. e5 dxe5 (11... Nxc2 $2 12. exf6 $1) 12. Bxe5 Bh5 {[%cal Yh5g6] and Black is very solid with his kingside well-defended and a powerful knight on d4.} 13. Qg3 (13. Qh4 Bg6 $17 {[%csl Rc2,Gd4]}) (13. Qd2 $2 {was seen in Shirov-Leko, Monte Carlo 2003, when Black has a surprising tactical shot:} b5 $1 14. Nxb5 Nxb5 15. Bxb5 Ng4 16. Bf4 Bxg5 17. Bxg5 Qb8 $19 {[%csl Rb5,Rh2]}) 13... Bg6 14. Qh3 Nxc2 15. Rac1 Nd4 $17 {Amonatov-Moiseenko, Belgorod 2010.}) (11. Qd2 {is the main continuation, see Sanal-Kuzubov.}) 11... h6 {Dave Smerdon: 'The most natural and consistent response.'} ({However, it's interesting to note that a high-level correspondence player tried something else:} 11... Qd7 {(Dave Smerdon) and now I can't see what's wrong with} 12. e5 $1 (12. Be3 Rac8 13. Rae1 b5 14. Bxf7+ Rxf7 15. Nxf7 Kxf7 16. Bxd4 cxd4 17. Qxd4 Kg8 $13 {1/2-1/2 (23) Krzyzanowski, A  (2459)-Galkowski, L (2431) ICCF 2004}) 12... dxe5 13. Bxe5 {with dangerous pressure e.g.} h6 14. Nxf7 $1 Rxf7 15. Bxf7+ Kxf7 16. Ne4 Kg8 17. Bxf6 gxf6 18. Nxf6+ Bxf6 19. Qxf6 Qg7 20. Qxg7+ Kxg7 21. Rae1 $16) 12. Nf3 (12. Nxf7 {Dave Smerdon: '!?' '!?' '!?' Dave Smerdon: 'is also possible here, although again, not everyone is comfortable handling the rook in these imbalances. In my experience, the minor pieces generally tend to do better in matches between weaker players, even when objectively the rook and pawns are stronger. But this is just an observation.'} Rxf7 13. Bxf7+ Kxf7 {isn't dangerous for Black.} 14. Be3 {Dave Smerdon} Kg8 (14... Nc6 $5 {may be stronger:} 15. Nd5 Be6 16. Qg3 Bxd5 17. exd5 Nb4 $1 18. c4 Nc2 19. Rab1 Nxe3 20. Qxe3 $15) 15. Bxd4 cxd4 16. Qxd4 Qa5 $13 {1/2-1/2 (60) Ivanovic, Z (2186)-Wagner, M (2114) ICCF 2007}) 12... Nxf3+ 13. gxf3 Bh3 14. Bxh6 {Dave Smerdon: '!!' '!!' '!!' '!!' Dave Smerdon: 'This is the big idea - spectacular!'} (14. Kh1 Nh5 $1 15. Be3 Bh4 16. Qe2 Bxf1 17. Qxf1 Bg3 $1 18. Qh3 Qh4 19. Qxh4 Bxh4 $17 {Vachier Lagrave-Yu,Y Doha 2016.}) (14. Qg3 Nh5 15. Qxh3 Nxf4 16. Qg4 Bg5 17. h4 h5 $1 18. Qg3 Bh6 $15) (14. Rfb1 Nh5 15. Be3 Bh4 16. Qe2 Bg5 (16... Kh7 17. f4 f5 18. Qf3 Bg4 19. Qg2 g5 $132 {Zherebukh-Salem, Fujairah 2012.}) 17. Kh1 Be6 18. Rg1 Bf4 19. Nd5 {Evtushenko-Efremov, ICCF email 2015.} Bxd5 20. Bxd5 Qf6 $132) 14... Bxf1 (14... gxh6 $4 {Dave Smerdon} 15. Qg3+ $18) 15. Qg3 Nh5 (15... Ne8 {Dave Smerdon} 16. Rxf1 $40) 16. Qg4 {Dave Smerdon: 'White only has a pawn for the rook, but the bishop on ff1 is stranded and Black's king is feeling less than secure.'} Qc8 {Dave Smerdon: '!' '!' '!' '!'} (16... Kh7 {Dave Smerdon} 17. Bd2 Nf6 18. Qf5+ g6 19. Qf4 $16) (16... Bxd3 {Dave Smerdon} 17. cxd3 Bf6 18. Kh1 $1 $40 {also looks dangerous.}) 17. Rxf1 (17. Qxh5 {Dave Smerdon} Qh3 $1 18. Qg6 Qxh6 19. Qxh6 gxh6 20. Kxf1 $44) 17... Qxg4+ 18. fxg4 gxh6 (18... Ng3 {Dave Smerdon} 19. Nd5 $1 Bd8 20. hxg3 gxh6 21. Ne3 $14 {the f5 and d5 outposts will fit sweetly for White's minor pieces.}) 19. gxh5 {Dave Smerdon: 'The dust has settled, and the engines announce "0.00". I'm not so sure. White has excellent control over the light squares and great spots for his pieces. I would rather play White for sure.'} Kh8 20. Ne2 {Dave Smerdon: 'Again, angling for f5.'} Rg8+ 21. Kh1 Rg4 $6 ({A more accurate move is} 21... Bh4 $1 {Dave Smerdon: 'was really necessary. Black needed to stop the knight landing on f5. Still,' when I don't see any advantage for White:} 22. Nf4 {Dave Smerdon: '!' '!' '!' '!'} (22. Rxf7 Raf8 $1) (22. Bxf7 $2 Raf8 $17) 22... Raf8 (22... Rg7 {Dave Smerdon} 23. Ng2 Bg5 24. h4 $1 Be7 25. Ne3 $1 {gets the knight there after all.}) 23. a4 Bg5 24. Ne2 {[%cal Ye2g3]} Bh4 25. Nf4 {with dynamic balance as Black isn't able to activate the rooks.}) 22. Ng3 Bg5 (22... Bh4 23. Nf5 $16) (22... Rf8 {Dave Smerdon} 23. Nf5 Bg5 24. Nxd6 Rh4 $1 25. Nf5 Rxh5 26. d4 $1 cxd4 27. Be2 $14 {White wins back the exchange and can push in this opposite-coloured bishop endgame.}) 23. Rxf7 $16 Rf4 (23... Bf4 {Dave Smerdon} 24. Be6 $1 Rh4 25. Kg2 Bxg3 26. hxg3 Rxh5 27. Rxb7 $16) 24. Nf5 Rf2 25. h4 Bc1 26. Rxb7 {Dave Smerdon: '' '' '' '' Dave Smerdon: 'Good enough for a big edge, but there was a stronger option.'} (26. Kg1 $1 {(Dave Smerdon) was a nice intermezzo, because the black rook would rather not move off the f-file:} Rxc2 27. Ne7 $3 $18) 26... Rf8 27. Bf7 Rxc2 28. Bg6 Rxf5 29. exf5 Bxb2 {Dave Smerdon: 'White has won back the exchange, but the opposite coloured bishops give Black decent drawing chances. Still, we definitely have to declare Black's opening a success.'} 30. Rxa7 ({It was a tough decision, but it transpires that the black king is worse off on g8, so} 30. Rh7+ {Dave Smerdon} Kg8 31. Rxa7 {was better.}) 30... Be5 31. a4 Rh2+ 32. Kg1 Rxh4 33. a5 c4 {Dave Smerdon: '!' '!' '!' '!'} 34. Rh7+ Kg8 35. dxc4 Rxc4 (35... Bg7 $5 {(Dave Smerdon) loses, but it's a little complicated:} 36. f6 $1 Rg4+ (36... Bxf6 37. Rd7 $18) 37. Kh1 Bxf6 38. Rd7 Bd4 39. Rxd6 Rg1+ 40. Kh2 Be5+ 41. Kxg1 Bxd6 42. Kf2 $18) 36. Rxh6 ({The endgame after} 36. Bf7+ {Dave Smerdon} Kxh7 37. Bxc4 {is somewhat beyond my pay grade, so I'm just going to assume these 2700s worked out it was drawn. However, it's pretty tricky:} Kg7 38. Kf2 Kf6 39. Bd3 Bc3 (39... Kg5 40. Ke3 Kxh5 $4 41. a6 Bh2 42. Kf3 Bg1 43. f6 $18) 40. a6 Bd4+ 41. Ke2 Ke5 42. Bc2 Bc5 43. Kd2 d5 44. Kc3 Kd6 45. Bd3 Kd7 46. Kb3 Kd6 47. Ka4 Ba7 {and I can't see how White makes progress.}) 36... Ra4 37. Rh7 Rxa5 38. Kg2 (38. h6 {Dave Smerdon} Ra1+ 39. Kg2 Ra2+ 40. Kf3 Rh2 41. Ke4 Rh4+ 42. Kd5 Bh8 $3 {(The only safe square for the bishop!)} 43. Ke6 Re4+ $1 44. Kxd6 Rh4 {and again, I can't see where the progress will come from.}) 38... Ra3 39. Re7 Rg3+ 40. Kf2 Rh3 41. Rf7 Rh4 42. Kg2 Rh2+ 43. Kf3 Rh4 44. Rd7 Rf4+ 45. Ke3 Rh4 46. Rf7 Bd4+ 47. Kd3 Be5 48. Rd7 Rd4+ 49. Kc3 Ra4+ 50. Kb3 Rh4 51. Rf7 Ba1 52. Re7 Be5 53. Rd7 Kh8 54. Rh7+ Kg8 55. Rd7 Kh8 56. Rh7+ Kg8 57. Rd7 {Dave Smerdon: 'Really excellent defence by Yangyi. Still, this is an exciting new idea in a line in which White hasn't found anything fresh for a while.'} 1/2-1/2


