1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 e6 7. f4 Qb6 8. Qd2 Qxb2 9. Rb1 Qa3 10. e5 h6 11. Bh4 dxe5 12. fxe5 {A very topical and sharp position.} g5 ({The alternatives are:} 12... Nfd7) ({and} 12... Nd5) 13. exf6 gxh4 14. Be2 ({Too slow was:} 14. Ne4 $6 Nd7 15. Rd1 Rg8 16. Bd3 h3 $15 {0-1 Bok, B (2488)-Edouard, R (2608)/Antwerp 2011}) 14... Qa5 15. O-O Nd7 16. Kh1 Qg5 17. Rf4 e5 18. Nd5 exd4 {This is a key position of the whole line with 12.... g5.} 19. Qxd4 $1 {The most dangerous continuation.} ({After} 19. Nc7+ Kd8 20. Nxa8 d3 $1 {Black was doing fine in Bromberger, S (2530) - Areshchenko, A / German Bundesliga 2010 [Richard Palliser]}) 19... Kd8 20. Ne7 {This looks critical as well.} ({The alternatives} 20. Bg4 $2) ({and} 20. Rd1 {were analysed in our PGN archive as well. You can see my notes to Duda, J (2563) - Wojtaszek, R (2713) / ch-Pol 2014 Warsaw [Roiz, M]}) 20... Qe5 $1 {The first precise move.} ({As I have discovered,} 20... Qc5 $6 {which was seen in 2 preceding games, gives White an additional dangerous possibility:} 21. Qb2 $1 $146 {keeping an eye on the rook!} (21. Qd2 Bxe7 22. fxe7+ Qxe7 {would just transpose to our game.}) 21... h3 (21... Qe5 22. Rd4 Qxe2 23. Qb6+ Ke8 24. Nd5 Be7 25. Nc7+ Kf8 26. fxe7+ Qxe7 27. Qa5 $40) 22. Bf3 hxg2+ 23. Bxg2 $40 {with a strong attack.}) 21. Qd2 {Keeping a pin along the d-file is the most natural continuation.} ({White had a couple of alternatives at his disposal:} 21. Nxc8 Rxc8 22. Rd1 Bd6 23. Qxd6 Qxd6 24. Rxd6 Rxc2 25. Bd1 Re8 (25... Rc6 $11) 26. h3 Rc6 27. Rxc6 bxc6 $11 {Safarli, E (2644)-Kurnosov, I (2649)/ Nakhchivan AZE 2013.}) (21. Qf2 $5 $146 Bxe7 (21... h3 22. Rd1 hxg2+ 23. Kg1 $44) 22. fxe7+ Qxe7 23. Rd1 $44) 21... Bxe7 ({Black had no time for:} 21... h3 $2 22. Bf3 $1 hxg2+ 23. Bxg2 {and White is just dominating. For instance,} Bxe7 24. fxe7+ Qxe7 25. Qa5+ b6 26. Qc3 $18) 22. fxe7+ Qxe7 23. Bg4 f5 $1 {A very important defensive resource. It is difficult to find it during a game.} (23... Re8 24. Rc4 $1 f5 (24... b6 25. Rd1 $40 {Kosteniuk, A (2469)-Ju, W (2536)/ Nalchik 2011}) 25. Bxf5 Qf7 26. Bxd7 Bxd7 27. Qa5+ Ke7 28. Qc5+ Kd8 29. Qc7+ Ke7 30. Re4+ Kf8 31. Rf4 Bf5 32. Qc5+ Kg8 33. Rxf5 $14) (23... b6 $6 24. Re1 Qc5 25. Rd4 Ra7 26. Qf4 Rg8 27. h3 $36) 24. Rxf5 ({It looks like Black is out of danger in other cases:} 24. Re1 Qg5 25. Rd1 fxg4 26. Qd4 Rg8 27. Qb6+ Ke8 28. Qe6+ Kd8 29. Rf7 Qb5 $11) (24. Bxf5 Rf8 25. Rd1 Qe5 $1 26. Re1 Qf6 27. Rd1 (27. Ree4 Qa1+ 28. Re1 Qf6 $11) 27... Qe5 $11) (24. Rd1 fxg4 25. Qa5+ Ke8 26. Qh5+ Kd8 27. Qa5+ Ke8 28. Re1 Rh7 29. Qh5+ (29. Rxg4 Nf6 30. Rxe7+ Rxe7 31. Rxh4 Bd7 32. Rxh6 Kf7 $132) 29... Kd8 30. Rxe7 Rxe7 31. Qxh4 Ne5 32. Rf8+ Kd7 33. Qxh6 Kc7 34. Qd2 Nc6 35. Qf4+ Kb6 36. Qf2+ Kc7 $11) 24... Re8 $1 {Reminding White of the 1st rank.} (24... b6 $6 25. Rd1 Ra7 26. Qf2 $1 $40) (24... Rf8 $6 25. Rxf8+ Qxf8 26. Rd1 $16) 25. Rd1 $146 {This novelty doesn't change the evaluation, but requires some accuracy from Black.} ({In my opinion, White's future attempts to fight for an opening advantage may be connected with:} 25. Rd5 b6 26. Rd1 $5 $146 (26. h3 {was covered in our PGN archive in Guseinov, G (2607) - Areshchenko, A (2720) / World Teams 2013 [Danny Gormally]}) 26... Ra7 27. Qf2 Rb7 28. h3 Rf8 29. Qd4 $44 {in this position White has full compensation for a piece.}) 25... Kc7 $1 {Black must avoid the pin as soon as possible.} ({There is no time for development:} 25... b6 $2 26. Bh5 Rg8 27. Rf7 Qe6 28. Qd4 Rb8 29. Qf4 Rb7 30. h3 $40) 26. Rf7 ({White has no more than a perpetual check after:} 26. Bh5 Rf8 27. Qf4+ Kb6 28. Qd4+ Kc7 $11) 26... Qxf7 27. Qd6+ Kd8 28. Qb6+ Ke7 29. Qd6+ Kd8 30. Qb6+ Ke7 31. Re1+ {Of course, White has no reason to accept a draw at this stage of the game - there is no risk.} Kf8 32. Qxh6+ Kg8 33. Qg5+ {Yu Yangui decides to finish the game immediately.} ({It seems like White could try to play without any risk after:} 33. Rxe8+ $5 Qxe8 34. Be6+ Qxe6 35. Qxe6+ Kg7 36. Qg4+ Kf7 37. Qh5+ Kg7 38. Qxh4 Nf6 39. Kg1 (39. Qg3+ Kf7 40. Qb3+ Kg6 $11) 39... Bf5 40. Qf4 {but after} Kg6 $1 41. h4 Bg4 $11 {Black should be able to set-up a blockade and secure a draw.}) 33... Kf8 34. Qh6+ Kg8 35. Qg5+ Kf8 36. Qh6+ 1/2-1/2


