{Shankland,Sam: '  This was my favourite of Wei Yi’s victories.   '} 1. e4 {GM Ioannis Papaioannou Shankland,Sam} c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 e5 7. Nf3 {Shankland,Sam: '!?'} ({Possibly the young Chinese star improvised to avoid concrete preparation from a player who almost always opens with 1...e5.} 7. Nb3 {(Shankland,Sam) had been Wei Yi’s choice in all of his previous games.}) 7... Qc7 8. a4 Be7 9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O Nbd7 {This continuation is new for our site.} (10... Be6 {was covered in detail in Bok, B (2590) - Gajewski, G (2631) / Fagernes GM Open 2014 [Roiz, M] was covered in detail in Bok, B (2590) - Gajewski, G (2631) / Fagernes GM Open 2014 [Roiz, M] was covered in detail in Bok, B (2590) - Gajewski, G (2631) / Fagernes GM Open 2014 [Roiz, M]}) ({Another popular continuation here is:} 10... b6 {Shankland,Sam: 'RR' Shankland,Sam: 'Najer,Evgeniy 2643 - Sjugirov,Sanan 2629, Russia 2011 - 112/138'} 11. a5 {like in Bologan, V (2688) - Naiditsch, A (2685) / Croatian Team Championship 2009 [Richard Palliser] like in Bologan, V (2688) - Naiditsch, A (2685) / Croatian Team Championship 2009 [Richard Palliser] like in Bologan, V (2688) - Naiditsch, A (2685) / Croatian Team Championship 2009 [Richard Palliser]} (11. Nd2 {was tried in Agopov, M (2445) - Palliser, R (2444) / Finnish League 2011 [Richard Palliser] was tried in Agopov, M (2445) - Palliser, R (2444) / Finnish League 2011 [Richard Palliser] was tried in Agopov, M (2445) - Palliser, R (2444) / Finnish League 2011 [Richard Palliser]})) 11. Nd2 {Shankland,Sam: 'Diagram    So far the game has gone down very normal channels, but Black’s next move is a very understandable mistake:   '} (11. a5 Nc5 12. Nd5 Nxd5 13. exd5 f5 {doesn't look dangerous for Black.}) 11... b6 $6 {This move is inaccurate, as it allows White to take control of the key d5-square. Still, it was played by many strong players before. This move is inaccurate, as it allows White to take control of the key d5-square. Still, it was played by many strong players before. Shankland,Sam: '?' Shankland,Sam: '  What could be more natural than preventing a5 and preparing to develop the last minor piece to its best square, pressuring e4 and controlling d5?  ' This move is inaccurate, as it allows White to take control of the key d5-square. Still, it was played by many strong players before.} ({Black's attempts to equalize in this line should be based on: Black's attempts to equalize in this line should be based on: Shankland,Sam: 'Yet, in view of how the game went, perhaps' Black's attempts to equalize in this line should be based on:} 11... Nc5 $1 {For instance, For instance, Shankland,Sam: 'could be recommended as an improvement.'} 12. a5 (12. Nd5 Nxd5 13. exd5 a5 (13... f5 14. a5 Bd7 15. c4 Be8 16. b4 Nd7 17. f4 $14) 14. Bb5 f5 15. Ra3 b6 16. Nc4 Bf6 $132) (12. Nc4 Rb8 13. f3 b5 ({or} 13... Be6 14. Nd5 Nxd5 15. exd5 Bf5 16. a5 Bg6 17. Qd2 f5 $132) 14. axb5 axb5 15. Na3 b4 16. Nab5 Qd8 17. Na2 Bd7 18. Nxd6 b3 $1 19. Bxc5 Qc7 $1 20. Bf2 bxc2 21. Qc1 Bxd6 22. Nc3 Rb4 23. Qxc2 Rfb8 $44 {with sufficient compensation for a pawn.}) (12. Bg5 Be6 13. Bf3 h6 14. Be3 Rfd8 (14... Rad8 $5) 15. Qe2 Nh7 16. Rfd1 Bg5 $11 {Bologan, V -Naiditsch, A /Venacu 20067}) 12... Be6 13. Bf3 Rac8 14. Qe2 Rfe8 15. Rfd1 Qc6 (15... h6 16. Nf1 $14 {was better for White in McShane, L -Papaioannou, I / Warsaw POL 2013 was better for White in McShane, L -Papaioannou, I / Warsaw POL 2013 was better for White in McShane, L -Papaioannou, I / Warsaw POL 2013}) 16. h3 h6 {with a complex strategical battle. with a complex strategical battle. with a complex strategical battle.}) 12. g4 $5 {A very ambitious novelty. Wei Yi doesn't mind seizing a lot of space on the k-side at the cost of exposing his king. GM Ioannis Papaioannou: '!' '!' A very ambitious novelty. Wei Yi doesn't mind seizing a lot of space on the k-side at the cost of exposing his king. Shankland,Sam: '!' Shankland,Sam: '  A fearless and strong move. White is unafraid of compromising his kingside in his fight to control the all-important d5 square.  ' A very ambitious novelty. Wei Yi doesn't mind seizing a lot of space on the k-side at the cost of exposing his king.} ({Another decent option was: Another decent option was: Another decent option was:} 12. Nc4 Bb7 13. f3 Rfd8 (13... Bc6 14. Bf2 b5 15. axb5 axb5 16. Rxa8 Rxa8 17. Ne3 $16 {Yu Yangyi -Indjic, A /Kocaeli TUR 2013}) (13... Rad8 {Shankland,Sam} 14. Bf2 d5 $5 15. Nxd5 Nxd5 16. exd5 Nf6 (16... Nc5) 17. Bxb6 Bc5+ 18. Bxc5 Qxc5+ 19. Kh1 Nxd5 {when he has clear compensation, though White should be at least modestly better after Qe1.}) 14. Bf2 {with a stable edge.}) 12... Bb7 {This move leads to a rather passive position. This move leads to a rather passive position. Shankland,Sam: 'N'} ({The most principled would be:} 12... h6 13. h4 {GM Ioannis Papaioannou: '!' '!' Shankland,Sam: 'would only serve to weaken Black’s kingside. RR Boey,Jozef Martin - Delabie,Jan, corr. 1991'} Bb7 (13... Nh7 14. Nd5 $16 Qd8 15. Nxe7+ $1 (15. Nc4 $5 Bxh4 16. Ndxb6 Nxb6 17. Bxb6 Qf6 18. Qxd6 Be6 19. Qxe5 $16) 15... Qxe7 16. Nc4 Qxh4 17. Kg2 $1 Nc5 18. Rh1 Qf6 19. f3 $16) 14. g5 hxg5 15. hxg5 Nh7 {winning a pawn, though} (15... Ne8 16. Bc4 g6 17. Qg4 $16) 16. g6 {GM Ioannis Papaioannou: '!' '!'} fxg6 17. Bc4+ Kh8 18. Nd5 (18. Qg4 $5) 18... Qd8 (18... Bxd5 19. Bxd5 Rac8 20. Bc4 Nc5 21. Qg4 $16) 19. Kg2 $36 {gives White a strong initiative.}) (12... Nc5 $6 13. g5 Ne8 14. Nd5 Qd8 15. b4 $1 Nd7 16. h4 Bb7 17. Nc4 $16) 13. g5 Ne8 14. Nc4 {GM Ioannis Papaioannou: '!' '!' Shankland,Sam: '' Shankland,Sam: 'Diagram    [Now the weakened light squares in Black’s position should prove to be his undoing. Note that Nc4 is only available because there is no longer any pressure against the e4 pawn from the knight, which has been pushed all the way back to e8.]   '} Qd8 15. h4 {GM Ioannis Papaioannou: '?!' '?!' Shankland,Sam: '?!' Shankland,Sam: '  This strikes me as careless.  '} ({Perhaps more accurate was:} 15. Qd2 $1 {connecting the rooks and restricting Black's active possibilities. For instance, connecting the rooks and restricting Black's active possibilities. For instance, Shankland,Sam: '' Shankland,Sam: ', defending the pawn while keeping the kingside intact and developing a new piece, looks much better to me.' connecting the rooks and restricting Black's active possibilities. For instance,} f6 (15... Nc5 16. f3 Rb8 17. h4 $16) (15... Rc8 16. h4 Nc5 17. f3 $16) 16. h4 fxg5 17. hxg5 Nc5 18. Bg4 Nxe4 19. Nxe4 Bxe4 20. Bxb6 Qb8 21. Be3 Qc7 22. Nb6 Rd8 23. c4 $16) 15... b5 $1 {The best practical chance - otherwise Black would be doomed to passive defence. The best practical chance - otherwise Black would be doomed to passive defence. Shankland,Sam: '  Black correctly looks for direct counterplay, and he is able to at least muddy the waters, but unfortunately his position is still bad.  ' The best practical chance - otherwise Black would be doomed to passive defence.} 16. axb5 axb5 17. Rxa8 $6 {This inaccuracy allows Black to activate his queen and disturb White's monarch. This inaccuracy allows Black to activate his queen and disturb White's monarch. This inaccuracy allows Black to activate his queen and disturb White's monarch.} ({Correct was} 17. Nxb5 $1 {now after} Rxa1 (17... Bxe4 18. Qd2 Qc8 (18... d5 19. f3 $1 dxc4 20. fxe4 Bc5 21. Bxc5 Nxc5 22. Qd5 $16) 19. Nc3 Bb7 20. Nd5 $16) 18. Qxa1 Bxe4 {White is able to prevent the further activation of Black's forces and fix an edge: White is able to prevent the further activation of Black's forces and fix an edge: White is able to prevent the further activation of Black's forces and fix an edge:} 19. Qa4 Bc6 20. Na5 Ba8 21. Na7 Nc5 22. Bxc5 dxc5 23. N5c6 Qc7 24. Nc8 Bxc6 25. Qxc6 Bd8 26. Qxc7 Nxc7 27. Nd6 Ne6 28. Bc4 $16) 17... Qxa8 18. Nxb5 Bxe4 19. Ncxd6 Nxd6 20. Nxd6 {Shankland,Sam: 'Diagram   '} Bxd6 $2 {Unfortunately, Samuel exchanges his important dark-squared bishop. Now White's pawn chain on the k-side is safe. Unfortunately, Samuel exchanges his important dark-squared bishop. Now White's pawn chain on the k-side is safe. Unfortunately, Samuel exchanges his important dark-squared bishop. Now White's pawn chain on the k-side is safe.} ({At the same time. At the same time. Shankland,Sam: 'The computer’s suggestion'} 20... Rd8 $1 {Shankland,Sam: 'is much more resilient. Then after'} 21. Nxe4 Qxe4 {Shankland,Sam: 'Black’s queen proves to be quite a nuisance.'} 22. Qd3 {Shankland,Sam: '!' Shankland,Sam: 'I prefer this to the computer’s 22.Bd3  '} (22. Bd3 {Shankland,Sam} Qxh4 23. Kg2 (23. Bf5) 23... g6 24. f3) 22... Qxh4 23. Qf5 {Shankland,Sam: '(Securing the White kingside)'} (23. Rd1 Bxg5 24. Bxg5 Qxg5+ 25. Kf1 g6 $132) 23... g6 24. Qg4 Qxg4+ 25. Bxg4 {Shankland,Sam: '' Shankland,Sam: 'Stockfish insists this position is completely equal, but with two connected passed pawns supported by a bishop pair, I think White can push hard for a victory.'} Nc5 $14 {gave Black excellent drawing chances due to the reduced material balance. gave Black excellent drawing chances due to the reduced material balance. gave Black excellent drawing chances due to the reduced material balance.}) 21. Qxd6 {Shankland,Sam: '+-' Shankland,Sam: '  And now it’s over. White has two connected passed pawns and Black is unable to make any serious kingside threats. Wei Yi finished in style:   '} Bf5 ({Pointless would be:} 21... Rd8 22. c3 Nf8 (22... Bd5 23. Rd1 Be6 24. h5 $18) (22... Bf3 23. Bxf3 Qxf3 24. Rd1 Qg4+ 25. Kf1 $18) 23. Qxe5 Bf3 24. Bxf3 Qxf3 25. Qg3 {and White should be able to convert his material advantage into a full point. and White should be able to convert his material advantage into a full point. and White should be able to convert his material advantage into a full point.}) 22. Rd1 $1 {Precise play is still required from White, but the position is winning now. Precise play is still required from White, but the position is winning now. Precise play is still required from White, but the position is winning now.} Qa4 ({Possibly Samuel has missed: Possibly Samuel has missed: Possibly Samuel has missed:} 22... Qe4 23. Qd3 $1 $18) ({Black achieves nothing also with:} 22... Be6 23. f3 $1 Rc8 24. c3 e4 25. fxe4 Qxe4 26. Qf4 Qb7 27. Rd2 Re8 28. b4 $18) 23. c4 g6 ({Hopeless was also:} 23... Qc2 24. Qd2 Qb3 25. c5 Nb8 26. Qc3 Qxc3 27. bxc3 Be4 28. f3 Bc6 29. Rd6 $18) 24. Rd2 {Covering the 2nd rank wasn't necessary.. Covering the 2nd rank wasn't necessary.. Covering the 2nd rank wasn't necessary..} ({More convincing was:} 24. b4 $1 Qc2 25. Qd2 Qe4 26. Qd5 Qxh4 27. Qh1 $18 {liquidating into a winning endgame.}) 24... Rb8 25. Kh2 Qa1 ({Somewhat more stubborn was:} 25... Qa8 26. h5 $1 ({Less clear is} 26. Qd5 Qxd5 27. cxd5 Rb4 28. Kg3 Kf8 $16) 26... gxh5 (26... Qe4 27. Qxb8+ Nxb8 28. Rd8+ Kg7 29. h6#) 27. Qh6 Qb7 28. Qxh5 Qc7 29. Qf3 Be6 30. Qg3 $18) 26. Qc7 {Now White gets a decisive material advantage, so the rest was just an agony. Now White gets a decisive material advantage, so the rest was just an agony. Now White gets a decisive material advantage, so the rest was just an agony.} Qa8 27. Rxd7 Bxd7 {Shankland,Sam: 'Diagram   '} 28. Qxd7 Rxb2 29. Bf3 e4 30. Bxe4 $1 {A final touch.} Qb8+ (30... Qxe4 31. Qd8+ Kg7 32. Bd4+ $18) 31. Kg2 h5 32. Bd5 {Shankland,Sam: '  [And the battle of the world’s two youngest GMs ended in favour of the Chinese. I was particularly impressed by how Wei Yi improvised with 7.Nf3 to avoid any preparation and then found a very original and very strong idea with 12.g4!, fighting hard for control of the light squares without worrying about his compromised kingside, after which he very accurately restricted his opponent’s counterplay and brought the point home.]  '} 1-0


