1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. h3 e5 7. Nde2 h5 8. g3 b5 {A new move for our PGN archive.} (8... Be7 9. Bg2 b5 (9... O-O 10. Be3 Nbd7 11. a4 Qc7 $2 12. g4 $1 $36 {was bad for Black in Ponomariov, R (2711) - Areschenko, A (2655) / 83rd ch-UKR 2014 [Roiz, M]}) 10. Nd5 Nbd7 11. Nxe7 Qxe7 12. Bg5 Bb7 13. Nc3 Qe6 14. h4 {offered White interesting play in Shirov, A  (2708) - Palliser, R (2453) /British League (4NCL) 2013 [Richard Palliser]}) 9. Nd5 {Sethuraman is following Shirov's approach from a previous note, so he occupies the key d5 square immediately. This move was never seen before, but the official novelty comes later.} ({Indeed, the premature} 9. a4 $6 b4 10. Nd5 {can be strongly met by:} Nbd7 $1 11. Nxb4 ({After} 11. Bg5 Bb7 12. Bg2 Be7 {Black's position is preferable due to the poor placement of Ne2.}) 11... Qa5 12. c3 Bb7 13. f3 d5 $36) ({Black is also doing well after} 9. Bg2 Bb7 10. O-O Be7 11. a4 b4 12. Nd5 Nxd5 13. exd5 a5 {Pancevski, F (2470)-Volokitin, A (2695) / Plovdiv 2012}) 9... Nbd7 {Now the game transposes into known paths.} (9... Nxd5 10. Qxd5 Ra7 11. Be3 {leaves Black with a worse position:} Rd7 (11... Rb7 12. Qd2 Nd7 13. Nc3 Nf6 14. O-O-O Be6 15. f3 $14) 12. Bg2 Bb7 13. Qd3 d5 (13... Be7 14. Nc3 $14) 14. exd5 Bxd5 15. Bxd5 Rxd5 16. Qe4 Nc6 17. O-O $14) 10. Bg5 ({It makes sense to start with} 10. Nec3 $5 {, since White's Ne2 hardly has other good routes. It looks like in that case Black has some problems to solve. For instance,} Bb7 (10... h4 11. Bg5 hxg3 12. fxg3 Be7 13. Nxe7 Qxe7 14. Nd5 Qd8 15. Bg2 $14) 11. Bg2 Nxd5 12. Nxd5 Nb6 13. Bg5 Qxg5 14. Nxb6 Rb8 15. h4 Qd8 16. Nd5 $14) 10... Bb7 (10... Be7 {most probably would transpose to the text:} 11. Nxe7 Qxe7 12. Bg2 Bb7 13. Nc3 Rc8) 11. Nec3 {White doesn't want to lose control over the d5-square.} (11. Bg2 {leads to complex play after:} Bxd5 12. exd5 Be7 13. O-O O-O $132) 11... Rc8 (11... Be7 12. Nxe7 Qxe7 13. Bg2 Qe6 14. a3 {could have transposed to the text} ({However, White gets an additional attractive option:} 14. h4 $5 O-O 15. a3 {and now, when 15...Rc8 can be strongly met by 16.Bh3, Black is under some pressure.})) 12. Bg2 ({After} 12. Bxf6 Nxf6 13. a4 b4 14. Nxf6+ gxf6 {Black gets sufficient counterplay a-la Sveshnikov:} 15. Nd5 f5 16. exf5 (16. Bg2 Rc5 {wouldn't change much}) 16... Rc5 17. Bg2 Qa8 18. Nb6 Qa7 19. Nd5 Qa8 $11) 12... Be7 13. Nxe7 (13. Bxf6 Nxf6 14. h4 Rc5 $11) 13... Qxe7 14. a3 {This prophylactic move is a novelty. It makes sense to secure the main protector of Pe4.} ({Black is doing well in case of} 14. O-O Qe6 15. Qd2 O-O 16. Rfd1 b4 17. Nd5 Rc4 $132) ({Deserves serious attention also:} 14. h4 Nb6 15. Qd3 {as was played in the following Top-level game:} Qc7 ({Possibly,} 15... O-O $5 {may be an improvement for Black:} 16. O-O-O Rc6 (16... b4 17. Nd5 Nbxd5 18. exd5 Rc5 19. Rd2 Rfc8 20. Kb1 $14) 17. f4 Rfc8 18. Bh3 Re8 19. Rhf1 Bc8 $132) 16. Bh3 Rb8 17. Bxf6 gxf6 18. O-O-O b4 19. Nd5 Nxd5 20. exd5 Bc8 21. f4 $14 {Karjakin, S (2759)-Gelfand, B (2777)/Wijk aan Zee NED 2014}) 14... Qe6 15. Qe2 ({The careless} 15. O-O $6 {can be strongly met by the thematic sac:} Rxc3 16. bxc3 Nxe4 $15) 15... O-O (15... d5 {doesn't fully solve Black's problems:} 16. exd5 Nxd5 17. Qd2 $1 Rc5 (17... Nxc3 18. Bxb7 Rc7 19. Bg2 Na4 20. Qa5 $1 Rc8 21. b3 Nac5 22. O-O $14) 18. O-O-O Nxc3 19. Bxb7 Rc7 20. Bd5 Nxd5 21. Qxd5 Qxd5 22. Rxd5 $14) ({But worth attention is:} 15... Nb6 $5 16. h4 Qc4 17. Qxc4 Nxc4 18. Bxf6 gxf6 19. O-O-O Ke7 20. Nd5+ Bxd5 21. Rxd5 Rc6 {with good chances for equality.}) 16. h4 $1 {Sethuraman finds a nice way to put some pressure on the Pd6. Now Black urgently has to remove the pieces from the h3-c8 diagonal.} ({The prosaic} 16. O-O Nb6 17. Rfd1 Nc4 18. Bc1 Rfd8 {led to a roughly equal position.}) 16... Rc4 17. Rd1 (17. Bh3 $5 Qe7 18. a4 Nc5 19. axb5 axb5 20. Bg2 Bc6 21. Nd5 Bxd5 22. exd5 $14) 17... Nc5 18. Bxf6 $6 {This exchange of the dark-squared bishop definitely makes Black's task easier.} ({The only way to pose Black some problems was:} 18. f3 $1 {this move looks like a concession, but White should be able to consolidate and keep some pressure:} Qe7 (18... d5 19. Bxf6 d4 20. Bg5 dxc3 21. b3 Rd4 22. O-O $14) 19. O-O Ne6 20. Be3 $1 (20. Bxf6 Qxf6 21. Rxd6 Nd4 22. Qxc4 Qxd6 23. Qd3 Qc5 24. Kh2 a5 $44) 20... Qc7 21. Rd2 $14) 18... Qxf6 19. O-O ({Nothing promised} 19. Nd5 Bxd5 20. Rxd5 g6 21. O-O Na4 22. c3 Nb6 23. Rd3 Qe7 24. Rfd1 Rc6 $11) 19... Qg6 20. Rfe1 Rd4 ({Another good way was:} 20... Rc8 21. Nd5 Bxd5 22. Rxd5 Na4 23. c3 Qf6 24. Red1 R4c6 $11) 21. Rxd4 {Inviting the simplifications.} ({After} 21. Bf3 Qf6 22. b4 (22. Bxh5 Nxe4 23. Rxd4 Nxc3 24. bxc3 exd4 $11) 22... Ne6 (22... Rc4 23. Qe3 Na4 24. Nxa4 bxa4 25. Bxh5 $14) 23. Nd5 Qd8 24. Bxh5 Rc4 25. c3 (25. Qd3 g6 26. Bg4 Bxd5 27. Qxd5 Nd4 $11) 25... Nc7 26. Ne3 Rxc3 27. Qb2 Rc6 {Black wins the pawn back and manages to equalize.}) 21... exd4 22. Nd5 (22. Na2 {is too passive and offers Black comfortable play after} Re8 23. Qd1 Bxe4 24. Qxd4 Re6 $11) 22... Bxd5 23. exd5 Na4 24. b3 {Now Black's knight gets an excellent square on c3, where it restricts White's heavy pieces.} ({More accurate was:} 24. Be4 Qh6 25. Qd1 Nxb2 26. Qxd4 Nc4 27. Bd3 Ne5 $11) 24... Nc3 25. Qd2 Qf6 26. Qd3 {White can only sit and wait, but Black is unable to make progress either.} Rd8 (26... g6 27. Bf3 Kg7 28. Kg2 $11) 27. Bf3 g6 28. Kg2 Kf8 29. Qd2 Kg7 30. Qd3 Kf8 {Black decides to call it a day - the Pd4 is a permanent cause of worry.} 31. Qd2 Kg7 32. Qd3 1/2-1/2


