1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. f4 {[%cal Ge4e5] A well-forgotten line, that was quite popular decades ago.} Qc7 {As the route of this game proves, delaying the development of the k-side pieces is somewhat risky.} ({The most common} 6... e5 7. Nf3 Nbd7 8. a4 Be7 9. Bd3 O-O 10. O-O Nc5 ({Or} 10... exf4 11. Kh1 Nc5 12. Bxf4 Bg4) 11. Kh1 exf4 12. Bxf4 Bg4 {This position was covered in a few old games on our site, and it definitely looks acceptable for Black. Undoubtedly, GM Yu Yangyi also had some ideas in mind in this case.}) 7. f5 $1 {[%csl Rc8,Ge5][%cal Gg2g4,Gg4g5] This strong move is new for our site. White makes it tougher for Black to castle, whereas g2-g4 is following soon.} (7. Be2 e5 8. Nf5 Bxf5 9. exf5 Nc6 {Black didn't face real problems in Ivanchuk,V (2753)-Dominguez Perez,L (2768) Havana CUB 2014 [Roiz, M]}) ({Black also reached a flexible setup after} 7. a4 g6 8. Nf3 Nbd7 9. Bd3 Bg7 10. O-O O-O {Dzhumaev,M (2530)-Wojtaszek,R (2734) Kolkata Open 2012  [Richard Palliser]}) 7... g6 $6 {GM Wei Yi comes up with a natural novelty, but it was nicely refuted by his strong opponent.} (7... b5 {can be well met by} 8. g4 $1 ({Worse is} 8. Bd3 Bb7 9. Qe2 Nbd7 {Black was fine in Firman,N - Ghaem Maghami,E Dresden 2007}) 8... Bb7 9. Bg2 Nbd7 10. a3 $36 {Black struggles to develop his dark-squared bishop.}) ({The optimal choice might be} 7... e5 {, even though Black's task is still not easy:} 8. fxe6 fxe6 9. Be2 (9. g4 {is traditionally well met by} d5 $1 10. exd5 Bb4 $132 {Micottis,D - Livaic, L Tarvisio 2017}) 9... Nc6 10. O-O Be7 11. Nxc6 Qxc6 12. Bh5+ g6 13. Bf3 {Black came under some pressure in the correspondence game Gruber,R - Pilgram,K email 2013}) 8. g4 $1 {[%cal Gg4g5,Gc3d5]} d5 {GM Wei Yi is trying to change the unfavorable route of the game, but once the position opens White's lead in development should tell.} ({After} 8... b5 9. Bg2 b4 (9... Bb7 10. O-O Bg7 11. g5 Nh5 12. Be3 $16) 10. Nd5 Nxd5 11. exd5 Bg7 12. O-O {Black's position is cramped, and he struggles to develop his knight.}) 9. Nxd5 ({I guess,} 9. exd5 $5 {was rejected by Yu Yangyi in view of} Qe5+ 10. Be2 Nxg4 {, and it looks like the Ke1 is unsafe.} (10... Nxd5 11. Nxd5 Qxd5 12. Rf1 Bg7 13. Be3 O-O 14. Qd2 $36) {However, this was also promising for White:} 11. Nf3 $1 Qxf5 12. Qd4 Nf6 13. Qa4+ Bd7 14. Qb3 $36 {the misplaced Qf5 is a cause of worries.}) 9... Nxd5 10. exd5 Qa5+ ({Worse is} 10... Qe5+ $2 11. Ne2 $1 gxf5 12. Bg2 fxg4 13. O-O Bg7 14. c3 O-O 15. Ng3 {, and White has a decisive attack - Black's king desperately lacks defenders.}) 11. Qd2 ({Equally good was} 11. c3 $5 Qxd5 12. Rg1 Bg7 13. Be3 O-O 14. Bg2 Qa5 15. Qf3 $36 {with strong pressure along the h1-a8 diagonal.}) 11... Qxd5 12. Bg2 Qe5+ 13. Qe3 $1 {[%csl Ra8,Rb7,Gg2] It turns out that White can afford to exchange queens - the powerful Bg2 would offer him the better prospects for sure.} (13. Kf2 Bg7 14. c3 Nd7) 13... Bg7 14. Qxe5 $2 {[%cal Gh8g8] However, this is premature. White overestimates Black's counterplay along the g-file.} ({Much stronger was} 14. c3 $1 {[%cal Ge5e3,Gg2a8]} Nd7 15. O-O {[%cal Ge5e3,Gc1e3]} Qxe3+ 16. Bxe3 Ne5 17. h3 Nc4 18. Bg5 $36) 14... Bxe5 15. Be3 gxf5 $1 16. gxf5 ({The more ambitious} 16. Nxf5 {[%csl Rb2]} Bxb2 17. Rb1 Bc3+ 18. Ke2 Nc6 {wouldn't yield White more than equality.}) 16... Rg8 17. Bf3 Bxd4 $1 {GM Wei Yi correctly gives up his dark-squared bishop - Black has to complete development as soon as possible.} (17... Nd7 $2 18. O-O-O Rb8 19. Ne2 $16) 18. Bxd4 Nc6 {[%cal Gh1a8,Gc8f5]} 19. Bxc6+ {This can be called 'a silent draw offer'. True, White didn't have any adequate alternatives.} bxc6 20. f6 {[%csl Re8,Gf6]} Rg2 {The active Rg2 leaves White nothing better than exchanging it.} ({Safe was also} 20... Bf5 21. O-O-O e6 22. Rhg1 O-O-O 23. Rg7 Bg6 $11) 21. O-O-O Bf5 {[%cal Gg2c2]} 22. Rd2 Rxd2 23. Kxd2 O-O-O {There is no intrigue now.} 24. Kc3 exf6 25. Bxf6 Rd5 26. b4 a5 {Inviting further simplifications.} 27. a3 axb4+ 28. axb4 Rd6 29. Be5 Re6 30. Re1 f6 31. Bg3 Rxe1 32. Bxe1 Be4 33. Bg3 1/2-1/2


