1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 e6 7. Be2 Be7 8. Qd2 O-O 9. O-O-O b5 {This move was mentioned by me} ({in the notes to} 9... Nc6 {Ponomariov,R (2711)-Ivanchuk,V (2726) Lviv UKR 2014 [Roiz,M], where White had excellent attacking prospects, but later came under strong pressure.}) 10. Bf3 {Absolutely the best.} (10. a3 $6 Bb7 11. f3 Nbd7 12. g4 Nb6 13. h4 Nfd7 {is more than comfortable for Black, was was shown in a couple of games.}) 10... b4 11. Nce2 Bb7 12. e5 Nd5 13. Nf4 {This novelty may hardly cause Black any problems.} ({In my opinion, the previously played} 13. exd6 {is preferable} Qxd6 ({Worse is} 13... Bxd6 $6 14. Nf5 $1 Be5 {This position was seen in Shevchenko,K - Nayhebaver,M Lviv UKR 2015 Now White should have played} 15. Nf4 $1 Nc6 16. Bxd5 exf5 17. Bf3 $36 {, keeping Black under strong pressure.}) 14. Nf5 {I have to admit, that my previous assessment of 'White is better' isn't correct, even though Black has to play precisely in order to solve his problems:} Qc7 15. Bg5 (15. Nxe7+ Qxe7 16. Bg5 f6 17. Bh4 Nc6 18. Bxd5 exd5 19. Qxd5+ Kh8 20. Rhe1 Rad8 $44) 15... exf5 16. Bxd5 Nc6 17. Bxe7 Nxe7 18. Bxb7 Qxb7 $132 {leads to an approximately equal position, where Black's active piece play compensates for the structural drawback.}) 13... Nxe3 14. Qxe3 Bxf3 15. gxf3 $6 {An over-optimistic decision! White takes a serious strategic risk, since now his pawn structure is much worse.} ({Correct was} 15. Qxf3 d5 ({Possible is also} 15... Ra7 $5 {, provoking} 16. Nfxe6 fxe6 17. Qb3 {, and after the cold-blooded} dxe5 18. Nxe6 Qb6 19. Nxf8+ Kxf8 $132 {Black should be fine.}) 16. Qg4 Bg5 17. g3 Nd7 18. Rhe1 $11 {, maintaining the balance.}) 15... Qa5 $2 {Returning the favor!} ({Much stronger was} 15... Bg5 $1 16. Kb1 ({Even worse is} 16. Rhg1 Bh6 17. Kb1 Nd7 {the pinned Nf4 would cause White serious problems.}) 16... d5 17. Rhg1 Bh6 $15 {, securing the king and putting pressure on White's weaknesses.}) 16. exd6 Bg5 {This move isn't as effective as before, but still not bad!} ({However, more precise seems} 16... Bf6 $1 17. Kb1 ({In case of} 17. Ndxe6 fxe6 18. Qxe6+ Kh8 19. Rd5 Qd8 20. Qg4 Rf7 21. Rh5 h6 $132 {White has enough play for a piece, but hardly more.}) 17... Qe5 18. Qxe5 Bxe5 $11 {Black should be able to regain the pawn and neutralize the activity of White's pieces.}) 17. Rhg1 Bh6 18. Kb1 e5 $2 {Another serious mistake - Black can't afford to delay the development of his q-side pieces for too long.} ({The natural} 18... Nd7 19. Qe4 ({Nothing special also promises} 19. Nc6 Qb5 20. Qe4 Nf6 21. Qd4 Qxc6 22. Qxf6 Rfc8 23. Rd2 g6 $132) 19... Nf6 20. Qb7 $1 {enables White to avoid the dangerous pin, but after} Qe5 $1 ({But not} 20... Bxf4 $1 21. Nxe6 $1 Bh6 22. Nxf8 Rxf8 23. d7 Bf4 24. Qc6 {, and the d-pawn should decide the game.}) 21. Nfe2 Nd5 $132 {Black would obtain decent counterplay.}) 19. Nf5 {On his turn, White is tempted by a sacrificial approach.} ({Better was:} 19. Qe4 $1 exd4 20. Qxa8 Bxf4 21. Rxd4 Nd7 22. Qe4 Bxh2 23. Rgd1 $16 {, and the strong Pd6 puts Black in a difficult situation.}) 19... Bxf4 20. Rxg7+ $6 {Another step in the wrong direction.} ({Once again, after} 20. Qe4 $1 {was very promising:} Nd7 21. Nxg7 $1 Kh8 22. Qf5 Qd8 23. Nh5 Bh6 24. Rg4 f6 25. Rxb4 $36) 20... Kh8 21. Qb3 Nc6 {Finally Black manages to connect his rooks.} 22. Rdg1 (22. Rxf7 {is well met by} Nd4 $1 23. Nxd4 exd4 24. d7 Rxf7 25. Qxf7 Qe5 $11 {, and Black is safe.}) 22... Qd8 $2 {Luckily for GM Wei Yi, his lower-rated opponent doesn't withstand the pressure.} ({Instead, after} 22... Nd4 23. Nxd4 exd4 24. Qd3 Qh5 25. d7 Rad8 26. Qe4 Bxh2 ({Possible is also} 26... Be5 27. R7g5 Qxh2 28. Qxe5+ Qxe5 29. Rxe5 Rxd7 $11) 27. R1g4 Bc7 {White would have nothing better than forcing a draw by perpetual:} 28. Rh4 Qxh4 29. Qxh4 Kxg7 30. Qg5+ $11) 23. Qd3 Qf6 24. Ne7 Qh6 ({Or} 24... Qxg7 25. Rxg7 Kxg7 26. Nxc6 $18) 25. Qf5 Nd4 26. Rxh7+ {A short, but exciting struggle!} 1-0


