1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 d6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nf6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 a6 8. O-O-O Be7 9. f4 Bd7 10. Nf3 b5 11. Bxf6 gxf6 12. Kb1 Qb6 13. g3 {As the route of this game shows, this natural move seems somewhat inaccurate.} (13. f5 O-O-O 14. g3 Kb8 15. fxe6 fxe6 16. Bh3 Na5 $1 {was covered in the previous Update in Pena Gomez,M (2483)-Demchenko,A (2670) Pontevedra ESP 2018}) ({For some reason,} 13. Bd3 $5 {is really uncommon, though it definitely contains venom. For instance,} O-O-O ({Riskier seems} 13... b4 14. Ne2 a5 15. f5 Qc5 16. Nf4 a4 17. Rhe1 {The following practical tests prove that Black suffers from strong pressure on the Pe6:} Ne5 (17... Bd8 18. b3 Qc3 19. Bb5 $16 {Timofeev,A - Alekseenko,K Samara 2015}) 18. fxe6 fxe6 19. Be2 O-O 20. Nd4 Qc8 21. Bb5 $1 $16 {Hartman,C - Schneider,L Stockholm 1987}) 14. Rhe1 Kb8 15. Nd5 $1 {This seems the most challenging} (15. Bf1 Rc8 16. Ne2 Na5 17. Ned4 Nc4 {was fine for Black in Chigaev,M - Lobanov,S St Petersburg 2014}) 15... exd5 16. exd5 Ne5 17. fxe5 fxe5 18. Qh6 Qc5 19. Qh5 Rdf8 20. Bf5 {White was better in Timman,J - Ivanovic,B Bugojno 1984}) 13... b4 $1 (13... O-O-O 14. f5 {could have transposed to the above-mentioned note, but the text is even more attractive!}) 14. Ne2 (14. Na4 $6 Qa5 15. b3 Na7 $36) 14... a5 15. f5 (15. Ned4 {, as in Kokarev,D - Savitskiy,S Khanty-Mansiysk RUS 2017 is hardly more promising, since} a4 16. f5 e5 17. Nb5 b3 $1 {offers Black sufficient counterplay, to say the least.}) 15... e5 {This position occurred in 2 games so far.} 16. Nc1 {This was still seen in both games, but it looks very passive.} ({More in the spirit of the position seems} 16. g4 $5 a4 17. Ng3 Qc5 18. Be2 {with very sharp, double-edged play.}) 16... Rc8 ({Possibly even stronger was} 16... Na7 $5 17. Qh6 Bc6 18. Bd3 Nb5 {, and Black seizes the initiative.}) 17. Qd5 $2 {A very unsuccessful innovation from the young Chinese grandmaster.} ({The previously played} 17. g4 {, as in Klovans,J-Kupreichik,V Soviet Union 1972 can be well met by} h5 $1 18. gxh5 (18. g5 fxg5 19. Nxg5 Nd4 $17) 18... a4 19. Rg1 Na5 $36) ({However, the energetic} 17. Qh6 $1 {seems to maintain the balance. For instance,} a4 18. Rxd6 $1 Bxd6 19. Qxf6 O-O 20. Qxd6 Qe3 21. Qf6 Qxf3 22. Qg5+ Kh8 23. Qf6+ $11) 17... Na7 {Jiri unlocks the c-file, so White's queen could be attacked soon.} ({There was also nothing wrong with} 17... a4 $5 18. Bb5 (18. Nd2 O-O 19. Nc4 Qa7 20. Nxd6 Rcd8 $19) 18... Ra8 19. Bc4 O-O $17) 18. Nd2 {A sad necessity. White is forced to fully focus on his defensive task.} ({There is no time for a counter-attack:} 18. Bc4 O-O 19. g4 Bb5 20. Nd2 Qa6 21. Bxb5 Nxb5 {, and White can hardly withstand the pressure on the q-side.}) 18... Bc6 19. Qd3 a4 {GM Stocek's play is very natural and strong.} 20. Nc4 Qc5 21. Qf3 $2 {Alas, after this move White loses almost without a fight.} ({The only way to put-up resistance was} 21. Ne3 Nb5 22. Nd5 Bxd5 ({Black hardly achieves more with} 22... Nd4 23. Ne2 Bxd5 24. exd5 Qxc2+ 25. Qxc2 Nxc2 26. Rc1 b3 27. Nc3 {, and White's pieces are getting into play.}) 23. Qxb5+ Bc6 24. Qxc5 dxc5 25. Bg2 $17) 21... Nb5 22. Qe3 (22. Ne3 {is nicely refuted by} Na3+ $1 23. bxa3 bxa3 24. Nc4 Qb4+ 25. Ka1 Bxe4 $19) 22... Nd4 {Of course, Black should avoid exchanging the queens.} 23. Bd3 (23. b3 Nb5 24. Qxc5 Nc3+ 25. Ka1 dxc5 26. Re1 Bxe4 $19) 23... d5 {Now almost all of Black's pieces join the attack.} 24. Nd2 ({Equally bad was} 24. exd5 Bxd5 25. b3 Nb5 $19) 24... a3 25. exd5 Bxd5 26. Ne4 Qc6 27. Nb3 O-O 28. Rhe1 ({Or} 28. Nxd4 exd4 29. Qxd4 axb2 $19 {, and the king is helpless.}) 28... Nxc2 {The rest has little chess value. What a disappointing defeat for such a talented young Grandmaster!} 29. Qh6 Bxb3 30. Ng5 Bxa2+ 31. Kc1 Nxe1+ 32. Kd2 Nf3+ 0-1


