1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 e6 7. f4 h6 8. Bh4 Qb6 9. Qd2 Qxb2 10. Rb1 Qa3 11. e5 {The most aggressive.} dxe5 12. fxe5 Nfd7 13. Ne4 Qxa2 14. Rd1 Qd5 15. Qe3 Qxe5 16. Be2 Bc5 17. Bg3 Qd5 $5 {A new move for our PGN Archive. It was successfully employed by MVL a few months ago in his victorious tournament in Dortmund. The main idea behind this move is to provoke the c2-c4 advance, when the pawn would lock White's minor pieces.} (17... Bxd4 {is much more popular. It was seen in all the games on this site so far.} 18. Rxd4 Qa5+ 19. Rd2 O-O {No doubt, this line was analysed in detail by GM Wei Yi - 5 years ago he had to defend the Black side!} 20. Bd6 {and now Black is at a crossroads:} Nc6 {This way of handling the position seems most natural - Black has a big material advantage, so there is no reason for any greediness. However, Black's position is still not to everyone's taste!} (20... Rd8 {Black has 3 extra pawns after this move, but his lack of development makes his position extremely risky: Another dangerous continuation was successfully employed by great Sicilian expert GM Negi:} 21. g4 $5 {It turns out that White can afford to keep the king in the centre and open-up the g-file:} (21. Qg3 Nc6 (21... Qf5 22. Be5 Qg6 23. Qh4 Nc6 {led Vishy to a victory in Motylev,A (2647)-Anand,V (2779) Wijk aan Zee 2007 [TonyK] , but had White played} 24. Bh5 $1 Qf5 25. Bxg7 $1 Kxg7 (25... Nc5 26. Nxc5 Kxg7 {as was played in Vorobiov,E (2575)-Askarov,M (2516) Serpukhov 2007, isn't a real improvement:} 27. Rf1 $1 Qe5+ 28. Ne4 Qa1+ 29. Rd1 Rxd1+ 30. Bxd1 Bd7 31. Rf6 $18) 26. Rf1 $18 {the attack would be unstoppable!}) 22. Bc7 Qb4 23. Nd6 {Tilicheev,V (2361)-Wei,Y (2286) Moscow 2011}) 21... Nc6 22. g5 hxg5 23. Rg1 Nf6 ({The real test of Negi's idea would be:} 23... f6 $1 24. h4 (24. Nxg5 {leads only to a draw:} Nc5 25. Nf7 Kxf7 26. Rxg7+ Kxg7 27. Qg3+ Kh8 28. Qh4+ Kg8 $11) 24... Nf8 25. c3 Ng6 26. hxg5 f5 27. Bh5 f4 28. Qf3 Qf5 $132 {This line definitely requires further practical tests.}) 24. Rxg5 Qa1+ 25. Rd1 Qxd1+ 26. Bxd1 Nxe4 27. Qxe4 Rxd6 28. h4 $36 {Negi,P (2615)-Huschenbeth,N (2459) Chotowa 2010}) ({Definitely inferior is:} 20... Re8 $6 21. O-O f5 22. Qg3 Nc6 23. Qg6 Qd8 {Black was able achieve a draw Shirov,A (2720)-Ftacnik,L (2582) Germany 2007 [Richard Palliser] , but had Alexei played} 24. Rd3 $1 {the game would be over soon. For instance,} Re7 25. Rg3 fxe4 26. Bxe7 Qxe7 27. Bh5 $18) 21. O-O {You can find a few commented games on our site, the latest example is Magem Badals,J (2564)-Alsina Leal,D (2523) Barcelona 2009 [Richard Palliser]}) 18. c4 (18. Bf3 {can hardly pose Black any problems:} O-O 19. Qc3 (19. Nf6+ $2 Nxf6 20. Bxd5 Bb4+ 21. Kf1 exd5 $17) 19... Bb6 $1 {It's important to avoid an exchange of the dark-squared bishop} (19... e5 $6 20. Nb3 Bd4 21. Nxd4 exd4 22. Rxd4 Qe6 23. Rd6 $36 {1-0 (44) Eryomenko,V (2512)-Malimonenko,V (2222) Azov 2010}) 20. Nf6+ Nxf6 21. Bxd5 exd5 22. O-O Nc6 {Losing a queen is not an issue here!} 23. Qb2 ({After} 23. Rxf6 Nxd4 24. Rxd4 gxf6 25. Bf2 Bxd4 26. Bxd4 Kh7 27. Be3 Re8 {White has nothing better than forcing a perpetual:} 28. Qxf6 Rxe3 29. Qxf7+ Kh8 30. Qf8+ $11) 23... Nxd4 24. Qxb6 Ne2+ 25. Kh1 Nxg3+ 26. hxg3 Be6 27. Qxb7 a5 {In my opinion, in the arising unbalanced position Black should be out of risk.}) 18... Bxd4 19. Rxd4 Qa5+ 20. Rd2 O-O 21. Bd6 f5 $1 {This is the point! Now, when the c4-square isn't vacant for the bishop, Black feels free to touch the f-pawn!} 22. Bxf8 Nxf8 23. Nd6 Nbd7 $1 {Black takes control over the c5-spot.} 24. Kf2 {A novelty. White's long-term compensation is based on his better piece coordination, and Black has to play precisely in order to solve the problem of the Bc8.} ({The above-mentioned game of GM Vachier Lagrave saw:} 24. g4 fxg4 ({The immediate} 24... Qe5 $5 {is also perfectly playable for Black, as was proved by Wei Yi:} 25. Qxe5 Nxe5 26. gxf5 exf5 27. O-O g6 28. Rb1 Be6 {Yu,Y (2667)-Wei,Y (2629) China 2014}) 25. Bxg4 Qa1+ 26. Rd1 Qe5 {and now White committed a blunder:} 27. Rd3 $2 ({Of course, he had to play} 27. Kf2 Qxe3+ 28. Kxe3 Ne5 29. Be2 {with approximate equality.}) 27... Nc5 $19 {Najer,E (2687)-Vachier Lagrave,M (2798) Dortmund GER 2016}) ({Black should also be fine after} 24. O-O Qc5 25. Qxc5 Nxc5 26. Rb1 Rb8 27. Bf3 g5 28. Rdb2 Nfd7 29. Bxb7 Bxb7 30. Nxb7 Ne4 $11) 24... Nc5 {Now the d7-square is vacant for the bishop.} ({An attempt to simplify matters by means of} 24... Qc5 $6 25. Rhd1 Qxe3+ 26. Kxe3 Nc5 {puts Black under some pressure after} 27. Bf3 Rb8 28. Rb1 $14) ({Also deserving of serious attention:} 24... Nf6 $5 25. Rb1 e5 26. Rdd1 e4 $132 {with excellent attacking prospects.}) 25. Rf1 $6 {White is playing too slowly, so Black gets enough time to consolidate.} ({Much more to the point was:} 25. Bf3 Rb8 26. Rb1 (26. g4 fxg4 27. Bxg4 Bd7 28. Rf1 $132) 26... e5 27. Kg1 f4 28. Qe2 Be6 29. Bd5 $132 {with complex, double-edged play.}) 25... Bd7 26. Kg1 ({After} 26. Bf3 $5 Bc6 27. Bxc6 bxc6 28. Kg1 Ncd7 29. Rb1 {Black is better, but the activity of his pieces offers White good drawing chances.}) 26... Bc6 27. g4 {Obviously White's chances are now connected solely with counterplay on the k-side.} Ne4 $1 {It makes sense to liquidate White's most active piece.} 28. Nxe4 fxe4 $1 ({Inaccurate would be:} 28... Bxe4 $6 29. gxf5 exf5 30. Bf3 Re8 (30... Bxf3 31. Rxf3 $132) 31. Rd4 Qc5 32. Bxe4 fxe4 33. Re1 $11) 29. Rd6 $2 {Only this move is inviting serious trouble.} ({Th correct} 29. g5 $1 Qxg5+ 30. Qxg5 hxg5 31. Bg4 a5 32. Ra2 a4 33. Rfa1 $15 {would allow White to mobilize all his forces, so a draw seems the most probable result - Black's pawns are too weak.}) 29... Qe5 $1 {As usual, the centralization of the queen is very effective.} 30. Rfd1 (30. Qd4 Qg5 31. Qd2 e3 32. Qd4 a5 $19) 30... Ng6 {Now the vulnerability of White's monarch starts to tell.} 31. Qd4 Qxd4+ $6 {A serious inaccuracy.} ({Black could have got a better version of the endgame by means of:} 31... Kf7 $1 32. Qxe5 Nxe5 33. Rd8 Rxd8 34. Rxd8 Ke7 35. Rd1 (35. Ra8 e3 36. c5 Nd7 $19) 35... e3 36. Kf1 g5 $19) 32. R6xd4 Nf4 33. Rd8+ Rxd8 34. Rxd8+ Kf7 35. Kf2 Kf6 $6 {Spoiling the lion's share of his advantage!} ({Much better was:} 35... Ke7 $1 36. Rd1 ({White has no time to grab a pawn:} 36. Rg8 g5 37. Rh8 a5 38. Rxh6 a4 $19) 36... Kf6 $17 {, heavily limiting White's activity.}) 36. Bf1 (36. h4 $5 {would fix the weak Pg7 and prevent Black from advancing the passer:} a5 (36... Ke5 37. h5 $1 a5 38. Bf1 a4 39. Ke3 $11) 37. Ra8 Ke5 $1 (37... a4 38. Ra5 $11) 38. Rxa5+ Kd4 39. h5 $15) 36... a5 37. Ke3 (37. Ra8 $5 a4 38. Ra5 g5 39. Ke3 e5 40. c5 $15) 37... g5 $6 {This endgame is extremely complex - that's why both players are making so many mistakes.} ({Better was:} 37... e5 38. h4 a4 39. Rd2 Ke6 40. Rd8 $15) 38. Rf8+ $2 {Returning the favour.} ({The precise} 38. h4 $1 a4 (38... Ke7 39. Rh8 Ng6 40. Rxh6 Nxh4 41. Rh5 Kf6 42. Rh6+ $11) 39. h5 {would solve all the problems:} Ke7 40. Rh8 Kf7 41. Rd8 e5 42. c5 $11) 38... Ke5 $6 ({After} 38... Ke7 $1 39. Ra8 (39. Rh8 a4 40. Rxh6 Kd6 $1 41. Rh8 Kc5 42. Ra8 e5 $19) 39... a4 40. Ra5 Kd6 41. h4 b6 42. Ra6 Kc7 43. hxg5 hxg5 44. Ra7+ Kd6 $19 {Black's passers would decide the game.}) 39. Ra8 a4 40. Ra5+ $2 {The last move before crossing the time control turns out to be a decisive mistake.} ({Necessary was:} 40. Rd8 $1 {, restricting the mobility of the king. In this case it would be difficult for Black to make progress. For instance,} Kf6 41. h4 Ke7 42. Rd1 e5 43. hxg5 hxg5 44. Rd2 $15) 40... Kd6 41. h4 (41. Kd4 e5+ 42. Ke3 b6 43. Ra7 Kc5 $19) 41... b6 42. Ra7 Kc5 43. h5 {Now it's too late!} (43. hxg5 hxg5 44. Rg7 {runs into} Ng6 $3 45. Kd2 (45. Rxg6 a3 46. Rg7 Kb4 47. Ra7 Ba4 $19) 45... Nh4 46. Kc3 Nf3 $19 {and White is helpless.}) 43... e5 44. Ra6 ({Or} 44. Rh7 Ne6 $1 45. Rxh6 a3 $19) 44... Ne6 $2 {It's hard to believe, but this move gives White a golden opportunity to save the game!} (44... Nd3 $1 {would win easily:} 45. Bxd3 exd3 46. Kxd3 b5 $19) 45. Be2 $2 {I guess Wei Yi won't be happy with his play in this game!} ({Had he played} 45. Bg2 $1 {Lu Shanglei would regret his previous move:} Nd4 ({After} 45... Nc7 46. Ra7 Ne8 47. Bxe4 Bxe4 48. Kxe4 Nd6+ 49. Kd3 a3 50. Rxa3 e4+ 51. Ke2 Nxc4 52. Ra8 Ne5 53. Re8 $11) 46. Bxe4 Bd7 47. Ra7 Bxg4 48. Rxa4 Bxh5 49. Ra7 Kxc4 50. Rh7 $11) 45... Nd4 46. Bd1 Nb3 47. Bc2 Na5 $19 {Finally the a-passer decides the game.} 48. Bxa4 {Painful.} Bxa4 49. Kxe4 Bd7 0-1


