1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. Bd3 Qc7 {GM Ivanchuk deviates from the most explored lines. Frankly speaking, this committal move can hardly be considered to be an adequate alternative to the most natural 7...d5.} ({The main} 7... d5 8. O-O Nf6 {is deeply covered in many games in our PGN Archive.}) 8. O-O ({I was surprised to discover that the natural} 8. Qg4 $5 {wasn't played in any game yet. At the same time, it looks like the queen's transfer to g3 offers White a comfortable advantage:} d5 (8... Nf6 9. Qg3 d6 {This position was actually seen in practice, but via an other move order:} 10. O-O e5 11. Bc4 Be6 12. Bxe6 fxe6 13. f4 $36 {Sadzikowski,D - Kruszynski,W Katowice POL 2017}) 9. Qg3 Qxg3 10. hxg3 Nf6 11. f3 $14) 8... Nf6 9. Qe2 d5 {A new move for our PGN Archive.} ({The dubious} 9... Bd6 $6 {was played in Kasparov,G (2838)-Movsesian,S (2631) Prague CZE 2001 [Fed]}) 10. Bg5 Bb7 11. f4 (11. Rae1 $5 Be7 ({The more ambitious} 11... Bb4 {doesn't seem to fully solve the problems:} 12. e5 ({Less promising is} 12. a3 Bxc3 13. bxc3 Nxe4 14. Bxe4 dxe4 15. Qxe4 O-O $11 {Swiercz,D - Rublevsky,S Berlin GER 2015}) 12... Nd7 13. f4 Nc5 {This position was reached in Fernandes, A - Lobron,E Thessaloniki 1984 White should have played} 14. a3 $1 Nxd3 15. Qxd3 Bc5+ 16. Kh1 $14 {, achieving a definite advantage.}) 12. f4 $1 ({Weaker is} 12. e5 h6 13. Bh4 Ng8 14. Bxe7 Nxe7 15. b3 c5 $11 {Hirneise,J - Strunski,A Willingen 2008}) 12... h6 {This position was seen in Heymann,U - Meissner,C Germany 1995 Now White should have maintained the tension:} 13. Bh4 $146 O-O 14. e5 Ne8 15. Bxe7 Qxe7 16. Nd1 $14) 11... h6 ({Hardly better is} 11... Be7 {, as played in a Classical game a long time ago:} 12. e5 Nd7 13. Bxe7 Kxe7 14. Rae1 $1 (14. Na4 c5 15. c4 d4 16. Be4 Bxe4 17. Qxe4 g6 $11 {Spassky, B-Petrosian,T Palma de Mallorca 1969}) 14... g6 15. Qg4 Qb6+ 16. Kh1 Qb4 17. Ne2 $36) 12. Bh4 Be7 13. Bg3 {A novelty. Even though White's idea was fully justified in the game, it is not the most dangerous move.} ({The obvious alternative -} 13. e5 Nd7 14. Bxe7 Kxe7 {leads to an original position, where Black's king is stuck in the centre. However, it wouldn't be easy for White to gain access to the Ke7. For instance,} 15. Rae1 g6 16. b3 c5 17. Nd1 Nb6 18. Ne3 d4 19. Ng4 Nd5 $132 {Inarkiev,E - Bocharov,D Apatity RUS 2011}) ({However, somewhat more natural seems to be} 13. Rae1 $5 {, transposing to Heymann,U - Meissner,C from the above-mentioned note.}) 13... O-O {Vassily completes development. There is nothing wrong with this move,} ({but a more convincing way of solving his problems was:} 13... Qb6+ $1 14. Kh1 (14. Bf2 Qxb2 15. Nxd5 cxd5 16. Rab1 Qa3 17. Rxb7 dxe4 18. Bxe4 Nxe4 19. Qxe4 O-O 20. f5 Bc5 $11) 14... Qxb2 15. Nxd5 (15. Rab1 Qxc3 16. Rxb7 dxe4 17. Bxe4 O-O 18. Rxe7 Qb4 19. Bxc6 Qxe7 20. Bxa8 Rxa8 $11) 15... cxd5 16. Rab1 Qc3 17. e5 Ne4 18. Rxb7 (18. Bxe4 dxe4 19. Rxb7 Qc6 20. Rfb1 Bd8 $11) 18... Qc6 19. Rb3 O-O 20. c4 Nxg3+ 21. hxg3 dxc4 22. Bxc4 g6 $11) 14. e5 Ne8 {After this retreat Black's setup loses its harmony.} ({The natural} 14... Nd7 $2 {runs into} 15. f5 {, and White's attack is crushing.}) ({However, safer was} 14... Nh7 $1 {, intending to meet} 15. f5 ({White also gets nothing special after} 15. Qg4 Kh8 16. f5 exf5 17. Qxf5 Ng5 18. h4 Bc8 19. Qf2 Ne6 $132) 15... exf5 16. Bxf5 {with} Ng5 $1 {, and Black manages to consolidate:} 17. e6 Bd6 18. Bxd6 Qxd6 19. exf7+ Rxf7 20. Bd3 Raf8 $11) 15. f5 exf5 16. Bxf5 Qb6+ $6 {Only this decision invites serious trouble.} ({Despite some inaccuracies, Vassily's position would be acceptable had he played} 16... a5 $1 {This cold-blooded move would enable Black to simplify matters:} 17. e6 (17. Rf3 Ba6 18. Qf2 Qa7 $11) 17... Ba6 18. exf7+ Rxf7 19. Qxa6 Rxa6 20. Bxc7 Nxc7 21. Na4 c5 $11) 17. Kh1 g6 18. Bd7 Rd8 $2 {Black cannot afford to waste a tempo in such a position.} ({Instead, Vassily should have either played} 18... Kh7 19. e6 (19. Rae1 Qd8 20. Bxe8 Qxe8 21. Na4 a5 22. Qe3 Ba6 23. Rf3 Bc8 $14) 19... f5 20. Bf2 Qc7 (20... d4 21. Qe5 c5 22. Na4 Qc7 23. Qxc7 Nxc7 24. c3 $16) 21. Na4 c5 22. b4 cxb4 23. Bb6 Qb8 24. Bd4 $36 {White's initiative is rather dangerous, but the game goes on.}) ({Or} 18... d4 $5 19. e6 f5 20. Na4 Qb5 21. Qd2 g5 (21... Qxa4 $2 22. Qxh6 Rf6 23. Be5 Bf8 24. Qg5 $18) 22. Qxd4 f4 23. Bf2 f3 24. gxf3 Rf4 25. Nc3 Qf5 26. Qd3 c5 $16 {- White is still much better, but Black manages to develop definite counterplay on the k-side.}) 19. e6 f5 20. Qd2 ({Good enough was also} 20. Bf2 d4 (20... Qxb2 21. Qd2 Bg5 22. Be3 Bf6 23. e7 Bxe7 24. Rab1 $18) 21. Qd2 $1 c5 22. Na4 Qd6 23. Bg3 f4 (23... Qd5 24. Nb6 Qe4 25. Rae1 Qg4 26. Qxh6 $18) 24. Bxf4 Qd5 25. Qe2 Ng7 26. Nb6 Qh5 27. Qxh5 gxh5 28. Bxh6 $18) 20... Kh7 21. Bf2 Qa5 ({In case of} 21... Qc7 22. Na4 Rxd7 23. exd7 Qxd7 24. Rae1 Rf7 25. Bd4 $18 {His full control of the dark squares offers White a winning position.}) 22. Be3 h5 ({After} 22... Nf6 23. Bxh6 Nxd7 24. exd7 Rf7 25. Rf3 Rxd7 26. Rh3 Kg8 27. Re1 Qd8 28. Na4 $18 {White's pieces are dominating the board.}) 23. Qf2 $2 ({Much stronger was} 23. b4 $1 Bxb4 24. Rab1 Bxc3 (24... Bc8 25. Qf2 Be7 26. Bb6 Qxc3 27. Bxd8 Bxd8 28. Bxc8 $18) 25. e7 Nd6 26. Qd3 Qc7 27. exd8=Q Rxd8 28. Bxf5 $1 $18 {, and Black's position is collapsing.}) 23... c5 $2 {Vassily returns the favour.} ({The correct} 23... Nf6 $1 24. Bb6 Qb4 25. Bxd8 Rxd8 26. Ne2 Ng4 27. Qd4 Qxd4 28. Nxd4 c5 $14 {would leave White with only a tiny advantage in this endgame.}) 24. Qf4 g5 25. Qf3 g4 (25... Ng7 26. Nxd5 f4 27. Bf2 c4 28. Rfd1 $18) 26. Qf4 $18 {The king is too exposed now.} Rf6 (26... Ng7 27. Qh6+ Kg8 28. Bg5 $18) 27. Bxe8 Rxe8 28. Qg5 {The rest is just unnecessary.} Ref8 29. Qxh5+ Kg7 30. Qg5+ Kh8 31. Qh5+ Kg7 32. Bg5 d4 33. Bxf6+ Rxf6 34. Rxf5 1-0


[Event "Lindores Abbey Prelim"]
