1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 a6 8. Nxc6 {A relatively rare move.} ({GM Wei Yi decides to avoid entering the well-explored theoretical position that arises after} 8. O-O-O Bd7 9. f4 b5) 8... bxc6 9. O-O-O Be7 10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. Bc4 {White intends to put his bishop on b3 in order to safeguard his king.} Bb7 $1 {Alexander illustrates his deep preparation and improves} ({over} 11... Rb8 12. Bb3 Qb6 13. f4 c5 14. Qe2 {Black had no counterplay and was soon crushed in Hovhannisyan,R (2591)-Gara,T  (2326) Doha QAT 2014 [Roiz, M]}) 12. Bb3 {White has to make this move sooner or later.} (12. f4 Qc7 13. Rhe1 d5 14. Bb3 O-O-O 15. exd5 cxd5 16. Qd4 f5 {was fine for Black in Pintor,S - Lillo Castany,V Pontevedra 2019}) 12... Qc7 13. f4 {A novelty. The standard plan in such positions is to attack the Pe6 with f4-f5, but in this case it doesn't seem effective.} ({In my opinion, the best approach is prophylactic:} 13. Rhe1 $5 O-O-O 14. Qe3 Kb8 15. Kb1 Qa5 ({Worth attention is} 15... Rhe8 $5 {, insisting on ...d6-d5.}) 16. h4 h5 17. Re2 f5 18. g3 fxe4 19. Nxe4 Qc7 20. Ng5 {White's position looked more active in Rashitov, D - Gabrielian,A ICCF email 2017}) 13... O-O-O 14. Rhf1 (14. f5 d5 15. fxe6 fxe6 16. exd5 cxd5 17. Rhe1 Bd6 18. Kb1 Be5 $132 {The central pawns are somewhat vulnerable, but the strong bishop pair compensates this.}) 14... d5 {Black has fully consolidated, so it's time to initiate play in the centre.} 15. Qe2 Kb8 ({Worth attention is also} 15... h5 $5 16. f5 h4 17. Kb1 Kb8 {, and Black's chances are by no means worse.}) 16. a3 h5 ({Even the committall} 16... f5 17. exf5 exf5 $5 {was a considerable options as after} 18. Qh5 d4 19. Ne2 c5 {Black manages to activate his bishop and expand in the centre.}) 17. Kb1 ({It made sense to fix the weak Ph5:} 17. h4 $5 Bd6 18. g3 Rhg8 19. Rf3 {A complex strategic struggle is ahead.}) 17... h4 18. f5 {A consistent continuation. Unfortunately for White, Black's dark-squared bishop is becoming active now.} Rde8 19. Rf3 Qe5 20. exd5 $6 {The first step in the wrong direction - in the endgame Black's chances are clearly better.} ({Instead, the cold-blooded} 20. Qf1 Reg8 21. h3 {would have kept an approximate balance.}) 20... Qxe2 21. Nxe2 exd5 $1 {Alexander makes a good choice. Now White is doomed to passive defence.} ({After} 21... cxd5 22. fxe6 fxe6 23. Nd4 e5 24. Nf5 $132 {White's previous play would be justified.}) 22. c4 ({Better was} 22. Ba4 Bc5 23. Nd4 Bxd4 24. Rxd4 Re1+ 25. Ka2 c5 26. Rdf4 Kc7 {, though White's position is very passive here.}) 22... d4 $1 {This tactical resource increases Black's positional advantage.} 23. Ba4 c5 24. Rb3 ({After} 24. Bxe8 Bxf3 25. gxf3 Rxe8 26. h3 Bd6 27. Nc3 Re3 28. Ne4 Kc7 $19 {The d4-passer should decide the game.}) 24... Rc8 {The only, but sufficient move.} 25. Nf4 (25. Nf4 Bd6 26. Nd5 Ka7 27. Rh3 {could have led to the same.}) 25... Bd6 26. Nd5 Ka7 27. Rh3 {Alas, there is no better square for this rook.} Be5 28. Rd2 Rhd8 {Alexander reasonably decides to give up the Ph4.} ({Deserving of attention is also} 28... Rcd8 $5) 29. Rxh4 Bxd5 30. cxd5 Rxd5 31. Rh7 $2 {This impulsive decision is a decisive mistake - the rook is out of play now.} (31. Re4 c4 32. h4 d3 33. h5 Ra5 34. Bd1 Rb5 $19) ({Perhaps the most stubborn was} 31. b3 Kb6 32. Rc2 d3 33. Rc1 $17 {, and White manages to temporarily set-up a blockade.}) 31... Rc7 32. Be8 Rd8 $1 {A simple refutation of Wei Yi's idea. Now the bishop has to go back.} 33. Ba4 c4 34. Ka2 d3 {Black just dominates the entire board.} 35. Rh4 Rb8 36. Re4 c3 37. bxc3 Bxc3 0-1


