1. e4 {GM Ioannis Papaioannou} c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 e5 7. Nb3 Be6 8. f3 h5 9. Qd2 Nbd7 10. Nd5 Bxd5 11. exd5 g6 12. O-O-O Bg7 {Anish is consistent in his opening repertoire. Anish is consistent in his opening repertoire.} (12... Nb6 {is much more common, but White always has a decent compensation after he loses the Pd5. is much more common, but White always has a decent compensation after he loses the Pd5.}) 13. Be2 (13. Kb1 {Dominguez Perez,L (2758)-Giri,A (2769) Moscow RUS 2019 [Roiz,M] Dominguez Perez,L (2758)-Giri,A (2769) Moscow RUS 2019 [Roiz,M]}) 13... b5 $5 {This new continuation was tested in dozens of corr. games. The top players are usually equipped with many fresh ideas that were often demonstrated in corr. games. GM Ioannis Papaioannou: 'I don't like playing Nb6 - Nxd5 as White always has enough space.' This new continuation was tested in dozens of corr. games. The top players are usually equipped with many fresh ideas that were often demonstrated in corr. games.} (13... O-O {, as in Leko,P (2690)-Vachier-Lagrave,M (2780) Batumi GEO 2018  [Roiz,M], looks dangerous for Black, even though at the end MVL was victorious. , as in Leko,P (2690)-Vachier-Lagrave,M (2780) Batumi GEO 2018 [Roiz,M], looks dangerous for Black, even though at the end MVL was victorious.}) (13... Qc7 {is also possible.}) 14. Na5 {GM Wei Yi naturally moves his knight towards the exposed c6-spot.} (14. Kb1 Nb6 15. Na5 O-O 16. Nc6 Qc7 17. Bxb6 Qxb6 {GM Ioannis Papaioannou: '!' '!' GM Ioannis Papaioannou: 'Black's typical plan would be Re8 and e4.'} 18. Bd3 (18. h3 Rfe8 19. Rhe1 Rac8 20. Bf1 Nxd5 21. Qxd5 Rxc6) 18... Kh7 (18... Rfe8 19. Be4 Kh7 20. Rhe1 a5) 19. g4 {led to sharp play in Walther,E-Schlenther,M IECC email 2014. I am pretty sure, that Black is doing well in this position. led to sharp play in Walther,E-Schlenther,M IECC email 2014. I am pretty sure, that Black is doing well in this position.}) ({In the endgame that arises after} 14. Rhe1 O-O 15. Qa5 e4 16. Qxd8 Rfxd8 $132 {Popescu,I - Ledford,S ICCF email 2016, the activity of Black's pieces fully compensates White's bishop pair. Popescu,I - Ledford,S ICCF email 2016, the activity of Black's pieces fully compensates White's bishop pair.}) 14... Nb6 {As usual, Black's counterplay is based on attacking the Pd5.} 15. Nc6 {The most consistent choice. GM Ioannis Papaioannou: 'The Knight on c6 is not contributing at all.'} ({The aggressive} 15. g4 hxg4 16. fxg4 Nbxd5 {hardly offers White more than equality, as he has nothing better than} 17. Nb7 Qd7 18. g5 Qxb7 19. gxf6 Nxf6 20. Qxd6 Rc8 21. Qxe5+ Kf8 {Black's king is out of danger. Black's king is out of danger.}) ({The quieter} 15. Kb1 {might invite major simplifications:} Nbxd5 16. Bg5 O-O 17. Qxd5 Nxd5 18. Bxd8 Nf4 19. Be7 Rfe8 20. Bxd6 Nxe2 {The chances were mutual in Almeida,R - Latour,G LSS email 2010 The chances were mutual in Almeida,R - Latour,G LSS email 2010}) 15... Qc7 16. Bxb6 {This is practically forced - White has to maintain the strong Nc6.} Qxb6 17. Kb1 ({Pointless was} 17. Qb4 Qc7 18. Kb1 O-O {, and the Qb4 is rather useless.}) 17... a5 {Anish comes up with a natural, but slightly risky idea. GM Ioannis Papaioannou: '!?' '!?'} ({The only correspondence game saw The only correspondence game saw} 17... Qc5 $5 18. Rhe1 Kf8 19. Bd3 Bh6 {Black didn't have any problems in Bokar,J - Delizia,C ICCF email 2019 Black didn't have any problems in Bokar,J - Delizia,C ICCF email 2019}) 18. Qd3 $6 {White chooses a somewhat timid plan and soon finds himself in an unpleasant endgame. White chooses a somewhat timid plan and soon finds himself in an unpleasant endgame.} ({The only way to challenge Anish's innovation was} 18. c3 $1 O-O 19. Rhf1 {, intending to attack the Pb5 on the next move. Then play might continue:} Rfe8 20. Qd3 b4 21. cxb4 axb4 22. Qb3 e4 23. Qxb4 {I prefer White's chances in this position, though Black has plenty of counterplay. I prefer White's chances in this position, though Black has plenty of counterplay.}) 18... b4 19. Qb5 {GM Ioannis Papaioannou: '?!' '?!'} Qxb5 20. Bxb5 Kf8 {The Rh8 is locked for a while, but White is unable to take advantage of his better development. Wei Yi's main issue here is he lacks a constructive plan. GM Ioannis Papaioannou: '!!' '!!' The Rh8 is locked for a while, but White is unable to take advantage of his better development. Wei Yi's main issue here is he lacks a constructive plan.} 21. h4 $6 {The Ph4 is a clear target for Black's pieces from now on. The Ph4 is a clear target for Black's pieces from now on.} ({The better idea was} 21. Rhe1 h4 22. Re3 Rh5 23. a3 {, trying to develop a counter-attack on the q-side, though Black's position is preferable here. , trying to develop a counter-attack on the q-side, though Black's position is preferable here.}) 21... Bh6 22. Rd3 Kg7 {GM Ioannis Papaioannou: 'Black is better. White's minor pieces are misplaced.'} 23. a3 {Now this is too late!} e4 ({Stronger was} 23... bxa3 $1 {GM Ioannis Papaioannou: '!!' '!!'} 24. Rxa3 (24. bxa3 e4 $17) 24... Nxd5 25. Rd3 (25. Rxa5 Rxa5 26. Nxa5 Ne3 27. g3 Nf5 $19) 25... Ne3 $17) 24. Rb3 exf3 25. Rxf3 Ne4 $1 {A well-timed knight centralization that enables Anish to maintain some initiative. A well-timed knight centralization that enables Anish to maintain some initiative.} ({Of course, not} 25... Nxd5 $2 26. Bc4 Nf4 27. Rhf1 $16) 26. Ka2 f5 {White is doomed to passive defence.} 27. Rd1 Kh7 28. Nd4 {This knight transfer turns out to be ineffective.} ({Possibly the best defensive approach was Possibly the best defensive approach was} 28. a4 $5 Bg7 29. Re3 Bf6 30. g3 {, and at least the Ra8 is tied to defending the pawn. , and at least the Ra8 is tied to defending the pawn.}) 28... Bg7 29. Ne6 Be5 30. Bd3 Nf6 $1 {GM Giri's piece play looks impressive.} 31. Bb5 Rhb8 32. a4 Ra7 {This is the point! Black feels free to move his rooks now. This is the point! Black feels free to move his rooks now.} 33. Bc6 $6 {The bishop is actually out of play now. The bishop is actually out of play now.} ({More to the point was} 33. Ng5+ $1 Kh6 34. Re3 Ng4 35. Re2 $15) 33... Ne4 $1 34. Bb5 $2 {A decisive mistake.} ({After} 34. Re1 Kh6 35. Re2 Rc8 36. Kb3 Re7 $17 {White can hardly maintain the material balance for very long, but it was the lesser evil. White can hardly maintain the material balance for very long, but it was the lesser evil.}) 34... Rc8 35. Bc6 Re7 $1 36. Ng5+ ({Or} 36. Nf4 Bxf4 37. Rxf4 Kg7 38. Rff1 Kf6 39. Rde1 Rcc7 $19 {Black has a decisive positional advantage. Black has a decisive positional advantage.}) 36... Nxg5 37. hxg5 Bg7 38. Rd2 ({The most stubborn was The most stubborn was} 38. Kb3 Re2 39. g3 Be5 40. Rdd3 Kg7 41. Rfe3 Rg2 {, though even then Black should be able to exploit the weak pawns on g3 and g5. , though even then Black should be able to exploit the weak pawns on g3 and g5.}) 38... Re4 39. Kb3 Be5 40. Bd7 (40. Rff2 Rg4 {is equally bad.}) 40... Rc7 41. Bc6 Kg7 {White is helpless, so Anish isn't in a rush.} 42. Bb5 Rc5 43. Bd3 Rxd5 {White's pawns start to fall.} 44. Rdf2 Rg4 45. Bc4 Rdd4 0-1


