1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. h3 e5 7. Nde2 h5 8. g3 Be6 9. Bg2 b5 {Quite an ambitious way of handling the position. Black delays the development of his k-side pieces in order to quickly expand on the opposite side.} 10. a4 $5 {This natural response is new to our site.} ({The fresh} 10. Bd2 {was recently covered in Fedoseev,V (2671)-Matlakov,M (2710) Izhevsk RUS 2019 [Roiz,M]}) ({The usual} 10. O-O Nbd7 11. a4 b4 12. Nd5 Nxd5 13. exd5 Bf5 {led to double-edged play in Tari,A (2599)-Xiong,J (2634) Wijk aan Zee NED 2018 [Roiz,M]}) 10... b4 11. Nd5 Nxd5 {Black can hardly avoid swapping knights.} ({In case of} 11... a5 12. O-O Nxd5 13. exd5 Bf5 14. c3 Qd7 15. Kh2 Na6 16. Be3 $14 {White gets the upper hand on the q-side.}) 12. exd5 Bf5 13. c3 bxc3 14. Nxc3 Be7 (14... Nd7 15. O-O Nf6 16. a5 Be7 17. Bg5 O-O 18. Bxf6 Bxf6 19. Qxh5 {doesn't offer Black sufficient compensation for a pawn.}) 15. O-O Nd7 {A novelty. This is a definite improvement} ({over} 15... h4 16. g4 Bg6 17. Be4 Bxe4 18. Nxe4 Nd7 19. b4 {White had a clear positional advantage in Xiong,J -Robson,R Saint Louis 2017}) 16. a5 h4 ({The quieter alternative was} 16... Rb8 17. Ra3 Nf6 18. Qe2 Qc8 19. Kh2 O-O 20. Be3 {In this complex position White's chances seem preferable, but it's definitely double-edged.}) 17. g4 Bh7 18. Be4 $1 {An excellent positional decision - the control of the e4-spot overcomes the vulnerability of White's king.} Bxe4 19. Nxe4 O-O 20. Qd3 ({Deserving of serious attention is} 20. Be3 $5 Nf6 21. Bb6 Qd7 22. Nxf6+ Bxf6 23. Rc1 Bg5 24. Rc6 f5 25. gxf5 Qxf5 26. Qg4 $14 {White manages to liquidate into a somewhat better endgame.}) 20... f5 $2 {GM Wei, Yi aims to complicate matters, but this is too risky.} ({Correct was} 20... Nf6 $1 21. Nc3 Nh7 22. Kh1 Bg5 23. Ne4 Bxc1 24. Rfxc1 Ng5 $132 {with mutual chances.}) 21. gxf5 Qe8 ({The natural} 21... Rxf5 {runs into} 22. Nxd6 $1 e4 23. Qxe4 Re5 24. Qg6 $18) 22. Be3 Rxf5 $6 ({Better was} 22... Qf7 23. Kh2 Qxf5 24. Rg1 Nf6 25. Nxf6+ Rxf6 26. Qxf5 Rxf5 27. Rg4 $16 {, though even then White's superiority is undeniable.}) 23. Kh2 $1 {It turns out that Black's king is much more exposed!} Qf7 24. Rg1 Rf3 25. Rg4 $1 {Miguel consistently increases the pressure along the g-file. It looks like Black's position should soon collapse.} Qf5 26. Rag1 $6 {This natural move spoils the major part of White's advantage.} ({Stronger was} 26. b4 $1 Nf6 27. Nxf6+ Bxf6 28. Qe4 Qxe4 29. Rxe4 Rf5 30. Rc1 {with a decisive positional advantage.}) 26... Nf6 $1 27. Nxf6+ ({Of course, not} 27. Rxg7+ $2 Kh8 28. Ng5 Rxh3+ 29. Nxh3 Qxd3 30. Rxe7 Qf5 {, and Black is out of danger.}) 27... Bxf6 28. Qxf5 Rxf5 29. Rc1 $6 {Another step in a wrong direction.} ({Much better was} 29. b4 $1 e4 30. Rd1 Re8 31. b5 axb5 32. a6 $16 {, and the a-passer puts Black in big trouble.}) 29... e4 $1 {Black manages to activate all of his pieces.} 30. b4 Rxd5 31. Rxe4 {This move was preceded by a draw offer. This decision was somewhat premature, though Black's problems are almost solved.} ({For instance,} 31. Rxe4 Rd3 $1 32. Bb6 Kf7 33. Kg2 Kg6 34. Rf4 Bg5 35. Rg4 Kf5 {, and it's very difficult to make any progress here.}) 1/2-1/2


