{Van de Oudeweetering,Arthur: 'China comes to town – The art of Donner || If during the past month tournament play was dominated by one country, I would definitely say it was China. After Yu Yangyi's victory in Qatar where he beat Giri and Kramnik, Tata Steel saw Ding Liren share second place in The Masters behind the world champ, as well as Wei Yi dominating the Challengers event with 10½ out of 13, edging out David Navara. Wei Yei proceeded to break the 2700 barrier at a record age – the boy is only fifteen – in Gibraltar, where Hou Yifan (also coming straight from Wijk aan Zee) saw her rating pass Judit Polgar's and thus the women's world champion now also occupies the number one position on the world list. (By the way, Nakamura scored a clear and convincing win here, Howell came clear second.) || Meanwhile the traditional Hastings tournament saw Zhao Jun reign supreme with out 8 of 9, while Ni Hua took the Australian open (10½ out of 11) and Zhao Xue the New Zealand Open (the 122nd, that certainly seems to be a traditional one too) with 8 out of 9. || The Rilton Cup got a Scandinavian winner – Norway's second player Hammer; however, they did not see any visitors from the far East except for shogi legend Yoshiharu Habu; something to do with the climate perhaps? || As a Dutchman I was warned at an early stage that China was a chess power-to-be. Two small incidents in the 1970s gave a clue. In 1975 Euwe as FIDE president went to China and played two exhibition games against the national Chinese champion Qi Jingxuan. This was just after an eight-year period from 1966 to 1974 during the Cultural Revolution when chess was forbidden in China. This will certainly have hampered the development of chess in China, though Euwe stated that the Chinese sure knew how to play chess. Another reason for the late rise of chess in China is that Xiang Qi has always been considered to be the superior form of chess in that nation, and has therefore been more popular. || Anyway, Euwe was quickly overrun in the first game, but managed to win the second one with White, and for a moment putting aside the promotional objectives that led him to visit China. I'm sure Jan Hein Donner approved of Euwe's handling of the a-pawn in this game, reminding him of his own game against Velimirovic, Havana 1971, which induced him to write a magnificent ode to his "dear pawn on a5" (The King) after his final move of the game (see PGN). || Three years later in 1978 China already made a debut at the Olympiad, with the same Qi Jingxuan on the first board. He was beaten by Timman when China met the Netherlands in the eighth round, but the match was drawn 2-2, as on third board the same Donner famously lost against Liu Wenzhe - in only 20 moves after a surprising opening, which was finished off with a nice queen sac. r2qnr2/pp3kbQ/2npb1p1/2pN1pP1/4P3/8/PPP1BP2/R1B1K1NR w KQ - 0 16 16.Qxg6! This also was to become the first game in Liu Wenzhe's book "The Chinese School of Chess." The introduction indicates that Donner's fear after the game had come true: He had become Kiezeritsky for the Chinese chessplayers. In his analysis Liu Wenzhe makes an interesting observation, which can be transferred to other contemporary openings. After 1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4. Be2 Bg7 5.g4, h6 Liu played 6.h3, which tempted Donner to castle after 6...c5 7.d5, but here after 7...0-0 Liu continued with 8.h4! Liu Wenzhe writes: "…he thought that since I hadn't dared to push my h-pawn two squares, he had forced me to give up the plan of attacking on the kingside altogether... Donner had made a fatal mistake, above all a psychological one... he drew the wrong conclusion from 6.h3." || These days the early thrust g2-g4 has become much more common, and I have to admit that in the Semi-Slav after 1.d4 d5 2.c4 c6 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.Nc3 e6 5.e3 Nbd7 6.Qc2 Bd6 7.g4 h6 my first thought of 8.h3 is: This must be harmless. || In general Donner's sense of danger let him down on numerous occasions, which made him an inconsistent player who produced more miniature losses than other grandmasters. Already in 1971 Tim Krabbé compiled a collection of these http://www.chessgames.com/perl/ chesscollection?cid=1011932 || By the way, Liu Wenzhe's win against Donner was not the first Chinese victory against a grandmaster, as some sources claim. Already in the first round of the same Olympiad the Chinese team had surprisingly won against the Icelandic team, with Qi Jingxuan beating GM Sigurjonsson. Eventually the Chinese team occupied a creditable 20th spot, with their second reserve Zhang Weida even winning the board prize with 6½ out of 8. Not long after China would usually place in the top 10 at the Olympiads. For instance 1990 saw the next generation finishing sixth in Novi Sad with Xu Jun, Ye Ronguang and Ye Jiangchuan on the top boards. The latter was to become the first Chinese player to cross the 2600 border and a longtime well-known representative of Chinese chess in international tournaments. And we all know what he achieved as a coach in Tromso last year! || It would obviously go too far to describe the progress of Chinese chess (also notably Chinese women's chess!) from 1975 in detail, but I would like to point out that it was Liu Wenzhe himself who was really the first one to beat a grandmaster as early as in 1965. In one of the friendly matches between China and the USSR he beat Nikolai Krogius in a game which he analyzes extensively in his book. Promptly Krogius also lost the very next game in that match, against Zhang Donglu. Psychology in chess... || In 1994 I myself had to opportunity to cross swords with Ye Rongguang, who had become China's first grandmaster in 1990. Like Donner I also got knocked down by a queen sacrifice. It was in Amsterdam in the second round of the Donner Memorial (weird coincidence): q2r2k1/pb2bp1p/4pnp1/1B2BP2/Pp1N4/1P2P1Q1/6PP/5RK1 b - - 0 23 23...Nh5 24.fxe6! Rxd4 25.Qf2 1-0 || But now let us return to 2015 and watch the young Chinese boy who people are whispering will become the next threat to Carlsen. Here he takes on Vladimir Potkin, the European champion from 2011. This is round two, so everything was still to play for in the Tata Challengers.'} 1. e4 {Arsovic,Goran} e6 ({Let's take the opportunity of White's first move to point out another remarkable Chinese victory.} 1... d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd6 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 g6 6. Nb5 Qb6 {Diagram [#] Here White started an impressive maneuver:} 7. Na3 c6 8. Nc4 Qc7 9. Nce5 {. Four consecutive knight moves to obtain a superfluous knight! Yet White's spatial advantage scored him a convincing win in Zhao Jun- Vakhidov, Hastings 2015. What's more Sutovsky followed the example in Gibraltar which also resulted in a very attractive victory against Spraggett.} Bg7 10. Bc4 O-O 11. O-O Nd5 12. Bb3 e6 13. c4 Nf6 14. h3 c5 15. Bf4 {and White proceeded to win rather easily.}) 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e5 ({In the last round of the tournament Potkin did not fare well against Van Kampen either after} 4. Bg5 {.}) 4... Nfd7 5. f4 c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Be3 a6 8. Qd2 b5 {Van de Oudeweetering,Arthur: 'Diagram [#]'} 9. Bd3 (9. dxc5 {is by far the main move in the position. is by far the main move in the position.} Bxc5 10. Bd3 Qb6 11. Bf2 b4 12. Na4 Bxf2+ 13. Qxf2 Qxf2+ 14. Kxf2 a5 15. Rac1 Bb7 (15... Rb8 {Eliseev-Ponkratev, Moscow Open 2015}) 16. c4 Ne7 17. cxd5 Bxd5 18. Bb5 Rb8 19. Nd4 Kd8 20. Rhd1 Nb6 21. Nc5 {1-0 against Bajarani, Al Ain classic 2014.}) (9. a3 {was Vallejo's choice against Ponkratov in the last round of the Moscow open this month.} Qa5 10. Be2 b4 11. Nd1 bxa3 12. Qxa5 Nxa5 13. dxc5 {. The exchange of queens did not stop him from winning quickly. Personally I find these miniatures without queens quite pleasing, as they expose a false feeling of safety.}) 9... b4 10. Na4 (10. Nd1 {(Arsovic,Goran) - 89/259} Qb6 (10... c4 11. Be2) 11. Qf2 a5 12. O-O Ba6 13. Bxa6 Rxa6 14. c3) 10... c4 11. Be2 c3 {Van de Oudeweetering,Arthur: 'Opening up the queenside before he gets run down on the kingside, without counterplay on the other side. All this has been seen before.'} 12. Qd1 (12. bxc3 Qa5 $1 $17) 12... cxb2 13. Nxb2 Be7 {Van de Oudeweetering,Arthur: 'It seems the Chinese players have an exceptionally friendly team spirit. This is not only something which people witnessed at the last Olympiad, but also something Bu Xiangzhi noted 12 years ago in an interview with Dirk Jan ten Geuzendam. In this position Wei Yi might have gained some insights from Wang Hao who played this position twice with Black in 2010.'} 14. O-O O-O {Van de Oudeweetering,Arthur: 'This is how Wang Hao played against Motylev, but one month later against Nakamura he decided it wise to delay castling with' The players are following the game Motylev-Wang Hao of 2010 andSvetushkin-Arizm endi of 2014. The players are following the game Motylev-Wang Hao of 2010 andSvetushkin-Arizm endi of 2014.} (14... Nb6 {(actually he played Nb6 first and then Be7). After} 15. Bd3 Bd7 16. Ng5 g6 17. Rf3 {he quickly initiated play on the queenside with} Na5 {. Potkin had planned another method of play to stop White's attacking pawns on the kingside.}) 15. Bd3 f5 {Arsovic,Goran: 'N' 'N' Arsovic,Goran: 'N' 'N' Van de Oudeweetering,Arthur: 'Definitely blocking White's f-pawn! Diagram [#] How should White follow up now?'} (15... a5 {Arsovic,Goran}) 16. g4 $5 {Arsovic,Goran: '!' '!' Arsovic,Goran: '!' '!' Van de Oudeweetering,Arthur: '!' Van de Oudeweetering,Arthur: 'Of course in itself this is a standard method to undermine Black's broad central pawn structure and simultaneously open up the g-file against the black king's position. The surprising factor here is that it can simply be taken. Still this has also been seen in practice before. A direct atacking move, this was also to the liking of Efim Geller in his game against Holm, Nimzowitsch Memorial 1960. And what should we think of this more modern example: r1b1kn1r/p1q1b1pp/1pn1p3/3pPp2/NPpP1P2/2P1BNP1/P5BP/ 1R1Q1RK1 w kq - 0 15 where Edouard played his g-pawn in two moves to g4 (like Liu Wenzhe's h2-h3 and then h3-h4) and went on to beat Michiels convincingly in Antwerp 2011. Finally, it is easily imaginable that Wei Yi had come across this position: r1bqk2r/b2n2pp/p1n1p3/1p1pPp2/1P3P2/P1NB1N2/2PB2PP/R2QK2R w KQkq f6 0 12 from the game Liu Wenzhe-Vaisser, Belgrade 1988, where 12.g4! was played.' Arsovic,Goran: '!' A bold attacking move by the Chinese player. A bold attacking move by the Chinese player.} a5 (16... fxg4 {Van de Oudeweetering,Arthur: 'Diagram [#] is of course an alternative. Instead the knight should just retreat, not letting Black exchange a piece and leaving Black's clutch of pieces as it is. For instance'} {Van de Oudeweetering,Arthur: 'Then after the seemingly active'} 17. Ng5 (17. Nd2 {Arsovic,Goran} Qe8 18. Qxg4 $36) (17. Ne1 a5 (17... h5 $5 18. Bg6 Rf5 {is another typical French idea: an exchange sacrifice for the light squares. For example, you can check Dvoretsky for this in a game Martin Gonzales-Dolmatov, Barcelona 1983.}) 18. Qxg4 Rf7 19. Nf3 {, and White will gradually move more pieces to the kingside.}) 17... Bxg5 {Van de Oudeweetering,Arthur: 'With'} 18. fxg5 (18. Qxg4 {might seem a nice option, connecting the rooks and also threatening to win back the piece by taking on e6 and c6. However Black can reply} Ndxe5 19. dxe5 Bh6 {and White's attack seems too slow.}) 18... Rxf1+ {Van de Oudeweetering,Arthur: 'The attempt to speed things up with'} 19. Kxf1 {Van de Oudeweetering,Arthur: 'would allow typical French counterthreats like'} (19. Qxf1 {Arsovic,Goran Arsovic,Goran Van de Oudeweetering,Arthur: 'White can slowly win back the g4-pawn, yet Black will have the time to build a defense with g7-g6 and Ne7-f5.'} Ne7 20. Qf4 g6 $13) 19... Nxd4 $5 (19... Qf8+ {Arsovic,Goran} 20. Kg1 Nxd4 21. Bxd4 Qf4 22. Bf2 (22. Be2 Nxe5 {.}) 22... Nxe5 $44) 20. Bxd4 Qxg5 $44) (16... g6 {Arsovic,Goran} 17. gxf5 gxf5 18. Kh1 Kh8 19. Rg1 $36) 17. gxf5 exf5 18. Qe2 {Van de Oudeweetering,Arthur: 'Stopping Black's bishop from going to a6. Black now has too many pieces struggling for the right squares.'} Nb6 {Van de Oudeweetering,Arthur: 'Preventing White's Nb2 in order to reach a4. In general around here my engine shows the tendency for White to initiate play on the queenside. Wei Yi's approach seems the more humanly sensible one.'} (18... Qe8 19. Na4 Nd8 20. Kh1) 19. Kh1 a4 20. Rg1 {Van de Oudeweetering,Arthur: 'Here it seems White can set up an attack without worrying about his offside knight on b2. It probably does serve some defensive purpose on the queenside, delaying Black's play there, but it does not seem a pretty piece. Here I was reminded of the game Caruana-Topalov from the recent Sinquefield Cup where Fabiano sacrificed a piece and carried out a decisive onslaught on Black's king position, where he had an offisde knight on a4 which just remained there for almost 20 moves up to the end of the game! How about that? Luckily for me in the Tata Masters Aronian did confirm my dogmatism regarding offside pieces by confidently and elegantly punishing Jobava for a stranded knight on b4: r2qnrk1/3p1pb1/1p4pp/pPpP4/1nP5/7P/1P2NPP1/RBBQ1RK1 w - - 0 17 17.Ra3! Nd6 18. Rg3 Nxc4 19.Nf4, and Black lasted only five more moves. On an earlier occasion I have quoted Donner on such a knight on b4 (and you will not find it in The King), but it is just too fitting here not to repeat again: "...Black has reached his goal and the knight is now on the strong b4-square. Of course he might as well have moved it to h9 or back to the hotel, where it would in no way have been less off-side. With an extra piece on the kingside the attack is now likely to succeed," referring to his game against Hartoch, Dutch championship 1981. In the present game however Black's counterplay on the queenside soon only led to the exchange of White's awkward-looking b2-knight, which apparently was in the right defensive place after all.'} a3 21. Nd1 Na4 {Arsovic,Goran: '?!' '?!'} (21... Be6 {Arsovic,Goran} 22. Rg3 Nc4 23. Qg2 Rf7 24. Bf2 N6a5 25. Ne3 Nxe3 26. Bxe3 Nc4 27. Bf2 Qd7 28. h4 $14) 22. Rg3 ({Again the engine diverts his attention to the queenside with moves like} 22. Bb5) ({or} 22. Rb1 {. Apparently no human ever told the engines they should double or triple their major pieces on the open file.}) 22... Rf7 (22... Be6 {was better. was better.}) 23. Qg2 {Arsovic,Goran: '?!' '?!' Arsovic,Goran: '?!' '?!' Van de Oudeweetering,Arthur: 'Diagram [#] Not exactly as Alekhine taught us – the queen should be behind both rooks. But for the moment that is just impossible.'} (23. Rb1 {Arsovic,Goran} Nb6 (23... Be6 $6 24. Bd2 g6 25. Qg2 Rg7 26. Ne3 Qd7 27. h4 $16) 24. Bd2 Nc4 25. Ne3 Nxe3 26. Qxe3 $14) 23... Nc3 $2 {Van de Oudeweet'Arsovic,Goran: '?'' ering,Arthur: 'With everything said about the defensive purposes of the d1-knight, this does make it easy on White. If you asked me, "playing white, which piece would you like to trade in the current position?" the e3-bishop would make a good candidate, but the d1-knight would win by a large margin.' The knight on d1 is not such a great piece. It makes no sense to go out of the way and exchange it. But it is not so easy to suggest an improvement for Black. White has a simple plan of Nf2 followed by Rag1, Nh3 and putting a knight on g5. The knight on d1 is not such a great piece. It makes no sense to go out of the way and exchange it. But it is not so easy to suggest an improvement for Black. White has a simple plan of Nf2 followed by Rag1, Nh3 and putting a knight on g5.} (23... Be6 24. Nf2 Nc3 (24... Qd7 25. Rg1 Bd8 26. Bb5 Ra7 27. Bxa4 Rxa4 28. Nd3 $36) 25. Rg1 Qf8 26. Nh3 $1 Ne4 27. Bxe4 fxe4 28. Nfg5 Bxh3 29. Qxh3 $18) (23... Qd7 24. Nf2 Nd8 25. Rg1 $40) (23... Na5 {Arsovic,Goran} 24. e6 Bxe6 25. Ne5 Qe8 26. Nxf7 (26. Bd2 Nb2) 26... Qxf7 $44) 24. Nxc3 bxc3 {Van de Oudeweetering,Arthur: 'Diagram [#]'} 25. Bb5 {Arsovic,Goran: '!' '!' Arsovic,Goran: '!' '!' Van de Oudeweetering,Arthur: '!' Van de Oudeweetering,Arthur: 'What's this? Switching to the queenside anyway? Well, sort of, but in the concrete variations the bishop will be attacking from e8! Very nice indeed.'} (25. Rg1 Qf8 26. Bb5 Nd8 (26... Bd7 27. Bxc6 Bxc6 28. e6 $18) 27. Be8 $1 {A very nice deflecting move. A very nice deflecting move.} Ne6 (27... Qxe8 28. Rxg7+ Kh8 29. Rg8+ Qxg8 30. Qxg8#) 28. Bxf7+ Qxf7 29. Ng5 Nxg5 30. fxg5 g6 (30... f4 31. g6 hxg6 32. Rxg6 $18) 31. Rb1 $16) 25... Qb6 (25... Nb4 26. Rg1 Bf8 (26... Qf8 27. Be8) (26... g6 27. Rxg6+ hxg6 28. Qxg6+ Kh8 29. Qxf7) 27. Ng5 Rb7 (27... Rfa7 28. Nxh7 Kxh7) 28. Rh3 $18) (25... Bb7 26. e6) 26. Rg1 {Arsovic,Goran: '!' '!'} Bf8 27. Rh3 $1 {Van de Oudeweet'Arsovic,Goran: '!'' ering,Arthur: 'White now has just too many points attacking the black king. Evidently this gives rise to some favorable tactics.'} (27. Ng5 {was also strong. was also strong.} Qxb5 (27... Rd7 28. e6) 28. Nxf7 Kxf7 29. Rxg7+ Bxg7 (29... Ke8 {Arsovic,Goran} 30. Rxh7 $18) 30. Qxg7+ Ke8 31. Bf2 $1 $18 Qe2 (31... Ra7 {Arsovic,Goran} 32. Qh8+ Kd7 33. Qxh7+ Ne7 34. Bh4 $18) 32. Qg8+ Kd7 33. Rg7+ Ne7 34. Qxd5+ $18) 27... g6 (27... Raa7 {Arsovic,Goran} 28. Rxh7 $1 Kxh7 29. Qg6+ Kg8 30. Ng5 $18) (27... Nd8 28. Be8 Rb7 29. Rxh7 Kxh7 30. Bg6+ Kg8 31. Qh3) 28. Ng5 {Arsovic,Goran: '+-' '+-'} Qxb5 (28... Raa7 {Arsovic,Goran} 29. Rxh7 Rxh7 30. Nxh7 Rxh7 31. Qxd5+ $18) 29. Nxf7 Ne7 30. Nh6+ Bxh6 (30... Kh8 {Arsovic,Goran} 31. Qg5 Qe8 32. Qf6+ Bg7 33. Nf7+ Kg8 34. Nd6 $18) 31. Rxh6 Ra7 32. Qh3 Qe2 (32... Nc6 33. Rgxg6+ hxg6 34. Rh8+ Kf7 35. Qh7+ Ke6 36. Qxg6+ Kd7 37. Qd6#) 33. Rxh7 Qxc2 34. Rh8+ Kf7 35. Qh7+ Ke6 36. Rxg6+ {Van de Oudeweetering,Arthur: 'Potkin resigned.' Van de Oudeweetering,Arthur: 'leads to a clean mate after' A beautiful attacking game by Wei Yi. A beautiful attacking game by Wei Yi.} Kd7 37. Qxe7+ Kxe7 38. Rg7+ Ke6 39. Rh6# {. Diagram [#] Liu Wenzhe passed away in 2011. Will there be a Chinese school of chess as he envisioned? In any case, considering his age Wei Yi is clearly the most promising among the Chinese top players, seemingly progressing even faster than Carlsen at the same age. If you look at the FIDE rating list of the Chinese top 100 you may feel that further down the list there is still some work to do in China, as the strength of the ratings rapidly decreases. But who knows? Perhaps there is also a much broader national rating list, with even more players like Wei Yi in the make? I guess the Masters Bulletin will need a reporter in the Far East to learn more about this. Meanwhile we will just enjoy the great games of the Chinese players known to us. 1-0 (39) Wei,Y (2675)-Potkin,V (2608) Wijk aan Zee 2015 CBM 165 [Sagar,Shah]} 1-0


