1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 Nd7 6. O-O Bg6 7. Nbd2 Nh6 8. Nb3 Nf5 9. Bd2 Be7 10. g4 Nh4 11. Nxh4 Bxh4 12. f4 f5 13. exf6 Qxf6 14. g5 Qf7 15. Na5 Nb6 16. Bd3 Bh5 17. Nxb7 Nc8 18. Be2 Bxe2 19. Qxe2 Qxb7 20. Qh5+ Qf7 21. Qxh4 Nd6 {It might seem unusual that I start my annotation from move 22 onwards but all of these moves have been seen in the game between Khalifman-Sjugirov, European Championship 2013.} 22. Qh3 $146 {The first new move of the game. Kalifman had preferred Bb4. How do we assess this position? It's an imbalanced position and an excellent one for us to take into consideration the various factors which go into correctly assessing the position. Materially White is a solid pawn up. But positionally there are a few trumps in Black's favour. His knight is excellently posted on d6 and has two wonderfully squares as outposts, f5 and e4. At the same time after 0-0 the rook of f8 stands quite well and also the rook on b8 will stand on the half open file. According to me Black has decent compensation. The debate is of course whether it is sufficient or not. Let's have a look.} Qf5 $5 {I find this move interesting. Black is even ready to go into a pawn down endgame on the basis of a superior minor piece.} (22... O-O $2 23. Bb4 $1 $16) (22... Rb8 $1 23. Rae1 Ne4 24. Qa3 h6 (24... Nxd2 25. Qd6 $18) (24... Qe7 25. Qxe7+ Kxe7 26. Bc1 a5 {could be another way to play.}) 25. Rxe4 $1 (25. gxh6 Qg6+ $1 26. Kh1 Qxh6 $40) 25... dxe4 26. Qd6 Rd8 27. Qxc6+ Qd7 28. Qxe4 hxg5 (28... Qxd4+ 29. Qxd4 Rxd4 30. Bc3 $14) 29. Qg6+ Qf7 30. Qxf7+ Kxf7 31. fxg5+ Kg6 $11 {And the game should be equal.}) 23. Qxf5 exf5 24. Rf3 Kd7 25. Re1 Ne4 26. Bb4 a5 27. Bc5 h6 $1 28. gxh6 Rxh6 29. Re2 Rg6+ 30. Rg2 Rxg2+ 31. Kxg2 Re8 32. a4 Re6 (32... Nxc5 33. dxc5 Re2+ 34. Rf2 Re3 $11 {is a drawish endgame.}) 33. h3 Nd2 34. Rf2 Ne4 35. Rf3 Nd2 36. Rg3 g5 $5 37. Rxg5 Re2+ 38. Kg3 Ne4+ 39. Kf3 Rxc2 40. Rxf5 Rxb2 (40... Rf2+ 41. Ke3 (41. Kg4 Rg2+ 42. Kh4 Rxb2) 41... Rxb2 {might be more accurate as later the king cannot go to g4.}) 41. Re5 Rb3+ 42. Kg4 Rg3+ 43. Kh4 Rg7 $2 (43... Rc3 $1 {It was imperative to remain active.}) 44. f5 Rh7+ 45. Kg4 Rg7+ 46. Kh5 Rh7+ 47. Kg6 Rxh3 48. Re7+ Kd8 49. Ra7 Ke8 50. Ra8+ Kd7 51. Rxa5 Rg3+ 52. Kf7 Ng5+ 53. Kf6 Nh7+ 54. Ke5 {White is just winning now. The a-pawn will prove to be too strong.} Re3+ 55. Kf4 Re4+ 56. Kf3 Nf6 57. Ra7+ Ke8 58. a5 Nd7 59. a6 Re1 60. Rb7 Ra1 61. a7 Kd8 62. Rb8+ {Gunina assessed the opening position correctly. Black has enough compensation to hold the balance. She even showed it till move 40 by making perfect moves. But imperceptibly everything started going downhill for her and finally Wei Yi's a-paawn gave him the full point.} 1-0


