{Sokolov,Ivan: 'Wei Yi (b. 1999) is youngest of the four dragons and has a very sharp eye for tactics!' Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: 'An immortal game was played by the 16-year old Chinese talent, Wei Yi! He crushes his Cuban opponent with some beautiful and shocking sacrifices.'' There is something about the way this Chinese kid plays. He doesn't just beat his opponents, but he crushes them. And his combinations are so crisp that you are left with this simple question in your head - "How does he do it against the best in the world?" Have a look at this game against Bruzon Batista which many say is the "Modern day immortal game."} 1. e4 {Paunovic,Tomislav Paunovic,Tomislav Sokolov,Ivan Paunovic,Tomislav} c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. Nc3 {Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: 'White chooses this unusual move order before playing the main 3.d4 to avoid some theoretical lines.''} a6 4. Be2 Nc6 {Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: 'Black is ready to play Nd4 in case of 5.0-0, therefore there is no time to waste on opening the center.''} 5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 Qc7 {Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: 'We have transposed now to the Sicilian Taimanov variation and soon it turns to the Sheveningen variation...'' The game has now transposed into a Sicilian Taimanov.} 7. O-O Nf6 8. Be3 Be7 {This move transposes into the Sicilian Scheveningen. An opening which has a rich history and always leads to interesting positions.} (8... Bb4 {Pure Taimanov players prefer this move.} 9. Na4 Be7 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Nb6 Rb8 12. Nxc8 Qxc8 13. Bd4 c5 14. Be5 Rb6) 9. f4 d6 10. Kh1 O-O {Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: 'DIAGRAM The starting position of the Sheveningen. The old main line used to be the move 11.Qe1, which happened in the game. After some time the 11.a4 alternative has become the most common line and now in the last years the fashion has come back to the old move thanks to the computers, which found some very interesting ideas for White.''} 11. Qe1 $5 {Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: 'White drops his queen to the kingside to obtain different kind of attacking potentials.'' This idea of putting your queen on g3 is common idea in the Scheveningen and thousands of games have been played in the past.} (11. a4) 11... Nxd4 12. Bxd4 b5 {Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: 'The point of 11.a4 would have been to prevent this typical idea.''} 13. Qg3 Bb7 (13... b4 14. e5 {! is very strong} dxe5 15. Bxe5 {and the knight is coming to e4!}) 14. a3 {Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: 'Black has various of options here. The latest development of the theory gives a first sight mysterious plan and Bruzon follows it...'' Usually a move like a3 is a waste of time in the Sicilian. But here it is totally justified as it is important to keep the knight on c3.} Rad8 15. Rae1 {Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: 'White brings all his pieces to the game.''} Rd7 {It might seem funny as to why exactly did Black place his rook on d7. But in doing so, he has vacated the d8-square for his queen. This setup of d7-d8 is very effective against e4-e5 break.} 16. Bd3 Qd8 {Paunovic,Tomislav: '?!' '?!' Paunovic,Tomislav: '?!' Sokolov,Ivan: '?!' Sokolov,Ivan: 'This move does not have a good reputation.' Doe,John: '?!' '?!' '?!' Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: '?' Gy,Pap: 'A sideline. Black leaves from the e5 dxe5 Bxe5 tempo. DIAGRAM''} (16... Re8 {Sokolov,Ivan: ', in order to be able to answer' Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: 'preparing for a counterplay with e5, however the new idea of the computer'' is the main move.} 17. Qh3 {(Sokolov,Ivan) with} (17. e5 dxe5 18. Bxe5 Qd8 19. f5 Bd6) (17. a4 {! seems to create some difficulties for Black. Both players were definitely familiar with the new ideas and Bruzon decided to deviate from this line.}) 17... e5 {, is considered the main line here. Doe,John: '!'}) 17. Qh3 {Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: '! Using the fact, that the queen has gone from c7, when Black could solve his problems with e5 (in the 16...Re8 line)! White has created the threat of e5 dxe5 fxe5 Rxd4 exf6 and Black faces problems on h7 square. Therefore he must ensure the safety of his h7 pawn.''} g6 (17... h6 {is computer's move but as Scheveningen experts already know, this is a very dangerous for Black and any sacrifice later on h6 would be almost decisive.} 18. Re3 $40) (17... Re8 18. e5 {[%cal Gh3h7,Gd3h7]}) 18. f5 $1 {Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: '!' Gy,Pap: '! The standard drawback of the g6 move. White opens the f-file now. With the pawn on g7 this move is usually not dangerous because of the central break with e5 Be3 and d5, but now Bh6 or Bg5 are much stronger.'' A strong attacking move. Something has gone horribly wrong for Bruzon right out of the opening.} e5 19. Be3 Re8 {Sokolov,Ivan: '?!' Sokolov,Ivan: 'Diagram [#]' Doe,John: '?!' '?!' '?!' Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: 'We are still following some games, but here comes the novelty. Despite all this could be known from practical games, I believe that Wei Yi finds all the forthcoming brilliant ideas over the board...It is not a home preparation.'' Little did Bruzon know that leaving the f7-point undefended would lead to a beautiful combination.} (19... Nh5 {(Paunovic,Tomislav) - 105/(67)} 20. Bh6 {Sokolov,Ivan} Re8 21. a4 {as in Kamsky,Gata 2725 - Stellwagen,Daniel 2612, Wijk aan Zee 2009 - 105/(67)} (21. Nd5 Bxd5 22. exd5 $16 {[%cal Gd3g6]})) 20. fxg6 {Sokolov,Ivan: '!' Sokolov,Ivan: 'White goes for a straightforward solution.'} hxg6 {Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: 'DIAGRAM''} (20... fxg6 $142 {Paunovic,Tomislav} 21. a4 $1 (21. Nd5 $6 Nxd5 22. Rf7 (22. exd5 Bxd5 23. Rd1 $44) 22... Nf6 (22... Kxf7 $2 23. Qxh7+ {- 20...hg6}) 23. Qe6 Kh8 24. Rf1 (24. Bg5 Nh5 $17) (24. Bh6 Bf8 25. Qxe8 Qxe8 26. Rxf8+ Qxf8 27. Bxf8 Nxe4 $1 $15) 24... Nh5 25. Rxh7+ Kxh7 26. Rf7+ Ng7 27. Qh3+ Kg8 28. Rxg7+ Kxg7 29. Qh6+ Kf6 30. Qh4+ Kf7 31. Qh7+ Ke6 32. Qh3+ $1 Kf7 $11) (21. Qe6+ Kh8 22. Rf3 Bc8 23. Ref1 Rb7 24. Qf7 Rf8 25. Qa2 $14) 21... b4 22. Nd5 (22. Na2 $5) 22... Nxd5 23. exd5 $14 {  Sokolov,Ivan: ''}) 21. Nd5 $5 $146 {Paunovic,Tomislav: 'N!' 'N!' Paunovic,Tomislav: 'N!' Sokolov,Ivan: 'N!' Doe,John: '!' '!' '!' Doe,John: 'Paunovic,Tomislav: 'N!' Gy,Pap: 'N!?' Gy,Pap: '! Wei Yi starts the firework with this move! He has no retreat after this sacrifice, otherwise he is just losing material. He obviously could not calculate all the lines until the end - as it is impossible - , but he had to have the intuition, that he has enough resources to finish the attack after the black king goes towards the center.'' A novelty and a very strong move by Wei Yi.} (21. Bb6 {Paunovic,Tomislav Paunovic,Tomislav Sokolov,Ivan: 'RR' Sokolov,Ivan: 'Sredojevic,Ivan 2396 - Rajkovic,Dusan 2474, Vrnjacka Banja 2008'}) 21... Nxd5 {Paunovic,Tomislav: '?!' '?!' Paunovic,Tomislav: 'Diagram ' Paunovic,Tomislav: '?!' Paunovic,Tomislav: 'Diagram ' Sokolov,Ivan: 'Diagram [#] This allows a king chase! Paunovic,Tomislav: '?!'' Doe,John: '?' '?' '?' Doe,John: 'Paunovic,Tomislav: '?!' Paunovic,Tomislav: 'Diagram ' Gy,Pap: 'DIAGRAM'' It is from this point onwards that Wei Yi's brilliant combination begins.} (21... Bxd5 {is the lesser of the evils but after} 22. exd5 $16 {Black's position is pretty bad.} Qc7 {Sokolov,Ivan} (22... Nxd5 {is much worse. The bishop on d5 could be a much better defender as it protects the f7. Now the same tactics works quite smoothly} 23. Rxf7 {!} Kxf7 24. Qh7+ Ke6 25. Bxg6 {! White creates many different mate threats. The most important ones are Qf7 and Bf5 followed by Qg6 mate. Black should try to cover the squares on the f-file with} (25. Qxg6+ {? comes to the mind at first to continue the attack with check, but Black is safe after} Nf6 {!}) 25... Rf8 {but it does not help in view of} 26. Qh3+ {!} Kf6 27. Be4 {+⁠− and Black has no defense against the mates. Qh6, Rf1 or Qf5-Qg6-Qh7 is a forced mate.}) 23. Qg3 Kg7 24. Rf2 $16) 22. Rxf7 $3 {Sokolov,Ivan: '!' Sokolov,Ivan: 'Paunovic,Tomislav: '!!'' Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: '!! The point of the previous move! White has deflected the knight from f6 in order to start the haunt of the black king! The only thing which makes the sacrifice easier to execute is the fact, that White always has a draw with perpetual check at his disposal, therefore White can go ahead, calculate the lines when they appear on the board and in the worst case if he does not see anything just make a draw...but of course, the main goal is to mate the black king.'' The term bolt from the blue looks pretty cliched at this point. I mean Bruzon being a 2669 rated player must have definitely anticipated this move, right? This is a very common pattern of dragging the black king out. What exactly did he have in mind against xf7 is unclear because even a minute's glance is enough to convince that the attack is very strong and at every juncture White has a draw in hand with a perpetual.} (22. exd5 $2 {Sokolov,Ivan: 'Paunovic,Tomislav' Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: '?''} Bxd5 $17 {Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: '''} 23. Bf5 {Paunovic,Tomislav} Rc7 $1 24. Rd1 Bc4 $17) 22... Kxf7 {Paunovic,Tomislav: '' ''} (22... Nf6 {Sokolov,Ivan: 'loses to' is met with} 23. Qe6 $1 {Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: '!''} Kh8 24. Bg5 $18 {Doe,John: 'Paunovic,Tomislav: '+-'' when Black is absolutely busted.} Nh7 (24... Bc8 25. Re3 $18 {[%cal Ge3h3]}) 25. Qxg6) 23. Qh7+ {Paunovic,Tomislav: '- 20...hg6'} Ke6 {Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: 'Here is a moment when White could force a draw with 24.Qh3, but Wei Yi thinks much deeper and continues searching for mate.''} (23... Kf8 24. Bh6# {is easy to calculate.}) (23... Kf6 {Sokolov,Ivan: 'Paunovic,Tomislav' Computer thinks that this is the easiest move to refute but I disagree. f1+ is very tempting and it leads to a draw. The correct move here is to take the knight.} 24. exd5 $1 {Doe,John: 'Paunovic,Tomislav: '!'' Doe,John: 'Paunovic,Tomislav: '!' Gy,Pap: '!''} (24. Rf1+ $2 {is incorrect due to} Nf4 25. Rxf4+ exf4 26. Bd4+ Ke6 $11 {and White has nothing more than a draw at this point.} (26... Kg5 $2 {Paunovic,Tomislav: '??' '??' Paunovic,Tomislav: '??' Sokolov,Ivan: '??' Doe,John: '??' '??'} 27. h4+ Kg4 28. Qxg6+ {with mate to follow in short order.} Bg5 {Paunovic,Tomislav} 29. Be2+ Kg3 30. Qh5 $18) 27. Qh3+ (27. Qxg6+ Bf6 $19) 27... Kf7 28. Qh7+ Ke6 $11 {and White has nothing more than a draw at this point.}) 24... e4 25. Rf1+ Ke5 26. Qxg6 exd3 27. Qf5# (27. Qe6# {(Paunovic,Tomislav) #})) 24. exd5+ {Sokolov,Ivan: 'Black’s king has to go on the run.' Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: '! White gains back some material and eliminates the knight which could have become an important defender if it returns to f6.''} Kxd5 {Paunovic,Tomislav: '' Paunovic,Tomislav: '' Sokolov,Ivan: 'Diagram [#]' Doe,John: 'Paunovic,Tomislav: '' Gy,Pap: 'Black tries to run away with his king to c6-c7. DIAGRAM'' Once again we reach a critical crossroad. Black is threatening to run away with Kc6-c7. White must stop him at all costs.} (24... Bxd5 {Sokolov,Ivan: 'loses to' Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: 'is similar to the 21...Bxd5 line. White must be precise with'' White has only one way to win at this point.} 25. Bxg6 $1 {Paunovic,Tomislav: '+-' '+-' Paunovic,Tomislav: '+-' Sokolov,Ivan: '+-' Doe,John: 'Paunovic,Tomislav: '+-' Gy,Pap: '!''} (25. Qxg6+ {Sokolov,Ivan: '?' Sokolov,Ivan: 'is only a draw' Doe,John: '? is not enough again'} Bf6 {Sokolov,Ivan: '='} 26. Bf5+ Ke7 {Doe,John: 'and Black saves himself.'} 27. Qh7+ (27. Bg5 {Sokolov,Ivan} Bxg5 28. Qg7+ Bf7 29. Qxg5+ Kf8 30. Qh6+ $11) 27... Bf7 $19 {and the black king has been nicely cordoned off.}) 25... Rf8 {Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: 'allows forced mate after''} (25... Bxg2+ {Sokolov,Ivan} 26. Kxg2 d5 {Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: 'Black opens a free way for his king towards the queenside, but he already gave back too much material and he loses even more after''} 27. Qf7+ Kd6 28. Qxe8 {Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: '+⁠−''}) (25... Bf6 26. Bf5#) 26. Qh3+ Kf6 27. Rf1+ $1 {Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: '!''} Kxg6 (27... Kg7 28. Qh7#) 28. Qh6#) 25. Be4+ $3 {Paunovic,Tomislav: '!' '!' Paunovic,Tomislav: '!' Sokolov,Ivan: '+-!!' Sokolov,Ivan: 'This further sacrifice keeps the black king in the centre! Paunovic,Tomislav: '!'' Doe,John: 'Paunovic,Tomislav: '!' Gy,Pap: '!! Another brilliant sacrifice! White prevents the hide of the black king to c6-c7 and lures it further more to his own camp to catch it with his remaining pieces.'' The king is dragged further into the center.} (25. Qf7+ $2 Kc6 $19) (25. c4+ Kc6 $19) (25. Bc4+ Kc6 $1 $19 (25... bxc4 $2 26. Qf7+ Kc6 27. Qxc4#) (25... Kxc4 26. Qf7+ d5 27. Qf1# {is a pretty mate.})) 25... Kxe4 {Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: 'Black has no choice, he must continue his journey. DIAGRAM''} (25... Ke6 {Sokolov,Ivan: 'Paunovic,Tomislav'} 26. Qxg6+ Bf6 27. Qf5+ (27. Bf5+ Ke7 28. Qh7+ Kf8 29. Bh6+ Bg7 (29... Rg7 30. Bg6) 30. Qh8+) 27... Ke7 (27... Kf7 {Paunovic,Tomislav} 28. Qh7+ $1) 28. Qh7+ Ke6 (28... Kf8 29. Bh6+ Rg7 (29... Bg7 30. Rf1+ $18) 30. Bxg7+ (30. Rf1 $18 {Paunovic,Tomislav}) 30... Bxg7 31. Rf1+ $18) 29. Bf5+ Kd5 30. Bxd7 $18 {Pawn up with opponent's king on d5. Things couldn't get better!}) (25... Kc4 {loses quickly to} 26. Qf7+ d5 27. Qf1#) 26. Qf7 $3 {Paunovic,Tomislav: '[ g1#]' Paunovic,Tomislav: '[ g1#]' Sokolov,Ivan: 'Paunovic,Tomislav: '[ Bg1#]'' Doe,John: '!' '!' '!' Doe,John: 'Paunovic,Tomislav: '[ g1#]' Gy,Pap: '!!' Gy,Pap: '!! What an amazing follow up! After sacrificing many pieces, White comes up with a silent move! The point is to stop the black king running back the d5-c6-c7 and creates different kind of mate in one threats, such as Qf3 or any bishop move with discovered mate along the g1-a7 diagonal.'' An extremely difficult move to foresee. Such moves are reminiscent of Tal who used to sacrifice material without care and then make a quiet move taking control of the important squares. Here the d5-square was the most important. Even though a piece and rook down Wei Yi takes control of that square.} (26. c4 $3 {Paunovic,Tomislav: '!' '!' Paunovic,Tomislav: '!' Sokolov,Ivan: '!' Sokolov,Ivan: 'is a computer-like solution:' Doe,John: 'Paunovic,Tomislav: '!' Gy,Pap: '!! a computer move, which is extremely hard to find over the board. It has the same idea as the game, White prevents the Kd5-c6-c7 defending plan and his has a special hidden point, which can be seen if Black takes on c4. The point if 26. c4 can be seenafter'' The engine points out this fascinating move which helps to get the c4-square later on also wins.} bxc4 (26... Kd3 {Paunovic,Tomislav Paunovic,Tomislav Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: 'Black tries to gain some benefits of the c4 move and makes an attempt to hide his king. However it is not succesful.''} 27. Qxg6+ {Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: '!''} Be4 {Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: 'DIAGRAM''} (27... e4 {DIAGRAM} 28. Qg4 {! White is a rook and a bishop down, but the most important factor is the king on d3, therefore he must focus on creating new and more threatening mate threats in each move...} Kxc4 29. Rc1+ Kb3 (29... Kd5 30. Qf5#) 30. Qd1+ Kxb2 31. Rb1+ Kxa3 32. Qb3#) (27... Kxc4 28. Rc1+ Kd5 29. Rd1+ Kc6 30. Qc2# {!}) 28. Rd1+ {Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: '!''} Kc2 29. Qxe4+ $18 {Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: 'White sacrifices even his rook and mates with only two of his pieces. The black ones are still in their initial position and they cannot take part in the defense.''} Kxd1 30. Qd3+ Ke1 31. Qd2+ Kf1 32. Qd1#) 27. Qxg6+ Kd5 28. Qf7+ {Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: '!''} Kc6 (28... Ke4 29. Qxc4+ Kf5 30. Rf1+ {Paunovic,Tomislav: '+-' '+-'} Kg6 31. Qf7#) 29. Qxc4# {Doe,John: '! is mate, which would not be so with the black pawn on b5! This is the reason of pushing 26.c4.' Now we see why c4 was such an amazing move!}) (26. Qxg6+ {? is too slow, Black runs away with} Kd5 27. Qf7+ Kc6 {−⁠+}) (26. Bb6+ {?} Kd5 27. Bxd8 Rexd8 {−⁠+ but Black already got too much material, after he hides his king in the next 2 moves he is already winning.}) 26... Bf6 {Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: 'Only move!''} (26... Rf8 {Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: 'prevents Qf3, but allows all the bishop moves, for instance''} 27. Bg1#) 27. Bd2+ (27. Bb6+ {Doe,John: '??'} Kf5 28. Rf1+ Kg5 29. Be3+ Kh5 {Doe,John: '-+' It might seem that h7 would end the game here but unfortunately the rook on d7 wouldn't allow that. In fact Black king is pretty safe on the h5 square.}) 27... Kd4 (27... Kf5 28. Rf1+ Kg4 29. Qxg6+ Bg5 30. h3+ Kg3 31. Be1#) 28. Be3+ {No harm in repeating the position to gain some time. But it just shows that things were not so easy for Wei Yi on the board. He had not yet found the exact way to win the game.} Ke4 {Paunovic,Tomislav: '' Paunovic,Tomislav: '' Sokolov,Ivan: 'Paunovic,Tomislav: '[#]'' Doe,John: 'Paunovic,Tomislav: '' Gy,Pap: 'DIAGRAM White again has a draw by perpetual check, but Wei Yi finds a subtle way to play for more!''} 29. Qb3 $3 {Sokolov,Ivan: '!' Sokolov,Ivan: 'Paunovic,Tomislav: '!!'' Doe,John: '!' '!' '!' Doe,John: 'Paunovic,Tomislav: '!!' Gy,Pap: '!!' Gy,Pap: '!! Keeping the cold-blooded style. Black has closed the f-file, succesfully excluded the queen from the attack, but as it is the longest ranged piece, it can quickly join back to the haunt of the black king. The new mate in one threat is Qd3. Black has only one move to avoid it.'' Once again fantastic control shown by the young lad. d3 is a mate and something must be done about it.} (29. Qxg6+ $2 Kd5 $19 {losing control over the d5 square is unforgivable.}) 29... Kf5 {Paunovic,Tomislav: '' '' The only move to avert the mate.} 30. Rf1+ {Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: '! Of course, White's only chance is to keep the king outside from the camp and try to catch it while it is running through the board.''} Kg4 {Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: 'DIAGRAM'' What to do next? The black king looks like a ripe juicy target but is there a way to finish him off?} 31. Qd3 $3 {Paunovic,Tomislav: '!' '!' Paunovic,Tomislav: '!' Doe,John: 'Paunovic,Tomislav: '!' Gy,Pap: '!' Gy,Pap: '! We are already used to this kind of silent moves. Despite the huge material disadvantage, White is not in rush to finish the game, because Black does not have any counterplay, he can only hope for consolidating, but for this he would need much better placed pieces.'' Isn't this unbelievable? Black has so many pieces but none of them can come to the rescue of their king. But the best part is that Wei Yi found this move which was the only to win in this position.} (31. Bh6 $2 Kh5 32. Qh3+ Bh4 $19 {and White falls short of ammunition.}) (31. Bd2 Kh5 32. Qh3+ Bh4 {is similar.}) (31. c4 $5 {Paunovic,Tomislav: '?' Paunovic,Tomislav: '( d1)' Sokolov,Ivan: '?' Sokolov,Ivan: '(Paunovic,Tomislav) ( Qd1)' Doe,John: '?' '?' Doe,John: '( d1)' trying to get the queen into the game from d1 is very interesting but fails due to a brilliant defensive idea.} Bxg2+ {Paunovic,Tomislav: '!' Sokolov,Ivan: '!' Doe,John: '!' '!'} (31... Kh4 $2 {Paunovic,Tomislav} 32. h3 $1 Qa8 33. Kh2 Bxg2 34. Bd2 $1 $18) 32. Kxg2 Qa8+ 33. Kg1 Qe4 $11 {Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: '='' and once the black queen enters the defence, things become very complicated.} 34. Rxf6 {Paunovic,Tomislav} Kh4 $1 (34... Kh5 $2 35. h3 $3 $18) 35. Bd2 Qg4+ 36. Kh1 $8 Qe4+ $11) 31... Bxg2+ {Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: 'Black decides to give back some material and try to bring the queen to the defend along the long diagonal with tempo.'' Unable to find anything Bruzon gives up his bishop in desperation.} (31... Rg7 {Sokolov,Ivan: 'loses to' Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: 'also loses to''} 32. Qe2+ Kh4 {Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: 'DIAGRAM''} 33. h3 {Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: '!! White always creates new concrete threats. Black has to defend against Qd7 now.''} Qd7 34. Kh2 $1 {Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: '!' Gy,Pap: '! Another subtle move! Black has only one move to avoid getting mated with g3!'' A quiet move threatening a mate in one.} Bxg2 {Sokolov,Ivan: 'Paunovic,Tomislav'} 35. Qxg2 {Paunovic,Tomislav: '+-' '+-' Paunovic,Tomislav: '+-' Sokolov,Ivan: '+-' Doe,John: 'Paunovic,Tomislav: '+-' Gy,Pap: 'White does not have a concrete threat, but still Black ha no defense. The f6 is hanging followed by mate on g5 and one possible finish of the game could be''} Bd8 (35... Rf8 36. Qf2+ Kh5 37. Qf3+ Kh4 38. Rg1) 36. Qf2+ Kh5 37. Qf3+ Kh4 38. Rg1 $18 {Doe,John: '+⁠− and Bf2 or Rg4 next wins.'}) (31... Kh5 {loses to} 32. Qe2+ Kh4 33. Rf3 {!!} Bxf3 34. Qxf3 {+⁠− and Black is unable to defend the mate in one with Qh3!}) 32. Kxg2 Qa8+ {The queen finally enters the game but it's too late.} 33. Kg1 {Unfortunately the black queen has no squares in the centre from where she can join in the battle. Now you can understand why d3 was such a fantastic move because the e4 square is controlled and the black queen cannot come on that square.} Bg5 {Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: 'Bruzon continues defend stubbornly, but it does not help this time!''} (33... e4 34. Qe2+ Kh4 35. Rf4+ Kg5 36. Rxe4+ Kf5 37. Qf3#) (33... Rg7 34. Rxf6 Rf8 35. Qe2+ Kh4 36. Qf2+) 34. Qe2+ {Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: '!''} (34. Qxg6 {Black holds after} Rg8 {!}) 34... Kh4 (34... Kh3 35. Bxg5 $18) 35. Bf2+ Kh3 {Sokolov,Ivan: 'Diagram [#]' Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: 'DIAGRAM'' At least Black gets the pleasure of threatening mate in one before going down!} 36. Be1 $1 {Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: '! A final blow and a last subtle move! White opens the f-rank in order to allow his rook joining to the mating attack. Rf3 is thethreat!'' There is just not way to prevent the mate with f3 on d3. What a mind Wei Yi must have to see all these mating patterns in this king hunt and that too with the clock ticking by! This game will enter many books and will played over by many generations of chess enthusiasts.} (36. Be1 {Sokolov,Ivan: 'The end could be' Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: '!''} Bf4 (36... Qa7+ {Paunovic,Tomislav} 37. Kh1 Qb7+ (37... Qa8+ 38. Rf3+ Kg4 39. Qg2+ Kh5 40. Rh3+ {+⁠−}) 38. Rf3+ Kg4 39. Qg2+ Kh5 40. Rh3+ {Sokolov,Ivan: 'Paunovic,Tomislav'} (40. Qh3+ {Sokolov,Ivan}) 40... Bh4 41. Rxh4# {#}) (36... Rf8 37. Rxf8 Qxf8 38. Qg2# {Doe,John: 'Gy,Pap: 'What an amazing game by the 16-year old Chinese super talent, Wei Yi!''}) (36... e4 {defends Rf3, but closes the long diagonal} 37. Qg2#) 37. Qd3+ Kg4 38. Qxg6+ Bg5 39. h3+ Kxh3 40. Qf5#) 1-0


