{There is something about the way this Chinese kid plays. He doesn't just beat his opponents, but he crushes them. And his combinations are so crisp that you are left with this simple question in your head - "How does he do it against the best in the world?" Have a look at this game against Bruzon Batista which many say is the "Modern day immortal game."} 1. Nf3 d5 2. d4 e6 3. c4 c6 4. Qc2 Nf6 5. g3 Nbd7 6. Bg2 Be7 {The game has now transposed into a Sicilian Taimanov.} 7. O-O O-O 8. Nbd2 b6 {This move transposes into the Sicilian Scheveningen. An opening which has a rich history and always leads to interesting positions.} 9. e4 (9. b3 Bb7 10. e4 Rc8) 9... Bb7 10. e5 Ne8 11. cxd5 $5 {This idea of putting your queen on g3 is common idea in the Scheveningen and thousands of games have been played in the past.} cxd5 12. Re1 Ba6 (12... Rc8 $11 {and White has nothing more than a draw at this point.} 13. Qa4 (13. Qd1 Qc7 14. Bf1 Qc2 15. Qxc2 Rxc2 16. Bd3 Rc8) 13... a5 (13... Nc7 $17 14. Bf1 {is the lesser of the evils but after} a5 $16 {Black's position is pretty bad.} 15. Bd3 {is computer's move but as Scheveningen experts already know, this is a very dangerous for Black and any sacrifice later on h6 would be almost decisive.} Ba6 $40 16. Bb1 {is the main move.} Nb5 {Pure Taimanov players prefer this move.} 17. Qb3 Nb8 18. Nf1 Rc4 19. Qd3 g6 20. Bh6 Rb4 21. Qd1 Rxb2 22. Bxf8 Qxf8 23. Bd3) 14. Bf1 Nb8 $11 {and White has nothing more than a draw at this point.} 15. Bd3 Ba6 $19 16. Bb1 $2 Nc6 17. Nf1 Bb4 {with mate to follow in short order.} 18. Bd2 {is met with} f5 $1 19. Qd1 Be7 $18 {when Black is absolutely busted.} 20. h4 $2) 13. Nf1 Rc8 14. Qd1 {Usually a move like a3 is a waste of time in the Sicilian. But here it is totally justified as it is important to keep the knight on c3.} Nc7 (14... Nb8 15. h4 h6 $18 (15... Qc7 {White has only one way to win at this point.} 16. Ne3 $1 (16. Ng5 Qc2 17. Qg4 Nc6) 16... Nc6 17. a3 Na5 18. Bf1 $1 (18. h5 h6 19. Bd2 Nc4 20. Nxc4 Bxc4 $2 {is incorrect due to}) 18... Bxf1 19. Rxf1 Qd7 20. Kg2 Nc7 21. Ng5 f6 22. exf6 $19 {and the black king has been nicely cordoned off.} gxf6 23. Nh3 {is easy to calculate.} Bd6 {Computer thinks that this is the easiest move to refute but I disagree. f1+ is very tempting and it leads to a draw. The correct move here is to take the knight.} 24. Ng4 $1 Nc6) 16. h5 Nc6 $18 17. a3 $2 b5 $19 18. N1d2 b4 $19 19. a4 Qb6 $1 $19 20. Nb3 $2 Bc4 21. Be3 Bxb3 22. Qxb3 Na5 23. Qd3 b3 {is a pretty mate.}) 15. h4 h6 {It might seem funny as to why exactly did Black place his rook on d7. But in doing so, he has vacated the d8-square for his queen. This setup of d7-d8 is very effective against e4-e5 break.} 16. h5 Nb8 (16... Qe8 $18 {Pawn up with opponent's king on d5. Things couldn't get better!} 17. Ne3 Nb8 18. Ng4) 17. Ne3 Nc6 18. Ng4 $1 {A strong attacking move. Something has gone horribly wrong for Bruzon right out of the opening.} Re8 19. Bxh6 gxh6 {Little did Bruzon know that leaving the f7-point undefended would lead to a beautiful combination.} 20. Rc1 Nb8 (20... Nb4 {Now we see why c4 was such an amazing move!} 21. Qd2 Rf8 (21... Nd3 22. Qxh6 Rf8 23. Rxc7) 22. Qxh6 Ne8 23. Rxc8 Bxc8 24. a3 Nd3 25. Rb1 Ba6 26. Bf1) 21. Qd2 $5 $146 {A novelty and a very strong move by Wei Yi.} Nd7 {It is from this point onwards that Wei Yi's brilliant combination begins.} (21... Bg5 $3 {The engine points out this fascinating move which helps to get the c4-square later on also wins.} 22. Nxg5 hxg5 (22... Qxg5 23. Nxh6+) 23. Nf6+) 22. Nxh6+ $3 {The term bolt from the blue looks pretty cliched at this point. I mean Bruzon being a 2669 rated player must have definitely anticipated this move, right? This is a very common pattern of dragging the black king out. What exactly did he have in mind against xf7 is unclear because even a minute's glance is enough to convince that the attack is very strong and at every juncture White has a draw in hand with a perpetual.} Kg7 23. g4 Rh8 24. g5 Qf8 {Once again we reach a critical crossroad. Black is threatening to run away with Kc6-c7. White must stop him at all costs.} 25. Qf4 $3 {The king is dragged further into the center.} Bc4 (25... Rxh6 26. gxh6+ Kh8 27. Ng5 {It might seem that h7 would end the game here but unfortunately the rook on d7 wouldn't allow that. In fact Black king is pretty safe on the h5 square.}) 26. b3 $3 {An extremely difficult move to foresee. Such moves are reminiscent of Tal who used to sacrifice material without care and then make a quiet move taking control of the important squares. Here the d5-square was the most important. Even though a piece and rook down Wei Yi takes control of that square.} (26. Nd2 $19 {losing control over the d5 square is unforgivable.} Bb5 27. Re3) 26... Bd3 27. Ng4 Kg8 (27... Rxh5 28. Nf6 Nxf6 {is similar.} 29. gxf6+ $5 {trying to get the queen into the game from d1 is very interesting but fails due to a brilliant defensive idea.} Kh7 30. fxe7 Qxe7 31. Re3 Bf5 $11 {and once the black queen enters the defence, things become very complicated.} 32. Rec3 $2) 28. Rc3 {No harm in repeating the position to gain some time. But it just shows that things were not so easy for Wei Yi on the board. He had not yet found the exact way to win the game.} (28. Nh6+) 28... Bb4 (28... Bf5 29. Rec1 Ba3 30. Rxc7 Bxc1 31. Qxc1 Rxc7 $18 32. Qxc7 $2 Bxg4 33. Qxd7 Rxh5 $19 {and White falls short of ammunition.}) 29. Rxd3 $3 {Once again fantastic control shown by the young lad. d3 is a mate and something must be done about it.} Bxe1 {The only move to avert the mate.} 30. Nxe1 Rxh5 {What to do next? The black king looks like a ripe juicy target but is there a way to finish him off?} 31. Nh6+ $3 {Isn't this unbelievable? Black has so many pieces but none of them can come to the rescue of their king. But the best part is that Wei Yi found this move which was the only to win in this position.} Kh7 {Unable to find anything Bruzon gives up his bishop in desperation.} 32. Rg3 Ne8 {The queen finally enters the game but it's too late.} 33. Bf1 {Unfortunately the black queen has no squares in the centre from where she can join in the battle. Now you can understand why d3 was such a fantastic move because the e4 square is controlled and the black queen cannot come on that square.} Ng7 34. Bd3+ Kh8 35. Nxf7+ Kg8 {At least Black gets the pleasure of threatening mate in one before going down!} 36. Nh6+ $1 {There is just not way to prevent the mate with f3 on d3. What a mind Wei Yi must have to see all these mating patterns in this king hunt and that too with the clock ticking by! This game will enter many books and will played over by many generations of chess enthusiasts.} (36. Bg6) 36... Kh8 37. Nf7+ Kg8 38. Bg6 Qe7 39. Nh6+ Kh8 40. Qf7 (40. Bxh5 Nxh5 41. Qf7 Qxf7 42. Nxf7+ Kg7 43. Rf3 Rf8 44. Nd6 $1 {A quiet move threatening a mate in one.}) 40... Qxf7 41. Nxf7+ Kg8 $18 42. Nh6+ Kh8 43. Bxh5 Nxh5 44. Rf3 1-0


