1. Nf3 {[%emt 0:00:00] Paunovic,Tomislav Paunovic,Tomislav} ({The Nimzo-Indian move order is} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. g3 O-O (4... c5 5. Nf3 {[%emt 0:00:05] transposes to the Kasparov Variation, which more commonly arises via 4 Nf3 c5 g3}) 5. Bg2 d5) 1... Nf6 {[%emt 0:00:20]} 2. c4 {[%emt 0:00:00]} e6 {[%emt 0:00:48]} 3. Nc3 {[%emt 0:00:00]} d5 {[%emt 0:00:16]} 4. d4 {[%emt 0:00:00]} Bb4 {[%emt 0:04:48]} 5. g3 $5 {[%emt 0:01:05] An interesting line against the Ragozin, taking the game into Catalan territory.} O-O {[%emt 0:01:17]} 6. Bg2 {[%emt 0:00:48] John Emms: 'This line is very similar to the Catalan, but with Black's bishop on b4 rather than e7.'} dxc4 {[%emt 0:00:26] John Emms: 'This is Black's most popular move here.'} ({An alternative is to play solidly, just like in the Closed Catalan, with} 6... c6 7. O-O Nbd7) 7. O-O {[%emt 0:00:11]} ({In the normal Catalan with an early Nc3,} 7. Ne5 {is White's main move. With the bishop on b4, however,} Nd5 {looks like a decent reply by Black.}) 7... Nc6 {[%emt 0:00:24]} 8. a3 {[%emt 0:02:31]} ({Alternatives include} 8. Bg5) ({and} 8. e3) 8... Be7 {[%emt 0:05:54] The most critical.} ({I was once preparing this line for White and I remember that if Black took on c3 I would be quite happy with the position.} 8... Bxc3 9. bxc3 Rb8 (9... Na5 10. a4 $44) 10. Bg5 b5 11. e4 h6 12. Bh4 e5 (12... g5 13. Nxg5 $36) 13. Nxe5 Nxe5 14. dxe5 Qxd1 15. Rfxd1 Nd7 16. f4 Re8 17. e6 fxe6 18. e5 Nxe5 19. Bd8 Nd3 20. Bxc7 {1-0 (73) Carlsen,M (2646)-Adams,M (2720) Turin 2006}) 9. e4 {[%emt 0:00:29] This is a typical Catalan pawn sacrifice. White is not interested in recovering his c4 pawn. Instead he just expands in the centre and looks for a kingside attack.} Na5 {[%emt 0:02:46] John Emms: 'This has turned out to be a real gambit. White isn't going to regain the c4-pawn any time soon, but his strong pawn centre and piece activity provide reasonable compensation.'} 10. Be3 {[%emt 0:02:49] White doesn't really care about the c4 pawn much. He continues with his development.} Rb8 {[%emt 0:19:43]} (10... Ng4 11. Bf4 $13) (10... Nb3 {(Paunovic,Tomislav) - 117/(179)}) (10... a6 {is another way to prepare ...b5.} 11. Qc2 ({White could play as in our main game with} 11. Qe2) 11... b5 12. Ng5 (12. Rad1 $5) 12... e5 $5 (12... g6) 13. Nf3 (13. dxe5 Ng4) 13... exd4 14. Bxd4 Be6 15. Rad1 Nd7 16. Be3 Nb3 17. Nd5 {with some compensation for White, but probably not enough, Feldborg, B-Rasmussen,E/ICCF email 2006.}) 11. Qe2 {[%emt 0:06:13]} b5 {[%emt 0:02:16]} 12. Rad1 {[%emt 0:02:20] Solid central play by Sambuev. He gets all his pieces into the game before doing anything concrete.} Bb7 {[%emt 0:06:31] John Emms: 'This is the first new move.'} ({An earlier game went} 12... a6 13. d5 Qe8 {, Onischuk, A-Karjakin, S/ Baku 2015.}) 13. Ne5 {[%emt 0:07:57]} a6 {[%emt 0:13:59] Paunovic,Tomislav: 'Diagram [#]'} 14. g4 $1 {[%emt 0:02:09][%cal Gg4g5,Gf2f4] Paunovic,Tomislav: 'N!?' 'N!?' 'N!?' John Emms: 'Sambuev decides against action with d4-d5, and instead keeps the centre firm and starts to advance on the kingside. This looks like a good practical choice for White. The engines prefer Black, but as the game demonstrates, it's not so easy to defend. Paunovic,Tomislav: 'N!?'' This was the move that Sambuev was very proud of. He starts to create some pressure on his opponent with the idea of the pawn storm with g5 followed by f4.} (14. f4 {Paunovic,Tomislav}) 14... Ne8 {[%emt 0:05:49] John Emms: 'Black wants to kick the knight away with ...f6, but doesn't get time to do so.'} (14... Nd7 $5 {Paunovic,Tomislav: '' '' '' John Emms: 'looks more logical, as it's natural for Black to want to relieve pressure via exchanges. Perhaps Wei Yi was afraid of Paunovic,Tomislav: '''} 15. f4 f6 {This was interesting!} (15... Nxe5 16. dxe5 Qc8 17. f5 {intending f6. This is understandable as it does look quite scary for Black, but Stockfish's calm} Rd8 {intending} 18. f6 Bf8 {seems to hold Black's position together.}) 16. Nf3 {with a complex position.} (16. d5 $6 Nxe5 $1 17. fxe5 fxe5 18. dxe6 Bd6 $17)) 15. d5 {[%emt 0:05:17] Paunovic,Tomislav: '!' '!' '!'} exd5 {[%emt 0:02:10]} (15... Bd6 16. f4 {was also possible.} exd5 17. exd5 Qe7 (17... Nf6 18. g5 Nd7 19. Nc6 $16 {White has a firm grip on the position.}) 18. Nc6 $13) 16. Nxd5 {[%emt 0:02:30]} Nd6 {[%emt 0:07:00]} (16... Bd6 {was a move that had to be considered.} 17. f4 Bxd5 18. exd5 Qe7 19. Qd2 Nb3 20. Qc3 {with a complicated position.}) 17. g5 $5 {[%emt 0:08:48] Once again a powerful move. The idea is to continue with f4.} (17. f4 f6 18. Nf3 {intending e5 is another option for White.}) 17... Bxd5 {[%emt 0:15:42] John Emms: '?'} ({John Emms: 'Black should go ahead and grab the pawn on g5. After'} 17... Bxg5 $5 {John Emms: '!' John Emms: 'Paunovic,Tomislav: '!?''} 18. Bxg5 Qxg5 19. Nd7 Rbe8 20. Nxf8 (20. f4 {Paunovic,Tomislav} Qf5 {John Emms: '!' John Emms: 'Black is very much alive.'} 21. exf5 Rxe2 22. Bf3 $13) 20... Bxd5 $13 21. f4 Qf5 $1 22. exf5 Rxe2 23. Rxd5 Kxf8 24. Rc5 Re7 $44 {[%csl Gf5] Black has good compensation for the sacrificed exchange.}) 18. Rxd5 {[%emt 0:01:10]} c6 {[%emt 0:00:45]} (18... Qe8 $5 {Paunovic,Tomislav} 19. f4 $36) 19. Rdd1 $14 {[%emt 0:01:45] The position has settled down and White is better because Black's pieces are awkwardly placed.} Qc7 {[%emt 0:00:08]} ({Taking the pawn with} 19... Bxg5 {doesn't look that good as after} 20. Bc5 Be7 21. Bh3 {[%cal Ge5d7] Threatening d7.} Rb7 22. Bb4 {[%cal Gb4a5,Ge5c6]} c5 23. Bxc5 $16 {White's piece activity plus bishop pair will give him a good advantage.}) 20. Qh5 {[%emt 0:03:46] Paunovic,Tomislav: '' '' '' John Emms: '!' John Emms: 'Black is now staring down a very nasty attack on the kingside, and there's no counterplay either. Paunovic,Tomislav: '''} g6 $2 {[%emt 0:03:49] John Emms: 'Paunovic,Tomislav: '?'' It's very rare that Wei Yi makes such huge errors in sharp positions. But if he does, it is usually when he is defending rather than attacking!} (20... Rbd8 $5 21. Ng4 {Paunovic,Tomislav: '' '' '' John Emms: ''} Nb3 22. f4 c3 $13) 21. Qh6 {[%emt 0:07:50] Paunovic,Tomislav: '' '' ''} Nxe4 $2 {[%emt 0:01:31] John Emms: 'This loses, but it was already a very difficult position for Black to defend.' Snatching the pawn is bad as White has an intermediate move.} (21... Rfd8 {was a better option to bring his bishop to f8 for the king's safety but White still holds all the trumps.} 22. Bf4 Bf8 23. Qh3 (23. Qh4 $18 {(Paunovic,Tomislav)  Ng4}) 23... Bg7 24. Ng4 $18) (21... Nab7 {Paunovic,Tomislav}) 22. Nd7 $1 {[%emt 0:01:48] Paunovic,Tomislav: '+-' '+-' '+-' Full credit to Sambuev for finding flaws in his opponent's calculation.} Nd6 {[%emt 0:00:45] Paunovic,Tomislav: 'Diagram  [#]' Paunovic,Tomislav: 'Diagram [#]'} 23. Bh3 {[%emt 0:00:45] Paunovic,Tomislav: '!' '!' '!' John Emms: '!' John Emms: 'Perhaps Wei Yi missed this. White's knight on d7 is worth much more than a rook!' The knight has been stopped from coming to f5. Now f6+ is a big threat.} (23. Nf6+ Bxf6 24. gxf6 Nf5 $17) 23... Rfd8 {[%emt 0:00:18]} (23... Rbd8 {Paunovic,Tomislav} 24. Nf6+ Bxf6 25. gxf6 Ne8 26. Bg5) {John Emms: 'For example,'} 24. Rd4 $1 {[%emt 0:00:58] John Emms: 'There's no good defence to the threat of Rh4.' The idea is just h4 and there is no good way to stop it. Wei Yi had had enough. Sambuev was very close to eliminating Wei Yi in this event. In the end he wasn't able to but he gave the Chinese phenomenon a very tough fight.} (24. Nf6+ Bxf6 25. gxf6 Ne8 {Black is somehow clinging on.}) 24... Rxd7 25. Rh4 Bd8 26. Qxh7+ Kf8 27. Qh8+ Ke7 28. Qf6+ Kf8 29. Rh8# 1-0


