{Wei Yi is known for scoring wins against lower rated players. With a rating of 2675, he has been able to consistently get better of 2550-2600 opponents. Today he faced Ari Dale who is rated just 2291. It would be safe to assume that the Chinese player who was nearly 400 points above his opponent would have an easy day but it was not to be. Ari Dale played a fantastic game filled with aggression and resourcefulness.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Nge2 d6 4. g3 (4. d4) 4... g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 6. O-O Rb8 7. Nd5 (7. d3 b5 8. f4 e6 9. f5 b4 10. fxe6 fxe6 11. e5 Nxe5 12. Ne4 Nf6 13. Bg5 O-O 14. d4 Ned7 15. Bh3 Qe7 16. Nf4 Nb6 17. dxc5 e5 18. Nxf6+ Bxf6 19. Nd5 Nxd5 20. Qxd5+ Kg7 21. cxd6 Qb7 22. Bxf6+ Rxf6 23. Qxb7+ Bxb7 24. Rxf6 Kxf6 25. Rf1+ Kg7 26. Be6 Rf8 27. d7 Rd8 28. Rf7+ Kh8 29. Re7 Bc6 30. Kf2 a6 31. c4 Rf8+ 32. Ke3 Rd8 33. b3) 7... e6 8. Ne3 Nge7 9. c3 O-O 10. d4 b5 (10... cxd4 11. cxd4 d5 12. e5 f5 13. h4 $18 Qb6 14. Nc2 Bd7 15. b3 a5 16. Bg5 h6 $15 17. Be3 Nb4 18. Na3 Rbc8 19. Qd2 Kh7 $11 {is an instant draw.} 20. Nc3 Rc7 $19 21. Na4 Bxa4 22. bxa4 Rfc8 $16 23. Qb2 $2 Qc6 $1 24. Nb5 Qc2 $18 25. Rfb1 Qxb2 26. Rxb2 Rc2 27. Rab1 {looks very logical. White has no traces of an attack and Black should be more than ok.} Rxb2 28. Rxb2 Rc2 29. Rxc2 Nxc2 30. Nc7 Nb4 {is one of the main lines.} 31. a3 {is the main line but the move b6 leads to less direct and much more complicated play.} Nc2 32. Nxe6 Nxa3 33. Nc7 Nc4 34. Bxd5 Nxe3 35. fxe3 b6 36. Bb7 Kg8 37. Kf1 Kf7 38. Ke2 h5 39. Kd3 Bh6 40. d5) 11. d5 Na5 12. b3 b4 13. Bd2 exd5 $146 14. exd5 {This is too ambitious but Black has to be accurate in order to keep the advantage.} Nf5 15. Nxf5 $5 Bxf5 16. cxb4 cxb4 (16... Bxa1 17. Qxa1 $15) 17. Rc1 $1 {When you say A you have to say B.} Bb2 18. Bh6 {Ba3 is the threat now. Black has a few good ways to meet it.} Re8 $5 {the most logical move making a luft for the king on g7.} 19. Nd4 Bxc1 20. Qxc1 $1 {Ari Dale knows that the only way to keep the fire going is to throw more wood into it. Will he run out of wood or will his opponent get burnt?} Be4 (20... Bd7 21. Qb2) 21. Ne6 fxe6 {The only way to defend g6.} 22. Bxe4 $1 e5 23. f4 Qb6+ 24. Kh1 $1 {Once again the only move. White needs to defend his bishop against Rh8.} Rbc8 25. Qb1 {now there is no way to prevent the draw with Qh6+} Qd4 26. f5 Rf8 27. f6 Kf7 28. Bxf8 (28. h4) 28... Kxf8 29. h4 (29. Rd1 $1 {An extremely difficult move to make.} Qe3) 29... Rc3 30. Kg2 Re3 {Not the best opening play by Ari but his middlegame play was imaginative and fearless.} 31. Re1 Qd2+ 1/2-1/2


