{Tadic,Branko: 'Wei Yi didn't have a good result in the Qatar Masters Open, but he played an interesting textbook game.'} 1. e4 {Tadic,Branko Tadic,Branko Tadic,Branko Sagar Shah/CB Website} e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. Nc3 Nxc3 6. dxc3 Be7 7. Be3 O-O 8. Qd2 Nd7 9. O-O-O {Tadic,Branko: '[#]'} c6 {Tadic,Branko: 'Quite a new move in this topical line of the Petrov.'} 10. c4 {Tadic,Branko: '!?'} (10. h4 {Tadic,Branko} d5 11. Bd3 Nc5 12. Bxc5 Bxc5 13. Rde1 Qf6 {Black has no problem. Carlsen-Ivanchuk rapid, Berlin 2015}) (10. Kb1 {Tadic,Branko} d5 11. c4 Nb6 12. cxd5 Nxd5 {Black just needs to play a few precise move to equalize completely. Vachier-Lagrave - Giri 2015}) 10... Nc5 (10... Re8 {Tadic,Branko} 11. Bd3 Ne5 12. Nxe5 dxe5 13. Qe2 {is slightly better for White. Kryvoruchko-Kuzubov, Ukrainian Championship December 2015}) 11. Bxc5 {Tadic,Branko: '!?' '!?' '!?'} dxc5 12. Qf4 {Tadic,Branko: 'N' 'N' 'N' Tadic,Branko: 'At first it doesn't seem very promising, but the white pieces are well placed to attack the king.'} (12. Bd3 {Tadic,Branko}) 12... Qa5 13. Bd3 Bf6 (13... Qxa2 $2 {Tadic,Branko} 14. Qe4 $18) 14. a3 {Tadic,Branko: '[#]'} Be6 (14... b5 {(Tadic,Branko) is a possible alternative to get some play on the queenside.} 15. cxb5 Be6 {!} 16. Ng5 Bxg5 17. Qxg5 c4 18. Be4 c3 {!} 19. Bxc6 Rac8 {with a wild game.}) 15. Ng5 {Tadic,Branko: '!'} Bxg5 16. Qxg5 {Tadic,Branko: '⩲ The white bishop is clearly stronger than his counterpart.'} Rad8 17. Rhe1 (17. f4 {(Tadic,Branko) !?} Bc8 18. Qh5 {also looks logical. The h1 rook might not necessarly develop on to e1.}) 17... Rfe8 18. f4 h6 19. Qh5 {Tadic,Branko: '[#]'} f6 {Tadic,Branko: '?' '?' '?' Tadic,Branko: '? This move opens the light squares around the king and permits a beautiful combination. Much more solid was 19...Bc8, trying to exchange some pieces.'} (19... Bc8 {Tadic,Branko} 20. Qh4 Qc7 21. f5 f6 22. h3 Rxe1 23. Rxe1 Kf8 24. Qf2 b6 25. Qe3 Qd6 26. g4 Bd7 $11) 20. Bg6 {Tadic,Branko: '!'} Rxd1+ 21. Qxd1 {Tadic,Branko: '!'} Rd8 {Tadic,Branko: 'Diagram ' Tadic,Branko: 'Diagram [#]' Wei Yi had not been having a great tournament in Doha, but in this round he showed some nice tactical brilliance. Here e2 was also good for a clear advantage for White, but the Chinese prodigy goes for the queen sacrifice. Wei Yi had not been having a great tournament in Doha, but in this round he showed some nice tactical brilliance. Here e2 was also good for a clear advantage for White, but the Chinese prodigy goes for the queen sacrifice.} 22. Rxe6 {Tadic,Branko: '!!' '!!' '!!'} (22. Qe2 {Tadic,Branko} Bf7 23. Bxf7+ Kxf7 24. Qe7+ Kg8 25. Re2 $16) 22... Rxd1+ 23. Kxd1 {The funny thing about this position is that the black king can never escape the mating net and hence the queen will always be tied down. At the right moment when the white king will be in the perfect position, White should play e8+ and make the transition to a winning pawn endgame. The funny thing about this position is that the black king can never escape the mating net and hence the queen will always be tied down. At the right moment when the white king will be in the perfect position, White should play e8+ and make the transition to a winning pawn endgame.} Qd8+ {Tadic,Branko: 'is the only way not to be mated immediately.'} 24. Ke2 Kf8 {Tadic,Branko: 'The end of the combination. Black's king is in a mating net, White needs to improve his position and transpose to a pawn endgame at the right moment.'} 25. Kf3 Qd7 (25... Qd1+ 26. Kg3 Qd8 27. Re1 {is similar to the game. is similar to the game.}) 26. Re1 {Tadic,Branko: '[#]'} Qd8 (26... f5 {(Tadic,Branko) is the other defensive idea. White wins with the following plan:} 27. h3 Qc8 28. g4 fxg4+ 29. hxg4 Qd7 30. Kg3 Qd8 31. Re2 Qd7 32. Kh4 Qd8+ 33. Kh5 Qd7 34. f5 Qd8 35. Re8+ Qxe8 36. Bxe8 Kxe8 37. Kg6 Kf8 38. f6 {+⁠−}) (26... b5 {(Tadic,Branko) loses immediately:} 27. cxb5 cxb5 28. Re8+ Qxe8 29. Bxe8 Kxe8 30. Ke4 {+⁠−}) 27. Kg4 Qd7+ 28. Kh5 Qd8 {Tadic,Branko: 'Black still cannot try anything on the queenside because it would weaken the c5 pawn with an immediate loss, for example:'} (28... b5 {Tadic,Branko} 29. cxb5 cxb5 30. Re8+ Qxe8 31. Bxe8 Kxe8 32. Kg6 Kf8 33. b3 Kg8 34. c4 b4 35. a4 Kf8 36. g4 Kg8 37. g5 {and after some exchanges White collects the c5 pawn.}) 29. a4 {Tadic,Branko: 'Preparing for a deadly zugzwang.' Improving the position to the maximum. Improving the position to the maximum.} (29. Re8+ {Just for curiousity's sake, the pawn ending even now is winning. Just for curiousity's sake, the pawn ending even now is winning.} Qxe8 30. Bxe8 Kxe8 31. Kg6 Kf8 32. Kh7 Kf7 33. h4 {is also winning as after is also winning as after} b5 34. b3 b4 35. a4 a5 36. g3 $1 (36. g4 f5 $1 (36... h5 $1 {Tadic,Branko} 37. gxh5 f5 38. h6 g6 39. Kh8 Kf8 $11) 37. g5 h5 $11) 36... Kf8 37. g4 Kf7 38. g5 $18 {wins as in the game. wins as in the game.}) 29... a5 $2 30. g4 Qd7 31. h4 Qd8 {Tadic,Branko: '[#]'} 32. Re8+ $1 {Tadic,Branko: 'The easiest move! The pawn endgame is very easily winning now.'} Qxe8 33. Bxe8 Kxe8 34. Kg6 Kf8 35. Kh7 Kf7 36. g5 $1 (36. g5 hxg5 37. hxg5 fxg5 38. fxg5 Kf8 39. g6 $18 {A nice game for Wei Yi but quite an easy calculation compared to the brilliant ones that he has shown in the past. A nice game for Wei Yi but quite an easy calculation compared to the brilliant ones that he has shown in the past.}) 1-0


