1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6 4. O-O Bd7 5. Re1 Nf6 6. c3 a6 7. Bf1 Bg4 8. d4 cxd4 9. cxd4 e5 10. d5 Nd4 11. Be3 Nxf3+ 12. gxf3 Bd7 13. a4 Nh5 $5 {A novelty, aiming for very aggressive play on the kingside.} (13... Be7 {has been played in all games which reached this position and was covered in the Archives in my notes to B.Yildiz (2333) - A.Muzychuk (2598), Kazan 2012 (0-1 in 35).}) 14. Qb3 g5 {This is the real novelty.} (14... Be7 {would return to similar positions to those arising after 13...Be7.}) 15. Qxb7 Rg8 16. Nd2 g4 {Black's compensation looks plainly insufficient with a computer running in the background, but I could see how such a try might have good results in practice. Wei defends coolly.} 17. fxg4 Rb8 {Throwing another pawn into the mix.} ({After} 17... Rxg4+ 18. Kh1 {Black has problems developing his kingside initiative, based on his lagging development and destroyed queenside. In addition, White has several pieces which are well placed for defence. Nothing looks convincing for Black here, for instance} Nf4 19. Rac1 Bxa4 20. Bxa6 {and the position simplifies to White's advantage after} Rb8 (20... Bd7 21. Rc7 Rxa6 22. Rxd7 Qxd7 23. Qxa6 $18) 21. Qxb8 $1 Qxb8 22. Rc8+) 18. Qxa6 Rxg4+ 19. Kh1 f5 {Insufficient, but nothing seems to work.} ({Moves like} 19... Nf4 {run into} 20. Bb5 $1 {when White's attack is stronger, in addition to his material plus.}) 20. exf5 Rxb2 21. Be2 $1 (21. Bb5 $18 {was still good enough, but Wei's move is more targeted.}) 21... Nf6 22. Nc4 $1 ({Of course there's no need to get involved with} 22. Bxg4 Nxg4) 22... Rxe2 23. Rxe2 {Winning the exchange, but leaving Black's pieces much more awkwardly placed than in the note to White's 22nd.} Bxf5 24. f3 {Covering important light squares around the king.} Rg6 25. Rg1 {Trading off a key attacker.} Kf7 26. Rxg6 hxg6 27. Bg5 Be7 28. Bxf6 {Again using tactics to trade down and win material.} Kxf6 (28... Bxf6 29. Nxd6+ $18) 29. Nxe5 Qb8 30. Ng4+ Kg5 (30... Bxg4 31. fxg4 {and Black has only one check.}) 31. Rxe7 Qb1+ 32. Kg2 Bd3 33. Qa7 {A strange game. Vachier Lagrave has superb preparation so I assume his novelty had some analysis behind it, but I just can't see the point.} (33. Qxd3 Qxd3 34. Kg3 {also mates!}) 1-0


