{[%evp 0,79,20,30,23,-13,-10,-17,-24,-23,-8,-30,-8,-28,-14,-24,-2,4,-15,0,4,-16,40,34,35,51,49,55,48,47,42,4,11,14,30,-25,-11,-63,-39,-11,-46,-24,-28,-21,-21,-87,-5,0,92,32,39,40,56,42,42,89,129,107,160,208,181,188,188,182,182,201,216,216,263,240,223,237,264,293,290,316,323,334,334,324,324,326]} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 dxc4 5. O-O Nbd7 6. Qc2 Nb6 (6... c5 7. Na3 Nd5 8. Nxc4 b5 9. Ne3 $1 $14 {- 132/6}) 7. a4 (7. Na3 Bxa3 8. bxa3 Bd7 9. Ne5 Ba4 10. Qc3 Nfd5 11. Qd4 Bb5 $13 {- 43/14}) 7... a5 8. Na3 Bxa3 9. Rxa3 O-O {Tadic,Branko: 'Diagram [#]'} 10. e4 $5 {I find this game remarkable for how Wei Yi manages to bring his trademark aggression and tactical prowess to a Réti position, and even to an endgame. Tadic,Branko: 'N!?' 'N!?' 'N!?' 'N!?' Tadic,Branko: 'Sam Collins: '!?' Sam Collins: 'I find this game remarkable for how Wei Yi manages to bring his trademark aggression and tactical prowess to a Réti position, and even to an endgame.'' I find this game remarkable for how Wei Yi manages to bring his trademark aggression and tactical prowess to a Réti position, and even to an endgame. Tadic,Branko: 'N!?' 'N!?' Tadic,Branko: 'Sam Collins: '!?' Sam Collins: 'I find this game remarkable for how Wei Yi manages to bring his trademark aggression and tactical prowess to a Réti position, and even to an endgame.''} ({I suspect that Tadic,Branko: 'Sam Collins: 'I suspect that''} 10. d3 {is the best move in this position. Tadic,Branko: 'Sam Collins: 'is the best move in this position.''} cxd3 11. Rxd3 Nbd5 $13) 10... e5 $5 {An interesting attempt to free his game immediately by temporarily returning the extra pawn. Tadic,Branko: 'Sam Collins: 'An interesting attempt to free his game immediately by temporarily returning the extra pawn.''} ({Alternatives are: a)} 10... Bd7 11. Ne5 Qe8 (11... c5 $5) 12. Nxd7 (12. Nxc4 Bxa4 13. b3 Nxc4 14. Rxa4 Ne5 15. d4 {, with excellent compensation, is a reasonable alternative}) 12... Qxd7 13. d3 cxd3 14. Rxd3 Qxa4 15. Qxc7 Qb5 16. Rfd1 Rac8 17. Qxb7 Rxc1 18. Rxc1 Qxd3 19. Qxb6 Qd2 {was level in P.Arnaudov-J.Schroeder, Germany 2019.}) ({b)} 10... Qe7 {led to a very instructive game after} 11. b3 $1 Qb4 12. Ne5 cxb3 {(White gets overwhelming compensation after this move, but allowing the recapture on c4 leaves White with a dominating position – two bishops, extra central pawn – at no cost)} 13. Rxb3 Qxa4 14. Bb2 Kh8 15. Ra1 Qe8 16. Qxc7 Nbd7 17. Rxa5 Rxa5 18. Qxa5 Nxe5 19. Qxe5 {Taking with the bishop was even stronger, but in either case White retained an overwhelming advantage in M.Marin-M.Luch, Roquetas de Mar 2019.}) 11. Nxe5 (11. b3 $5 {Tadic,Branko: 'N!?'} cxb3 (11... Qe7 12. bxc4 Bg4 13. Rc3 Bxf3 14. Ba3 c5 15. Rxf3 Rad8 16. Rb3 $14) 12. Rxb3 {retains promising positional compensation for the pawn.} Nxa4 (12... Re8 13. Bb2 Qd6 14. Rc1 $14) 13. Nxe5 Qd6 14. Nf3 $14) 11... Qd4 12. Qc3 (12. Nf3 $6 Qxe4 13. d3 cxd3 14. Qxc7 Nbd5 15. Qe5 Bf5 16. Re1 Qxe5 17. Rxe5 Be4 (17... Bg6 18. Nh4 Rfc8 19. Bg5 h6 20. Bd2 Rc2 21. Bxd5 Nxd5 22. Rxd5 Rxd2 23. Nxg6 fxg6 24. Rb3 $11) 18. Bd2 Nb6 19. b3 Rfd8 20. Rxa5 Rac8 $15) 12... Qxc3 (12... Rd8 {is also reasonable.}) 13. Rxc3 (13. dxc3 {Tadic,Branko: ''!?''} Re8 14. f4 Nfd7 15. Nxd7 Bxd7 $11) 13... Be6 {QUESTION: Should White defend the a3-pawn?  Tadic,Branko: 'Sam Collins: 'QUESTION: Should White defend the a3-pawn? ''} 14. d4 $1 {ANSWER: No! Wei Yi finds an excellent way to generate compensation, instead of the horribly passive 14 Ra3? Tadic,Branko: 'Sam Collins: '!' Sam Collins: 'ANSWER: No! Wei Yi finds an excellent way to generate compensation, instead of the horribly passive 14 Ra3?''} (14. f4 {Tadic,Branko: '!?' '!?' '!?' '!?'} Nxa4 15. Rc2 {is also interesting but I prefer Wei Yi's central approach. Tadic,Branko: '' '' '' '' Tadic,Branko: 'Sam Collins: 'is also interesting but I prefer Wei Yi's central approach.'' is also interesting but I prefer Wei Yi's central approach. Tadic,Branko: '' '' Tadic,Branko: 'Sam Collins: 'is also interesting but I prefer Wei Yi's central approach.''}) 14... Nxa4 {Tadic,Branko: ''!''} (14... cxd3 15. b3 {and the d3-pawn will fall, with excellent play for White. Tadic,Branko: ''}) 15. Ra3 (15. Rc2 b5 16. Bf4 (16. d5 Bc8 17. Be3 $44) 16... Rfe8 17. Ra1 Nb6 18. f3 $44) 15... b5 16. f4 Nb6 {This looks like a typical battle between Black's extra pawn and White's central dominance. Standard play might continue 17 d5 or 17 f5, with unclear play. However, Wei Yi plays I move which, I suspect, few players would even consider. Tadic,Branko: 'Sam Collins: 'This looks like a typical battle between Black's extra pawn and White's central dominance. Standard play might continue 17 d5 or 17 f5, with unclear play. However, Wei Yi plays I move which, I suspect, few players would even consider.''} ({The engine suggests} 16... Ng4 {, but White retains wonderful compensation after} 17. Nc6 {.}) 17. g4 $6 {This is an amazing concept which works wonderfully in the game, but objectively it's quite dubious.  Tadic,Branko: 'Sam Collins: 'This is an amazing concept which works wonderfully in the game, but objectively it's quite dubious. ''} (17. d5 Bc8 18. Be3 Re8 19. Bd4 $44) (17. Nc6 $5 Rfe8 18. Bd2 Bd7 (18... a4 19. Nb4 $5) 19. e5 Nfd5 20. Nxa5 c6 $13) 17... Nxg4 ({a)} 17... b4 18. Rg3 {improves White's kingside prospects, though the position remains quite unclear.}) ({b)} 17... Bxg4 18. f5 {leaves the bishop short of squares, though this might have been the best choice for Black. After} Be2 19. Re1 Bd3 20. Nxd3 b4 $1 21. Nxb4 axb4 22. Rg3 {the position remains very difficult to assess. Normally I would expect that the bishop pair and powerful mobile centre would provide more than enough compensation for a mere pawn. However, if either white central pawn advances, it will make squares available to the black knights.}) 18. f5 Nxe5 19. dxe5 Bd7 20. Rg3 {Even without queens, White's kingside initiative looks threatening.  Tadic,Branko: 'Sam Collins: 'Even without queens, White's kingside initiative looks threatening. ''} Bc6 $2 {Tadic,Branko: 'Sam Collins: '?''} (20... b4 {Tadic,Branko: '!?' '!?' '!?' '!?'} 21. Bh6 g6 {is a far better version of the game for Black. Tadic,Branko: '' '' '' '' Tadic,Branko: 'Sam Collins: 'is a far better version of the game for Black.'' is a far better version of the game for Black. Tadic,Branko: '' '' Tadic,Branko: 'Sam Collins: 'is a far better version of the game for Black.''}) 21. Bh6 g6 22. Rg5 $2 {Tadic,Branko: '!?' '!?' '!?' '!?' Tadic,Branko: 'Diagram [#] Sam Collins: '?'' Tadic,Branko: '!?' '!?' Tadic,Branko: 'Diagram [#] Sam Collins: '?''} (22. Bh3 $1 Bxe4 23. fxg6 hxg6 24. e6 {seems to lead to a draw with best play.}) 22... c3 $2 (22... Na4 {and the advantage would again be with Black. Tadic,Branko: '!' '!' '!' '!' Tadic,Branko: 'Sam Collins: 'and the advantage would again be with Black.'' and the advantage would again be with Black. Tadic,Branko: '!' '!' Tadic,Branko: 'Sam Collins: 'and the advantage would again be with Black.''} 23. Rf2 (23. Bxf8 Rxf8 24. fxg6 fxg6 25. e6 Rxf1+ 26. Bxf1 Kg7 $17) 23... b4 24. Bf1 Nxb2 25. Rxb2 c3 26. Rf2 Bxe4 $17) (22... Rfe8 $6 23. e6 fxe6 24. fxg6 $40) 23. bxc3 Nc4 {Tadic,Branko: '?' '?' '?' '?' Tadic,Branko: 'Diagram [#]' Tadic,Branko: '?' '?' Tadic,Branko: 'Diagram [#]'} (23... Nd7 $142 24. Bxf8 Nxf8 25. Kf2 $14) 24. fxg6 {Tadic,Branko: '?!' '?!' '?!' '?!'} (24. Bxf8 {Tadic,Branko: '!' '!' '!' '!'} Rxf8 25. e6 $1 {, and the advantage would again be with Black. Tadic,Branko: 'Sam Collins: '!' Sam Collins: ', and the advantage would again be with Black.''} fxe6 26. fxg6 Rxf1+ 27. Bxf1 hxg6 28. Bxc4 bxc4 29. Rc5 $18) 24... fxg6 25. Bxf8 Rxf8 26. e6 $1 {Tadic,Branko: 'Sam Collins: '!''} Be8 27. Rd1 Rf6 28. Rd8 Kf8 {Tadic,Branko: '?!' '?!' '?!' '?!'} (28... Rxe6 $142 29. Rxb5 Nd6 30. Rd5 Nxe4 31. c4 $16) 29. Rxb5 Ke7 30. Rbb8 Bc6 31. Rdc8 {Wei Yi has a winning advantage and converts with impressive technique.  Tadic,Branko: 'Sam Collins: 'Wei Yi has a winning advantage and converts with impressive technique. ''} Rxe6 32. Rxc7+ Kd6 33. Rxh7 a4 34. Ra7 Kc5 35. e5 {Tadic,Branko: '+-!' '+-!' '+-!' '+-!'} Bxg2 36. Kxg2 a3 37. Rc7+ Rc6 38. Rxc6+ Kxc6 39. Rc8+ Kd5 40. e6 a2 41. Ra8 Kxe6 42. Rxa2 $18 1-0


