{In the penultimate round, Adhiban had the white pieces against Le Quang, Wei Yi was Black against Kasimdzhanov, followed by Ganguly and myself on the third and fourth boards, half a point behind. Le Quang played a nice positional game to outwit Adhiban and Wei too won in impressive style. Ganguly drew against the rock solid Chinese Wen Yang. On the fourth board I won against the local upcoming grandmaster, Jahonigir Vakhidov, in a well contested game. Now a draw would guarantee me a place in the World Cup, once again thanks to my high number of wins. If you take the last two Asian championships, I drew only three out a total of 18 games, which clearly shows that this is the ideal tiebreak for someone like me who tries so hard to win games. On the other hand, quite a few players were complaining about the unfairness of the tiebreak rule, but then again there is no perfect system, everything has its own flaws. So, a tense final round got underway, which was to end in a totally unexpected way which no one would have thought possible, including yours truly! I was paired against one of the leaders, Wei Yi, with the black pieces, while Le Quang was up against my compatriot Ganguly. In fact both leaders had the white pieces and were obviously ambitious and not about to make short draws. Ganguly too was in a tense situation, as he needed to win with Black to give him a good chance of qualifying for the World Cup. And now for my crucial last round encounter. In my game, Wei Yi played the aggressive Shabalov system in the Meran, which I countered with a new idea causing my opponent to spend a great deal of time on the clock and land in a difficult position. Meanwhile Ganguly rejected Le Quang's draw offer in a slightly better position.} 1. d4 {The first surprise. Throughout the whole tournament my opponent had preferred 1.e4 and indeed he can be considered to be a dangerous king’s pawn player, especially if you study his breathtaking wins against the Sicilian. However, in his last three or four tournaments he has started to adopt different setups and openings. Nevertheless, taking into account the crucial nature of this round, it came as a surprise to me, and I asked myself “Perhaps he has found something special against my customary opening repertoire?”} d5 {After a couple of minutes thought I decided to stick to my favourite Slav Defence, which had brought me some good wins in the tournament.} 2. c4 c6 3. e3 {(Probably my opponent wanted to avoid 3.Nc3 dc4 or 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.Nc3 dc4, although I have never used such systems in practice.)} (3. Nc3 dxc4) (3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 (4. e3 Bg4) 4... dxc4) 3... Nf6 ({With White’s particular move order Black also has the option of playing} 3... Bf5 {. But I didn’t want to play it over the board without proper study and preparation.}) 4. Nc3 e6 5. Nf3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 {Now we transpose into the Meran system. Diagram [#]} 7. g4 $5 {(The second surprise. This move has gone out of fashion over the past few years. I was expecting 7.Bd3 but my opponent, true to himself, was clearly in an aggressive mood which explains his choice of this pawn thrust.)} Nxg4 $5 {(This was the main line in older times but it has become very rare nowadays due to 7...h6. Nevertheless there are lots of resources and unexplored territories in 7...Ng4, which is why I chose it.)} (7... h6 {is the main move leading to a different path}) 8. Rg1 {Diagram [#]} Qf6 (8... Nxh2 9. Nxh2 Bxh2 10. Rxg7 Nf8 11. Rg2 Bd6 12. e4 Ng6 13. Bg5 Be7 14. Be3 $146 (14. Bxe7 $145 {Morozevich,Alexander 2788 - Kramnik,Vladimir 2788, Moscow 2008 - 103/310}) 14... dxe4 15. O-O-O f5 $13 {Rapport,Richard 2671 - Eljanov,Pavel 2723, Biel 2015}) 9. Rxg4 Qxf3 10. Rxg7 Nf6 (10... Nf8 11. Rg1) 11. Rg5 {Diagram [#]} Qh1 {A new direction! In tournament practice - which of course means testing the opening line against computers :) - I had prepared this entire concept one year previously. Luckily enough, I revised it during this tournament, since I had considered the possibility of trying the 7.g4 Meran myself, with the white pieces, a few rounds before and was looking at all kinds of options for Black. And this idea crossed my mind once again! That’s the advantage of preparing an opening from a general point of view, then you can employ it from both sides of the chessboard rather than sticking to one colour.} (11... Ne4 {- 99/300}) 12. Bd2 {Developing the bishop is quite normal, yet my opponent spent quite a lot of time over his next few moves.} (12. f4 Bb4 13. Rg2 (13. Bd2 Qxh2) 13... Bd7 14. Bd2 O-O-O 15. O-O-O Rdg8) 12... Bd7 13. O-O-O {Diagram [#]} Qxh2 {When it is on offer, why not grab a pawn? After all, a pawn is a pawn! :) After the 12th move I was on my own, nevertheless I was playing quite quickly in order to put my opponent under pressure. In any event my replies were logical compared to his, since he had to make some crucial decisions in order to pose problems for me before I consolidated my position.} 14. f4 $146 {White’s main idea is usually to establish the f3-e4 pawn centre, but after this advance he loses control over the e4 square, making Black’s life easier.} (14. Rg2 Qh4 15. f3 O-O-O 16. e4 Bf4 (16... dxe4 $145 {Ingersol,Harry 2392 - Noble,Mark Frederick 2375, Internet 2009}) 17. e5 $13) (14. f3) 14... Rg8 $1 15. Bd3 O-O-O {(Up to this point all my moves were very logical and ideal.)} 16. cxd5 exd5 (16... Rxg5 $142 17. fxg5 Nxd5 18. Ne4 Be7 {and White does not have enough compensation for the pawn.}) 17. Nb5 {Diagram [#] Here I faced a tough choice and made the wrong one, underestimating White’s attacking resources.} (17. Nxd5 $145 Nxd5 (17... Rxg5 18. Nxf6 Rg1 19. Nxd7 Kxd7 20. Qb3 Rxd1+ 21. Kxd1 Kc7 22. Qxf7+ Rd7 23. Qf5 $44) 18. Rxd5 Bg4 19. Rf1 Kb8 20. Rg5 $13) 17... Bb8 $6 (17... Be7 $1 18. Re5 (18. Nxa7+ Kb8) 18... Kb8 $1 19. Rxe7 cxb5 $17 {was simplest.}) 18. Qc5 b6 19. Nxa7+ (19. Nd6+ Kc7 20. Qa3 Rxg5 21. Nxf7 $1 Rgg8 22. Qd6+ Kb7 23. Nxd8+ Rxd8 24. Qxf6 Bc7 $13) 19... Kb7 {Diagram [#] We had reached a very complex position with hanging pieces all over the place. But I was ahead on time, whilst my opponent was down to five minutes for the next twenty moves. He was clearly under severe pressure.} 20. Qe7 Qh6 21. Nxc6 Kxc6 $6 {Diagram [#]} (21... Rde8 $142 {An intermezzo} 22. Qa3 Bxc6 23. Qa6+ Kc7 24. Kb1 {and it’s hard to make a correct evaluation.}) 22. Kb1 ({White has instead} 22. Qa3 $1 {but this is not an easy move to see in time pressure. My opponent’s Kb1 looks more natural, as it brings the rook on d1 into play, but the queen move looks very strong because it prevents Black’s king going to b7, so leading to a lack of coordination between the black pieces. The variations analysed below are hard to imagine for a human mind, but just to show how full of resources and complications this position really is, I will mention a few mind-blowing variations.} Bg4 $1 23. Rf1 $3 {The only move to fight for an advantage.} (23. Re1 Rxg5 24. fxg5 Qxg5 25. e4 Bf4 26. Qa4+ Kb7 27. Qa6+ Kc7 28. Qa7+ Kc6 29. Qa4+ $11) 23... Ne4 {Diagram  Diagram [#]} 24. Bb4 $3 {Diagram [#] Completely unhuman-like play! However, there is a sound and deep positional idea behind it in that the bishop controls the enemy king’s escape square. Now the black king is in great danger of being trapped.} (24. Bxe4 dxe4 25. Qa8+ Kc7 26. Kb1 Rxg5 27. fxg5 Qxg5 {Diagram [#]} (27... Qe6 28. Rc1+ Kd7 29. d5 Qg6 30. Bc3 {The only move otherwise White stands worse:} Qxg5 31. Qc6+ Ke7 32. Bb4+ Bd6 33. Qc7+ Ke8 34. Bxd6 Rc8 35. Qxb6 Qxd5 36. Bc5 $13) 28. Rc1+ (28. Rxf7+ Bd7 (28... Rd7 $2 29. Rf1 Rd8 30. Bb4 $18) 29. d5 Qg6 30. Bc3 Rc8 {creating an escape route for the king.} 31. Be5+ (31. Rg7 Qf5 32. Qc6+ Kd8 33. Qxb6+ Ke8 34. Rg8+ Kf7 35. Rg7+ Ke8 36. Rg8+ Kf7 37. Rxc8 Qf1+ 38. Kc2 Qd3+ $11) 31... Kd8 32. Rf8+ Ke7 33. Rxc8 Bxe5) 28... Kd7 29. Qc6+ Ke7 30. Bb4+ Bd6 31. Qc7+ Ke8 32. Bxd6 Rc8 33. Bf4 $1 Qd5 34. Qe5+ $11) (24. Rxd5 Nxd2 25. Qa8+ Kc7) (24. Rxg8 Rxg8 25. Qa8+ Kc7 26. Qxd5 Nxd2 27. Qxf7+ Bd7 28. Kxd2 Rg2+) (24. Qa8+ Kc7 25. Bxe4) {If now} 24... Nxg5 25. fxg5 (25. Qa8+ Kc7 26. Kb1 Rc8 $1 (26... Qc6 27. Rc1 Qxc1+ 28. Kxc1 Ne4 29. Ba6 Bc8 30. Bxc8 Kxc8 31. Qc6+ Bc7 32. Qa8+ Bb8 $11) 27. f5 $3 (27. Rc1+ Kd8 $19) (27. Qxd5 Bd7 28. Ba6 Rge8 $3 29. Rc1+ Bc6 30. fxg5 Qg6+) 27... Qc6 $8 (27... Kd8 28. Qxd5+ Bd6 29. f6 $18) 28. Rc1 Qxc1+ 29. Kxc1 Bf3 $13) 25... Qxg5 {and here White has two options, both of which are promising: Diagram [#]} 26. Kb1 $1 {A cool, calm and collected move in a position where he is simply a full rook down! After all this is modern chess. :)} (26. Qa8+ Kc7 {Diagram [#]} 27. Kd2 $3 {Who would see this!! The beauty of computer analysis and still it is not clear, although at the end of the day White should be better:} Rc8 28. Rc1+ Kd7 29. Bb5+ Kd8 30. Rxc8+ Bxc8 31. Qxb8 $16) 26... Kd7 $1 27. Qa4+ Ke6 28. Qc6+ Bd6 (28... Rd6 29. Bxd6 Bxd6 30. e4 Ke7 31. e5 Bxe5 32. dxe5 Qxe5 33. Qxb6 $16) 29. e4 f6 {Diagram  Diagram [#]} 30. Ka1 $3 {Mind-blowing prophylaxis whilst conducting an attack} (30. e5 fxe5 31. dxe5 Qe3 $1 32. Bxh7 Kxe5 33. Bc3+ d4 34. Qxb6 Bf3 $13) (30. exd5+ Kf7 31. Bxd6 Bd7) 30... Kf7 31. Bxd6 dxe4 32. Bxe4 $16 { }) 22... Kb7 {Now everything is under control. The king is safe and my pieces are coming out!} 23. Rc1 Bc7 24. Rf5 Ne4 {Played instantly, which brought me immediate relief in that there now follows the exchange of one of White’s bishops.} (24... Qg6 25. Qxf6 Bxf5 26. Qxf5 Qxf5 27. Bxf5 h5 $15) 25. Bxe4 dxe4 26. Rf6 Rg6 (26... Qf8 $142 27. Qxe4+ Kb8 28. Qxh7 Qg7 $17) 27. Rxf7 Rc6 {Diagram [#]} 28. Rxh7 {A strange decision. Capturing the e4 pawn instead would have made Black’s task of converting his advantage more difficult.} (28. Qxe4 Qg6 29. Qxg6 hxg6 30. e4 {and it is still not clear how to convert my advantage into a win. Perhaps there is no way!}) 28... Rxc1+ 29. Bxc1 Qc6 30. Rh2 Rc8 31. Rh7 Be6 (31... Bg4 $142 $19 { e2-d3 î x î Pe2-d3}) 32. b3 Kb8 {Diagram [#] Here I suddenly noticed that I only had three minutes for eight moves, although of course that should be quite sufficient for the present position. Nevertheless I was still a little nervous about converting it without spoiling the nuances of the position.} 33. Kb2 Bf5 34. Rf7 Be6 35. Rh7 Rg8 36. Rg7 Re8 {So I began to repeat moves a few times in order to get to the 40 move time control.} 37. Qb4 Rh8 38. Qc3 Rh2+ 39. Bd2 {Diagram [#]} Qxc3+ {Exchanging queens was a very important decision. I was sure that the endgame would be won for Black because of the strong pawn on e4, as it is established in such a way that it cannot be exchanged. And in fact my intitution proved to be right, even though some might have thought it better to keep queens on the board.} 40. Kxc3 b5 41. a3 Ba5+ $1 {Fixing the white pawns.} 42. b4 Bc7 43. Rg6 Bd5 44. Rg5 Bc4 45. Rg1 Bd3 46. Ra1 Bd6 47. Rg1 Kc7 48. Rg7+ Kc6 49. Rg1 Rf2 50. Rh1 Rg2 51. Ra1 {Diagram [#]} Kd5 {Now comes a king walk to the other side of the board, targeting the e3 pawn.} 52. Rh1 Be7 53. Ra1 Rh2 54. Rg1 Ke6 55. Ra1 Rh8 56. Kb2 Kf5 57. a4 bxa4 58. Rxa4 Kg4 59. Ra7 Bh4 60. Rb7 Kf3 61. b5 Rh5 62. b6 Rb5+ 63. Ka3 Bd8 64. f5 {Diagram [#] Creating some counterchances but two bishops make a very strong team indeed. :)} Rxf5 65. Bb4 Kxe3 66. Bc5 Rf1 67. Rb8 Ra1+ 68. Kb2 Rb1+ 69. Ka3 (69. Ka2 Bg5 (69... Bh4 70. b7 Be1 $19) 70. b7 Kd2 $19) 69... Bg5 70. d5+ Ke2 71. Bb4 Bc1+ 72. Ka4 Bd2 73. Bxd2 Kxd2 74. b7 e3 {Diagram [#] By this time my compatriot Surya Ganguly had already won a nice game with the black pieces in impressive fashion against the top seed Le Quang, which meant I had won the championship. At first I couldn't believe what had just happened but after resigning the game my opponent immediately congratulated me on my victory in the tournament. I have to say, I was very touched by this sportsmanlike and gentlemanly gesture! I have to admit I was rather nervous in the final stages of my game as there was so much at stake and I did not want to throw away my chances of victory. As it turned out, by making a series of accurate technical moves I was able to convert my advantage smoothly into a win, by which time Ganguly had also won his game, and to my astonishment it finally hit me: I had now become Asian Champion! In fact it was a double delight for me to know that India had now won both the men's and women's championships. On the other hand, Ganguly was not so fortunate. After winning so impressively in the last round, a little later he received the heartbreaking news that the tiebreak had conspired against him and he had failed to achieve the desired qualification. This really was a pity since he had played wonderful chess throughout the tournament and was one of the few players who had remained undefeated. Chess, like any competitive sport, can be so brutal.} 0-1


