1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5 Be6 9. Nbd2 Nc5 10. c3 Be7 11. Bc2 d4 12. Nb3 d3 {*} 13. Bb1 Nxb3 14. axb3 Bf5 15. Re1 O-O 16. Be3 Qd5 17. Bd4 Rfd8 {Mikhalevski, V: 'Wesley decides to avoid the long theoretical lines, which ensue in case of 17...d2.'} ({The main line is} 17... d2 {, as in Bruzon Bautista, L (2689)-Mikhalevski, V (2552)/Washington D.C. 2013/  [Mikhalevski, V]}) 18. Re3 {Mikhalevski, V: '!?'} (18. Bxd3 {is the main alternative. Here play may continue} Bxd3 19. Qxd3 Qxb3 20. e6 $5 fxe6 21. Qe4 Qc4 {and White was unable to set problems in a few recent games.}) 18... Nxd4 19. cxd4 (19. Nxd4 {isn't dangerous either.} Bg6 20. b4 c5 (20... a5 $1 {looks more accurate.}) 21. bxc5 Bxc5 22. Ba2 Qb7 23. e6 Bxd4 24. cxd4 Rxd4 25. exf7+ Bxf7 26. Bxf7+ Qxf7 27. Rxd3 Rxd3 28. Qxd3 Re8 $1 29. h3 Qe6 $11 {and Black equalised in Kosteniuk, A (2501)-Koneru, H (2610)/Beijing 2012.}) 19... c5 {Mikhalevski, V: '!'} 20. Bxd3 cxd4 21. Re2 (21. Bxf5 $2 dxe3 22. Qxd5 Rxd5 23. Be4 Rdd8 24. Bxa8 $2 e2 $1 25. Nd4 $8 Rxd4 26. Bf3 Rd2 27. Re1 Rxb2 28. g3 Rxb3 $17 {Marin,Mihail}) 21... Qe6 {Mikhalevski, V: '!' Mikhalevski, V: 'This position has been known for almost 20 years.'} 22. Rd2 $146 {Mikhalevski, V: '!?' Mikhalevski, V: 'Wey Yi's novelty. White wants to blockade the d-pawn with his rook from where it attacks the d4-pawn and protects his weakness on b3.'} ({Mikhalevski, V: 'In two preceding games White tested'} 22. h3 Rac8 23. Ne1 Rc6 (23... Bg6 $5 {also looks good.}) 24. Qb1 Bxd3 25. Qxd3 h6 26. f4 Qc8 {and Black created counterplay connected with the . ..Rc1 idea, Svidler, P (2735)-Motylev, A (2651)/Moscow 2004.}) ({The attempt to build a blockade on d3 by means of} 22. Ne1 {can be answered by} Bg4 $1 {Black provokes a weakening of the dark squares.} 23. f3 Bh5 24. Be4 Rac8 25. Nd3 Bg6 {and Black is fine.}) 22... Bxd3 23. Rxd3 Bc5 24. Qd2 {Mikhalevski, V: 'White is bringing his queen to f4.'} Rd5 ({The immediate} 24... h6 {also makes sense.}) 25. h3 h6 26. Qf4 (26. b4 $5 {was worth a try in order to fix the a-pawn on a6.}) 26... Re8 (26... a5 $1 {deserved attention, with the idea to secure his a-pawn by means of 27...Bb6 before activating his queen's rook and putting pressure on e5.}) 27. Qd2 {Mikhalevski, V: '!?' Mikhalevski, V: 'White admits that his previous move wasn't necessary.'} Ba7 {Mikhalevski, V: 'Black is transferring the bishop to b8 in order to put pressure on e5.'} 28. Rd1 Bb8 {Mikhalevski, V: '!?' Mikhalevski, V: 'After an exchange of the e and d-pawns Black will have a marginally better rook endgame thanks to the doubled pawns on the b-file.'} 29. Re1 {Mikhalevski, V: '!'} (29. Nxd4 $6 Qxe5 30. Nf3 (30. g3 $2 Red8 $19) 30... Rxd3 31. Qxd3 Qxb2 $17) 29... Bxe5 30. Nxe5 Rxe5 31. Rxe5 Qxe5 32. Rxd4 $11 Qe1+ 33. Kh2 $1 {White wants his rook on the second rank.} Qxd2 34. Rxd2 Kf8 $15 {Black is slightly better in this endgame, but White should be able to hold.} 35. Kg3 Re6 36. Kf3 Ke7 37. b4 Rc6 38. Ke3 Ke6 39. b3 Ke5 (39... g5 $1 {with the idea of 40...Ke5 would set White more problems.}) 40. f4+ Ke6 41. Rd3 (41. Ke4 $1 {is more accurate. Now after} Rc3 42. Ra2 Rxb3 43. Rxa6+ Ke7 44. Ke5 Rxb4 45. Ra7+ Kf8 46. Ra8+ {a draw is inevitable.}) 41... Rc2 42. Rd2 Rc3+ 43. Rd3 Rc1 44. Kf3 $6 (44. g3 $5 $11) 44... Rf1+ 45. Ke3 g5 $1 $15 {Now White has to solve some problems.} 46. fxg5 hxg5 47. Kd4 $1 {The young Chinese GM understands that he needs to create counterplay.} f5 48. Re3+ (48. g3 $1 Kf6 49. Rc3 $1 $15 {was better.}) 48... Kf6 49. Re2 (49. Rc3 $5) 49... f4 {Now the g2-pawn is weak.} 50. Kc5 (50. Ra2 $5 Kf5 $1 51. Kc5 Rb1 $1 52. Rxa6 Rb2 53. Rb6 $1 Rxg2 54. Rxb5 $15 {is another logical way to defend.}) 50... Ra1 $5 51. Rd2 $6 ({It wasn't easy to realize, but White needed the position after 52.Rd2 with Black to move.} 51. Rf2 $1 Kf5 52. Rd2 $1 $15) 51... Ra3 $6 {This inaccurate move facilitates White's task.} (51... Kf5 $1 {was correct.} 52. Kd4 $1 ({Now after} 52. Rd5+ Kg6 53. Rd2 Kh5 $17 {White experiences serious problems.})) 52. Rd6+ Kf5 53. Rd5+ Kg6 54. Rd3 $1 Ra1 ({or} 54... Kh5 55. g3 $1 $11) 55. g4 $1 Kf6 56. Kd4 $1 $11 {Now White just keeps Black's king at bay, while the rook is protecting the weaknesses on b3 and h3.} Rc1 57. Ke4 Re1+ 58. Kd4 Rc1 59. Ke4 Ke6 60. Kd4 Rc2 61. Ke4 Re2+ 62. Kd4 Kd6 63. Rf3 Re7 64. Rd3 Re8 65. Rf3 Re5 66. Rc3 Re6 67. Rf3 Re8 68. Rd3 Kc6 69. Rf3 Kd6 70. Rd3 Re5 {This game proved that 17...Rfd8 is a good alternative to 17...d2 and also promises equal chances. ½-½ (70) Wei Yi (2706)-So,W (2773) Wijk aan Zee NED 2016 [Mikhalevski, V]} 1/2-1/2


