1. e4 {GM Mihail Marin Ftacnik,Lubomir Ftacnik,Lubomir Ftacnik,L Ftacnik,Lubomir: 'Stamenkovic,Zoran' GM Mihail Marin Ftacnik,Lubomir Ftacnik,Lubomir Ftacnik,Lubomir Ftacnik,L Ftacnik,Lubomir: 'Stamenkovic,Zoran' Ftacnik,Lubomir GM Mihail Marin Ftacnik,Lubomir Ftacnik,Lubomir Ftacnik,Lubomir Ftacnik,L Ftacnik,Lubomir: 'Stamenkovic,Zoran'} e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nc4 {GM Mihail Marin: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: 'Grandmaster Rapport, one of the most creative players in the world, loves to skate on the outer fringes of theory. This surprise move is harmless for Black, and the position feels rather lifeless, but just watch what happens in a game where both sides strive to complicate.''} Nxe4 5. Qe2 ({An alternative is} 5. Nc3 {GM Mihail Marin} Nxc3 6. bxc3 ({after} 6. dxc3 d5 7. Ne3 c6 8. Qd4 Be6 9. f4 f6 10. c4 c5 11. Qd3 d4 12. Qe4 Qe7 13. Nd5 Bxd5 14. Qxe7+ Bxe7 15. cxd5 Nd7 16. c4 {was S.Sulskis-M.Zulfugarli, Bydgoszcz 1999, and now} dxc3 17. bxc3 O-O-O {, the ending looks equal}) 6... g6 $1 {(White was planning d2-d4 and Bd3, taking aim at Black's kingside; this move blunts that plan)} 7. d4 Bg7 8. Bd3 O-O 9. O-O Nd7 10. Qf3 Nb6 11. Ne3 c5 $1 {and Black has equalized, Ma.Carlsen-V.Kramnik, Nice (rapid) 2008. This game is annotated in 'The Petroff: Move by Move'.}) 5... Qe7 6. Ne3 {Ftacnik,Lubomir: 'Playing against Rapport is not easy for any chessplayer as the Hungarian star loves unusual lines, original positions.' Ftacnik,L: 'Playing against Rapport is not easy for any chessplayer as the Hungarian star loves unusual lines, original positions.' Ftacnik,L: 'Playing against Rapport is not easy for any chessplayer as the Hungarian star loves unusual lines, original positions.'} Be6 {Ftacnik,Lubomir: 'Black is sensibly deciding not to lose time on pawn moves like ...c6 and rather develop the pieces as quickly as possible.' GM Mihail Marin: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: 'Wei Yi decides to develop.'' Ftacnik,L: 'Black is sensibly deciding not to lose time on pawn moves like ...c6 and ra