ronical weakness on f6 and the relative vulnerability of the black king even more relevant.' GM Mihail Marin: 'One of those moves which are hard to evaluate. Wei Yi must have thought that he had done everything right so far and, not seeing any constructive ways of slowly strengthening the position, decided that he could and should start forcing play. Hard to believe he calculated too much (if he had, he would have found the relatively obvious hole); it must have been more of a matter of intuition. Abstractly there are a few problems with his reasoning: 1) White did not do anything wrong either, so there is no reason to think he deserves such radical punishment. White's play was original, of course, but entirely sound. 2) After the introductory moves of the attack, a white knight will jump to d5, making the newly created chronical weakness on f6 and the relative vulnerability of the black king even more relevant. Cyrus Lakdawala: '?' Cyrus Lakdawala: 'This is a bit too radical.'' Diagram [#] Ftacnik,L: '?' Ftacnik,Lubomir: '?' '?' '?' '?' Ftacnik,Lubomir: 'Stamenkovic,Zoran: '?!' Stamenkovic,Zoran: 'Diagram [#]'' Ftacnik,Lubomir: 'It is easy to dismiss this courageous idea with the help of a computer and some hindsight. Black is accepting a high degree of risk when a simple knight move was enough to maintain equality.' GM Mihail Marin: 'One of those moves which are hard to evaluate. Wei Yi must have thought that he had done everything right so far and, not seeing any constructive ways of slowly strengthening the position, decided that he could and should start forcing play. Hard to believe he calculated too much (if he had, he would have found the relatively obvious hole); it must have been more of a matter of intuition. Abstractly there are a few problems with his reasoning: 1) White did not do anything wrong either, so there is no reason to think he deserves such radical punishment. White's play was original, of course, but entirely sound. 2) After the introductory