{l'Ami,Erwin: 'The clash between the number one and number two came early in the tournament in round five. Navara came well-prepared, but Wei Yi showed tremenduous tenacity in defense.'} 1. Nf3 {Navara knows his opponent from the Chinese league and he wanted to lure him into a concrete variation. l'Ami,Erwin: 'Stohl,I: 'Navara knows his opponent from the Chinese league and he wanted to lure him into a concrete variation.''} ({After} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 {Wei Yi also plays the Nimzo-Indian. He had one full-blooded Grünfeld in Wijk:} g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bg5 (5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Qb3 {is an attempt to transpose into the game, but here Black has the alternative} Nxc3 7. bxc3 c5 8. e3 O-O 9. Be2 Nc6 10. O-O Na5 11. Qa3 cxd4 12. exd4 (12. cxd4 Be6 {with typical counterplay.}) 12... b6 13. Bg5 f6 14. Be3 Be6 15. Nd2 Qd6 16. Qxd6 exd6 17. Bf4 d5 18. Rfe1 Kf7 19. Ba6 Rad8 20. h4 Bc8 21. Bb5 Bd7 22. a4 Rfe8 $11 {Anton Guijarro,D (2490)-Nabaty,T (2582) Benasque 2012}) 5... Ne4 6. Bf4 Nxc3 ({Grischuk lately experimented with} 6... O-O $5 {} 7. Nxd5 c5 $44) 7. bxc3 dxc4 (7... c5 {is more popular, but the text is no worse.}) 8. e3 Be6 9. Qb1 b6 10. Ng5 Bd5 11. e4 h6 12. Nf3 ({The position after} 12. exd5 hxg5 13. Qb5+ {occurs more often with the bishop on h4. Then Black can also consider 13...c6!? 14.dxc6 a6=, now he has the standard} Qd7 14. Qxd7+ Nxd7 15. Bxg5 b5 16. a4 b4 $132 (16... Nb6 $5 17. axb5 O-O-O $11)) 12... Be6 13. Be5 f6 $5 ({This ugly, but concrete move seems stronger than} 13... O-O 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. d5 Bc8 16. Bxc4 c6 17. O-O Bb7 18. Bb3 cxd5 19. exd5 Nd7 20. c4 Nc5 21. Qb2+ Kh7 22. Rad1 $14 {Frog,I (2295)-Baikov,V (2370) Moscow 1995}) 14. Bg3 (14. d5 Bf7 15. Bg3 {Maris,I (2178)-Leenhouts,K (2385) Vlissingen 2014} f5 16. Be5 O-O {is only a transposition.} ({Moreover, Black can consider} 16... Bxe5 $5 17. Nxe5 Qd6 $13)) 14... O-O 15. d5 f5 16. Be5 Bf7 {l'Ami,Erwin: 'Stohl,I: 'is only a transposition.''} 17. Bxc4 Bxe5 18. Nxe5 Qd6 19. f4 Nd7 20. Nxd7 (20. Nxf7 Qxf4 $1 21. d6 Rxf7 $44 {[%csl Re1] }) 20... Qxd7 21. exf5 $2 (21. O-O c6 22. exf5 gxf5 23. dxc6 Qxc6 $11) 21... Bxd5 22. Qe4 Rxf5 23. O-O-O e6 $17 {Timman,J (2593)-Wei,Y (2675) Wijk aan Zee-B 2015}) 1... Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 {l'Ami,Erwin: 'The Anti-Grunfeld (where White delays the advance d2-d4) has served David well in both colors. I recall a victory with the black pieces against Levon Aronian, also in Wijk aan Zee.'} 5. Qb3 (5. Qc2 {was introduced by Topalov against Kamsky in 2011. Black's best is} Nc6 {and now:} 6. d4 (6. Qb3 Nb6 7. d4 {is a paradoxical idea, White has invested a tempo and tries to prove the c6 is misplaced. After} Be6 8. Qd1 Bg7 9. e3 O-O 10. Be2 Bc4 11. Bxc4 Nxc4 12. O-O Qd7 13. b3 Nb6 (13... Nd6 $5 $11) 14. Bb2 Rad8 15. Qc2 e5 16. dxe5 Nxe5 17. Nxe5 Bxe5 18. Ne4 {Vallejo Pons,F (2698)-Wei,Y (2634) Leon rpd 2014} {Black can hold the balance with} Bxb2 19. Qxb2 Nd5 20. Rad1 Qe7 $11) 6... Ndb4 7. Qa4 Bd7 8. Qd1 e5 9. dxe5 Bf5 10. Bg5 Be7 (10... Nc2+ 11. Qxc2 Bxc2 12. Bxd8 Rxd8 13. Rc1 Bf5 14. e4 Bh6 15. Rd1 Rxd1+ 16. Kxd1 Bg4 17. Bb5 Bxf3+ 18. gxf3 Bf4 19. Nd5 Bxe5 20. Nb4 Bxb2 21. Ke2 Ba3 $132 {So,W (2653)-Gupta,A (2644) Ho Chi Minh City 2012}) 11. e4 Bg4 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. a3 Bxf3 14. gxf3 Rd8 15. Qa4 Nd3+ 16. Bxd3 Rxd3 17. Qb5 {and here Black has a choice:} Rxf3 (17... Rd4 18. f4 (18. Nd5 Qxe5 19. Qxb7 Rxe4+ 20. Kf1 Qxd5 21. fxe4 Qc4+ 22. Kg1 Qxe4 23. Qc8+ Ke7 24. Qxc7+ (24. Qxh8 Nd4 {and White can't avoid a perpetual}) 24... Kf8 25. h4 {½, Szymanski,R (2414)-Spiegel,W (2373) email 2011} Nd4 26. Rh3 Qg4+ 27. Rg3 Ne2+ $11) 18... O-O 19. h4 (19. Qxb7 Qe6 20. Qa6 Nxe5 21. Qxe6 Nd3+ $11) 19... Qe6 20. Qe2 Rfd8 21. h5 Qb3 (21... g5 $5 22. Rg1 h6 $13) 22. hxg6 hxg6 23. Rh3 Rd2 24. Qg4 R2d3 25. Rxd3 Rxd3 26. Rd1 Rxd1+ 27. Nxd1 Nd4 28. Qd7 Qd3 {½, Zhao,J (2577)-Gao,R (2427) Ho Chi Minh City 2012}) 18. Qxb7 Nd8 19. Qb4 Qh4 $5 (19... Qxe5 20. Rd1 c6 (20... a5 $2 {has been played at least twice to avoid the following endgame. Surprisingly White hasn't found the decisive} 21. Qa4+ c6 22. Rxd8+ $1 Kxd8 23. Qd1+ $18) 21. O-O Ne6 22. Qd6 Qxd6 23. Rxd6 O-O 24. Kg2 Rd3 $11 {/, Vorobiov,E (2574)-Sutovsky,E (2700) WCup Khanty-Mansiysk 2011}) 20. O-O-O a5 21. Qb5+ (21. Qxa5 $142 O-O 22. Qxc7 Ne6 $44 {is an engine evaluation. White's kingside is weak and his queenside passed pawns can't move forward so easily...}) 21... Kf8 22. e6 $2 (22. Qxa5 Ne6 $13) 22... Qf4+ $1 23. Kb1 Nxe6 24. Rd3 Rxf2 25. Qxa5 Rxh2 26. Rxh2 Qxh2 $15 {Arnaudov,P (2476)-Cheparinov,I (2664) BUL-ch Panagyurishte 2012}) 5... Nb6 ({Now} 5... Nxc3 $2 6. Qxc3 {is inferior, as both} Rg8 ({and} 6... f6 {are serious positional concessions.})) 6. d4 Bg7 (6... Be6 7. Qc2 Bg4 $5 ({After} 7... Bg7 8. e4 Bg4 9. Ne5 $14 {Black's results in practice have been horrible.}) 8. Qe4 Bxf3 9. Qxf3 c6 (9... Qxd4 10. Qxb7 Bg7 11. g3 Qb4 12. Qf3 $14 {[%csl Ra7,Gc1,Rc7,Gf1]}) 10. e3 Bg7 11. Be2 e5 12. dxe5 Bxe5 13. Qe4 Qe7 14. Bd2 N8d7 15. Qc2 O-O 16. O-O Rfe8 17. Rfd1 a5 $1 18. Be1 a4 19. Rab1 Nc5 20. Bf1 Red8 21. g3 Bg7 22. Rxd8+ Rxd8 23. b4 axb3 24. axb3 Ra8 25. b4 $11 {/, Gelfand,B (2740)-Svidler,P (2747) London Candidates 2013; For more details see the notes to this game in CBM 154 by Marin.}) 7. Bf4 ({Navara used to play} 7. e4 {here; his opponent was undoubtedly prepared:} Bg4 (7... O-O 8. Be3 Bg4 {tranposes to the Smyslov System (D98-99), which is not Black's main choice against the f3, b3 Grünfeld nowadays.}) 8. Bb5+ c6 9. Ng5 O-O 10. Be2 Bxe2 11. Nxe2 {Possibly the most reliable reaction is the pawn sacrifice} c5 $5 (11... h6 12. Nf3 $14 {[%csl Gd4]}) (11... e5 12. dxe5 h6 13. Nh3 $5 N8d7 14. f4 Nc5 15. Qc2 Nd3+ 16. Kf1 $13 {/ and Black's compensation is questionable}) (11... Na6 12. Qh3 h6 13. Nf3 h5 (13... Qd7 14. Qh4 (14. g4 $5 h5 15. Rg1 $13) 14... g5 $6 (14... h5 $142) 15. Bxg5 $1 hxg5 16. Nxg5 Rfd8 17. Qh5 e5 18. O-O f6 19. Qh7+ Kf8 20. f4 exd4 21. f5 fxg5 22. f6 $18 {Navara,D (2710)-Ris,R (2407) Reykjavik 2013}) 14. Rg1 Nd7 15. e5 Nb4 16. g4 Nc2+ 17. Kf1 Nxe5 $5 18. Nxe5 Bxe5 19. gxh5 Qc8 20. Rg4 Qf5 21. dxe5 Rad8 22. hxg6 fxg6 $1 (22... Rd1+ $2 23. Kg2 Ne1+ 24. Kg3 Qf3+ 25. Kh4 Qxf2+ 26. Kg5 f6+ 27. Kh6 $18 {Cheparinov,I (2678)-Sutovsky,E (2660) Poikovsky 2013} {White's king march is decisive!} Qxe2 28. Re4 $1 Qg2 29. Qe6+ Kh8 30. h4 {[%cal Re4g4,Re6e7]}) 23. Nf4 Rd1+ 24. Ke2 (24. Kg2 Qe4+ 25. f3 Ne1+ 26. Kg3 Rd3 $1 $11 {/}) 24... Re1+ 25. Kd2 Rd8+ 26. Kc3 Nxa1 27. Rxg6+ Qxg6 28. Nxg6 Rxc1+ 29. Kb4 Rd4+ 30. Ka3 Nc2+ $11) 12. dxc5 N6d7 13. Qxb7 Qa5+ 14. Bd2 Qa6 15. c6 Qxc6 16. Qxc6 Nxc6 17. Rc1 Rac8 18. b3 Rfd8 (18... Nce5 19. O-O Nd3 20. Rxc8 Rxc8 21. Be3 Rc2 22. Nc1 Nxc1 23. Rxc1 Rxa2 24. Kf1 h6 25. Rc8+ Nf8 26. Nf3 a5 $11 {Anton Guijarro,D (2607)-Harika,D (2505) Doha 2014}) 19. Nf3 Bb2 {Lupulescu,C (2630)-Swiercz,D (2614) Bundesliga 2014} 20. Rc2 Nb4 $1 21. Rxc8 Nd3+ $11) 7... Be6 {This is the main move. The Grünfeld is a very concrete opening and sometimes Black must even postpone castling to get effective counterplay. l'Ami,Erwin: 'Stohl,I: 'This is the main move. The Grünfeld is a very concrete opening and sometimes Black must even postpone castling to get effective counterplay.''} ({After} 7... O-O 8. e3 ({or even} 8. Rd1 {it's more difficult for Black to break up, or threaten White's centre.})) 8. Qa3 {A strange square for the queen, but on the other hand White's play aims to keep his centre intact as long as possible. l'Ami,Erwin: 'Stohl,I: 'A strange square for the queen, but on the other hand White's play aims to keep his centre intact as long as possible.''} (8. Qd1 c5 $1 9. e3 (9. e4 $5 cxd4 10. Nb5 Na6 11. Nbxd4 O-O 12. Bxa6 bxa6 13. O-O Bg4 $132) (9. dxc5 Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 Qxd1+ 11. Rxd1 Na4 12. Nd4 Bc4 $5 $11) 9... O-O 10. dxc5 Bxc3+ (10... Nd5 11. Nxd5 Qxd5 {also looks good:} 12. Qxd5 Bxd5 13. Be5 Rc8 $1 $11) 11. bxc3 Qxd1+ 12. Rxd1 Na4 13. Nd4 Nxc5 14. Nxe6 Nxe6 15. Bg3 Rc8 16. c4 Nc6 17. Be2 {[%csl Ra2,Rc4,Ge2,Gg3] Grigoriants,S (2570)-Navara,D (2727) Wroclaw blitz 2014} Nc5 $13) (8. Qc2 Nc6 {[%cal Yc6b4,Ye6f5] also gives Black tempi and counterplay after} 9. e3 (9. Rd1 Nb4 10. Qb1 O-O 11. e3 Bf5 12. e4 Bg4 13. Be2 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 Bxd4 15. Nd5 {Hebert,J (2378)-Fier,A (2567) Cannes 2014} N4xd5 16. Rxd4 Nxf4 17. Rxd8 Rfxd8 $44) (9. e4 Nxd4 $5 10. Nxd4 Qxd4 11. Nb5 Qb4+ $1 12. Bd2 Qxb2 13. Nxc7+ (13. Qxb2 Bxb2 14. Rb1 $2 Be5 15. f4 a6 $17) 13... Kd8 $11 {and White's compensation is at best good enough only for equality.}) 9... Nb4 10. Qd1 O-O 11. a3 N4d5 12. Nxd5 Bxd5 13. Rc1 c6 14. Be2 Nd7 $11 {[%cal Yd8b6,Yf8e8,Ye7e5]} (14... a5 15. O-O a4 16. Bg3 Nd7 17. Bc4 Qa5 18. Bxd5 Qxd5 19. Qe2 f5 20. Rfd1 Ra5 21. Ne1 Rb5 22. Nd3 Rb3 23. Rc2 Qf7 24. Qd2 Ra8 25. Qc1 Rb5 26. Rc4 Bf8 27. Qc2 Nb6 28. Rc5 $14 {Kholmov,R (2540)-Hort,V (2600) Moscow 1975})) 8... c5 $5 {[%mdl 512] l'Ami,Erwin: 'Diagram [#] Stohl,I: '!?'' The most aggressive alternative, Black sacrifices a pawn to open either the long diagonal, or the c-file and disrupt White's development. l'Ami,Erwin: 'Stohl,I: 'The most aggressive alternative, Black sacrifices a pawn to open either the long diagonal, or the c-file and disrupt White's development.''} (8... Bc4 {seems rather artificial:} 9. O-O-O (9. b3 Ba6 10. e3 $14 {is not bad, but perhaps White can aspire to more.}) (9. Ne5 $5 Ba6 10. Rd1 {is also interesting.}) 9... c6 10. h4 N8d7 11. h5 a5 12. e4 e5 13. Bg5 f6 14. Bxc4 Nxc4 15. Qb3 b5 16. Be3 $1 (16. h6 $6 Bf8 17. dxe5 fxg5 18. e6 Nc5 $1 19. Rxd8+ Rxd8 20. Qc2 {Stohl,I (2528)-Cernousek,L (2455) CZE-chT 2014} g4 $44) 16... a4 17. Qc2 $14 {[%csl Re8][%cal Yh5g6,Yh5h6,Yd4d5]}) (8... Nc6 9. e3 (9. O-O-O $5 {was the famous game Topalov-Kamsky, Kazan 2011, but nowadays attention has shifted to the game continuation.}) 9... a5 10. Rc1 $5 (10. Bb5 O-O 11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. Qc5 (12. O-O Nc4 13. Qc5 Nxb2 14. Qxc6 Nd3 15. Bg3 Nb4 16. Qc5 Na6 17. Qb5 c5 18. Rfd1 {Jakovenko,D (2713)-Navara,D (2715) GRE-chT Achaia 2013} Qd7 $5 19. Qxa5 Rfc8 $44) 12... Nd5 13. Be5 Nxc3 14. Qxc3 Bd5 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. O-O Bxf3 17. gxf3 Qd5 18. Rfc1 Qxf3 19. Qxc6 Qg4+ 20. Qg2 Qxg2+ 21. Kxg2 Rfb8 22. b3 a4 23. bxa4 Rxa4 24. Rxc7 e6 25. Rc2 Rba8 26. Kf3 R8a5 $44 {Iturrizaga Bonelli,E (2656)-Cheparinov,I (2710) Leon 2012}) 10... O-O 11. Be2 Nb4 12. b3 c6 13. O-O Bg4 14. Rfd1 N6d5 15. Nxd5 Nxd5 16. Bg3 Qb6 17. h3 Bh5 18. Bh4 $1 {[%cal Rg2g4]} Bxf3 19. Bxf3 e6 20. e4 $14 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4,Gf3,Gh4] Wang,H (2739)-Nepomniachtchi,I (2718) St Petersburg 2012}) ({Black has reasonable chances to equalise after the modest} 8... O-O 9. e3 N8d7 ({Even here} 9... Nc6 10. Be2 a5 11. O-O Nb4 12. Rfc1 c6 13. Be5 Bh6 14. Ne4 Nd7 15. Nc5 Nxc5 16. Rxc5 Nd5 17. Bc4 Qb6 18. e4 Nf6 19. Bxe6 fxe6 20. Rc2 Qb4 21. Qd3 $14 {/, Kramnik,V (2800)-Nakamura,H (2758) Moscow 2011}) 10. Rd1 $5 (10. Be2 c5 $1 {eases Black's task:} 11. dxc5 Nc4 12. Qb4 a5 13. Qb5 Rc8 14. O-O (14. Nd4 Nxc5 $1 $15 {} 15. Bxc4 $2 Bd7 {[%csl Rb5]}) 14... Rxc5 15. Qxb7 Nxb2 16. Nd4 Rxc3 17. Qxb2 Rc5 $11) 10... c6 (10... Nd5 11. Bg3 $5 (11. Nxd5 Bxd5 12. Be2 c6 13. O-O Re8 $1 14. Bg3 Qb6 15. b3 e5 (15... a5 $142 $1 $11 {[%cal Yb6b4,Ye7e5] Eljanov}) 16. Nxe5 Nxe5 17. dxe5 Bxe5 18. Bc4 Bxc4 19. bxc4 Bxg3 20. hxg3 $11 {/, Eljanov,P (2687)-Shirov,A (2740) Foros 2008}) 11... c6 12. e4 Nxc3 13. bxc3 Nf6 14. Bd3 Bg4 15. Rb1 Bxf3 16. gxf3 b6 17. Qa4 Qd7 18. Bf4 Rfd8 19. Rd1 Qh3 20. Ke2 Bh6 $132 {Rahman,Z (2528)-Vachier Lagrave,M (2722) WCup Khanty-Mansiysk 2011}) 11. Ng5 Bd5 12. e4 Bc4 $1 (12... e5 13. dxe5 Bxe5 14. Bxe5 Nxe5 {Eljanov,P (2687)-Svidler,P (2746) Foros 2008} 15. f4 $1 $14) 13. Bxc4 Nxc4 14. Qb3 e5 15. Qxc4 exf4 16. Nf3 c5 $5 17. dxc5 Bxc3+ 18. bxc3 Qe7 (18... Qc7 $11) 19. c6 Nb6 20. Qb4 Rfe8 (20... Qxb4 21. cxb4 bxc6 $11 {[%cal Ya7a5,Yf8e8]}) 21. Qxe7 (21. cxb7 $142 $5 Qxb4 22. cxb4 Rxe4+ 23. Kd2 Rb8 $11) 21... Rxe7 22. cxb7 Rxb7 23. Rd4 $6 Na4 $1 24. Rb4 {Goganov,A (2581)-Grandelius,N (2576) Stockholm 2014} Rab8 25. Kd2 Nxc3 $1 26. Rxb7 Nxe4+ $15) 9. e4 $5 {[%mdl 64] l'Ami,Erwin: '!' l'Ami,Erwin: 'Stohl,I: '!?'' A sharp thrust, which actually also wins material and leads the game into murky tactical waters. l'Ami,Erwin: 'Stohl,I: 'A sharp thrust, which actually also wins material and leads the game into murky tactical waters.''} (9. O-O-O $6 cxd4 10. Nxd4 (10. Nb5 $2 Nd5) 10... Bxd4 11. e3 Nc6 $15 {[%csl Rc1]}) ({Modest, but playable is} 9. e3 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Bxd4 11. Rd1 (11. exd4 {forces White to reckon with the greedy} Qxd4 $5 12. Be3 Qe5 $13) 11... Nc6 12. exd4 (12. Nb5 O-O 13. Nxd4 Nxd4 14. Rxd4 Qc8 $32 {[%cal Gc8c1] }) 12... Nd5 (12... O-O $5 13. Be2 Qd7 $132) 13. Bh6 Qb6 14. Be2 O-O-O 15. O-O Nxd4 $6 (15... Qb4 $5 $11 {Krasenkow}) 16. Bg7 $40 {Inarkiev,E (2693)-Sutovsky,E (2660) Poikovsky 2013} (16. Rxd4 $5 Qxd4 17. Rc1 $40)) ({l'Ami,Erwin: 'The only serious test. Instead'} 9. Qxc5 {is solid:} Nc6 10. e3 (10. e4 $5) 10... Rc8 11. Qa3 O-O {l'Ami,Erwin: 'offers Black plenty of play for the pawn. It is interesting to note though that Navara himself was unable to prove that compensation in a game against Le Quang Liem. He undoubtely had an improvement prepared there.'} (11... Nc4 12. Bxc4 Bxc4 13. d5 $1 Qa5 14. Qxa5 Nxa5 15. Be5 $36) 12. Rd1 (12. Be2 Nc4 13. Qa4 (13. Bxc4 Bxc4 14. d5 Na5 15. Be5 Bxd5 $1 {[%cal Ra5c4] } 16. Bxg7 Nc4 17. Qxa7 Bxf3 18. Bxf8 Bxg2 19. Qd4 Qxd4 20. exd4 Bxh1 21. Bxe7 Nxb2 $11) 13... Nxb2 14. Qb5 Nc4 $1 15. O-O Qa5 16. Rfc1 Qxb5 (16... Na3 $6 17. Qxb7 Nb4 18. Ne1 Bf5 19. g4 Nac2 20. Nxc2 Bxc2 21. Nb5 $16 {Le Quang Liem (2703)-Navara,D (2706) Belfort 2012}) 17. Nxb5 Nb6 $11) 12... a5 $5 (12... Nd5 13. Nxd5 Bxd5 14. Bd3 $5 (14. Be2 $14) 14... Bxf3 15. gxf3 Qb6 16. Bg5 h6 17. Bh4 e5 18. d5 e4 19. fxe4 Nb4 20. O-O g5 21. Bg3 $16 {Lalith,B (2529)-Jansa,V (2460) Pardubice 2012}) 13. Ne5 Nd5 14. Nxc6 Rxc6 15. Bg3 $142 $1 (15. Bb5 $2 Rb6 (15... Rxc3 $1 16. bxc3 Nxf4 17. exf4 Qd5 $40) 16. Qxa5 $2 (16. Be2 Nxf4 17. exf4 $15) 16... Nxf4 17. exf4 Bb3 $1 {[%cal Rb3d1,Rb6e6]} 18. O-O Bxd1 19. Rxd1 Rd6 $19 {Sadorra,J (2451)-Ganguly,S (2625) Subic Bay 2009}) 15... a4 $5 (15... Nxc3 16. bxc3 Bd5 17. f3 Qb6 18. e4 Bc4 19. Bxc4 Rxc4 20. O-O $14) (15... Qc8 16. Rc1 Nb4 17. Bb5 Nxa2 18. O-O Nxc1 19. Rxc1 $14) 16. Bb5 Rxc3 17. bxc3 Qa5 18. Qxa4 Qxc3+ 19. Rd2 Rc8 $44) ({No one has yet tried} 9. dxc5 {l'Ami,Erwin: 'is the other move, but here also after'} Nc4 {l'Ami,Erwin: 'Black has excellent play, and what better proof of the rule not to bring the queen out too early?!'} 10. Qb4 Na6 11. Qxb7 Nxc5 12. Qb5+ Nd7 13. e3 Nd6 $32 ({or} 13... a6 $44 {White's undeveloped kingside certainly looks discouraging.})) 9... cxd4 10. Nb5 {l'Ami,Erwin: 'The point. Black is now forced to give up the exchange because 10...Na6 11.Rd1! is very uncomfortable.'} O-O $1 {l'Ami,Erwin: 'Stohl,I: '!'' Black must be generous! l'Ami,Erwin: 'Stohl,I: 'Black must be generous!''} (10... Na6 $6 11. Rd1 $36 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gd1d8]}) 11. Nc7 ({White shouldn't be too greedy:} 11. Bc7 $6 {is very dangerous:} Qd7 12. Bxb6 Nc6 13. Nc7 (13. Ba5 b6 14. Bd2 a6 $36 {/}) 13... Rac8 14. Ng5 Bg4 15. h3 Bh5 16. g4 axb6 17. Nd5 Qd8 18. Nf3 f5 $1 $36) 11... Nc6 12. Nxa8 Qxa8 {l'Ami,Erwin: 'White is up material, but it is way too early to call this an advantage. Black is already fully mobilized and has a pawn for the exchange.'} 13. Rc1 {l'Ami,Erwin: 'Diagram [#]' Kingside development must still wait for a while. l'Ami,Erwin: 'Stohl,I: 'Kingside development must still wait for a while.''} (13. Bd3 $143 Nc4 $36) ({Important. White would like to finish development with} 13. Be2 {followed by 0-0, but runs into} Nc4 {because taking} 14. Bxc4 Bxc4 {would leave the king stranded on e1 forever.}) 13... f5 {l'Ami,Erwin: '!' l'Ami,Erwin: 'This is not the time to play it slow. If White is allowed to castle, he will be clearly better.'} 14. e5 {l'Ami,Erwin: 'Keeping the position closed, which is the desirable thing to do with the king stuck on e1. With his last move, White gives up the d5-square, which Wei Yi immediately puts to use.'} Nd5 15. Bd2 Nxe5 ({The text move is stronger than} 15... Qb8 16. Bb5 Bxe5 (16... Nxe5 17. Nxd4 Bf7 18. O-O $14 {[%csl Gg1] , safeguarding the king.}) 17. O-O Bf7 18. Bxc6 Bd6 $1 (18... bxc6 $6 19. Nxe5 Qxe5 20. Rxc6 f4 21. Qd3 Re8 22. Re1 Qg5 23. Qxd4 e5 24. Qc5 $18 {Bu,Xiangzhi (2670)-Tomczak,J (2560) Guimaraes 2012}) 19. b4 $14 (19. Bxd5 Bxa3 20. Bxf7+ Kxf7 21. bxa3 e5 22. Rc5 $14)) 16. Nxd4 (16. Ng5 $5 {could be an interesting area to investigate, with the idea of following up with f2-f4 and Bc4. In my view though, Black should have enough activity in all of these lines.}) 16... Bf7 17. Be2 Nb6 {l'Ami,Erwin: '!' l'Ami,Erwin: 'Referring to my comment on move 13, White can't be allowed to rest.'} ({Again concrete play, after} 17... Rd8 18. Nf3 Nxf3+ 19. Bxf3 e5 20. O-O e4 21. Be2 Qb8 22. Rfd1 Be5 23. h3 Bh2+ 24. Kh1 Nf4 25. Bf1 Nd3 26. Bxd3 Rxd3 27. Bc3 $16 {Khismatullin,D (2656)-Popov,I (2653) ECC Rhodes 2013 White has consolidated his slight material advantage.}) 18. b3 (18. Qh3 Nec4 (18... Rd8 $142 $1 19. Bc3 Nd5 $44 {[%csl Gd5,Ge5]}) 19. Bc3 Na4 20. Nxf5 $1 Nxc3 21. Rxc3 Bxc3+ 22. Qxc3 gxf5 23. Bxc4 Qc8 24. Qg3+ Kh8 25. Qe5+ Kg8 26. Bxf7+ Kxf7 27. O-O $14 {[%csl Rf7,Gg1] Wagner,D (2481)-Seger,R (2374) Bundesliga 2014 Material is equal again, but White with his safer king has a long-term advantage.}) (18. O-O Nec4 $1 {was the point behind the previous move.}) 18... Qd8 $5 {l'Ami,Erwin: 'Stohl,I: '!?''} (18... Rd8 19. Nf3 $14 {and in a few moves White finally manages to castle...}) 19. Nf3 {l'Ami,Erwin: 'Diagram [#] Needless to say, the players were still banging out their moves here. Welcome to modern chess, ladies and gentlemen!' White should strive for simplification. l'Ami,Erwin: 'Stohl,I: 'White should strive for simplification.''} (19. Bc3 Nd5 $36 {can be unpleasant}) 19... Nd3+ ({This move was also played quickly; the players are still following the game Svidler-Sutovsky from which Navara is about to deviate. I believe Black has an interesting alternative in} 19... Nxf3+ $5 20. Bxf3 Bd5 $1 {and it's not so easy for White to respond. For instance:} 21. Bc3 (21. Qxa7 {is the computer suggestion, but} Rf6 22. Bg5 Re6+ 23. Kf1 Qd6 $5 {leaves White in a difficult spot. It would go beyond the scope of my tournament report to go into further detail here, but the main threat is to take on f3 and trap the bishop with f5-f4.}) (21. O-O Bxf3 22. gxf3 Qxd2 $1) 21... Bxf3 22. Bxg7 Kxg7 23. gxf3 Nd5 {and I think the open king and ruined pawn structure don't give White much reason for optimism.}) 20. Bxd3 Qxd3 21. Qxa7 {l'Ami,Erwin: 'Not only taking the pawn on a7 but also destabilizing the knight. Going into this type of computer-like preparation is typical for David Navara. Personally, I would think twice before entering this position.'} Bb2 ({l'Ami,Erwin: 'Investing yet more material to keep the white king centralized. I'm curious what David had planned after' An untested computer line is} 21... Nd5 {l'Ami,Erwin: 'since the following line seems more or less forced'} 22. Qc5 e5 $5 (22... Qe4+ 23. Kf1 Bb2 24. Re1 Qd3+ 25. Kg1 e5 $1 {with a very double-edged position. At least the engine's main line} 26. Qc4 (26. Bh6 $5) 26... Nf4 27. Qxd3 Nxd3 28. Rb1 Rc8 29. Ne1 Nxe1 30. Bxe1 Rc2 {is far from convincing. With the bishop coming to d4 I'd take black here!}) (22... Bb2 23. Qc2 $1 {hence the check on e4.}) 23. Qc2 Qa6 24. Ng5 Nf4 25. Bxf4 exf4 26. Nxf7 Re8+ 27. Kd1 Bc3 $1 28. Rb1 Qa5 29. Nd6 Rd8 30. Ke2 (30. Qd3 Qe5 31. Qc4+ Kh8 32. Kc2 Rxd6 33. Rhd1 Rc6 34. Rd5 Qe7 35. Kxc3 Rxc4+ 36. bxc4 Kg7 $132) 30... Qe5+ 31. Kf1 Rxd6 32. Qe2 (32. Rd1 Re6 33. Qc1 Qe2+ 34. Kg1 Bd2 35. Qa1 Bc3 $11) 32... Rd2 33. Qxe5 Bxe5 $44 {and White has hardly more than} 34. Re1 Bd4 35. Re2 Rd1+ 36. Re1 Rd2 $11) (21... Rc8 22. Qxb6 Rxc1+ 23. Bxc1 Bc3+ 24. Bd2 Qb1+ 25. Ke2 Bc4+ 26. bxc4 Qxb6 27. Bxc3 $14) 22. Qxb6 $8 {l'Ami,Erwin: 'Stohl,I: ''' Practically forced l'Ami,Erwin: 'Stohl,I: 'Practically forced''} (22. Rd1 Nd5 $36 {can be dangerous only for White.}) 22... Bxc1 23. Bxc1 Rd8 24. Nd2 Rd6 {l'Ami,Erwin: 'Diagram [#]'} 25. Qa7 $5 $146 {[%mdl 8]} ({l'Ami,Erwin: 'Novelty! Yes, you read that correctly, I was as shocked as you are. Svidler chose'} 25. Qb4 Bd5 26. f3 {l'Ami,Erwin: 'when'} Qe3+ $1 (26... Re6+ 27. Kd1 Re2 28. Bb2 Rxg2 29. Kc1 Bxf3 30. Re1 Rxh2 31. Bc3 $36 {Svidler,P (2740)-Sutovsky,E (2657) ECC Rhodes 2013 Here Black also has 3 pawns for the knight, but White's forces are better coordinated and his extra piece starts to tell.}) 27. Kd1 (27. Kf1 $2 Re6 $19) 27... Bxf3+ $1 {l'Ami,Erwin: 'would have been fine for Black. From a7 the queen does a good job covering the e3-square and can sometimes create counterchances on the eighth rank in combination with the bishop coming to the a1-h8 diagonal.'} 28. Kc2 Bxg2 29. Rd1 f4 $44 {is a line given by Krasenkow in CBM 157.} (29... Kf8 $5 $11)) 25... Bd5 {[%csl Re1] Of course, Black must keep e1 trapped! l'Ami,Erwin: 'Stohl,I: 'Of course, Black must keep e1 trapped!''} (25... Qc2 $2 26. O-O $18) (25... Re6+ $2 26. Kd1 $18) 26. f3 Re6+ ({Navara in his preparation concentrated on} 26... Rc6 $1 27. Kd1 (27. Nc4 Bxc4 28. bxc4 Qxc4 29. Kf2 Qh4+ {just barely scrapes a draw after} 30. Ke2 $11 (30. g3 $6 Rc2+ 31. Ke3 Qb4 $1 32. Qb8+ Kf7 33. Qe5 Rc3+ 34. Kf2 Rxc1 35. Rxc1 Qd2+ $17)) (27. Qa3 Re6+ 28. Kd1 Re2 {gives Black plenty of play. It is important that the white queen is on a3 in this line, and not on a7, as we will see later.}) 27... Rxc1+ 28. Kxc1 Qc3+ 29. Kb1 ({l'Ami,Erwin: 'or'} 29. Kd1 Qa1+ 30. Kc2 Qxh1 31. Qc5 e6 {and White has only a perpetual after} 32. Qe7) 29... Qd3+ 30. Kb2 Qxd2+ 31. Ka3 {and Black can force a perpetual with} Bxf3 $5 (31... Qxg2 $11 {is also playable}) 32. gxf3 Qd6+ 33. Ka4 (33. b4 Qd3+ 34. Ka4 b5+ 35. Ka5 Qa3+ 36. Kb6 Qe3+ $11) 33... Qd7+ 34. Kb4 (34. Ka5 Qd2+ 35. Kb6) 34... Qd2+ 35. Kb5 Qd3+ $11 36. Kb6 $6 (36. Kb4) 36... Qe3+ 37. Kxb7 Qxf3+ $15 {Some novelties objectively don't win, but 25.a7!? promised White good practical chances - Wei Yi was down to 17 minutes, while David started thinking only now.} 38. Kb6 Qxh1 {could be pushing it too hard for White. Black's f-pawn is already far advanced.}) 27. Kd1 $8 {l'Ami,Erwin: 'Stohl,I: '''} (27. Kf2 $2 Re2+ 28. Kg1 (28. Kg3 $2 f4+ $1 $18 {mates}) 28... Re1+ $19) 27... Ra6 (27... Rc6 $142 $1 $11 {[%cal Rc6c1] l'Ami,Erwin: '!?' l'Ami,Erwin: 'was possible again, setting up the same drawing mechanism. Surprisingly, even with an extra tempo (Kd1) White is unable to prevent the draw!' and despite the extra tempo it's surprisingly difficult to meet the main threat. After} 28. Rf1 Ra6 29. Qc5 Rxa2 30. Qxe7 h5 $5 (30... Rxd2+ $2 31. Bxd2 Qxf1+ 32. Kc2 $40 {[%cal Re7d8,Rd2c3,Rc3b4]}) {it's difficult to see how White should untangle his forces:} 31. Qg5 Rxd2+ 32. Bxd2 Qxf1+ 33. Kc2 Kf7 $11) ({With the queen on a7 the move} 27... Re2 {doesn't work:} 28. Qb8+ Kf7 29. Qg3 $1 {followed by Re1.}) 28. Qc5 (28. Qb8+ Kf7 29. Qe5 Rxa2 30. Bb2 Bxb3+ 31. Ke1 Qc2 {forces} 32. Qg7+ Ke8 33. Qh8+ Kd7 34. Qd4+ Ke8 $11 (34... Kc8 35. Bc3 $1 (35. Qc3+ $2 Qxc3 36. Bxc3 Rc2 $17) 35... Qd1+ 36. Kf2 Qxh1 37. Qc5+ $40)) 28... Rxa2 (28... Rc6 $2 29. Qb4 $1 $16) 29. Qxe7 {l'Ami,Erwin: 'Diagram [#]'} Bxb3+ ({With engines becoming stronger and stronger it becomes increasingly difficult to get the point of why they are spitting out certain moves with certain evaluations. This is a beautiful example. Here, apparently,} 29... h5 $3 {is the move. I could try to explain it, or pretend to get the point, but honestly I don't.}) 30. Ke1 Bf7 $2 ({Both players saw} 30... Rc2 $2 31. Qe8+ Kg7 32. Bb2+ $1 $16) ({l'Ami,Erwin: 'The first real mistake of the game. Instead' Wei Yi discarded l'Ami,Erwin: 'Stohl,I: 'Wei Yi discarded''} 30... Qd4 $142 $1 {l'Ami,Erwin: '!' l'Ami,Erwin: 'Stohl,I: '!'' due to l'Ami,Erwin: 'Stohl,I: 'due to''} 31. f4 (31. Nxb3 Qf2+ 32. Kd1 Qc2+ $11) {, but Black should hold the endgame after l'Ami,Erwin: 'Stohl,I: ', but Black should hold the endgame after''} 31... Bd5 (31... Qxf4 $2 32. Rf1) 32. Qe8+ (32. h4 $5) 32... Kg7 33. Qe5+ Qxe5+ 34. fxe5 Bxg2 35. Rg1 Bd5 $44 {l'Ami,Erwin: 'should be holdable, though slightly unpleasant. Stohl,I: '''}) 31. Kf2 $6 {l'Ami,Erwin: 'Stohl,I: '?!'' Instinctively escaping from the centre. l'Ami,Erwin: 'Stohl,I: 'Instinctively escaping from the centre.''} ({However, Houdini indicates the extremely strong} 31. Qe5 $1 {and now:} Rc2 (31... Ra8 32. Ne4 $1 fxe4 33. Bh6 $18 {[%cal Re5g7]}) 32. Qb8+ Kg7 33. Bb2+ $1 Kh6 (33... Rxb2 34. Qe5+ $18) 34. Qf8+ Kh5 (34... Kg5 35. Ne4+ $1 fxe4 36. Qe7+ Kh5 37. g4+ Kh6 38. Qh4#) 35. Qb4 Bc4 36. Kd1 $18 {Black is in zugzwang, as he has no way to develop his play - bishop moves run into g4+.}) ({David's desire to bring his king to safety couldn't be more natural but perhaps} 31. Qb4 $1 {is even more convincing. It's very hard for Black to up the pressure, and trying to force matters with} Rc2 32. Ba3 Qe3+ 33. Kd1 Rxd2+ 34. Qxd2 Qxa3 35. Qd8+ Kg7 36. Qd4+ Kg8 37. Re1 {just looks lost.}) 31... f4 {l'Ami,Erwin: '!'} ({l'Ami,Erwin: 'The best chance, of course.' A simple enough way is l'Ami,Erwin: 'Stohl,I: 'A simple enough way is''} 31... Rxd2+ 32. Bxd2 Qxd2+ 33. Qe2 {l'Ami,Erwin: 'would make life easy for White.'} Qd4+ 34. Qe3 $16 {/+-}) ({White's task is more difficult after} 31... Rc2 $5 {} 32. Kg3 f4+ 33. Kh3 Qd5 $1 (33... Qf5+ 34. g4 Qc8 35. Bb2 $1 Rxb2 36. Ne4 $40 {Navara}) 34. Re1 Qh5+ 35. Qh4 Qc5 36. Ne4 Qc8+ 37. g4 Rxc1 (37... fxg3+ $2 38. Kxg3 Rxc1 39. Nf6+ Kg7 40. Nh5+ gxh5 41. Qg5+ $18) 38. Qh6 Be6 39. Re2 $1 $36 {White has returned the piece, safeguarded his king and has attacking chances, but the game is still far from over.}) 32. g4 $5 {l'Ami,Erwin: '!' l'Ami,Erwin: 'Stohl,I: '!?''} Qd4+ $6 {l'Ami,Erwin: 'Stohl,I: '?!''} (32... Rc2 $142 {was still better, when Navara intended to play} 33. Qe1 $5 $14 (33. Qe4 Qc3 34. Qxf4 Rxc1 35. Rxc1 Qxc1 36. Qb8+ Kg7 37. Qe5+ Kg8 38. Ne4 h5 $14 {/=})) 33. Kg2 Rxd2+ 34. Bxd2 Qxd2+ 35. Kh3 Qd5 36. Qe4 {[%mdl 4096] The position has finally stabilised. Navara felt that the queen swap leads to an easily won endgame, but the position is still quite tricky. l'Ami,Erwin: 'Stohl,I: 'The position has finally stabilised. Navara felt that the queen swap leads to an easily won endgame, but the position is still quite tricky.''} ({Therefore afterwards he suggested l'Ami,Erwin: 'Stohl,I: 'Therefore afterwards he suggested''} 36. Qe2 $5 {l'Ami,Erwin: 'followed by Rd1 also deserved attention, but David correctly assesses the endgame as being a win.'} h5 37. Rd1 hxg4+ 38. fxg4 $16 {[%csl Rg8] , when White plays for the attack.}) 36... Qxe4 37. fxe4 {[%cal Rg4g5]} g5 $8 {l'Ami,Erwin: 'Stohl,I: '''} 38. Kg2 {Flexible and good. l'Ami,Erwin: 'Stohl,I: 'Flexible and good.''} ({After} 38. Rb1 $6 Bc4 {White has to play} 39. Kg2 {anyway.}) 38... b5 39. h4 h6 {l'Ami,Erwin: 'Diagram [#]'} 40. hxg5 $2 {l'Ami,Erwin: '??' l'Ami,Erwin: 'Stohl,I: '?'' Only the last move before the control allows Black to save the game. l'Ami,Erwin: 'Stohl,I: 'Only the last move before the control allows Black to save the game.''} ({l'Ami,Erwin: 'A huge slip! It was vital to keep the h-pawns on the board. The winning procedure is not that easy but definitely worth studying:' After l'Ami,Erwin: 'Stohl,I: 'After''} 40. Ra1 $1 $16 {l'Ami,Erwin: '!' l'Ami,Erwin: 'and now: Stohl,I: '!'' Black has extra problems with the weakness on h6, the players analysed l'Ami,Erwin: 'Stohl,I: 'Black has extra problems with the weakness on h6, the players analysed''} Kg7 (40... Bc4 41. Ra6 Kg7) (40... Be6 41. Kf3 Bb3 {is an interesting defense, trying to meet a rook lift with Bd1+. With a series of precise moves White should nevertheless win;} 42. Rb1 Bc4 43. Rd1 b4 44. Rd4 Bb3 45. hxg5 hxg5 46. Rxb4 Bd1+ 47. Kf2 Kg7 (47... Bxg4 48. Rb5 $1) 48. Rb1 Bc2 49. Rb7+ Kg6 50. e5 Bd1 51. Rb6+ Kg7 52. Rb1 Bxg4 53. Rg1 {and wins.}) (40... b4 $2 41. hxg5 hxg5 42. Ra5 {loses the g-pawn and the game.}) 41. Ra5 Bc4 42. Ra7+ Kf6 (42... Kg8 43. hxg5 $1 {Now it's time to take and go after the g-pawn.} hxg5 44. Rb7 (44. Kf3 Bb3 $5) 44... Be2 45. Kf2 Bxg4 46. Rxb5 {with an easy technical win. l'Ami,Erwin: '!'}) 43. h5 $1 {[%csl Rh6]} Bd3 (43... Be2 44. Rh7 Bxg4 45. Rxh6+ {l'Ami,Erwin: 'is a line that illustrates why it was important to keep the h-pawns.'} Ke7 (45... Ke5 46. Rg6 $18) 46. e5 $18) 44. Kf3 b4 45. Rh7 Ke5 46. Rxh6 Bxe4+ 47. Ke2 Kd4 {[%cal Rd4c3]} 48. Kd2 $1 $18 {The only winning move, overlooked from the distance by Navara. Preventing c3 stops Black's counterplay and decides the game.}) 40... hxg5 41. Rh6 Kg7 ({Good enough, but Black had also} 41... b4 $5 42. Rb6 b3 43. Rb5 Bc4 44. Rxg5+ Kf7 45. Rc5 Bd3 $11) 42. Rb6 Bc4 {l'Ami,Erwin: 'The difference with the above lines now becomes obvious. White has no way to push the black king to the last rank. David tries a few more moves but eventually has to agree to a draw. There is simply no way through.'} 43. Kf3 ({The attempt to force zugzwang with} 43. Kf2 $5 Kf7 44. Kf3 {is insufficient due to} Bd3 45. e5 b4 46. Rxb4 Ke6 47. Rb3 Bc4 48. Rb6+ Kxe5 49. Rg6 Bd5+ 50. Kf2 Be6 $1 $11) 43... Kf7 44. Rd6 (44. e5 Bd5+ 45. Kf2 b4 $5 (45... Be6 46. Rxb5 Bxg4 $11) 46. Rxb4 Ke6 47. Rb6+ Kxe5 {transposes to the previous note.}) 44... Be6 45. Rb6 Bc4 46. Kf2 Bd3 47. e5 Bc4 (47... b4 $5 48. Rxb4 Ke6 $11) 48. Rf6+ {l'Ami,Erwin: 'Diagram [#]'} Ke7 {l'Ami,Erwin: '!'} ({No need to fear ghosts. The threat is now Be6! Instead} 48... Kg7 49. Kf3 b4 50. Ke4 {looks a bit scary.}) 49. Rb6 (49. Rg6 b4 50. Rxg5 b3 {and White can stop the passed pawn only with} 51. Rg6 Be6 52. Rg7+ Bf7 53. e6 Kxe6 54. Rg5 Kd6 55. Rf5 Bc4 $11) (49. Kf3 Be6 $1) 49... Kf7 50. Kg2 Ke7 51. Kf3 Bd5+ 52. Ke2 b4 $1 {l'Ami,Erwin: 'Forcing a transition to a drawn endgame on one wing. Stohl,I: '!'' Wei Yi precisely calculates the aforementioned liquidation. l'Ami,Erwin: 'Stohl,I: 'Wei Yi precisely calculates the aforementioned liquidation.''} 53. Rxb4 Ke6 54. Kd3 (54. Rb6+ Kxe5 55. Rg6 Be6 $11) 54... Kxe5 55. Rb5 Ke6 56. Kd4 Bf3 57. Rxg5 Kf6 58. Rf5+ Kg6 59. Rxf4 Bd1 $11 {[%csl Rg4][%cal Rg6g5] l'Ami,Erwin: 'Stohl,I: '=''} 60. Ke5 Kg5 61. Rf1 Bxg4 62. Rg1 Kh5 63. Kf4 Be6 64. Rg5+ Kh6 (64... Kh4 $4 65. Rg6 $18) 65. Rf5 {Black's king is in the good corner and Navara decided not to test his opponent anymore. l'Ami,Erwin: 'Stohl,I: 'Black's king is in the good corner and Navara decided not to test his opponent anymore.''} Bxf5 66. Kxf5 {l'Ami,Erwin: 'I thought both players were very impressive this game. Sometimes a draw is a fair result!'} 1/2-1/2


