{Stamenkovic,Zoran: 'In this new column for CEWN I will try to find the most interesting games by strong junior players. Today I decided to comment on one from the 15-year old Chinese Wei Yi who helped his team, the current Olympic champions, to beat Armenia 3,5-0,5!'} 1. e4 {Stamenkovic,Zoran Stamenkovic,Zoran Kuzmin,Alexey Stamenkovic,Zoran Szabo,Kr Szabo,Kr Stamenkovic,Zoran Kuzmin,Alexey Stamenkovic,Zoran Szabo,Kr} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 {Stamenkovic,Zoran: 'The four knights is often employed by Wei Yi along with the Italian game.'} Bb4 (4... Nd4 {(Stamenkovic,Zoran) is my favorite move.}) (4... Bc5 {Stamenkovic,Zoran} 5. Nxe5 Nxe5 6. d4 a6 {!? is an interesting new option, Wei Yi-Eljanov 2014.}) 5. O-O O-O 6. d3 d6 7. Ne2 {Szabo,Kr: 'A new and fashionable move.' Kuzmin,Alexey: '!?' Stamenkovic,Zoran: 'A new, fashionable and very logical move. The big theory is' A new and fashionable move. Stamenkovic,Zoran: 'Szabo,Kr: 'A new and fashionable move.''} (7. Bg5 {Szabo,Kr: 'is the real main line.' is the real main line.} Bxc3 {Stamenkovic,Zoran} 8. bxc3 Qe7 9. Re1 Nd8 10. d4 Ne6 {with still more than 500 games played.}) 7... Ne7 8. c3 Ba5 9. Ng3 c6 ({Szabo,Kr: '3 days later Mamedyarov played' 3 days later Mamedyarov played} 9... Ng6 {Stamenkovic,Zoran: 'Szabo,Kr'} 10. d4 Bb6 11. Re1 c6 12. Bd3 Re8 13. h3 h6 14. Be3 Be6 15. Qc2 Qc7 16. a3 a5 17. c4 a4 18. Red1 exd4 19. Bxd4 Ne5 $11 {Szabo,Kr: 'with an approximately equal position, although later White managed to win, Anand-Mamedyarov, Shamkir 2015.' with an approximately equal position, although later White managed to win, Anand-Mamedyarov, Shamkir 2015.}) 10. Ba4 Ng6 11. d4 {Szabo,Kr: 'The most natural move, White gains the centre. Black will develop his pieces before going for the counterbreak with d5.' Stamenkovic,Zoran: 'Normal play for the center. Melkumyan will develop his pieces before going for the counterbreak with d5.' The most natural move, White gains the centre. Black will develop his pieces before going for the counterbreak with d5. Stamenkovic,Zoran: 'Szabo,Kr: 'The most natural move, White gains the centre. Black will develop his pieces before going for the counterbreak with d5.''} Re8 {Stamenkovic,Zoran: '[#]'} ({The attemp to open the centre immediately with} 11... d5 {Kuzmin,Alexey Stamenkovic,Zoran: 'is a very decent try.' was used even in the XIXth century! White's chances are slightly preferable:} 12. Nxe5 ({I think that the modern way} 12. Bg5 $5 {isn't bad either.} h6 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. dxe5 Nxe5 15. Nxe5 Qxe5 16. exd5 Qxd5 17. Qxd5 cxd5 18. Rfd1 $14) 12... Nxe5 (12... Nxe4 13. Nxe4 (13. Nxg6 {Stamenkovic,Zoran} hxg6 14. Nxe4) 13... dxe4 14. Nxg6 hxg6 {Lipke,P-Pillsbury,H Vienna 1898.} 15. Re1 $14 Re8 {Stamenkovic,Zoran} 16. Bf4 {⩲}) 13. dxe5 Nxe4 14. Nxe4 dxe4 15. Bf4 $14 {Maroczy,G-Leonhardt,P San Sebastian 1911. Stamenkovic,Zoran: 'I am still not sure that Black can fully equalize here.'}) 12. Bc2 h6 {Kuzmin,Alexey: 'The symmetrical plan with ...e8, ...h6 and ...e6 looks solid. But it doesn't promise equal chances, because White has a space advantage: d4-pawn against d6-pawn.'} (12... d5 $6 {Kuzmin,Alexey isn't good. After} 13. Bg5 $36 {Black is in troubles. For instance} exd4 14. Nxd4 h6 15. Bxf6 Qxf6 16. exd5 cxd5 17. Bxg6 ({or} 17. Nh5 Qd6 18. Bxg6 fxg6 19. Qa4 $14) 17... fxg6 18. Qa4 Qd8 19. Qb3 $14) 13. h3 ({White can begin with} 13. Be3 {Kuzmin,Alexey , because} Ng4 {doesn't seriously disturb him:} 14. Bd2 c5 15. Ba4 Bd7 16. Bxd7 Qxd7 17. d5 $14 {Artemiev-Pashikian, Lake Sevan, 2016, The space advantage and the black pawns fixed on dark squares promise better chances for White.}) 13... Be6 (13... Bb6 {(Stamenkovic,Zoran) - 93/259}) ({Again} 13... d5 $6 {Kuzmin,Alexey is too early:} 14. Nxe5 $1 Nxe5 15. dxe5 Nxe4 16. Nxe4 (16. Qh5 $5) 16... dxe4 17. Qh5 $1 (17. Bf4 {Popov,I-Demchenko,A New Delhi 2016}) 17... g6 18. Qxh6 Rxe5 19. Rd1 $14) 14. Re1 {Kuzmin,Alexey: ''} (14. Be3 $5 {Kuzmin,Alexey is possible too. The moves e3 and e1 are s