{David Cummings: 'En route to a dominant tournament victory in Danzhou, Wang Yue faced the 16-year old emerging superstar Wei Yi in the 3rd round. This was the day after Wei Yi had beaten Bruzon in a brilliant king-hunt which has already been dubbed the Game of the Century. Using an original move order in the Pseudo-Grunfeld, Wang Yue managed to steer the game into a queenless middlegame where he was in his element. From there he confidently outplayed his young opponent.'} {Fischer,Johannes: 'David Cummings: 'The game started with the common move order '' Fischer,Johannes: 'Tadic,Branko: 'David Cummings: 'The game started with the common move order'''} 1. Nf3 (1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. cxd5 Nxd5 4. Nf3 {1-0 (43) Wang Yue-Wei Yi 35: Danzhou 2015 OR: The English [David Cummings]}) 1... Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 {Fischer,Johannes: 'David Cummings: '.'' Fischer,Johannes: 'Tadic,Branko: 'David Cummings: '.'''} 5. h4 {David Cummings: 'At first sight, this looks like an aggressive attempt to blow Black out of the water, but Wang Yue has a more subtle plan in mind.'} ({Fischer,Johannes: 'To understand the course of the game, it is necessary to review the line with an immediate' David Cummings: 'To understand the course of the game, it is necessary to review the line with an immediate'} 5. e4 Nxc3 6. dxc3 Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 {which was pioneered by Ulf Andersson in the late 70s and early 80s. In this position Fischer,Johannes: 'which was pioneered by Ulf Andersson in the late 70s and early 80s. In this position' David Cummings: 'which was pioneered by Ulf Andersson in the late 70s and early 80s. In this position'} Bg7 {is regarded as inferior or even an outright mistake! See the game Batchuluun-Li Chao in the archives for further details.} ({The best response for Black here is} 7... f6 $1 {when the game Kekelidze-Robson World Open Philadelphia, 2012 showed Black's idea of trading the dark squared bishops with Fischer,Johannes: ', with the idea of trading the dark-squared bishops, is the best response for Black, for example' David Cummings: ', with the idea of trading the dark-squared bishops, is the best response for Black, for example'} 8. Be3 e5 9. Kc2 Nd7 10. Nd2 Bc5 {- see the notes on this game in the PGN archive for more background on this line. Fischer,Johannes: 'and Black is fine.'})) 5... Bg7 {* Fischer,Johannes: 'Tadic,Branko: '*''} ({Fischer,Johannes: 'Alternatives are: '} 5... h6 6. d3 {was played in another recent game of Wang Yue:} (6. e4 {Perhaps this is where Wang Yue drew his inspiration from - L'Ami shows the idea of h2-h4 followed by e2-e4 having provoked ...h7-h6 Fischer,Johannes: '. This line is similar to 5 e4, but with h2-h4 and ....h7-h6 inserted. This makes a small but significant difference. Now Black has:' David Cummings: '. This line is similar to 5 e4, but with h2-h4 and ....h7-h6 inserted. This makes a small but significant difference. Now Black has:'} Nxc3 (6... Nb6 {gives White a kind of ideal Grünfeld where Black has not challenged White's pawn centre. An example featuring Bent Larsen continued David Cummings: 'gives White a kind of ideal Grünfeld where Black has not challenged White's pawn centre. An example featuring Bent Larsen continued'} 7. d4 Bg7 8. Be3 Bg4 9. Qd2 Bxf3 10. gxf3 e6 11. O-O-O Nc6 12. Bb5 Qf6 13. Qe2 a6 14. Bxc6+ bxc6 15. h5 {and White generated a strong attack in B.Larsen-Z.Franco Ocampos, Buenos Aires 1979.}) 7. dxc3 Qxd1+ 8. Kxd1 {Fischer,Johannes: 'and now:'} Nd7 ({Here} 8... f6 {doesn't make sense because of Fischer,Johannes: 'is much less effective than in the note to White's 5th move, since Black's light squares have been compromised by the combination of 5...h6 and 8...f6. White can continue' David Cummings: 'is much less effective than in the note to White's 5th move, since Black's light squares have been compromised by the combination of 5...h6 and 8...f6. White can continue'} 9. h5 (9. Bc4 e5 10. h5 g5 11. Be3 Nd7 12. Nd2 Bc5 13. Nf1 {and White's light square control gives him a slight advantage. David Cummings: 'and White's light square control gives him a slight advantage.'})) (8... Bg4 9. Kc2 {Fischer,Johannes: 'and practice has seen: '} Bxf3 ({or} 9... Nd7 10. Be3 Bxf3 11. gxf3 e5 12. Bh3 Bd6 {, P.Eljanov-E.Sutovsky, Netanya (blitz) 2009, and now David Cummings: ', P.Eljanov-E.Sutovsky, Netanya  (blitz) 2009, and now'} 13. Rad1 {is a little better for White}) 10. gxf3 h5 11. f4 Nd7 12. f5 {with a slight edge for White was Naiditsch, A (2687)-Ni, H (2657) Wijk aan Zee 2010 1/2-1/2 (52) Fischer,Johannes: 'opening the position for the two bishops gave White a slight edge in A.Naiditsch-Ni Hua, Wijk aan Zee 2010.' David Cummings: 'opening the position for the two bishops gave White a slight edge in A.Naiditsch-Ni Hua, Wijk aan Zee 2010.'}) 9. Bf4 c6 10. Bc4 Bg7 11. Kc2 Nc5 12. Nd2 Be6 13. f3 b6 14. a4 Bxc4 15. Nxc4 O-O-O 16. h5 g5 17. Be5 {and White is better, L'Ami, E (2615)-Negi, P (2621) Wijk aan Zee 2010 1-0 (35) Fischer,Johannes: 'and White is better due to Black's pawn weaknesses, E.l'Ami-P.Negi, Wijk aan Zee 2010. ' David Cummings: 'and White is better due to Black's pawn weaknesses, E.l'Ami-P.Negi, Wijk aan Zee 2010.'}) 6... Bg7 7. Bd2 c5 8. g3 Nc6 9. Bg2 e6 10. O-O b6 11. Nxd5 exd5 12. Bc3 O-O {with equality, Wang, Y (2726)-Zeng, C (2541) China 2015 1/2-1/2 (31)}) ({Fischer,Johannes: 'and'} 5... Nf6 {Fischer,Johannes: 'are covered in the next game.' David Cummings: 'are covered in the next game.'} 6. d4 {is featured in Piket-Svidler and Zvjaginsev-Najer in the Archives}) (5... h5 {White can again try the plan with e2-e4 and dxc3, although this has hardly been seen in practice. One example: Fischer,Johannes: 'and White can again try the plan with '} 6. e4 Nxc3 7. dxc3 Qxd1+ 8. Kxd1 {Fischer,Johannes: ', for example '} Bg4 9. Kc2 Nd7 10. Be3 (10. Ng5 f6 11. f3 fxg5 12. fxg4 gxh4 13. Rxh4 {with a powerful pin on the h-file, D.Forcen Esteban-R.Perez Garcia, Lorca 2015. David Cummings: 'with a powerful pin on the h-file, D.Forcen Esteban-R.Perez Garcia, Lorca 2015.'}) 10... e5 11. Bc4 Bxf3 12. gxf3 Bc5 {Raineri de Luca, P (2275)-Vila Gazquez, X (2456) Catalunya 2012, 1/ 2-1/2 (53), and here} 13. a4 {is a little better for White}) (5... Nc6 {, and now White can try David Cummings: ', and now White can try'} 6. e4 {, for example} Ndb4 7. d3 Bg4 8. a3 Bxf3 9. gxf3 Na6 10. Be3 Bg7 11. f4 (11. h5 {immediately looks best}) 11... Nd4 12. h5 c6 $6 13. h6 Bf8 14. Qa4 {, and White has the initiative due to Black's stalled development, T.Lei-R.Padmini, Al Ain 2015.}) (5... Nxc3) 6. e4 {David Cummings: 'White's idea is to enter an improved version of the queenless middlegame. Since Black's bishop is committed to the g7-square, the equalizing plan given in the note to White's 5th move is not available.'} (6. h5 {is covered in Vallejo Pons-Safarli and Shimanov-Mchedlisvhvili - see PGN Archives Fischer,Johannes: 'is a major alternative that keeps the queens on the board and leads to a dynamic game, for example ' David Cummings: 'is a major alternative that keeps the queens on the board and leads to a dynamic game, for example'} Nc6 7. g3 Bg4 8. h6 Bxc3 9. dxc3 Qd6 10. Bg2 O-O-O {with chances for both sides, Ding Liren-Wei Yi, FIDE World Cup, Baku 2015.}) 6... Nxc3 $146 {Fischer,Johannes: 'Tadic,Branko: 'N''} ({Fischer,Johannes: 'The knight retreat '} 6... Nb6 {Fischer,Johannes: 'again gives White the centre. After '} 7. d4 Bg4 8. Be3 O-O 9. Qd2 Bxf3 10. gxf3 e5 11. d5 h5 12. Bg5 Qd6 $6 (12... Bf6 13. O-O-O $14 {Fischer,Johannes: 'is slightly better for White'}) 13. Nb5 Qd7 14. Rc1 c6 15. Bh3 {and White is on top, Zhou, J (2652)-Li, C (2619) Danzhou 2010 Fischer,Johannes: 'and White's bishops leap into action, Zhou Jianchao-Li Chao, Danzhou 2010.'}) 7. dxc3 Qxd1+ 8. Kxd1 {Diagram  David Cummings: 'Black has a wide choice here.' Fischer,Johannes: 'Tadic,Branko: 'Diagram [#]''} b6 {David Cummings: 'Black is likely better off not touching his queenside pawns for now, as in the game his weakened structure becomes a target.'} ({Fischer,Johannes: 'Other tries: ' Fischer,Johannes: 'David Cummings: 'Other tries:''} 8... Nd7 {Fischer,Johannes: 'is probably the most solid. Now White can choose:' David Cummings: 'is probably the most solid. Now White can choose:'} 9. Bc4 (9. h5 {is my recommendation, disrupting Black's kingside with the h-pawn. Play could continue David Cummings: 'is my recommendation, disrupting Black's kingside with the h-pawn. Play could continue'} Nc5 ({or} 9... Nf6 10. h6 Bf8 11. Bd3 {and White leads in development}) 10. h6 Bf8 11. e5 {and now:} Bf5 (11... Bg4 12. Be3 Bxf3+ (12... O-O-O+ 13. Kc1 Nd3+ 14. Kc2 Bf5 15. Kb3 $5 Be6+ 16. c4 {and White is better in this unusual endgame}) 13. gxf3 e6 14. Kc2 Nd7 15. Rd1 Nxe5 16. Bd4 f6 17. Bh3 Bd6 18. f4 Nd7 19. Bxe6 {and White won in Bai Jinshi-Gao,Rui, Shenzhen (rapid) 2016. David Cummings: 'and White won in Bai Jinshi-Gao,Rui, Shenzhen (rapid) 2016.'}) 12. Be3 Nd3 13. Bxd3 Bxd3 14. Ke1 b6 15. Rd1 Rd8 {and now} 16. Rh4 {, activating the h1-rook, gives White an edge here. David Cummings: ', activating the h1-rook, gives White an edge here.'}) 9... Nf6 (9... Nc5 10. Re1 Bd7 {with a solid position}) 10. Re1 Ng4 11. Ke2 Bd7 12. a4 {Fischer,Johannes: ', Ni Hua-Wei Yi, Danzhou 2015 and now ' Fischer,Johannes: 'David Cummings: ', Ni Hua-Wei Yi, Danzhou 2015 and now''} e6 (12... Rf8 {is OK for Black according to Mikhalevski. David Cummings: 'is OK for Black according to Mikhalevski.'}) (12... Z0) 13. h5 O-O-O 14. Rh1 f5 15. Ng5 Rde8 16. hxg6 hxg6 17. Rxh8 Bxh8 18. f3 Ne5 19. Bb3 $14) (8... Bg4 9. Kc2 {and now Black has tried a number of moves:} Nc6 (9... Nd7 10. Be3 {with a further branch:} e5 (10... Nf6 11. Nd2 Be6 12. f3 Nh5 13. Bb5+ c6 14. Bc4 Bxc4 15. Nxc4 f5 16. exf5 Ng3 17. Rhe1 Nxf5 18. Rad1 Bf6 19. Bg5 Bxg5 20. hxg5 Rd8 {, Q.Le-A.Gupta, Asian Championship, Al Ain 2015, and now} 21. Rxd8+ Kxd8 22. Rh1 $1 {and White is clearly better because of Black's weak pawns and passive h8-rook David Cummings: 'and White is clearly better because of Black's weak pawns and passive h8-rook'} (22. Z0)) 11. Bc4 Bxf3 12. gxf3 h5 13. Rad1 Nb6 14. Bb3 Bh6 15. a4 Nc8 $6 16. Rd5 f6 17. Rhd1 Nd6 18. Bc5 O-O-O 19. Bxa7 {with a clear extra pawn for White, B.Adhiban-A.Puranik, Doha 2015.}) (9... Bxf3 10. gxf3 Nd7 11. h5 O-O-O 12. Be3 a6 13. a4 Bf6 14. f4 e5 $6 15. fxe5 Nxe5 16. f4 Ng4 17. Bc5 Bg7 18. e5 Kb8 19. Be2 {and White's rampant bishops give him a great position, B.Deac-E.Karavade, Zalakaros 2016. David Cummings: 'and White's rampant bishops give him a great position, B.Deac-E.Karavade, Zalakaros 2016.'}) 10. Be3 Ne5 11. Nxe5 Bxe5 12. Bb5+ c6 13. Bc4 h5 14. f3 Be6 15. Bxe6 fxe6 16. Rad1 Bd6 17. Rd3 e5 18. c4 c5 19. Rd5 {with a big advantage for White, since the d6-bishop is just a big pawn in this position, Bai Jinshi-M.Turov, Graz 2016. David Cummings: 'with a big advantage for White, since the d6-bishop is just a big pawn in this position, Bai Jinshi-M.Turov, Graz 2016.'}) 9. Bf4 Bb7 10. Bb5+ {David Cummings: '!' David Cummings: 'White provokes Black's next.'} c6 {David Cummings: 'This loosens Black's queenside structure and also blocks his b7-bishop for now.'} ({Fischer,Johannes: 'The alternative was'} 10... Nd7 11. Ne5 Bxe5 12. Bxe5 f6 13. Bxc7 Bxe4 14. f3 {when White's two bishops give him the better game Fischer,Johannes: ', when White's two bishops give him the better game.' David Cummings: ', when White's two bishops give him the better game.'}) 11. Be2 (11. Bc4 {is more active Fischer,Johannes: 'is more active, although Wang Yue repeated 11 Be2 in a later game.' David Cummings: 'is more active, although Wang Yue repeated 11 Be2 in a later game.'}) 11... Nd7 ({Instead,} 11... Ba6 $6 12. a4 (12. h5 {also looks good}) 12... O-O 13. a5 Rd8+ 14. Nd2 Bxe2+ 15. Kxe2 Nd7 16. Rhd1 Be5 17. Be3 Bc7 18. Nb3 {and White retained his slight pull, Wang Yue-P.Maghsoodloo, Abu Dhabi 2016.}) 12. Kc2 e5 13. Be3 c5 14. Nd2 f5 15. f3 Nf6 16. Bd3 O-O 17. a4 {David Cummings: 'White initiates a typical pawn lever against Black's queenside structure. White stands slightly better.' Fischer,Johannes: 'The queens are off the board but White manages to keep Black under pressure and plays on both wings.'} ({David Cummings: 'Wang Yue didn't want to be drawn into lines such as ' David Cummings: 'Wang Yue didn't want to be drawn into lines such as' Fischer,Johannes: 'Tadic,Branko: 'Wang Yue didn't want to be drawn into lines such as'' After} 17. exf5 {Black plays} Nd5 {David Cummings: 'etc.' Fischer,Johannes: 'Tadic,Branko: 'etc.''}) 17... Rac8 18. a5 b5 {David Cummings: '?!' David Cummings: 'Further loosening his queenside. Perhaps Black wanted to provoke complications, but White is well placed to meet them.'} (18... Rc7 {looks better Fischer,Johannes: 'looks better.'}) 19. a6 $16 {Fischer,Johannes: 'Tadic,Branko: '''} Ba8 20. Bxb5 ({Fischer,Johannes: 'Instead, '} 20. exf5 c4 21. Be4 Nxe4 22. Nxe4 gxf5 23. Nd6 {also gives White a clear advantage Fischer,Johannes: 'also gives White a clear advantage.' David Cummings: 'also gives White a clear advantage.'}) 20... fxe4 21. Bc4+ Kh8 22. h5 {the h4-pawn finally sees some more action! David Cummings: 'The h4-pawn finally sees some more action!' Fischer,Johannes: 'Tadic,Branko: 'The h4-pawn finally sees some more action!''} ({Fischer,Johannes: 'In any case,'} 22. Ra5 {without sacrificing the h-pawn, was also very strong. Fischer,Johannes: ', without sacrificing the h-pawn, was also very strong.' David Cummings: ', without sacrificing the h-pawn, was also very strong.'}) 22... exf3 23. gxf3 gxh5 24. Rh4 $6 {Fischer,Johannes: 'Tadic,Branko: '?!''} ({Fischer,Johannes: 'Komodo prefers to set its sight on the queenside and wants to play'} 24. Ra5 {was more clear cut, targeting the c5-pawn Fischer,Johannes: 'David Cummings: 'was more clear cut, targeting the c5-pawn.'' Fischer,Johannes: 'Tadic,Branko: 'was more clear cut, targeting the c5-pawn.'' Fischer,Johannes: 'here - with a clear advantage for White. After the textmove Black comes close to equality again.'}) 24... Rfe8 $6 {Fischer,Johannes: 'Tadic,Branko: '?!''} (24... Nd5 {followed by trading one of the bishops, would have limited White's advantage Fischer,Johannes: 'followed by trading one of the bishops, would have limited White's advantage.'}) 25. Ne4 Nxe4 26. fxe4 Bf6 27. Rxh5 Bxe4+ 28. Bd3 Bxd3+ 29. Kxd3 {Fischer,Johannes: 'Black is a pawn up but all his pawns are weak and White's king is much more active than Black's. Komodo here recommends'} Re6 ({Black is a pawn up but all his pawns are weak and White's king is much more active than Black's. Komodo here recommends} 29... c4+ 30. Ke4 Re7 31. Rh6 Rf7 32. Rf1 $14) 30. Kc4 Rcc6 $6 {The rooks are awkwardly placed here, and allows White to demonstrate a remarkable idea David Cummings: 'The rooks are awkwardly placed here, and allows White to demonstrate a remarkable idea.' Fischer,Johannes: 'Tadic,Branko: 'The rooks are awkwardly placed here, and allows White to demonstrate a remarkable idea.'' Fischer,Johannes: 'Now Black gets into trouble.'} ({Fischer,Johannes: 'Instead '} 30... Rc7 31. Bxc5 e4 32. Kd5 Re8 {gave better chances for counterplay Fischer,Johannes: 'gave better chances for counterplay.' David Cummings: 'gave better chances for counterplay.'}) 31. Bxc5 Be7 (31... Rxa6 {is answered by} 32. Rah1 {Fischer,Johannes: 'winning the h7-pawn.'}) 32. b4 Bxc5 33. bxc5 e4 34. Kd5 $1 {An extraordinary "King fork" motif! David Cummings: 'An extraordinary 'King fork' motif!' Fischer,Johannes: 'Tadic,Branko: 'An extraordinary 'King fork' motif!'' Fischer,Johannes: 'White's king has the two black rooks well under control.'} e3 35. Rh3 $1 {White chases down the e-pawn, which cannot be saved. If a pair of rooks is traded, White's advanced c-pawn and active King give him a winning position in the resulting single rook endgames. Fischer,Johannes: 'Tadic,Branko: '!' Tadic,Branko: 'White chases down the e-pawn, which cannot be saved. If a pair of rooks is traded, White's advanced c-pawn and active King give him a winning position in the resulting single rook endgames.''} e2 36. Rh2 Rg6 37. Rxe2 Rc8 38. Re5 (38. Rae1 {followed by exchanging a pair of rooks, also wins Fischer,Johannes: 'followed by exchanging a pair of rooks, also wins.' David Cummings: 'followed by exchanging a pair of rooks, also wins.'}) 38... Rd8+ 39. Kc4 Rg4+ 40. Kb5 Rb8+ 41. Kc6 Rg6+ 42. Kc7 Rb3 {Black has run out of checks, and now White activates his a1-rook with decisive effect David Cummings: 'Black has run out of checks, and now White activates his a1-rook with decisive effect.' Fischer,Johannes: 'Tadic,Branko: 'Black has run out of checks, and now White activates his a1-rook with decisive effect.''} 43. Rd1 {1-0 (43) Wang Yue (2716)-Wei Yi (2724) Danzhou CHN 2015 [David Cummings] Fischer,Johannes: 'Tadic,Branko: '1-0 (43) Wang Yue-Wei Yi 35: Danzhou 2015 OR: The English [David Cummings]''} *


