1. c4 c5 (1... Nf6 2. Nc3 c5 {1-0 (16) Ganguly,S (2638)-Wei Yi (2737) Changsha CHN 2019 [David Cummings]}) 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 e6 6. g3 Qb6 {David Cummings: 'This line has a good theoretical reputation for Black, but gives him a bigger burden in preparation. White has many alternatives over the next few moves, including several sharp ideas. This game shows that this can be a challenge even for 2700+ players. We Yi goes wrong very early on, and Ganguly wins a miniature with great preparation and great calculation.'} 7. Ndb5 {David Cummings: 'We have also looked at:'} (7. Nb3 {(the old main line) and now} Ne5 8. e4 Bb4 9. c5 $5 {is Bruzon Batista-Swiercz in the Archives}) (7. Nf3 {- see Harikrishna-Vachier-Lagrave}) (7. Nc2 {- see Dubov-Gabrielian}) 7... Ne5 8. Bg2 (8. Bf4 {is another major branch, see Topalov-Caruana and earlier games in the Archives}) 8... a6 9. Qa4 {David Cummings: 'Alternatives, both involving a sac of the c-pawn, are:'} (9. Na4 Qd8 10. Nbc3 Nxc4 11. b3 {see Navara-So in the Archives}) (9. Na3 Bxa3 10. bxa3 Nxc4 11. O-O {is Howell-Jumabayev, also in the Archives}) 9... Bc5 {David Cummings: '?' David Cummings: 'It turns out this active, developing move is just a mistake, although in 10 previous games White had not punished it. The mainline is:'} (9... Rb8 {- 136/18} 10. Na3 (10. Be3 {can be found in Harikrishna-Grischuk in the Archives}) 10... Bxa3 11. Qxa3 Nxc4 12. Qb3 {which is another variation on the c4-sac theme in Matlakov-Rambaldi, also in the Archives}) 10. Bf4 $1 {Diagram [#] Diagram [#] David Cummings: 'Giving up the f2-pawn looks scary, but the tactics all work out for White. Most earlier games had seen:' Diagram [#] Diagram [#] David Cummings: 'Giving up the f2-pawn looks scary, but the tactics all work out for White. Most earlier games had seen:' Diagram } (10. O-O {- 48/44 - 48/44 David Cummings: 'but this is nothing special for White, for example'} Nxc4 11. Qxc4 axb5 12. Qxb5 Qxb5 13. Nxb5 {Serper,G (2541)-Rodriguez Vila,A (2500) Reno 1999 1/2-1/2 (17), and now} O-O {is about equal.}) 10... Bxf2+ $2 $146 {David Cummings: 'Instead:'} (10... Nfg4 {David Cummings: 'and now:'} 11. O-O-O {David Cummings: '?!' '?!'} (11. h3 $1 {is an important move, with some sample lines going} g5 (11... Bxf2+ 12. Kf1 Bxg3 13. c5 Qxc5 14. Ne4 {and White wins material}) 12. Bxg5 Nxf2 (12... Bxf2+ 13. Kf1 Bxg3 {transposes to the main game}) 13. Bf6 Nxh1 14. Bxe5 axb5 15. Qxa8 O-O 16. Bxh1 d6 17. Bf6 {and White emerges from the complications with a clear advantage.}) 11... Rb8 (11... Bxf2 $2 12. Nd6+ Ke7 13. h3 Be3+ 14. Kb1 g5 15. Nf5+ $1 Kf8 (15... exf5 16. Nd5+) 16. Nxe3 Nxe3 17. Bxe5 $18) 12. b4 (12. Na3 f6 {David Cummings: 'is fine for Black. Now'} 13. Ne4 (13. Nc2 $2 Nxf2 14. b4 Nxd1 15. Rxd1 Be7 {left Black well on top in Bang,A (2315)-Fedder,S (2390) Lyngby 1989 0-1 (26)}) 13... Nxf2 14. Nxf2 Bxf2) 12... Be7 13. c5 $5 axb5 14. Nxb5 Bxc5 (14... Qd8 $2 15. h3 $18 (15. Qa7 $18)) 15. bxc5 (15. h3 $5) 15... Qxc5+ 16. Kb1 O-O $13) (10... axb5 $2 11. Qxa8 O-O 12. Bxe5 Ng4 13. Qb8 {leaves White ahead too much material}) 11. Kf1 $1 Nfg4 (11... Neg4 12. Nc7+ Kd8 13. Nxa8 $18) 12. h3 g5 13. Bxg5 Bxg3 {Diagram [#] Diagram [#] David Cummings: 'transposes to the main game' Diagram [#] Diagram [#] David Cummings: 'transposes to the main game' Diagram } 14. c5 $3 {David Cummings: '!' David Cummings: 'This is a key idea, allowing Nc3-e4 to hit the queen and defend the f2-square.'} Qxc5 15. Ne4 Qg1+ {David Cummings: '!?' David Cummings: 'A nice joke in a lost position.'} (15... Ne3+ 16. Kg1 {David Cummings: 'even wins, since Black has no time to give discovered check'} (16. Bxe3 Qxe3 17. Nxg3 O-O 18. Rg1 {and White is a piece up}) 16... Qb6 17. Nbd6+ Kf8 18. Bh6+ Ke7 19. Nxc8+ Rhxc8 20. Qa3+ d6 21. Bxe3 $18) 16. Kxg1 (16. Rxg1 $4 Nh2# {David Cummings: 'was unlikely to happen!'}) 1-0


