1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5 5. Ng3 Bg6 6. h4 h6 7. Nf3 Nd7 8. h5 Bh7 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 e6 11. Bd2 Ngf6 12. O-O-O Be7 13. Kb1 {Black has been struggling here recently after the usual moves (13...0-0 and 13...Qb6!?) so it's interesting to see a new approach in this game, even though it's ultimately unsuccessful.} a5 $5 {A very logical choice from Antonio - he doesn't want to castle kingside into a big attack so instead he aims to gain space on the queenside and wait to see White's plan} 14. Ne4 a4 $1 15. c4 {I'm not at all convinced by this move as it seems to allow Black good play} (15. Nxf6+ $1 {is the critical test of this line} Nxf6 (15... Bxf6 16. g4 (16. a3 $1 {looks like a safe path to a slight edge, e.g.} Nb6 17. Bf4 Qd5 18. Ne5 O-O 19. Ng4 Bg5 20. Ne3 Qd8 21. Be5 {and White is ready to push on the kingside with g4 and f4.}) 16... Qb6 17. Bc1 Qa6 $1 {and Black had almost equalised in Stopa, J (2470)-Tangborn, E (2455) ICC 2006}) 16. Ne5 $1 Qd5 17. f3 (17. Qg3 $1 {gives Black more problems, for example} a3 18. b3 Rg8 19. Bc1 {and it's not clear where Black's king is going in the long term.}) 17... b5 18. g4 Rd8 19. Rhe1 Nd7 $6 (19... a3 $1 20. b3 Nd7 {is about equal}) 20. Nxc6 $2 (20. Ng6 $1 {was the right way to sacrifice the piece with excellent compensation after} fxg6 21. Qxg6+ Kf8 22. Rxe6 Bh4 23. g5 $1) 20... Qxc6 21. d5 Qc4 22. Qxc4 bxc4 23. Ba5 Ra8 {and White didn't have enough for the piece in Kunal, M (2288)-Lalith, B (2484) New Delhi 2012}) 15... Qb6 $1 {Another useful waiting move keeping the option of castling on either side.} (15... Nxe4 16. Qxe4 a3 17. b3 Nf6 {might equalise for Black although he still should be careful of a quick g4. Play could continue} 18. Qe2 Qd6 19. g4 $5 Nxg4 20. Rhg1 f5 21. Bc1 {and White has excellent compensation for the sacrificed pawn}) 16. g4 $5 {A tricky pawn sacrifice that should probably be accepted. Other moves don't seem to cause Black too many problems as castling kingside should be safe enough} Nxe4 (16... Nxg4 $1 {must also be investigated here. White gets reasonable compensation after} 17. Rhg1 f5 18. Rde1 $1 {but Black may be OK after} O-O $1 ({not} 18... fxe4 $6 19. Qxe4 Nxf2 20. Qe3 {and White will regain the piece with an excellent position}) 19. Ng3 Bf6 20. Rxe6 {and now Black can force a draw with} ({or} 20. Re2 Rf7 {and White has enough compensation for the pawn but no more}) 20... Nc5 $1 21. Qe2 Nxe6 22. Qxe6+ Kh8 23. Nxf5 Rae8 24. Qd7 Rd8 25. Qe6 Rde8) 17. Qxe4 Bf6 18. Bc3 (18. Bf4 $1 {also looks sensible, preparing Ne5 on the next move. I don't see an easy way for Black to equalise here, for example} a3 19. b3 Be7 20. Rhg1 {and Black is running out of moves to avoid castling. Kingside is not a good option with g5 coming but} O-O-O 21. Ne5 Nxe5 22. c5 $1 Qa6 23. Qxe5 Kd7 {is obviously rather awkward for Black if not immediately losing.}) 18... a3 $6 (18... Qa6 $1 {would be my choice here and now White's best chance for an edge is probably} 19. Ne5 {but after} Nb6 $1 (19... Bxe5 $6 20. dxe5 Nb6 21. Qd4 O-O 22. g5 $1 {gives White a fantastic and probably just a winning attack}) 20. f4 Bxe5 21. Qxe5 Qxc4 22. Qxg7 Rf8 23. a3 O-O-O {the position is just very unclear}) 19. b3 O-O-O {Once Black has been forced to castle queenside it seems clear to me that his early queenside aggression hasn't really helped - Wei Yi has control of the centre here and here he prepares to double on the d-file.} 20. Rd2 c5 {A try for counterplay but it doesn't really work - still, it's probably better than just sitting and waiting for White to improve his position further.} 21. Rhd1 Qc7 22. Qe3 cxd4 $6 ({perhaps Black should wait with} 22... Rhe8 {and see what White's plan is. Perhaps the way to improve the position is} 23. Rd3 Kb8 24. Kc2 {preparing dxc5} Rc8 25. Ne5 Nxe5 26. dxe5 Bg5 27. f4 Be7 28. Rd7 Qc6 29. Qe2 {and White is clearly better although Black is still fighting hard for the draw after} Rc7) 23. Bxd4 {Now White is very comfortable.} ({not} 23. Nxd4 $2 Bg5 $1) 23... Qc6 24. Kc1 ({an immediate} 24. g5 $1 {was stronger, e.g.} hxg5 25. Nxg5 Bxg5 (25... e5 26. Bc3 {changes nothing}) 26. Qxg5 e5 27. Be3 {and Black will lose a pawn - the pin on the d-file is a real problem.}) 24... Qc7 25. Kc2 Rhe8 26. g5 $1 {Finally the breakthrough comes} hxg5 27. Nxg5 Bxd4 28. Qxd4 Nf6 29. Qa7 $1 (29. Qxd8+ {also wins a pawn after} Rxd8 30. Rxd8+ Qxd8 31. Rxd8+ Kxd8 32. h6 $1 gxh6 33. Nxf7+ Ke7 34. Nxh6) 29... Rxd2+ 30. Rxd2 Qe5 (30... Qe7 {also fails to} 31. c5 Nd5 ({or} 31... Rd8 32. Rxd8+ Qxd8 33. Nxf7) (31... Kc7 32. Rd4 $1 {and now Black must play} Nd5 {and again allow} 33. Ne4) 32. Ne4) 31. Nxf7 Qb2+ 32. Kd3 Qb1+ 33. Kd4 {Amazingly the king is safe enough in the centre of the board as the knight on f7 prevents a check on d8} (33. Ke2 $1 {was still a safer option when after} Qe4+ 34. Qe3 Qxe3+ 35. Kxe3 {the ending should be winning for White}) 33... Qe4+ $2 {A final mistake after which the position is hopeless for Black} (33... e5+ {gives Black swindling chances but after accurate play White should still win:} 34. Kc5 Ne4+ 35. Kb6 Re6+ 36. Kb5 Nc3+ 37. Kb4 Nxa2+ 38. Rxa2 $1 Qe1+ (38... Qxa2 $2 {allows mate in 5 with} 39. Qa8+ Kc7 40. Qd8+ Kc6 41. Qc8+ Kb6 42. Qc5+ Ka6 43. Qa5#) 39. Kc5 {and White's extra piece should win the game although with the king so exposed Black can still hope to cause problems. One line would be} Qd1 40. Qa8+ Kc7 41. Qd8+ Qxd8 42. Nxd8 Kxd8 43. Rxa3 {which gives back the piece for a good ending. With an active king and an extra pawn White must have excellent winning chances}) 34. Kc3 Qf3+ 35. Kb4 $1 Nd5+ {A desperate last try} 36. Rxd5 (36. cxd5 Qf4+ 37. Rd4 {wins more easily}) 36... exd5 37. Qa8+ Kc7 38. Qxe8 {The dust has settled and Black's position is hopeless. 13...a5 deserves more outings as in this game Black was definitely close to equalising and 16... Nxg4! looks like it was playable.} 1-0


