1. c4 g6 2. Nc3 c5 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. g3 Nc6 5. Bg2 e6 {If White wants to win this line is a real problem.} 6. e3 (6. O-O Nge7 7. d3 {is the most popular, but is just too easy to play for Black.} (7. e3 {would transpose after} O-O 8. d4)) 6... Nge7 7. d4 (7. O-O Nf5 $5 (7... O-O 8. d4 cxd4 9. Nxd4 Nxd4 10. exd4 d5 {as below.}) 8. Ne4 d6 9. d4 $1 {see Bejtovic, J-Grandelius, N, in the Archive.}) 7... O-O $5 {Extremely rare.} (7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nxd4 9. exd4 d5 10. cxd5 Nxd5 {is the very drawish mainline, although this normally arrives from a Nge2 line, rather than Nf3 as here, see Bacrot, E-Vaisser, A in the PGN Archive.}) 8. O-O {White is happy to transpose.} (8. d5 Na5 9. Nd2 Rb8 10. a4 d6 11. O-O exd5 12. cxd5 {gave Black a perfectly reasonable Benoni position in Landgren, P (2182) -Tikkanen, H (2232)/Hallsberg 2000.}) (8. dxc5 Qa5) 8... b6 $5 {Black continues to search for a more interesting game.} (8... cxd4 9. Nxd4 Nxd4 ({or} 9... d5) 10. exd4 {reaches the mainline once again.}) (8... d6 {is also possible, and scores well,} 9. Re1 $5 (9. b3 Nf5) 9... Re8 10. b3 Rb8 (10... e5 $5) 11. Bb2 cxd4 12. exd4 d5 13. cxd5 exd5 14. Ne5 {with a small plus to White in Grischuk, A (2783)-Dominguez Perez, L (2754)/Beijing 2013.}) 9. b3 {New.} (9. dxc5 bxc5 10. Ne4 Ba6 $1 11. Qa4 Qa5 12. Qxa5 Nxa5 {De Andrade, W (2250) -Bruzon Batista, L (2488)/Sao Bernardo 1999,} 13. Rd1 {equal.}) (9. d5 Na5 10. dxe6 fxe6 11. Ne5 $2 d5 12. f4 Bxe5 13. fxe5 Nxc4 14. Rxf8+ {Marinangeli, M  (2143)-Arjona, J/ Olavarria 2002,} Qxf8 $1 15. Nxd5 Nxd5 16. Bxd5 Qd8 $1 17. Bf3 Qxd1+ 18. Bxd1 Bb7 {and ...Nxe5.}) (9. Re1 Ba6 10. Qa4 Bb7 {is nothing, Quirico, P (2118) -Bergero, S (1707)/Torino 2013.}) 9... d5 {The position is almost entirely symmetrical with White to move. The only difference is the placement of the respective kingside knights, but if anything this favours Black as the f3-knight masks the g2-bishop. This suggests that White would be better off with his knight on e2 instead, food for thought!} 10. cxd5 exd5 11. Ba3 Bg4 {The d4-pawn is pinned.} 12. h3 cxd4 $1 13. exd4 (13. Bxe7 Nxe7 14. exd4 Bxf3 15. Bxf3 Nf5 {is 'equalish' but only Black can be better.}) 13... Bxf3 14. Qxf3 Nxd4 15. Qd3 {It seems strange that White can play good logical moves from the beginning of the game, and already be struggling to regain his pawn and hold a draw! Where did he go wrong?} Rc8 {Threatening ...Rxc3.} 16. Rac1 (16. Bxe7 $6 Qxe7 (16... Rxc3 17. Qxc3 Qxe7 18. Rae1 Ne2+ 19. Rxe2 Qxe2 {with a pawn more, although a draw is likely.}) 17. Rae1 Qa3 18. Nxd5 Rc2 {with advantage.}) 16... Re8 17. Kh1 h6 18. Rfe1 Kh7 19. Kh2 Qd7 20. Bxe7 $1 {White chooses the perfect time to liquidate.} Rxe7 21. Rxe7 Qxe7 22. Nxd5 Qd7 23. Rxc8 Qxc8 {Now the position is a total draw, although the game continues a bit.} 24. Nf4 Qc5 25. Qe3 Qc2 26. Bd5 Nf5 27. Qe2 Qxe2 28. Nxe2 Nd4 29. Nxd4 Bxd4 30. Bxf7 Bxf2 {I suppose there must have been a no-draw rule of some sort, as playing on here is totally absurd, of course.} 31. Kg2 Be1 32. Kf3 Kg7 33. Be8 Kf6 34. g4 g5 35. Ke4 Ke7 36. Bb5 Kf6 37. Bc4 Ke7 38. Ba6 Kd6 39. Kf5 Kc5 40. a4 Kb4 41. Bc4 a6 42. Kg6 b5 43. axb5 axb5 44. Bg8 Kc5 45. Kxh6 Bh4 46. Kg6 Kd6 47. Kf5 Kc5 48. Bf7 Kd6 49. b4 Kc6 50. Be8+ Kb6 51. Bd7 Ka6 52. Be8 Kb6 53. Bd7 Ka6 54. Be8 Kb6 1/2-1/2


