1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 a6 7. Qd2 Nf6 8. O-O-O (8. f4 $5 d6 9. Be2 (9. O-O-O $1 {is more in the spirit of White's previous move.}) 9... Bd7 (9... Be7 {is the normal move here.}) 10. O-O (10. O-O-O {is still an option.}) 10... Be7 11. Rad1 O-O 12. Nb3 b5 13. a3 Rfd8 14. Bf3 Rab8 15. g4 $5 {Attacking in classical style.} Be8 (15... Bc8 16. g5 Nd7 {to relocate the bishop on the long diagonal actually looks fine for Black.}) 16. Qg2 Nd7 17. g5 Nb6 18. Bc1 ({The immediate} 18. f5 {looks more straightforward.}) 18... Nc4 (18... Na4 $5) 19. Kh1 Qb6 20. Bg4 Bd7 $6 (20... a5 {seems to be the right strategy here, preparing b4 to push the knight back from c3 and making it possible to answer f5 with exf5.}) 21. Qh3 Qb7 22. f5 N6e5 23. g6 $1 {Now White is getting his play going.} fxg6 24. fxg6 Nxg6 25. Bxe6+ $6 (25. Nd4 $1) 25... Bxe6 26. Qxe6+ Kh8 27. Nd4 Re8 28. Qd5 Bf6 29. Qxb7 Rxb7 30. Nd5 Bxd4 31. Rxd4 Kg8 {and, although this position is fairly balanced, Black eventually went on to win in Stukopin-Cori, Kocaeli 2013.}) 8... Be7 (8... b5 9. Bf4 Ne5 10. Nf3 Nxf3 11. gxf3 Qa5 {was played in Safarli-Jumabayev, Baku 2013, but here the simple} 12. Kb1 b4 13. Ne2 d5 {and now a move like} 14. Nd4 {looks attractive for White.}) 9. f4 $5 (9. f3 b5 10. g4 Nxd4 11. Bxd4 (11. Qxd4 Bb7 12. g5 Nh5 13. Kb1 (13. Bh3 f6 $5 (13... Rc8 {also works well.}) 14. Kb1 fxg5 15. Bg4 Nf6 16. Bxg5 Bc5 17. Qd2 Nxg4 18. fxg4 O-O 19. Qxd7 Qxd7 20. Rxd7 Bc6 21. Rc7 Rac8 22. Rxc8 Rxc8 $36 {Kurayan-Pavlidis, Kocaeli 2013}) 13... Rc8 14. Qd3 $146 {Sanal-Ter Sahakyan, Kocaeli 2013, and here Black has} d5 $1 15. exd5 Rd8 16. a3 Bxd5 {with a very comfortable position.}) 11... Bb7 (11... b4 $5 12. Na4 Rb8 13. Kb1 O-O 14. Qf2 d5 15. e5 Nd7 $132 {Kanarek-Vidit, Kocaeli 2013.}) 12. Bd3 (12. g5 Nh5 13. Be5 Qxe5 14. Qxd7+ Kf8 15. Qxb7 Bxg5+ 16. Kb1 Qb8 $1 {is an important point.}) (12. Kb1 O-O 13. h4 (13. Be3 b4 14. Ne2 d5 15. g5 Nd7 16. exd5 Bxd5 17. Nf4 Bc6 $17 {Idani-Grover, Kocaeli 2013.}) 13... Rac8 14. Bd3 $6 e5 $1 15. Be3 $6 Bb4 $17 {Kurayan-Stukopin, Kocaeli 2013.}) 12... O-O 13. Ne2 (13. Kb1 b4 14. Na4 d5 15. e5 Nd7 16. Qe3 Rab8 17. f4 Bc6 18. Nc5 Nxc5 19. Bxc5 Bb5 $132) (13. g5 Nh5 14. Ne2 f6 $132) 13... d6 14. Ng3 Nd7 15. Kb1 Ne5 {Black is already doing very well here.} 16. f4 Nf3 (16... Nxd3 17. cxd3 Rfc8 {is an interesting middlegame option.}) 17. Qc3 Qxc3 18. Bxc3 d5 19. exd5 Bxd5 20. Be4 Bxe4 21. Nxe4 Rfd8 22. Rdf1 Nd4 23. f5 exf5 24. gxf5 f6 25. Rhg1 Kf7 26. Ng3 (26. Ba5 {had to be played to keep the position balanced.}) 26... Bf8 27. Rf4 Nc6 28. a3 a5 29. b3 Bc5 30. Rg2 Rd1+ 31. Ka2 Nb4+ $1 {A nice tactic, gaining a winning advantage.} 32. Bxb4 axb4 33. a4 bxa4 34. Nh5 Bf8 $1 {This bishop kills any hope of counterplay.} 35. bxa4 Rxa4+ 36. Kb2 Raa1 37. Kb3 Rdb1+ 38. Kc4 Ra5 39. Kd3 Re5 40. Kd2 Rd5+ 41. Ke2 Rc5 42. Kd3 Rd1+ 43. Ke4 Rc4+ 44. Ke3 Rc3+ 45. Ke4 Re1+ {0-1, Eliseev-Yu Yangyi, Kocaeli 2013}) 9... b5 10. e5 b4 11. Ncb5 axb5 12. Nxb5 Qa5 $1 (12... Qb8 13. exf6 gxf6 14. Kb1 d5 15. c4 (15. Qf2 Ba6 16. Bb6 Bxb5 17. Bxb5 Qb7 18. b3 Rb8 19. Bxc6+ Qxc6 20. Bd4 {is probably fine for Black, but you might as well avoid it.}) 15... bxc3 16. Qxc3 Bd7 17. Bc5 O-O 18. Qg3+ Kh8 19. Qh4 Bxc5 20. Qxf6+ Kg8 21. Qg5+ Kh8 22. Qf6+ Kg8 23. Qg5+ Kh8 24. Qf6+ Kg8 25. Qg5+ Kh8 {1/2-1/2, Yu Yangyi-Cori, Kocaeli 2013.}) 13. exf6 gxf6 14. Nd6+ Bxd6 15. Qxd6 Qxa2 16. Rd3 Qa1+ 17. Kd2 Ra2 18. Rb3 (18. Bd4 Nxd4 19. Rxd4 Rxb2 20. Bb5 Qa5 21. Bxd7+ Bxd7 22. Ra1 $1 Qxa1 23. Qb8+ Ke7 24. Qd6+ {with a perpetual.}) 18... Rxb2 19. Bb5 Qa2 20. Rxb2 Qxb2 21. Bc5 Qc3+ 22. Kd1 {Diagram [#] As an aspiring Taimanov player, you need to be aware of the f4 options that White has within the English Attack, on move eight and nine, that is. In Stukopin-Cori 8.f4!? was answered by the modest 8...d6 and now 9.0-0-0 actually looks quite attractive for White. The alternative 9.f4!? was played twice on the top boards at the World Junior. In Yu Yangyi-Cori Black played 12...Qb8 and drew without problems (15.Qf2 may be an alternative there). In Wei Yi-Stukopin Black deviated with 12...Qa5! and after relatively forcing play the diagram position was reached. Here Black found the only move 22...Ba6!, which solved all his problems. The new main line of the Taimanov, 9.f3 b5 10.g4 Nxd4, was tested six times at the World Junior and with three wins and three draws Black scored yet another fantastic result. The most prominent of these games was Eliseev-Yu Yangyi, which helped the latter to become World Champion. Black consistently obtained pleasant positions from the opening and it's still hard to see where White can improve.} Ba6 $1 {The only move.} 23. Bxa6 (23. Bxc6 Qa1+ 24. Kd2 Qc3+ {with a perpetual.}) 23... Qa1+ 24. Kd2 Qxa6 25. Bd4 $6 (25. Rb1 Kd8 26. Bxb4 Nxb4 27. Qxb4 {and White is active enough to compensate for the minus pawn.}) 25... Rg8 26. g3 Qb7 $6 ({Here} 26... b3 $1 {would still test White and challenge him to find two accurate rook moves:} 27. Rb1 $1 (27. cxb3 Qa2+ {is good for Black.}) (27. Ra1 Qb7 28. Bc5 b2 29. Rb1 f5 30. c3 f6 31. Kc2 Kf7 32. Rxb2 Qc8 $15) 27... bxc2 28. Ra1 $1 c1=Q+ (28... Qb7 29. Bc5 {is dynamically balanced.}) 29. Rxc1 Qa2+ 30. Kd1 Qa4+ 31. Kd2 $11) 27. Bc5 Qb8 28. Qxb8+ Nxb8 29. Ra1 Nc6 30. Ra8+ Nd8 31. f5 exf5 32. Bxb4 f4 33. gxf4 1/2-1/2


