{THE KING IN THE MIDDLE} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bd7 5. Nf3 Bc6 6. Neg5 Nd7 {Diagram [#] Here we have an even more recent example where the young Chinese player was more or less following in the footsteps of his compatriot.} 7. Nxf7 $5 Kxf7 8. Ng5+ Ke8 9. Bc4 {White is about to capture a second pawn on e6, and though there is no immediate danger of mate, the black king will be stuck in the middle for a while.} Bd5 ({"The computer" fearlessly takes on g2 first:} 9... Bxg2 10. Rg1 Bd5 11. Nxe6 {but Black's loss of the right to castle is still troublesome; after, for example,} Bxe6 12. Bxe6 {(a 'beastly bishop', see CVT 117)} Qh4 13. Qf3 Ngf6 14. Bf4 {White seems to have sufficient compensation.}) 10. Nxe6 Bxe6 11. Bxe6 Bd6 12. O-O Ngf6 {White has definite positional compensation, but if and when Black manages to disentangle the position, material balance will gradually tell and both sides have their practical chances.} 13. Qf3 ({The immediate} 13. Re1 {may be more to the point, to answer} c6 {with} 14. c4) 13... c6 14. Re1 Qa5 15. Bf4 Bxf4 16. Qxf4 Kd8 17. Qg3 g6 18. c3 {Here White continued very 'solidly', whereas perhaps} (18. Rad1) ({or} 18. c4 {would have been more appropriate. In the game Black eventually managed to evacuate his king safely to b8 after having manoeuvred his queen to d6. But just before the 40th move he collapsed under the constant pressure.}) 18... Re8 19. Bf7 Re7 20. Bb3 Rxe1+ 21. Rxe1 Qc7 22. Qg5 Qd6 23. Re6 Qf8 24. c4 Rc8 25. c5 Rc7 26. h3 Kc8 27. Qe3 Kb8 28. Re7 Rc8 29. Rf7 Qe8 30. Be6 Rd8 31. Qf4+ Ka8 32. Qc7 a6 33. Kh2 h5 34. Bc4 Rc8 35. Qd6 Rd8 36. Qc7 Rc8 37. Qd6 Rd8 38. Re7 Qf8 39. Bxa6 Ne8 40. Bxb7+ Ka7 41. Qxc6 Qxe7 42. Qa6+ Kb8 43. Bf3 Nxc5 44. Qa8+ Kc7 45. Qa7+ Kd6 46. Qb6+ 1-0


