{ANAND'S MURDEROUS TWIN GUNS Maybe you've always been impressed by the positioning of the bishops in Lasker-Bauer. After last week you know you'd seen nothing yet. Bring on Anand's murderous twin guns! Of course I'm talking about the Aronian-Anand game from the Tata tournament in Wijk aan Zee, which is coming to an end this weekend. It was Game of the Week in CVO 211 and you might just have spotted the game elsewhere too. So we won't discuss it here, but we will look into some other deadly bishops aimed at the opponent's king.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 {ANAND'S MURDEROUS TWIN GUNS Maybe you've always been impressed by the positioning of the bishops in Lasker-Bauer. After last week you know you'd seen nothing yet. Bring on Anand's murderous twin guns! Of course I'm talking about the Aronian-Anand game from the Tata tournament in Wijk aan Zee, which is coming to an end this weekend. It was Game of the Week in CVO 211 and you might just have spotted the game elsewhere too. So we won't discuss it here, but we will look into some other deadly bishops aimed at the opponent's king.} Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Nge2 c6 6. a3 Ba5 7. b4 Bc7 8. Bb2 d5 9. Ng3 Re8 10. f4 b6 11. Be2 dxc4 12. Bxc4 Nd5 13. Qd2 Nd7 14. O-O N7f6 15. Nge2 Bb7 16. e4 Nxc3 17. Nxc3 {Diagram [#]} c5 {Here comes bishop no. 1.} 18. e5 {The logical follow-up, but now the b7-bishop's path is no longer blocked by any enemy pawns (cf. CVT 68, "War on the Long Diagonal"), recalling Aronian-Anand.} cxd4 19. Nb5 Ne4 20. Qe1 $2 ({The natural} 20. Qc2) ({and} 20. Qxd4 {are both preferable.}) 20... a6 21. Nxd4 ({This is the point. After} 21. Nxc7 Qxc7 {the bishop on c4 is under attack and Black keeps his extra pawn. After the text move Black's dark-squared bishop also comes to life.}) 21... b5 22. Bb3 Bb6 {Now the position resembles the famous Rotlewi-Rubinstein game, which Anand also referred to immediately after his game against Aronian.} 23. Rd1 Re7 24. Kh1 Rd7 25. Qe3 Kh8 $6 (25... g6 $1 26. Bc2 Rc8 27. Bxe4 Bxe4 28. Qxe4 Rc4) 26. f5 exf5 27. Rxf5 Rc8 28. e6 fxe6 29. Bxe6 {Now White also has two fearsome bishops - difficult calculation lies ahead.} Rc2 30. Bxd7 Rxb2 31. Qf4 $2 {Obvious, but wrong. White unpins his knight and is threatening mate, but after the cool reply Black is on top. Apparently} (31. Qe1 {was the best move, leaving White in charge (} Nf6 32. Bc6 $1 {).}) 31... Nf6 $1 {Defending against mate and attacking both g2 and d7. Suddenly White's pieces are uncoordinated while Black's bishops - and not only the bishops - can do their thing.} 32. Nf3 Qxd7 33. Qb8+ Ng8 34. Rf1 Qxf5 35. Qxb7 Rb1 0-1


