1. d4 {Arsovic,Goran Arsovic,Goran Krasenkow,M: 'Krasenkow,Michal'} Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. h3 O-O 6. Nf3 e5 7. d5 a5 8. Bg5 Na6 9. Be2 {Now we are technically in a Petrosian Variation.} Qe8 10. g4 (10. Nd2 Nd7 11. a3 h6 $6 {see Movsesian, S (2698) -Grischuk, A (2763) Istanbul 2012.}) 10... Kh8 {Generally I do not like to play this move unless White has played Rg1, but Black has done well here in the past.} ({Instead} 10... Nc5 {see Varga, P (2475)-Efimenko, Z (2435) Master Open, Lausanne 2001.}) ({I have expressed preference for} 10... Nd7 $1 {and only after} 11. Rg1 (11. Nd2 Ndc5 {intending ...f5}) (11. a3 Nb6 $1 {is another typical idea}) 11... Kh8 ({or just} 11... Ndc5)) 11. Nd2 {Krasenkow,M: 'Not the most accurate move order.'} ({Krasenkow,M: 'Korobov's'} 11. Be3 {Krasenkow,M: 'is more appropriate here (see my "Opening trends" article in CBM 182).'} Ng8 12. g5 $5 {see Korobov,A (2705)-Smirin,I  (2638) Eilat 2012} ({This turns out to be very effective. White can also play more slowly with} 12. Nd2)) 11... Ng8 {Preparing ...f5 and possibly ...Bh6. Preparing ...f5 and possibly ...Bh6. Krasenkow,M: '!'} 12. h4 f5 {this has scored very well for Black} (12... f6 13. Be3 f5 14. f3 $1 (14. gxf5 gxf5 15. exf5 Bxf5 (15... Nh6 16. Bh5 Qd7 17. f6 Rxf6 18. Nde4 Rf8 {0-1 (44) Polivanov,A (2421)-Vovk,A (2339) Lvov 2005} 19. Qd2 Nf5 20. O-O-O $14) (15... Bh6 16. Bg5 Bxg5 17. hxg5 Bxf5 18. Nde4 $14 {1/2 (18) Giddins,S (2290)-Gullaksen,E (2365) Skei 1995}) 16. Nde4 Nf6 17. Ng3 Qd7 {(Black's bishop has no h7-square)} 18. h5 Rf7 19. h6 Bf8 20. Bd3 Bxd3 21. Qxd3 Ng4 22. Nce4 Nxe3 23. fxe3 Qg4 24. Kd2 $14 {0-1 (36) Polak,T (2544)-Novikov,S (2562) Pardubice 2007}) 14... f4 15. Bf2 {is better for White, because all the play will shift to the queenside, where White has a significant space advantage.}) (12... h6 $5 13. Be3 f5 {is possible, transposing to the position from my game against Spirin, examined in the same article.}) 13. gxf5 ({After} 13. f3 {Arsovic,Goran: '- 82/508'} f4 {Black threatens to win the g5-bishop, and} (13... fxg4 $5 14. fxg4 Nf6 $132) 14. h5 Bf6 {allows Black to both trade his bad bishop and keep some open lines on the kingside.} 15. hxg6 Qxg6 16. Bxf6+ Nxf6 17. Nb3 b6 18. Qd2 Bd7 19. O-O-O {Krasenkow,M: '' Krasenkow,M: '0-1 (40) Lazarev,V (2500)-Cebalo,M (2465) Estensi 2001'} Kg7 20. Rdg1 h6 {with chances for both sides in Lazarev,V (2500)-Cebalo,M (2465) Lido degli Estensi 2001, 0-1 (40)}) 13... gxf5 14. Bh5 $5 (14. exf5 Bxf5 15. Nde4 Nf6 16. Ng3 Qd7 $1 17. Rg1 Nb4 $132 {Georgiadis,I (2449)-Simeonidis,I (2238) Rethymno 2013, 1/2-1/2 (45)} 18. Rc1 e4 $132 {1/2 (45) Georgiadis,I (2449)-Simeonidis,I (2238) Rethymno 2013}) (14. Qc2 {has been played in some correspondence games.} Nf6 (14... Nb4 15. Qb3 Nf6 16. O-O-O Nd7 17. Qa3 Nc5 $132 {Sidenko,A (2286) -Mancuso,A (2244) Lechenicher SchachServer 2010}) 15. a3 Nc5 16. exf5 e4 (16... Qd7 $5 $146) 17. h5 Bxf5 {led to a mess. Make of it what you will, with engines running.} 18. h6 Nd3+ 19. Kf1 Nxf2 $1 20. hxg7+ Kxg7 21. Rg1 Kh8 22. Nb5 Nd3 23. Rg3 Bg4 24. Bxd3 Nh5+ 25. Kg1 Nxg3 26. Nxe4 Qh5 $1 $19 27. Qh2 Nxe4 28. Bxe4 Bh3 29. Bg2 Qxg5 30. Qxh3 Rf6 31. Nxc7 Rg8 32. Ne6 Qd2 33. Rf1 Rxg2+ 34. Qxg2 Qe3+ 35. Rf2 Rg6 36. b3 Rxg2+ 37. Kxg2 h5 38. Rf3 Qe2+ 39. Kg3 h4+ 40. Kf4 a4 {0-1 (40) Malkov,A (2233)-Ulasevich,S (2319) ICCF 2012}) 14... Qd7 {Now both the Bh5 and Qd7 are somewhat misplaced.} 15. Qe2 $146 (15. exf5 $6 Qxf5 16. Nde4 Nc5 $1 {is already looking good for Black.} 17. Qe2 Nxe4 18. Nxe4 Nf6 {Arsovic,Goran: ''} 19. Ng3 Qd7 20. Rg1 {Solomon,K (2350)-Popovic,D (2553) Cappelle-la-Grande 2014} b5 $1 {with excellent play.} (20... c6 $132 {0-1 (32) Solomon,K (2350)-Popovic,D (2553) Cappelle-la-Grande 2014})) 15... Nf6 16. Bf3 fxe4 {A concrete move. A concrete move. Krasenkow,M: '?!'} (16... Qf7 {was also possible.}) (16... Nc5 {Arsovic,Goran Krasenkow,M: 'is a normal continuation. If'} 17. O-O-O {Krasenkow,M: 'then'} Qf7 {Krasenkow,M: '!?'} (17... fxe4 18. Ndxe4 Nfxe4