{Yi Wei in another blitz game has a chance to carry out a similar sacrifice but doesn't take it.} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 {The Arkell-Khenkin variation.} 4. dxc5 e6 5. a3 Bxc5 6. Qg4 (6. b4 Bb6 7. Nf3 Ne7 8. Bd3) 6... Ne7 7. Bd3 (7. b4 Bb6 8. Nf3 Ng6 9. Bd3 Nc6 10. Bb2) 7... O-O (7... Nd7) 8. Nf3 f5 $1 9. exf6 Rxf6 10. Qh4 $2 (10. Qh5 g6 11. Qh4 {weakening the dark squares was better}) 10... h6 11. O-O Nbc6 12. c4 Qf8 13. Nc3 Ng6 $2 (13... Rxf3 $1 {Brings back clear echoes of the Turner game. Black gets great compensation. I think if Yi Wei had more time to think he would have played this anyway, as it's clearly the right idea.} 14. gxf3 Ne5 15. Be2 Nxf3+ 16. Bxf3 Qxf3 $17) 14. Qh5 Nge5 15. Nxe5 Rxf2 16. Be3 $1 {Karjakin defends well, as always.} Bxe3 17. Rxf2 Bxf2+ (17... Nxe5 18. Kh1 Bxf2 (18... Qxf2 19. Qe8+ Qf8 20. Bh7+ Kxh7 21. Qxf8) 19. Qxe5) 18. Kh1 Nxe5 19. Qxe5 Qf6 20. Qe2 {Now it's a crapshoot} dxc4 21. Bc2 Qh4 22. Ne4 Bd4 23. Rd1 Bxb2 (23... Be5 $1 24. g3 Qe7 $15) 24. Nd6 e5 $4 {Such terrible moves are common at blitz. Black weakens his light-squares} (24... Bd7 25. Nxc4 Bd4 26. Qd3 Rf8 $15) 25. Nxc4 $18 (25. Be4 Be6 (25... Bd4 26. Qxc4+ {with a mating attack}) 26. Qxb2) 25... Bd4 26. Qd3 $2 (26. Nxe5 $1 Be6 27. Nf3) 26... Qf6 27. Qh7+ Kf7 28. Bd3 Ke7 (28... Be6 29. Rf1 Bf2 30. Qe4 $18) 29. Rf1 Qg5 30. Bg6 e4 31. Rf7+ Ke6 32. Qg8 1-0


