{As mentioned earlier, Navara initially ran away in the tournament standings, but by round 11 it was Wei Yi who had taken the lead. In the previous round he had disposed of yours truly in a matter of two hours. Painful indeed! In game 11 he continued his streak:} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 O-O 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 d6 7. Nf3 Nc6 {Diagram [#] A slightly offbeat way of handling the 4.Qc2-Nimzo. I say "slightly," because countless top players from past and present have occasionally played this way.} 8. b4 e5 9. dxe5 dxe5 ({Strangely enough this natural recapture is not the most popular move in this position. People have been toying with} 9... Ne4 $5 10. Qe3 f5 {although I don't quite believe this after} 11. Bb2 {but perhaps.}) (9... Nxe5 10. Nxe5 dxe5 {is interesting. It can't be unfavorable for Black to get the knights off.}) 10. Bb2 (10. Nxe5 Nxe5 11. Qxe5 Re8 {is known to be pretty dangerous, for instance} 12. Qb2 a5 $1 13. b5 Qd3 $1 {with the idea} 14. e3 Qg6 {and White can barely move.}) 10... e4 11. Nd2 Re8 12. g3 Bf5 13. Bg2 {I like how Michiels handled the opening. He has two bishops and is about to castle, while it's not entirely clear what Black has to show for it.} Ne5 14. O-O Qd7 15. Rfd1 Rad8 {Diagram [#]} 16. Qb3 $6 (16. Nf1 $1 {was a very instructive way to get a large advantage. After the further} Qxd1 17. Rxd1 Rxd1 18. Qc2 $1 {Black is forced to retreat with} Rdd8 {, and now} 19. Ne3 $1 Bg6 (19... Bc8 20. h3 {gives White a large positional advantage; this is an interesting case where two rooks are no match for the queen because White has the better minor pieces.}) 20. Qa4 $1 (20. h3 Nf3+ $1 {was the reason behind 19...Bg6.}) 20... Nfg4 (20... a6 21. Qa5 $1) 21. Nxg4 Nxg4 22. h3 {followed by Qxa7.}) 16... Qe6 $1 17. Bxe5 $6 (17. Nf1 $5 {was a good way to bail out;} Qxc4 18. Qxc4 Nxc4 19. Bxf6 gxf6 20. Rdc1 $1 {despite being a pawn down, White should be able to hold due to numerous weaknesses in Black's camp.}) 17... Qxe5 18. Nf1 Be6 19. Ne3 h5 {Black is very comfortable now and starts a little kingside demonstration.} 20. h4 $6 ({The more restrained} 20. h3 {would have prevented Black's next move.}) 20... Ng4 $1 21. Nxg4 hxg4 22. e3 {Diagram [#] Time is of the essence in chess. If White gets some of it in this position, he will exchange all the rooks, bring his bishop to e2 and all his problems will be solved. It will never happen in this game.} Rd3 $1 (22... b5 $6 23. Bf1 bxc4 24. Bxc4 Rd3 25. Bxe6 $1 (25. Qa2 Bxc4 26. Qxc4 Rxe3 $1 27. fxe3 Qxg3+ 28. Kf1 Re6 $1 {leads to a serious whooping of the white king.}) 25... Rxb3 26. Bxb3 {is much less convincing and most likely to end in a draw.}) 23. Qc2 ({The tactical point behind Black's previous move is} 23. Rxd3 Bxc4 $3 24. Qxc4 Qxa1+ {followed by exd3. The intermediate capture on c4 was to ensure that White can't play} 25. Rd1 {here.}) 23... Red8 24. Bf1 R8d6 (24... b5 25. cxb5 Bb3 26. Bxd3 Bxc2 27. Bxc2 Rxd1+ 28. Rxd1 {is similar to my comment on move 22. White should hold without any trouble. Wei Yi now starts to gradually improve his position.}) 25. a4 ({Note that} 25. Bxd3 exd3 {weakens the light squares too much. The combined strength of bishop and queen is likely to make use of that.}) 25... b6 26. Rac1 Bf5 27. Be2 c5 ({I like Wei Yi's approach of slowly improving his position. Here the engine shouts} 27... Rxe3 $1 28. Rxd6 cxd6 29. fxe3 Qxg3+ 30. Kf1 Qxe3 {with a winning advantage, and while that is certainly true – White is surprisingly helpless against Black's forces – it is not at all easy to see that from a human viewpoint. Furthermore, we have now invested a full rook. Why take such risks? For completeness sake:} 31. Qc3 Qf4+ 32. Kg1 g3 $1 {with winning threats against the king.}) 28. bxc5 Qxc5 {Diagram [#]} 29. Bxd3 $4 ({It's difficult to live with such a rook inside your position, but White had to sit tight and await developments. After a waiting move like} 29. Rb1 {it's not at all easy to break White's position.}) 29... exd3 30. Qb2 Be4 {The joy Wei Yi must have felt when he placed his bishop on e4... a better case for the relative value of pieces is difficult to find! The rest is easy.} 31. Rd2 Qf5 32. f4 gxf3 33. Qb5 Qg4 34. Kh2 Bf5 35. Qe5 Qh3+ 36. Kg1 Rg6 37. Rh2 f2+ {White resigned. Mate will follow shortly.} 0-1



